title: Maltose
complex: Maltose ( or ), also known as maltobiose or malt sugar, is a disaccharide formed from two units of glucose joined with an α(1→4) bond. <s> In the isomer isomaltose, the two glucose molecules are joined with an α(1→6) bond.
simple: Maltose (known as malt sugar) is a disaccharide (sometimes called di-glucose).

title: Médée (Cherubini)
complex: Médée is a French language opéra-comique by Luigi Cherubini. <s> The libretto by François-Benoît Hoffman (Nicolas Étienne Framéry) was based on Euripides' tragedy of Medea and Pierre Corneille's play "Médée". <s> It is set in the ancient city of Corinth. <s> The opera was premiered on 13 March 1797 at the Théâtre Feydeau, Paris. <s> It met with a lukewarm reception and was not immediately revived.
simple: Médée is a French opera in three acts. <s> Luigi Cherubini wrote the music. <s> The libretto is by François-Benoît Hoffmann (Nicolas Étienne Framéry). <s> It is based on Euripides' tragedy of Medea and on Pierre Corneille's play "Médée". <s> It was first performed in Paris on 13 March 1797.

title: Satellite DNA
complex: Satellite DNA consists of very large arrays of tandemly repeating, non-coding DNA. <s> Satellite DNA is the main component of functional centromeres, and form the main structural constituent of heterochromatin. <s> Satellite DNA, together with minisatellite and microsatellite DNA, constitute the tandem repeats.
simple: Satellite DNA has many sections of repeating, non-coding DNA. <s> Satellite DNA is a type of tandem repeat. <s> Satellite DNA is the main component of centromeres. <s> It forms the main part of heterochromatin. <s> Tandem repeats also include minisatellite and microsatellite DNA.

title: Everett Dirksen
complex: Everett McKinley Dirksen (January 4, 1896 – September 7, 1969) was an American politician of the Republican Party. <s> He represented Illinois in the United States House of Representatives and the United States Senate. <s> As Senate Minority Leader from 1959 to 1969, he played a highly visible and key role in the politics of the 1960s. <s> He helped write and pass the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Civil Rights Act of 1968, both landmark pieces of legislation during the Civil Rights Movement. <s> He was also one of the Senate's strongest supporters of the Vietnam War. <s> A talented orator with a florid style and a notably rich baritone voice, his flamboyant speeches caused his detractors to refer to him as "The Wizard of Ooze". <s> Dirksen was a Freemason and was a member of Pekin Lodge #29 in Pekin. <s> In 1954, he was Grand Orator of the Grand Lodge of Illinois. <s> He was honored with the 33rd degree in 1954. <s> In August 1969, chest x-rays disclosed an asymptomatic peripherally located mass in the upper lobe of the right lung. <s> Dirksen entered Walter Reed Army Hospital for surgery, which was undertaken on September 2. <s> A right upper lobectomy removed what proved to be lung cancer (adenocarcinoma). <s> Mr. Dirksen initially did well, but progressive complications developed into bronchopneumonia. <s> He suffered a cardiopulmonary arrest and died on September 7, 1969, at age 73.
simple: Everett McKinley Dirksen (January 4, 1896 – September 7, 1969) was an American politician. <s> He represented Illinois in the U.S. House of Representatives (1933–1949) and U.S. Senate (1951–1969). <s> As Senate Minority Leader for ten years, he was very important in the politics during the 1960s. <s> Some things he did was to help passing the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Open Housing Act of 1968, both landmarks of civil rights legislation. <s> He was also one of the Senate's strongest supporters of the Vietnam War and was known as "The Wizard of Ooze" for his oratorical style. <s> Dirksen was a freemason. <s> Dirksen died on September 7, 1969 in Washington, D.C. from cardiopulmonary arrest caused by lung cancer-related bronchopneumonia, aged 73.

title: Gichin Funakoshi
complex: Gichin Funakoshi (船越 義珍 , Funakoshi Gichin , November 10, 1868 – April 26, 1957) is the founder of Shotokan Karate-Do, perhaps the most widely known style of karate, and is known as a "father of modern karate". <s> Following the teachings of Anko Itosu and Anko Asato, he was one of the Okinawan karate masters who introduced karate to the Japanese mainland in 1922.
simple: Gichin Funakoshi (船越 義珍, Funakoshi Gichin, 10 November 1868-26 April 1957) was the founder of Shotokan, which is the most widely known school or style of karate. <s> He is known as the "father of modern karate".

title: Miranda (novel)
complex: Miranda is a novel written by Antoni Lange in 1924. <s> It was the last great work of Lange before he died , and his most famous book today. <s> It is said that "Miranda" is an "occultic fiction" and a "romance ranked to a philosophical treaty". <s> The novel is also known as "novelty writing" which conciliates dystopia and utopia. <s> It is a matter of opinion to classify the novel to modernism or interwar period. <s> The title of the novel refers to the person of Miranda from Shakespeare's play called "The Tempest". <s> "Miranda" is also full of allusions to many classics such as: "Men Like Gods" by Herbert George Wells, "The City of the Sun" by Tommaso Campanella, "Lenore" by Edgar Allan Poe, "Genezis z Ducha" by Juliusz Słowacki, poems by Cyprian Kamil Norwid, writings of Friedrich Nietzsche (criticism of concept of the Übermensch), Arthur Schopenhauer, Plato and Sanskrit epics of ancient India. <s> The novel tells about ideal civilisation of powerful mages which have invited paranormal skills like telepathy, levitation and mediumism. <s> The Brahmins value anarchy, freedom, peace, free love and anti-work. <s> Their country is organized by Ministry of Love, Ministry of Power and Ministry of Wisdom, and they use a strange substance classified as Nivridium in order to their self-perfect idea. <s> The main plot is the history of love of Polish emigrant Jan Podobłoczny (Lange's own "porte-parole") to the materialization of an ideal woman named Damayanti. <s> A tragic end of their romance comes from clash between physical and spiritual sides of human existence. <s> In the last chapter of the novel, Damayanti sacrifices her body in order to let her spirit fly to higher stage of consciousness. <s> Miranda is a Scottish spiritual medium, who lives in Warsaw. <s> She can contact the soul of Damayanti and materialize the mysterious person of Lenore, who meets Jan Podobłoczny when he is close his death. <s> In the moment when Damayanti dies, Miranda disappears. <s> The novel was translated into English (in 1968), French, Spanish and Italian.
simple: Miranda is a novel written by Antoni Lange in 1924. <s> It is the last great work of Lange and his most famous book today. <s> It is said that "Miranda" is an "occultic fiction" and a "romance ranked to a philosophical treaty". <s> The novel is also known as a mix of dystopia and utopia. <s> The novel's title refers to the character Miranda, from Shakespeare's play "The Tempest". <s> "Miranda" also has been influenced by work such as: "Men Like Gods" by Herbert George Wells; "The City of the Sun" by Tommaso Campanella; "Lenore" by Edgar Allan Poe,;"Genezis z Ducha" by Juliusz Słowacki; poems by Cyprian Kamil Norwid; writings of Friedrich Nietzsche (criticism of concept of the Übermensch); Arthur Schopenhauer; Plato; and Sanskrit epics of ancient India. <s> The novel tells about a civilization of Brahmans who have powerful skills. <s> The Brahmans in the book think the most important things are anarchy, freedom, peace, and free love. <s> Their country is led by the Ministry of Love, Ministry of Power and Ministry of Wisdom. <s> The Brahmans use a strange chemical named Nivridium to keep their self-perfect idea. <s> The story is the of a Polish emigrant named Jan Podobłoczny (Lange's own "parte-parole") falling in love with a woman named Damayanti. <s> In the last chapter of the novel, Damayanti sacrifices her body in order to let her spirit fly to a greater level of though. <s> Miranda is a Scottish spiritual medium, who lives in Warsaw. <s> She can talk with the soul of Damayanti and make a woman named Lenore appear. <s> She meets Jan Podobłoczny when he is close to his death. <s> In the moment when Damayanti dies, Miranda disappears. <s> The novel was translated into English (in 1968), French, Spanish and Italian.

title: Arm wrestling
complex: Arm wrestling is a sport involving two participants. <s> Each places one arm on a surface with their elbows bent and touching the surface, and they grip each other's hand. <s> The goal is to pin the other's arm onto the surface, the winner's arm over the loser's arm. <s> In the early years different names were interchangeably used to describe the same sport: "skanderbeg", "arm turning", "arm twisting", "arm wrestling", "indian arm wrestling", "twisting wrists", "wrist turning", "wrist wrestling". <s> Organized armwrestling tournaments started being held in the 1950s. <s> Various factors can play a part in one's success in arm wrestling. <s> Technique and overall arm strength are the two greatest contributing factors to winning an arm wrestling match. <s> Other factors such as the length of an arm wrestler's arm, his/her muscle and arm mass/density, hand grip size, wrist endurance and flexibility, reaction time, as well as countless other traits, can add to the advantages of one arm wrestler over another . <s> It is sometimes used to prove who is stronger between two or more people. <s> In "competitive arm wrestling", as sanctioned by the United States Armwrestling Federation (USAF), arm wrestling is performed with both competitors standing up with their arms placed on a "tournament arm wrestling table" . <s> Arm wrestling tournaments are also divided into weight classes as well as left and right-handed divisions. <s> Furthermore, strict rules such as fouls given to penalties (such as the competitor's elbow leaving a matted area where the elbow is to remain at all times, or a false start), and trying to escape a possible arm pin by breaking the grip with the opponent may result in a loss at the table . <s> Paraphrasing USAF rules, arm wrestlers must straighten their wrists without a time lapse of one minute during competition. <s> The World Armwrestling Federation (WAF) is the universally recognized global governing body of professional arm wrestling and comprises 80 member countries. <s> Arm wrestling puts enormous torque/torsion stress on the upper arm's humerus bone to a degree seen in few other physical activities. <s> Most people's bones are not accustomed to being significantly stressed in this direction, and severe injuries can occur. <s> The arm typically fails because of a diagonal break at or below the midpoint between the shoulder and the elbow; this is known as the 'break arm' position. <s> The most common injury is the humeral shaft fracture.
simple: Arm wrestling is a sport with two players. <s> Each player places one arm, either the right or left, on a surface, with their elbows bent and touching the surface, and they grip each other's hand. <s> The goal is to pin the other's arm onto the surface, with the winner's arm over the loser's arm. <s> Many things can play a part in a player's success in arm wrestling. <s> Skill and overall arm strength are the two greatest contributing things to winning an arm wrestling match. <s> Other things such as the length of an arm wrestler's arm, his/her muscle and arm mass/density, hand grip size, wrist endurance and flexibility, reaction time, as well as countless other traits, can add to the advantages of one arm wrestler over another. <s> It is sometimes used to prove who is stronger between two or more people. <s> The World Armwrestling Federation, also called the WAF, has more than 85 member countries. <s> Arm wrestling puts enormous pressure/twist on the upper arm's humerus bone to a degree seen in few other physical activities. <s> Most people's bones are not used to being so stressed in this way, and injuries can occur surprisingly easily. <s> The arm typically fails because of a diagonal break at or below the midpoint between the shoulder and the elbow.

title: Anne Vermeer
complex: Anne Rinse Vermeer (12 December 1916 – 26 July 2018) was a Dutch politician of the Labour Party (PvdA).
simple: Anne Rinse Vermeer (12 December 1916 – 26 July 2018) was a Dutch politician and economist. <s> Vermeer was a member of the Labour Party (PvdA).

title: SMS Helgoland
complex: SMS "Helgoland", the lead ship of her class, was a dreadnought battleship of the German Imperial Navy. <s> "Helgoland"' s design represented an incremental improvement over the preceding "Nassau" class , including an increase in the bore diameter of the main guns, from 28 cm (11 in) to . <s> Her keel was laid down on 11 November 1908 at the Howaldtswerke shipyards in Kiel. <s> "Helgoland" was launched on 25 September 1909 and was commissioned on 23 August 1911. <s> Like most battleships of the High Seas Fleet, "Helgoland" saw limited action against Britain's Royal Navy during World War I. <s> The ship participated in several fruitless sweeps into the North Sea as the covering force for the battlecruisers of the I Scouting Group. <s> She saw some limited duty in the Baltic Sea against the Russian Navy, including serving as part of a support force during the Battle of the Gulf of Riga in August 1915. <s> "Helgoland" was present at the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916, though she was located in the center of the German line of battle and not as heavily engaged as the "König" - and "Kaiser"-class ships in the lead. <s> "Helgoland" was ceded to Great Britain at the end of the war and broken up for scrap in the early 1920s. <s> Her coat of arms is preserved in the Military History Museum of the Bundeswehr in Dresden.
simple: SMS "Helgoland", the lead ship of her class, was a dreadnought battleship of the German Imperial Navy. <s> "Helgoland"'s design was an improvement on the earlier "Nassau class". <s> Construction began on 11 November 1908 at the Howaldtswerke shipyards in Kiel. <s> "Helgoland" was launched on 25 September 1909 and was commissioned on 23 August 1911. <s> "Helgoland" saw some action against Britain's Royal Navy during World War I. <s> The ship was part of the I Scouting Group in the North Sea. <s> She also served in the Baltic Sea against the Russian Navy, including the Battle of the Gulf of Riga in August 1915. <s> "Helgoland" was at the Battle of Jutland on 31 May – 1 June 1916. <s> She was given to Great Britain at the end of the war and broken up for scrap in the early 1920s. <s> Her coat of arms is now in the Military History Museum of the Bundeswehr in Dresden.

title: Igis
complex: Igis "(Romansh: Eigias)" is a former municipality in the district of Landquart in the Swiss canton of Graubünden. <s> Far more known than its proper name Igis is its hamlet Landquart, for its Rail Station and motorway exit. <s> The municipalities of Igis and Mastrils merged on 1 January 2012 into the new municipality of Landquart.
simple: Igis is a former municipality in the district of Landquart in the canton of Graubünden in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2012 the former municipalities of Igis and Mastrils merged into the new municipality of Landquart.

title: ISO 639-2
complex: ISO 639-2:1998, "Codes for the representation of names of languages — Part 2: Alpha-3 code", is the second part of the ISO 639 standard, which lists codes for the representation of the names of languages. <s> The three-letter codes given for each language in this part of the standard are referred to as "Alpha-3" codes. <s> There are 487 entries in the list of ISO 639-2 codes. <s> Work was begun on the ISO 639-2 standard in 1989, because the ISO 639-1 standard, which uses only two-letter codes for languages, is not able to accommodate a sufficient number of languages. <s> The ISO 639-2 standard was first released in 1998. <s> In practice, ISO 639-2 has largely been superseded by ISO 639-3 (2007), which includes codes for all the individual languages in ISO 639-2 plus many more. <s> It also includes the special and reserved codes, and is designed not to conflict with ISO 639-2. <s> ISO 639-3, however, does not include any of the collective languages in ISO 639-2; most of these are included in ISO 639-5. <s> While most languages are given one code by the standard, twenty of the languages described have two three-letter codes, a "bibliographic" code (ISO 639-2/B), which is derived from the English name for the language and was a necessary legacy feature, and a "terminological" code (ISO 639-2/T), which is derived from the native name for the language and resembles the language's two-letter code in ISO 639-1. <s> There were originally 22 B codes; scc and scr are now deprecated. <s> The codes in ISO 639-2 have a variety of "scopes of denotation", or types of meaning and use, some of which are described in more detail below. <s> The collective language codes in ISO 639-2 are listed below.
simple: ISO 639 is a set of international standards that lists short codes for language names. <s> First there was ISO 639-1. <s> To list more languages, ISO 639-2 was made. <s> Later versions include ISO 639-3 and ISO 639-5. <s> The following is a complete list of three-letter ISO 639-2 codes. <s> Where two ISO 639-2 codes are given in the table, the one with the asterisk is the bibliographic code (B code) and the other is the terminological code (T code). <s> The list below shows all the codes in ISO 639-2.

title: La Roque-Alric
complex: La Roque-Alric is a commune in the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in southeastern France.
simple: La Roque-Alric is a commune of 54 people (1999). <s> It is in the region Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur in the Vaucluse department in the south of France.

title: Federal Capital Territory (Pakistan)
complex: The Federal Capital Territory (FCT) around Karachi was the original capital territory of Pakistan. <s> The FCT was created in 1948 from the city of Karachi and surrounding areas as the location for Pakistan's capital following independence. <s> The FCT was bordered by the province of Sind to the northeast and the princely state of Las Bela to the northwest with the Arabian Sea to the south.
simple: The Federal Capital Territory (FCT) around Karachi was the original Capital territory of Pakistan. <s> The FCT was created in 1948 from the city of Karachi and surrounding areas as the location for Pakistan's capital following independence. <s> The FCT was bordered by the province of Sind Province (1936–1955) to the northeast and the princely state of State of Las Bela to the northwest with the Arabian Sea to the south.

title: Cartigny-l'Épinay
complex: Cartigny-l'Épinay is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Cartigny-l'Épinay is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Venus (disambiguation)
complex: Venus is a planet in the Solar System, named after Venus (mythology), the Ancient Roman goddess of love.
simple: Venus is a planet in the Solar System.

title: Juris Ekmanis
complex: Juris Ekmanis (2 December 1941 – 9 April 2016) was the President of Latvian Academy of Sciences (2004—2012). <s> He was appointed Junior Research Associate at the Riga Polytechnical Institute from 1961 to 1986, and Professor from 1986 to 1994. <s> He was Visiting Professor at Cornell University (Ithaca), Iowa State University (Ames), University of California, Berkeley, United States in 1974 and at Manchester University in 1993. <s> In 1976 he became a Visiting Scientist at McGill University (Montreal). <s> In 1990 he became the Director of the Institute of the Physical Energetics at the Latvian Academy of Sciences, and he was the President of said academy from 2004 to 2012.
simple: Juris Ekmanis, (2 December 1941 – 9 April 2016) was a Latvian educator and physicist. <s> He was the President of Latvian Academy of Sciences from 2004 through 2012. <s> Ekmanis died of complications from a stroke in Riga, Latvia on 9 April 2016, aged 74. <s> He was appointed Junior Research Associate at the Riga Polytechnical Institute from 1961-1986, and Professor from 1986-1994. <s> He was Visiting Professor at Cornell University (Ithaca), Iowa State University (Ames), University of California, Berkeley, USA in 1974 and at Manchester University in 1993. <s> In 1976 he became a Visiting Scientist at McGill University (Montreal). <s> In 1990 he became the Director of the Institute of the Physical Energetics at the Latvian Academy of Sciences.

title: Fishers, Indiana
complex: Fishers is a city in Fall Creek and Delaware townships, Hamilton County, Indiana, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census the population was 76,794, and by 2017 the estimated population was 91,832. <s> A suburb of Indianapolis, Fishers has grown rapidly in recent decades: about 350 people lived there in 1963, 2,000 in 1980, and only 7,500 as recently as 1990.
simple: Fishers is a city in the state of Indiana, in the United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 76,794.

title: Brianna Wu
complex: Brianna Wu (born July 6, 1977) is an American video game developer and computer programmer. <s> She co-founded Giant Spacekat, an independent video game development studio, with Amanda Warner in Boston, Massachusetts. <s> She is also a blogger and podcaster on matters relating to the video game industry, and unsuccessfully ran for Congress as Massachusetts Representative in 8th district. <s> Wu has begun a second campaign for the 2020 election. <s> Wu lost to Lynch in the Democratic primary held on September 4, 2018, having received approximately 24% of the vote to Lynch's 70%. <s> Wu has begun a second campaign for the 2020 election.
simple: Brianna Wu (born July 6, 1977) is an American video game developer and computer programmer. <s> She co-founded Giant Spacekat, an independent video game development studio. <s> She is also a blogger and podcaster on matters relating to the video game industry. <s> Wu unsuccessfully ran against incumbent Stephen F. Lynch in Massachusetts for the 8th district for the U.S. House of Representatives in 2018. <s> Wu has begun a second campaign for the 2020 election.

title: Saint-Didier-de-Formans
complex: Saint-Didier-de-Formans is a commune in the Ain department in eastern France.
simple: Saint-Didier-de-Formans is a commune.

title: Lenham
complex: Lenham is a market village and civil parish in Kent situated on the southern edge of the North Downs, halfway between Maidstone and Ashford. <s> The picturesque square in the village has two public houses (one of which is a hotel), a couple of restaurants, and a tea-room.
simple: Lenham is a village and civil parish in Kent, England.

title: Schoep's Ice Cream
complex: Schoep's Ice Cream is an ice cream manufacturing company based in Madison, Wisconsin. <s> It is the largest independent ice cream manufacturer in Wisconsin. <s> Schoep's Ice Cream was founded by E.J. Schoephoester in 1928. <s> Schoephoester made and sold the ice cream in his grocery store. <s> By 1937 Schoep's Ice Cream had grown in local popularity, and E.B. Schoephoester sold his company in 1940 to Peter B. Thomsen, a butter maker. <s> The company has been kept in the Thomsen family, and as of 2008, it was owned in part by nineteen members of the Thomsen family. <s> As of 2018, four third-generation Thomsens work at the Madison headquarters. <s> Third-generation management includes Alan Thomsen, CEO; Eric Thomsen, VP of innovation and technology; Richard Thomsen, operations manager; and John Thomsen, food service sales and special events. <s> All of Schoep's Ice Cream is currently produced from a single factory located on Division Street in Madison, Wisconsin. <s> By 2008, Schoeps was producing 6,000 gallons of ice cream an hour and 2.5 million gallons a year. <s> With this high production rate, Schoeps has been recognized as the top producer of ice cream in the state of Wisconsin. <s> Due to its growth, in 2005 Schoep's opened a $7 million, 46000 sqft distribution center on Manufacturers Drive, near the Dane County Regional Airport. <s> This new facility featured space for 3,600 pallets and 14 loading-dock doors. <s> Before this facility was built, Schoeps had shipped all of their ice cream from two loading docks at their factory. <s> Schoep's Ice Cream under the Schoep's brand is not generally distributed outside of the Midwest United States, but instead as Walgreens brand Ice Cream and other private pack names. <s> Since 1993, Schoep's has been the sole producer of ice cream sold under the Walgreens label. <s> This contract accounts for more than 25 percent of Schoep's business.
simple: Schoep's Ice Cream is an ice cream manufacturing company based in Madison, Wisconsin. <s> Schoep's Ice Cream was founded by E.J. Schoephoester in 1928. <s> Schoephoester produced and sold the ice cream in his grocery store. <s> By 1937 Schoep's Ice Cream had become well known locally and E. B. Schoephoester sold his company to Peter B. Thomsen, a butter maker. <s> The company has been kept in the Thomsen family, and as of 2008 it was owned in part by nineteen members of the Thomsen family. <s> All of Schoep's Ice Cream is currently produced from a single factory located on Helena Street in Madison, Wisconsin. <s> As of 2008 Schoep's was producing 6,000 gallons of ice cream an hour and 2.5 million gallons a year. <s> With this high production rate, Schoep's has been recognized as the top producer of ice cream in the state of Wisconsin. <s> Due to this growth, in 2005, Schoep's opened a $7 million, 46,000-square-foot distribution center on Manufacturers Drive, near the Dane County Regional Airport. <s> This new facility features space for 3,600 pallets and 14 loading-dock doors. <s> Before this facility was built, Schoep's had shipped all of their ice cream from two loading docks at their factory. <s> Schoep's is not well known around the United States as Schoep's Ice Cream, but as Walgreens brand Ice Cream. <s> Since 1993 Schoep's has been the sole producer of ice cream sold under the Walgreens label. <s> This contract accounts for more than 25 percent of Schoep's business.

title: Assumption College (Thailand)
complex: Assumption College (sometimes called "Assumption Bang Rak", "Assumption Krung Thep", "อ ส ช" ) is a private Catholic boys school in Bangkok, Thailand. <s> The school, founded by Rev. Father Emile August Colombet on 16 February 1885, is the first school founded by the Gabrielite Brothers in Thailand. <s> Assumption College is the third-oldest boys school in Thailand. <s> The school provides education for students from grades 1 through 12. <s> Matriculation, especially in the first grade, is highly competitive. <s> Assumption College has a long list of distinguished former pupils including four Prime Ministers of Thailand, 15 privy counselors, and three pupils among Thailand's 10 Richest. <s> Assumption College is the one of four schools which participates in Jaturamitr Samakkee, a traditional football match by the four oldest boys' schools in Thailand: Suankularb Wittayalai School, Debsirin School, Bangkok Christian College, and Assumption College. <s> Father Colombet's school was in an ordinary wooden house. <s> Classes at the beginning were small; his first student was a Chinese-Thai, Siew Meng Tek. <s> The number of students steadily increased, and today more than 51,000 boys have been educated at Assumption College.
simple: Assumption College , is a private Catholic school for boys in Thailand. <s> Assumption College is in Bang Rak, Bangkok. <s> It was founded in 1885 by Father Emile August Colombet, and is the third-oldest school in Thailand. <s> The list of graduates includes four former Prime Ministers of Thailand, several businessmen, fifteens privy counselors, etc. <s> The school is one of the four schools in Jaturamitr Samakkee, a traditional football match by four oldest boys' schools in Thailand including Suankularb Wittayalai School, Debsirin School and Bangkok Christian College. <s> A lot of students are Chinese Thais and the first student of school name Mr. Siew Meng Tek is also Chinese-Thai. <s> As of today, more than 50,000 students have been educated at Assumption College.

title: Argenteuil-sur-Armançon
complex: Argenteuil-sur-Armançon is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Argenteuil-sur-Armançon is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Florida's Turnpike
complex: Florida's Turnpike, designated as unsigned State Road 91 (SR 91), is a toll road in the U.S. state of Florida, maintained by Florida's Turnpike Enterprise (FTE). <s> Spanning approximately 309 mi along a northwest–southeast axis, the turnpike is in two sections. <s> The SR 91 mainline runs roughly 265 mi , from its southern terminus at an interchange with Interstate 95 (I-95) in Miami Gardens to an interchange with I-75 in Wildwood at its northern terminus. <s> The Homestead Extension of Florida's Turnpike (abbreviated HEFT and designated as unsigned SR 821) continues from the southern end of the mainline for another 48 mi to US Highway 1 (US 1) in Florida City. <s> The slogan for the road is "The Less Stressway". <s> The mainline opened in stages between 1957 and 1964, while the extension was completed in 1974. <s> The turnpike runs through Miami, Fort Lauderdale, and West Palm Beach, where it parallels I-95, and through Orlando, where it crosses I-4. <s> Florida's Turnpike is one of the busiest highways in the country. <s> The operation of Sunshine State Parkway gas stations and service centers was originally bid out under separate contracts, and as a result, differing petroleum brands operated concurrently along the parkway, with varying levels of service and pricing.
simple: Florida's Turnpike (TPK), designated as the Ronald Reagan Turnpike is a north–south toll road. <s> This has the hidden designation of State Road 91 (SR 91). <s> The Turnpike itself has two sections. <s> The first is the Mainline, a 265 mi route from the Golden Glades Interchange (north of Miami) to Wildwood. <s> The second is the 48 mi long Homestead Extension of Florida's Turnpike (HEFT). <s> It was opened in stages between 1957 and 1964. <s> This was completed in 1974. <s> It starts from U.S. Route 1 in Florida City, running through Miami, Fort Lauderdale. <s> At West Palm Beach, it runs parallel to Interstate 95, and then in Orlando, it crosses Interstate 4, to its northern end at Interstate 75 near Wildwood. <s> Florida's Turnpike is considered one of the busiest highways in the country (according to the IBBTA, the highway is the nation's 3rd most heavily traveled toll road).

title: Ancyloxypha numitor
complex: Ancyloxypha numitor, the least skipper, is a North American butterfly in the family Hesperiidae. <s> They have a weak, Satyrinae-like flight. <s> The least skipper's rounded wings and slender body are distinctive. <s> Their checkered antennae have no hooks. <s> The upper sides of the forewings are dark brownish black sometimes having a patch of orange. <s> The hindwing is orange with a broad dark brownish-black band surrounding the orange area completely. <s> The underside of the wings is orange with the hindwing discal area being a little bit darker. <s> The hindwing veins are whitish. <s> Its wingspan ranges from 17 to 26 mm. <s> There are four similar species in the least skipper's range. <s> They are the European skipper ("Thymelicus lineola"), the tropical least skipper ("Ancyloxypha arene"), the orange skipperling ("Copaeodes aurantiaeca"), and the southern skipperling ("Copaeodes minima"). <s> The tropical least skipper has more orange on the upper side of the wings than the least skipper, and the underside of the wings has very small black marginal spots. <s> The least skipper favors damp or wet habitats with tall grasses. <s> Adults may be noticed on the wing from May to September in the north and February to December in the south. <s> It may be seen all year in southern Florida. <s> To find females, males will patrol through stands of grass. <s> Females lay their eggs singly on the host plant. <s> The pale yellow eggs will soon form an orange-red ring round the middle. <s> The larvae make a nest by rolling up a single blade of grass or by using silk to tie together multiple leaves. <s> The variable larva is grass green with four white pairs of distinct wax glands along the subventral area of the abdomen. <s> The head is either brown or tan and is usually darker in the center. <s> The collar has a white stripe and a black stripe. <s> The cream pupa has brownish colored markings. <s> It overwinters as a larva in the third or fourth instar. <s> It has two to four broods per year.
simple: The least skipper ("Ancyloxypha numitor") is a butterfly in the family Hesperiidae. <s> They have a weak, bouncy flight. <s> The least skipper has rounded wings and a skinny body. <s> Their antennae are checkered and have no hooks. <s> The upper side of the top wing is dark brown, sometimes having orange on it. <s> The bottom wing is orange with a dark brown border around it. <s> The underside of the wings is bright orange. <s> The bottom wing's veins are a whitish color. <s> There are some species of butterflies that are similar to the least skipper. <s> They are the European skipper ("Thymelicus lineola"), the tropical least skipper ("Ancyloxypha arene"), the orange skipperling ("Copaeodes aurantiaeca"), and the southern skipperling ("Copaeodes minima"). <s> The least skipper can be found in damp or wet habitats with tall grasses. <s> In the northern part of the its range, adults may be seen from May to September. <s> In the southern part of its range, adults can be found from February to December. <s> It may be seen all year in southern Florida. <s> Males find females by looking for them in tall grasses. <s> Females lay their eggs one at a time on the caterpillar's host plant (the plant that the caterpillar feeds on). <s> The eggs are pale yellow. <s> The caterpillar makes a nest of grass and silk. <s> It has four pairs of white wax glands on the abdomen near the underside. <s> The head is brown or tan. <s> It is usually darker in the center. <s> The collar (the area between where the head and the body connect) has a white stripe and a black stripe. <s> The chrysalis is a cream color and has brown markings. <s> The least skipper has 2-4 broods each year.

title: Étienne Tshisekedi
complex: Étienne Tshisekedi wa Mulumba (14 December 1932 – 1 February 2017) was a Congolese politician and the leader of the Union for Democracy and Social Progress (UDPS), the main opposing political party in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). <s> A long-time opposition leader, he served as Prime Minister of the country (then called Zaire) on three brief occasions: in 1991, 1992–1993, and 1997. <s> On 15 February 1982, Tshisekedi co-founded the Union for Democracy and Social Progress (UDPS). <s> The party remains popular in Congo's capital Kinshasa, the two Kasai and Bas-Congo provinces as well as other provinces, with its main goal being a non-violent change to democratic rule. <s> On 24 January 2017, Tshisekedi left the DRC to travel to Belgium for medical treatment. <s> The 84-year-old died a week later on 1 February in Brussels.
simple: Étienne Tshisekedi wa Mulumba (14 December 1932 – 1 February 2017) was a Congolese politician. <s> He was the leader of the Union for Democracy and Social Progress (UDPS). <s> He served as the Prime Minister of Zaire three times: in 1991, 1992–1993 and 1997. <s> Tshisekedi died from a pulmonary embolism on 1 February 2017 in Brussels, Belgium at the age of 84.

title: Balod district
complex: Balod district of Chhattisgarh state has its headquarters at Balod.
simple: Balod district is a district of Chhattisgarh, India. <s> The district headquarters is Balod.

title: Swisher, Iowa
complex: Swisher is a city in Johnson County, Iowa, United States. <s> It is part of the Iowa City, Iowa Metropolitan Statistical Area.
simple: Swisher is a city of Iowa in the United States. <s> It is in Johnson County.

title: Dana Delany
complex: Dana Welles Delany (born March 13, 1956) is an American actress, producer, and activist. <s> After appearing in small roles early in her career, Delany received her breakthrough role as Colleen McMurphy on the ABC television drama "China Beach" (1988–1991), for which she twice received the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series in 1989 and 1992. <s> She received further recognition for her appearances in the films "Light Sleeper" (1992), "Tombstone" (1993), "Exit to Eden" (1994), "" (1995), "Fly Away Home" (1996), "True Women" (1997), and "Wide Awake" (1998).
simple: Dana Welles Delany (born March 13, 1956) is an Emmy Award-winning American movie and television actress. <s> She is well known for her role as Colleen McMurphy on the ABC television show "China Beach" (1988–1991), "Katherine Mayfair" on "Desperate Housewives" (2007–2010) and "Megan Hunt" on "Body of Proof" (2011–present).

title: Campigneulles-les-Petites
complex: Campigneulles-les-Petites is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Campigneulles-les-Petites is a commune.

title: Somniloquy
complex: Somniloquy or sleep-talking is a parasomnia that refers to talking aloud while asleep. <s> It can be quite loud, ranging from simple mumbling sounds to loud shouts and long, frequently inarticulate speeches, and can occur many times during a sleep cycle.
simple: Somniloquy is a sleep disorder.

title: Kelvedon Hatch
complex: Kelvedon Hatch is a village in civil parish of Kelvedon Hatch, in the Borough of Brentwood in south Essex, England. <s> It is situated just north of Pilgrims Hatch, approximately 4 mi to the north of Brentwood and is surrounded by Metropolitan Green Belt.
simple: Kelvedon Hatch is a village and civil parish in Brentwood District, Essex, England.

title: Cindy Hyde-Smith
complex: Cindy Hyde-Smith (born May 10, 1959) is an American politician serving as the junior United States Senator from Mississippi, in office since 2018. <s> A member of the Republican Party, she was previously the Mississippi Commissioner of Agriculture and Commerce and a member of the Mississippi State Senate. <s> On March 21, 2018, Governor Phil Bryant announced his intention to appoint Hyde-Smith to the United States Senate seat being vacated due to the resignation of Thad Cochran. <s> Hyde-Smith was sworn into office on April 9, 2018. <s> She is the first woman to represent Mississippi in Congress. <s> Hyde-Smith was a candidate in the 2018 U.S. Senate special election for the remainder of Cochran's term, which expires in 2021. <s> She finished first in the top-two general election on November 6, 2018, but did not receive more than 50% of the vote, thus advancing to a November 27 special runoff election versus Mike Espy. <s> Hyde-Smith won the runoff election, becoming the first woman elected to Congress from Mississippi.
simple: Cindy Hyde-Smith (born May 10, 1959) is an American politician. <s> She is the junior United States Senator from Mississippi since 2018. <s> She served as the Mississippi Commissioner of Agriculture and Commerce from 2012 to 2018. <s> Governor Phil Bryant announced on March 21, 2018 that he will appoint Hyde-Smith to the United States Senate seat that was vacated by Thad Cochran on April 1, 2018. <s> She is the first female member of Congress from Mississippi. <s> On November 6, 2018, Hyde-Smith and Democrat Mike Espy advanced to a run-off election held on November 27, where she beat Espy in the election.

title: Billy the Exterminator
complex: Billy the Exterminator (formerly The Exterminators) is an American reality television series which aired on the A&E network. <s> The show followed the professional life of William "Billy" Bretherton, an expert in the field of pest control and the proprietor of Vexcon Animal and Pest Control in Benton, Louisiana, which serves the Shreveport-Bossier metropolitan area. <s> Bretherton, a former Senior Airman in the United States Air Force, had previously been featured on the Discovery Channel's "Dirty Jobs" series on the season 1 episode "Vexcon", and the season 2 episode "Termite Controller".
simple: The Exterminators (renamed "Billy the Exterminator" in 2010) is an American television program. <s> The program follows Vexcon employees, "Billy" and "Ricky Breatherton" as they try to rid pests and unwanted animals from clients homes and businesses in Louisiana.

title: Mitsuko Uchida
complex: Dame Mitsuko Uchida, DBE (内田光子 ) , born 20 December 1948) is a classical pianist and conductor, born in Japan and naturalised in Britain, particularly noted for her interpretations of Mozart and Schubert. <s> Born in Atami, a seaside town close to Tokyo, Japan, Uchida moved to Vienna, Austria, with her diplomat parents when she was 12 years old, after her father was named the Japanese ambassador to Austria. <s> She enrolled at the Vienna Academy of Music to study with Richard Hauser, and later Wilhelm Kempff and Stefan Askenase, and remained in Vienna to study when her father was transferred back to Japan after five years. <s> She gave her first Viennese recital at the age of 14 at the Vienna Musikverein. <s> She also studied with Maria Curcio, the last and favourite pupil of Artur Schnabel. <s> In 1969 Uchida won the first prize in the Beethoven Competition in Vienna and in 1970 the second prize in the International Chopin Piano Competition. <s> In 1975, she won second prize in the Leeds Piano Competition. <s> She is an acclaimed interpreter of the works of Mozart, Beethoven, Schubert, Chopin, Debussy and Schoenberg. <s> She has recorded all of Mozart's piano sonatas (a project that won the Gramophone Award in 1989), and concerti, the latter with the English Chamber Orchestra, conducted by Jeffrey Tate. <s> Her recording of the Schoenberg Piano Concerto with Pierre Boulez won another Gramophone Award.
simple: Dame Mitsuko Uchida, DBE (内田光子, Uchida Mitsuko) (born Atami, Japan, December 20, 1948) is a Japanese pianist who lives in London. <s> Mitsuko Uchida was born in Atami, a seaside town near Tokyo, Japan. <s> When she was 12 her father became the Japanese ambassador to Austria, so the family moved to Vienna. <s> She studied at the Vienna Academy of Music. <s> Her teachers were Richard Hauser, and later Wilhelm Kempff and Stefan Askenase. <s> After five years, her father went back to Japan, but she stayed in Vienna. <s> She gave her first recital when she was 14 in the Vienna Musikverein. <s> In 1969 she won the first prize in the Beethoven Competition in Vienna and in 1970 the second prize in the International Frederick Chopin Piano Competition. <s> Then, in 1975, she won second prize in the Leeds Piano Competition. <s> She is well known for her playing of the works of Mozart, Beethoven, Schubert, Chopin, Debussy and Schoenberg. <s> She played all the Mozart Piano Concertos with the Cleveland Orchestra. <s> Her recordings include all of Mozart's piano sonatas and concertos, and won many awards for her recordings.

title: List of heads of state of India
complex: This is a list of the heads of state of India, from the independence of India in 1947 to the present day. <s> The current head of state of India is Ram Nath Kovind, elected in 2017 after being nominated by BJP, the party run by Prime Minister Narendra Modi. <s> From 1947 to 1950 the head of state under the Indian Independence Act 1947 was King of India, who was also the Monarch of the United Kingdom and of the other Dominions of the British Commonwealth. <s> The monarch was represented in India by a Governor-General. <s> India became a republic under the Constitution of 1950 and the Monarch and Governor-General were replaced by a ceremonial President. <s> The succession to the throne was the same as the succession to the British throne. <s> The Governor-General was the representative of the Monarch in India and exercised most of the powers of the Monarch. <s> The Governor-General was appointed for an indefinite term, serving at the pleasure of the Monarch. <s> After the passage of the Statute of Westminster 1931, the Governor-General was appointed solely on the advice of the Cabinet of India without the involvement of the British government. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Chief Justice served as Officer Administering the Government. <s> Under the Constitution, of the Republic of India, the President replaced the Monarch as ceremonial head of state. <s> The President is elected by the Electoral College for a five-year term. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Vice-President serves as Acting President.
simple: This is a list of the heads of state of India, from the independence of India in 1947 to the present day. <s> The current head of state of India is Ram Nath Kovind, elected in 2017 after being nominated by BJP, the party run by Prime Minister Narendra Modi. <s> From 1947 to 1950 the head of state under the Indian Independence Act 1947 was King of India, who was also the Monarch of the United Kingdom and of the other Dominions of the British Commonwealth. <s> The monarch was represented in India by a Governor-General. <s> India became a republic under the Constitution of 1950 and the Monarch and Governor-General were replaced by a ceremonial President. <s> The succession to the throne was the same as the succession to the British throne. <s> The Governor-General was the representative of the Monarch in India and exercised most of the powers of the Monarch. <s> The Governor-General was appointed for an indefinite term, serving at the pleasure of the Monarch. <s> After the passage of the Statute of Westminster 1931, the Governor-General was appointed solely on the advice of the Cabinet of India without the involvement of the British government. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Chief Justice served as Officer Administering the Government. <s> Under the Constitution, of the Republic of India, the President replaced the Monarch as ceremonial head of state. <s> The President is elected by the Electoral College for a five-year term. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Vice-President serves as Acting President.

title: Oshima Province
complex: Oshima Province (渡島国 , Oshima-no kuni ) was a short-lived province located in Hokkaidō. <s> It corresponded to the southern part of today's Oshima and Hiyama Subprefectures <s> After 1869, the northern Japanese island was known as Hokkaido; and regional administrative subdivisions were identified, including Oshima Province.
simple: Oshima Province (渡島国, Oshima-no kuni) was a old province of Japan on the island of Hokkaido. <s> After 1869, the northern Japanese island was known as Hokkaido. <s> Regional subdivisions were established.

title: Manuel Lanzini
complex: Manuel Lanzini (] ; born 15 February 1993) is an Argentine professional footballer who plays as an attacking midfielder for English club West Ham United and the Argentina national team. <s> He has previously played for River Plate and Fluminense. <s> He is described as possessing phenomenal dribbling ability, as well as fantastic acceleration and vision and the ability to ghost past defenders.
simple: Manuel Lanzini (born 15 February 1993) is an Argentine football player. <s> He plays for River Plate.

title: Wessex Sound Studios
complex: Wessex Sound Studios was a recording studio located in Highbury New Park, London, England. <s> Many renowned popular music artists recorded there, including Sex Pistols, King Crimson, The Clash, Theatre of Hate, XTC, The Sinceros, Queen, Talk Talk, The Rolling Stones, Pete Townshend and The Damned . <s> The property was sold to a residential development company in 2003.
simple: Wessex Sound Studios was a recording studio in Highbury New Park, London, England. <s> Many renowned music artists recorded there, including The Sex Pistols, King Crimson, The Clash, Theatre of Hate, XTC, The Sinceros, Queen, Talk Talk and The Rolling Stones. <s> It was sold to a residential development company in 2003.

title: Accolay, Yonne
complex: Accolay is a former commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France. <s> On 1 January 2017, it was merged with Cravant into the new commune of Deux Rivières.
simple: Accolay is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Wittenberg (district)
complex: Wittenberg is a district in the east of Saxony-Anhalt, Germany. <s> Neighboring districts are (from west clockwise) Anhalt-Bitterfeld, the district-free city of Dessau-Roßlau, the districts of Potsdam-Mittelmark, Teltow-Fläming and Elbe-Elster in Brandenburg, and the district of Nordsachsen in the Free State of Saxony. <s> In 1994 the district was merged with the district of Jessen and a small part of the district of Gräfenhainichen. <s> In 2007, 27 municipalities from the former district Anhalt-Zerbst were added to the district of Wittenberg. <s> After the resolution of 6 October 2005, as part of municipal reform, the (then) 27 towns and municipalities of the former Verwaltungsgemeinschaften of Coswig and Wörlitzer Winkel, formerly in the Anhalt-Zerbst district, were assigned to Wittenberg district on 1 July 2007.
simple: Wittenberg is a district ("Kreis") in the east of Saxony-Anhalt, Germany. <s> In 1994 the district was merged with the district of Jessen and a small part of the district of Gräfenhainichen. <s> In 2007, 27 municipalities from the former district Anhalt-Zerbst were added to the district of Wittenberg. <s> After the resolution of 6 October 2005, as part of municipal reform, the 27 towns and communities of the Verwaltungsgemeinschaften of Coswig and Wörlitzer Winkel, formerly in the Anhalt-Zerbst district, were assigned to Wittenberg district on 1 July 2007.

title: Allan Clarke (singer)
complex: Harold Allan Clarke (5 April 1942, Salford, Lancashire, England) is an English pop rock singer, who was one of the founding members and the original lead singer of The Hollies. <s> He retired from performing in 1999, and was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2010.
simple: Harold Allan Clarke (born 5 April 1942) is a retired English pop rock singer. <s> He was one of the founding members and the original lead singer of The Hollies. <s> He retired from performing in 1999. <s> He was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2010.

title: Sense of balance
complex: The sense of balance or equilibrioception is one of the physiological senses related to balance. <s> It helps prevent humans and animals from falling over when standing or moving. <s> Balance is the result of a number of body systems working together: the eyes (visual system), ears (vestibular system) and the body's sense of where it is in space (proprioception) ideally need to be intact.
simple: Equilibrioception is the sense of balance. <s> This is what prevents a person or animal from falling over while walking or doing other physical activity.

title: Arrondissement of Riom
complex: The arrondissement of Riom is an arrondissement of France in the Puy-de-Dôme department in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> Since the January 2017 reorganization of the arrondissements of Puy-de-Dôme, it has 155 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Riom is an arrondissement of France. <s> It is part of the Puy-de-Dôme "département", Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region. <s> When the Puy-de-Dôme department was created in 1790, the "arrondissement" of Riom was part of that original department.

title: Lauderdale County, Alabama
complex: Lauderdale County is a county located in the northwestern corner of the U.S. state of Alabama. <s> As of the 2010 census the population was 92,709. <s> Its county seat is Florence. <s> Its name is in honor of Colonel James Lauderdale, of Tennessee.
simple: Lauderdale County is a county in the northwestern corner of the U.S. state of Alabama. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 92,709. <s> The county seat is Florence. <s> The name is in honor of Colonel James Lauderdale, of Tennessee.

title: 1924 Winter Olympics
complex: The 1924 Winter Olympics, officially known as the I Olympic Winter Games , were a winter multi-sport event which was held in 1924 in Chamonix, France. <s> Originally held in association with the 1924 Summer Olympics, the sports competitions were held at the foot of Mont Blanc in Chamonix, and Haute-Savoie, France between January 25 and February 5, 1924. <s> The Games were organized by the French Olympic Committee, and were originally reckoned as the "International Winter Sports Week." <s> With the success of the event, it was retroactively designated by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) as the I Olympic Winter Games. <s> Athletes from 16 nations competed in the first Winter Olympic Games. <s> Germany was banned from competing in the games, and instead hosted a series of games called Deutsche Kampfspiele.
simple: The 1924 Winter Olympics, officially known as the I Olympic Winter Games, were held in 1924 in Chamonix, Haute-Savoie, Europe (FRANCE) between 30 January and 2 February 1922. <s> At first, the games were called "Semaine Internationale des Sports d'Hiver" ("International Winter Sports Week") and were held as part of the 1924 Summer Olympics. <s> It was later decided by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) that the Games would be called the I Olympic Winter Games. <s> Athletes from 16 nations competed in the first Winter Olympic Games.

title: Shu Kamo
complex: Shu Kamo (加茂 周 , Kamo Shu , born October 29, 1939) is a former Japanese football player and manager. <s> He managed Japan national team. <s> Kamo was born in Ashiya on October 29, 1939. <s> After graduation from Kwansei Gakuin University, he played for Yanmar Diesel from 1965 to 1967.
simple: Shu Kamo (born 29 October 1939) is a retired Japanese football player. <s> He played for Yanmar Diesel.

title: Parable of the Mustard Seed
complex: The Parable of the Mustard Seed is one of the shorter parables of Jesus. <s> It appears in Matthew (13:31–32), Mark (4:30–32), and Luke (13:18–19). <s> In the Gospels of Matthew and Luke, it is immediately followed by the Parable of the Leaven, which shares this parable's theme of the Kingdom of Heaven growing from small beginnings. <s> It also appears in the non-canonical Gospel of Thomas (verse 20). <s> I. Howard Marshall writes that the parable "suggests the growth of the kingdom of God from tiny beginnings to worldwide size." <s> The Parable of the Leaven (which in the Gospels of Matthew and Luke immediately follows) shares this theme of large growth from small beginnings. <s> As with the Parable of the Sower, which in "Matthew" and "Mark" occurs earlier in the same chapter, the man sowing the seed represents Jesus, and the plant is the Kingdom of God.
simple: The Parable of the Mustard Seed is one of the parables of Jesus. <s> It is found in three of the Gospels of the New Testament: Gospel of Matthew (13:31–32), Gospel of Mark (4:30–32), and Gospel of Luke (13:18–19). <s> In Matthew and Luke, this parable is followed by the Parable of the Leaven. <s> The Parable of the Leaven also has a theme about the Kingdom of Heaven growing from small beginnings. <s> A version of the parable also occurs in the non-canonical Gospel of Thomas 20. <s> The parables from Mark and Luke are similar.

title: Chuckle Brothers
complex: The Chuckle Brothers were an English comedy double act comprising Barry David Elliott (24 December 1944 – 5 August 2018) and Paul Harman Elliott (born 18 October 1947). <s> They were known for their BBC children's programme "ChuckleVision", which celebrated its twenty-first series with a 2010 stage tour entitled "An Audience with the Chuckle Brothers". <s> The comedy of the Chuckle Brothers usually derived from slapstick, wordplay and other visual gags, and their catchphrases included "To me, to you" and "Oh dear, oh dear". <s> The brothers were born in Rotherham to Amy and James Patton Elliott, in 1944 and 1947. <s> Their father was a Gang Show performer whose stage name was Gene Patton; he worked with the 18-year-old Peter Sellers in 1943 in The No. 10 Gang and gave performances in London, Orkney and the Hebrides, Iceland, the Far East, India, and Burma. <s> Their two older brothers, Jimmy and Brian, are known professionally as the Patton Brothers and have appeared in "ChuckleVision", Jimmy as the nameless character known colloquially as "No Slacking", and Brian as another unnamed character known as "Getoutofit". <s> On 5 August 2018, Barry died after a period of ill health. <s> Paul grieved Barry's death stating "I've not just lost my brother, I've lost my theatrical partner of many, many years and my very best friend."
simple: The Chuckle Brothers were an English children's entertainment comedy double act, comprising Barry David Elliott (24 December 1944 – 5 August 2018) and Paul Harman Elliott (born 18 October 1947). <s> They were known for their work on their BBC show "ChuckleVision". <s> The comedy of the Chuckle Brothers usually were slapstick and other visual gags, and their catchphrases included "To me, to you" and "Oh dear, oh dear". <s> Their older brothers, Jimmy and Brian, were the comedy duo Patton Brothers. <s> On 5 August 2018, Barry died after a long battle with bone cancer, aged 73.

title: Wisbech
complex: Wisbech is a Fenland market town, inland port and civil parish in the Fens of Cambridgeshire, England. <s> It had a population of 31,573 in 2011.
simple: Wisbech is a town in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom.

title: Catamarca Province
complex: Catamarca (] ) is a province of Argentina, located in the northwest of the country. <s> The province had a population of 334,568 as per the 2001 census , and covers an area of 102,602 km. <s> Its literacy rate is 95.5%. <s> Neighbouring provinces are (clockwise, from the north): Salta, Tucumán, Santiago del Estero, Córdoba, and La Rioja. <s> To the west it borders the country of Chile. <s> The capital is San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca, usually shortened to Catamarca. <s> Other important cities include Andalgalá, Tinogasta, and Belén.
simple: Catamarca is a Province of Argentina. <s> It is in the northwest of the country. <s> The province has 334,568 people as per the 2001 census. <s> To the west, it borders Chile. <s> The capital is San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca, usually shortened to Catamarca. <s> Other important cities are Andalgalá, Tinogasta, and Belén.

title: Pericles
complex: Pericles ( ; "Periklēs", ] in Classical Attic; c. 495 – 429 BC) was a prominent and influential Greek statesman, orator and general of Athens during its golden age – specifically the time between the Persian and Peloponnesian wars. <s> He was descended, through his mother, from the powerful and historically influential Alcmaeonid family. <s> Pericles had such a profound influence on Athenian society that Thucydides, a contemporary historian, acclaimed him as "the first citizen of Athens". <s> Pericles turned the Delian League into an Athenian empire, and led his countrymen during the first two years of the Peloponnesian War. <s> The period during which he led Athens, roughly from 461 to 429 BC, is sometimes known as the "Age of Pericles", though the period thus denoted can include times as early as the Persian Wars, or as late as the next century. <s> Pericles promoted the arts and literature; it is principally through his efforts that Athens acquired the reputation of being the educational and cultural center of the ancient Greek world. <s> He started an ambitious project that generated most of the surviving structures on the Acropolis (including the Parthenon). <s> This project beautified and protected the city, exhibited its glory, and gave work to the people. <s> Pericles also fostered Athenian democracy to such an extent that critics call him a populist. <s> He, along with several members of his family, succumbed to the Plague of Athens in 429 BC, which weakened the city-state during a protracted conflict with Sparta. <s> Pericles, following Athenian custom, was first married to one of his closest relatives, with whom he had two sons, Paralus and Xanthippus, but around 445 BC, Pericles divorced his wife. <s> He offered her to another husband, with the agreement of her male relatives. <s> The name of his first wife is not known; the only information about her is that she was the wife of Hipponicus, before being married to Pericles, and the mother of Callias from this first marriage.
simple: Pericles or Perikles (ca. 495–429 BC, , meaning ""surrounded by glory"") was a prominent and influential statesman. <s> He also was an orator, and general of Athens. <s> He lived between the Persian and Peloponnesian wars. <s> He was descended, through his mother, from the Alcmaeonid family. <s> Pericles had great influence on Athenian society. <s> Thucydides, a contemporary historian, described him as "the first citizen of Athens". <s> Pericles turned the Delian League into an Athenian empire and led his countrymen during the first two years of the Peloponnesian War. <s> The period during which he led Athens, roughly from 461 to 429 BC, is sometimes known as the "Age of Pericles,". <s> This period though can include times as early as the Persian Wars, or as late as the next century. <s> Pericles promoted the arts and literature. <s> This was a chief reason Athens holds the reputation of being the educational and cultural centre of the ancient Greek world. <s> He started an ambitious project that built most of the surviving structures on the Acropolis (including the Parthenon). <s> This project made the city more beautiful., It also showed its glory, and gave work to the people. <s> Furthermore, Pericles fostered Athenian democracy to such an extent that critics call him a populist. <s> Pericles also got married and had 2 sons. <s> His wife's name is unknown.

title: WWE 2K14
complex: WWE 2K14 is a professional wrestling video game developed by Yuke's and published by 2K Sports for PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360. <s> It is the first game published by 2K Sports since Take-Two Interactive gained the license from THQ in a bankruptcy filing. <s> It is the sequel to "WWE '13" and it is succeeded by "WWE 2K15". <s> It is the first game in the "WWE 2K" series. <s> It was released on October 29, 2013 in North America, October 30 in Japan and November 1, 2013 in Europe. <s> It is the final WWE videogame that featured the scratch logo, first appeared in the Attitude Era, as the company introduced a new logo in 2014. <s> IGN gave the game an 8.7 out of 10 saying "It still lacks the brains to deliver competent AI and commentators, but "WWE 2K14" has more than enough brawn to make up for it. <s> 30 Years of Wrestlemania provides the strongest campaign backbone the series has had in a long time, the in-ring action is faster and more fluid than it's been in years, and thanks to "WWE 2K14"′ s continually expanding creation suite, we're swimming in more options than we ever knew we wanted. <s> It is indeed "time to play the game". <s> GameSpot rated the game a 6 out of 10, saying that the game was clunky, "It's a shame the wrestling isn't up to par in "WWE 2K14" because the elements surrounding it are so interesting... For anyone who grew up loving professional wrestling, be prepared to be swept away in a tide of nostalgia. <s> If only the core action could have been as compelling."
simple: WWE 2K14 is a professional wrestling video game developed by Yuke's & Visual Concepts and published by 2K Sports. <s> It is the first game in the WWE 2K video game series and the first WWE game to be released under 2K Sports since Take-Two acquired the license from THQ in a bankruptcy filing. <s> The game was released on October 29, 2013 in North America, October 30, 2013 in Japan and November 1, 2013 in both Europe and India. <s> IGN rated the game a 8.7 out of 10 and said "It still lacks the brains to deliver competent AI and commentators, but WWE 2K14 has more than enough brawn to make up for it. <s> 30 Years of Wrestlemania provides the strongest campaign backbone the series has had in a long time, the in-ring action is faster and more fluid than it’s been in years, and thanks to WWE 2K14′s continually expanding creation suite, we’re swimming in more options than we ever knew we wanted. <s> It is indeed “time to play the game.” <s> GameSpot gave the game a 6 out of 10 and said that the game was clunky, they stated "It’s a shame the wrestling isn’t up to par in WWE 2K14 because the elements surrounding it are so interesting...For anyone who grew up loving professional wrestling, be prepared to be swept away in a tide of nostalgia. <s> If only the core action could have been as compelling."

title: Nightmare disorder
complex: Nightmare disorder, also known as dream anxiety disorder, is a sleep disorder characterized by frequent nightmares. <s> The nightmares, which often portray the individual in a situation that jeopardizes their life or personal safety, usually occur during the REM stages of sleep. <s> Though most people have experienced at least one nightmare during their life, subjects with nightmare disorder experience them with a greater frequency. <s> The disorder's DSM-IV number is 307.47.
simple: Nightmare disorder, also known as "dream anxiety disorder", is a sleep disorder characterized by frequent nightmares. <s> The nightmares, which often portray the individual in a situation that jeopardizes their life or personal safety, usually occur during the second half of the sleeping process, called the REM stage. <s> Though such nightmares occur within many people, those with nightmare disorder experience them with a greater frequency. <s> The disorder's DSM-IV number is 307.47.

title: Tokaji
complex: Tokaji ( ] ) or Tokay is the name of the wines from the Tokaj wine region (also "Tokaj-Hegyalja wine region" or "Tokaj-Hegyalja") in Hungary or the adjoining Tokaj wine region in Slovakia. <s> This region is noted for its sweet wines made from grapes affected by noble rot, a style of wine which has a long history in this region.
simple: Tokaji is white wine from the Tokaj wine region in Hungary.

title: Cult of Domesticity
complex: The Culture of Domesticity (often shortened to Cult of Domesticity) or Cult of True Womanhood is a term used by historians to describe what they consider to have been a prevailing value system among the upper and middle classes during the 19th Century in the United States and the United Kingdom. <s> This value system emphasized new ideas of femininity, the woman's role within the home and the dynamics of work and family.
simple: The cult of domesticity, also known as the cult of true womanhood, is an opinion about women in the 1800s.

title: Servins
complex: Servins is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Servins is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Cognat-Lyonne
complex: Cognat-Lyonne is a commune in the department of Allier in Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes in central France.
simple: Cognat-Lyonne is a French commune. <s> It is in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Cayman Islands at the Olympics
complex: The Cayman Islands first competed at the Olympic Games in 1976, and has participated in each Summer Games since then, missing only the 1980 Summer Olympics by participating in the American-led boycott of the 1980 Summer Olympics. <s> The Cayman Islands have yet to win any Olympic medals. <s> After Jamaican independence in 1962, the Cayman Islands became a separate British Overseas Territory. <s> The Cayman Islands Olympic Committee was formed in 1973 and recognized in 1976. <s> The Cayman Islands made its Winter Olympic Games début at the 2010 Winter Olympics.
simple: The Cayman Islands were first at the Olympic Games in 1976. <s> They have been in each Games since, missing the 1980 Summer Olympics. <s> The Cayman Islands have not won an Olympic medal. <s> After Jamaican independence in 1962, the Cayman Islands became a separate British Overseas Territory. <s> The Cayman Islands Olympic Committee was formed in 1973 and recognized in 1976. <s> The first time the Cayman Islands competed in any Winter Olympic Games was at the 2010 Winter Olympics.

title: Hannes Löhr
complex: Johannes Löhr (5 July 1942 – 29 February 2016) was a German international football player and manager.
simple: Hannes Löhr (5 July 1942 – 29 February 2016) is a former German football player.

title: Safra Square
complex: Safra Square ( , "Kikar Safra") is the site of Jerusalem's city hall. <s> The compound was named for Jacob and Esther Safra, parents of the Lebanese-Jewish philanthropist Edmond J. Safra. <s> Construction began in 1988 but was only completed in 1993.
simple: Safra Square (, "Kikar Safra") is Jerusalem's City Hall public square. <s> It is named after Jacob and Esther Safra, the parents of Edmond J. Safra, a Jewish philanthropist who helped to renovate downtown Jerusalem.

title: Leighton Buzzard
complex: Leighton Buzzard is a town in Bedfordshire, England, near the Chiltern Hills and lying between Luton and Milton Keynes. <s> It adjoins Linslade and the name Leighton Linslade is sometimes used to refer to the combination of the two towns; parts of this article also apply to Linslade as well as Leedon.
simple: Leighton Buzzard is a town in Bedfordshire, England.

title: Benue River
complex: The Benue River , previously known as the Chadda River or Tchadda, is the major tributary of the Niger River. <s> The river is approximately 1400 km long and is almost entirely navigable during the summer months. <s> As a result, it is an important transportation route in the regions through which it flows. <s> It rises in the Adamawa Plateau of northern Cameroon, from where it flows west, and through the town of Garoua and Lagdo Reservoir, into Nigeria south of the Mandara mountains, and through Jimeta, Ibi and Makurdi before meeting the Niger River at Lokoja. <s> Large tributaries are the Faro River, the Gongola River and the Mayo Kébbi, which connects it with the Logone River (part of the Lake Chad system) during floods. <s> Other tributaries are Taraba River and River Katsina Ala.
simple: It is the major tributary of the Niger River. <s> The river is about 1,400 km long. <s> It is an important transportation route in the places it flows through. <s> It starts in the Adamawa Plateau of northern Cameroon. <s> It flows west, and through the town of Garoua and Lagdo Reservoir, into Nigeria south of the Mandara mountains. <s> Then it goes through Jimeta, Ibi and Makurdi before meeting the Niger at Lokoja. <s> Large tributaries are the Gongola River and the Mayo Kébbi. <s> Other tributaries are Taraba River and River Katsina Ala.

title: Turin King List
complex: The Turin King List, also known as the Turin Royal Canon, is an ancient Egyptian hieratic papyrus thought to date from the reign of Pharaoh Ramesses II, now in the Museo Egizio (Egyptian Museum) in Turin. <s> The papyrus is the most extensive list available of kings compiled by the ancient Egyptians, and is the basis for most chronology before the reign of Ramesses II. <s> The papyrus is believed to date from the reign of Ramesses II, during the middle of the New Kingdom, or the 19th Dynasty. <s> The beginning and ending of the list are now lost; there is no introduction, and the list does not continue after the 19th Dynasty. <s> The composition may thus have occurred at any subsequent time, from the reign of Ramesses II to as late as the 20th Dynasty. <s> The papyrus lists the names of rulers, the lengths of reigns in years, with months and days for some kings. <s> In some cases they are grouped together by family, which corresponds approximately to the dynasties of Manetho’s book. <s> The list includes the names of ephemeral rulers or those ruling small territories that may be unmentioned in other sources. <s> The list also is believed to contain kings from the 15th Dynasty, the Hyksos who ruled Lower Egypt and the River Nile delta. <s> The Hyksos rulers do not have cartouches (enclosing borders which indicate the name of a king), and a hieroglyphic sign is added to indicate that they were foreigners, although typically on King Lists foreign rulers are not listed. <s> The papyrus was originally a tax roll, but on its back is written a list of rulers of Egypt – including mythical kings such as gods, demi-gods, and spirits, as well as human kings. <s> That the back of an older papyrus was used may indicate that the list was not of great formal importance to the writer, although the primary function of the list is thought to have been as an administrative aid. <s> As such, the papyrus is less likely to be biased against certain rulers and is believed to include all the kings of Egypt known to its writers up to the 19th or 20th Dynasty. <s> The papyrus was found by the Italian traveler Bernardino Drovetti in 1820 at Luxor (Thebes), Egypt and was acquired in 1824 by the Egyptian Museum in Turin, Italy and was designated Papyrus Number 1874. <s> When the box in which it had been transported to Italy was unpacked, the list had disintegrated into small fragments. <s> Jean-Francois Champollion, examining it, could recognize only some of the larger fragments containing royal names, and produced a drawing of what he could decipher. <s> A reconstruction of the list was created to better understand it and to aid in research. <s> The Saxon researcher Gustav Seyffarth (1796–1885) re-examined the fragments, some only one square centimeter in size, and made a more complete reconstruction of the papyrus based only on the papyrus fibers, as he could not yet determine the meaning of the hieratic characters. <s> Subsequent work on the fragments was done by the Munich Egyptologist Jens Peter Lauth, which largely confirmed the Seyffarth reconstruction. <s> In 1997, prominent Egyptologist Kim Ryholt published a new and better interpretation of the list in his book, "The Political Situation in Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period c. 1800–1550 B.C." After another study of the papyrus, an updated version from Ryholt is expected. <s> Egyptologist Donald Redford has also studied the papyrus and has noted that although many of the list's names correspond to monuments and other documents, there are some discrepancies and not all of the names correspond, questioning the absolute reliability of the document for pre-Ramesses II chronology. <s> Despite attempts at reconstruction, approximately 50% of the papyrus remains missing. <s> This papyrus as presently constituted is 1.7 m long and 0.41 m wide, broken into over 160 fragments. <s> In 2009, previously unpublished fragments were discovered in the storage room of the Egyptian Museum of Turin, in good condition. <s> A new edition of the papyrus is expected. <s> The name Hudjefa, found twice in the papyrus, is now known to have been used by the royal scribes of the Ramesside era during the 19th dynasty of ancient Egypt when the scribes compiled king lists such as the royal table of Sakkara and the royal canon of Turin and the name of a deceased pharaoh was unreadable, damaged, or completely erased. <s> The papyrus is divided into eleven columns, distributed as follows. <s> The names and positions of several kings are still being disputed, since the list is so badly damaged.
simple: The Turin King List, also called the Turin Royal Canon, is a list of the kings of Egypt. <s> The list is now in the Egyptian Museum in Turin. <s> The papyrus is the most complete list of kings written by the Egyptians. <s> It is the basis working out the dates of kings before the rule of Ramesses II. <s> It is thought to date from the rule of Pharaoh Ramesses II. <s> The papyrus is believed to have been written in the time of Ramesses II, during the middle of the New Kingdom, or the 19th Dynasty. <s> The beginning and ending of the list are lost. <s> There is no introduction, and the list stops after the 19th Dynasty. <s> It may have been written at any later time, from Ramesses II to as late as the 20th Dynasty. <s> The papyrus lists the names of rulers, the lengths of their rule in years, with months and days for some kings. <s> In some cases they are grouped together by family. <s> This grouping is almost the same as the dynasties of Manetho’s book. <s> The list includes the names of kings who only ruled for a very short time, or those ruling small areas that may not be in listed in other sources. <s> The list also is believed to contain kings from the 15th Dynasty, the Hyksos who ruled Lower Egypt and the River Nile delta. <s> The Hyksos rulers do not have cartouches (borders around the name of a king). <s> They do have a hieroglyphic sign to show that they were foreigners. <s> The papyrus was a tax roll, but on its back is written a list of rulers of Egypt. <s> It includes the mythical kings such as gods, demi-gods, and spirits, as well as human kings. <s> As the papyrus was reused for the tax roll, it shows the list was not of great formal importance to the writer. <s> The list is thought to have been used as an administrative aid. <s> As such, the papyrus is not supposed to be biased against certain rulers and is believed to include all the kings of Egypt up through at least the 19th Dynasty. <s> The papyrus was found by the Italian traveler Bernardino Drovetti in 1820 at Luxor (Thebes). <s> In 1824 was put in the Egyptian Museum in Turin, Italy, and known as Papyrus Number 1874. <s> When the box in which it had been taken to Italy was unpacked, the list had broken up into small pieces. <s> Jean-Francois Champollion could read only some of the larger pieces which had royal names. <s> The Saxon researcher Gustav Seyffarth (1796–1885) looked carefully at some of the pieces, some only one square centimeter in size. <s> He made a more complete reconstruction of the papyrus based only on the papyrus fibers, as he could not read the hieratic characters. <s> Later work by the Munich Egyptologist Jens Peter Lauth, largely agreed with Seyffarth's work. <s> In 1997 Egyptologist Kim Ryholt published a new version of the list in his book, "The Political Situation in Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period c.1800-1550 B.C." Egyptologist Donald Redford has also studied the papyrus and has noted that many of the list’s names match historic monuments and other documents. <s> The list may not be completely accurate for pre-Ramesses II chronology. <s> About 50% of the papyrus is missing. <s> It is 1.7 m long and 0.41 m wide, broken into over 160 pieces. <s> In 2009 new pieces were discovered in the storage room of the Egyptian Museum of Turin, in good condition. <s> A new edition of the papyrus is expected. <s> The name Hudjefa, is listed twice in the papyrus. <s> The name is now known to have been used by the royal scribes of Ramesses II when the name of a king was unreadable or missing. <s> The papyrus is divided into eleven columns. <s> The names and positions of several kings are still uncertain as the list is so badly damaged.

title: Candlelight vigil
complex: A candlelight vigil or candlelit vigil is an outdoor assembly of people carrying candles, held after sunset in order to show support for a specific cause. <s> Such events are typically held either to protest the suffering of some marginalized group of people, or in memory of the dead.
