simple: A candlelight vigil is where a group of people mourn the loss of someone who was close to them.

title: Jump blues
complex: Jump blues is an up-tempo style of blues, usually played by small groups and featuring saxophone or brass instruments. <s> It was popular in the 1940s and was a precursor of rhythm and blues and rock and roll.
simple: Jump blues is a type of up-tempo blues music.

title: Poteau, Oklahoma
complex: Poteau is a city in, and county seat of, Le Flore County, Oklahoma, United States. <s> The population was 8,520 as of the 2010 census.
simple: Poteau is a city of Oklahoma in the United States. <s> It is the county seat of Le Flore County.

title: Symphony Center
complex: Symphony Center is a music complex located at 220 South Michigan Avenue in the Loop area of Chicago, Illinois. <s> Home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra; Chicago Symphony Chorus; Civic Orchestra of Chicago; and the Institute for Learning, Access, and Training; Symphony Center includes the 2,522-seat Orchestra Hall, which dates from 1904; Buntrock Hall, a rehearsal and performance space; Grainger Ballroom, an event space overlooking Michigan Avenue and the Art Institute of Chicago; a public multi-story rotunda; tesori restaurant; and administrative offices. <s> In June 1993, plans to significantly renovate and expand Orchestra Hall were approved and the $110 million project resulting in Symphony Center began in 1995 and was completed in 1997. <s> Orchestra Hall was designated a National Historic Landmark on April 19, 1994. <s> It has been listed on the National Register of Historic Places since 1978. <s> Built in 1904, Orchestra Hall was designed by renowned Chicago architect Daniel Burnham. <s> The new hall was specifically designed as a home for the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, which had previously performed in the larger Auditorium Theater.
simple: Symphony Center is a music complex in Chicago, Illinois. <s> The Symphony Center includes Orchestra Hall, which dates from 1904; Buntrock Hall, a rehearsal and performance space; a public multi-story rotunda; Rhapsody restaurant; and administrative offices. <s> Between 1995 and 1997 a lot of work to improve the buildings took place. <s> The Orchestra Hall was called a National Historic Landmark in 1994. <s> It was designed by Daniel Burnham.

title: Stratovolcano
complex: A stratovolcano, also known as a composite volcano, is a conical volcano built up by many layers (strata) of hardened lava, tephra, pumice and ash. <s> Unlike shield volcanoes, stratovolcanoes are characterized by a steep profile with a summit crater and periodic intervals of explosive eruptions and effusive eruptions, although some have collapsed summit craters called calderas. <s> The lava flowing from stratovolcanoes typically cools and hardens before spreading far, due to high viscosity.
simple: A stratovolcano is a tall, conical volcano built up by many layers (strata) of hardened lava, tephra, pumice, and volcanic ash. <s> Unlike shield volcanoes, stratovolcanoes have a steep slope and explosive eruptions every now and then.

title: Aryabhata (satellite)
complex: Aryabhatta was India's first satellite, named after the famous Indian astronomer of the same name.
simple: Aryabhata was India's first satellite. <s> It got its name from the Indian astronomer of the same name.

title: Castration
complex: Castration (also known as orchidectomy) is any action, surgical, chemical, or otherwise, by which an individual loses use of the testicles: the male gonad. <s> Surgical castration is bilateral orchidectomy (excision of both testes), and chemical castration uses pharmaceutical drugs to deactivate the testes. <s> Castration causes sterilization (preventing the castrated person or animal from reproducing); it also greatly reduces the production of certain hormones, such as testosterone. <s> Surgical castration in animals is often called neutering. <s> Castration was frequently used for religious or social reasons in certain cultures in Europe, South Asia, Africa, and East Asia. <s> After battles in some cases, winners castrated their captives or the corpses of the defeated to symbolize their victory and seize their "power". <s> Castrated men — eunuchs – were often admitted to special social classes and were used particularly to staff bureaucracies and palace households: in particular, the harem. <s> Castration also figured in a number of religious castration cults. <s> Other religions, such as Judaism, were strongly opposed to the practice. <s> The Leviticus Holiness code, for example, specifically excludes eunuchs or any males with defective genitals from the priesthood, just as castrated animals are excluded from sacrifice. <s> Eunuchs in China had been known to usurp power in many eras of Chinese history, most notably in the Later Han, late Tang and late Ming dynasties. <s> There are similar recorded Middle Eastern events. <s> Either surgical removal of both testicles or chemical castration may be carried out in the case of prostate cancer. <s> Testosterone-depletion treatment (either surgical removal of both testicles or chemical castration) is used to slow down the cancer, greatly reduce sex drive or interest in those with sexual drives, obsessions, or behaviors, or any combination of those that may be considered deviant. <s> Edward Gibbon's "Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire" reports castration of defeated foes at the hands of the Normans during their invasions of Sicily and Italy. <s> During the reign of Mu of the Zhou Dynasty (10th c. BCE) the Minister of Crime, Marquis Lu, reformed the law in 950 BC to make it easier for people to be sentenced to castration instead of death. <s> As long as the practice existed in China, not only were the testicles merely removed but castration included the severing of one's entire genitalia. <s> Both organs were cut off with a knife at the same time. <s> In Europe, when women were not permitted to sing in church or cathedral choirs in the Roman Catholic Church, boys were castrated to develop a special high voice and to prevent their voices breaking at puberty. <s> The first documents mentioning "castrati" are Italian church records from the 1550s. <s> In the baroque and classical music eras these singers were highly appreciated by opera composers as well. <s> Mozart's "Exultate Jubilate", Allegri's "Miserere" and other pieces from this period now sung by sopranos and countertenors were written for "castrati". <s> Some of the alto parts of Handel's Messiah were first sung by a "castrato". <s> "Castrati" include Farinelli, Senesino, Carestini, and Caffarelli. <s> The last true "castrato" was Alessandro Moreschi (1858–1922) who served in the Sistine Chapel Choir. <s> It was not until the late 19th century that the Roman Catholic Church officially condemned the production of "castrati". <s> In Modern times, the Mexican Javier Medina is the only professional opera singer that can perform as a castrato, since he suffered from an involuntary chemical castration, as a result from a cancer treatment that he had before he reached puberty. <s> Humans commonly castrate domestic animals not intended for breeding. <s> Domestic animals are usually castrated to avoid unwanted or uncontrolled reproduction; to reduce or prevent other manifestations of sexual behaviour such as defending the herd from humans and other threats, or intra-herd aggression (e.g. fighting between groups of entire (uncastrated) males of a species); or to reduce other consequences of sexual behavior that may make animal husbandry more difficult, such as boundary/fence/enclosure destruction when attempting to get to nearby females of the species. <s> Male horses are usually castrated (gelded) using emasculators, because stallions are rather aggressive and troublesome. <s> The same applies to male mules, although they are sterile. <s> Male cattle are castrated to improve fattening and docility in feedlots or for use as oxen. <s> Breeding individuals are kept entire and used for breeding: they may fetch higher prices when sold.
simple: Castration is any action, surgical, chemical, or otherwise, by which a male loses the functions of the testes or a female loses the functions of the ovaries. <s> Castration was frequently used in certain cultures of Europe, the Middle East, India, Africa and China, for political, religious or social reasons. <s> After battles in some cases, victors castrated their captives or the corpses of the defeated to symbolise their victory and 'seize' their power. <s> Castrated men — eunuchs — were often admitted to special social classes and were used particularly to staff bureaucracies and palace households: in particular, the harem. <s> Castration also figured in a number of religious castration cults. <s> Other religions, for example Judaism and Islam, were strongly opposed to the practice. <s> The "Leviticus Holiness code", for example, specifically excludes eunuchs or any males with defective genitals from the priesthood, just as castrated animals are excluded from sacrifice. <s> Eunuchs in China have been known to usurp power in many eras of Chinese history, most notably in the Later Han, late Tang and late Ming Dynasties. <s> There are similar recorded Middle Eastern events. <s> Unless both testicles are cancerous, only one is removed. <s> Edward Gibbon's famous work "Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire" reports castration of defeated foes at the hands of the Normans. <s> In China, to become a servant of the emperor, men had to be castrated. <s> In Europe, when females were not permitted to sing in church or cathedral choirs in the Roman Catholic Church, boys were sometimes castrated to prevent their voices breaking at puberty and to develop a special high voice. <s> The first documents mentioning castrati are Italian church records from the 1550s. <s> Castration is commonly performed on domestic animals not intended for breeding. <s> Domestic animals are usually castrated in order to avoid unwanted or uncontrolled reproduction; to reduce or prevent other ways of sexual behaviour such as territorial behaviour or aggression (like fighting between groups of uncastrated males of a species); or to reduce other consequences of sexual behaviour that may make animal husbandry more difficult, such as fence destruction when animals try to get to nearby females of the species. <s> Male horses are usually castrated, because stallions are rather aggressive. <s> The same applies to male mules, although they are sterile. <s> Male cattle are castrated to improve docility for use as oxen.

title: Mymensingh Division
complex: Mymensingh Division is one of the eight administrative divisions of Bangladesh. <s> It has an area of 10,485 km2 and a population of 11,370,000 as of the 2011 census. <s> It was created in 2015 from districts previously comprising the northern part of Dhaka Division.
simple: Mymensingh Division is an administrative division of Bangladesh. <s> The division has an area of 10,485 km2, and a population of 11,370,000.

title: Curt Görans
complex: Curt Görans was a dansband from Eskilstuna, Sweden, scoring mid 1970s Svensktoppen chart successes.
simple: Curt Görans was a dansband from Eskilstuna in Sweden . <s> The band scored Svensktoppen chart succcesses during the mid 1970s.

title: Red Norvo
complex: Red Norvo (born Kenneth Norville, March 31, 1908 – April 6, 1999) was one of jazz's early vibraphonists, known as "Mr. Swing". <s> He helped establish the xylophone, marimba, and vibraphone as jazz instruments.
simple: Kenneth "Red" Norvo (31 March 1908, Beardstown, Illinois - 6 April 1999, Santa Monica, California) was an American jazz musician and dancer.

title: Best Of (Vanilla Ninja album)
complex: Best Of is a best-of album by the Estonian girl band Vanilla Ninja. <s> The album was released in December 2005 and consists of thirteen songs from their "Traces of Sadness" and "Blue Tattoo" albums. <s> The album was released in several countries in Central Europe, failing to make the top 100 in Germany and Austria, and peaking at #70 in Switzerland.
simple: Best Of is a best-of album by the Estonian girl band Vanilla Ninja. <s> The album was released in December 2005, and consisted of thirteen songs from their "Traces of Sadness" and "Blue Tattoo" albums.

title: Fishburn (1780 ship)
complex: Fishburn was built at Whitby in 1780. <s> the largest of the three First Fleet storeships. <s> According to her 1786 Deptford survey, she was 6 ft between decks afore, 5 ft midships and 7 ft abaft. <s> "Fishburn" left Portsmouth on 13 May 1787, and arrived at Port Jackson on 26 January 1788. <s> She left Port Jackson on 19 November 1788, keeping company with "Golden Grove" until losing sight of her on 11 April 1789 after several days at the Falkland Islands for recovery of crew members who were sick with scurvy. <s> She arrived back in England on 25 May 1789. <s> The fate of "Fishburn" is unknown; she appears to have disappeared from the records after being discharged from Her Majesty's service at Deptford, nine days after her arrival.
simple: It had been built in Whitby in 1780. <s> The Fishburn was a store ship in the First Fleet. <s> The ships left England in May 1787 and arrived in Australia in January 1788. <s> The "Fishburn" and the "Golden Grove" left Port Jackson in November 1788 to return to England. <s> She had to rest at the Falkland Islands for several days as several sailors were sick. <s> She was returned to her owners at Deptford on May 25, 1789.

title: Syzygium cumini
complex: Syzygium cumini, commonly known as Malabar plum, Java plum, or black plum, is an evergreen tropical tree in the flowering plant family Myrtaceae. <s> It is native to the Indian Subcontinent, adjoining regions of Southeast Asia, China and Queensland. <s> The name of the fruit is sometimes mistranslated as blackberry, which is a different fruit in an unrelated order. <s> "Syzygium cumini" has been spread overseas from India by Indian emigrants and at present is common in tropical former British colonies. <s> The tree was introduced to Florida in 1911 by the USDA, and is also now commonly grown in Suriname, Guyana and Trinidad and Tobago. <s> In Brazil, where it was introduced from India during Portuguese colonization, it has dispersed spontaneously in the wild in some places, as its fruits are eagerly sought by various native birds such as thrushes, tanagers and the great kiskadee. <s> This species is considered an invasive in Hawaii. <s> A slow growing species, it can reach heights of up to 30 m and can live more than 100 years. <s> Its dense foliage provides shade and is grown just for its ornamental value. <s> At the base of the tree, the bark is rough and dark grey, becoming lighter grey and smoother higher up. <s> The wood is water resistant. <s> Because of this it is used in railway sleepers and to install motors in wells. <s> It is sometimes used to make cheap furniture and village dwellings though it is relatively hard to work on. <s> "Syzygium cumini" trees start flowering from March to April. <s> The flowers are fragrant and small, about 5 mm in diameter. <s> The fruits develop by May or June and resemble large berries; the fruit of "Syzygium" species is described as "drupaceous". <s> The fruit is oblong, ovoid. <s> Unripe fruit looks green. <s> As it matures, its color changes to pink, then to shining crimson red and finally to black color. <s> A variant of the tree produces white coloured fruit. <s> The fruit has a combination of sweet, mildly sour and astringent flavour and tends to colour the tongue purple. <s> The seed of the fruit is used in various alternative healing systems like Ayurveda, Unani and Chinese medicine. <s> Wine and vinegar are also made from the fruit. <s> It has a high source in vitamin A and vitamin C.
simple: Jambul or Jamun or Jamblang ("Syzgium cumini"), Naavar Pazham (Tamil) is an evergreen tropical tree in the flowering plant family Myrtaceae, native to India, Pakistan, Indonesia and Bangladesh. <s> The tree was also introduced to Florida, USA in 1911 by the USDA, and is also now commonly planted in Suriname. <s> In Brazil, where it was introduced from India during Portuguese colonisation, it has spread out in the wild in some places, as many native birds such as thrushes, tanagers and the Great Kiskadee want their fruits. <s> A fairly fast growing species, it can grow as high as 30 metres, and can live more than 100 years. <s> Its dense foliage provides shade and is grown just for its ornamental value. <s> The wood is strong and water resistant. <s> Because of this it is used in railway sleepers and to install motors in wells. <s> It is sometimes used to make cheap furniture and village dwellings though it is relatively hard to work on. <s> The Jamun tree starts flowering in March-April. <s> The fragrant flowers of Jamun are small, nearly 5 millimetres in diameter. <s> This is followed by the fruit which appears in May-June and resembles a large berry. <s> The berry is oblong and ovoid. <s> It is green when just appearing, pink when as it matures, and shining crimson black when fully ripe. <s> Jamun fruit is a mixture of sweet, slightly sub acid spicy flavour that stands out even after eaten since it turns the tongue into purple color. <s> The seed is also used in various alternative healing systems like Ayurveda, Unani and Chinese medicine for digestive ailments. <s> Wine and vinegar are also made from the fruit.

title: Alan Steel
complex: Sergio Ciani (7 September 1931 – 5 September 2015), best known as Alan Steel, was an Italian bodybuilder and actor. <s> Ciani died in his sleep at his house in Ostia, Rome, at age 79, just two days short of what would have been his 80th birthday.
simple: Sergio Ciani (7 September 1935 – 5 September 2015), best known as Alan Steel, was an Italian bodybuilder and actor. <s> Ciani died in his sleep at his house in Ostia, Rome, aged 79.

title: Indus Valley Desert
complex: The Indus Valley Desert is an almost uninhabited desert ecoregion of northern Pakistan. <s> The Indus Valley desert covers an area of 19,501 km2 in northwestern Punjab Province between the Chenab and Indus rivers. <s> The Indus Valley Desert is drier and less hospitable than the northwestern thorn scrub forests that surround it with temperatures ranging from freezing in winter to extremely hot (more than 45 °C ) in summer with only 600 - of rainfall per year.
simple: The Indus Valley Desert is a desert ecoregion of northern Pakistan. <s> The Indus Valley desert covers an area of 19,500 square kilometers (7,500 square miles) in northwestern Punjab Province, lying between the Chenab River and Indus rivers. <s> The Indus Valley Desert is drier and less hospitable than the Northwestern thorn scrub forests that surround it.

title: Steropodon
complex: Steropodon galmani was a prehistoric species of monotreme, or egg-laying mammal, that lived about 105 million years ago (mya) in the Lower Cretaceous period. <s> It is one of the oldest monotremes discovered, and is one of the oldest Australian mammal discoveries.
simple: Steropodon galmanii was a prehistoric species of monotreme, or a egg-laying mammal, that lived during the Mesozoic, in the Lower Cretaceous period.

title: Pat Harrington Sr.
complex: Daniel Patrick Harrington Sr. (February 6, 1901 – September 2, 1965) was a Canadian actor. <s> Born Daniel Patrick Harrington in Montreal, Quebec, Canada, he made his Broadway debut in "Panama Hattie" in 1940. <s> Additional Broadway credits included the patriotic revue "Star and Garter" (1942), "The Front Page" (1946), "Call Me Madam" (1950) and "Sunday in New York" (1961). <s> He also appeared on the early television series "A Couple of Joes" (1949) and "The Wonderful John Acton" (1953).
simple: Daniel Patrick "Pat" Harrington, Sr. (February 6, 1901 – September 2, 1965) was a Canadian actor. <s> Harrington was born in Montreal, Quebec. <s> His Broadway credits include "Panama Hattie" (1940), "Star and Garter" (1942), "The Front Page" (1946), "Call Me Madam" (1950) and "Sunday in New York" (1961). <s> He also appeared in the early television series "A Couple of Joes" (1949) and "The Wonderful John Acton" (1953).

title: HTTP 404
complex: The HTTP 404, 404 Not Found, 404, Page Not Found, or Server Not Found error message is a Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) standard response code, in computer network communications, to indicate that the browser was able to communicate with a given server, but the server could not find what was requested. <s> Further, when the requested information is found but access is not granted, the server may return a 404 error if it wishes to not disclose this information, as well.
simple: The 404 or Not Found is an HTTP error message meaning the web server could be contacted, but the file or webpage trying to be accessed could not be found.

title: Franz Welser-Möst
complex: Franz Leopold Maria Möst (born 16 August 1960), known professionally as Franz Welser-Möst, is an Austrian conductor. <s> He is currently music director of the Cleveland Orchestra. <s> Franz Leopold Maria Möst was born in Linz, Austria, and later studied under the composer . <s> As a youth in Linz, he studied the violin and had developed an interest in conducting. <s> After suffering injuries in a car crash that led to nerve damage, he stopped his violin studies and shifted full-time to conducting studies. <s> In 1985, Möst assumed the stage name "Welser-Möst" on suggestion of his mentor, Baron Andreas von Bennigsen of Liechtenstein, thus paying homage to the city of Wels where he grew up. <s> In 1986, he was adopted by Bennigsen. <s> In 1992, Welser-Möst married Bennigsen's former wife, Angelika. <s> His first major debuts were at the Salzburg Festival in 1985, followed by the London Philharmonic Orchestra in 1986 and the Orchester Musikkollegium Winterthur in 1988. <s> Between 1986 and 1991 Welser-Möst served as the principal conductor of Norrköping Symphony Orchestra, Sweden, and in 1990 he became principal conductor of the London Philharmonic Orchestra (LPO). <s> His LPO tenure was controversial, with London critics giving him the nickname "Frankly Worse than Most". <s> He concluded his LPO tenure in 1996. <s> From 1995 to 2000, he was music director with the Zürich Opera House. <s> He became general music director of the Zürich Opera in September 2005, with an original commitment to the Opera through 2011. <s> However, he stood down from the Zürich post in July 2008, after having agreed to serve in the same capacity at the Vienna State Opera. <s> In the USA, Welser-Möst made his American conducting debut with the St. Louis Symphony in 1989. <s> He first guest-conducted the Cleveland Orchestra in February 1993. <s> Welser-Möst became music director of the Cleveland Orchestra with the 2002/2003 season, for an initial contract of five years. <s> At the end of his first season, his contract was extended for another five years. <s> In June 2008, the orchestra announced a further extension of his contract with the Cleveland Orchestra through the 2017/2018 season. <s> In October 2014, the orchestra announced an additional extension of his Cleveland Orchestra contract through the 2021-2022 season. <s> Welser-Möst first conducted at the Vienna State Opera in 1987, as a substitute for Claudio Abbado in a production of Gioachino Rossini's "L'italiana in Algeri". <s> On June 6, 2007, the Austrian government announced the appointment of Welser-Möst as "Generalmusikdirektor" of the Vienna State Opera, effective September 2010, alongside Dominique Meyer as director ("Staatsoperndirektor"). <s> In September 2014, he announced his resignation from the Vienna State Opera, effective immediately.
simple: Franz Welser-Möst (born Linz, 16 August 1960) is an Austrian conductor. <s> He is the conductor (music director) of the Cleveland Orchestra. <s> Franz Leopold Maria Möst was born in Linz, Austria. <s> He learned to play the violin, but after being injured in a car accident he changed to conducting. <s> In 1985 he changed his stage-name to "Welser-Möst" after the town of Wels where he grew up. <s> He appeared at the Salzburg Festival in 1985, then conducted the London Philharmonic Orchestra in 1986 and, from 1989 he appeared a lot in the United States. <s> In 1990, Welser-Möst became main (principal) conductor of the London Philharmonic Orchestra. <s> He received a lot of criticism and left the LPO in 1996. <s> In 1995 he went to the Zurich Opera House where he conducted many operas including complete cycles of Wagner's Ring Cycle. <s> He left the Zurich post in 2008. <s> Since 2002 Welser-Möst has been conductor of the Cleveland Orchestra. <s> In 2007, the Austrian government made him Musical Director (Generalmusikdirektor) of the Vienna State Opera beginning in September 2010.

title: Web accessibility
complex: Web accessibility is the inclusive practice of ensuring there are no barriers that prevent interaction with, or access to, websites on the World Wide Web by people with physical disabilities, situational disabilities, and socio-economic restrictions on bandwidth and speed. <s> When sites are correctly designed, developed and edited, generally all users have equal access to information and functionality.
simple: Web accessibility is how easy it is to use the internet for people with disabilities.

title: Mirosława Litmanowicz
complex: Mirosława Litmanowicz (née Kałęcka; 6 September 1928 – 18 August 2017) was a Polish chess player who won the Polish Women's Chess Championship in 1968. <s> FIDE Woman International Master (1967).
simple: Mirosława Litmanowicz (Mirosława Kałęcka; 6 September 1928 – 18 August 2017) was a Polish chess player. <s> Litmanowicz died on 18 August 2017 at the age of 89. <s> She won the Polish Women's Chess Championship in 1968 and the FIDE Woman International Master in 1967.

title: All-America
complex: An All-America team is a hypothetical American sports team composed of outstanding amateur players. <s> These players are broadly considered by media and other relevant commentators as the best players in a particular sport, of a specific season, for each team position. <s> As of 2009, the term is used in U.S. team sports to refer to players who are selected by members of the national media. <s> The term is used primarily with regard to college and, occasionally, to high school players.
simple: In sports, an All-America "team" is a group of amateur athletes who are honored for being the best in the sport. <s> The players who are on these teams are usually selected by members of the media or companies who sponsor the team.

title: Esch-sur-Alzette
complex: Esch-sur-Alzette ( ] , ] or "Esch-an-der-Alzig", ) is a commune with town status in south-western Luxembourg. <s> It is the country's second "city", and its second-most populous commune, with a population of 35,040 inhabitants, as of 2018 . <s> It lies in the south-west of the country, on the border with France and in the valley of the Alzette, which flows through the town. <s> The town is usually referred to as just Esch; however, the full name distinguishes it from the village and commune of Esch-sur-Sûre which lies 45 km further north. <s> The country's capital, Luxembourg City, is roughly 15 km to the north-east. <s> For a long time Esch was a small farming village in the valley of the Uelzecht river. <s> This changed when important amounts of iron ore were found in the area in the 1850s. <s> With the development of the mines and the steel industry the town's population multiplied tenfold in a couple of decades. <s> In 1911 the steel- and iron-producing company ARBED was founded.
simple: Esch-sur-Alzette (, German: "Esch-an-der-Alzette" or "Esch-an-der-Alzig", ) is a commune with city status in south-western Luxembourg, capital of the canton Esch-sur-Alzette. <s> Esch-sur-Alzette is in the south-west of the country, on the border with France. <s> The town is usually referred to just as Esch, but there is also a village and "commune" further north, in the Wiltz canton, named Esch-sur-Sûre from which to distinguish it. <s> For a long time Esch-sur-Alzette was a small farming village in the valley of the Alzette river. <s> This changed when important amounts of iron ore were found in the area in the 1850s. <s> With the development of the mines and the steel industry the town's population multiplied tenfold in a couple of decades.

title: Gillian Welch
complex: Gillian Howard Welch ( ; born October 2, 1967) is an American singer-songwriter. <s> She performs with her musical partner, guitarist David Rawlings.
simple: Gillian Howard Welch (born October 2, 1967 in New York City) is an American singer-songwriter.

title: Tilly-sur-Seulles
complex: Tilly-sur-Seulles is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Tilly-sur-Seulles is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Basse-Normandie in the Calvados department in the northwest of France.

title: Dennis Haskins
complex: Dennis Haskins (born November 18, 1950) is an American actor known for his role as principal Richard Belding in the teen sitcom "Saved by the Bell", which ran from 1989 to 1993 on NBC. <s> He then went on to star in "", which aired from 1993 to 2000. <s> He also portrayed the role as a regular in "Good Morning, Miss Bliss".
simple: Dennis Haskins (born November 18, 1950) is an American actor. <s> He is known for his role as principal Richard Belding in the teen sitcom "Saved by the Bell" which ran from 1989 to 1993 on NBC. <s> He then went on to star in "", which aired from 1993 to 2000. <s> He also portrayed the role as a regular in "Good Morning, Miss Bliss".

title: Néris-les-Bains
complex: Néris-les-Bains is a commune in the Allier department in the Auvergne region in central France.
simple: Néris-les-Bains is a commune. <s> It is found in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Kim (surname)
complex: Kim is a surname with multiple origins. <s> Kim, sometimes spelt Gim, is the most common family name in Korea.
simple: Kim is a surname. <s> Kim, sometimes spelled "Gim", is the most common family name in Korea.

title: East Coast Main Line
complex: The East Coast Main Line (ECML) is a 393 mi electrified railway between London and Edinburgh via Peterborough, Doncaster, York, Darlington, Durham and Newcastle. <s> The line is a key transport artery on the eastern side of Great Britain running broadly parallel to the A1 road.
simple: East Coast Main Line is an electrified main line between London and Edinburgh in United Kingdom.

title: Tidal (album)
complex: Tidal is the debut studio album by American singer-songwriter Fiona Apple, released on July 23, 1996 by Work Records and Columbia Records (Sony Music). <s> "Tidal" produced six singles: "Shadowboxer", "Slow Like Honey", "Sleep to Dream", "The First Taste", "Criminal" and "Never Is a Promise". <s> "Criminal", the album's most popular single, won a Grammy Award for "Best Female Rock Vocal Performance" in 1998. <s> In 2017, "Tidal" got its first vinyl run as a 'Vinyl Me, Please' exclusive "Record of the Month." <s> In 2010, "Rolling Stone" ranked the album at number 83 among the 100 greatest albums of the 1990s. <s> The following year, "Slant Magazine" placed it at number 74.
simple: Tidal is the 1996 first album by Fiona Apple. <s> Six singles were released from it: "Shadowboxer", "Slow Like Honey", "Sleep to Dream", "The First Taste", "Criminal" and "Never Is a Promise". <s> "Criminal" received the 1997 Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance. <s> "Rolling Stone" put it at #83 in their 100 Best Albums of the Nineties.

title: Gorno-Altaysk
complex: Gorno-Altaysk (Russian: , ; , "Tuulu Altay") is the capital town of the Altai Republic, Russia.
simple: Gorno-Altaysk (; , "Tuulu Altay") is the capital city of the Altai Republic, Russia.

title: Teruki Miyamoto
complex: Teruki Miyamoto (宮本 輝紀 , Miyamoto Teruki , December 26, 1940 – February 2, 2000) was a Japanese football player and manager. <s> He played for Japan national team.
simple: Teruki Miyamoto (宮本 輝紀, Miyamoto Teruki, December 26, 1940 - February 2, 2000) was a Japanese football player. <s> He has played for the Japanese national team.

title: Jon Skolmen
complex: Jon Skolmen (1 November 1940 – 28 March 2019) was a Norwegian actor and comedian who appeared in several Norwegian and Swedish films. <s> He gained special recognition for his role as Ole Bramserud in "Sällskapsresan" (1980) opposite Lasse Åberg. <s> Between 1963 and 1981, Skolmen was employed by the Norwegian state broadcasting company, NRK, where he most notably co-wrote and appeared in the show "The Nor-Way to Broadcasting" alongside Trond Kirkvaag. <s> The show won the Golden Rose of Montreux and the Chaplin Award at the Montreux Television Festival in 1976. <s> He also appeared on British children's television. <s> In 1971, he presented "Play School" for the BBC, though for only one week. <s> In 1981, he appeared in a one-off special co-produced by the BBC and NRK called "Jon, Brian, Kirsti and Jon" in which he appeared with his compatriot Kirsti Sparboe, and the British performers Brian Cant (with whom Skolmen co-wrote the script) and Jonathan Cohen. <s> Skolmen received the Komiprisen honorary prize for lifetime achievement in 2009. <s> Skolmen was the father of actors Christian and Tine Skolmen, brother of director Eli Skolmen Ryg and uncle of actors Anne Ryg and Hege Schøyen. <s> He acted alongside Schøyen in the 1991 Swedish comedy film "Den ofrivillige golfaren". <s> He died on 28 March 2019 at the age of 78.
simple: Jon Skolmen (1 November 1940 – 28 March 2019) was a Norwegian actor, comedian and presenter. <s> He acted in many Norwegian and Swedish movies. <s> He was known for his role as Ole Bramserud in the Swedish comedy movie "Sällskapsresan" (1980) with Lasse Åberg. <s> He worked for the Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation (NRK) from 1963 to 1981. <s> He also appeared on British children's television. <s> For only a week in 1971, he presented "Play School" for the BBC. <s> In 1981, he appeared in the BBC/NRK special "Jon, Brian, Kirsti and Jon". <s> He starred in this with fellow Norwegian Kirsti Sparboe, and British performers Brian Cant and Jonathan Cohen. <s> Skolmen was awarded the Komiprisen honorary prize for lifetime achievement in 2009. <s> He was the father of actors Christian and Tine Skolmen, brother of director Eli Skolmen Ryg and uncle of actors Anne Ryg and Hege Schøyen. <s> Skolmen died on 28 March 2019 in Oslo, at the age of 78.

title: Good Times
complex: Good Times is an American sitcom that aired for six seasons on CBS from February 8, 1974, to August 1, 1979. <s> Created by Eric Monte and Mike Evans, and developed by Norman Lear, the series' primary executive producer, it was television's first African American two-parent family sitcom. <s> "Good Times" is a spin-off of "Maude", which was itself a spin-off of "All in the Family".
simple: Good Times is an American sitcom that originally aired from February 8, 1974, until August 1, 1979, on CBS. <s> It was created by Eric Monte and Mike Evans, and developed by Norman Lear, the series' primary executive producer. <s> "Good Times" is a spin-off of "Maude", which is itself a spin-off of "All in the Family".

title: Mike Huckabee 2016 presidential campaign
complex: The 2016 presidential campaign of Mike Huckabee, the 44th Governor of Arkansas, began on May 5, 2015 at an event in his hometown of Hope, Arkansas. <s> Huckabee's candidacy for the Republican nomination in the 2016 Presidential election was his second, after having previously run in 2008. <s> Following a disappointing showing in the Iowa caucuses, Huckabee ended his run on February 1, 2016. <s> On May 5, 2015, Huckabee officially declared his candidacy at a rally in his hometown of Hope, Arkansas.
simple: The Mike Huckabee presidential campaign of 2016 began on May 5, when Huckabee announced his intention to run for the Republican nomination in the 2016 Presidential election. <s> Huckabee made the announcement in his hometown, Hope, Arkansas. <s> He suspended his campaign on February 1, 2016.

title: Marske-by-the-Sea
complex: Marske-by-the-Sea is a village in the unitary authority of Redcar and Cleveland and the ceremonial county of North Yorkshire, England. <s> It is located on the coast, between the seaside resorts of Redcar and Saltburn-by-the-Sea, although it is not itself a seaside resort. <s> Marske is in the civil parish of Saltburn, Marske and New Marske and comprises the wards of Longbeck (shared with New Marske) and St Germains. <s> The majority of the residents of Marske do not work within the village, but work in nearby industry or in Middlesbrough or Redcar. <s> Marske has a range of local shops and a mixture of light industries on the Industrial Estate notably label and barcode specialists Weyfringe. <s> There is also small scale sea fishing using cobles and tractors from the beach. <s> The village has its own post office, medical centres, leisure centre and a library. <s> The village has Methodist, Baptist, Church of England and Roman Catholic churches and five public houses: The Frigate, The Ship Inn, The Zetland, The Mermaid and The Clarendon. <s> Marske is served by Longbeck and Marske railway stations, which connect to Darlington railway station. <s> The main road through Marske is the A1085 Coast Road and High Street.
simple: Marske by the Sea is a village in the borough of Redcar and Cleveland in England. <s> Most of the people who live in Marske do not work in the village, but work in the nearby factory or in Middlesbrough or Redcar. <s> Marske has a decent range of local shops. <s> The village has a Methodist, Roman Catholic (St Bede's) and Church of England (St Mark's) church. <s> The Longbeck railway station and Marske railway station, which connect to Darlington mainline station, are the only means of transport there.

title: Nuits
complex: Nuits (also known, though unofficially, as Nuits-sur-Armançon) is a commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France.
simple: Nuits is a commune.

title: August Kekulé
complex: Friedrich August Kekulé, later Friedrich August Kekule von Stradonitz ( ; ] ; 7 September 1829 – 13 July 1896), was a German organic chemist. <s> From the 1850s until his death, Kekulé was one of the most prominent chemists in Europe, especially in theoretical chemistry. <s> He was the principal founder of the theory of chemical structure. <s> The son of a civil servant, Kekulé was born in Darmstadt, the capital of the Grand Duchy of Hesse. <s> After graduating from secondary school (the Grand Ducal Gymnasium in Darmstadt), in the fall of 1847 he entered the University of Giessen, with the intention of studying architecture. <s> After hearing the lectures of Justus von Liebig in his first semester, he decided to study chemistry. <s> Following four years of study in Giessen and a brief compulsory military service, he took temporary assistantships in Paris (1851–52), in Chur, Switzerland (1852–53), and in London (1853–55), where he was decisively influenced by Alexander Williamson. <s> His Giessen doctoral degree was awarded in the summer of 1852. <s> In 1856 Kekulé became Privatdozent at the University of Heidelberg. <s> In 1858 he was hired as full professor at the University of Ghent, then in 1867 he was called to Bonn, where he remained for the rest of his career. <s> Basing his ideas on those of predecessors such as Williamson, Edward Frankland, William Odling, Auguste Laurent, Charles-Adolphe Wurtz and others, Kekulé was the principal formulator of the theory of chemical structure (1857–58). <s> This theory proceeds from the idea of atomic valence, especially the tetravalence of carbon (which Kekulé announced late in 1857) and the ability of carbon atoms to link to each other (announced in a paper published in May 1858), to the determination of the bonding order of all of the atoms in a molecule. <s> Archibald Scott Couper independently arrived at the idea of self-linking of carbon atoms (his paper appeared in June 1858), and provided the first molecular formulas where lines symbolize bonds connecting the atoms. <s> For organic chemists, the theory of structure provided dramatic new clarity of understanding, and a reliable guide to both analytic and especially synthetic work. <s> As a consequence, the field of organic chemistry developed explosively from this point. <s> Among those who were most active in pursuing early structural investigations were, in addition to Kekulé and Couper, Frankland, Wurtz, Alexander Crum Brown, Emil Erlenmeyer, and Alexander Butlerov. <s> Kekulé's most famous work was on the structure of benzene. <s> In 1865 Kekulé published a paper in French (for he was then still in Belgium) suggesting that the structure contained a six-membered ring of carbon atoms with alternating single and double bonds. <s> The following year he published a much longer paper in German on the same subject. <s> The empirical formula for benzene had been long known, but its highly unsaturated structure was a challenge to determine. <s> Archibald Scott Couper in 1858 and Joseph Loschmidt in 1861 suggested possible structures that contained multiple double bonds or multiple rings, but the study of aromatic compounds was in its earliest years, and too little evidence was then available to help chemists decide on any particular structure.
simple: Friedrich August Kekule von Stradonitz (also August Kekulé) (7 September 1829 – 13 July 1896) was a German organic chemist. <s> Kekulé was born in Darmstadt, the son of a civil servant. <s> After graduating from secondary school, in 1847 he entered the University of Giessen, with the intention of studying architecture. <s> After hearing the lectures of Justus von Liebig he decided to study chemistry. <s> Following his education in Giessen, he took further doctorate fellowships in Paris (1851-52), in Chur, Switzerland (1852-53), and in London (1853-55), where he was decisively influenced by Alexander Williamson. <s> In 1858, he was hired as a full professor at the University of Ghent. <s> Kekulé's most famous work was on the structure of benzene. <s> In 1865 Kekulé published a paper in French suggesting that the structure contained a six-membered ring of carbon atoms with alternating single and double bonds. <s> The next year he published a much longer paper in German on the same subject. <s> The empirical formula for benzene had been long known, but its highly unsaturated structure was challenging to determine. <s> Archibald Scott Couper in 1858 and Joseph Loschmidt in 1861 suggested possible structures that contained multiple double bonds or multiple rings, but the study of aromatic compounds was in its earliest years, and too little evidence was then available to help chemists decide on any particular structure.

title: PCC streetcar
complex: The PCC (Presidents’ Conference Committee) is a streetcar (tram) design that was first built in the United States in the 1930s. <s> The design proved successful in its native country, and after World War II it was licensed for use elsewhere in the world where PCC based cars were made. <s> The PCC car has proved to be a long-lasting icon of streetcar design, and many are still in service around the world.
simple: The PCC (Presidents' Conference Committee) streetcar (tram) design was first built in the United States in the 1930s. <s> The design was very successful in America. <s> After World War II it was allowed to be used in other countries in the world. <s> The PCC car has proved to be a long lasting icon of streetcar design, and PCC cars are still in service in various places around the world.

title: Stephen P. Synnott
complex: Stephen P. Synnott (born 1946) is an American astronomer and Voyager scientist at JPL, and expert in spacecraft optical navigation techniques. <s> He has discovered several natural satellites of outer Solar System planets such as Metis, Puck, Larissa (recovered), Cressida, Thebe and Proteus. <s> The minor planet 6154 Stevesynnott, discovered by Henry E. Holt in 1990, was named in his honour. <s> The approved naming citation was published by the Minor Planet Center on 1 July 1996 (M.P.C. 27461 ).
simple: Stephen P. Synnott is an American astronomer. <s> He is also a scientist for the Voyager program. <s> He discovered several moons of Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. <s> He discovered Metis, Puck, Larissa, Proteus, and Thebe. <s> The minor planet 6154 Stevesynnott was named after him.

title: Arena rock
complex: Arena rock (also known as stadium rock, corporate rock, melodic rock, pomp rock, AOR ) is a style of rock music that originated in the mid-1970s. <s> As hard rock bands and those playing a softer yet strident kind of pop rock became increasingly popular, groups began creating material inherently designed for large audiences, and arena rock developed from their use of more commercially oriented and radio-friendly sounds.
simple: Event Centre rock (also known as arena rock, corporate rock, industry rock,or stadium rock) is a word to describe a form of rock music which is played, or intended to be played, in large venues, such as event centres, arenas, stadia, and open-air concert spaces.

title: John Bertrand (sailor, born 1946)
complex: Sailing John Edwin Bertrand (born 20 December 1946) is a yachtsman from Australia, who skippered "Australia II" to victory in the 1983 America's Cup, ending 132 years of American supremacy. <s> Bertrand won the bronze medal in the Finn competition at the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal. <s> In 2010 and 2016, he won the world Etchells class sailing championships. <s> He is a life member of both the Royal Brighton Yacht Club in Melbourne, and the Sorrento Sailing Couta Boat Club. <s> John Bertrand was born in Melbourne, Victoria.
simple: John Bertrand is an Australian yachtsman. <s> In 1983, Bertrand was the captain of the "Australia II" at the America's Cup. <s> Bertrand’s team was the first to beat the United States in the America's Cup in 132 years. <s> In 1976 Bertrand won a bronze medal at the Olympic Games also for the finn competition. <s> Bertrand went to Monash University in Melbourne, Australia.

title: Preemptive war
complex: A preemptive war is a war that is commenced in an attempt to repel or defeat a perceived imminent offensive or invasion, or to gain a strategic advantage in an impending (allegedly unavoidable) war "shortly before" that attack materializes. <s> It is a war that preemptively 'breaks the peace'. <s> The term 'preemptive war' is sometimes confused with the term 'preventive war'. <s> The difference is that a preventive war is launched to destroy the potential threat of the targeted party, when an attack by that party is not imminent or known to be planned.
simple: A preemptive war is one in which a country takes military action against another country or group that poses a real threat of waging a war against them. <s> Preemptive war is thought of as a defensive act. <s> A preemptive war is one in which striking first gives a country an advantage over an enemy whose intentions are clearly to strike and do great harm. <s> There is often confusion between preemptive war and a preventative war. <s> By calling it "preemptive" it does not change if from being preventive.

title: Colony
complex: The metropolitan state is the state that rules the colony. <s> In Ancient Greece, the city that founded a colony was known as the metropolis.
simple: The metropolitan state is the country that owns the colony. <s> A colonist is a person from the metropolitan state who lives in a colony.

title: Franck Goldnadel
complex: Franck Goldnadel, born 14 August 1969, is a French public servant and former director of Paris-Charles de Gaulle Airport. <s> Graduating from the "École nationale de l'aviation civile" (French civil aviation academy, promotion 1990), he started his career in 1993 at the air transport department of ENAC where he was working on the Airbus training programs. <s> From 1994 to 1997, he was commercial manager of "Alyzia Airport Services", subsidiary of "Aéroports de Paris" for ground handling services. <s> He joins "Aéroports de Paris" in 1997 where he would become director of Paris-Orly Airport and then head of the Terminal 2 at Paris-Charles de Gaulle Airport. <s> On 1 March 2011 Goldnadel was appointed director of Charles de Gaulle Airport. <s> He left his position in February 2018, replaced by Marc Houalla.
simple: Franck Goldnadel, born the 14th of August 1969, is a French aerospace engineer. <s> He graduated from the French Civil Aviation University (Promotion 1990). <s> Marc Houalla replaced him in February 2018.

title: Redshirts (Italy)
complex: Redshirts (Italian Camicie Rosse) or Red coats (Italian Giubbe Rosse) is the name given to the volunteers who followed Giuseppe Garibaldi in southern Italy during his expedition of the Thousand to southern Italy, but sometimes extended to other campaigns of his. <s> The name derived from the color of their shirts or loose fitting blouses (complete uniforms were beyond the finances of the Italian patriots).
simple: Redshirts or Red coats is the name given to the volunteers who followed Giuseppe Garibaldi. <s> The name came from the color of their shirts.

title: Disney Television Animation
complex: Disney Television Animation (DTVA) is an American animation studio that creates, develops and produces animated television series, films, specials and other projects. <s> It is a division of the Disney Channels Worldwide, ultimately owned by The Walt Disney Company. <s> Established in 1984 during the reorganization and subsequent re-incorporation of The Walt Disney Company following the arrival of then-Disney CEO Michael Eisner, the entity was formerly known as the Walt Disney Pictures Television Animation Group before being shortened to Walt Disney Television Animation in 1987, and was shortened again in 2011 to Disney Television Animation.
simple: Disney Television Animation (DTVA) is the television animation production arm of the Disney Channels Worldwide dedicated to creating, developing and producing animated television series, films, specials and other projects. <s> Made in 1984 during the reorganization and Was brought back in to The Walt Disney Company following the arrival of then-Disney CEO Michael Eisner, it was known as The Walt Disney Pictures Television Animation Group, the name was then changed and shortened to Walt Disney Television Animation starting in 1987 and was its name up until 2011, when it has been shortened again to Disney Television Animation.

title: Maastricht Treaty
complex: While the current version of the TEU entered into force in 2009, following the Treaty of Lisbon (2007), the older form of the same document was implemented by the Treaty of Maastricht (1992). <s> The signing of the Treaty of Maastricht took place in Maastricht, Netherlands, on 7 February 1992. <s> The Dutch government, by virtue of holding Presidency of the Council of the European Union during the negotiations in the second half of 1991, arranged a ceremony inside the government buildings of the Limburg province on the river Maas (Meuse).
simple: European integration went even further with the Treaty of Lisbon, which was signed in 2007 and became effective in December 2009. <s> The Treaty of Maastricht was a treaty signed between European countries, in the Dutch city of Maastricht, in 1992.

title: Peter Mark Richman
complex: Peter Mark Richman (born April 16, 1927) is an American actor who has starred in films and on television, who was for many years credited as Mark Richman. <s> He appeared in over 30 films and over 130 television series since the 1950s. <s> Born Marvin Jack Richman in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, to Jewish parents, he is the son of Yetta Dora (née Peck) and Benjamin Richman, a painting and paper-hanger contractor. <s> He has been married to actress Helen (Landess) Richman since 1953, and they have five children together, including composer and Grammy Award-winning conductor Lucas Richman.
simple: Peter Mark Richman (born Marvin Jack Richman, April 16, 1927) is an American movie, television, stage, voice, and radio actor who is known for his roles in productions like "", "", "Friendly Persuasion", "Agent for H.A.R.M" and "Dark Intruder". <s> Richman was born on April 16, 1927 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania to Yetta Dora Peck and to Benjamin Richman.Richman studied at the Actors Studio. <s> He was married to Helen Richman since 1953. <s> They have five children.

title: Chera dynasty
complex: The Chera dynasty (Cēra) was one of the principal lineages in the early history of the present day states of Kerala and Tamil Nadu in southern India. <s> Together with the Cholas of Uraiyur and the Pandyas of Madurai, the early Cheras were known as one of the three major powers (muventar) of ancient Tamilakam (a macro region in south India) in the early centuries of the Common Era.
simple: The Chera dynasty (Tamil: சேரர் Malayalam: േചര ) was one of the ancient Tamil dynasties who ruled the southern India from ancient times until around the fifteenth century CE. <s> The Early Cheras ruled over the Malabar Coast, Coimbatore, Karur and Salem Districts in South India, which now forms part of the modern day Kerala and Tamil Nadu states of India.

title: Louis Henri de Pardaillan de Gondrin
complex: Louis Henri de Pardaillan de Gondrin, marquis de Montespan (1640 – 1 December 1691) was a French nobleman, most notable as the husband of Louis XIV's mistress Madame de Montespan. <s> He was the son of Roger-Hector de Pardaillan de Gondrin, marquis of Antin, and Marie-Christine de Zamet de Murat. <s> In February 1663 he married Françoise-Athénaïs de Rochechouart de Mortemart.

title: List of heads of state of the Gambia
complex: This is a list of the heads of state of The Gambia, from the independence of The Gambia in 1965 to the present day. <s> From 1965 to 1970 the head of state under the Gambia Independence Act 1964 was the Queen of The Gambia, Elizabeth II, who was also the Monarch of the United Kingdom and the other Commonwealth realms. <s> The Queen was represented in The Gambia by a Governor-General. <s> The Gambia became a republic in 1970 and the Monarch and Governor-General were replaced by an executive President. <s> The succession to the throne was the same as the succession to the British throne. <s> The Governor-General was the representative of the Monarch in The Gambia and exercised most of the powers of the monarch. <s> The Governor-General was appointed for an indefinite term, serving at the pleasure of the Monarch. <s> The Governor-General was appointed solely on the advice of the Cabinet of The Gambia without the involvement of the British government. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Chief Justice served as Officer Administering the Government. <s> Under the 1970 Constitution, the first constitution of the Republic of The Gambia, the President replaced the Monarch as executive head of state. <s> The President was elected by the National Assembly for a five-year term. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Vice-President served as Acting President. <s> Colonel Yahya Jammeh led a coup d'état which overthrew President Jawara and his government, all political parties and Parliament were dissolved. <s> Under the current constitution of the Republic of The Gambia, the President is executive head of state. <s> The President is elected by popular vote for a five-year term. <s> In the event of a vacancy, the Vice-President will serve as Acting President.
simple: This is a list of the heads of state of The Gambia, from the independence of The Gambia in 1965 to the present day. <s> From 1965 to 1970 the head of state under the Gambia Independence Act 1964 was the Queen of The Gambia, Elizabeth II, who was also the Monarch of the United Kingdom and the other Commonwealth realms. <s> The Queen was represented in The Gambia by a Governor-General. <s> The Gambia became a republic in 1970 and the Monarch and Governor-General were replaced by an executive President. <s> The succession to the throne was the same as the succession to the British throne. <s> The Governor-General was the representative of the Monarch in The Gambia and exercised most of the powers of the monarch. <s> The Governor-General was appointed for an indefinite term, serving at the pleasure of the Monarch. <s> The Governor-General was appointed solely on the advice of the Cabinet of The Gambia without the involvement of the British government. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Chief Justice served as Officer Administering the Government. <s> Denotes Chief Justice acting as Officer Administering the Government Under the 1970 Constitution, the first constitution of the Republic of The Gambia, the President replaced the Monarch as executive head of state. <s> The President was elected by the National Assembly for a five-year term. <s> In the event of a vacancy the Vice-President served as Acting President. <s> Denotes Vice-President acting as President Colonel Yahya Jammeh led a coup d'état which overthrew President Jawara and his government, all political parties and Parliament were dissolved. <s> Under the current constitution of the Republic of The Gambia, the President is executive head of state. <s> The President is elected by popular vote for a five-year term. <s> In the event of a vacancy, the Vice-President will serve as Acting President.

title: For loop
complex: In [computer science], a for-loop (or simply for loop) is a [control flow] [statement (programming)|statement] for specifying [iteration], which allows code to be [execution (computers)|executed] repeatedly. <s> Various keywords are used to specify this statement: descendants of [ALGOL] use "for", while descendants of [Fortran] use "do". <s> There are other possibilities, for example [COBOL] which uses "PERFORM VARYING". <s> A for-loop has two parts: a header specifying the iteration, and a body which is executed once per iteration. <s> The header often declares an explicit [For_loop#Loop counters|loop counter] or loop variable, which allows the body to know which iteration is being executed. <s> For-loops are typically used when the number of iterations is known before entering the loop. <s> For-loops can be thought of as shorthands for while-loops which increment and test a loop variable. <s> The name "for-loop" comes from the English word [Wiktionary:for|for], which is used as the [Keyword (computing)|keyword] in many programming languages to introduce a for-loop. <s> The term in English dates to [ALGOL 58] and was popularized in the influential later [ALGOL 60]; it is the direct translation of the earlier German [wikt:für|für], used in "[Superplan]" (1949–1951) by [Heinz Rutishauser], who also was involved in defining ALGOL 58 and ALGOL 60. <s> The loop body is executed "for" the given values of the loop variable, though this is more explicit in the [ALGOL] version of the statement, in which a list of possible values and/or increments can be specified. <s> In [computer programming] a loop counter is the [variable (programming)|variable] that controls the iterations of a loop (a computer [programming language] construct). <s> It is so named because most uses of this construct result in the variable taking on a range of integer values in some orderly sequences (example., starting at 0 and end at 10 in increments of 1) <s> Loop counters change with each [iteration] of a loop, providing a unique value for each individual iteration. <s> The loop counter is used to decide when the loop should terminate and for the program flow to continue to the next [instruction (computer science)|instruction] after the loop. <s> A common [identifier naming convention] is for the loop counter to use the variable names i, j, and k (and so on if needed), where i would be the most outer loop, j the next inner loop, etc. <s> The reverse order is also used by some programmers.
simple: In computer science, a for-loop (or “for loop”) is used to run specified lines of code repeatedly. <s> In different languages, there are different keywords to specify this statement—ways to identify a for loop—but they all do the same task. <s> A for-loop has two parts: a header, and a body of code. <s> The header often declares how many loops to compete, generally indicated by either a loop counter or a loop variable. <s> For-loops are typically used when the number of repetitions are known. <s> For-loops are similar to “while-loops”, but usually have a known number of repetitions. <s> The name for-loop comes from the English word for, which is the direct translation of the earlier German "für", used by Heinz Rutishauser, who also helped define ALGOL 58 and 60. <s> In computer science, a loop counter is a variable that controls how many repetitions the loop will do. <s> Loop counters change each iteration. <s> With each repeat, there is unique counter value. <s> The loop counter is the deciding factor for when a loop should end and go onto the next section of code. <s> Common identifier names for loop counters are i, j, and k(and so on, if needed).

title: Ravan A. G. Farhâdi
complex: Professor Abdul Ghafoor Ravan Farhâdi (born 23 August 1929 in Kabul, Afghanistan) is an Afghan academic and diplomat who served as Afghanistan's Ambassador to the United Nations from 1993 to 2006. <s> Farhâdi is an ethnic Tajik from Kabul. <s> He graduated from Lycée Esteqlal in 1948. <s> Farhâdi studied at the Institut d'études politiques in Paris, France, achieving a MA degree in 1952. <s> He then earned his Ph.D. at the Sorbonne, in Indo-Iranian Studies, in 1955. <s> His paper was on ""le Persan parlé en Afghanistan"", later translated to English and Russian. <s> Farhâdi speaks French, English and Persian fluently. <s> In 1964, he returned to Kabul to work at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. <s> From 1964 till 1968, he served as Director-General for Political Affairs at the ministry and then he was Deputy Foreign Minister for 5 years. <s> Between 1965 and 1971 he also was Secretary of the Council of Ministers of the Afghan Government.
simple: Professor Abdul Ghafoor Ravan Farhâdi (born 23 August 1929) is an Afghan academic and diplomat. <s> He was born in Kabul, Afghanistan. <s> He served as Afghanistan's Ambassador to the United Nations from 1993 to 2006. <s> His paper was on ""le Persan parlé en Afghanistan"", later translated to English and Russian. <s> Farhâdi speaks French, English and Persian fluently. <s> In 1964, he returned to Kabul to work at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. <s> From 1964 till 1968, he served as Director-General for Political Affairs at the ministry and then he was Deputy Foreign Minister for 5 years. <s> Between 1965 and 1971 he also was Secretary of the Council of Ministers of the Afghan Government.

title: North Sioux City, South Dakota
complex: North Sioux City is a city in Union County, South Dakota, United States. <s> The population was 2,530 at the 2010 census. <s> It is part of the Sioux City, IA-NE-SD Metropolitan Statistical Area.
simple: North Sioux City is a city in the far southeastern part of the U.S. state of South Dakota. <s> North Sioux City is near the borders of Iowa and Nebraska, and it is a suburb of Sioux City, Iowa. <s> It became a city in 1951, and 2,530 people lived there at the 2010 census.

title: Robert J. Lagomarsino
complex: Robert John "Bob" Lagomarsino (born September 4, 1926) is a former Republican congressman from California. <s> Lagomarsino began his service in the United States House of Representatives in 1974 and was re-elected every two years until 1992, when he was defeated for renomination by Michael Huffington. <s> Prior to serving in the House, Lagomarsino served in the California State Senate from 1961 until 1974, and prior to that, he served as the mayor of Ojai, California.
simple: Robert John "Bob" Lagomarsino (born September 4, 1926) is an American politician. <s> He was a former Republican congressman from California. <s> Lagomarsino began his service in the United States House of Representatives in 1974 and was re-elected every two years until 1992, when he was defeated for renomination by Michael Huffington. <s> Before he began serving in the House, Lagomarsino served in the California State Senate from 1961 until 1974, and before to that, he served as the mayor of Ojai, California.

title: Chanhassen, Minnesota
complex: Chanhassen is a city southwest of Minneapolis in Carver County, Minnesota, United States. <s> The population was 22,952 at the 2010 census. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 22,952 people, 8,352 households, and 6,257 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 1122.9 PD/sqmi . <s> There were 8,679 housing units at an average density of 424.6 /sqmi . <s> The racial makeup of the city was 92.5% White, 1.1% African American, 0.1% Native American, 3.9% Asian, 0.9% from other races, and 1.5% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.3% of the population. <s> Chanhassen is home to several attractions that are well-recognized throughout the state and even nationally. <s> Chanhassen is located in Minnesota's 3rd congressional district, represented by Dean Phillips, a Democrat. <s> President George W. Bush was the first sitting United States president to visit Chanhassen. <s> He held a rally on October 9, 2004 at Chanhassen's City Center Park during the United States presidential elections of 2004.

Bush was the first sitting United States president to visit Chanhassen.

title: Halophile
complex: Halophiles are organisms that thrive in high salt concentrations. <s> They are a type of extremophile organism. <s> The name comes from the Greek word for "salt-loving". <s> While most halophiles are classified into the Archaea domain, there are also bacterial halophiles and some eukaryota, such as the alga "Dunaliella salina" or fungus "Wallemia ichthyophaga". <s> Some well-known species give off a red color from carotenoid compounds, notably bacteriorhodopsin. <s> Halophiles can be found anywhere with a concentration of salt five times greater than the salt concentration of the ocean, such as the Great Salt Lake in Utah, Owens Lake in California, the Dead Sea, and in evaporation ponds. <s> Halophiles are categorized as slight, moderate, or extreme, by the extent of their halotolerance. <s> Slight halophiles prefer 0.3 to 0.8 M (1.7 to 4.8%—seawater is 0.6 M or 3.5%), moderate halophiles 0.8 to 3.4 M (4.7 to 20%), and extreme halophiles 3.4 to 5.1 M (20 to 30%) salt content. <s> Halophiles require sodium chloride (salt) for growth, in contrast to halotolerant organisms, which do not require salt but can grow under saline conditions. <s> High salinity represents an extreme environment to which relatively few organisms have been able to adapt and occupy. <s> Most halophilic and all halotolerant organisms expend energy to exclude salt from their cytoplasm to avoid protein aggregation ('salting out'). <s> To survive the high salinities, halophiles employ two differing strategies to prevent desiccation through osmotic movement of water out of their cytoplasm. <s> Both strategies work by increasing the internal osmolarity of the cell. <s> In the first (which is employed by the majority of halophilic bacteria, some archaea, yeasts, algae and fungi), organic compounds are accumulated in the cytoplasm—osmoprotectants which are known as compatible solutes. <s> These can be either synthesised or accumulated from the environment. <s> The most common compatible solutes are neutral or zwitterionic, and include amino acids, sugars, polyols, betaines, and ectoines, as well as derivatives of some of these compounds. <s> The second, more radical adaptation involves the selective influx of potassium (K) ions into the cytoplasm. <s> This adaptation is restricted to the moderately halophilic bacterial order Halanaerobiales, the extremely halophilic archaeal family Halobacteriaceae, and the extremely halophilic bacterium "Salinibacter ruber". <s> The presence of this adaptation in three distinct evolutionary lineages suggests convergent evolution of this strategy, it being unlikely to be an ancient characteristic retained in only scattered groups or passed on through massive lateral gene transfer. <s> The primary reason for this is the entire intracellular machinery (enzymes, structural proteins, etc.) must be adapted to high salt levels, whereas in the compatible solute adaptation, little or no adjustment is required to intracellular macromolecules; in fact, the compatible solutes often act as more general stress protectants, as well as just osmoprotectants.
simple: Halophiles are organisms that need salt in their environment to live. <s> The name "halophile" comes from Greek for "salt-loving". <s> Most halophiles are archaeans, but some bacteria and eukaryotes are also halophiles, such as the alga "Dunaliella salina". <s> Halophiles live in evaporation ponds or salt lakes such as Great Salt Lake, Owens Lake, or Dead Sea. <s> Halophiles are categorized by the levels of salt at which they grow best. <s> Halophiles can either be categorized as slight halophiles, moderate halophiles, or extreme halophiles. <s> Slight halophiles grow best in concentrations of salt around 2% to 5%. <s> Moderate halophiles grow best in concentrations of salt around 5% to 20%. <s> Extreme halophiles grow best in concentrations of salt from 20% to 30%. <s> Most halophilic and salt-eating animals use energy to remove salt from their cytoplasm. <s> To get to this state, halophiles use two different methods. <s> In the first (mainly used by bacteria, some archaea, yeasts, algae and fungi), organic compounds are stored in the cytoplasm. <s> The most commonly used solutes for this process are neutral and include amino acids and sugars. <s> The second, less common adaptation, is the selective intake of potassium (K) ions into the cytoplasm. <s> The main disadvantage to this adaption is that all of the machinery inside the cell (enzymes, structural proteins, etc.) must be adapted to high levels of non-organic ions, and high salt levels.

title: Ventforet Kofu
complex: Ventforet Kofu (ヴァンフォーレ甲府 , Vanfōre Kōfu ) is a Japanese football (soccer) club from Kōfu in Yamanashi Prefecture. <s> The team competes in the J2 League. <s> Its home ground is the Kose Sports Stadium. <s> The club was founded in 1965 when the old boys' club of Kofu Dai-ichi High School, the Kakujo Club, started to recruit graduates of other high schools with the intention of promotion to the Japan Soccer League.
simple: Ventforet Kofu (ヴァンフォーレ甲府, Vanfōre Kōfu) is a Japanese professional football club in Kofu. <s> The club was founded in 1965.

title: James Green (historian)
complex: James Robert Green (November 4, 1944 – June 23, 2016) was an American historian, author, and labor activist. <s> He was Professor of History Emeritus at the University of Massachusetts Boston. <s> Green's research focuses on radical political and social movements in the U.S. (including new social movements), as well as the history of labor unions in the United States. <s> Green writes social and political history from "the bottom up." <s> He writes from a leftist theoretical standpoint. <s> Green died in Boston on June 23, 2016, of complications from leukemia.
simple: James Robert Green (November 4, 1944 – June 23, 2016) was an American historian. <s> He was also a well-known author and labor activist. <s> He was the Professor of History Emeritus at the University of Massachusetts Boston. <s> Green's research focuses on radical political and social movements in the U.S. (including new social movements), as well as the history of labor unions in the United States. <s> Green writes social and political history from "the bottom up." <s> He writes from a leftist theoretical standpoint. <s> Green died in Boston on June 23, 2016, of complications from leukemia.

title: Utmankhel
complex: The Utmankhel (Pashto: اتمان خیل) or Utman Khel, are a Yusufzai Pashtun tribe living in Pakistan, with considerable numbers in Afghanistan. <s> The Utman Khel mostly live in the Bajaur District, Malakand District and Lower Dir. <s> They lie between the Mohmands and the Ranizais of Swat, to the west and south-west of the junction of the Swat and Panjkora rivers. <s> They claim to be descendants of Baba Utman Shamraiz, who also assisted Mahmud of Ghaznavi in his expedition into India in 997. <s> The Utman Khel are a tall, stout and fair race, but their dress and general customs have been assimilated by the neighbouring peoples of Bajaur.
simple: The Utmankhel are a Pashtun tribe who live in the hills to the north of Peshawar in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan. <s> Their land lies between the Mohmands and the Ranizais of Swat, to the west and south-west of the junction of the Swat and Panjkora rivers. <s> They claim to be descendants of Baba Utman Shamraiz, who accompanied Mahmud of Ghazni in his expedition into India in 997. <s> The Utman Khel are a tall, stout and fair race, but their dress and general customs have been assimilated by the neighbouring peoples of Bajour.

title: Stanley Cavell
complex: Stanley Louis Cavell ( ; September 1, 1926 – June 19, 2018) was an American philosopher. <s> He was the Walter M. Cabot Professor of Aesthetics and the General Theory of Value at Harvard University. <s> He worked in the fields of ethics, aesthetics, and ordinary language philosophy. <s> As an interpreter, he produced influential works on Wittgenstein, Austin, Emerson, Thoreau, and Heidegger. <s> His work is characterized by its conversational tone and frequent literary references. <s> Cavell died in Boston, Massachusetts of heart failure on June 19, 2018 at the age of 91. <s> He was buried at Mount Auburn Cemetery.
simple: Stanley Louis Cavell (; September 1, 1926 – June 19, 2018) was an American philosopher. <s> He was the Walter M. Cabot Professor of Aesthetics and the General Theory of Value, Emeritus, at Harvard University. <s> He worked in the fields of ethics, aesthetics, and ordinary language philosophy. <s> His influential works were on Wittgenstein, Austin, Emerson, Thoreau, and Heidegger. <s> His work is seen and known by its conversational tone and many literary references. <s> Cavell died in Boston, Massachusetts of heart failure on June 19, 2018 at the age of 91.

title: Rosenborg BK

title: Crookes
complex: Crookes is a suburb of the City of Sheffield, England, about 1.5 mi west of the city centre. <s> It borders Broomhill to the south, Walkley and Crookesmoor to the east and open countryside around the River Rivelin to the north. <s> The population of the ward of the same name was 17,700 at the 2011 Census. <s> The suburb is said to derive its name from the Old Norse "Krkor" which means a nook or corner of land.
simple: Crookes is an area of the City of Sheffield, England, about 2.5 kilometers (1.5 miles) west of the center of the city. <s> It borders Broomhill to the south, Walkley and Crookesmoor to the east and open countryside around the River Rivelin to the north. <s> The area is thought to have got its name from the Old Norse word "Krkor" which means a corner of land.

title: List of Duck Dynasty episodes
complex: The following is a list of episodes of the A&E reality television series "Duck Dynasty". <s> The series is set in West Monroe, Louisiana and stars Willie Robertson, CEO of Duck Commander, a duck call company, and his family and co-workers. <s> Duck Dynasty premiered on March 21, 2012 and aired 130 episodes over 11 seasons, concluding its run on March 29, 2017. <s> A 90-minute retrospective, "Looking Back and Talking Quack," aired on April 5, 2017.
