title: Ramsey theory
complex: Ramsey theory, named after the British mathematician and philosopher Frank P. Ramsey, is a branch of mathematics that studies the conditions under which order must appear. <s> Problems in Ramsey theory typically ask a question of the form: "how many elements of some structure must there be to guarantee that a particular property will hold?" <s> More specifically, Ron Graham describes Ramsey theory as a "branch of combinatorics". <s> A typical result in Ramsey theory starts with some mathematical structure that is then cut into pieces. <s> How big must the original structure be in order to ensure that at least one of the pieces has a given interesting property? <s> This idea can be defined as partition regularity. <s> For example, consider a complete graph of order "n"; that is, there are "n" vertices and each vertex is connected to every other vertex by an edge. <s> A complete graph of order 3 is called a triangle. <s> Now colour every edge red or blue. <s> How large must "n" be in order to ensure that there is either a blue triangle or a red triangle? <s> It turns out that the answer is 6. <s> See the article on Ramsey's theorem for a rigorous proof. <s> Another way to express this result is as follows: at any party with at least six people, there are three people who are all either mutual acquaintances (each one knows the other two) or mutual strangers (each one does not know either of the other two). <s> See theorem on friends and strangers.
simple: The Ramsey theory is named after the British mathematician and philosopher Frank Ramsey (1903–1930). <s> It is a branch of mathematics that studies the conditions under which order must appear. <s> Ramsey theory is now a complete branch of mathematics. <s> A typical result in Ramsey theory starts with some mathematical structure that is then cut into pieces. <s> How big must the original structure be, so that at least one of the pieces has a given interesting property? <s> This idea can be defined as partition regularity. <s> For example, consider a complete graph of order "n"; that is, there are "n" vertices and each vertex is connected to every other vertex by an edge. <s> A complete graph of order 3 is called a triangle. <s> Now colour every edge red or blue. <s> How large must "n" be in order to ensure that there is either a blue triangle or a red triangle? <s> It turns out that the answer is 6. <s> Another way to express this result is as follows: at any party with at least six people, there are three people who are either (a) mutual acquaintances (each one knows the other two) or (b) mutual strangers (each one does not know either of the other two).

title: British Rail Engineering Limited
complex: British Rail Engineering Limited (BREL), incorporated on 31 October 1969, was the railway systems engineering subsidiary of British Rail until the design and building of trains in the UK was privatised in 1989. <s> BREL built prototypes such as the Class 210 DEMU and the experimental high-speed Advanced Passenger Train (APT) tilting during the 1970s and early 1980s. <s> The Class 210 were externally very similar to the first batch of Class 317 EMUs, but half of the forward carriage was taken up by the engine room.
simple: BREL stands for British Rail Engineering Limited, which was the engineering division for British Rail until the design and building trains in the United Kingdom went private. <s> They made trains like the British Rail Class 210 diesel multiple unit and the experimental Advanced Passenger Train (APT) tilting High Speed Train during the 1970s and early 1980s.

title: Ecological succession
complex: Ecological succession is the process of change in the species structure of an ecological community over time. <s> The time scale can be decades (for example, after a wildfire), or even millions of years after a mass extinction.
simple: Ecological succession, is the process by which a specific ecology has more or less orderly and predictably changed after a disturbance like a fire. <s> In long-term studies, there is a species succession process in the way forests develop.

title: Frýdlant

title: Fushimi Inari-taisha
complex: Fushimi Inari-taisha (伏見稲荷大社 ) is the head shrine of the "kami" Inari, located in Fushimi-ku, Kyoto, Kyoto Prefecture, Japan. <s> The shrine sits at the base of a mountain also named Inari which is 233 m above sea level, and includes trails up the mountain to many smaller shrines which span 4 km and take approximately 2 hours to walk up. <s> This popular shrine is said to have as many as 32,000 sub-shrines ("bunsha" (分社 ) ) throughout Japan. <s> From 1871 through 1946, Fushimi Inari-taisha was officially designated one of the "Kanpei-taisha" (官幣大社 ) , meaning that it stood in the first rank of government supported shrines.
simple: Fushimi Inari-taisha (伏見稲荷大社) is a large Shinto shrine in Fushimi Kyoto, Japan. <s> It is the head shrine of Inari, the rice god. <s> There are 32,000+ sub-shrines or "bunsha" (分社). <s> From 1871 through 1946, it was in the first rank of government supported shrines.

title: Die Deutschen Inschriften
complex: The project "Deutsche Inschriften Online" (engl.: German Inscriptions Online) was planned and implemented as an interacademic venture by the Academies of Sciences in Mainz and Göttingen. <s> The project's aim was to digitise the volumes DI 66/45/56/58/61 and make them available online. <s> The realisation is based on a database which was developed by the Inscription-offices in Greifswald and Mainz. <s> The venture has an innovative character. <s> It is a broadening of the project "Inschriften Mittelrhein-Hunsrück (IMH)" (engl.: Inscriptions of the Middlerhine-Hunsrück) conducted in 2008 in cooperation with the "Institut für Geschichtliche Landeskunde an der Universität Mainz" (engl.: Institute for Regional History located at the University of Mainz). <s> The project digitised the volume "Die Inschriften des Rhein-Hunsrück Kreises I (DI 60)" (engl.: The Inscriptions of the Rhine-Hunsrück District) edited by epigraphist Eberhard J. Nikitsch. <s> In the meantime the website of the IMH-Project has merged into the DIO-Web portal. <s> There is a long term plan for digitising and making available online further volumes; and well as providing an English translation of the DIO-Website. <s> Besides the digitized scientific volumes DIO features; an advanced search interface; information concerning epigraphy; a number of regular series, on topics such as "Epigraphischer Tipp" (engl.: Epigraphical Hint) and "Inschrift im Fokus" (engl.: Focused on Inscription); a glossary; and a list of topical weblinks. <s> In addition the site presents a wide range of photographic images and illustrations of inscriptions or similar objects as a means of interlinking all possible information. <s> Currently there are 30 volumes available on the database, including more than 11,000 items and more than 11,000 illustrations and photographs.
simple: The Academies of Sciences in Mainz and Göttingen planed and carried the project "Deutsche Inschriften Online" (English: German Inscriptions Online) out. <s> The project's ambition was to digitalize the volumes DI 66/45/56/58/61 and make them available online. <s> The realisation is based on a database who was developed by the Inscription-offices in Greifswald and Mainz. <s> The venture has an innovative character. <s> It is seeing itself as a broadening of the project "Inschriften Mittelrhein-Hunsrück (IMH)" (English: Inscriptions of the Middlerhine-Hunsrück). <s> The project digitalized the volume "Die Inschriften des Rhein-Hunsrück Kreises I (DI 60)" (English: The Inscriptions of the Rhine-Hunsrück District) edited by epigraphist Eberhard J. Nikitsch. <s> In the meantime the website of the IMH-Project has merged into the DIO-Web portal. <s> In the long run digitalization and making available online of further volumes is scheduled. <s> Also a translation of the DIO-Website into the English language is projected. <s> Besides the digitalized volumes DIO features an elaborated search interface, news concerning epigraphy and series of articles. <s> The series featured are "Epigraphischer Tipp" (English: Epigraphical Hint) and "Inschrift im Fokus" (English: Focused on Inscription). <s> There are also a glossary and a list of topical weblinks. <s> Additionally the site presents a wide array of photographs and pictures of inscriptions or things alike. <s> Today twelve volumes including more than 4170 items and more than 4000 illustrations and photographs can be retrieved by the user.

title: Billy Knight (basketball, born 1979)
complex: William Price Knight (January 20, 1979 – July 8, 2018) was an American professional basketball player. <s> He played college basketball for the UCLA Bruins. <s> His last professional stops were in Japan with Hamamatsu, Osaka, Hyogo and Yamagata. <s> Knight helped the Hamamatsu Higashimikawa Phoenix to their first bj league title in 2009–2010, when he was the league's third-leading scorer, averaging 19.6 points per game. <s> He and teammate Wendell White formed a duo dubbed the "White-Knight Show". <s> In 2012–13, he helped lead the Hyogo Storks to their first Japan Basketball League (JBL2) championship. <s> On June 13, 2018, Knight was arrested on six counts of molestation charges, including two counts of sexual conduct with a minor. <s> He committed suicide through multiple blunt force injuries on July 8 in Phoenix, shortly after posting a video to YouTube talking about his mental illness and encouraged others to seek help.
simple: William Price Knight (January 20, 1979 – July 8, 2018) was an American professional basketball player. <s> His last professional stops were in Japan with Hamamatsu, Osaka, Hyogo and Yamagata. <s> Knight helped the Hamamatsu Higashimikawa Phoenix to their first bj league title in 2009–10, when he was the league's third-leading scorer, averaging 19.6 points per game. <s> Knight abused an ex-girlfriend’s nine-year-old daughter and was arrested on June 13, 2018.

title: Mir Taqi Mir
complex: Mir Muhammad Taqi Mir (February 1723 - 21 September 1810), also known as Mir Taqi Mir or Meer Taqi Meer, was an Urdu poet of the 18th century Mughal India, and one of the pioneers who gave shape to the Urdu language itself. <s> He was one of the principal poets of the Delhi School of the Urdu "ghazal" and is often remembered as one of the best poets of the Urdu language.

title: Josh Brolin
complex: Joshua James Brolin ( ; born February 12, 1968) is an American actor. <s> Brolin has appeared in films such as "The Goonies" (1985), "Mimic" (1997), "Hollow Man" (2000), "Grindhouse" (2007), "No Country for Old Men" (2007), "American Gangster" (2007), "W." (2008), "Milk" (2008), "True Grit" (2010), "Men in Black 3" (2012), "Inherent Vice" (2014), "Sicario" (2015), "Hail, Caesar!" <s> (2016), and "Deadpool 2" (2018). <s> Brolin was born in Santa Monica, California, the son of Jane Cameron (Agee), a wildlife activist who was a native of Corpus Christi, Texas, and actor James Brolin. <s> Brolin was raised on a ranch in Templeton, California, with little exposure to his father's acting career. <s> His parents divorced in 1984, when he was 16 years old. <s> Brolin was married to actress Alice Adair from 1988 until 1994; they have two children. <s> He was engaged to actress Minnie Driver for six months. <s> He married actress Diane Lane on August 15, 2004. <s> Brolin and Lane divorced in 2013. <s> In March 2015, Brolin became engaged to his former assistant and model Kathryn Boyd.
simple: Josh James Brolin (born February 12, 1968) is an American movie, television, stage, and voice actor. <s> He is known for his roles in "W.", "No Country for Old Men", "Milk", "True Grit", and in "Men in Black 3". <s> Brolin was born on February 12, 1968 in Santa Monica, California to James Brolin and to Jane Cameron Agee. <s> He was raised in Corpus Christi, Texas. <s> Brolin was married to Alice Adair from 1988 until they divorced in 1992. <s> Brolin has two children from Adair. <s> He has been married to Diane Lane since 2004. <s> Lane filed for divorce in February 2013.

title: William Saroyan
complex: William Saroyan ( ; August 31, 1908 – May 18, 1981) was an Armenian-American novelist, playwright, and short story writer. <s> He was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for Drama in 1940, and in 1943 won the Academy Award for Best Story for the film adaptation of his novel "The Human Comedy". <s> William Saroyan was born on August 31, 1908 in Fresno, California, to Armenak and Takuhi Saroyan, Armenian immigrants from Bitlis, Ottoman Empire. <s> His father came to New York in 1905 and started preaching in Armenian Apostolic churches. <s> At the age of three, after his father's death, Saroyan, along with his brother and sister, was placed in an orphanage in Oakland, California. <s> He later went on to describe his experience in the orphanage in his writings. <s> Five years later, the family reunited in Fresno, where his mother, Takuhi, had already secured work at a cannery. <s> He continued his education on his own, supporting himself with jobs, such as working as an office manager for the San Francisco Telegraph Company.
simple: William Saroyan (August 31, 1908 - May 18, 1981) was an American author who wrote many plays and short stories about growing up impoverished as the son of Armenian immigrants. <s> Saroyan was born in Fresno, California, the son of an Armenian immigrant. <s> At the age of four, William Saroyan was placed in the Fred Finch Orphanage in Oakland, California, together with his brother and sister - an experience he later described in his writing. <s> Five years later the family reunited in Fresno, where his mother, Takoohi, had obtained work in a cannery.

title: Holly Beach, Louisiana
complex: Holly Beach , also known as the "Cajun Riviera" , is a coastal community in unincorporated community Cameron Parish, Louisiana, United States. <s> Known for crabbing and a drive on the beach, this small Southwest Louisiana community mainly consisted of beach-front cabins called "camps" which, due to the threat of hurricanes, were "built-to-be-rebuilt" by its residents. <s> It is part of the Lake Charles metropolitan area, which has a population of 194,138.

title: Ahmed Kathrada
complex: Ahmed Mohamed Kathrada (21 August 1929 – 28 March 2017), sometimes known by the nickname "Kathy", was a South African politician, political prisoner and anti-apartheid activist. <s> Kathrada's involvement in the anti-apartheid activities of the African National Congress (ANC) led him to his long-term imprisonment following the Rivonia Trial, in which he was held at Robben Island and Pollsmoor Prison. <s> Following his release in 1990, he was elected to serve as a member of parliament, representing the ANC. <s> He authored a book, "No Bread for Mandela – Memoirs of Ahmed Kathrada, Prisoner No. 468/64". <s> Kathrada died at a medical centre in Johannesburg from complications of a cerebral embolism on 28 March 2017, aged 87. <s> He was buried the next day in Johannesburg in accordance with Islamic rites.
simple: Ahmed Mohamed Kathrada (21 August 1929 – 28 March 2017), sometimes known by the nickname "Kathy", was a South African politician and former political prisoner and anti-apartheid activist. <s> Kathrada's involvement in the anti-apartheid activities of the African National Congress (ANC) led him to his long-term imprisonment following the Rivonia Trial. <s> He was held at Robben Island and Pollsmoor Prison with Nelson Mandela and Walter Sisulu. <s> Following his release in 1990, he was elected to serve as a member of parliament, representing the ANC. <s> Kathrada died at a medical center in Johannesburg from complications of a blood clot in the brain on 28 March 2017, aged 87.

title: British Rail Class 22
complex: The British Rail Class 22 or "Baby Warship" was a class of diesel-hydraulic locomotives designed for the Western Region of British Railways and built by the North British Locomotive Company. <s> They were very similar in appearance to the Class 21 diesel-electrics. <s> The nickname "Baby Warship" related to the similarity in appearance (and internal equipment) to the British Rail Class D20/2 or Class 41 "Warship Class". <s> The Class 22s were numbered D6300-D6357.
simple: The British Rail Class 22, originally called the North British Type 2 diesel-hydraulic, was a class of diesel-hydraulic locomotives designed for the Western Region of British Railways and built by North British Locomotive Company. <s> They were very similar in appearance to the Class 21 diesel-electrics. <s> The Class 22 was nicknamed "Baby Warship" because of its similarity to the British Rail Class D20/2.

title: Tiny Toon Adventures
complex: Tiny Toon Adventures is an American animated comedy television series that was broadcast from September 14, 1990 through December 6, 1992 as the first collaborative effort of Warner Bros. <s> Animation and Steven Spielberg's Amblin Entertainment after being conceived in the late 1980s by Tom Ruegger. <s> The show follows the adventures of a group of young cartoon characters who attend Acme Looniversity to become the next generation of characters from the "Looney Tunes" series. <s> The series centers on a group of young cartoon characters who attend a school called Acme Looniversity to be the next generation of "Looney Tunes" characters.
simple: Tiny Toon Adventures, also known as Steven Spielberg Presents Tiny Toon Adventures, is an American animated television series. <s> It follows a group of young cartoon characters who attend Acme Looniversity in the town of Acme Acres to become the next generation of "Looney Tunes" characters.

title: Porfirio Lobo Sosa
complex: Porfirio Lobo Sosa (born 22 December 1947), known as Pepe Lobo, is a Honduran politician and agricultural landowner who served as President of Honduras from 2010 to 2014. <s> A member of the conservative National Party and a former deputy in the National Congress of Honduras from 1990, he was president of the National Congress of Honduras from 2002 to 2006.
simple: Porfirio Lobo Sosa (born 22 December 1947), known as Pepe Lobo is a Honduran politician. <s> He was President of Honduras from 2010 to 2014.

title: Permeance
complex: Permeance, in general, is the degree to which a material admits a flow of matter or energy. <s> Permeance is usually represented by a curly capital P: formula_1.
simple: Permeance is how well matter or energy flows through something. <s> In science, permeance is usually shown as: formula_1.

title: Joseph Strutt (engraver and antiquary)
complex: Joseph Strutt (27 October 1749 – 16 October 1802) was an English engraver, artist, antiquary, and writer. <s> He is today most significant as the earliest and "most important single figure in the investigation of the costume of the past", making him "an influential but totally neglected figure in the history of art in Britain", according to Sir Roy Strong. <s> Strutt died on 16 October 1802 at his house in Charles Street, Hatton Garden, and was buried in St. Andrew's churchyard, Holborn.
simple: Joseph Strutt was an English engraver in 1749. <s> He died in 1802.

title: 39th G8 summit
complex: The 39th G8 summit was held on 17–18 June 2013, at the Lough Erne Resort, a five-star hotel and golf resort on the shore of Lough Erne in County Fermanagh, Northern Ireland, United Kingdom. <s> It was the sixth G8 summit to be held in the United Kingdom and the first to be held in Northern Ireland. <s> The earlier G8 summits hosted by the United Kingdom were held in London (1977, 1984, 1991), Birmingham (1998) and Gleneagles (2005). <s> The attendees included the leaders of the eight G8 member states, as well as representatives of the European Union. <s> A number of national leaders, and heads of international organizations, are traditionally invited to attend the summit and to participate in some, but not all, G8 summit activities. <s> The 39th G8 summit was the first and only summit for Italian Prime Minister Enrico Letta.
simple: The 39th G8 summit took place in Northern Ireland on 17th and 18th June 2013. <s> The meeting was at the Lough Erne Golf Resort in Enniskillen, Northern Ireland <s> Previous G8 summits have been hosted by the United Kingdom at London (1977, 1984, 1991) and Birmingham (1998) in England. <s> A number of national leaders are traditionally invited to attend the summit. <s> They are asked to participate in some, but not all, G8 summit activities. <s> Discussions at the 39th G8 summit will include some issues which remain unresolved from previous summits.

title: Vollèges
complex: Vollèges is a municipality in the district of Entremont in the canton of Valais in Switzerland.
simple: Vollèges is a municipality of the district of Entremont in the canton of Valais in Switzerland.

title: André S. Labarthe
complex: André S. Labarthe (18 December 1931 – 5 March 2018) was a French actor, film producer and director. <s> He starred alongside Anna Karina in the 1962 film "Vivre sa vie". <s> He was the director of many television documentaries that profiles specific individuals, beginning with "Cinéastes de notre temps".
simple: André S. Labarthe (18 December 1931 – 5 March 2018) was a French actor, movie producer and director. <s> Labarthe died in Paris on 5 March 2018 at the age of 86. <s> He starred alongside Anna Karina in the 1962 movie "Vivre sa vie" (1962). <s> Labarthe was the director of many television documentaries and was known for his work "Cinéastes de notre temps".

title: Jean-Léon Gérôme
complex: Jean-Léon Gérôme (11 May 1824 – 10 January 1904) was a French painter and sculptor in the style now known as academicism. <s> The range of his oeuvre included historical painting, Greek mythology, Orientalism, portraits, and other subjects, bringing the academic painting tradition to an artistic climax.
simple: Jean-Léon Gérôme (11th May 1824-10th January 1904) was a French painter and sculptor.

title: Commercial (First)
complex: The Commercial (First) functional constituency is a functional constituency in the elections for the Legislative Council of Hong Kong first created in 1985. <s> The constituency is composed of bodies that are members of the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce entitled to vote at general meetings of the Chamber.
simple: The Commercial (First), is a functional constituency in the elections for the Legislative Council of Hong Kong first created in 1998. <s> The constituency is composed of the members of the associations in the Commercial Industry.

title: Manacor
complex: Manacor (] ) is a town and municipality on the island of Mallorca, part of the Spanish autonomous community of the Balearic Islands. <s> It has tourist areas like Porto Cristo, site of the famous Caves of Drach, and Cales de Mallorca. <s> Manacor has one of the busiest street markets on the island, held every Monday morning. <s> Manacor is famous for furniture manufacture and artificial pearls.
simple: Manacor is a town and a municipality on the island of Majorca. <s> It is well known for its artificial pearls but also for its furniture manufacture.

title: Vianden (canton)
complex: Vianden is a canton in the north of Luxembourg. <s> The capital is Vianden. <s> In January 2006, the commune of Bastendorf was ceded from the canton of Diekirch, to Vianden, increasing its territory by 24.44 km2. <s> Bastendorf subsequently merged with Fouhren to form the new commune of Tandel.
simple: Vianden is a canton in the north of Luxembourg. <s> Its capital is Vianden. <s> On 1 January 2006, the "communes" of Bastendorf (in the Diekirch canton) and Fouhren were merged to form the "commune" of Tandel.

title: Eduardo da Silva
complex: Eduardo Alves da Silva (] ; born 25 February 1983), commonly known as Eduardo, sometimes nicknamed Dudu, is a Brazilian-born Croatian footballer.
simple: Eduardo da Silva (born 25 February 1983) is a Croatian football player.

title: Kolbingen
complex: Kolbingen is a town in the district of Tuttlingen in Baden-Württemberg in Germany. <s> It is situated about 15 km northeast of Tuttlingen and 7 km from Mühlheim an der Donau. <s> To help people to help themselves Württemberg plant alley of fruit-trees.(
simple: Kolbingen is a municipality in the district of Tuttlingen in Baden-Württemberg in Germany. <s> It is about 15 km northeast of Tuttlingen and 7 km from Mühlheim an der Donau.

title: Dourados
complex: Dourados is a Brazilian municipality, situated in the state of Mato Grosso do Sul, 225 km Southwest of Campo Grande (the state's capital). <s> It has a population of about 210,000 inhabitants, and its economy is based mainly in arable agriculture (particularly Soya, Maize and Sugar Cane) and in cattle ranching. <s> Dourados is also the second most populous and important city of this state.
simple: Dourados is a Brazilian city of the state of Mato Grosso do Sul. <s> It has about 200,000 inhabitants and an area of 4,086 km2.

title: Kapurthala State
complex: Kapurthala State, with its capital at Kapurthala, was a former Princely state of Punjab, Ruled by Ahluwalia Sandhu Sikh rulers, spread across 352 sqmi . <s> According to the 1901 census the state had a population of 314,341 and contained two towns and 167 villages.
simple: Kapurthala State ( (Gurmukhi), کپورتھلہ (Shahmukhi), कपूरथला (Devanagari)), with its capital at Kapurthala, was a princely state in East Punjab. <s> It was spread across 352 sqmi.

title: Nielsen ratings
complex: Nielsen ratings are the audience measurement systems operated by Nielsen Media Research that seek to determine the audience size and composition of television programming in the United States using a rating system. <s> Nielsen Media Research was founded by Arthur C. Nielsen, a market analyst who started his career in the 1920s with brand advertising analysis and had expanded into radio market analysis during the 1930s, culminating in Nielsen ratings of radio programming, which was meant to provide statistics as to the markets of radio shows. <s> The first Nielsen ratings for radio programs were released the first week of December 1947. <s> They measured the top 20 programs in four areas: total audience, average audience, cumulative audience, and homes per dollar spent for time and talent. <s> In 1950, Nielsen moved to television, developing a ratings system using the methods he and his company had developed for radio. <s> That method became the primary source of audience measurement information in the US television industry.
simple: Nielsen ratings is an audience measurement system that was developed by the Nielsen Company. <s> They created the system in an effort to determine the audience size and composition of television programming in the United States. <s> The Nielsen Media Research was founded by Arthur Nielsen. <s> Nielsen was a market analyst and began his career in the 1920s. <s> He expanded his career into the radio market analysis during the 1930s. <s> This helped give ratings of radio programing which was meant to provide statistics as to the markets of radio shows. <s> In 1950, Nielsen moved to television and developed ratings systems using the methods he and his company had developed for radios.

title: Grillby
complex: Grillby is a locality situated in Enköping Municipality, Uppsala County, Sweden with 972 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Grillby is a locality in Enköping Municipality in Uppsala County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 972 people lived there.

title: Wolf Point South Tower
complex: Wolf Point South Tower is the tallest of three planned buildings to be developed in the Near North Side community area on the Wolf Point property at a fork in the Chicago River in downtown Chicago. <s> The building was originally planned to be 950 ft tall. <s> However, in late 2018, the naming rights (Salesforce Tower Chicago) were sold for a redesigned shorter tower of 813 ft .
simple: Wolf Point South Tower is the tallest of three planned buildings to be developed in the Near North Side community area on the Wolf Point next to the Chicago River in downtown Chicago. <s> The building is planned to be 950 ft tall.

title: Chicago River
complex: The Chicago River is a system of rivers and canals with a combined length of 156 mi that runs through the city of Chicago, including its center (the Chicago Loop). <s> Though not especially long, the river is notable because it is one of the reasons for Chicago's geographic importance: the related Chicago Portage is a link between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River Basin, and ultimately the Gulf of Mexico. <s> The river is represented on the Municipal Flag of Chicago by two horizontal blue stripes. <s> Its three branches serve as the inspiration for the Municipal Device, a three-branched, Y-shaped symbol that is found on many buildings and other structures throughout Chicago. <s> The Main Stem flows 1.5 mi west from the controlling works at Lake Michigan; passing beneath the Outer Drive, Columbus Drive, Michigan Avenue, Wabash Avenue, State Street, Dearborn Street, Clark Street, La Salle Street, Wells Street, and Franklin Street bridges "en route" to its confluence with the North Branch at Wolf Point. <s> At McClurg Court it passes the Nicholas J Melas Centennial Fountain, which was built in 1989 to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the Metropolitan Water Reclamation District of Greater Chicago; between May and October the fountain sends an arc of water over the river for ten minutes every hour. <s> On the north bank of the river, near the Chicago Landmark Michigan Avenue Bridge, is Pioneer Court, which marks the site of the homestead of Jean Baptiste Point du Sable who is recognized as the founder of Chicago. <s> On the south bank of the river is the site of Fort Dearborn, an army fort, first established in 1803. <s> Notable buildings surrounding this area include the NBC Tower, the Tribune Tower, and the Wrigley Building. <s> The river turns slightly to the south west between Michigan Avenue and State Street, passing the Trump International Hotel and Tower, 35 East Wacker, and 330 North Wabash. <s> Turning west again the river passes Marina City, the Reid, Murdoch & Co. <s> Building, and Merchandise Mart, and 333 Wacker Drive. <s> As part of a more than fifty-year-old Chicago tradition, the Chicago River is dyed green in observance of St. Patrick's Day. <s> The actual event does not necessarily occur on St. Patrick's Day and is scheduled for the Saturday before March 17, unless the 17th falls on a Saturday (when the event takes place on St. Patrick's Day). <s> For the Chicago Cubs rally and parade for their 2016 World Series Championship celebrations, the river was dyed Cubs blue.
simple: The Chicago River is 156 miles long (251 km) and goes through the city of Chicago, Illinois, including the center of the city (the Chicago Loop). <s> The river is not long, but it is known for being the reason why Chicago became an important place, as the connection between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi Valley waterways. <s> The river is memorialized, in part, by two horizontal blue stripes on the Municipal Flag of Chicago. <s> The river also serves as inspiration for one of Chicago's symbols: a three-branched, Y-shaped symbol (called the municipal device) is found on many buildings and other structures throughout Chicago; it represents the three branches of the Chicago River. <s> The Main Stem flows 1.5 miles (2.4 km) west from the direction at Lake Michigan; passing under the Outer Drive, Columbus Drive, Michigan Avenue, Wabash Avenue, State Street, Dearborn Street, Clark Street, La Salle Street, Wells Street, and Franklin Street bridges en route to the North Branch at Wolf Point. <s> At McClurg Court it passes the Nicholas J Melas Centennial Fountain, which was built in 1989 to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the Metropolitan Water Reclamation District of Greater Chicago; between May and October the fountain sends an arc of water over the river for ten minutes every hour. <s> On the north bank of the river, near the Chicago Landmark Michigan Avenue Bridge, is Pioneer Court, which marks the site where Jean Baptiste Point du Sable came to Chicago. <s> Point du Sable is known as the founder of Chicago. <s> On the south bank of the river is the site of Fort Dearborn. <s> Well known buildings surrounding this area include the NBC Tower, the Tribune Tower, and the Wrigley Building. <s> The river turns slightly to the south west between Michigan Avenue and State Street, passing the Trump International Hotel and Tower, 35 East Wacker, and 330 North Wabash. <s> Turning west again the river passes Marina City, the Reid, Murdoch & Co. <s> Building, Merchandise Mart, and 333 Wacker Drive. <s> The Chicago River is also noted for the local custom of dyeing it green on St. Patrick's Day. <s> For the Chicago Cubs rally and parade for their 2016 World Series Championship celebrations, the river was dyed Cubs blue.

title: WaveBird Wireless Controller
complex: The WaveBird Wireless Controller (stylized as WAVEBIRD, commonly abbreviated as WaveBird or WaveBird controller) is a radio frequency-based wireless controller manufactured by Nintendo for use with the Nintendo GameCube home video game console. <s> Its name is a reference to Dolphin, the GameCube's codename during development. <s> The WaveBird was available for purchase separately as well as in bundles with either "Metroid Prime" or "Mario Party 4", which were exclusive to Kmart in the US. <s> Radio Frequency controllers were not possible in the late 1980s as the early digital RF links were bulky and used too much power to be useful in battery-powered devices. <s> However, advancements in integrated circuits made radio controllers for game consoles commercially viable only a decade later. <s> The WaveBird, released in 2002, solved previous usability problems of wireless controllers by relying on radio frequency communication instead of infrared, allowing the controller to be used anywhere within 6 meters (20 ft) of the console. <s> Although Nintendo only certifies the WaveBird to work within this 6 meter (20 ft) range, tests have proven that they may work as far as 27.5 meters (90 ft) on all 16 different channels. <s> The WaveBird Wireless Controller maintains the same overall aesthetic design as the standard GameCube controller. <s> The components (analog sticks, buttons, and triggers) and layout remain the same, while adding wireless functionality and space for two standard AA batteries. <s> It is somewhat larger and heavier than a standard GameCube controller, with a channel selector dial, an on/off switch, and an orange LED power indicator on the face of the controller in place of the gap between the D-pad and the C-stick. <s> Functionally, the only feature the WaveBird controller lacks compared to the standard controller is the rumble feature, the motors of which would reduce battery life. <s> Like all GameCube controllers, the WaveBird Wireless Controller is compatible with the Wii, for use with GameCube and Virtual Console titles as well as certain Wii games and WiiWare titles. <s> Since the launch of the Wii, the WaveBird has seen increased popularity due to its ability to control these games wirelessly.
simple: The WaveBird Wireless Controller is a wireless game controller for the Nintendo GameCube video game console. <s> Its name is a reference to Dolphin, which is what the GameCube was named during development. <s> It was released in 2002. <s> The WaveBird controller has the same design as the normal GameCube controllers. <s> It is a little bigger and heavier than the normal GameCube controllers. <s> It has a dial for selecting the channel a person wants the controller on, an on/off switch, and an orange LED light which is used to show that the controller is turned on. <s> The WaveBird does not have the rumble feature that the normal GameCube controller has, as that would make the battery last for a shorter amount of time. <s> Like the normal GameCube controller, the WaveBird can be used with the Wii. <s> It can be used for GameCube and Virtual Console titles, as well as with some Wii games and WiiWare titles. <s> The WaveBird became more popular after the Wii's release because of how it can control those games wirelessly.

title: Yucatán Channel
complex: The Yucatán Channel or Straits of Yucatán (Spanish: "Canal de Yucatán") is a strait between Mexico and Cuba. <s> It connects the Yucatán Basin of the Caribbean Sea with the Gulf of Mexico. <s> It is just over 200 km wide and nearly 2800 m deep at its deepest point near the coast of Cuba.
simple: The Yucatán Channel is a strait between Mexico and Cuba. <s> It is also called the Straits of Yucatán. <s> The channel connects the Caribbean Sea with the Gulf of Mexico. <s> It is just over 200 km wide. <s> It is about 2800 m deep at its deepest point near the coast of Cuba.

title: Imam Reza shrine
complex: The Imam Reza shrine in Mashhad, Iran is a complex which contains the mausoleum of Imam Reza, the eighth Imam of Twelver Shiites. <s> It is the largest mosque in the world by area. <s> Also contained within the complex are the Goharshad Mosque, a museum, a library, four seminaries, a cemetery, the Razavi University of Islamic Sciences, a dining hall for pilgrims, vast prayer halls, and other buildings. <s> The complex is one of the tourism centers in Iran and has been described as "the heart of the Shia Iran" with 12 million Iranian and non-Iranian Shias visiting the shrine each year, according to a 2007 estimate. <s> The complex is managed by Astan Quds Razavi Foundation currently headed by a prominent Iranian cleric, Ahmad Marvi
simple: Imām Rezā shrine (Persian: ) is a complex in Mashhad, Iran. <s> It contains the mausoleum of Imām Ridhā, the eighth Imām of Twelver Shi'ites. <s> Also in the complex are the Goharshad Mosque, a museum, a library, seminaries, a cemetery, a dining hall for pilgrims, vast prayer halls, and other buildings. <s> This complex is the center of tourism in Iran.

title: Beaulon
complex: Beaulon is a commune in the Allier department in central France.
simple: Beaulon is a French commune. <s> It is in the Allier department in the center of France.

title: Sorites paradox
complex: The sorites paradox ( ; sometimes known as the paradox of the heap) is a paradox that arises from vague predicates. <s> A typical formulation involves a heap of sand, from which grains are individually removed. <s> Under the assumption that removing a single grain does not turn a heap into a non-heap, the paradox is to consider what happens when the process is repeated enough times: is a single remaining grain still a heap? <s> If not, when did it change from a heap to a non-heap? <s> Another formulation is to start with a grain of sand, which is clearly not a heap, and then assume that adding a single grain of sand to something that is not a heap does not turn it into a heap. <s> Inductively, this process can be repeated as much as one wants without ever constructing a heap. <s> A more natural formulation of this variant is to assume a set of colored chips exists such that two adjacent chips vary in color too little for human eyesight to be able to distinguish between them.
simple: Sorites paradox (also called Paradox of the heap) is a paradox that arises when unclear terms are used. <s> There are different versions, but a typical one involves a heap of sand. <s> The heap is made of many grains of sand. <s> If one begins with one grain of sand and adds another, and then another; when do the grains of sand become a heap? <s> This process can be repeated, until only one grain of sand is left.

title: Vujadin Boškov
complex: Vujadin Boškov (, ] ; 16 May 1931 – 27 April 2014) was a Serbian footballer and coach. <s> Boškov died after long illness in Novi Sad, on 27 April 2014, aged 82.
simple: Vujadin Boškov (16 May 1931 – 27 April 2014) was a former Serbian football player. <s> Boškov died on 27 April 2014 in Novi Sad, aged 82.

title: Herman Philipse
complex: Herman Philipse (born 13 May 1951) is a professor of philosophy at Utrecht University in the Netherlands. <s> Philipse taught at Leiden University from 1986 until 2003 where he obtained his doctorate in 1983.
simple: Herman Philipse (born May 13, 1951 in The Hague) is a Dutch philosopher, specialized in epistemology. <s> Since 2003 he has been a philosophy professor at Utrecht University. <s> From 1986 to 2003 he was a philosophy professor at Leiden University.

title: PZL-102 Kos
complex: The PZL-102 Kos ("blackbird") is a Polish two-seat touring and training monoplane designed and built by PZL.
simple: The PZL 102 Kos is a Polish training and sport light aircraft.

title: Clumsy (Our Lady Peace album)
complex: Clumsy is the second studio album by the Canadian rock band Our Lady Peace, released on January 23, 1997 by Columbia Records. <s> The album is the band's most successful to date, achieving diamond status in Canada (1 million units sold) and strong sales in other countries, including platinum status in the U.S. for another 1 million sales. <s> In 2007, it ranked No. 76 on "The Top 100 Canadian Albums" by Bob Mersereau and No. 33 on The Top 102 New Rock Albums of All Time by 102.1 The Edge (in 2009). <s> The album features five hit singles: "Superman's Dead", "Automatic Flowers", "Clumsy", "4am" and "Carnival".
simple: Clumsy is the second studio album by Canadian rock band Our Lady Peace. <s> It was released on January 23, 1997. <s> It sold over 1,000,000 copies making it diamond status in Canada. <s> It peaked #33 on The Top 102 New Rock Albums of All Time by 102.1 The Edge in 2009.

title: Ralph J. Lamberti
complex: Ralph J. Lamberti (born November 14, 1934) is a member of the Democratic Party, and held the office of borough president of Staten Island, New York from 1984 to 1989. <s> On November 10, 1984, Lamberti was sworn in as the 12th Borough President of Staten Island.
simple: Ralph J. Lamberti (born November 14, 1934) is an American politician. <s> He is a member of the Democratic Party. <s> Lamberti was borough president of Staten Island, New York from 1984 to 1989.

title: Jack Hills
complex: The Jack Hills are a range of hills in Mid West Western Australia. <s> They are best known as the source of the oldest material of terrestrial origin found to date: Hadean zircons that formed around 4.39 billion years ago. <s> These zircons have enabled ground-breaking research into the conditions on earth in the Hadean eon. <s> In 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks there.
simple: The Jack Hills are a range of hills in Western Australia. <s> They include the oldest material of terrestrial origin found on Earth. <s> These are zircons which formed about 4.4 billion years ago (bya). <s> The zircons are used in research on the conditions on Earth in the Hadean eon.

title: Jefferson County, Arkansas
complex: Jefferson County, Arkansas is a county located in the U.S. state of Arkansas in the area known as the Arkansas Delta, that extends west of the Mississippi River. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 77,435. <s> Its county seat and largest city is Pine Bluff. <s> Jefferson County is Arkansas's 21st county, formed on November 2, 1829, from portions of Arkansas and Pulaski counties, and named for Thomas Jefferson, third President of the United States. <s> Jefferson County is included in the Pine Bluff, Arkansas Metropolitan Statistical Area.
simple: Jefferson County is a county in the Arkansas Delta of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 77,435. <s> Its county seat and largest city is Pine Bluff. <s> Jefferson County was founded on November 2, 1829, and named for Thomas Jefferson, third President of the United States (1801–1809).

title: Vautorte
complex: Vautorte is a commune in the Mayenne department in north-western France.
simple: It is in the Pays de la Loire region in the Mayenne department in northwest France.

title: Saxon Switzerland
complex: Saxon Switzerland is a hilly climbing area and national park around the Elbe valley south-east of Dresden in Saxony, Germany. <s> Together with the Bohemian Switzerland in the Czech Republic it forms the Elbe Sandstone Mountains. <s> Saxon Switzerland alone has some 1,000 climbing peaks, as well as several hollows. <s> The area is popular with Dresden locals and international climbers. <s> The administrative district for the area is Sächsische Schweiz-Osterzgebirge. <s> The fortress of Königstein is a well-known landmark. <s> The German name for Saxon Switzerland, "Sächsische Schweiz", appeared in the 18th century. <s> Two Swiss artists, Adrian Zingg and Anton Graff, were appointed in 1766 to the Dresden Academy of Art. <s> They felt the landscape was reminiscent of their homeland, the Swiss Jura, and reported in their exchange of letters on the difference between their homeland and "Saxon Switzerland". <s> Previously, the Saxon part of the Elbe Sandstone Mountains had merely been referred to as the Meissen Highlands ("Meißner Hochland"), Meissen Oberland ("Meißen Oberland") or Heath above Schandau ("Heide über Schandau"). <s> In English the usual translation is "Saxon Switzerland". <s> However other sources call it "Saxony Switzerland" or even "Swiss Saxony". <s> The development of the area for tourism began in earnest in the 19th century. <s> In connexion with that, one of the first trolleybus lines in the world was opened in Saxon Switzerland, the Biela Valley Trolleybus, that was in operation from 1901 to 1904 and worked out of Königstein. <s> Romantic artists were inspired by the beauty of wilderness, like the painter Ludwig Richter or the composer Carl Maria von Weber, who set his famous opera "Der Freischütz" with its Wolfsschlucht ("Wolf's Gorge") scene set near the town of Rathen. <s> Saxon Switzerland is characterized by its sandstone rocks which draw many rock climbers. <s> There are some 14,000 climbing routes on over 1,100 rock pinnacles. <s> At the beginning of the 20th century, the Saxon Rules for rock climbing were established. <s> They are considered to be one of the origins of free climbing.
simple: It is a mountainous climbing area and national park near Dresden in Saxony, Germany. <s> It is called the Bohemian Switzerland in the Czech Republic. <s> Sächsische Schweiz has some 1,000 climbing peaks, as well as several hollows. <s> The area is popular with Dresden locals and international climbers. <s> The administrative district for the area is Sächsische Schweiz Rural District. <s> Sächsische Schweiz means "Saxon Switzerland" in English. <s> The area became popular with tourists during the 19th century. <s> Romantic artists were inspired by the beauty of wilderness, like the painter Ludwig Richter or the composer Carl Maria von Weber, who set his famous opera Der Freischütz with its Wolfsschlucht ("wolf's gorge") scene near the city of Rathen. <s> Saxon Switzerland is characterized by its sandstone rocks which draw many rock climbers. <s> At the beginning of the 20th century the 'Saxon Rules' for rock climbing were made, the first ever of their kind worldwide.

title: Children in the military
complex: The Convention on the Rights of the Child defines a child as any person under the age of 18. <s> In 2002 the Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers (now Child Soldiers International) said that, "while there are reports of children participating in hostilities, there is no evidence of systematic recruitment by armed groups".
simple: The age limit of 18 years is taken from the Convention on the Rights of the Child. <s> The Coalition to stop the use of Child Soldiers says that no one less than 18 years old should be recruited by regular or auxiliary troops.

title: Mamie Van Doren
complex: Mamie Van Doren (born Joan Lucille Olander; February 6, 1931) is an American actress, model, singer, and sex symbol who is known for being one of the first actresses to imitate the look of Marilyn Monroe. <s> Van Doren is perhaps best remembered for the rock 'n' roll, juvenile delinquency exploitation movie "Untamed Youth" (1957), and other films of this calibre. <s> Van Doren was born on February 6, 1931, in Rowena, South Dakota, the daughter of Warner Carl Olander (1908 – 1992) and Lucille Harriet Bennett (1912 – 1995). <s> She is of three-quarters Swedish ancestry; the remainder is mixed English and German.
simple: Mamie Van Doren (born February 6) is an American actress and model. <s> Her many movies include "Untamed Youth" (1957). <s> Mamie was born in Rowena, South Dakota. <s> Her date of birth is varied between 1931 and 1934.

title: She-Hulk
complex: She-Hulk (Jennifer Walters) is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. <s> Created by writer Stan Lee and artist John Buscema, she first appeared in "Savage She-Hulk" #1 (cover-dated February 1980). <s> Following an injury, Walters received an emergency blood transfusion from her cousin, Bruce Banner, and acquired a milder version of his Hulk condition. <s> As such, Walters becomes a large, powerful green-hued version of herself while still largely retaining her personality. <s> In particular, she retains her intelligence and emotional control, although like Hulk, she still becomes stronger if enraged.
simple: Her alter ego is Jennifer Walters, and she became She-Hulk after an injury. <s> She-hulk is a human mutate created by Marvel Comics in 1980. <s> She needed an emergency blood transplant, and received one from her cousin, Bruce Banner (Hulk). <s> She then contracted a milder condition of his disease, meaning that she can turn green and powerful, yet still retain her emotional stability and her personality.

title: Hayden, Idaho
complex: Hayden is a city in Kootenai County, Idaho, United States. <s> Located in the northern portion of the state, it is a suburb of nearby Coeur d'Alene and its population was 13,294 at the 2010 census.
simple: Hayden is a city of Kootenai County in the state of Idaho in the United States.

title: Ross County F.C.
complex: Ross County Football Club is a Scottish professional football club based in Dingwall, Highland. <s> They play all of their home matches at Victoria Park in Dingwall. <s> The club currently play in the Scottish Premiership, after being promoted from the Scottish Championship in the 2018–19 season. <s> Prior to the 1994–95 season they played in the Highland Football League, a competition they won three times. <s> They have also won the Scottish First Division, Scottish Championship, Second Division, Third Division (once each) and Challenge Cup three times. <s> In 2010, they reached the Scottish Cup Final, and in 2016 they won the Scottish League Cup. <s> Nicknamed "The Staggies", County's colours are dark blue, red and white. <s> Their manager for a very short spell until October 2005, was former Inverness and Hearts manager John Robertson. <s> He left the club on 24 October 2005, due to differences of opinion on a number of fundamental issues with the chairman. <s> Gardner Spiers, a former Aberdeen coach, was appointed caretaker manager, but he too left in April 2006 after being told he would not be considered for appointment on a permanent basis. <s> Director of Football George Adams took temporary charge before former Motherwell player Scott Leitch was appointed on 18 April 2006. <s> Ross County won their first ever nationwide trophy when they won the Scottish Challenge Cup in November 2006 on penalties with Jason Crooks scoring the deciding spot kick on his competitive debut. <s> Leitch, after winning the Challenge Cup but suffering relegation, stood down at the end of the 2006–07 season, almost exactly one year after his appointment. <s> Former Partick Thistle manager Dick Campbell was announced as his replacement in May 2007. <s> However, after a good run of results to start their Division 2 campaign, Campbell and the Ross County board decided to part company on 2 October 2007. <s> Derek Adams (son of George Adams) took over as caretaker, and was confirmed as permanent manager a month later, after the side's good form continued. <s> County again reached the final of the Scottish Challenge Cup in 2008.
simple: Ross County F.C. are a Scottish professional football team who currently play in the Scottish Football League. <s> They play their home matches at Victoria Park in the Highland town of Dingwall, Ross and Cromarty. <s> Their manager, up until October 2005, was former Inverness Caledonian Thistle and Heart of Midlothian manager John Robertson. <s> He left the club on the 24 October 2005, due to differences of opinion on a number of fundamental issues with the chairman. <s> Gardner Spiers, a former Aberdeen coach, was appointed caretaker manager, but he too left in April 2006 after being told he would not be considered for appointment on a permanent basis. <s> Director of Football George Adams took temporary charge before former Motherwell player Scott Leitch was appointed on 18 April 2006. <s> Leitch, after winning the Challenge Cup but suffering relegation, stood down at the end of the 2006-2007 season, almost exactly one year after his appointment. <s> Former Partick Thistle manager Dick Campbell was announced as his replacement in May 2007. <s> However, after a good run of results to start their Division 2 campaign, Campbell and the Ross County board decided to part company on 2 October 2007. <s> Derek Adams (son of George Adams) took over as caretaker, and was confirmed as permanent manager a month later, after the side's good form continued.

title: Agent Cody Banks
complex: Agent Cody Banks is a 2003 American spy comedy film directed by Harald Zwart. <s> It follows the adventures of the 15-year-old title character, played by Frankie Muniz, who has to finish his chores, avoid getting grounded, and save the world by going undercover for the CIA as a James Bond type superspy.
simple: ‘’’Agent Cody Banks’’’ is an American film set in 2002.

title: Striptease
complex: A striptease is an erotic or exotic dance in which the performer gradually undresses, either partly or completely, in a seductive and sexually suggestive manner. <s> The person who performs a striptease is commonly known as a "stripper" or exotic dancer. <s> There is a stripping aspect in the ancient Sumerian myth of the descent of the goddess Inanna into the Underworld (or Kur). <s> At each of the seven gates, she removed an article of clothing or a piece of jewelry. <s> As long as she remained in hell, the earth was barren. <s> When she returned, fecundity abounded. <s> Some believe this myth was embodied in the dance of the seven veils of Salome, who danced for King Herod, as mentioned in the New Testament in Matthew 14:6 and Mark 6:21-22. <s> However, although the Bible records Salome's dance, the first mention of her removing seven veils occurs in Oscar Wilde's play of 'Salome', in 1893. <s> In ancient Greece, the lawgiver Solon established several classes of prostitutes in the late 6th century BC. <s> Among these classes of prostitutes were the auletrides: female dancers, acrobats, and musicians, noted for dancing naked in an alluring fashion in front of audiences of men. <s> In ancient Rome, dance featuring stripping was part of the entertainments "(ludi)" at the Floralia, an April festival in honor of the goddess Flora. <s> Empress Theodora, wife of 6th-century Byzantine emperor Justinian is reported by several ancient sources to have started in life as a courtesan and actress who performed in acts inspired from mythological themes and in which she disrobed "as far as the laws of the day allowed". <s> She was famous for her striptease performance of "Leda and the Swan". <s> From these accounts, it appears that the practice was hardly exceptional nor new. <s> It was, however, actively opposed by the Christian Church, which succeeded in obtaining statutes banning it in the following century. <s> The degree to which these statutes were subsequently enforced is, of course, opened to question. <s> What is certain is that no practice of the sort is reported in texts of the European Middle Ages. <s> Some claim the origin of the modern striptease lies in Oscar Wilde's play of 'Salome', in 1893. <s> In the Dance of the Seven Veils the female protagonist dances for King Herod and slowly removes her veils until she lies naked. <s> After Wilde's play and Richard Strauss's operatic version of the same, first performed in 1905, the erotic 'dance of the seven veils', became a standard routine for dancers in opera, vaudeville, film and burlesque. <s> A famous early practitioner was Maud Allan who in 1907 gave a private performance of the dance to King Edward VII. <s> In the 1880s and 1890s, Parisian shows such as the Moulin Rouge and Folies Bergère were featuring attractive scantily clad women dancing and tableaux vivants. <s> In this environment, an act in the 1890s featured a woman who slowly removed her clothes in a vain search for a flea crawling on her body. <s> "The People's Almanac" credits the act as the origin of modern striptease. <s> In 1905, the notorious and tragic Dutch dancer Mata Hari, later shot as a spy by the French authorities during World War I, was an overnight success from the debut of her act at the Musée Guimet. <s> The most celebrated segment of her act was her progressive shedding of clothing until she wore just a jeweled bra and some ornaments over her arms and head. <s> Another landmark performance was the appearance at the Moulin Rouge in 1907 of an actress called Germaine Aymos, who entered dressed only in three very small shells. <s> In the 1920s and 1930s the famous Josephine Baker danced topless in the "danse sauvage" at the Folies and other such performances were provided at the Tabarin. <s> These shows were notable for their sophisticated choreography and often dressing the girls in glitzy sequins and feathers. <s> In his 1957 book "Mythologies", semiotician Roland Barthes interpreted this Parisian striptease as a "mystifying spectacle", a "reassuring ritual" where "evil is advertised the better to impede and exorcise it". <s> By the 1960s "fully nude" shows were provided at such places as Le Crazy Horse Saloon. <s> Also produced in 1965 was "Carousella", a documentary about Soho striptease artistes, directed by John Irvin. <s> Another documentary film, which looked at the unglamorous side of striptease, is the 1966 film called,"Strip", filmed at the Phoenix Club in Soho. <s> "Secrets of a Windmill Girl" (1966) featured Pauline Collins and April Wilding and was directed by Arnold L. Miller.
simple: The Sumerians had a myth of the goddess Inanna descending into the Underworld. <s> At each of the seven gates, she removed an article of clothing or a piece of jewelry. <s> As long as she remained in hell, the earth was barren. <s> When she returned, fecundity abounded. <s> Salome's dance for King Herod is referred to in the New Testament (Matthew 14:6 and Mark 6:21-22). <s> However, the first mention of her removing seven veils is in Oscar Wilde's play of "Salome" in 1893. <s> In ancient Greece, the lawgiver Solon established several classes of prostitutes in the late 6th century BC. <s> Among these were the "auletrides": female dancers, acrobats, and musicians, noted for dancing naked in an alluring fashion in front of audiences of men. <s> In ancient Rome, dance featuring stripping was part of the Floralia, an April festival. <s> Empress Theodora, wife of 6th-century Byzantine emperor Justinian is reported by several ancient sources to have started in life as a courtesan and actress who performed in acts inspired from mythological themes and in which she disrobed "as far as the laws of the day allowed". <s> She was famous for her striptease performance of "Leda and the Swan". <s> From these accounts, it appears that the practice was not exceptional or new. <s> It was, however, actively opposed by the Christian Church, which got statutes banning it in the following century. <s> The degree to which these statutes were enforced is open to question. <s> No practice of the sort is reported in texts of the European Middle Ages. <s> Some have claimed as the origin of modern striptease. <s> After Wilde's play and Richard Strauss's opera "Salome", first performed in 1905 the erotic 'dance of the seven veils', became a standard routine in opera, vaudeville, film and burlesque. <s> A famous early practitioner was Maud Allan who in 1907 gave a private performance of the dance to Edward VII. <s> In the 1880s and 1890s, Parisian shows such as the Moulin Rouge and Folies Bergère had attractive scantily-clad women dancing and "tableaux vivants" (static poses). <s> Acts in the 1890s had a woman slowly removed clothes in a vain search for a flea crawling on her body. <s> The "People's Almanac" credits this as the origin of modern striptease. <s> Starting in 1905, Mata Hari entered the scene. <s> Another landmark performance was the appearance at the Moulin Rouge in 1907 of an actress called Germaine Aymos who entered dressed only in three very small shells. <s> In the 1930s the famous Josephine Baker danced semi-nude in the "danse sauvage" at the Folies and other such performances were provided at the Tabarin. <s> These shows were notable for their sophisticated choreography and often dressing the girls in glitzy sequins and feathers. <s> By the 1960s "fully nude" shows were provided at such places as Le Crazy Horse Saloon. <s> There is also a film called "Striptease".

title: Mytilus (bivalve)
complex: Mytilus is a cosmopolitan genus of medium to large-sized edible, mainly saltwater mussels, marine bivalve molluscs in the family Mytilidae. <s> Species within the genus "Mytilus" include: "Mytilus" mussels are widely exploited as food and used in marine-culture. <s> For instance, in California, they have been consumed by coastal Native American people for almost 12 000 years.
simple: Mytilus is a common genus of medium to large-sized marine mussels. <s> They are bivalve molluscs of the family Mytilidae. <s> "Mytilus" mussels are widely used as food. <s> In California they were eaten by coastal Native American people for almost 12,000 years.

title: Hyades (mythology)
complex: In Greek mythology, the Hyades ( ; , popularly "rain-makers" or "the rainy ones" from ὕω "hyo" "I fall as rain", but probably from ὗς "hys" "swine") are a sisterhood of nymphs that bring rain. <s> The Hyades were daughters of Atlas (by either Pleione or Aethra, one of the Oceanides) and sisters of Hyas in most tellings, although one version gives their parents as Hyas and Boeotia. <s> The Hyades are sisters to the Pleiades and the Hesperides. <s> The main myth concerning them is envisioned to account for their collective name and to provide an etiology for their weepy raininess: Hyas was killed in a hunting accident and the Hyades wept from their grief. <s> They were changed into a cluster of stars, the Hyades, set in the head of Taurus. <s> Their number varies from three in the earliest sources to fifteen in the late ones. <s> The names are also variable, according to the mythographer, and include: Additionally, Thyone and Prodice were supposed to be daughters of Hyas by Aethra, and have been added to the group of stars.
simple: In Greek mythology the Hyades were nymphs who were responsible for letting it rain. <s> They were the daughters of Atlas, and most stories say that they were the sisters of Hyas. <s> The main story is that Hyas was killed in a hunting accident, so the Hyades wept because of their grief. <s> Their number varies from originally three to fifteen.

title: Kilometres per hour
complex: The kilometre per hour (American English: kilometer per hour) is a unit of speed, expressing the number of kilometres travelled in one hour. <s> Internationally, km/h is the most commonly used unit of speed on traffic signs and speedometers. <s> Several representations of "kilometres per hour" have been used since the term was introduced and many are still in use today; for example, dictionaries list "km/h", "kmph" and "km/hr" as English abbreviations. <s> The SI representations, classified as symbols, are "km/h", "km h " and "km·h ".
simple: Kilometres per hour is a unit of measurement, which measures speed or velocity. <s> The unit is the most commonly used unit of speed worldwide, more common than the SI unit of speed, metres per second. <s> The unit symbol is km/h or km·h. By definition, an object travelling at a speed of 1 km/h in a straight line for 1 hour moves 1 kilometre.

title: Yorkshire and the Humber
complex: Yorkshire and the Humber is one of nine official regions of England at the first level of Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics (NUTS) for statistical purposes. <s> It comprises most of Yorkshire (the administrative areas of South Yorkshire, West Yorkshire, East Riding of Yorkshire, Hull, North Yorkshire and the City of York), as well as North Lincolnshire and North East Lincolnshire. <s> It does not include Middlesbrough, Redcar and Cleveland or other areas of the historic county of Yorkshire, such as Sedbergh not included in the aforementioned administrative areas. <s> The largest settlements are, Leeds, Sheffield, Bradford, Hull, and York. <s> The population in 2011 was 5,284,000. <s> The highest point of the region is Whernside, in the Yorkshire Dales, at 737 m . <s> The largest freshwater lake in the region is Hornsea Mere in the East Riding of Yorkshire. <s> Key: †shire county | *metropolitan county
simple: Yorkshire and the Humber is one of the regions of England. <s> It covers most of the historic county of Yorkshire, along with the part of northern Lincolnshire that was previously in the administrative area of Humberside (which existed 1974-1996). <s> The highest point of the region is Whernside, in the Yorkshire Dales, at 737 metres. <s> The largest freshwater lake is Hornsea Mere in the East Riding of Yorkshire. <s> Key: shire county = † | metropolitan county = *

title: Gomel Region
complex: Gomel Region or Homyel’ Voblasc’ is one of the regions of Belarus. <s> Its administrative center is Gomel. <s> The total area of the region is 40400 km2 , the population in 2011 stood at 1,435,000 with the number of inhabitants per km at 36. <s> Important cities within the region include: Gomel, Mazyr, Zhlobin, Svietlahorsk, Rechytsa, Kalinkavichy, Rahachow, Dobrush. <s> Both the Gomel Region and the Mogilev Region suffered severely after the Chernobyl nuclear reactor catastrophe. <s> The Gomel Province borders the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone in places, and parts of it is designated as mandatory or voluntary resettlement areas as a result of the radioactive contamination. <s> Gomel Region comprises 21 districts and 2 city municipalities. <s> The districts comprise 278 selsovets, 17 cities and towns.
simple: Homiel Voblast or Gomel Oblast is a province (voblast) of Belarus. <s> Its administrative center is Homyel. <s> Important cities in the voblast include: Gomel, Mazyr, Zhlobin, Svetlahorsk, Rechytsia, Kalinkavichy, Rahachow, Dobrush <s> Homiel Province and Mahilyow Voblast were hurt severely after the Chernobyl nuclear reactor catastrophe. <s> The Gomel Province borders the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone in places. <s> Part of it is a mandatory or voluntary resettlement areas as a result of the radioactive contamination. <s> The Homiel Voblast has 21 districts (raions), 278 selsovets, 17 cities, and 8 city municipalities.

title: Vietnam Airlines
complex: Vietnam Airlines is the flag carrier of Vietnam. <s> The airline was founded in 1956 and later established as a state-owned enterprise in April 1989. <s> Vietnam Airlines is headquartered in Long Biên District, Hanoi, with hubs at Noi Bai International Airport and Tan Son Nhat International Airport. <s> The airline flies to 64 destinations in 17 countries, excluding codeshared services. <s> Vietnam Airlines became a member of SkyTeam in June 2010, making it the first Southeast Asian carrier to have joined that alliance.
simple: Vietnam Airlines is the flag carrier and the largest airline of Vietnam. <s> It was started by the government in 1956. <s> Since June 2010, it has been a member of SkyTeam.

title: David Hockney
complex: David Hockney, (born 9 July 1937) is an English painter, draftsman, printmaker, stage designer, and photographer. <s> As an important contributor to the pop art movement of the 1960s, he is considered one of the most influential British artists of the 20th century. <s> On 15 November 2018, Hockney's 1972 work "Portrait of an Artist (Pool with Two Figures)" sold at Christie's auction house in New York City for $90 million (£70 million), becoming the most expensive work by a living artist sold at auction. <s> This broke the previous record, set by the 2013 sale of Jeff Koons' "Balloon Dog (Orange)" for $58.4 million. <s> Hockney held this record until 15 May 2019, Jeff Koons reclaimed the honour when his "Rabbit" sold for more than $91 million dollars at Christie's in New York. <s> Hockney was born in Bradford, West Yorkshire, England, to Laura and Kenneth Hockney (a conscientious objector in the Second World War), the fourth of five children. <s> He was educated at Wellington Primary School, Bradford Grammar School, Bradford College of Art (where his teachers included Frank Lisle and his fellow students included Norman Stevens, David Oxtoby and John Loker) and the Royal College of Art in London, where he met R. B. Kitaj.
simple: David Hockney (born 9 July 1937) is a British artist. <s> An important contributor to the pop art movement of the 1960s, he is one of the most influential artists of the 20th century. <s> Hockney's 1972 work "Portrait of an Artist (Pool with Two Figures)" sold at auction and broke the world record for a living artist on 15 November 2018 when it sold for $90 million (£70 million) at Christie's auction house New York City. <s> He was born in Bradford, West Riding of Yorkshire.

title: Ames, Pas-de-Calais
complex: Ames is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region of France.
simple: Ames, Pas-de-Calais is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: President of Cyprus
complex: The President of Cyprus is the head of state and the head of government of the Republic of Cyprus. <s> The office was created in 1960, after Cyprus gained its independence from the United Kingdom. <s> Currently, the President of Cyprus is Nicos Anastasiades, since 28 February 2013.
simple: The President of Cyprus is the head of state and the head of government of the Republic of Cyprus. <s> The office was created in 1960, after Cyprus gained its independence from the United Kingdom. <s> The current President of Cyprus is Nicos Anastasiades.

title: George Lowe
complex: George Edward Lowe (born November 10, 1957) is an American voice actor and comedian whose voice roles include Space Ghost on the animated series "Space Ghost Coast to Coast" and its spin-off, "Cartoon Planet". <s> He continued to voice Space Ghost in several cameos in other programs for several years following the conclusion of the series.
simple: George Lowe is an American voice actor.

title: Emmeline Pankhurst
complex: Emmeline Pankhurst (born Emiline Goulden; 15 July 1858 – 14 June 1928) was a British political activist and organizer of the British suffragette movement who helped women win the right to vote. <s> In 1999 "Time" named Pankhurst as one of the , stating "she shaped an idea of women for our time; she shook society into a new pattern from which there could be no going back". <s> She was widely criticised for her militant tactics, and historians disagree about their effectiveness, but her work is recognised as a crucial element in achieving women's suffrage in the United Kingdom. <s> In 1903, Pankhurst founded the Women's Social and Political Union (WSPU), an all-women suffrage advocacy organisation dedicated to "deeds, not words". <s> The group identified as independent from – and often in opposition to – political parties. <s> It became known for physical confrontations: its members smashed windows and assaulted police officers. <s> Pankhurst, her daughters, and other WSPU activists received repeated prison sentences, where they staged hunger strikes to secure better conditions, and were often force-fed. <s> As Pankhurst's eldest daughter Christabel took leadership of the WSPU, antagonism between the group and the government grew. <s> Eventually the group adopted arson as a tactic, and more moderate organisations spoke out against the Pankhurst family. <s> In 1913 several prominent individuals left the WSPU, among them Pankhurst's younger daughters, Adela and Sylvia. <s> Emmeline was so furious that she "gave Adela a ticket, £20, and a letter of introduction to a suffragette in Australia, and firmly insisted that she emigrate". <s> Adela complied and the family rift was never healed. <s> Sylvia became a socialist. <s> With the advent of the First World War, Emmeline and Christabel called an immediate halt to militant suffrage terrorism in support of the British government's stand against the "German Peril". <s> They urged women to aid industrial production and encouraged young men to fight, becoming prominent figures in the white feather movement. <s> In 1918, the Representation of the People Act granted votes to all men over the age of 21 and women over the age of 30. <s> This discrepancy was intended to ensure that men did not become minority voters as a consequence of the huge number of deaths suffered during the First World War. <s> She transformed the WSPU machinery into the Women's Party, which was dedicated to promoting women's equality in public life. <s> In her later years, she became concerned with what she perceived as the menace posed by Bolshevism and joined the Conservative Party. <s> She was selected as the Conservative candidate for Whitechapel and St Georges in 1927. <s> She died on 14 June 1928, only weeks before the Conservative government's Representation of the People Act (1928) extended the vote to all women over 21 years of age on 2 July 1928. <s> She was commemorated two years later with a statue in Victoria Tower Gardens, next to the Houses of Parliament.
simple: Emmeline Pankhurst (née Goulden; 15 July 1858 – 14 June 1928) was the leader of the British suffragette movement which helped women win the right to vote. <s> In 1999 "Time" named Pankhurst as one of the 100 Most Important People of the 20th Century, stating: "she shaped an idea of women for our time; she shook society into a new pattern from which there could be no going back." <s> She was widely criticized for her militant tactics, but her work helped to achieve women's suffrage in Britain. <s> After her husband died in 1898, Pankhurst founded the Women's Social and Political Union (WSPU), an organisation dedicated to "deeds, not words". <s> The group became infamous when its members smashed windows and assaulted police officers. <s> Pankhurst, her daughters, and other WSPU activists were sentenced to repeated prison sentences, where they staged hunger strikes to secure better conditions. <s> As Pankhurst's oldest daughter Christabel took the helm of the WSPU, antagonism between the group and the government grew. <s> Eventually arson became a common tactic among WSPU members, and more moderate organisations spoke out against the Pankhurst family. <s> In 1913 several prominent individuals left the WSPU, among them Pankhurst's daughters Adela and Sylvia. <s> The family rift never healed. <s> With the advent of the First World War, Emmeline and Christabel called an immediate halt to militant suffrage activism in support of the British Government's stand against the "German Peril". <s> They urged women to aid industrial production and encouraged young men to fight. <s> In 1918 the Representation of the People Act granted votes to women over the age of 30 and the WSPU was disbanded. <s> Pankhurst transformed the WSPU machinery into the Women's Party, dedicated to promoting women's equality in public life. <s> In her later years she became concerned with the 'Bolshevik menace' and – unhappy with the political alternatives – joined the Conservative Party. <s> She died in 1928, 17 days before women got equal voting rights and was commemorated two years later with a statue in London's Victoria Tower Gardens.

title: Soupir
complex: Soupir is a commune in the Aisne department in Hauts-de-France in northern France.
simple: Soupir is a commune. <s> It is in the Picardie region in the Aisne department in north France.

title: Ostend Manifesto
complex: The Ostend Manifesto, also known as the Ostend Circular, was a document written in 1854 that described the rationale for the United States to purchase Cuba from Spain while implying that the U.S. should declare war if Spain refused. <s> Cuba's annexation had long been a goal of U.S. slaveholding expansionists, and was supported by a faction in Cuba itself.
simple: The Ostend Manifesto was an 1854 document describing the reasons for the United States to buy Cuba.

title: Liberal Democratic Party (Australia)
complex: The Liberal Democratic Party (shortened as LDP, Liberal Democrats or Lib Dems) is an Australian political party founded in Canberra in 2001. <s> The party espouses smaller government and supports policies that are based on classical liberal and right-libertarian principles. <s> The LDP is a registered party in the Australian Capital Territory, New South Wales, South Australia, Victoria and Western Australia and is also registered for federal elections with the Australian Electoral Commission. <s> It also has a member of the Western Australian Legislative Council, Aaron Stonehouse, two representatives in the Victorian Legislative Council, Tim Quilty and David Limbrick, and elected representatives in some local governments.
simple: The Liberal Democratic Party (abbreviation as LDP or called the Liberal Democrats) is a political party in Australia. <s> It was started in 2001. <s> It also also has two representatives at the local government level in New South Wales.

title: Bit-level parallelism
complex: Bit-level parallelism is a form of parallel computing based on increasing processor word size. <s> Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute in order to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word. <s> (For example, consider a case where an 8-bit processor must add two 16-bit integers. <s> The processor must first add the 8 lower-order bits from each integer, then add the 8 higher-order bits, requiring two instructions to complete a single operation. <s> A 16-bit processor would be able to complete the operation with single instruction.) <s> From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, advancements in computer architecture were done by increasing bit-level parallelism, as 4-bit microprocessors were replaced by 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors. <s> This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which were a standard in general purpose computing for two decades. <s> 64 bit architectures were introduced to the mainstream with the eponymous Nintendo 64 (1996), but beyond this introduction stayed uncommon until the advent of x86-64 architectures around the year 2003, and 2014 for mobile devices with the ARMv8-A instruction set.
