simple: Bit-level parallelism is a form of parallel computing based on increasing processor word size, depending on very-large-scale integration (VLSI) technology. <s> Enhancements in computers designs were done by increasing bit-level parallelism <s> Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute in order to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word. <s> (For example, consider a case where an 8-bit processor must add two 16-bit integers. <s> The processor must first add the 8 lower-order bits from each integer, then add the 8 higher-order bits, requiring two instructions to complete a single operation. <s> A 16-bit processor would be able to complete the operation with single instruction) <s> Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors, then 64-bit microprocessors. <s> 32-bit processors has been a standard in general purpose computing for about 20 years, but now 64-bit processors are taking the lead.

title: Beebe Freitas
complex: Beebe Freitas (August 28, 1938 – February 17, 2018) was an American pianist, organist, vocal coach and educator. <s> She was the Head of Music for Hawaii Opera Theatre. <s> Beatrice Pauline (Botty) Freitas was born in Youngstown, Ohio, to father John Botty and mother Pauline (Esterhay) Botty. <s> Freitas's father was Pastor of the Hungarian United Presbyterian Church in Youngstown, was born in Hungary and was a naturalized citizen of the United States. <s> Freitas's mother was Dean of Women and Head of the Sociology Department at Youngstown State University and an attorney. <s> Beebe married Lewis P. Freitas November 30, 1964 and is the mother of Roslyn Kapuamakalaniepaheahe Freitas Catracchia and John Botty Freitas. <s> She passed away at her home in Aina Haina, Hawaii on February 17, 2018.
simple: Beebe Freitas (August 28, 1938 - February 17, 2018) was an American pianist, organist, vocal coach and educator. <s> She was the Head of Music for Hawaii Opera Theatre. <s> She was born in Youngstown, Ohio. <s> Freitas died at her home in Aina Haina, Hawaii on February 17, 2018 of congestive heart failure at the age of 79.

title: Ardabil
complex: Ardabil ( , , , also romanized as Ardabīl and Ardebīl) is an ancient city in northwestern Iran, and the capital of Ardabil Province. <s> Located in the northeastern part of Iran's historic Azerbaijan region, at the 2011 census, Ardabil's population was 564,365, in 156,324 families. <s> The dominant majority in the city are ethnic Iranian Azerbaijanis and the primary language of the people is Azerbaijani. <s> Ardabil is known for its trade in silk and carpets. <s> Ardabil rugs are renowned and the ancient Ardabil Carpets are considered among the best of classical Persian carpets. <s> Ardabil is also home to a World Heritage Site, the Ardabil Shrine, the sanctuary and tomb of Shaikh Safî ad-Dîn, eponymous founder of the Safavid dynasty. <s> The name Ardabil comes from the Avesta "Artavila" which means a "holy town" or a "holy place".
simple: Ardabil (Persian and Azeri: اردبیل, also Romanized as Ardabīl and Ardebīl) is a historical city in north-western Iran. <s> At the 2011 census, its population was 564,365, in 156,324 families, Its inhabitants are ethnic Azeris. <s> Ardabil is also known for the sanctuary and tomb of Shaikh Safî ad-Dîn, eponym of the Safavid Dynasty. <s> The name Ardabil comes from the Zoroastrian name of "Artawila", meaning a holy place.

title: Abdeljalil Hadda
complex: Abdeljalil Hadda ( ; born 23 March 1972), sometimes nicknamed Kamatcho, is a Moroccan retired footballer who played as a striker.
simple: Abdeljalil Hadda (born 21 March 1972) is a former Moroccan football player.

title: Meenad
complex: s of 2001 India census, Meenad had a population of 29497 with 14087 males and 15410 females. <s> Meenad is well connected with Paravur Town and Chathannoor. <s> The well furnished Paravur-Chathannoor road is passing through Meenad. <s> The proximity of this place to Paravur Railway Station and National Highway-47 makes Meenad a major residential area in the district. <s> Paravur Railway Station is an 'Adersh Railway Station', so a good number of important daily trains have halts here.
simple: s of 2001 India census, Meenad had a population of 29497 with 14087 males and 15410 females. <s> Meenad is well connected with Paravur Town and Chathannoor. <s> The well furnished Paravur-Chathannoor road is passing through Meenad. <s> The proximity of this place to Paravur Railway Station and National Highway-47 makes Meenad a major residential area in the district. <s> Paravur Railway Station is an 'Adersh Railway Station', so a good number of important daily trains have halts here.

title: Ralphie May
complex: Ralph Duren May (February 17, 1972 – October 6, 2017) was an American stand-up comedian and actor, known for his extensive touring and comedy specials on Netflix and other outlets. <s> May was born on February 17, 1972, in Chattanooga, Tennessee, and raised in Clarksville, Arkansas, the youngest of 4 children. <s> In 2003, May was chosen to participate in the first season of "". <s> He finished in second place in the competition, with Dat Phan winning first place. <s> Afterwards, May appeared in comedy shows, such as "The Wayne Brady Show" and "The Tonight Show with Jay Leno". <s> In 2005, he was the only white comedian on "The Big Black Comedy Show", which also featured Mo'Nique, Rodman, and Vince Morris. <s> On July 3, 2005, May married comedian Lahna Turner. <s> The couple had two children: daughter April June May and son August James May. <s> The couple filed for divorce in October 2015 and sought physical and joint custody of their children, but the divorce was never finalized. <s> On October 6, 2017, May went into cardiac arrest. <s> May had been battling pneumonia for several weeks and had cancelled shows over the previous month, his publicist Stacey Pokluda confirmed following his death.
simple: Ralph Oliver "Ralphie" May (February 17, 1972 – October 6, 2017) was an American stand-up comedian and actor. <s> He was born in Chattanooga, Tennessee, but raised in Clarksville, Arkansas. <s> In 2003, May was chosen to participate in the first season of "Last Comic Standing". <s> He finished in second place in the competition. <s> After that, he appeared in comedy shows like "The Wayne Brady Show" and "The Tonight Show with Jay Leno". <s> In 2005, he was the only white comedian on "The Big Black Comedy Show", which also featured Mo'Nique, Rodman, and Vince Morris. <s> May was married to Lahna Turner from 2005 until they separated in 2015. <s> They had two children. <s> May died of a pneumonia-related heart attack at his home in Las Vegas, Nevada on October 6, 2017 at the age of 45.

title: San Joaquin Valley
complex: The San Joaquin Valley is the area of the Central Valley of the U.S. state of California that lies south of the Sacramento–San Joaquin River Delta and is drained by the San Joaquin River. <s> It comprises seven counties of Northern and one of Southern California, including, in the north, all of San Joaquin and Kings counties, most of Stanislaus, Merced, and Fresno counties, and parts of Madera and Tulare counties, along with a majority of Kern County, in Southern California. <s> Although a majority of the valley is rural, it does contain cities such as Fresno, Bakersfield, Stockton, Modesto, Turlock, Tulare, Porterville, Visalia, Merced, and Hanford.
simple: The San Joaquin Valley is the area of the Central Valley of the U.S. state of California that lies south of the Sacramento–San Joaquin River Delta and is drained by the San Joaquin River. <s> It is made up of seven Northern California counties—all of Kings County; a majority of Fresno, Merced, Stanislaus counties; segments of Madera and Tulare counties—and a majority of Kern County, in Southern California.

title: The Parent Trap (1961 film)
complex: The Parent Trap is a 1961 Walt Disney Technicolor film. <s> It stars Hayley Mills (in a dual role), Maureen O'Hara and Brian Keith in a story about teenage twins on a quest to reunite their divorced parents. <s> The screenplay by the film's director David Swift was based upon the 1949 book "Lottie and Lisa" (German: ) by Erich Kästner. <s> "The Parent Trap" was nominated for two Academy Awards, was broadcast on television, saw three television sequels, was remade in 1998 with Lindsay Lohan, and has been released on digital stereo LaserDisc format in 1986 as well as VHS and DVD in 2002. <s> The original film was Mills' second of six films for Disney. <s> The film was nominated for two Academy Awards: one for Sound by Robert O. Cook, and the other for Film Editing by Philip W. Anderson. <s> The film and its editor, Philip W. Anderson, won the inaugural 1962 Eddie Award of the American Cinema Editors. <s> The Disney Studios produced three television sequels "The Parent Trap II" (1986), "Parent Trap III" (1989) and "" (1989). <s> The original was remade in 1998 starring Lindsay Lohan, Dennis Quaid and Natasha Richardson. <s> Joanna Barnes also made an appearance as Vicki, the mother of Dennis Quaid's character's fiancée, Meridith.
simple: The Parent Trap is a 1961 Walt Disney Productions movie. <s> It stars Hayley Mills, Maureen O'Hara, and Brian Keith. <s> The movie was based on the book "Lottie and Lisa" ("Das Doppelte Lottchen") by Erich Kästner. <s> The movie was nominated for two Academy Awards. <s> Three television sequels were made. <s> The original movie was remade in 1998 with Lindsay Lohan.

title: Bonnie and Clyde
complex: Bonnie Elizabeth Parker (October 1, 1910 – May 23, 1934) and Clyde Chestnut Barrow (March 24, 1909 – May 23, 1934) were an American criminal couple who traveled the Central United States with their gang during the Great Depression, known for their bank robberies although they preferred to rob small stores or rural gas stations. <s> Their exploits captured the attention of the American press and its readership during what is sometimes referred to as the "public enemy era" between 1931 and 1934, and they are believed to have killed at least nine police officers and several civilians. <s> They were killed in May 1934, during an ambush by law officers near Gibsland, Bienville Parish, Louisiana. <s> The 1967 film "Bonnie and Clyde", directed by Arthur Penn and starring Warren Beatty and Faye Dunaway in the title roles, revived interest in the criminals and glamorized them with a romantic aura. <s> Clyde Chestnut Barrow was born in 1909 into a poor farming family in Ellis County, Texas, southeast of Dallas.
simple: Bonnie Elizabeth Parker (October 1, 1910 – May 23, 1934) and Clyde Chestnut Barrow (March 24, 1909 – May 23, 1934) were American outlaws and robbers. <s> They traveled the Central United States with their gang during the Great Depression. <s> Clyde is known today for his bank robberies. <s> However, he preferred to rob small stores or rural gas stations. <s> The gang is believed to have killed at least nine police officers and several civilians. <s> The couple were eventually surprised and killed by police in Bienville Parish, Louisiana. <s> A 1967 movie about them, "Bonnie and Clyde", stars Faye Dunaway and Warren Beatty.

title: Laocoön (El Greco)
complex: The Laocoön is an oil painting created between 1610 and 1614 by Greek painter El Greco. <s> It is part of a collection at the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.. <s> El Greco's oil painting of Laocoön represents the influence of both classical mythology and artistry.
simple: Laocoön is an oil painting by El Greco. <s> It dates to 1604–1614. <s> It hangs in the National Gallery of Art, Washington DC.

title: Hockenheimring
complex: The is a motor racing circuit situated in the Rhine valley near the town of Hockenheim in Baden-Württemberg, Germany, located on the Bertha Benz Memorial Route. <s> Amongst other motor racing events, it biennially hosts the German Grand Prix, with the most recent being in 2019. <s> The circuit has very little differences in elevation. <s> The circuit has an FIA Grade 1 license.
simple: The Hockenheimring Baden-Württemberg is an automobile racing track near the town of Hockenheim in Baden-Württemberg, Germany. <s> Amongst other motor racing events, it holds the annual Formula One German Grand Prix in turns with the Nürburgring. <s> Being in the Rhine valley, the circuit is almost completely flat, with very little change in height.

title: Daniel Viglietti
complex: Daniel Alberto Viglietti Indart (24 July 1939 – 30 October 2017) was an Uruguayan folk singer, guitarist, composer, and political activist. <s> He was one of the main exponents of Uruguayan popular song and also of the "Nueva Canción" or "New Song" of the 1960s and early 1970s. <s> Viglietti was imprisoned in 1972 by his own government. <s> He was supported by the likes of Jean-Paul Sartre as an international man of conscience, a voice for peace, and an opponent of the fascism and tyranny that plagued South America in the 1970s. <s> Rumors about possible mistreatment against him forced the authorities to bring him out in front of television cameras to show that, in particular, his hands were fine.
simple: Daniel Alberto Viglietti Indart (24 July 1939 – 30 October 2017) was an Uruguayan folk singer, guitarist, composer, and political activist. <s> He was one of the main singers of Uruguayan popular song and also of the "Nueva Canción" or "New Song" of the 1960s and early 1970s. <s> Viglietti was imprisoned in 1972 by his own government. <s> He was an activist against fascism in South America during the 1970s.

title: Cartoon Network: Block Party
complex: Cartoon Network: Block Party is an arcade-style video game for Game Boy Advance developed by American studios Monkeystone Games and One Man Band LLC and published by Majesco Entertainment in the United States on August 5, 2004, and in Europe and Oceania on September 15, 2004. <s> It features characters from Cartoon Network original animated series such as "Johnny Bravo", "Ed Edd n Eddy", "Courage the Cowardly Dog", and "Cow and Chicken". <s> The gameplay is similar to Nintendo's "Mario Party" video game series. <s> Players can experience places from Cartoon Network shows in a board game style. <s> They can also play up to 30 mini-games based on the Cartoon Network shows. <s> Players can choose any of the Cartoon Network characters they like. <s> First, Cow and Chicken have gone to a farm, and after eating too many potatoes, their parents suggest that they have some protein. <s> Cow and Chicken both want their favorite protein food: pork butts. <s> In this board the player has to get four pork butts before returning to the start and winning. <s> Second, in the "Ed, Edd n Eddy" world, Eddy wants to win a skateboarding competition. <s> Double-D doubts Eddy has a chance. <s> The player must collect three trophies and 50 dollars before returning to the start and winning. <s> Then, in the world of Johnny Bravo, Johnny is trying his luck with the ladies, when Carl arrives. <s> It turns out he has a date, and Johnny wants to help him prepare. <s> The player must collect a pie, hair goo, a corn dog, a black shirt, and at least 50 dollars before returning to the start and winning. <s> Last, in Courage's world, Eustace and Muriel are trapped in the mansion of the evil Katz. <s> Courage is in the mansion and is attempting to save them. <s> The player must collect three spiders and 75 cobwebs before returning to the start and winning.
simple: Cartoon Network: Block Party is an arcade-style video game for Wii developed by Majesco Entertainment and released in the United States on January 19, 2008 and in Europe and Oceania on February 16, 2008. <s> It features characters from Cartoon Network original animated series such as "Johnny Bravo", "Ed, Edd n Eddy", "Courage the Cowardly Dog", "Cow and Chicken", "Pet Alien", and "Class of 3000". <s> The gameplay is similar to Nintendo's "Mario Party" video game series. <s> Players can experience places from Cartoon Network shows in a board game style. <s> They can also play up to 30 mini-games based on the Cartoon Network shows. <s> Players can choose any of the Cartoon Network characters they like. <s> First, Cow and Chicken have gone to a farm, and after eating too many potatoes, their parents suggest that they have some protein. <s> Cow and Chicken both want their favorite protein food: pork butts. <s> In this board the player has to get four pork butts before returning to the start and winning. <s> Second, in the "Ed, Edd n Eddy" world, Eddy wants to win a skateboarding competition. <s> Double-D doubts Eddy has a chance. <s> The player must collect three trophies and 50 dollars before returning to the start and winning. <s> Then, in the world of Johnny Bravo, Johnny is trying his luck with the ladies, when Carl arrives. <s> It turns out he has a date, and Johnny wants to help him prepare. <s> The player must collect a pie, hair goo, a corn dog, a black shirt, and at least 50 dollars before returning to the start and winning. <s> Last, in Courage's world, Eustace and Muriel are trapped in the mansion of the evil Katz. <s> Courage is in the mansion and is attempting to save them. <s> The player must collect three spiders and 75 cobwebs before returning to the start and winning.

title: Ronald R. Blanck
complex: Ronald Ray Blanck, D.O. (born October 8, 1941) was the 39th Surgeon General of the United States Army, from 1996 to 2000. <s> He is a Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine (D.O.) and is the only such physician ever appointed Surgeon General of the Army. <s> He was also president of the University of North Texas Health Science Center at Fort Worth from 2000 to 2006. <s> He currently serves as Chairman of the Board of Regents of the Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences.
simple: Ronald Ray Blanck (born October 8, 1941) is an American osteopathic physician and retired lieutenant general in the U.S. Army. <s> He served as the 39th Surgeon General of the United States Army from 1996 to 2000. <s> He was also president of the University of North Texas Health Science Center in Fort Worth, Texas from 2000 to 2006.

title: Hammarby Fotboll
complex: Hammarby Fotboll, more commonly known as Hammarby IF or Hammarby (] locally also ] ), is a Swedish football club based at Tele2 Arena in Johanneshov but founded in the neighbouring Södermalm district of Stockholm City Centre, an area the club considers its heartland. <s> Competing in Sweden's first tier, Allsvenskan, Hammarby are placed twelfth in the all-time Allsvenskan table, and has won the league once, in 2001.
simple: Hammarby IF is an association football club in the town of Stockholm in Sweden. <s> The club won Allsvenskan, becoming Swedish national champions, in 2001.

title: Race Horses (band)
complex: Race Horses were a Welsh band based in Cardiff, Wales and originally from Aberystwyth. <s> Formed in 2005 as Radio Luxembourg, they changed their name in 2009 due to possible legal problems with the radio station of the same name. <s> Initially the majority of their music was in Welsh, but their final album "Furniture" was entirely in English.
simple: Race Horses are an indie/pop band from Aberystwyth, Wales. <s> They started in 2005 as Radio Luxembourg.

title: Jalpaiguri division
complex: Jalpaiguri Division is a division in the Indian state of West Bengal.
simple: Jalpaiguri Division is a division in the Indian state of West Bengal.

title: Idris Muhammad
complex: Idris Muhammad ( ; born Leo Morris; November 13, 1939 – July 29, 2014) was an American jazz drummer who recorded with Ahmad Jamal, Lou Donaldson, Pharoah Sanders, and Tete Montoliu. <s> He died aged 74 in 2014.
simple: Idris Muhammad (; born Leo Morris; November 13, 1939 – July 29, 2014) was an American jazz drummer who has recorded a lot of music with many artists including Ahmad Jamal, Grant Green, Grover Washington, Hank Crawford, Gene Ammons, and Houston Person. <s> Muhammad died in New Orleans, Louisiana, he was 74.

title: Recruitment
complex: Recruitment refers to the overall process of attracting, shortlisting, selecting and appointing suitable candidates for jobs (either permanent or temporary) within an organization. <s> Recruitment can also refer to processes involved in choosing individuals for unpaid roles.
simple: Recruitment is the process of finding new people to do a job.

title: Vinča culture
complex: The Vinča culture, ʋîːntʃa also known as Turdaș culture or Turdaș–Vinča culture, was a Neolithic archaeological culture in southeastern Europe, in present-day Serbia, and smaller parts of Bulgaria and Romania (particularly Transylvania), dated to the period 5700–4500 BC or 5300–4700/4500 BC. <s> Named for its type site, Vinča-Belo Brdo, a large tell settlement discovered by Serbian archaeologist Miloje Vasić in 1908, it represents the material remains of a prehistoric society mainly distinguished by its settlement pattern and ritual behaviour.
simple: The Vinča culture was a culture during the stone age, roughly from 5400 BC to 4600 BC.

title: Charadriiformes
complex: Charadriiformes (meaning "having the form of the Eurasian stone-curlew") is a diverse order of small to medium-large birds. <s> It includes about 350 species and has members in all parts of the world. <s> Most Charadriiformes live near water and eat invertebrates or other small animals; however, some are pelagic (seabirds), some occupy deserts and a few are found in thick forest. <s> This is a list of the charadriiform families, presented in taxonomic order.
simple: Charadriiformes is a diverse order of small to medium-large birds. <s> It includes about 350 species. <s> It has members in all parts of the world. <s> Most charadriiformes live near water and eat invertebrates or other small animals. <s> However, some are pelagic (sea birds), some occupy deserts, and a few are found in thick forest. <s> This is a list of the charadriiform families, presented in taxonomic order.

title: José Ron
complex: Édgar José Ron Vásquez (born August 6, 1981), is a Mexican television actor best known for his roles in telenovelas such as "Juro que te amo", "Los exitosos Pérez", "La que no podía amar", "La mujer del Vendaval" and "Muchacha italiana viene a casarse".
simple: José Ron (born Édgar José Ron Vázquez, August 8, 1981 in Guadalajara, Jalisco, Mexico), is a Mexican actor known for his performances in telenovelas, series and theater.

title: Circuit diagram
complex: A circuit diagram (electrical diagram, elementary diagram, electronic schematic) is a graphical representation of an electrical circuit. <s> A pictorial circuit diagram uses simple images of components, while a schematic diagram shows the components and interconnections of the circuit using standardized symbolic representations.
simple: A circuit diagram is a diagram that shows an electrical circuit.

title: Susi Kentikian
complex: Susianna "Susi" Levonovna Kentikian ( ; born Syuzanna Kentikyan on 11 September 1987) is an Armenian-German professional boxer. <s> She was born in Yerevan, Armenian SSR, but left the country with her family at the age of five because of the Nagorno-Karabakh War. <s> Kentikian has lived in Hamburg since 1996 and began boxing at the age of twelve. <s> Following a successful amateur career, she turned professional in 2005 upon signing with the Hamburg-based Spotlight Boxing promotion. <s> Kentikian is a two-time flyweight world champion, having held the World Boxing Association (WBA) female title from 2007 to 2012, and from 2013 to 2017. <s> Additionally, she was the World Boxing Organization (WBO) flyweight champion from 2009 to 2012, and held the Women's International Boxing Federation (WIBF) title from 2007 to 2012 and 2015 to 2017.
simple: Susianna "Susi" Kentikian (born September 11, 1987) is a woman boxer from Germany. <s> She was born in Yerevan, Armenian SSR, but she left the country together with her family when she was five years old, because of the Nagorno-Karabakh War. <s> Kentikian has lived in Hamburg since 1996 and has signed a contract with the Hamburg boxing promoter Spotlight Boxing. <s> Kentikian is the current world champion with the boxing organizations WBA and WIBF in the flyweight weight class.

title: Lorraine Toussaint
complex: Lorraine Toussaint (born April 4, 1960) is a Trinidadian-American actress and producer. <s> Toussaint began her career in theatre before supporting performances in films such as "Breaking In" (1989), "Hudson Hawk" (1991), and "Dangerous Minds" (1995). <s> As lead actress, she is best known for her role as Rene Jackson in the critically acclaimed Lifetime television drama series "Any Day Now", from 1998 to 2002, and her recurring role as defense attorney Shambala Green in the NBC legal drama "Law & Order". <s> Toussaint later appeared as a regular cast member in the NBC police procedural "Crossing Jordan" (2002–03) and the TNT crime drama "Saving Grace" (2007–10). <s> Toussaint has also made over 30 guest appearances on television, starred in a number of made-for-television movies, and had recurring roles in "Ugly Betty", "Friday Night Lights", "Body of Proof", and "The Fosters". <s> She co-starred in the ABC fantasy-drama series "Forever" (2014–15), and recently co-starred in the Fox comedy-drama "Rosewood". <s> Toussaint received critical acclaim and an Independent Spirit Award nomination for her performance in the 2012 drama film "Middle of Nowhere", written and directed by Ava DuVernay. <s> In 2014, she played the role of Yvonne "Vee" Parker, the main antagonist in the second season of the Netflix comedy-drama series "Orange Is the New Black", for which she received critical acclaim and a Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Drama Series.
simple: Lorraine Toussaint (born April 4, 1960) is a Trinidadian-American movie and television actress, and producer. <s> She was also in the movies "Breaking In" (1989), "Hudson Hawk" (1991), and "Dangerous Minds" (1995). <s> She is known for her role as Rene Jackson in the televison drama "Any Day Now" (1998-2002). <s> Toussaint was also in the television series "Crossing Jordan" (2002-2003), "Saving Grace" (2007-2010) and "Orange Is the New Black" (2012). <s> For "Middle of Nowhere" (2012) she was nominated for a Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Actress.

title: Albert I of Belgium
complex: Albert I (8 April 1875 – 17 February 1934) reigned as King of the Belgians from 1909 to 1934. <s> This was an eventful period in the history of Belgium, which included the period of World War I (1914–1918), when 90 percent of Belgium was overrun, occupied, and ruled by the German Empire. <s> Other crucial issues included the adoption of the Treaty of Versailles, the ruling of the Belgian Congo as an overseas possession of the Kingdom of Belgium along with the League of Nations mandate of Ruanda-Urundi, the reconstruction of Belgium following the war, and the first five years of the Great Depression (1929–1934).
simple: Albert I (April 8, 1875 – February 17, 1934) reigned as King of the Belgians from 1909 to 1934. <s> This was an eventful period in the history of Belgium. <s> It included the period of World War I (1914-1918).

title: Tlazōlteōtl
complex: In Aztec mythology, Tlazolteotl (or , , ] ) is a deity of vice, purification, steam baths, lust, midwives, filth, and a patroness of adulterers. <s> She is known by three names, ('she who eats or filthy excrescence sin') and ('the death caused by lust'), and or ( , Deity of Cotton), the latter of which refers to a quadripartite association of four sister deities. <s> was called "Deity of Dirt" and "Eater of Ordure" ( , 'she who eats dirt sin'), with her dual nature of deity of dirt and also of purification. <s> Sins were symbolized by dirt.
simple: Tlazolteotl (or "Tlaçolteotl") is an Aztec goddess. <s> She is the goddess of purification, steam bath, midwives, sin and adulterers. <s> Thus, Tlazolteotl was a goddess of filth (sin), vice and sexual misdeeds. <s> However, she was also a purification goddess.

title: Pray (Sam Smith song)
complex: "Pray" is a song by English singer and songwriter Sam Smith. <s> It was written by Smith, Larrance Dopson, Darryl Pearson, Timbaland, Jose Valasquez and Jimmy Napes, with production handled by Timbaland, Napes and Steve Fitzmaurice. <s> The song was released on 6 October 2017 through Capitol Records, as a promotional single from Smith's second studio album, "The Thrill of It All" (2017).A <s> A new version of the song featuring American rapper Logic was released as the third single from the album on 29 March 2018.
simple: "Pray" is a song by English singer-songwriter Sam Smith. <s> It was written by Smith, Larrance Dopson, Darryl Pearson, Timbaland, Jose Valasquez and Jimmy Napes. <s> The song was released on 6 October 2017 through Capitol Records. <s> It was a promotional single from Smith's second studio album, "The Thrill of It All" (2017). <s> A new version of the song featuring American rapper Logic was released as the third single from "The Thrill of It All" on 29 March 2018.

title: Jackson County, Florida
complex: Jackson County is a county located in the U.S. state of Florida, on its northwestern border with Alabama. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 49,746. <s> Its county seat is Marianna. <s> Jackson County was created by the Florida Territorial Council in 1822 out of Escambia County, at the same time that Duval County was organized from land of St. Johns County, making them the third and fourth counties in the Territory. <s> The county was named for General Andrew Jackson, a hero of the War of 1812, who had served as Florida's first military governor for six months in 1821. <s> Jackson County originally extended from the Choctawhatchee River on the west to the Suwannee River on the east. <s> By 1840 the county had been reduced close to its present boundaries through the creation of new counties from its original territory, following an increase of population in these areas. <s> Minor adjustments to the county boundaries continued through most of the 19th century, however. <s> There were no towns in Jackson County when it was formed. <s> The first county court met at what was called "Robinson's Big Spring" (later called Blue Springs) in 1822 and then at the "Big Spring of the Choctawhatchee" in 1823. <s> The following year the county court met at "Chipola Settlement", which is also known as Waddell's Mill Pond. <s> Gradually towns were developed. <s> In January 1821, Webbville had been established as the first town in Jackson County, and it was first designated as the county seat. <s> Marianna was founded by Robert Beveridge, a native of Scotland, in September 1821. <s> It developed about 9 mi southeast of Webbville. <s> The first county seat thrived until 1828, when Beveridge and other Marianna settlers went to Tallahassee to lobby for the county seat to be moved to Marianna. <s> They enticed the Florida Legislature with offers of free land, paying to construct a county courthouse and develop a public square, and donating an additional $500 to purchase a quarter section of land to be sold at public auction as a way to finance the new government, if the county seat was moved to Marianna. <s> Beveridge and his supporters succeeded in their civic bribe. <s> Marianna became the "de facto" county seat of the county justice and civil authority, although it was never officially proclaimed to be such. <s> Marianna began to grow and prosper when the county government moved into the new courthouse in 1829. <s> It became the market and court town for the rural county. <s> Webbville's prominent citizens moved to Marianna to follow the courts, as did numerous businesses. <s> When the L&N Railroad decided to bypass putting a station at Webbville, the town declined further and became defunct. <s> Tensions broke out into violence and in 1869 Jackson County became the center of a guerrilla war extending through 1871; it became known as the Jackson County War. <s> The local Ku Klux Klan, insurgent Confederate Army veterans, directed their violence at eradicating the Republican Party in the county, assassinating more than 150 Republican Party officials and other prominent African Americans as part of a successful campaign to retain white Democratic power in the county. <s> Another source says that in Jackson County, 200 "leading Republicans" were assassinated in 1869 and 1870 alone; no one was arrested or brought to trial for these crimes. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 955 sqmi , of which 918 sqmi is land and 37 sqmi (3.9%) is water. <s> Jackson County is the only county in Florida that borders both Georgia and Alabama. <s> Jackson County is in the Central Standard Time Zone. <s> Its eastern border with Gadsden County forms the boundary in this area between the Central Standard and Eastern Standard Time Zones. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 46,755 people, 16,620 households, and 11,600 families residing in the county. <s> The population density was 51 people per square mile (20/km2). <s> There were 19,490 housing units at an average density of 21 per square mile (8/km2). <s> The racial makeup of the county was 72.18% White, 24.56% Black or African American, 0.77% Native American, 0.46% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.61% from other races, and 1.40% from two or more races. <s> 2.91% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race. <s> There were 16,620 households out of which 30.90% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.50% were married couples living together, 14.40% had a female householder with no husband present, and 30.20% were non-families. <s> 27.00% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.80% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. <s> The average household size was 2.44 and the average family size was 2.95. <s> In the county, the population was spread out with 22.30% under the age of 18, 9.70% from 18 to 24, 29.60% from 25 to 44, 23.80% from 45 to 64, and 14.60% who were 65 years of age or older. <s> The median age was 38 years. <s> For every 100 females there were 110.40 males. <s> For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 111.20 males. <s> The median income for a household in the county was $29,744, and the median income for a family was $36,404. <s> Males had a median income of $27,138 versus $21,180 for females. <s> The per capita income for the county was $13,905. <s> About 12.80% of families and 17.20% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.70% of those under age 18 and 21.00% of those age 65 or over.
simple: Jackson County is a county in the U.S. state of Florida. <s> Its county seat is Marianna, Florida. <s> Marianna became the county seat, but not without controversy. <s> Jackson County was created by the Florida Territorial Council in 1822 by splitting from Escambia County, making it the third county in the Territory. <s> The county was named for Andrew Jackson, who had served as Florida's first military governor for six months in 1821. <s> Jackson County originally spread from the Choctawhatchee River on the west to the Suwannee River on the east. <s> The county had been shrunk close to its current boundaries by 1840 through the creation of new counties from its original land. <s> Small changes to the county border continued through most of the 19th century, however. <s> There were no towns in Jackson County when it was formed. <s> The first county court met at what was called "Robinson's Big Spring" (later called Blue Springs) in 1822 and then at the "Big Spring of the Choctawhatchee" in 1823. <s> The following year the county court met at "Chipola Settlement" which is also known as Waddell's Mill Pond. <s> Webbville thrived until 1828 when Beveridge and other Marianna settlers went to Tallahassee and enticed the Florida Legislature with free land, construction of a courthouse, a public square and $500 to purchase a quarter section of land to be sold at public auction as a way to finance the new government, if the county seat was moved to Marianna. <s> Beveridge and his supporters succeeded and Marianna became the county seat of the county justice and civil authority, even though it was never officially named the county seat. <s> Marianna began to grow and prosper when the county government moved into the new courthouse in 1829. <s> Webbville's important citizens moved to Marianna and the L&N Railroad decided to bypass the town. <s> From 1869-71, Jackson County was the center of a low-level guerrilla war known as the Jackson County War. <s> Ku Klux Klan members, including Confederate Army veterans, assassinated over 150 Republican Party officials and important African-Americans as part of a successful campaign to retain conservative white Democratic power. <s> According to the 2000 census, the county has a total area of 954.58 sqmi, of which 915.64 sqmi (or 95.92%) is land and 38.94 sqmi (or 4.08%) is water. <s> Jackson County is the only county in Florida that borders both Georgia and Alabama. <s> Jackson County is in the Central Standard Time Zone. <s> Its eastern border with Gadsden County forms the boundary in this area between the Central Standard and Eastern Standard Time Zones. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 46,755 people, 16,620 households, and 11,600 families living in the county. <s> The population density was 51 people per square mile (20/km2). <s> There were 19,490 housing units at an average density of 21 per square mile (8/km2). <s> The racial makeup of the county was 70.18% White, 26.56% Black or African American, 0.67% Native American, 0.36% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.81% from other races, and 1.40% from two or more races. <s> 2.91% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race. <s> There were 16,620 households out of which 30.90% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.50% were married couples living together, 14.40% had a female householder with no husband present, and 30.20% were not related. <s> 27.00% of all households were made up of people living alone and 12.80% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. <s> The average household size was 2.44 and the average family size was 2.95. <s> In the county the population was spread out with 22.30% under the age of 18, 9.70% from 18 to 24, 29.60% from 25 to 44, 23.80% from 45 to 64, and 14.60% who were 65 years of age or older. <s> The median age was 38 years. <s> For every 100 females there were 110.40 males. <s> For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 111.20 males. <s> The median income for a household in the county was $29,744, and the median income for a family was $36,404. <s> Males had a median income of $27,138 versus $21,180 for females. <s> The per capita income for the county was $13,905. <s> About 12.80% of families and 17.20% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.70% of those under age 18 and 21.00% of those age 65 or over.

title: Georges Lemaître
complex: Georges Henri Joseph Édouard Lemaître, RAS Associate (] ; 17 July 1894 – 20 June 1966) was a Jesuit trained Belgian Catholic priest, mathematician, astronomer, and professor of physics at the Catholic University of Louvain. <s> He was the first to identify that the recession of nearby galaxies can be explained by a theory of an expanding universe, which was observationally confirmed soon afterwards by Edwin Hubble. <s> He was the first to derive what is now known as Hubble's law, or the Hubble–Lemaître law, and made the first estimation of what is now called the Hubble constant, which he published in 1927, two years before Hubble's article. <s> Lemaître also proposed what later became known as the "Big Bang theory" of the origin of the universe, initially calling it the "hypothesis of the primeval atom". <s> Lemaître was a pioneer in applying Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity to cosmology.
simple: Monsignor Georges Lemaître (Georges Henri Joseph Édouard Lemaître, 17 July 1894 – 20 June 1966) was a Belgian priest, astronomer , mathematician and professor of physics at the Catholic University of Louvain. <s> Lemaître was also the first to make the Hubble's law and the Hubble constant. <s> Lemaître also started what became known as the Big Bang theory of the origin of the Universe. <s> He called it his 'hypothesis of the primeval atom'.

title: Djurgårdens IF Hockey
complex: Djurgårdens IF Ishockeyförening (English: "Djurgården IF Ice Hockey Club") is a professional ice hockey team based in Stockholm, Sweden, affiliated with the Djurgårdens IF umbrella organization. <s> Djurgården is the most successful Swedish hockey team of all time, as 16-time Swedish Champions, 10-time runners-up, and leaders of the marathon table for the top flight of Swedish hockey, as well as two-time European Cup winners.
simple: Djurgårdens IF Hockey is the ice hockey section of sports club Djurgårdens IF in the town of Stockholm in Sweden.

title: Mastic (plant resin)
complex: Mastic is a resin obtained from the mastic tree ("Pistacia lentiscus"). <s> In pharmacies and nature shops, it is called Arabic gum (not to be confused with gum arabic) and Yemen gum. <s> In Greece, it is known as tears of Chios, being traditionally produced on that Greek island, and, like other natural resins, is produced in "tears" or droplets. <s> Originally a sap, mastic is sun-dried into pieces of brittle, translucent resin. <s> When chewed, the resin softens and becomes a bright white and opaque gum. <s> The flavor is bitter at first, but after some chewing, it releases a refreshing flavor similar to pine and cedar. <s> Mastic is used in some varnishes. <s> Mastic varnish was used to protect and preserve photographic negatives.
simple: Mastic ( "Mastika") is a resin that comes from the mastic tree, "Pistacia lentiscus". <s> In pharmacies and nature shops, it is called "Arabic gum" (not to be confused with gum arabic). <s> The resin is harvested in various places, especially the Greek island of Chios. <s> Then it dries in the sun into drops of hard resin. <s> When chewed, the resin softens and becomes a white, opaque gum. <s> The flavour is bitter at first. <s> After some chewing, it has a refreshing, slightly pine or cedar-like flavour. <s> Mastic is used in food, medicine, and industry.

title: Anglards-de-Saint-Flour
complex: Anglards-de-Saint-Flour is a commune in the Cantal department in the Auvergne region in south-central France.
simple: Anglards-de-Saint-Flour is a commune. <s> It is in the Cantal department.

title: Joep Lange
complex: Joseph Marie Albert "Joep" Lange (] ; 25 September 1954 – 17 July 2014) was a Dutch clinical researcher specialising in HIV therapy. <s> He served as the president of the International AIDS Society from 2002 to 2004. <s> He was a passenger on Malaysia Airlines Flight 17, which was shot down on 17 July 2014 over Ukraine. <s> Lange was born on 25 September 1954 in Nieuwenhagen in the Netherlands. <s> He was a Youth for Understanding foreign exchange student from 1971 to 1972 at Robinson High School in Tampa, Florida. <s> He later studied medicine at the University of Amsterdam, receiving his MD in 1981 and his PhD in 1987. <s> Lange and his partner Jacqueline van Tongeren were passengers on Malaysia Airlines Flight 17, which was shot down near Hrabove, Ukraine, on 17 July 2014. <s> He was en route to Melbourne to attend the 20th International AIDS Conference, starting on 20 July. <s> His death was mourned by his peers, with the IAS stating that they had "truly lost a giant", while conference delegates interviewed by the media were described as being in "total shock".
simple: Joseph Marie Albert "Joep" Lange (25 September 1954 – 17 July 2014) was a Dutch medical doctor and researcher. <s> He mainly worked in HIV therapy. <s> He served as the President of the International AIDS Society (IAS) from 2002 to 2004. <s> Lange was born in Nieuwenhagen, Limburg. <s> He studied at the University of Amsterdam in Amsterdam. <s> Lange, his wife and other IAS members were on board the Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 when it was shot down on 17 July 2014, killing all people on board. <s> He and the IAS members were planning to go to Melbourne, Australia for the 20th International AIDS Conference, starting on 19 July.

title: Mir Hazar Khan Khoso
complex: Mir Hazar Khan Khoso (Urdu, ) (born 30 September 1929), was the caretaker Prime Minister of Pakistan from 25 March 2013 to 5 June 2013. <s> A jurist, Khoso is a retired judge who previously served as the Chief Justice of the Federal Shariat Court and served as the interim prime minister ahead of the general elections scheduled in May 2013.
simple: Justice (R) Mir Hazar Khan Khoso (Urdu, ) (born 30 September 1929), was the caretaker Prime Minister of Pakistan, from 25 March 2013 to 5 June 2013. <s> Khoso is a retired judge. <s> He was the Chief Justice of the Federal Shariat Court. <s> He was the interim Prime Minister ahead of the general elections scheduled in May 2013.

title: Hollis, New Hampshire
complex: Hollis is a town in Hillsborough County, New Hampshire, United States. <s> The population was 7,684 at the 2010 census. <s> The town center village is listed on the National Register of Historic Places as Hollis Village Historic District.
simple: Hollis is a town in Hillsborough County, New Hampshire, United States. <s> The population was 7,684 at the 2010 census.

title: Ron Brace
complex: Ronald Jeffery "Ron" Brace III (December 18, 1986 – April 23, 2016) was an American football nose tackle. <s> He was drafted by the New England Patriots in the second round of the 2009 NFL Draft as a defensive end. <s> He played college football at Boston College. <s> Brace died of an apparent heart attack on April 23, 2016, in Springfield, Massachusetts, at the age of 29.
simple: Ronald "Ron" Jeffery Brace III (December 18, 1986 – April 23, 2016) was an American football nose tackle. <s> He was drafted by the New England Patriots in the second round of the 2009 NFL Draft as a defensive end. <s> He played for the Patriots from 2009 through 2012. <s> He played college football at Boston College. <s> Brace died suddenly from an apparent heart attack on April 23, 2016 in Springfield, Massachusetts at the age of 29.

title: Arrondissement of Cahors
complex: The arrondissement of Cahors is an arrondissement of France in the Lot department in the Occitanie région. <s> Since the January 2017 reorganization of the arrondissements of Lot, it has 98 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Cahors is an arrondissement of France. <s> It is part of the Lot "département" in the Occitanie region.

title: No Fixed Address (band)
complex: No Fixed Address is an Australian Aboriginal reggae rock group formed in 1979. <s> The band was led by Bart Willoughby (lead vocals and drums) Pitjanjatjara from Koonibba Mission near Ceduna in the far south west of South Australia, together with Ricky Harrison (rhythm guitarist and principal songwriter) Kurnai from Morwell in Victoria, Leslie Lovegrove Freeman (lead guitarist), Ngarrindjeri from Murray Bridge in South Australia, John Miller (bass) from Port Lincoln in South Australia and Veronica Rankine (tenor saxophone), Ngarrindjeri from the south east of South Australia. <s> Many members were related through family ties, Willoughby, Miller and Freeman were cousins. <s> Freeman, related to Harrison through marriage, recruited him from Victoria and they all met and formed the band at the Centre for Aboriginal Studies in Music (CASM) in North Adelaide, South Australia. <s> The band members were students at CASM and there first heard reggae music from Jamaica. <s> The band were a very popular pub rock outfit among students and the alternative music scene, especially supported by community radio station 5MMM. <s> In 1979, the band played its first large concert at the National Aboriginal Day held at Taperoo, South Australia. <s> In 1980 the band made a movie "Wrong Side of the Road" with another CASM band, Us Mob. <s> The movie dealt with the trials and joys of touring and the contrasting receptions they received in Indigenous and non-Indigenous communities. <s> With the recording of the soundtrack, No Fixed Address and Us Mob became the first contemporary aboriginal bands to be recorded. <s> On the strength of their live performances and airplay of their demo recordings on 5MMM they were the cover story on the August 1980 edition of national rock magazine "Roadrunner". <s> In 1982 the band were contracted to Rough Diamond Records, a subsidiary of Polygram Records and released their debut mini album "From My Eyes". <s> The album was launched at the Hilton Hotel by the Australian Prime Minister, Bob Hawke. <s> The video for the single, "From My Eyes" was filmed at Hanging Rock, Victoria and the Old Melbourne Gaol. <s> The band toured Australia in 1982, in support of Peter Tosh. <s> Following the success of the Peter Tosh tour, the band became the first Aboriginal band to travel overseas, touring Great Britain, playing at nine cities including London, Bristol, Leeds, Plymouth and Manchester. <s> Didgeridoo player, Billy Inda, made a guest appearance, Joe Geia played the introduction didgeridoo on folk rock band Goanna's single "Solid Rock" from their 1982 album, "Spirit of Place" – it peaked at No. 3 in October on the Kent Music Report Singles Chart – it is the first charting rock song to feature the didgeridoo. <s> The 1984 video for "We Have Survived" was filmed at Palm Beach and Botany Bay in Sydney. <s> The song has become an unofficial anthem for many of Australia's indigenous peoples. <s> Returning to Australia Willoughby joined his cousin (Bunna Lawrie)'s band, Coloured Stone in 1984. <s> In 1987 Willoughby reformed the band and they toured Europe, including a number of eastern bloc countries, appearing at the East Berlin Festival. <s> In late 1988 Willoughby joined Yothu Yindi and as result the group disbanded again. <s> In 2008 the band reformed and played at the Dreaming Festival & Tarerer Festival in Woodford, Queensland, where they released a limited edition CD copy of "From My Eyes". <s> Also in 2008 the band's song "We Have Survived" was added to the National Film and Sound Archive's Sounds of Australia registry. <s> In August 2011 No Fixed Address, along with Coloured Stone, were inducted into the Hall of Fame at the inaugural National Indigenous Music Awards.
simple: No Fixed Address is an Australian Aboriginal reggae rock band. <s> It formed in 1979 in North Adelaide. <s> Bart Willoughby is the lead singer and played drums. <s> All the original members were related through family ties. <s> It played its first concert on National Aboriginal Day held at Taperoo in 1979. <s> In 1980, the band made a movie called "Wrong Side of the Road" with another band, Us Mob. <s> The movie was about the different receptions they received in Indigenous and non-Indigenous communities. <s> With the recording of the movie's soundtrack, No Fixed Address and Us Mob became some of the first Aboriginal rock bands to be recorded. <s> In 1982, the band released its first album, "From My Eyes". <s> The album was launched at the Hilton Hotel by Prime Minister Bob Hawke. <s> The band toured Australia in 1982, in support of Peter Tosh. <s> After this, the band became the first Aboriginal band to travel overseas. <s> They played at nine cities in Great Britain. <s> The band's didgeridoo player, Billy Inda, played the didgeridoo on a song from Goanna's album, "Spirit of Place", in 1982. <s> The song, "Solid Rock", peaked at No. 3 in October on the Kent Music Report Singles Chart. <s> It is the first charting rock song to feature the didgeridoo. <s> The band released "We Have Survived" in 1984. <s> The song has become an unofficial anthem for many of Australia's indigenous peoples. <s> The first time was in 1984, when Willoughby joined his cousin Bunna Lawrie's band, Coloured Stone. <s> They reformed in 1987 to tour through Europe. <s> They played at the East Berlin Festival in the same year. <s> In late 1988, Willoughby joined Yothu Yindi and as result the group broke up again. <s> The band reformed again in 2008. <s> It was added to the National Film and Sound Archive's Sounds of Australia registry in 2008. <s> In August 2011, No Fixed Address and Coloured Stone were both listed in the Hall of Fame at the first National Indigenous Music Awards.

title: Interleukin 2
complex: Aldesleukin is a form of recombinant interleukin-2. <s> It is manufactured using recombinant DNA technology and is marketed as a protein therapeutic and branded as Proleukin.
simple: Interleukin-2 is a form of Interleukin.

title: Wheel 2000
complex: Wheel 2000 (also known as Wheel of Fortune 2000) is a children's version of the American game show "Wheel of Fortune" (and the last version of Wheel of any sort to air on Daytime television). <s> The show was created by Scott Sternberg and was hosted by David Sidoni, with Tanika Ray providing voice work and motion capture for a virtual reality hostess named "Cyber Lucy". <s> The show premiered on September 13, 1997 on CBS, aired as part of the network's attempt to meet the then-new E/I mandates during its Saturday morning block, and ran through February 7, 1998 with repeats continuing through September 26. <s> Game Show Network broadcast "Wheel 2000"' s episodes concurrently with their airings on CBS. <s> It was taped at Sony Pictures Studios. <s> The gameplay of "Wheel 2000" was very similar to the adult version, except children aged 10–15 competed for points and prizes instead of cash with the eventual winner playing for a grand prize in the bonus round. <s> Round categories were chosen by the contestants from a possible three; the names of the categories were updated to reflect the younger contestants ("Place", for example, became "Globetrotter"). <s> New categories replaced those chosen in each round. <s> In Round 1, the coin toss winner/the red contestant would choose, Round 2, the yellow contestant, Round 3, the blue contestant and so on.
simple: Wheel 2000 (full title Wheel of Fortune 2000) was a childrens' television game show. <s> It was a spin-off of the television game show "Wheel of Fortune". <s> It was hosted by David Sidoni. <s> It aired on Saturday mornings on CBS from September 13, 1997 to February 7, 1998. <s> Gameplay was the same as the adult version of "Wheel of Fortune", with some differences. <s> A new category replaced the one picked in the next round.

title: Bobby Seale
complex: Robert George Seale (born October 22, 1936) is an American political activist. <s> He and fellow activist Huey P. Newton co-founded the Black Panther Party. <s> Seale is the eldest of three children. <s> He has a younger brother, Jon, and a younger sister, Betty. <s> He was born in Liberty, Texas to George Seale, a carpenter, and Thelma Seale (née Traylor), a homemaker. <s> The Seale family lived in poverty during most of Bobby Seale's early life.
simple: Robert George "Bobby" Seale (born October 22, 1936) is an American political activist. <s> He and fellow activist Huey P. Newton co-founded the Black Panther Party. <s> He was born in Dallas, Texas.

title: Coit Tower
complex: Coit Tower is a 210 ft tower in the Telegraph Hill neighborhood of San Francisco, California, offering panoramic views over the city and the bay. <s> The tower, in the city's Pioneer Park, was built between 1932 and 1933 using Lillie Hitchcock Coit's bequest to beautify the city of San Francisco. <s> It was added to the National Register of Historic Places on January 29, 2008. <s> The art deco tower, built of unpainted reinforced concrete, was designed by architects Arthur Brown, Jr. and Henry Howard. <s> The interior features fresco murals in the American Social Realism style, painted by 25 different on-site artists and their numerous assistants, plus two additional paintings installed after creation off-site. <s> Also known as the Coit Memorial Tower, it was dedicated to the volunteer firemen who had died in San Francisco's five major fires. <s> Although an apocryphal story claims that the tower was designed to resemble a fire hose nozzle due to Coit's affinity with the San Francisco firefighters of the day, the resemblance is coincidental. <s> In her will she wished for one third of her fortune, amounting to $118,000, "to be expended in an appropriate manner for the purpose of adding to the beauty of the city which I have always loved." <s> Two memorials were built in her name.
simple: Coit Tower is a 210 ft tower in the Telegraph Hill neighborhood of San Francisco, California. <s> The tower, in the city's Pioneer Park, was built in 1933. <s> The art deco tower is made of unpainted reinforced concrete. <s> Architects Arthur Brown, Jr. and Henry Howard designed it. <s> The tower has fresco murals by 27 different on-site artists and their assistants, plus two additional paintings installed after creation off-site. <s> The tower was not designed to resemble a fire hose nozzle, despite Coit's affinity with the San Francisco firefighters of the day, in particular with Knickerbocker Engine Company Number 5. <s> Lillie Hitchcock Coit left one-third of her estate to the city "to be expended in an appropriate manner for the purpose of adding to the beauty of the city which I have always loved".

title: Quantifier (logic)
complex: In logic, quantification specifies the quantity of specimens in the domain of discourse that satisfy an open formula. <s> The two most common quantifiers mean "for all" and "there exists". <s> For example, in arithmetic, quantifiers allow one to say that the natural numbers go on forever, by writing that "for all" n (where n is a natural number), there is another number (say, the successor of n) which is one bigger than n. <s> Two fundamental kinds of quantification in predicate logic are universal quantification and existential quantification. <s> The traditional symbol for the universal quantifier "all" is "∀", a rotated letter "A", and for the existential quantifier "exists" is "∃", a rotated letter "E". <s> These quantifiers have been generalized beginning with the work of Mostowski and Lindström. <s> Quantification is used as well in natural languages; examples of quantifiers in English are "for all", "for some", "many", "few", "a lot", and "no;" see Quantifier (linguistics) for details. <s> Consider the following statement: This has the appearance of an "infinite conjunction" of propositions. <s> From the point of view of formal languages this is immediately a problem, since syntax rules are expected to generate finite words. <s> The two most common quantifiers are the universal quantifier and the existential quantifier. <s> The traditional symbol for the universal quantifier is "∀", a rotated letter "A", which stands for "for all" or "all". <s> The corresponding symbol for the existential quantifier is "∃", a rotated letter "E", which stands for "there exists" or "exists". <s> An example of translating a quantified statement in a natural language such as English would be as follows. <s> Given the statement, "Each of Peter's friends either likes to dance or likes to go to the beach," key aspects can be identified and rewritten using symbols including quantifiers. <s> So, let "X" be the set of all Peter's friends, "P"("x") the predicate ""x" likes to dance", and "Q"("x") the predicate ""x" likes to go to the beach". <s> Then the above sentence can be written in formal notation as formula_1, which is read, "for every "x" that is a member of "X", "P" applies to "x" or "Q" applies to "x"." <s> The order of quantifiers is critical to meaning, as is illustrated by the following two propositions: This is clearly true; it just asserts that every natural number has a square. <s> The meaning of the assertion in which the order of quantifiers is inversed is different: This is clearly false; it asserts that there is a single natural number "s" that is at the same time the square of "every" natural number. <s> This is because the syntax directs that any variable cannot be a function of subsequently introduced variables. <s> A few other quantifiers have been proposed over time. <s> In particular, the solution quantifier, noted § (section sign) and read "those". <s> For example, is read "those "n" in N such that "n" ≤ 4 are in {0,1,2}." <s> The same construct is expressible in set-builder notation as <s> Term logic, also called Aristotelian logic, treats quantification in a manner that is closer to natural language, and also less suited to formal analysis. <s> Term logic treated "All", "Some" and "No" in the 4th century BC, in an account also touching on the alethic modalities. <s> Gottlob Frege, in his 1879 "Begriffsschrift", was the first to employ a quantifier to bind a variable ranging over a domain of discourse and appearing in predicates. <s> He would universally quantify a variable (or relation) by writing the variable over a dimple in an otherwise straight line appearing in his diagrammatic formulas. <s> Frege did not devise an explicit notation for existential quantification, instead employing his equivalent of ~∀"x"~, or contraposition. <s> Frege's treatment of quantification went largely unremarked until Bertrand Russell's 1903 "Principles of Mathematics". <s> In work that culminated in Peirce (1885), Charles Sanders Peirce and his student Oscar Howard Mitchell independently invented universal and existential quantifiers, and bound variables. <s> Peirce and Mitchell wrote Π and Σ where we now write ∀"x" and ∃"x". <s> Peirce's notation can be found in the writings of Ernst Schröder, Leopold Loewenheim, Thoralf Skolem, and Polish logicians into the 1950s. <s> Most notably, it is the notation of Kurt Gödel's landmark 1930 paper on the completeness of first-order logic, and 1931 paper on the incompleteness of Peano arithmetic. <s> Peirce's approach to quantification also influenced William Ernest Johnson and Giuseppe Peano, who invented yet another notation, namely ("x") for the universal quantification of "x" and (in 1897) ∃"x" for the existential quantification of "x". <s> Hence for decades, the canonical notation in philosophy and mathematical logic was ("x")"P" to express "all individuals in the domain of discourse have the property "P"," and "(∃"x")"P"" for "there exists at least one individual in the domain of discourse having the property "P"." <s> Peano, who was much better known than Peirce, in effect diffused the latter's thinking throughout Europe. <s> Peano's notation was adopted by the "Principia Mathematica" of Whitehead and Russell, Quine, and Alonzo Church. <s> In 1935, Gentzen introduced the ∀ symbol, by analogy with Peano's ∃ symbol. <s> ∀ did not become canonical until the 1960s.
simple: For example, every natural number has another natural number larger than it. <s> Two basic kinds of quantifiers used in predicate logic are universal and existential quantifiers. <s> Quantifiers are also used in natural languages. <s> Examples of quantifiers in English are "for all", "for some", "many", "few", "a lot", and "no". <s> This is a problem for formal languages, since a formal statement needs to be finite in length. <s> The two quantifiers most widely used are the universal quantifier and the existence quantifier. <s> The universal quantifier is symbolized with "∀", an upside down "A", to stand for "all". <s> An existence quantifier (symbolized with "∃") states that at least one element considered fits the criteria. <s> The existential quantifier is symbolized with "∃", a backwards "E", to stand for "exists". <s> We can rewrite an example English statement with symbols, predicates representing criteria, and quantifiers. <s> The example is "Each of Peter's friends either likes to dance or likes to go to the beach". <s> Let "X" be the set of all Peter's friends. <s> Let "P"("x") be the predicate ""x" likes to dance". <s> Let "Q"("x") be the predicate ""x" likes to go to the beach". <s> We can rewrite the example using formal notation as formula_1. <s> The statement can be read as "for every "x" that is a member of "X", "P" applies to "x" or "Q" applies to "x"." <s> It states that every natural number has a square. <s> However, if we turn the order of the quantifiers around: This statement is false. <s> It claims that there is one natural number "s" that is the square of "every" natural number. <s> The solution quantifier is represented by a § (section sign). <s> The use of quantification was closer to that of natural language. <s> This meant that statements in term logic with quantifiers were less suited for formal analysis. <s> Term logic included quantifiers for "All", "Some" and "No" (none) in 4th century BC. <s> In 1879, Gottlob Frege created a notation for universal quantification. <s> Unlike today, he would represent a universal quantification by writing a variable over a dimple in an otherwise straight line. <s> Frege did not create a notation for existential quantification. <s> Frege's use of quantification was not widely known until Bertrand Russell's 1903 "Principles of Mathematics". <s> In 1885, Charles Sanders Peirce and his student Oscar Howard Mitchell also created a notation for universal and existential quantifiers. <s> They wrote Π and Σ where we now write ∀"x" and ∃"x". <s> Pierce's notation was used by many mathematicians into the 1950s. <s> In 1897, William Ernest Johnson and Giuseppe Peano created another notation for universal and existential quantification. <s> Johnson and Peano used the simple ("x") for universal quantification, and ∃"x" for existential quantification. <s> In 1935, Gerhard Gentzen created the ∀ symbol for universal quantification. <s> It was not widely used until the 1960s.

title: Dawn Wells
complex: Dawn Elberta Wells (born October 18, 1938) is a beauty queen and an American actress who became known for her role as Mary Ann Summers on the CBS sitcom "Gilligan's Island". <s> She and Tina Louise are the last surviving regular cast members from that series. <s> On October 18, 1938, Wells was born as Dawn Elberta Wells in Reno, Nevada, where she attended Reno High School. <s> In 1959, Wells was crowned Miss Nevada and represented her state in the Miss America 1960 pageant in Atlantic City, New Jersey.
simple: Dawn Elberta Wells (born October 18, 1938 in Reno, Nevada) is an American actor, producer and author. <s> She played Mary Ann Summers in the TV series "Gilligan's Island" during the 1960s. <s> Before that, she was Miss Nevada in 1959 and competed in the Miss America Pageant in 1960.

title: Altica ericeti
complex: Altica ericeti (Altica sandini) is a species of leaf beetles in the family Chrysomelidae. <s> It can be found in the Iberian Peninsula, France, England, West Germany, Netherlands, Morocco.
simple: Altica ericeti (or Altica sandini) is a species of leaf beetle. <s> It can be found in France, England, Germany, Netherlands, Morocco and the Iberian Peninsula.

title: Genius
complex: A genius is a person who displays exceptional intellectual ability, creative productivity, universality in genres or originality, typically to a degree that is associated with the achievement of new advances in a domain of knowledge. <s> Despite the presence of scholars in many subjects throughout history, many geniuses have shown high achievements in only a single kind of activity.
simple: A genius is a person who is exceptionally intelligent.

title: Takaya Kurokawa
complex: Takaya Kurokawa (黒河 貴矢 , Kurokawa Takaya , born April 7, 1981) is a former Japanese football player.
simple: Takaya Kurokawa (黒河 貴矢, Kurokawa Takaya, born April 7, 1981) is a Japanese professional athlete.

title: The Rock 'n' Sock Connection
complex: The Rock 'n' Sock Connection was a professional wrestling tag team of The Rock and Mankind/Mick Foley that wrestled in the World Wrestling Federation (WWF) between 1999 and 2000 and briefly in 2004. <s> As a team, they held the WWF Tag Team Championship three times. <s> Several days later, Mick Foley and Dwayne Johnson helped "Raw Is War" achieve its highest rating ever with a segment featuring himself (as Mankind) and The Rock.
simple: The Rock 'N' Sock Connection was a professional wrestling tag team. <s> The team was made up of The Rock and Mankind. <s> The Rock 'N' Sock Connection are best known for competing in World Wrestling Federation (WWF). <s> During their time as a tag team, they were able to win the WWF Tag Team Championship on three different occasions.

title: Täby Church
complex: Täby Church is a medieval church in Täby Municipality, in the province of Uppland north of Stockholm. <s> The church is best known for its painted walls and ceilings by Albertus Pictor. <s> The church was built during the second half of the 13th century. <s> It was first constructed as a square hall church.
simple: Täby Church is a medieval church in Täby Municipality in Sweden. <s> On its walls and ceilings are paintings by Albertus Pictor. <s> It was belongs to the Church of Sweden and was built during the 13th century.

title: Blood Blockade Battlefront
complex: Blood Blockade Battlefront (Japanese: 血界戦線 , Hepburn: Kekkai Sensen , lit., "Bloodline Battlefront") is a Japanese "shōnen" manga by Yasuhiro Nightow. <s> It has been published bimonthly in the magazine "Jump SQ19" from February to April 2009 and moved to "Jump Square" upon the former's ending. <s> The plot revolves around a young photographer named Leonardo Watch, who obtains 'the All Seeing Eyes of the Gods' at the cost of his sister's eyesight. <s> After the incident, Leonardo moves to the city of Hellsalem's Lot to join an organization known as Libra to fight several monsters as well as terrorists. <s> The manga has been published in the United States by Dark Horse Comics. <s> An anime adaptation by Bones premiered in early 2015, Funimation licensed the series for streaming in North America. <s> Both the manga and anime were well received by publications due to its story and characters. <s> A second season aired from October to December 2017. <s> The first DVD of the series sold 4,784 units during its debut. <s> Meanwhile, the first Blu-ray sold 12,171 units in its first week of release. <s> For the "Newtype" preliminary awards for 2015, the series was sixth in the category "Sound" while fourth in the category "Theme Song" for "Sugar Song to Bitter Step." <s> In the category "Best Mascot", Sonic ranked first. <s> In another poll by the Japanese magazine "Entermix", the series was voted as the second most popular one.
simple: Blood Blockade Battlefront (Japanese: 血界戦線, Hepburn: Kekkai Sensen, lit., "Bloodline Battlefront") is a Japanese "shōnen" manga by Yasuhiro Nightow. <s> The story takes place around a young photographer named Leonardo Watch. <s> He gets 'the All Seeing Eyes of the Gods' at the cost of his sister's eyesight. <s> Leonardo then moves to the city of Hellsalem's Lot. <s> There he joins an organization known as Libra. <s> The organization fights many monsters as well as terrorists. <s> The manga has been published in the United States by Dark Horse Comics. <s> An anime based on this manga by Bones premiered in early 2015. <s> Funimation licensed the series for streaming in North America. <s> A second season aired from October to December 2017. <s> The series was sixth in the category "Sound" and fourth in the category "Theme Song" for "Sugar Song to Bitter Step" in the "Newtype" preliminary awards for 2015. <s> Sonic, a monkey in the show, ranked first in the category "Best Mascot".

title: Versam
complex: Versam is a former municipality in the district of Surselva in the canton of Graubünden in Switzerland. <s> The municipalities of Valendas, Versam, Safien and Tenna merged on 1 January 2013 into the new municipality of Safiental.
simple: Versam is a former municipality of the district of Surselva in the canton of Graubünden in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2013 the former municipalities of Versam, Valendas, Safien and Tenna merged into the new municipality of Safiental.

title: Asier del Horno
complex: Asier del Horno Cosgaya (born 19 January 1981) is a Spanish retired footballer who played as a left back.
simple: Asier del Horno (born 19 January 1981) is a Spanish football player.

title: Richard Arvin Overton
complex: Richard Arvin Overton (May 11, 1906 – December 27, 2018) was an American supercentenarian who at the age of 112 years, 230 days was the oldest verified surviving U.S. World War II veteran and oldest man in the United States. <s> He served in the United States Army. <s> In 2013, he was honored by President Barack Obama. <s> He resided in Austin, Texas, until his death. <s> Overton was born in Bastrop County, Texas, to Gentry Overton, Sr. and Elizabeth Franklin Overton Waters. <s> He served in the South Pacific from 1940 through 1945, including stops in Hawaii, Guam, Palau, and Iwo Jima. <s> He left the U.S. Army in October 1945 as a technician fifth grade. <s> Overton gained media attention during the 2013 Memorial Day weekend when he told Fox News he would spend his Memorial Day "smoking cigars and drinking whiskey-stiffened coffee." <s> On that same Memorial Day, Overton met with Texas Governor Rick Perry. <s> Overton was also invited to the White House where he met with President Barack Obama, and to the Veterans Day ceremony at Arlington National Cemetery, where he was singled out by name for praise by the President. <s> During an NBA game between the San Antonio Spurs and the Memphis Grizzlies on March 24, 2017, Overton was honored during a half-time break. <s> On May 11, 2016, Overton became a supercentenarian. <s> Following the death of Clarence Matthews (born May 1, 1906) on July 22, 2017, Overton became the oldest living American man. <s> Overton was hospitalized for pneumonia in December 2018. <s> He was placed in a rehabilitation center, where he died on December 27, 2018, aged 112 years 230 days. <s> Overton lived in Austin, Texas. <s> On December 11, 2014, Austin Community College recognized Overton with an honorary associate degree, the college's highest distinction.
simple: Richard Arvin Overton (May 11, 1906 – December 27, 2018) was an American supercentenarian. <s> He was the oldest verified surviving American World War II veteran, as well as the oldest American man. <s> In 2013 he was honored by President Barack Obama. <s> He was born in Bastrop County, Texas. <s> Overton served in the South Pacific from 1940 through 1945, including stops in Hawaii, Guam, Palau and Iwo Jima. <s> He left the U.S. Army in October 1945. <s> On that same Memorial Day, Overton met with Texas Governor Rick Perry. <s> During an NBA game between the San Antonio Spurs and the Memphis Grizzlies on March 24, 2017, Overton was honored during a half-time break. <s> On May 11, 2016, Overton became a supercentenarian. <s> Overton died in Austin on December 27, 2018 from complications of pneumonia at the age of 112. <s> He lived in Austin, Texas.

title: Moero! Nekketsu Rhythm Damashii Osu! Tatakae! Ouendan 2
complex: Nekketsu Rhythm Damashii: Osu! <s> Ouendan 2 is a rhythm video game developed by iNiS and published by Nintendo for the Nintendo DS handheld video game console. <s> It is the third game to use its gameplay, and is the sequel to "Osu! <s> Ouendan" while incorporating many of the improvements in gameplay made in "Elite Beat Agents". <s> The game has 4-player wireless play, supports the Nintendo DS Rumble Pak accessory, and was released in Japan on May 17, 2007.
simple: Nekketsu Rhythm Damashii Osu! <s> Ouendan 2 (燃えろ!熱血リズム魂 押忍!闘え!応援団2, Moero! <s> Cheer Squad 2") is a rhythm video game made by iNiS and published by Nintendo for the Nintendo DS handheld game console. <s> It's the third game in its series, after "Osu! <s> Ouendan" and "Elite Beat Agents", both for the DS.

title: Adriaen Coorte
complex: Adriaen Coorte (ca. 1665 – after 1707) was a Dutch Golden Age painter of still lifes, who signed works between 1683 and 1707. <s> He painted small and unpretentious still lifes in a style more typical of the first half of the century, and was "one of the last practitioners of this intimate category". <s> Very little is known of his life, but he is assumed to have been born and died in Middelburg. <s> He became a pupil of Melchior d'Hondecoeter around 1680 in Amsterdam. <s> Hondecoeter is known for repetitions of certain birds in certain poses, and he apparently took on pupils who were set to work copying these into their compositions. <s> From 1683 he seems to have returned to Middelburg, where he set up a workshop and signed his small, carefully balanced minimalist still lifes. <s> He often painted on paper that was glued to a wooden panel. <s> About 80 signed works by him have been catalogued, and nearly all of them follow the same pattern; small arrangements of fruits, vegetables, or shells on a stone slab, lit from above, with the dark background typical of still lifes earlier in the century. <s> Instead of the Chinese or silver vessels favoured by his contemporaries, his tableware is very basic pottery. <s> "Objects and light are studied intensely, and are painted with a wondrous tenderness". <s> Neither his birth nor death date is certain, and archival evidence only exists in Middelburg for his membership in the Guild of St. Luke there from 1695 onwards, when he was fined for selling a painting without being a member of the guild. <s> His works appear frequently in contemporary Middelburg taxation inventories <s> Coorte was apparently not well known to his contemporaries outside the small city of Middelburg and, like Vermeer a century before, he was almost entirely forgotten until the 1950s, when the Dutch art historian Laurens J. Bol revived his reputation, beginning with an article in 1952, and finally publishing the first monograph and "catalogue raisonné" on Coorte in 1977 ("Adriaen Coorte", Amsterdam). <s> Bol arranged an exhibition of 35 examples of Coorte's work in 1958 at the Dordrechts Museum, which became a sensation in the Netherlands, with the poets Hans Faverey and Ed Leeflang both being inspired by the paintings. <s> In 2003 there was an exhibition at the National Gallery of Art, Washington. <s> In 2008 a new travelling exhibition was set up; "Ode to Coorte", that was as nearly as successful, making Coorte the most celebrated "rediscovered" Dutch Baroque painter of recent decades. <s> Testifying to Coorte's recent popularity is the December 1st, 2009 auction of two of his new-found paintings, which each sold for more than ten times the estimated price.
