simple: Adriaen Coorte (about 1665 – 1707) was a Dutch painter. <s> He signed works between 1683 and 1707. <s> He mainly painted 'still life'. <s> Coorte was "one of the last practitioners of this intimate category". <s> Very little is known about his life. <s> He was probably born in Middelburg and also died there. <s> He became a pupil of Melchior d'Hondecoeter around 1680 in Amsterdam. <s> From 1683 he seems to have returned to Middelburg, where he set up a workshop and signed his small, carefully balanced minimalist still lifes. <s> He often painted on paper that was glued to a wooden panel. <s> About 80 signed works by him have been catalogued, and nearly all of them follow the same pattern; small arrangements of fruits, vegetables, or shells on a stone slab, lit from above, with the dark background typical of still lifes earlier in the century. <s> Instead of the Chinese or silver vessels favoured by his contemporaries, his tableware is very basic pottery. <s> "Objects and light are studied intensely, and are painted with a wondrous tenderness". <s> Neither his birth nor death date is certain, and archival evidence only exists in Middelburg for his membership in the Guild of St. Luke there from 1695 onwards, when he was fined for selling a painting without being a member of the guild. <s> His works appear frequently in contemporary Middelburg taxation inventories <s> Coorte was probably not well known to the people who lived at the same time, outside the city of Middelburg. <s> Much like Vermeer, he was almost entirely forgotten. <s> In the 1950s, the Dutch art historian Laurens J. Bol revived his reputation, beginning with an article in 1952, and finally publishing the first monograph and catalogue raissone on Coorte in 1977 ("Adriaen Coorte", Amsterdam). <s> Bol arranged an exhibition of 35 examples of Coorte's work in 1958 at the Dordrechts Museum. <s> This became a sensation in the Netherlands; the poets Hans Faverey and Ed Leeflang were both inspired by the paintings. <s> In 2003 there was an exhibition at the National Gallery of Art, Washington. <s> In 2008 a new travelling exhibition was set up; "Ode to Coorte", that was nearly as successful, making Coorte the most celebrated "rediscovered" Dutch Baroque painter of recent decades.

title: Maureen Dowd
complex: Maureen Brigid Dowd ( ; born January 14, 1952) is an American columnist for "The New York Times" and an author. <s> During the 1970s and the early 1980s, Dowd worked for "Time" magazine and the "Washington Star", where she covered news and sports and wrote feature articles. <s> Dowd joined "The New York Times" in 1983 as a Metropolitan Reporter, and became an op-ed writer for the newspaper in 1995. <s> In 1999, Dowd was awarded a Pulitzer Prize for her series of columns on the Monica Lewinsky scandal in the Clinton administration. <s> Dowd was born the youngest of five children in Washington, D.C. <s> Her mother, Margaret "Peggy" (Meenehan), was a housewife, and her father, Mike Dowd, worked as a Washington, D.C. police inspector.
simple: Maureen Dowd (born January 14, 1952) is an American columnist for "The New York Times". <s> She worked for "Time" magazine in the 1970s and 1980s. <s> She worked for the "Washington Star". <s> She first joined "The New York Times" in 1983. <s> In 1999, Dowd received a Pulitzer Prize. <s> It was for her series of columns on the Monica Lewinsky scandal in the Clinton administration. <s> She was born in Washington, D.C..

title: Birthplace of Ronald Reagan
complex: The Birthplace of Ronald Reagan, also known as the Graham Building, is located in an apartment on the second floor of a late 19th-century commercial building in Tampico, Illinois, United States. <s> The building was built in 1896 and housed a tavern from that time until 1915. <s> On February 6, 1911 the future 40th President of the United States, Ronald Reagan, was born in the apartment there, the family moving into a house in Tampico a few months later. <s> Architecturally, the two-story brick building is similar to its neighbors, all of which are part of a historic district added to the U.S. National Register of Historic Places in 1982.
simple: The Birthplace of Ronald Reagan, also known as the Graham Building, is located in an apartment on the second floor of a late 19th-century commercial building in Tampico, Illinois, United States. <s> The building was built in 1896 and housed a tavern from that time until 1915. <s> On February 6, 1911 the future 40th President of the United States, Ronald Reagan, was born in the apartment there, the family moving into a house in Tampico a few months later. <s> Architecturally, the two story brick building is similar to its neighbors, all of which are part of a historic district added to the U.S. National Register of Historic Places in 1982.

title: Paul Sahlin
complex: Paul Sahlin, originally "Johansson", born 30 March 1955 in Strömslund in Trollhättan, Sweden, is a Swedish singer and songwriter, scoring successes in Sweden and West Germany. <s> Later he became a funeral director He is well known for songs like the 1977 Svensktoppen hit "Guenerina"., <s> , "Flyg min fjäril flyg" and the Christmas song "Jag önskar er alla en riktigt god jul". <s> He also was the singer in Matz Bladhs between 1991 and 2004. <s> Earlier, he had been the singer in the band "Säwes". <s> Later, he became active with his dansband "Paul Sahlins".
simple: Paul Sahlin, originally "Johansson", born 30 March 1955 in Strömslund in Trollhättan, Sweden, is a Swedish singer and songwriter. <s> He scored successes in Sweden and West Germany. <s> Later he bcame a funeral director He is well-known for songs like the 1977 Svensktoppen hit "Guenerina", "Flyg min fjäril flyg" and the Christmas song "Jag önskar er alla en riktigt god jul". <s> He also was the singer in Matz Bladhs between 1991 and 2004. <s> Earlier, he had been the singer in the band "Säwes". <s> Later, he became active with his dansband "Paul Sahlins".

title: Bangladesh–India border
complex: India is constructing the India–Bangladesh barrier, a 3406 km fence of barbed wire and concrete just under 3 m high, to prevent smuggling of narcotics. <s> Out of this, 500 km of fencing was completed at the cost of by November 2007.
simple: The Indo-Bangladeshi barrier is a 4,000-kilometer fence that India is presently constructing to seal off the Indian-Bangladeshi international border from what was formerly East Bengal.

title: Joel Grey
complex: Joel Grey (born Joel David Katz; April 11, 1932) is an American actor, singer, dancer, director, and photographer. <s> He is best known for portraying the Master of Ceremonies in the Kander & Ebb musical "Cabaret", as well as in the 1972 film adaptation. <s> He has won an Academy Award, Tony Award, and Golden Globe Award. <s> Grey was born in Cleveland, Ohio, the son of Goldie "Grace" (née Epstein) and Mickey Katz, a Jewish actor, comedian, and musician. <s> He attended Alexander Hamilton High School in Los Angeles, California. <s> Grey originated the role of the Master of Ceremonies in the Broadway musical "Cabaret" in 1966 for which he won a Tony Award. <s> Additional Broadway credits include "Come Blow Your Horn" (1961), "Stop the World - I Want to Get Off" (1962), "Half a Sixpence" (1965), "George M!" <s> (1968), "Goodtime Charley" (1975), "The Grand Tour" (1979), "Chicago" (1996), "Wicked" (2003), and "Anything Goes" (2011). <s> In November 1995, he performed as the Wizard in "" a staged concert of the popular story at Lincoln Center to benefit the Children's Defense Fund. <s> The performance was originally broadcast on Turner Network Television (TNT) in November 1995, and released on CD and video in 1996. <s> Grey won an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor in March 1973 for his performance as the Master of Ceremonies in the 1972 film version of "Cabaret". <s> His victory was part of a "Cabaret" near-sweep, which saw Liza Minnelli win Best Actress and Bob Fosse win Best Director, although it lost the Best Picture Oscar to "The Godfather." <s> For that role, Grey also won a BAFTA award for "The Most Promising Newcomer to Leading Film Roles" and Best Supporting Actor awards from the Golden Globes, Kansas City Film Critics Circle, National Board of Review of Motion Pictures, National Society of Film Critics, and a Tony Award for his original stage performance six years prior, making him one of only ten people who have won both a Tony Award and an Academy Award for the same role. <s> In 1958, Grey married Jo Wilder; they divorced in 1982. <s> Together, they had two children: actress Jennifer (star of the film "Dirty Dancing") and chef James. <s> He is a photographer; his first book of photographs, "Pictures I Had to Take", was published in 2003; its follow-up, "Looking Hard at Unexpected Things", was published in 2006. <s> His third book, "1.3 – Images from My Phone", a book of photographs taken with his camera phone, was published in 2009. <s> An exhibition of his work was held in April 2011 at the Museum of the City of New York, titled "Joel Grey/A New York Life." <s> His fourth book, "The Billboard Papers: Photographs by Joel Grey", came out in 2013 and depicts the many-layered billboards of New York City. <s> In January 2015, Grey discussed his sexuality in an interview with "People", stating: "I don't like labels, but if you have to put a label on it, I'm a gay man." <s> Grey writes about his family, his acting career, and the challenges of being gay in his 2016 memoir, "Master of Ceremonies".
simple: Joel Grey (born Joel David Katz; April 11, 1932) is an American actor, singer, dancer, and photographer. <s> He also won the Golden Globe Award. <s> Gray was born in Cleveland, Ohio to Goldie Epstein and to Mickey Katz. <s> He studied at the Cleveland Play House and at Alexander Hamilton High School in Los Angeles, California. <s> Grey played the role of the Master of Ceremonies in the Broadway musical "Cabaret" in 1966 for which he won the Tony Award. <s> Grey won an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor in March 1973 for his performance in the same role in the 1972 film version of "Cabaret". <s> In 1958, Grey married Jo Wilder; they divorced in 1982. <s> Together, they had two children: actress Jennifer Grey and chef James. <s> Gray is also a published photographer, with books "Pictures I Had to Take" 2003; its follow-up, "Looking Hard at Unexpected Things" 2006. <s> His third book, "1.3 – Images from My Phone", a book of photographs taken with his camera phone, was published in 2009. <s> An exhibit of his work was held in April 2011 at the Museum of the City of New York, titled "Joel Grey/A New York Life." <s> In January 2015, Grey talked about his sexuality in an interview with "People", stating: "I don't like labels, but if you have to put a label on it, I'm a gay man".

title: St. Moritz
complex: St. Moritz (also , , , ) is a high Alpine resort town in the Engadine in Switzerland, at an elevation of about 1800 m above sea level. <s> It is Upper Engadine's major village and a municipality in the district of Maloja in the Swiss canton of Graubünden. <s> St. Moritz lies on the southern slopes of the Albula Alps below the Piz Nair (3,056 m ) overlooking the flat and wide glaciated valley of the Upper Engadine and eponymous lake: Lake St. Moritz. <s> It hosted the Winter Olympics in 1928 and 1948.
simple: Saint Moritz (; ; ) is a ski resort in the Engadine valley in Switzerland. <s> The Olympic Winter Games were held here in 1928 and 1948.

title: Imp
complex: An imp is a mythological being similar to a fairy or demon, frequently described in folklore and superstition. <s> The word may perhaps derive from the term "ympe", used to denote a young grafted tree. <s> Imps are often described as mischievous more than seriously threatening, and as lesser beings rather than more important supernatural beings. <s> The attendants of the devil are sometimes described as imps. <s> They are usually described as lively and having small stature.
simple: An imp is a mythological creature similar to a fairy or demon, usually described in folklore and superstition. <s> Imps are usually described as mischievous more than a serious threat, and as lesser creatures, not important supernatural beings. <s> The small helpers who attend the devil are sometimes described as imps. <s> They are usually described as small and very active.

title: Crimean Tatar Wikipedia
complex: The Crimean Tatar Wikipedia is the Crimean Tatar language edition of the free online encyclopedia Wikipedia. <s> The articles were originally written in Wikimedia Incubator, and the Crimean Tatar Wikipedia was created on January 12, 2008. <s> Currently ( 2019), Crimean Tatar has 6618 articles. <s> As of 2019, Crimean Tatar Wikipedia has 6618 articles. <s> The main problem of the project is a lack of volunteers. <s> The vast majority of edits are made by several volunteers, none of whom is a native speaker.
simple: The Crimean Tatar Wikipedia is the Crimean Tatar language edition of the free online encyclopedia Wikipedia. <s> The articles were originally written in Wikimedia Incubator, and the Crimean Tatar Wikipedia was created on January 12, 2008. <s> As of ( 2019), Crimean Tatar has 6599 articles. <s> As of 2019, Crimean Tatar Wikipedia has 6599 articles. <s> The main problem of the project is a lack of volunteers. <s> The vast majority of edits are made by several volunteers, none of whom is a native speaker.

title: Dore (river)
complex: The Dore is a 141 km long river in central France in the department of Puy-de-Dôme. <s> It is a right tributary of the Allier. <s> Its source is near the town of Saint-Germain-l'Herm in the Massif Central. <s> The Dore flows generally north, through the following towns: Arlanc, Ambert, Courpière, and Puy-Guillaume. <s> The Dore flows into the Allier 6 km north of Puy-Guillaume.
simple: The Dore is a river in central France in the Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes region, in the Puy-de-Dôme department. <s> The Dore river has a length of 140.5 km, and a drainage basin with an area of 1710 km2. <s> It is a right tributary of the Allier river and it is one of the three more important tributaries of the Allier river (with the Sioule and Alagnon rivers). <s> It flows through the following "communes", among others: Dore-l’Église, Marsac-en-Livradois, Ambert, Vertolaye, Olliergues, Sauviat, Courpière, Néronde-sur-Dore, Peschadoires, Dorat, Puy-Guillaume. <s> Finally, it flows into the Allier river in the "commune" of Ris.

title: Auguste Vestris
complex: Marie-Jean-Augustin Vestris, known as Auguste Vestris (27 March 1760 – 5 December 1842), was a French dancer. <s> He was born in Paris as the illegitimate son of Gaétan Vestris and Marie Allard (1742–1802). <s> His father was a Florentine dancer who had joined the Paris Opéra in 1748, his mother was a French dancer in the same theatre. <s> He was dubbed "le dieu de la danse", ("the god of dance"), a popular title bestowed on the leading male dancer of each generation (previous 'Gods of the Dance' included his father Gaétan and Gaétan's teacher, Louis Dupré). <s> He made his debut at the Paris Opéra (as had his mother, Marie Allard) in the third divertissement of the pastorale "La Cinquantaine" (written by Desfontaines-Lavallée and set to music by Jean-Benjamin de La Borde) in 1772 and was immediately recognized for his talent. <s> He was accepted as a regular member of the troupe in 1775, became a soloist in 1776, a "premier danseur" (principal dancer) in 1778, and finally he was appointed "premier sujet de la danse" (roughly corresponding to modern étoile) in 1780, holding this rank in the corps de ballet for the next 36 years. <s> After his retirement he trained many famous dancers of the 19th century including August Bournonville, Marius Petipa, Lucien Petipa, Fanny Elssler, Jules Perrot and Marie Taglioni. <s> It was with Taglioni in 1835 that he performed a minuet at the age of 75. <s> Auguste Vestris is not to be confused with his son, Armand Vestris, who married the English actress-manager Lucia Elizabeth Vestris in 1813.
simple: Marie-Jean-Augustin Vestris (27 March 1760 – 5 December 1842) was a French dancer and choreographer. <s> He is known as Auguste Vestris <s> Vestris was born in Paris, the son of Gaetano Vestris and his mistress, the dancer Marie Allard. <s> He was taught by his father, and made his debut in 1772 in the divertissement "La Cinquantaine". <s> Vestris was appointed a soloist at the Paris Opéra in 1776, "premier danseur" in 1778, and "premier sujet de la danse" in 1780. <s> He taught many of the famous dancers of the age. <s> Among his pupils were Marius Petipa, Fanny Elssler, August Bournonville, Marie Taglioni and Jules Perrot. <s> In 1835, at the age of 75, he danced a minuet at the Opéra with Taglioni.

title: DuckDuckGo
complex: DuckDuckGo (DDG) is an internet search engine that emphasizes protecting searchers' privacy and avoiding the filter bubble of personalized search results. <s> DuckDuckGo distinguishes itself from other search engines by not profiling its users and by showing all users the same search results for a given search term, and emphasizes returning the best results, rather than the most results, generating those results from over 400 individual sources, including crowdsourced sites such as Wikipedia, and other search engines like Bing, Yahoo!, and Yandex. <s> As of August 2019, it had 44,196,092 daily direct searches on average. <s> The company is based in Paoli, Pennsylvania, in Greater Philadelphia, and has 67 employees as of July 2019 . <s> The company name is a reference to the children's game duck, duck, goose.
simple: Duckduckgo is a search engine made by Gabriel Weinberg. <s> As of August 2019, it received 44,196,092 searches every day. <s> It is headquartered in Paoli, Pennsylvania, USA.

title: Johnson County, Wyoming
complex: Johnson County is a county in the north central part of the U.S. state of Wyoming. <s> At the 2010 United States Census, the population was 8,569. <s> The county seat is Buffalo. <s> Kaycee is the only other incorporated town in the county. <s> At the 2010 United States Census, there were 8,569 people, 3,782 households, and 2,410 families in the county.
simple: Johnson County is a county in the U.S. state of Wyoming. <s> The population was 8,569 as of the 2010 census. <s> The county seat is Buffalo. <s> The only other incorporated territory in the county is Kaycee.

title: Ice hockey at the Olympic Games
complex: Ice hockey tournaments have been staged at the Olympic Games since 1920. <s> The men's tournament was introduced at the 1920 Summer Olympics and was transferred permanently to the Winter Olympic Games program in 1924, in France. <s> The women's tournament was first held at the 1998 Winter Olympics.
simple: Ice hockey tournaments have been played at the Olympic Games since 1920. <s> The men's tournament was first played at the 1920 Summer Olympics, but was moved to the Winter Olympics in 1924. <s> The women's tournament was first held at the 1998 Winter Olympics.

title: Nguyễn Thiện Nhân
complex: Nguyễn Thiện Nhân (born 12 June 1953) is a Vietnamese politician and the current Secretary of Ho Chi Minh City's Central Party Committee since May 10, 2017. <s> His previous post was the Chairman of the Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front. <s> He was a Deputy Prime Minister of Vietnam between 2007 and 2013, and was Minister of Education and Training of Vietnam between 2006 and 2010.
simple: Nguyễn Thiện Nhân (born 12 June 1953) is the Secretary of Communist Party of Vietnam in Ho Chi Minh City from 10 May 2017. <s> His previous post was Chairman of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front

title: Charles Barkley
complex: Charles Wade Barkley (born February 20, 1963) is an American retired professional basketball player who is currently an analyst on "Inside the NBA". <s> Nicknamed Chuck, Sir Charles, Street Beef, and The Round Mound of Rebound, Barkley established himself as one of the National Basketball Association's most dominant power forwards. <s> An All-American power forward at Auburn University, he was drafted as a junior by the Philadelphia 76ers with the 5th pick of the 1984 NBA draft.
simple: Charles Wade Barkley (born February 20, 1963) is an American retired professional basketball player and politician. <s> He is an analyst on the television show "Inside the NBA". <s> Nicknamed "Sir Charles" for his aggressive and outspoken behavior and "The Round Mound of Rebound," for his unusual build and talent as a player, Barkley established himself as one of the National Basketball Association's most dominating power forwards.

title: Unforgiven: In Your House
complex: Unforgiven: In Your House was the 21st professional wrestling pay-per-view (PPV) event under the In Your House name from the World Wrestling Federation (WWF). <s> It took place on April 26, 1998, at the Greensboro Coliseum in Greensboro, North Carolina. <s> This was the first WWF pay-per-view that used the new "scratch" logo for promotional work, which had first appeared on the ring apron at WrestleMania XIV. <s> This event saw the first Inferno match and WWF's first evening gown match.
simple: Unforgiven: In Your House was a professional wrestling pay-per-view show made by World Wrestling Federation (WWF). <s> It was the 21st pay-per-view to be held under the WWF's In Your House name. <s> It was held on April 26, 1998 at Greensboro Coliseum in Greensboro, North Carolina. <s> The PPV was also the first to use the "scratch" logo for their promotional work, while WrestleMania XIV featured the logo on the ring apron, the official graphic still featured the New Generation logo. <s> The pay-per-view also held the first ever Inferno Match and WWF's first evening gown match.

title: Simplon, Valais
complex: Simplon (earlier name "Simpeln", Walliser German: "Simpilu", Italian: "Sempione", French: "Simplon") is a municipality in the district of Brig in the canton of Valais in Switzerland. <s> The former member of the Swiss Federal Council Josef Escher was born in Simplon.
simple: Simplon is a municipality of the district of Brig in the canton of Valais in Switzerland. <s> A member of the Swiss Federal Council Josef Escher was born in Simplon.

title: Kiyan Prince Foundation Stadium
complex: The Kiyan Prince Foundation Stadium is an all-seater football stadium in Shepherd's Bush, London, which is home to Queens Park Rangers. <s> The stadium was traditionally known as Loftus Road but was formally renamed on 7 June 2019 when the football club announced it was gifting stadium naming rights to 'The Kiyan Prince Foundation', a charity set up in honour of former QPR youth player Kiyan Prince.
simple: Loftus Road is a football stadium in Shepherd's Bush, West London.

title: LimeWire
complex: In November 2010, as a response to the legal challenges regarding LimeWire, an anonymous individual by the handle of Meta Pirate released a modified version of LimeWire Pro, which was entitled LimeWire Pirate Edition. <s> It came without the Ask.com toolbar, advertising, spyware, and backdoors, as well as all dependencies on LimeWire LLC servers.
simple: In June 2010, the National Music Publishers Association also took legal action against LimeWire.

title: Pour Some Sugar on Me
complex: "Pour Some Sugar on Me" is a song by the English rock band Def Leppard from their 1987 album "Hysteria". <s> It reached number 2 on the US "Billboard" Hot 100 on 23 July 1988, behind "Hold On to the Nights" by Richard Marx. <s> "Pour Some Sugar on Me" was ranked #2 on VH1's "100 Greatest Songs of the 80s" in 2006.
simple: "Pour Some Sugar on Me" is a 1987 heavy metal single by Def Leppard. <s> The song was from Def Leppard's studio album "Hysteria". <s> It reached #2 on "Billboard" Hot 100 in July of 1988.

title: Jacques Hamel
complex: Jacques Hamel (30 November 1930 – 26 July 2016) was a French Catholic priest who served in Saint-Étienne-du-Rouvray. <s> On 26 July 2016, Hamel was murdered during the 2016 Normandy church attack by two Muslim men pledging allegiance to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant while he celebrated Mass in his church. <s> The circumstances of his death have led him to be called a martyr by Christians, including Pope Francis, non-Christians, and the press. <s> Calls to make him a saint started soon after his death. <s> The canonization cause was officially opened at diocesan level in April 2017, after Pope Francis had waived the otherwise mandatory five-year waiting period for the opening of such causes. <s> Hamel was born on 30 November 1930 in Darnétal, France. <s> At the age of six he became a choirboy in and at 14 he entered the minor seminary.
simple: Jacques Hamel (30 November 1930 – 26 July 2016) was a French Catholic priest. <s> He worked in the parish of Saint-Étienne-du-Rouvray. <s> On 26 July 2016, Hamel was murdered during the 2016 Normandy church attack by two Muslim men pledging allegiance to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant while he celebrated Mass in his church. <s> Hamel was called a martyr by some international press shortly after his death. <s> Calls to make him a saint started soon after his death. <s> The canonization cause was officially opened at diocesan level in April 2017, after Pope Francis had waived the otherwise mandatory five-year waiting period for the opening of such causes. <s> He was born in Darnétal, Seine-Maritime, France.

title: Ginsters
complex: Ginsters is a company based in Callington in Cornwall, in the south-west of England. <s> The biggest selling pasty maker in the UK, it specialises in making mass-produced pasties, sausage rolls, sandwiches, pasta bowls and other savoury snacks.
simple: Ginsters is a company in Callington, Cornwall that makes pasties.

title: Jim Edgar
complex: James Edgar (born July 22, 1946) is an American politician who was the 38th Governor of Illinois from 1991 to 1999. <s> Previously he served as a member of the Illinois House of Representatives from 1976 to 1979 and as Illinois Secretary of State from 1981 to 1991. <s> Though still popular, he surprised many by retiring from elected office after his second term as governor, claiming that heart problems he had while governor were not a factor in his decision.
simple: James "Jim" Edgar (born July 22, 1946) is an American Republican politician. <s> He was Governor of Illinois from January 1991 through January 1999. <s> Edgar was born on July 22, 1946 in Vinita, Oklahoma. <s> He was the Illinois Secretary of State from January 1981 through January 1991.

title: Don McCarthy
complex: Donald McCarthy, (19 June 1955 – 21 July 2018) was a British entrepreneur and philanthropist. <s> He was most known for having been the chairman of House of Fraser. <s> From 2007 until 2012 McCarthy also was chairman of Aurum, a British watch and jewellery retailer. <s> Aurum was acquired by US private equity firm Apollo Global Management in December 2012. <s> McCarthy, who had controlled 25% of the shares, left Aurum after the Apollo acquisition. <s> McCarthy was appointed Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the 2017 New Year Honours for services to business and philanthropy.
simple: Donald McCarthy, CBE (19 June 1955 – 21 July 2018) was a British entrepreneur and philanthropist. <s> McCarthy died on 21 July 2018 from cancer in London at the age of 63. <s> He was known for being the chairman of House of Fraser from 2006 to 2014. <s> From 2007 until 2012 McCarthy also was chairman of Aurum, a British watch and jewellery retailer. <s> McCarthy was appointed Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the 2017 New Year Honours for services to business and philanthropy.

title: Heinz Lieven
complex: Heinz Lieven (born April 18, 1928) is a German actor. <s> Lieven was born in Blankenese, Hamburg, where he was raised. <s> In 1948, he began an actor's training with the actors Helmuth Gmelin and Bernhard Minetti. <s> He married a makeup artist in 1966 and has two sons with her. <s> He made his international film debut in Aleksandar Petrovic's "Group Portrait with a Lady", and played a former SS Officer named Aloise Lange in the 2011 movie "This Must Be the Place".
simple: Heinz Lieven (born April 18, 1928) is a German actor. <s> He was born in Hamburg, Germany. <s> Lieven made his international movie debut in Aleksandar Petrovic's "Group Portrait with Lady" and played a former SS Officer named Aloise Lange in the 2011 movie "This Must Be the Place".

title: Isaías Pimentel
complex: Isaías "Iyo" S. Pimentel (16 February 1933 – 26 June 2017) was a Venezuelan international tennis player. <s> Born on the Dutch island of Curaçao in 1933, Pimentel was three times Curaçaoan champion. <s> He competed in the Davis Cup, representing Venezuela, a number of times, from 1957 to 1966.
simple: Isaías "Iyo" S. Pimentel (16 February 1933 — 26 June 2017) was a Venezuelan international tennis player. <s> He was born on the Dutch island of Curaçao. <s> Pimentel was three times Curaçaoan champion. <s> He competed in the Davis Cup, representing Venezuela, a number of times, from 1957 to 1966.

title: Monkey Island (series)
complex: Monkey Island is a series of adventure games. <s> The first four games in the series were produced and published by LucasArts, formerly known as Lucasfilm Games. <s> The fifth installment of the franchise was developed by Telltale Games in collaboration with LucasArts. <s> The games follow the misadventures of the hapless Guybrush Threepwood as he struggles to become the most notorious pirate in the Caribbean, defeat the plans of the evil undead pirate LeChuck and win the heart of governess Elaine Marley. <s> Each game's plot usually involves the mysterious Monkey Island and its impenetrable secrets. <s> Each of the games takes place on in the Caribbean around the Golden Age of Piracy sometime between the 17th and 18th centuries. <s> The islands teem with pirates dressed in outfits that seem to come from films and comic books rather than history, and there are many deliberate anachronisms and references to modern-day popular culture.
simple: Monkey Island is a well-known adventure game series made and published by LucasArts. <s> In the different games the main character Guybrush Threepwood, who wants to become a pirate, has many adventures. <s> Each of the games usually involves the evil undead pirate LeChuck and the island which gave the series its name. <s> The story takes place in the Caribbean.

title: Altamonte Springs, Florida
complex: Altamonte Springs is a suburban city in Seminole County, Florida, United States, which had a population of 41,496 at the 2010 census. <s> The city is in the northern suburbs of the Orlando–Kissimmee–Sanford Metropolitan Statistical Area, which the United States Census Bureau estimated had a population of 2,054,574 in 2008. <s> As of the census of 2000, there were 41,200 people, 18,821 households, and 10,012 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 4,631.1 inhabitants per square mile (1,787.3/km).
simple: Altamonte Springs is a city of Florida in the United States. <s> The population of this town was about 41,200 in 2000.

title: Judith McConnell
complex: Judith Lynn McConnell (born April 6, 1944) is an American actress, best known for her role as Sophia Wayne Capwell on the TV series "Santa Barbara", on which she appeared from 1984 to 1993. <s> Prior to her stints as Valerie Conway on "As the World Turns" from 1976–79 and as Sophia Capwell on Santa Barbara, Judith played Nurse Augusta McLeod on "General Hospital" from 1973-75. <s> Her character murdered longtime GH villain Phil Brewer which aired December 6, 1974 after he threatened her in regards to her unborn child fathered by the married Dr. Peter Taylor.
simple: Judith McConnell (born April 6, 1944 in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania) is an American actress. <s> Sheplayed Sophia Wayne Capwell on the soap opera "Santa Barbara". <s> She also played Nurse Augusta McLeod on the series "General Hospital".

title: List of U.S. state insects
complex: State insects are designated by 48 individual states of the fifty United States. <s> Some states have more than one designated insect, or have multiple categories (e.g., state insect and state butterfly, etc.).
simple: Forty-one of the fifty United States have selected state insects.

title: St Breward
complex: St Breward is a civil parish and village in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. <s> It is on the western side of Bodmin Moor, about 6 miles (10 km) north of Bodmin. <s> At the 2011 census the parish population including Cooksland and Fentonadle was 919. <s> The parish name derives from Saint Branwalader. <s> Until the 19th century it was commonly known by the corrupt form of the name: 'Simonward'. <s> In the 17th century St. Breward was two separate villages, Churchtown (higher) and St. Breward (lower). <s> More houses were built and slowly the villages merged into one. <s> There are several main parts to the village: Churchtown, Rylands, Row, Limehead, Wenford, Penvorder, Higher Penquite and Lower Penquite. <s> The bridge and hamlet of Wenfordbridge lies on the River Camel at the boundary of St Breward parish with the neighbouring parish of St Tudy. <s> The parish includes a moorland area which contains Rough Tor and Brown Willy, which is the highest point in Cornwall.
simple: St Breward is a parish and village in Cornwall, United Kingdom. <s> It is on the western side of Bodmin Moor about 6 miles (10 km) north of Bodmin. <s> The parish name derives from Saint Branwalader. <s> In the 17th century St Breward was two separate villages, Churchtown (higher) and St. Breward (lower). <s> More houses were built and slowly the villages merged into one. <s> There are several main parts to the village: Churchtown, Rylands, Limehead, Wenford, Penvorder, Higher Penquite and Lower Penquite. <s> The parish includes a moorland area which contains Rough Tor and Brown Willy, which is the highest point in Cornwall.

title: Arnett E. Girardeau
complex: Arnett Elysus Girardeau Sr. (July 15, 1929 – October 26, 2017) was an American dentist and former politician in the state of Florida. <s> Girardeau was born in 1929 in Jacksonville, Florida. <s> He graduated from Howard University where he earned a D.D.S. degree; he also attended graduate school at Wayne State University and Fisk University. <s> The first African-American elected outside of Miami since Reconstruction, Girardueau served in the Florida House of Representatives from 1976 to 1983. <s> In 1982, he was elected to the State Senate and he served until 1992. <s> He was president pro tempore of the senate in the later years of his term. <s> Girardeau died on October 26, 2017 at the age of 88.
simple: Arnett Elysus Girardeau Sr. (July 15, 1929 – October 26, 2017) was an American dentist, civil rights activist and former politician in the state of Florida. <s> He was born in Jacksonville, Florida. <s> He was a member of the Florida House of Representatives from the 16th distrist from 1976 to 1982. <s> Girardeau died on October 26, 2017 in Jacksonville of a heart attack at the age of 88.

title: Lindesbergs VBK
complex: Lindesbergs VBK is a volleyball club in Lindesberg, Sweden, established in 1971. <s> The club won the Swedish women's national championship in 2012
simple: Lindesbergs VBK is a volleyball club in Lindesberg, Sweden. <s> It was established in 1971. <s> The club won the Swedish women's national championship in 2012

title: Ontario Highway 5
complex: King's Highway 5, commonly referred to as Highway 5 and historically as the Dundas Highway, is a provincially maintained highway in the Canadian province of Ontario. <s> The east–west highway travels a distance of 12.7 km between Highway 8 at Peter's Corners, north of Hamilton, and Highway 6 at Clappison's Corners. <s> Prior to several sections being downloaded to the municipalities in which they reside, Highway 5 served as bypass to Highway 2, connecting with it in both Paris and Toronto, a distance of 114.3 km . <s> It begins at the southern end of Highway 8 in Peter's Corners, next to the junction with former Highway 52. <s> To the west, the road is known as Hamilton Regional Road 5 and proceeds towards Paris.
simple: Ontario Highway 5 is a provincial highway in Ontario, Canada. <s> The highway is 12.7 kilometers (7.9 miles) long. <s> It starts at Highway 8 near Peter's Corners. <s> It ends at Highway 6 at Clappisons Corners.

title: Yevgeny Primakov
complex: Yevgeny Maksimovich Primakov ( , tr. <s> "Yevgeniy Maksimovich Primakov"; 29 October 1929 – 26 June 2015) was a Russian politician and diplomat who served as Prime Minister of Russia from 1998 to 1999. <s> During his long career, he also served as Foreign Minister, Speaker of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union, and chief of the intelligence service. <s> Primakov was an academician (Arabist) and a member of the Presidium of the Russian Academy of Sciences. <s> Primakov was born in Kiev in the Ukrainian SSR and grew up in Tbilisi in the Georgian SSR. <s> Primakov served as Minister of Foreign Affairs from January 1996 until September 1998.
simple: Yevgeny Maksimovich Primakov (, tr. <s> "Yevgeniy Maksimovich Primakov"; 29 October 1929 – 26 June 2015) was a Russian politician and diplomat. <s> He was the Prime Minister of Russia from 1998 to 1999. <s> Primakov was born to a partly Jewish family (his mother was Jewish) in Kiev, Ukrainian SSR, Soviet Union now Ukraine.

title: Peristeri
complex: Peristeri (Greek: Περιστέρι, meaning "pigeon/dove" in Greek) is a suburban municipality in the northwestern part of the Athens agglomeration, Greece. <s> With 139,981 inhabitants (2011 census), it is the seventh-largest municipality of Greece by population. <s> Peristeri is located about 4 km northwest of the centre of Athens. <s> It lies between the Egaleo Mountain in the northwest and the Cephissus river in the southeast.
simple: Peristeri is a suburban municipality in the northwestern part of Athens agglomeration, Greece. <s> It has 139,981 inhabitants (2011 census). <s> It is the seventh-largest municipality of Greece by population. <s> It is about 4 km.

title: Syllogism
complex: A syllogism (Greek: "syllogismos", "conclusion, inference") is a kind of logical argument that applies deductive reasoning to arrive at a conclusion based on two or more propositions that are asserted or assumed to be true. <s> In antiquity, two rival theories of the syllogism existed: Aristotelian syllogistic and Stoic syllogistic. <s> Aristotle defines the syllogism as "a discourse in which certain (specific) things having been supposed, something different from the things supposed results of necessity because these things are so". <s> Despite this very general definition, in "Prior Analytics" Aristotle limits himself to categorical syllogisms that consist of three categorical propositions. <s> These include categorical modal syllogisms. <s> Within academic contexts, the syllogism was superseded by first-order predicate logic following the work of Gottlob Frege, in particular his "Begriffsschrift" ("Concept Script") (1879), but syllogisms remain useful in some circumstances, and for general-audience introductions to logic. <s> Each of the three distinct terms represents a category. <s> In the above example, "humans", "mortal", and "Greeks". <s> "Mortal" is the major term, "Greeks" the minor term. <s> The premises also have one term in common with each other, which is known as the "middle term"; in this example, "humans". <s> Both of the premises are universal, as is the conclusion. <s> Here, the major term is "die", the minor term is "men", and the middle term is "mortals". <s> Again, both premises are universal, hence so is the conclusion. <s> A sorites is a form of argument in which a series of incomplete syllogisms is so arranged that the predicate of each premise forms the subject of the next until the subject of the first is joined with the predicate of the last in the conclusion. <s> For example, one might argue that all lions are big cats, all big cats are predators, and all predators are carnivores. <s> To conclude that therefore all lions are carnivores is to construct a sorites argument.
simple: A syllogism is a deduction. <s> It is a kind of logical argument in which one proposition (the "conclusion") is inferred from two or more others (the premises). <s> In the "Prior Analytics", Aristotle defines the syllogism as "a discourse in which, certain things having been supposed, something different from the things supposed results of necessity because these things are so". <s> The syllogism was replaced by first-order logic after the work of Gottlob Frege, published in 1879. <s> Each of the three distinct terms represents a category. <s> In the above example, "men," "mortal," and "Greeks." <s> "Mortal" is the major term; "Greeks", the minor term. <s> The premises also have one term in common with each other, which is known as the "middle term"; in this example, "man." <s> Both of the premises are universal, as is the conclusion. <s> The major premise is universal; the minor premise and the conclusion are particular. <s> Here, the major term is "die", the minor term is "men," and the middle term is "mortals". <s> A sorites is a form of argument in which a series of incomplete syllogisms is so arranged that the predicate of each premise forms the subject of the next until the subject of the first is joined with the predicate of the last in the conclusion. <s> For example, if one argues that a given number of grains of sand does not make a heap and that an additional grain does not either, then to conclude that no additional amount of sand will make a heap is to construct a sorites argument.

title: Kinathukadavu taluk
complex: Kinathukadavu taluk is a taluk in the Coimbatore district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters is the town of Kinathukadavu. <s> It was carved out of the Pollachi taluk in 2012.
simple: Kinathukadavu taluk is a taluk of rural Coimbatore district of the Indian state of Tamil Nadu. <s> The headquarters is the town of Kinathukadavu..

title: Toy Fox Terrier
complex: The Toy Fox Terrier is a small terrier breed of dog, directly descended from the larger Fox Terrier but considered a separate breed.
simple: The Toy Fox Terrier (also known as American Toy Terrier, Amertoy) is a small terrier breed of dogs. <s> They are related to the Fox Terrier, but are considered a separate breed.

title: Leuze-en-Hainaut
complex: Leuze-en-Hainaut is a municipality in the province of Hainaut, Wallonia, Belgium. <s> Comprising the former municipalities of Blicquy, Chapelle-à-Oie, Chapelle-à-Wattines, Gallaix, Grandmetz, Leuze-en-Hainaut, Pipaix, Thieulain, Tourpes, and Willaupuis, it had a population on 1 January 2016 of 13,699.
simple: Leuze-en-Hainaut is a municipality in the Belgian province of Hainaut.

title: Red Hat Linux
complex: Red Hat Linux, created by the company Red Hat, was a widely used Linux distribution until its discontinuation in 2004. <s> In 2003, Red Hat discontinued the Red Hat Linux line in favor of Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) for enterprise environments. <s> Fedora, developed by the community-supported Fedora Project and sponsored by Red Hat, is a free-of-cost alternative intended for home use. <s> Red Hat Linux 9, the final release, hit its official end-of-life on April 30, 2004, although updates were published for it through 2006 by the Fedora Legacy project until that shut down in early 2007.
simple: Red Hat Linux is a discontinued Linux operating system, replaced by RHEL (Red Hat Enterprise Linux). <s> The last publicly-released version was Red Hat Linux 9 in April, 2003.

title: Eugene Allen
complex: Eugene Allen (July 14, 1919 – March 31, 2010) was an American waiter and butler who worked for the US government at the White House for 34 years until he retired as the head butler in 1986. <s> Allen's life was the inspiration for the 2013 film "The Butler". <s> Allen was born in Buckingham County, Virginia and raised on Shirland Farm near Scottsville. <s> He worked as a waiter for many years, in "whites-only resorts and country clubs", including The Homestead resort in Hot Springs, Virginia, and a club in Washington. <s> He started in the White House in 1952 as a "pantry man", a job which involved basic tasks such as dish washing, stocking and cleaning silverware. <s> Over the years Allen rose in his position, becoming the butler to the president. <s> Allen finally attained the most prestigious rank of butlers serving in the White House, "Maître d'hôtel", in 1981, during the presidency of Ronald Reagan. <s> Reagan invited Allen and his wife Helene to a state dinner in honor of Helmut Kohl at the White House. <s> Allen was the first White House butler ever to be invited as a guest to a state dinner. <s> He retired in 1986. <s> Allen had been married to his wife, Helene, for 65 years. <s> They met at a birthday party in Washington in 1942, and married a year later in 1943. <s> The couple had one son, Charles Allen. <s> He and his wife had intended to vote for Barack Obama in 2008, but she died the day before the election, on November 3. <s> Allen died of kidney failure at the Washington Adventist Hospital in Takoma Park, Maryland on March 31, 2010. <s> Allen's life was the inspiration for the 2013 film "The Butler".
simple: Eugene Allen (July 14, 1919 – March 31, 2010) was an American waiter and butler. <s> He worked for the White House for 34 years until he retired in 1986. <s> Allen's life was the inspiration for the movie "The Butler", released in 2013. <s> Allen was born in Scottsville, Virginia on July 14, 1919. <s> He began working as a waiter at a pool club. <s> He began working at the White House in 1952. <s> Allen earned the highest rank of butlers serving in the White House. <s> At the Maître d'hôtel in 1981, President Ronald Reagan invited Allen and his wife Helene to a state dinner at the White House. <s> The dinner was in honor of Helmut Kohl. <s> Allen met his wife Helene in 1942. <s> They had a son, Charles Allen. <s> Helene wanted to vote for Barack Obama in 2008, but she died the day before the election, on November 3, 2008. <s> Allen died at a hospital in Takoma Park, Maryland, from kidney failure.

title: Nasjonal Samling
complex: Nasjonal Samling (] , NS; literally "National Rally") was a Norwegian far-right party active from 1933 to 1945. <s> It was the only legal party of Norway from 1942 to 1945. <s> It was founded by former minister of defence Vidkun Quisling and a group of supporters such as Johan Bernhard Hjortwho led the party's paramilitary wing ("Hirden") for a short time before leaving the party in 1937 after various internal conflicts. <s> The party celebrated its founding on 17 May, Norway's national holiday, but was founded on 13 May 1933.
simple: Nasjonal Samling (Norwegian for "National Gathering" or "National Unity") was a fascist party in Norway, active in the period 1933–1945. <s> The party was founded by Vidkun Quisling and a group of sympathisers. <s> The party's paramilitary wing was called "Hirden" (the Hird).

title: Geer
complex: Geer is a Walloon municipality of Belgium in Province of Liège. <s> On January 1, 2006, Geer had a total population of 2,854.
simple: Geer is a municipality in the Belgian province of Liège.

title: Sint Philipsland (island)
complex: Sint Philipsland is a former island in the Dutch province of Zeeland. <s> Nowadays it is part of the municipality of Tholen.
simple: Sint Philipsland is a (former) island of the province of Zeeland, the Netherlands. <s> It belongs to the municipality of Tholen.

title: Donkey Konga
complex: Donkey Konga is a GameCube rhythm video game starring the ape Donkey Kong, developed by Namco and published by Nintendo. <s> Instead of the standard GameCube controllers, the game is intended to be played with a special controller called the DK Bongos that resemble two small bongo drums. <s> "Donkey Konga" was developed by the team who made the "Taiko no Tatsujin" series. <s> The tracks include hits such as "Louie Louie", "We Will Rock You", "Shining Star", "Rock Lobster" and "Losing My Religion". <s> There are tracks from the "Mario" series, "The Legend of Zelda" series and other Nintendo related music. <s> All regional variants of the game have differing track listings, and in the North American version of both games, almost all of the licensed non-Nintendo/traditional songs are shortened covers. <s> The Japanese, PAL, and US versions have different track lists. <s> The first two games have around 30 tracks each; "Donkey Konga 3" has 58. <s> Donkey Konga 2, marketed in Japan as "Donkey Konga 2: Hit Song Parade!", <s> , is the 2004 sequel to "Donkey Konga" for the Nintendo GameCube, a video game where the player must pound on a special, barrel-like controller called the DK Bongos along with a selected song.
simple: Donkey Konga is a rhythm video game for the Nintendo GameCube. <s> It was created by Namco and published by Nintendo. <s> It is played with the DK Bongos, a controller that looks like two bongo drums. <s> Music from Nintendo game series such as "Super Mario Bros." and "The Legend of Zelda" are included. <s> The Japanese, European, and American versions all have different song lists. <s> "Donkey Konga 3" was only released in Japan.

title: 1980s
complex: The 1980s (pronounced "nineteen-eighties", shortened to "the ' 80s") was a decade of the Gregorian calendar that began on January 1, 1980, and ended on December 31, 1989. <s> The 1980s was a decade of transformation in television.
simple: The 1980s was the decade that started on January 1, 1980 and ended on December 31, 1989.

title: Yasunari Kawabata
complex: Yasunari Kawabata (川端 康成 , Kawabata Yasunari , 11 June 1899 – 16 April 1972) was a Japanese novelist and short story writer whose spare, lyrical, subtly-shaded prose works won him the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1968, the first Japanese author to receive the award. <s> His works have enjoyed broad international appeal and are still widely read.
simple: Yasunari Kawabata (14 June 1899–16 April 1972) was a Japanese writer. <s> He was the winner of the 1968 Nobel Prize in Literature. <s> He was the first Japanese author to receive the award.

title: Jjigae
complex: Jjigae (Korean: 찌개, ] ) is a Korean dish similar to a Western stew. <s> There are many varieties; it is typically made with meat, seafood or vegetables in a broth seasoned with "gochujang", "doenjang", "ganjang" or "saeujeot". <s> "Jjigae" is usually served in a communal dish and boiling hot. <s> A Korean meal almost always includes either a "jjigae" or a "guk". <s> During the Joseon dynasty, it was known as "jochi", and two varieties would always be present on the King's "surasang". <s> The types of "jjigae" are often named according to their principal ingredients, such as "saengseon jjigae" (생선찌개) made from fish or "dubu jjigae" (두부찌개) made from tofu, or according to their broth and seasonings like "gochujang jjigae" (고추장찌개) or "doenjang jjigae" (된장찌개).
simple: Jjigae (찌개) is a Korean food like stew. <s> However, it is usually made with meat, seafood or vegetables in a broth flavored with "gochujang", "doenjang", or "ganjang". <s> "Jjigae" can also be well seasoned with red chili pepper and served boiling hot. <s> A Korean meal almost always includes either a "jjigae" or a "guk" (국, soup). <s> In the Joseon Dynasty "jjigae" was called "jochi". <s> Different kinds of "jjigae" are often called according to their main ingredients such as "saengseon jjigae" (생선찌개).

title: Messeturm
complex: The Messeturm is located near the Frankfurt Trade Fair grounds. <s> Helmut Jahn designed the Messeturm in a postmodern architectural style. <s> It is regarded as one of the design classics among European skyscrapers. <s> Despite its name, the Messeturm is not used for trade fair exhibitions but as an office building. <s> It is one of the few buildings in Germany with their own postal code (60308), the others being Opernturm, another Frankfurt skyscraper, and the summit station on Zugspitze. <s> The Messeturm is similar in design to towers by other architects including the Bank of America Plaza in Atlanta, Georgia and Key Tower (1991) in Cleveland, Ohio. <s> Frankfurters often call it "Bleistift" ("pencil") due to its shape. <s> The construction of the building's foundation set a world record for the longest continuous concrete pour. <s> Ninety trucks poured concrete for 78 hours into the 6 m deep foundation. <s> Its ground floor area is just 1681 m2 , and features a 36.3 m pyramid at the top.
simple: MesseTurm is located in Frankfurt's district "Westend". <s> Because of this shape, people in Germany often call it "The Pencil." <s> The construction of the building's foundation set a world record. <s> The world record was for the longest continuous concrete pour. <s> Ninety trucks poured concrete for 78 hours. <s> They poured it into the 6 m deep foundation. <s> It is 36.3 m tall.

title: Touchstone Pictures
complex: Touchstone Pictures is a dormant label created and owned by The Walt Disney Company. <s> Feature films released under the Touchstone name were financed or produced by The Walt Disney Studios with more mature themes and/or targeted towards elder audiences, than those feature films released under the studio's flagship family entertainment Walt Disney Pictures banner. <s> As such, Touchstone was merely a pseudonym brand for the studio, and did not exist as a distinct business operation. <s> Due to increased public assumption that Disney films were aimed at children and families, films produced by the Walt Disney Productions began to falter at the box office as a result. <s> In late 1979, Disney Productions released "The Black Hole", a science-fiction movie that was the studio's first production to receive a PG rating (the company, however, had already distributed via Buena Vista Distribution its first PG-rated film, "Take Down" almost a year before the release of "The Black Hole"). <s> Over the next few years, Disney experimented with more PG-rated fare, such as the 1981 film "Condorman". <s> With Disney's 1982 slate of PG-rated films—including the horror-mystery "The Watcher in the Woods", the thriller drama "Night Crossing", and the science-fiction film "Tron"—the company lost over $27 million. <s> "Tron" was considered a potential "Star Wars"-level success film by the film division. <s> Touchstone Films was started by then-Disney CEO Ron W. Miller on February 15, 1984 as a label for their PG films with an expected three to four movies released under the label. <s> Touchstone's first film was "Splash", a huge hit for grossing $68 million at the domestic box office was released that year. <s> Incoming Disney CEO Michael Eisner and film chief Jeffrey Katzenberg considered renaming the label to Hollywood Pictures. <s> Disney's former non-Disney branded television division Touchstone Television Productions, LLC (formerly known as Touchstone Films Television Division, Touchstone Films Television, Touchstone Pictures Television and Touchstone Pictures and Television itself an alternate version of the Walt Disney Television names and later Touchstone Television) is known for being the production company of the series "The Golden Girls", "Blossom", "Home Improvement", "The Sinbad Show", "Boy Meets World" (all five began before Disney's ABC acquisition), "My Wife and Kids", "Desperate Housewives", "Lost", "Grey's Anatomy", "Scrubs", "Miracles," and "Monk".
simple: Touchstone Pictures (also known as Touchstone Films in its early years) is one of several alternate movie labels of The Walt Disney Company, established in 1984. <s> Its releases typically feature more mature themes than those that gets released under the Walt Disney Pictures banner. <s> Touchstone Pictures is merely a brand and does not exist as a separate company: the two de facto companies behind it are Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures Group and Walt Disney Pictures (formerly "Walt Disney Pictures and Television"). <s> Walt Disney Productions' "The Black Hole" (1979) was the first Disney movie to get a PG rating. <s> Over the next few years, Disney experimented with more PG-rated fare, such as the 1981 movie "Condorman", 1982's "Tron" and 1983's "Never Cry Wolf" and "Trenchcoat". <s> Started by then Disney CEO Ron W. Miller in 1984, Touchstone's first release was "Splash". <s> The studio's former television division, Touchstone Television Productions, LLC (formerly known as Touchstone Pictures and Television and later Touchstone Television), is known for producing the series "The Golden Girls", "Blossom", "Boy Meets World", "My Wife and Kids", "Desperate Housewives", "Lost", "Grey's Anatomy" , and "Scrubs".

title: Xavier Porras
complex: Xavi Porras (Olot, Girona, Spain, August 22, 1981) is a Spanish paralympic sprinter and jumper who belongs to F.C. Barcelona and competes in the T11 / B1 category for blind athletes or athletes with a very reduced vision. <s> He competed in the 2004 Summer Paralympics in Athens, Greece, the 2008 Summer Paralympics in Beijing, China where he was the third best athlete in the triple jump. <s> He competed at the 2012 Summer Paralympics, where he finished fifth in the triple jump.
simple: Javier Porras Santana (born on August 22, 1981 in Olot, Girona) is a athlete from Spain. <s> He has a disability: he cannot see and is a T11/B1 type athlete. <s> He competed in the 2004 Summer Paralympics in Athens, Greece. <s> He competed at the 2008 Summer Paralympics in Beijing, China and was the third best athlete in the triple jump. <s> He competed at the 2012 Summer Paralympics.

title: Thallium(I) bromide
complex: Thallium(I) bromide is a chemical compound of thallium and bromine with a chemical formula TlBr. <s> It is used in room-temperature detectors of X-rays, gamma-rays and blue light, as well as in near-infrared optics. <s> Thallium is extremely toxic and a cumulative poison which can be absorbed through the skin. <s> Acute and chronic effects of ingesting thallium compounds include fatigue, limb pain, peripheral neuritis, joint pain, loss of hair, diarrhea, vomiting and damage to central nervous system, liver and kidneys.
simple: Thallium(I) bromide, also known as thallous bromide, is a chemical compound. <s> Its chemical formula is TlBr. <s> It has thallium and bromide ions in it. <s> Thallium(I) bromide is a yellow-white solid. <s> Thallium(I) bromide is made by reacting thallium and bromine or by reacting sodium or potassium bromide with any thallium compound. <s> It is used in semiconductors and gamma ray and X-ray detectors. <s> It is very toxic, like all thallium compounds.

title: Moreno Torricelli
complex: Moreno Torricelli (] ; born 23 January 1970) is an Italian football manager and former defender, who usually played as a full-back on the right flank. <s> Torricelli played for several Italian clubs throughout his career, but achieved prominence during his successful stint with Juventus, with whom he won several titles; he also had a spell in Spain with Espanyol.

title: Gamma
complex: Gamma (uppercase Γ , lowercase γ ; "gámma") is the third letter of the Greek alphabet. <s> In the system of Greek numerals it has a value of 3. <s> In Ancient Greek, the letter gamma represented a voiced velar stop /ɡ/ . <s> In Modern Greek, this letter represents either a voiced velar fricative or a voiced palatal fricative. <s> Letters that arose from the Greek gamma include Etruscan (Old Italic) 𐌂, Roman C and G, Runic "kaunan" ᚲ , Gothic "geuua" 𐌲 , the Coptic Ⲅ, and the Cyrillic letters Г and Ґ.
simple: Gamma (uppercase/lowercase Γ γ), is the third letter of the Greek alphabet, used to represent the "g" sound in Ancient and Modern Greek. <s> In the system of Greek numerals, it has a value of 3. <s> Letters that came from it include the Roman C and Cyrillic Г.

title: Robert F. Marx
complex: Robert F. Marx (December 8, 1936 – July 4, 2019) was an American pioneer in scuba diving and was best known for his work with shipwrecks and sunken treasure. <s> Although he was considered controversial for his frequent and successful forays into treasure hunting, fellow treasure hunter E. Lee Spence described Marx as the "true father of underwater archaeology". <s> Marx became a diving specialist in the United States Marine Corps in 1953. <s> He went on to make over 5,000 dives and authored over 800 reports/articles and 59 books on history, archaeology, shipwrecks and exploration. <s> Marx and his wife, Jenifer, lived in Indialantic, Florida. <s> They were co-authors of several non-fiction books.
simple: Robert F. Marx (December 8, 1936 – July 4, 2019) was an American scuba diver. <s> He was best known for his work with shipwrecks and sunken treasure. <s> Marx died on July 4, 2019 in Indialantic at the age of 85. <s> Although he was criticized for his treasure hunting, he was known as the "true father of underwater archaeology". <s> Marx became a diving specialist in the United States Marine Corps in 1953. <s> He was born in Indialantic, Florida.

title: Valery Rozhdestvensky
complex: Valery Ilyich Rozhdestvensky (Russian: Валерий Ильич Рождественский, 13 February 1939 – 31 August 2011) was a Soviet cosmonaut. <s> Rozhdestvensky was born in Leningrad and graduated from the Higher Military Engineering School of Soviet Navy in Pushkin in engineering. <s> From 1961 to 1965 he was commander of a deepsea diving unit in the Baltic Sea War Fleet. <s> Rozhdestvensky was selected as a cosmonaut on 23 October 1965 and flew as Flight Engineer on Soyuz 23. <s> After his space flight he continued to work with the space program at the Yuri Gagarin Cosmonaut Training Center. <s> He retired on 24 June 1986 and worked with Metropolis Industries. <s> He was married with one child.
simple: Valery Ilyich Rozhdestvensky (February 13, 1939–August 31, 2011) was a USSR cosmonaut. <s> Rozhdestvensky was born in Leningrad and studied engineering at the Higher Military Engineering School of the Soviet Navy in Pushkin. <s> From 1961 to 1965 he was commander of a deep sea diving unit in the Baltic Sea War Fleet. <s> He was chosen to be a cosmonaut on October 23, 1965 and flew as Flight Engineer on Soyuz 23 in 1976. <s> After his space flight he continued to work with the space program at the Yuri Gagarin Cosmonaut Training Center. <s> He retired on June 24, 1986 and worked with Metropolis Industries.

title: Roman Polák
complex: Roman Polák (born 28 April 1986) is a professional ice hockey defenceman who currently plays with the Dallas Stars of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> Polák was drafted in the sixth round, 180th overall, just ahead of Adrain 69 at the 2004 NHL Entry Draft by the St. Louis Blues, the organization with which he spent his entire NHL career prior to joining the Toronto Maple Leafs in 2014. <s> He rejoined the Maple Leafs in 2016, after a brief stint with the San Jose Sharks. <s> In the 2018 offseason, Polák signed a one-year deal with the Dallas Stars. <s> Polák was drafted in the sixth round, 180th overall, in the 2004 NHL Entry Draft by the St. Louis Blues. <s> After playing in the Western Hockey League (WHL) in the 2004–05 season with the Kootenay Ice, he returned to his native Czech Republic to make his professional debut with HC Vítkovice of the Czech Extraliga. <s> In the 2006–07 season, Polák returned to North America and appeared in his first NHL game on 9 October 2006, against the Anaheim Ducks. <s> After two seasons between the Blues and their affiliate, the Peoria Rivermen, Polák made the starting roster for the Blues in the 2008–09 season. <s> Polák scored his first NHL goal in his 57th game on 20 December 2008, against the Minnesota Wild. <s> He finished the season with 15 points in 69 games and was re-signed by the Blues to a two-year contract on 24 July 2009. <s> Emerging as a mainstay in the Blues defense and establishing himself as one of the Blues' top defensive-defensemen over the next two seasons, Polák was re-signed by St. Louis to a five-year contract extension on 2 June 2011. <s> On 28 June 2014, Polák was traded to the Toronto Maple Leafs in exchange for defenseman Carl Gunnarsson and a 2014 fourth-round draft pick (Ville Husso). <s> During his first season in Toronto, Polák set a career-high in goals scored (5).
simple: Roman Polák (born April 28, 1986) is a Czech ice hockey defenceman. <s> He was drafted 180th overall by the St. Louis Blues in the 2004 NHL Entry Draft. <s> He has also played for the St. Louis Blues. <s> Before playing in the NHL, Polák played parts of 1 season with the Kootenay Ice of the Western Hockey League (WHL) and half of 1 season with HC Vítkovice Steel of the Czech Extraliga. <s> On October 9, 2006, Polák made his NHL debut in a 2-0 loss against the Anaheim Ducks. <s> On December 20, 2008, he scored his first NHL goal against Niklas Bäckström of the Minnesota Wild in a 4-2 win. <s> On June 2, 2011, the Blues resigned Polák to a five-year contract extension. <s> On June 28, 2014, the Blues traded Polák to the Toronto Maple Leafs in exchange for Carl Gunnarsson and a fourth-round pick in the 2014 NHL Entry Draft.

title: Tom Stoppard
complex: Sir Tom Stoppard (born Tomáš Straussler; 3 July 1937) is a Czech-born British playwright and screenwriter. <s> He has written prolifically for TV, radio, film and stage, finding prominence with plays such as "Arcadia", "The Coast of Utopia", "Every Good Boy Deserves Favour", "Professional Foul", "The Real Thing", "The Invention of Love", and "Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead". <s> He co-wrote the screenplays for "Brazil", "The Russia House", and "Shakespeare in Love", and has received an Academy Award and four Tony Awards. <s> His work covers the themes of human rights, censorship and political freedom, often delving into the deeper philosophical thematics of society.

title: Lacrimal bone
complex: The lacrimal bone is a small and fragile bone of the facial skeleton; it is roughly the size of the little fingernail. <s> It is situated at the front part of the medial wall of the orbit. <s> It has two surfaces and four borders. <s> Several bony landmarks of the lacrimal bone function in the process of lacrimation or crying. <s> Specifically, the lacrimal bone helps form the nasolacrimal canal necessary for tear translocation. <s> A depression on the anterior inferior portion of the bone, the lacrimal fossa, houses the membranous lacrimal sac. <s> Tears or lacrimal fluid, from the lacrimal glands, collect in this sac during excessive lacrimation. <s> The fluid then flows through the nasolacrimal duct and into the nasopharynx.
simple: The lacrimal bone is the smallest bone in the face; about the size of the little fingernail. <s> It is at the front of the inside wall of the eye socket. <s> The lacrimal bone is involved in crying. <s> The lacrimal sac is where tears flow when you cry.

title: Tsukushi Province
complex: Tsukushi Province (筑紫国 , Tsukushi-no kuni ) was an ancient province of Japan, in the area of Chikuzen and Chikugo provinces. <s> This province was located within Fukuoka Prefecture. <s> It was sometimes called Chikushū (筑州 ) .
simple: Tsukushi Province (筑紫国, Tsukushi-no kuni), also known as Chikushū (筑州), was a very old province of Japan, in the area of Chikuzen and Chikugo provinces. <s> This province was located within Fukuoka Prefecture.

title: Shōjo
complex: Shōjo, shojo or shoujo (少女 , shōjo ) is a Japanese word for "girl". <s> The word is derived from a Chinese expression written with the same characters. <s> The Chinese characters (少 and 女) literally mean "little" and "woman" respectively. <s> In Japanese, these kanji refer specifically to a young woman approximately 7–18 years old. <s> Like most kanji compounds, the term shōjo is borrowed from Classical Chinese characters. <s> The original term is written as "少女", which could be pronounced as "shào nǚ" in Mandarin (pinyin romanization), "so nyŏ" in Korean (McCune-Reischauer romanization), "thiếu nữ" in Vietnamese, and "shōjo" in Japanese (Hepburn romanization). <s> In the 7th century, the word was introduced into the Japanese language through the adoption of the Chinese-style Ritsuryō legal system, where it referred to females between the ages of 17 and 20. <s> In legal settings, "shōjo" is a subset of shōnen (meaning "minor") and refers to any female juvenile who has not reached the age of 20.
simple: Shōjo (少女) is a Japanese word meaning "girl". <s> The characters, or kanji, mean "little" and "woman". <s> Like many Japanese words, the characters of the word shōjo come from Chinese. <s> The word was brought to Japan in the 7th century, when they began using a Chinese-style legal system. <s> Nowadays, the word shōjo is legally used to mean any woman or girl under 20.

title: Professor
complex: Professor (commonly abbreviated as Prof.) is an academic rank at universities and other post-secondary education and research institutions in most countries. <s> Literally, "professor" derives from Latin as a "person who professes" being usually an expert in arts or sciences, a teacher of the highest rank. <s> In most systems of academic ranks the word "professor" only refers to the most senior academic position, sometimes informally known as "full professor". <s> In some countries or institutions, the word "professor" is also used in titles of lower ranks such as associate professor and assistant professor; this is particularly the case in the United States, where the word professor is sometimes used colloquially to refer to anyone in an academic post. <s> This colloquial usage would be considered incorrect among most other academic communities. <s> However, the unqualified title Professor designated with a capital letter usually refers to a full professor also in English language usage. <s> Professors often conduct original research and commonly teach undergraduate, professional and postgraduate courses in their fields of expertise. <s> In universities with graduate schools, professors may mentor and supervise graduate students conducting research for a thesis or dissertation. <s> In many universities, 'full professors' take on senior managerial roles, leading departments, research teams and institutes, and filling roles such as president, principal or vice-chancellor. <s> The role of professor may be more public facing than that of more junior staff, and professors are expected to be national or international leaders in their field of expertise. <s> A professor is an accomplished and recognized academic. <s> In most Commonwealth nations, as well as northern Europe, the title "professor" is the highest academic rank at a university. <s> In the United States and Canada, the title of "professor" applies to most post-doctoral academics, so a larger percentage are thus designated. <s> In these areas, professors are scholars with doctorate degrees (typically Ph.D. degrees) or equivalent qualifications who teach in four-year colleges and universities. <s> An emeritus professor is a title given to selected retired professors with whom the university wishes to continue to be associated due to their stature and ongoing research. <s> Emeritus professors do not receive a salary, but they are often given office or lab space, and use of libraries, labs, and so on. <s> The term professor is also used in the titles "assistant professor" and "associate professor", which are not considered professor-level positions in all European countries. <s> In Australia, the title "associate professor" is used in place of the term "reader" as used in the United Kingdom and other Commonwealth countries; ranking above senior lecturer and below full professor. <s> Beyond holding the proper academic title, universities in many countries also give notable artists, athletes and foreign dignitaries the title "honorary professor", even if these persons do not have the academic qualifications typically necessary for professorship and they do not take up professorial duties. <s> However, such "professors" usually do not undertake academic work for the granting institution. <s> In general, the title of professor is strictly used for academic positions rather than for those holding it on honorary basis. <s> A professor typically earns a base salary and a range of benefits. <s> In addition, a professor who undertakes additional roles in their institution (e.g., department chair, dean, head of graduate studies, etc.) earns additional income. <s> Some professors also earn additional income by moonlighting in other jobs, such as consulting, publishing academic or popular press books, giving speeches, or coaching executives. <s> Some fields (e.g., business and computer science) give professors more opportunities for outside work. <s> The table below shows the final reference wages (per month or year?) <s> expressed in net amounts of Dutch Euros in 2014. <s> (i.e., converted into Dutch purchasing power). <s> In a number of countries, the title "research professor" refers to a professor who is exclusively or mainly engaged in research, and who has few or no teaching obligations. <s> For example, the title is used in this sense in the United Kingdom (where it is known as research professor at some universities and professorial research fellow at some other institutions) and in northern Europe. <s> Research professor is usually the most senior rank of a research-focused career pathway in those countries, and regarded as equal to the ordinary full professor rank. <s> Most often they are permanent employees, and the position is often held by particularly distinguished scholars; thus the position is often seen as more prestigious than an ordinary full professorship.
simple: Professor (commonly abbreviated as "prof.") is an academic rank at most universities and colleges. <s> The word "professor" comes from Latin. <s> It means a "person who professes", being usually an expert in arts or sciences. <s> A professor is a teacher of the highest rank. <s> Professors are often active in research. <s> In many institutions, the job title 'professor' is synonymous with that of an instructor. <s> A professor is an accomplished and recognized academic. <s> In most Commonwealth nations, as well as northern Europe, the title "professor" is the highest academic rank at a university. <s> In the United States and Canada, the title of "professor" is also the highest rank, but a higher percentage achieve it. <s> In these areas, professors are scholars with doctorate degrees (typically Ph.D. degrees) or equivalent qualifications. <s> Most professors teach in four-year colleges and universities. <s> An emeritus professor is a title given to selected retired professors with whom the university wishes to continue to be associated due to their stature and ongoing research. <s> Emeritus professors do not receive a salary. <s> However, they are often given office or lab space, and use of libraries, labs, and so on. <s> The term professor is also used in the titles assistant professor and associate professor, which are not considered professor-level positions in some European countries. <s> In Australia, the title "associate professor" is used in place of "reader", ranking above senior lecturer and below full professor. <s> Beyond holding the proper academic title, universities in many countries also give notable artists, athletes and foreign dignitaries the title "honorary professor", even if these persons do not have the academic qualifications typically necessary for professorship and they do not take up professorial duties. <s> However, such "professors" usually do not undertake academic work for the granting institution. <s> In general, the title of professor is strictly used for academic positions rather than for those holding it on honorary basis. <s> A professor's salary can vary by education, school, subject taught and country. <s> A professor typically earns a base salary and a range of benefits. <s> In addition, a professor who undertakes additional roles in her institution (e.g., department chair, dean, head of graduate studies, etc.) earns additional income. <s> They usually rank below a full professor.

title: Ridgewood, New Jersey

title: Philip Glass
complex: Philip Glass (born January 31, 1937) is an American composer. <s> He is widely regarded as one of the most influential musicians of the late 20th century. <s> Glass's work has been described as "minimal music", having similar qualities to other "minimalist" composers such as La Monte Young, Steve Reich, and Terry Riley. <s> Glass describes himself as a composer of "music with repetitive structures", which he has helped evolve stylistically. <s> Glass founded the Philip Glass Ensemble, with which he still performs on keyboards. <s> He has written numerous operas and musical theatre works, twelve symphonies, eleven concertos, eight string quartets and various other chamber music, and film scores. <s> Three of his film scores have been nominated for Academy Awards.

title: Grade retention

title: Waltz (music)
complex: A waltz (German: "Walzer"; French: "Valse", Italian: "Valzer", Spanish: "Vals", Polish: "Walc"), probably deriving from German "Ländler", is dance music in triple meter, often written in time. <s> A waltz typically sounds one chord per measure, and the accompaniment style particularly associated with the waltz is (as seen in the example to the right) to play the root of the chord on the first beat, the upper notes on the second and third beats. <s> In a jazz context, "waltz" signifies any piece of music in 3/4 time, whether intended for dancing or not . <s> Although there are early examples such as the "Missouri Waltz" by Dan and Harvey’s Jazz Band (1918) and the "Jug Band Waltz" or the "Mississippi Waltz" by the Memphis Jug Band (1928), they are exceptional, as almost all jazz before 1955 was in duple meter.
simple: Waltzes typically have one chord per measure, and the accompaniment style particularly associated with the waltz is (as seen in the example to the right) to play the root of the chord on the first beat, the upper notes on the second and third beats. <s> Waltz music is written in 3/4 time (three beats per bar).
