title: John Gould Veitch
complex: John Gould Veitch (April 1839 – 13 August 1870) was a horticulturist and traveller, one of the first Victorian plant hunters to visit Japan. <s> A great-grandson of John Veitch, the founder of the Veitch horticulture dynasty, he also visited the Philippines, Australia, Fiji, and other Polynesian islands. <s> He brought back a number of the glasshouse plants in vogue at the time, such as "Acalyphas", "Cordylines", "Codiaeums" (Crotons) and "Dracaenas", and, from Fiji, a palm of a new genus later named after him, "Veitchia joannis". <s> The Veitch family name is honoured by hundreds of plant names, including the genus "Veitchia". <s> The Veitch nursery introduced 232 orchids, some 500 greenhouse plants, 118 exotic ferns, about 50 conifers, 153 deciduous trees, 72 evergreen and climbing shrubs, 122 herbaceous and 37 bulbous plants from various corners of the globe. <s> In Japan, he came across the eminent plant collector Robert Fortune, and their competing collections returned to England on the same ship. <s> For example, both men claimed discovery of a species of "Chamaecyparis pisifera". <s> He was married to Jane Hodge soon after his return to England in 1866 and fathered two sons, James Herbert Veitch (1868 – 1907) and John Gould Veitch, Jr. (1869 – 1914) before dying of tuberculosis at the age of 31.
simple: John Gould Veitch (April 1839 – 13 August 1870) was an expert on plants and growing plants, he was also a traveller and one of the first Victorian British plant experts to visit Japan to look for and collect new plants. <s> He was a great-grandson of John Veitch, the founder of the Veitch family plant growing business. <s> He also visited the Philippines, Australia, Fiji, and other Polynesian islands looking for new plants to bring back to Great Britain. <s> He brought back a number of the glasshouse plants that were in fashion at the time, such as "Acalyphas", "Cordylines", "Codiaeums" (Crotons) and "Dracaenas", and from Fiji, a palm of a new genus later named after him, "Veitchia joannis", in addition to this genus the Veitch family name is honoured by hundreds of other plant names. <s> In Japan, he met another famous plant collector called Robert Fortune, and their competing collections returned to England on the same ship. <s> For example, each man claimed that they had discovered a species of "Chamaecyparis pisifera" (a kind of cypress). <s> He married Jane Hodge soon after his return to England in 1866 and they had two sons, James Herbert Veitch, (1868 – 1907) and John Gould Veitch, Jr. (1869 – 1914) <s> John Gould Veitch died of tuberculosis at the age of 31.

title: Carbon diet
complex: A carbon diet refers to reducing the impact on climate change by reducing greenhouse gas production specifically, CO2 production. <s> In today’s society, humans produce CO2 in every day activities such as driving, heating, deforestation and the burning of fossil fuels such as coal, oil and gas. <s> It has been found that carbon dioxide from the burning of coal, natural gas, and oil for electricity and heat is the largest single source of global greenhouse gas emissions. <s> For years, governments and corporations have been attempting to balance out their emissions by participating in carbon-offsetting — the practice in which they invest in renewable energy to compensate for the global warming pollution that they produce.
simple: Carbon diet is the process of reducing the production of greenhouse gas, primarily carbon dioxide, to reduce effects on climate change and global warming. <s> It is different from a low carbon diet which is done by choosing what to eat to reduce greenhouse gas discharge. <s> Carbon dioxide is produced from heating, driving and consuming products.

title: Antony, Hauts-de-Seine
complex: Antony (] ) is a French commune in the southern suburbs of Paris, France. <s> It is located 11.3 km from the centre of Paris. <s> Antony is a subprefecture of the Hauts-de-Seine department and the seat of the arrondissement of Antony. <s> Watered by the Bièvre, a tributary of the Seine, Antony is located at the crossroads of very important transport routes, especially the main north-south axis which has existed for 2,000 years. <s> Little urbanized until the early 20th century, the city grew considerably between the two wars, under Senator-Mayor Auguste Mounié, from 4,000 to 20,000 inhabitants. <s> In the early 1960s the population quickly increased from 25,000 to 50,000 to accommodate the repatriated people from Algeria. <s> Now incorporated in the Paris Metropolitan Area, it is particularly strong in education with one of the largest private institutions in France and in the health field with the largest private establishment in Île-de-France.

title: Pamela Rai
complex: Pamela Leila Rai (born March 29, 1966, in New Westminster, BC, Canada) is a former freestyle and butterfly swimmer who represented Canada from 1980 to 1987. <s> Rai competed at the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles, California where she won an Olympic bronze medal in the 4 × 100-metre medley relay, with teammates Anne Ottenbrite, Reema Abdo and Michelle MacPherson. <s> Rai successfully represented Canada at many international meets throughout her career. <s> Other notable accomplishments include University of Victoria Athlete of the Year 1986, City of Victoria Athlete of the Year 1985, 1983 Hapoel Games silver, 1983 Pan American Games silver, and 1986 Commonwealth Games gold medals. <s> From 1984 to 1987 Rai swam for the University of Victoria, where she dominated Canadian university women's swimming. <s> Rai is currently a high school math and social justice teacher and a certified yoga instructor trained in India of the Sivananda lineage.

title: Eudora, Kansas
complex: Eudora is a city in Douglas County, Kansas, United States. <s> The city is located along the Kansas and Wakarusa Rivers. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city population was 6,136. <s> Eudora is located at (38.938213, −95.097417). <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 2.94 sqmi , of which, 2.89 sqmi is land and 0.05 sqmi is water. <s> Eudora is part of the Lawrence, Kansas Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 6,136 people, 2,210 households, and 1,600 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 2123.2 PD/sqmi . <s> There were 2,306 housing units at an average density of 797.9 /sqmi . <s> The racial makeup of the city was 93.3% White, 0.8% African American, 1.6% Native American, 0.7% Asian, 0.8% from other races, and 2.8% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino of any race were 4.5% of the population. <s> The Eudora government consists of five City Commissioners, which elects the Mayor. <s> The City Commission meets the second and fourth Monday of each month at 7PM.

title: Ivan Stoyanov (footballer, born 1949)
complex: Ivan Stoyanov ( ; 20 January 1949 – 10 December 2017) was a Bulgarian footballer who played as a midfielder for Bulgaria in the 1974 FIFA World Cup. <s> He also played for Spartak Sofia and Levski Sofia. <s> His death was announced on December 10, 2017, aged 68.
simple: Ivan Stoyanov (; 20 January 1949 – 10 December 2017) was a Bulgarian footballer. <s> He also played for the Bulgaria national team in the 1974 FIFA World Cup. <s> At club level, he played for Spartak Sofia and Levski Sofia. <s> Stoyanov died on 10 December 2017, at the age of 68.

title: Pressurized heavy-water reactor
complex: A pressurized heavy-water reactor (PHWR) is a nuclear reactor, commonly using natural uranium as its fuel, that uses heavy water (deuterium oxide DO) as its coolant and neutron moderator. <s> The heavy water coolant is kept under pressure, allowing it to be heated to higher temperatures without boiling, much as in a pressurized water reactor. <s> While heavy water is significantly more expensive than ordinary light water, it creates greatly enhanced neutron economy, allowing the reactor to operate without fuel-enrichment facilities (offsetting the additional expense of the heavy water) and enhancing the ability of the reactor to make use of alternate fuel cycles. <s> At the beginning of 2001, 31 heavy water cooled and moderated nuclear power plants were in operation, having a total capacity of 16.5 GW(e), representing roughly 7.76% by number and 4.7% by generating capacity of all current operating reactors.
simple: A pressurized heavy-water reactor (PHWR) is a nuclear reactor developed by Canada. <s> It commonly uses uranium as its fuel. <s> It uses heavy water (deuterium oxide DO) as its coolant and neutron moderator. <s> The heavy water coolant is kept under pressure. <s> This allows it to be heated to higher temperatures without boiling. <s> While heavy water is a lot more expensive than ordinary water, it creates greatly enhanced neutron economy. <s> This allows the reactor to operate without fuel-enrichment facilities (offsetting the additional expense of the heavy water).

title: Viber
complex: Viber is a cross-platform voice over IP (VoIP) and instant messaging (IM) software application operated by Japanese multinational company Rakuten, provided as a freeware for the Android, iOS, Microsoft Windows, macOS and Linux platforms. <s> Users are registered and identified through a cellular telephone number, although the service is accessible on desktop platforms without needing mobile connectivity.
simple: Viber is an application for iOS, Windows Phone and Android OS.

title: Liberec
complex: Liberec (] ; ] ) is a city in the Czech Republic. <s> It is on the Lusatian Neisse and surrounded by the Jizera Mountains and Ještěd-Kozákov Ridge. <s> It is the fifth-largest city in the Czech Republic.

title: Molar heat capacity
complex: The molar heat capacity of a chemical substance is the amount of energy that must be added, in the form of heat, to one mole of the substance in order to cause an increase of one unit in its temperature. <s> Alternatively, it is the heat capacity of a sample of the substance divided by the number of moles of the sample; or also the specific heat capacity of the substance times its molar mass.
simple: The molar heat capacity of a substance is the energy needed to raise the temperature of one mole of it by one degree Celsius. <s> The molar heat capacity of a given substance can be found by heating the substance by releasing a known amount of energy into the substance and measuring the temperature change.

title: Diwan (poetry)
complex: In Islamic cultures of the Middle East, North Africa, Sicily and South Asia, a Diwan ( , "divân", , "dīwān") is a collection of poems by one author, usually excluding his or her long poems (mathnawī). <s> These poems, frequently sung or set to music, were often composed and collected in the imperial courts of various sultanates and were very well known for their ability to inspire. <s> In Urdu poetry diwan are also a collection of poems, but here they are mainly ghazals.
simple: These poems were often written and collected in the royal courts of various sultanates. <s> They were very well known for their ability to inspire. <s> Diwan is a collection of poems.

title: Craig Gruber
complex: Craig M. Gruber (June 15, 1951 – May 5, 2015) was an American rock bassist, best known as the original bassist in Rainbow and most recently was a member for the band Zvekan. <s> He also played in Elf, consisting of vocalist Ronnie James Dio, keyboardist Mickey Lee Soule, drummer Gary Driscoll and guitarist David Feinstein. <s> Craig Gruber died of prostate cancer in Florida on May 5, 2015, aged 63.

title: Matt Vogel (puppeteer)
complex: Matt Vogel (born October 6, 1970) is an American puppeteer, director and singer who has worked for the Jim Henson Company and Sesame Workshop. <s> He has performed with the Muppets, "Sesame Street", and "Oobi". <s> Vogel first auditioned for the Jim Henson Company in 1993 and joined the crew of "Sesame Street" in 1996 as an ensemble puppeteer. <s> He has served as a director and puppet captain on "Sesame Street" since 2008. <s> He inherited many of Jerry Nelson's Muppet character roles in 2008, when he began performing with The Muppets Studio. <s> Since 2017, he has been the performer of Kermit the Frog.
simple: Matthew J. "Matt" Vogel II is an American puppeteer. <s> He has worked with the Muppets, "Sesame Street", and "Oobi". <s> In 2017, he started playing Kermit the Frog.

title: Kyōko Kagawa
complex: Kyōko Kagawa (香川 京子 , Kagawa Kyōko , born 5 December 1931) is a Japanese actress known for her roles in films like "Tokyo Story", "Sansho the Bailiff", "Mothra", and "High and Low". <s> She has appeared in 118 films. <s> Her most recent film was "Ballad" in 2009. <s> In late 2011, the National Museum of Modern Art, Tokyo, honored her long career and her contribution to Japanese cinema with an exhibition titled 'Kyoko Kagawa, Film Actress.'
simple: Kyōko Kagawa (香川 京子, Kagawa Kyōko, born 5 December 1931) is a Japanese actress. <s> She is known for her roles in movies like "Tokyo Story", "Sansho the Bailiff" and "High and Low". <s> She has appeared in 118 movies. <s> Her most recent movie was "Ballad" in 2009. <s> In late 2011, the National Museum of Modern Art, Tokyo, honored her long career and her contribution to Japanese cinema with an exhibition titled 'Kyoko Kagawa, Film Actress'.

title: Alexandre do Nascimento
complex: Alexandre do Nascimento (born 1 March 1925) is an Angolan Cardinal of the Catholic Church. <s> He served as Archbishop of Luanda from 1986 to 2001, and was elevated to the cardinalate in 1983. <s> On 10 August 1975, Nascimento was appointed the fourth bishop of Malanje by Pope Paul VI. <s> He received his episcopal consecration on the following 31 August from Archbishop Giovanni De Andrea, with Archbishops Manuel Nunes Gabriel and Eduardo Muaca serving as co-consecrators. <s> Nascimento was Vice-President of the Angolan Episcopal Conference from 1975 to 1981, and was named the third Archbishop of Lubango on 3 February 1977. <s> Archbishop do Nascimento was kidnapped by guerrillas during a pastoral visit on 15 October 1982; he was later freed on 16 November of that same year after Pope John Paul II made an appeal for his release.
simple: Alexandre do Nascimento (born 1 March 1925) is an Angolan Cardinal of the Catholic Church. <s> He was the Archbishop of Luanda from 1986 to 2001, and was elevated to the cardinalate in 1983 by Pope John Paul II. <s> On 10 August 1975, Nascimento was appointed the fourth bishop of Malanje by Pope Paul VI. <s> Nascimento was kidnapped by guerrillas during a pastoral visit on 15 October 1982; he was later freed on 16 November of that same year after Pope John Paul II made an appeal for his release.

title: Edward D. DiPrete
complex: Edward Daniel DiPrete (born July 8, 1934) is an American Republican Party politician and convicted felon from Rhode Island. <s> He served as the 70th Governor of Rhode Island for three two-year terms, serving from 1985 to 1991. <s> Convicted of numerous corruption charges, he is the only Rhode Island governor to have gone to prison.
simple: Edward Daniel DiPrete (born July 8, 1934) is an American Republican Party politician from Rhode Island. <s> He served as the 70th Governor of Rhode Island for three two-year terms, serving from 1985 to 1991.

title: Bone Wars
complex: The Bone Wars, also known as the Great Dinosaur Rush, was a period of intense and ruthlessly competitive fossil hunting and discovery during the Gilded Age of American history, marked by a heated rivalry between Edward Drinker Cope (of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia) and Othniel Charles Marsh (of the Peabody Museum of Natural History at Yale). <s> Each of the two paleontologists used underhanded methods to try to outdo the other in the field, resorting to bribery, theft, and the destruction of bones. <s> Each scientist also sought to ruin his rival's reputation and cut off his funding, using attacks in scientific publications. <s> Their search for fossils led them west to rich bone beds in Colorado, Nebraska, and Wyoming. <s> From 1877 to 1892, both paleontologists used their wealth and influence to finance their own expeditions and to procure services and dinosaur bones from fossil hunters. <s> By the end of the Bone Wars, both men had exhausted their funds in the pursuit of paleontological supremacy. <s> Cope and Marsh were financially and socially ruined by their attempts to outcompete and disgrace each other, but they made important contributions to science and the field of paleontology and provided substantial material for further work—both scientists left behind many unopened boxes of fossils after their deaths. <s> The efforts of the two men led to more than 136 new species of dinosaurs being discovered and described. <s> The products of the Bone Wars resulted in an increase in knowledge of prehistoric life, and sparked the public's interest in dinosaurs, leading to continued fossil excavation in North America in the decades to follow. <s> Many historical books and fictional adaptations have been published about this period of intense fossil-hunting activity. <s> While Cope and Marsh dueled for fossils in the American West, they also tried their best to ruin each other's professional credibility.
simple: The Bone Wars was a period of fossil finding and discovery in the U.S.A during the late 19th century. <s> There was a heated rivalry between Edward Drinker Cope (of the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia) and Othniel Charles Marsh (of the Peabody Museum of Natural History at Yale). <s> They used bribery, theft, and destruction of bones. <s> Each scientist attacked the other in scientific publications, seeking to ruin his credibility and have his funding cut off. <s> Their search for fossils led them west to rich "bone beds" in the western United States. <s> From 1877 to 1892, both paleontologists used their wealth and influence. <s> They paid for their own expeditions, and the services and dinosaur bones from fossil hunters. <s> By the end of the Bone Wars, both men had exhausted their funds in this way. <s> Cope and Marsh were financially and socially ruined by their attempts to disgrace each other. <s> Their contributions to paleontology were massive and provided plenty of material for later work: both scientists left behind many unopened boxes of fossils after their deaths. <s> 142 new species of dinosaurs were discovered and described by them, though today only 32 of their names are valid. <s> The products of the Bone Wars increased our knowledge of prehistoric life, and sparked the public's interest in dinosaurs. <s> This led to more fossil excavation in North America in the decades that followed. <s> Several historical books and fictional adaptations have been published about this period of intense fossil-hunting activity.

title: Brian Eno
complex: Brian Peter George St John le Baptiste de la Salle Eno, RDI ( ; born Brian Peter George Eno, 15 May 1948) is an English musician, record producer, visual artist, and theorist best known for his pioneering work in ambient music and contributions to rock, pop, and electronica. <s> A self-described "non-musician", Eno has helped introduce unique conceptual approaches and recording techniques to contemporary music.
simple: Brian Eno (born 15 May 1948) is an English musician.

title: Never Gonna Leave This Bed
complex: "Never Gonna Leave This Bed" is a song performed by American pop rock band Maroon 5, taken from their third studio album, "Hands All Over" (2010). <s> The song is a ballad and was written by frontman Adam Levine and produced by Robert John "Mutt" Lange. <s> It was released as the third single by A&M Octone Records. <s> It was released in Australia in January 2011. <s> The song was listed under Cool New Music on All Access in the Hot Adult Contemporary section and in early February 2011, it started gaining airplay there, even though an official Hot AC radio adds date never came to fruition. <s> It had an official radio adds date to Mainstream Radio on May 17, 2011. <s> The music video for the song was shot at several different places including Santa Monica and downtown Los Angeles, California. <s> The video shows scenes of Levine and Vyalitsyna in three different bed settings, including one at a pier on the beach of Santa Monica, another on Broadway in Los Angeles, and a third setting in an upper floor of the Hilton Hotel. <s> The video also features the band performing in a glass truck from Aardvark Event Logistics, alternatively while driving down a highway during the day, and on a busy street in downtown Los Angeles at night, while onlookers take photos. <s> The music video for the song was released on February 4, 2011 and premiered the day after on VH1. <s> The video hit number seven on the Yahoo! Video chart published by "Billboard".
simple: Never Gonna Leave This Bed is the 4th single released by pop/rock band "Maroon 5" under A&M/Octone Records off the album "Hands All Over". <s> The song was written by frontman Adam Levine and produced by producer Robert "Mutt" Lange. <s> The music video for the song was shot at several different places including Santa Monica and downtown Los Angeles, California. <s> The video shows scenes of Levine and his girlfriend in 3 different bed settings including a bed setting on the beach of Santa Monica, a bed setting on Broadway in Los Angeles, CA, and a bed setting in the upper floor of the Hilton Hotel. <s> The video also features the band performing in a small room, or box, more likely to be explained, on a busy street in downtown Los Angeles singing the song. <s> The music video was released on iTunes on 8 February 2011. <s> The music video for the single premiered on February 5th, 2011 on VH1's Top 20 Video Countdown.

title: Coal ball
complex: In 1855, two English scientists, Joseph Dalton Hooker and Edward William Binney, made the first scientific description of coal balls in England, and the initial research on coal balls was carried out in Europe. <s> North American coal balls were discovered and identified in 1922. <s> Coal balls have since been found in other countries, leading to the discovery of hundreds of species and genera. <s> Coal balls may be found in coal seams across North America and Eurasia. <s> North American coal balls are more widespread, both stratigraphically and geologically, than those in Europe. <s> The oldest known coal balls date from the Namurian stage of the Carboniferous; they were found in Germany and on the territory of former Czechoslovakia. <s> Marie Stopes and David Watson analysed coal ball samples and decided that coal balls formed "in situ". <s> They stressed the importance of interaction with seawater, believing that it was necessary for the formation of coal balls. <s> Some supporters of the "in situ" theory believe that Stopes' and Watson's discovery of a plant stem extending through multiple coal balls shows that coal balls formed "in situ", stating that the drift theory fails to explain Stopes' and Watson's observation. <s> They also cite fragile pieces of organic material projecting outside some coal balls, contending that if the drift theory was correct, the projections would have been destroyed, and some large coal balls are large enough that they could never have been able to be transported in the first place. <s> Coal balls are not made of coal; they are non-flammable and useless for fuel. <s> Coal balls are calcium-rich permineralised life forms, mostly containing calcium and magnesium carbonates, pyrite, and quartz. <s> Other minerals, including gypsum, illite, kaolinite, and lepidocrocite also appear in coal balls, albeit in lesser quantities. <s> Although coal balls are usually about the size of a man's fist, their sizes vary greatly, ranging from that of a walnut up to 3 ft in diameter. <s> Coal balls have been found that were smaller than a thimble. <s> In 1962, Sergius Mamay and Ellis Yochelson analysed North American coal balls. <s> Their discovery of marine organisms led to classification of coal balls were sorted into three types: normal (sometimes known as floral), containing only plant matter; faunal, containing animal fossils only; and mixed, containing both plant and animal material. <s> Mixed coal balls are further divided into heterogeneous, where the plant and animal material was distinctly separated; and homogeneous, lacking that separation. <s> Three main factors determine the quality of preserved material in a coal ball: the mineral constituents, the speed of the burial process, and the degree of compression before undergoing permineralisation. <s> Generally, coal balls resulting from remains that have a quick burial with little decay and pressure are better preserved, although plant remains in most coal balls almost always show differing signs of decay and collapse. <s> Coal balls containing quantities of iron sulfide have far lower preservation than coal balls permineralised by magnesium or calcium carbonate, which has earned iron sulfide the title "chief curse of the coal ball hunter". <s> Thin sectioning was an early procedure used to analyse fossilised material contained in coal balls. <s> The process required cutting a coal ball with a diamond saw, then flattening and polishing the thin section with an abrasive. <s> It would be glued to a slide and placed under a petrographic microscope for examination. <s> Although the process could be done with a machine, the large amount of time needed and the poor quality of samples produced by thin sectioning gave way to a more convenient method. <s> The thin section technique was superseded by the now-common liquid-peel technique in 1928. <s> In this technique, peels are obtained by cutting the surface of a coal ball with a diamond saw, grinding the cut surface on a glass plate with silicon carbide to a smooth finish, and etching the cut and the surface with hydrochloric acid.
simple: In 1855, two English scientists, Joseph Dalton Hooker and Edward William Binney, found coal balls in England. <s> Because of that, the initial research on coal balls was done in Europe. <s> Coal balls were found and identified in North America in 1922. <s> Since then, coal balls have been found in other countries and several theories on their formation have been proposed. <s> Coal balls are in coal seams across North America and Eurasia. <s> North American coal balls are in more places than in Europe. <s> The oldest coal balls were found in Germany and former Czechoslovakia. <s> Marie Stopes and D.M.S. Watson also examined coal ball samples. <s> They agreed that coal balls formed "in situ". <s> They also added that interaction with a marine environment was necessary for a coal ball to form. <s> Coal balls are not made of coal, even though they have the name "coal ball". <s> Coal balls are permineralised life forms that are full of calcium, magnesium and occasionally iron sulfide. <s> In 1962, Sergius Mamay and Ellis Yochelson found signs of marine animal remains in North American coal balls. <s> The quality of the preservation of organic material depends on the speed of the burial process and the degree of compression before undergoing permineralisation. <s> Generally, coal balls resulting from remains that have a quick burial with little decay and pressure have a higher preservation degree. <s> However, plant remains in most coal balls show various signs of decay and collapse. <s> Thin sectioning was an early procedure used to analyse fossilised material contained in coal balls. <s> The ball was cut into thin sections with a diamond saw. <s> Then it was flattened and polished with an abrasive. <s> Then it was examined under a microscope. <s> The time needed, and the poor quality of samples produced, led to a more convenient method. <s> The new method, first used in 1928, is called the "liquid peel technique".

title: Bonner Springs, Kansas
complex: Bonner Springs is a city in Wyandotte, Leavenworth, and Johnson counties, Kansas, United States. <s> It is part of the Kansas City Metropolitan Area. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city population was 7,314, and in 2016 the estimated population was 7,665. <s> Bonner Springs was incorporated as a city on November 10, 1898. <s> Bonner Springs is home to the Providence Medical Center Amphitheater, the National Agricultural Center and Hall of Fame, and the annual Kansas City Renaissance Festival. <s> Bonner Springs is located at (39.0597260, −94.8835754), primarily on the north side of the Kansas River. <s> It is mainly in southwestern Wyandotte County, with small portions extending west into Leavenworth County and south across the Kansas River into Johnson County. <s> It is bordered to the north by Kansas City, Kansas, to the east by Edwardsville, and to the south across the Kansas River by Shawnee. <s> Interstate 70, the Kansas Turnpike, passes through the northern part of the city, with access from Exits 224 and 224A (U.S. Route 73 and Kansas Highway 7). <s> I-70 leads east 17 mi to Kansas City, Missouri, and west 21 mi to Lawrence, while US-73 leads north 16 mi to Leavenworth, and K-7 leads south the same distance to Olathe. <s> K-32 runs through the center of Bonner Springs close to the Kansas River, leading east 4 mi into Edwardsville and west 10 mi to Linwood. <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 41.42 sqkm , of which 41.40 sqkm are land and 0.93 sqkm , or 2.26%, are water. <s> Bonner Springs has a humid continental climate, typically experiencing hot, humid summers and cold, dry winters. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 7,314 people, 2,810 households, and 1,917 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 465.0 PD/sqmi .

title: Singapore General Hospital
complex: The Singapore General Hospital (SGH; ) is the largest and oldest hospital in Singapore, of which the foundation of its first building was laid in 1821. <s> SGH was ranked as the third best hospital in the world by Newsweek in 2019. <s> The hospital, which is operated by SingHealth, occupies sprawling grounds in the eastern part of Bukit Merah, sharing space with four national specialty centres, namely the Singapore National Eye Centre (SNEC), the National Heart Centre Singapore (NHCS), the National Cancer Centre Singapore (NCCS) and the National Dental Centre Singapore (NDCS). <s> The Singapore General Hospital was established in 1821, when the first General Hospital was located in the cantonment for British troops near the Singapore River. <s> It later shifted to Pearl Banks apartment and then to the Kandang Kerbau district, before finally settling at Sepoy Lines along Outram Road in 1882. <s> The modern history of Singapore General Hospital began on 29 March 1926, with the opening of 800 beds in the Bowyer, Stanley and Norris Blocks. <s> Today, only the Bowyer Block with its historically distinctive clock tower remains. <s> The Bowyer Block is now home to the Singapore General Hospital Museum (SGH Museum). <s> In 1981, the hospital was rebuilt, with its current 8-block complex housing in-patient wards, ambulatory and support services, research laboratories and a postgraduate medical institute. <s> On 1 April 1989, the hospital was restructured, in an effort to modernise the organisation of the hospital, due to rapidly developing changes in healthcare services and patient expectations for better service. <s> As a restructured hospital, the Singapore General Hospital is still 100 per cent government-owned and is a not-for-profit institution. <s> More than 60 per cent of the beds are allocated for subsidised patients, giving them access to an internationally established standard of affordable healthcare. <s> The Singapore General Hospital Museum is a repository of artefacts and records, where visitors can trace the long and rich history of the Singapore General Hospital. <s> It is also a place where one can learn about the development of medical specialties and medical education in Singapore, presented with the aid of audio-visual and multimedia technology. <s> The SGH Museum was officially opened by President SR Nathan on 20 May 2005. <s> The museum adopts a thematic approach in presenting the hospital's long history, where visitors get not just an insight into the significant developments of the hospital through the years, but also an understanding of the impact these incidents have on the people and the community. <s> In 2015, 22 patients in the renal ward were infected with Hepatitis C. 8 out of the 22 patients died in the outbreak.
simple: The Singapore General Hospital (SGH; ) is the largest and oldest hospital in Singapore, which was founded in 1821. <s> SGH ranked third as the best hospital in the world by Newsweek in 2019. <s> The hospital occupies a large portion of the eastern part of Bukit Merah. <s> It shares space with the Singapore National Eye Centre (SNEC), the National Heart Centre Singapore (NHCS), the National Cancer Centre Singapore (NCCS), National Dental Centre Singapore (NDCS) and the Duke–NUS Medical School. <s> The hospital was established in 1821, when the first General Hospital was located in the cantonment for British troops near the Singapore River. <s> The hospital moved several times before settling down at Sepoy Lines along Outram Road in 1882. <s> Modern history of the hospital began on 29 March 1926, with the opening of 800 beds. <s> Today, only the Bowyer Block with its historically distinctive clock tower remains. <s> The Bowyer Block is now home to the The SGH Museum. <s> The campus now houses its current 8-block complex housing in-patient wards, ambulatory and support services, research laboratories and a postgraduate medical institute. <s> In the 1990's, the hospital was rebuilt and restructured to modernise the organisation of the hospital. <s> It is a repository of artefacts and records, where the long and rich history of the hospital can be traced. <s> One can also learn about the development of medical specialties and medical education in Singapore at the museum. <s> The SGH Museum was officially opened by President S. R. Nathan on 20 May 2005. <s> In 2015, 22 patients in the renal ward were infected with Hepatitis C and 8 out of which died in the outbreak.

title: Luba Goy
complex: Luba Goy ( ; born November 8, 1945) is a Canadian actress, comedian and one of the stars of "Royal Canadian Air Farce".
simple: Luba Goy (born 8 November 1945 in Germany) is now a Canadian comedienne and a Canadian television star. <s> She was probably best known as one of the stars of the Canadian comedy show "Royal Canadian Air Farce".

title: French Chess Championship
complex: The French Chess Championship is the annual, national chess tournament of France. <s> It was officially first played in 1923 after the formation of the "Fédération Française des Echecs" in 1921. <s> The first unofficial national tournament was played in 1880, in the Café de la Régence, where further edition were held in 1881 and 1883. <s> The 1903 and 1914 tournaments were the first real predecessors of the official championship. <s> They ran under the name "Championnat de France des amateurs" (Championship of the chess enthusiasts).
simple: The French Chess Championship is the annual national chess tournament of France. <s> It was officially first played in 1923 after the formation of the "Fédération Française des Echecs" in 1921. <s> The first unofficial national tournament was played in 1880, in the Café de la Régence, where further events were held in 1881 and 1883. <s> The 1903 and 1914 tournaments were the first real predecessors of the official championship. <s> They ran under the name "Championnat de France des amateurs" (Championship of the chess enthusiasts).

title: Ecosystem
complex: An ecosystem is a community of living organisms in conjunction with the nonliving components of their environment, interacting as a system. <s> These biotic and abiotic components are linked together through nutrient cycles and energy flows. <s> Energy enters the system through photosynthesis and is incorporated into plant tissue. <s> By feeding on plants and on one-another, animals play an important role in the movement of matter and energy through the system. <s> They also influence the quantity of plant and microbial biomass present. <s> By breaking down dead organic matter, decomposers release carbon back to the atmosphere and facilitate nutrient cycling by converting nutrients stored in dead biomass back to a form that can be readily used by plants and other microbes. <s> Primary production is the production of organic matter from inorganic carbon sources. <s> This mainly occurs through photosynthesis. <s> The energy incorporated through this process supports life on earth, while the carbon makes up much of the organic matter in living and dead biomass, soil carbon and fossil fuels. <s> It also drives the carbon cycle, which influences global climate via the greenhouse effect. <s> Through the process of photosynthesis, plants capture energy from light and use it to combine carbon dioxide and water to produce carbohydrates and oxygen. <s> The photosynthesis carried out by all the plants in an ecosystem is called the gross primary production (GPP). <s> About half of the GPP is consumed in plant respiration. <s> The remainder, that portion of GPP that is not used up by respiration, is known as the net primary production (NPP). <s> Total photosynthesis is limited by a range of environmental factors. <s> These include the amount of light available, the amount of leaf area a plant has to capture light (shading by other plants is a major limitation of photosynthesis), rate at which carbon dioxide can be supplied to the chloroplasts to support photosynthesis, the availability of water, and the availability of suitable temperatures for carrying out photosynthesis. <s> Ecosystems are dynamic entities. <s> They are subject to periodic disturbances and are in the process of recovering from some past disturbance.
simple: An ecosystem is a large community of living organisms (plants, animals and microbes) in a particular area. <s> The living and physical components are linked together through nutrient cycles and energy flows. <s> What drives all ecosystems is the primary production. <s> Primary production is the production of organic matter from inorganic carbon sources. <s> This happens through photosynthesis. <s> It drives the carbon cycle, which influences global climate via the greenhouse effect. <s> Through the process of photosynthesis, plants capture energy from light and use it to combine carbon dioxide and water to produce carbohydrates and oxygen. <s> The photosynthesis carried out by all the plants in an ecosystem is called the gross primary production (GPP). <s> About 48–60% of the GPP is consumed in plant respiration. <s> The rest is known as the net primary production (NPP). <s> Total photosynthesis is limited by a range of environmental factors. <s> These include the amount of light available, the amount of leaf area a plant has to capture light (shading by other plants limits photosynthesis), the supply of carbon dioxide and water, and suitable temperatures for carrying out photosynthesis. <s> Ecosystems are stable, but not rigid.

title: Metroid: Zero Mission
complex: Metroid: Zero Mission is a side-scrolling action-adventure video game published by Nintendo, and developed by its Research & Development 1 (R&D1) division for the Game Boy Advance. <s> It is a remake of the 1986 game "Metroid"—the first installment in the "Metroid" video game series, and is designed to retell that entry's story with modernized gameplay. <s> It was initially released in North America in February 2004.
simple: Metroid: Zero Mission (メトロイドゼロミッション, Metoroido Zero Misshon) is an action-adventure video game made by Nintendo for the Game Boy Advance game console. <s> It is a remake of the NES game "Metroid", and it retells its story.

title: Jarilo
complex: Jarylo (Cyrillic: Ярило or Ярила; ; , Јарило; ), alternatively Yarylo, Iarilo, or Gerovit, is a Slavic god of vegetation, fertility and springtime. <s> The only historic source that mentions this deity is a 12th-century biography of the proselytizing German bishop Otto of Bamberg, who, during his expeditions to convert the pagan tribes of Wendish and Polabian Slavs, encountered festivals in honor of the war-god Gerovit in the cities of Wolgast and Havelberg. <s> Gerovit is most likely a German corruption of the original Slavic name "Jarovit". <s> Up until the 19th century in Russia, Belarus and Serbia, folk festivals called "Jarilo" were celebrated in late spring or early summer. <s> Early researchers of Slavic mythology recognised in them relics of pagan ceremonies in honor of an eponymous spring deity. <s> In Northern Croatia and Southern Slovenia, especially White Carniola, similar spring festivals were called "Jurjevo" or "Zeleni Juraj" or "Zeleni Jurij" (Green George), nominally dedicated to St. George, and fairly similar to the Jarilo festivals of other Slavic nations.
simple: Jarilo (Cyrillic: Ярило, Ярила or Јарило) is a Slavic god of vegetation, fertility and springtime. <s> The only historical source that mentions Jarilo was from a German bishop who encountered pagans celebrating a festival called Gerovit (likely a German way of saying, "Jarovit"). <s> Until the 19th century in Russia, Belarus and Serbia, folk festivals called "Jarilo" were celebrated in late spring. <s> Similar festivals occurred in Croatia and Slovenia.

title: Fish Hooks
complex: Fish Hooks is an American animated television series created by Noah Z. Jones that originally aired on Disney Channel from September 3, 2010 to April 4, 2014. <s> Twenty-one episodes were ordered for the first season. <s> The first season premiered on September 24, 2010. <s> In 2009, President of entertainment Gary Marsh said of the show, "The "Fish Hooks" team has created one of the most original, inventive animated series on television – bringing an ingenious twist to the classic archetypes of high school life."
simple: Fish Hooks is a 2010 animated series. <s> It was created by Noah Z. Jones. <s> The show ended on April 4, 2014. <s> The series was first broadcast on September 24, 2010.

title: Bill Peduto
complex: William Mark Peduto (born October 30, 1964) is an American politician who serves as the 60th Mayor of Pittsburgh. <s> A member of the Democratic Party, he previously served as a member of the Pittsburgh City Council from 2002 until 2014. <s> In the 2013 election, Peduto defeated opponents Joshua Wander and Lester Ludwig, winning 84% of the vote. <s> After being elected Mayor to succeed the outgoing Luke Ravenstahl, Peduto was inaugurated in January 2014. <s> In the 2017 election, he was re-elected to a second term as Mayor, winning 96% of the vote.
simple: William Mark Peduto (born October 30, 1964) is an American politician. <s> He is the 60th Mayor of Pittsburgh. <s> He is a member of the Democratic Party. <s> Before being mayor, he was a member of the Pittsburgh City Council from 2002 until 2014. <s> In the 2013 election, Peduto won the mayoral election by winning 84% of the vote. <s> After being elected Mayor to succeed the outgoing Luke Ravenstahl, Peduto was inaugurated in January 2014. <s> In the 2017 election, he was re-elected to a second term as Mayor, winning 96% of the vote.

title: Colubridae
complex: Colubridae ( , commonly known as colubrids , from Latin "coluber", snake) is a family of snakes. <s> With 524 genera and approximately 1,760 species, it is the largest snake family, and includes just over 51% of all known living snake species. <s> The earliest species of the family date back to the Oligocene epoch. <s> Colubrid snakes are found on every continent except Antarctica. <s> While most colubrids are not venomous (or have venom that is not known to be harmful to humans) and are mostly harmless, a few groups, such as genus "Boiga", can produce medically significant bites, while the boomslang, the twig snakes, and the Asian genus "Rhabdophis" have caused human fatalities. <s> In the past, the Colubridae were not a natural group, as many were more closely related to other groups, such as elapids, than to each other. <s> This family was historically used as a "wastebasket taxon" for snakes that do not fit elsewhere. <s> Until recently, colubrids were basically colubroids that were not elapids, viperids, or "Atractaspis".
simple: A colubrid (from Latin "coluber", snake) is a snake that is a member of the Colubridae "family". <s> Colubridae is the largest snake family, and includes about two-thirds of all known living snake species. <s> Most colubrids are not venomous and are normally harmless. <s> A few groups, such as genus "Boiga", can produce medically significant bites. <s> In addition, the Boomslang and African twig snake have both caused human fatalities. <s> However, The Colubrids are "certainly not a natural group", and many are more closely related to other groups, such as elapids, than to each other. <s> This family has classically been a dumping ground for snakes that do not fit anywhere else.

title: Equation solving
complex: In mathematics, to solve an equation is to find its solutions, which are the values (numbers, functions, sets, etc.) that fulfill the condition stated by the equation, consisting generally of two expressions related by an equality sign. <s> When seeking a solution, one or more free variables are designated as unknowns. <s> A solution is an assignment of expressions to the unknown variables that makes the equality in the equation true.
simple: Equation solving is field of mathematics that is about finding the functions or values that will make an equation true. <s> An equation says that two expressions are equal. <s> These expressions contain one or more unknowns, which are usually called free variables.

title: Tony Conrad
complex: Anthony Schmalz "Tony" Conrad (March 7, 1940 – April 9, 2016) was an American avant-garde video artist, experimental filmmaker, musician, composer, sound artist, teacher, and writer. <s> Active in a variety of media since the early 1960s, he was a pioneer of both structural film and drone music. <s> He performed and collaborated with a wide range of artists over the course of his career, most prominently the 1960s New York experimental music group Theatre of Eternal Music. <s> Conrad had been a faculty member in the State University of New York at Buffalo since 1976. <s> He continued to teach there in the Department of Media Study as well as work on many notable black and white film image projects with Princess G. St. Mary until his death in 2016. <s> Conrad died in Cheektowaga, New York on April 9, 2016 at age 76 after fighting prostate cancer.
simple: Anthony Schmaltz "Tony" Conrad (March 7, 1940 – April 9, 2016) was an American avant-garde video artist, experimental filmmaker, musician, composer, sound artist, teacher and writer. <s> His career began in the early 1960s. <s> He was a pioneer of both structural movie and drone music. <s> Conrad had been a faculty member in the State University of New York at Buffalo since 1976. <s> He continued to teach there in the Department of Media Study as well as work on many notable B&W film image projects with Princess G. St. Mary until his death in 2016. <s> Conrad died in Cheektowaga, New York on April 9, 2016 at age 76 after fighting prostate cancer.

title: Vince Neil
complex: Vincent Neil Wharton (born February 8, 1961) is an American musician. <s> He is best known as the lead vocalist of heavy metal band Mötley Crüe which he co-founded in 1981, but he has also released three albums as a solo artist. <s> He is known for his turbulent personal life which has led to multiple arrests and convictions, including one for vehicular manslaughter. <s> Neil was discovered while performing with his band Rock Candy in 1979, and joined Mötley Crüe in 1981. <s> Neil had been friends with Tommy Lee in high school. <s> Mötley Crüe was looking for a lead vocalist at the time and were impressed by Neil after hearing him through Lee. <s> Mötley Crüe released its first album, "Too Fast for Love", in 1981. <s> The band then began a string of hit releases throughout the decade—1983's "Shout at the Devil", which established the band as a big act in rock and roll, 1985's "Theatre of Pain", 1987's hit "Girls, Girls, Girls", and their highest-selling album, 1989's "Dr. Feelgood"—establishing the quartet as one of the biggest hard rock/metal bands of the '80s. <s> Following the band's first compilation album "Decade of Decadence 81-91" Mötley Crüe parted ways with Vince Neil in February 1992. <s> By 1997, Neil's solo career and Mötley's fortunes were declining, so the four reunited that year. <s> "They admitted they couldn't do it without me", he recalled, "and I wasn't selling records the way Mötley Crüe had." <s> They released "Generation Swine", which debuted at #4 on the "Billboard" charts. <s> Tension soon erupted, however, this time prompting Tommy Lee to leave. <s> The other members replaced him with Randy Castillo and recorded "New Tattoo" in 2000. <s> The renewed band went on hiatus when Castillo died from cancer in 2002. <s> In 2008, Mötley Crüe released the album "Saints of Los Angeles", featuring all the original members.
simple: Vincent Neil Wharton (born February 8, 1961 in Hollywood, California) is an American musician. <s> He is the lead singer of the heavy metal band Mötley Crüe. <s> He joined Mötley Crüe in 1981 and released "Too Fast for Love" on November 10, 1981. <s> He then went on to record "Shout at the Devil", "Theatre of Pain", "Girls, Girls, Girls" and "Dr. Feelgood" with Mötley Crüe before both Neil and Mötley Crüe parted ways. <s> He then went on a solo career but rejoined Mötley Crüe when both their fortunes were declining. <s> Lee was replaced by Randy Castillo and the band recorded "New Tattoo" on July 11, 2000. <s> The band went on hiatus after Castillo died of cancer on March 26, 2002. <s> The band then released their ninth studio album "Saints of Los Angeles" on June 24, 2008.

title: Ernst Heinrich Weber
complex: Ernst Heinrich Weber (24 June 1795 – 26 January 1878) was a German physician who is considered one of the founders of experimental psychology. <s> He was an influential and important figure in the areas of physiology and psychology during his lifetime and beyond. <s> His studies on sensation and touch, along with his emphasis on good experimental techniques gave way to new directions and areas of study for future psychologists, physiologists, and anatomists. <s> Ernst Weber was born into an academic background, with his father serving as a professor at the University of Wittenberg. <s> Weber became a doctor, specializing in anatomy and physiology. <s> Two of his younger brothers, Wilhelm and Eduard, were also influential in academia, both as scientists with one specializing in physics and the other in anatomy. <s> Ernst became a lecturer and a professor at the University of Leipzig and stayed there until his retirement. <s> In a book titled "De Tactu", which translates to "Concerning touch" in English, he decided that there was a threshold of sensation in each individual.
simple: Ernst Heinrich Weber (24 June 1795 – 26 January 1878) was a German physician. <s> He was one of the founders of experimental psychology. <s> Weber was an influential and important figure in the areas of physiology and psychology during his lifetime and beyond. <s> His studies on sensation and touch, and his emphasis on good experimental techniques were notable. <s> They gave new direction and areas of study to future psychologists, physiologists, and anatomists. <s> Weber was born into an academic background, with his father serving as a professor at the University of Wittenberg. <s> Weber became a doctor, specializing in anatomy and physiology. <s> Two of his younger brothers, Wilhelm and Eduard, were also influential in academia, both as scientists. <s> One did physics and the other anatomy. <s> Ernst became a lecturer and a professor at the University of Leipzig and stayed there until his retirement.

title: Savannah monitor
complex: The savannah monitor ("Varanus exanthematicus") is a medium-sized species of monitor lizard native to Africa. <s> The species is known as Bosc’s monitor in Europe, since French scientist Louis Bosc first described the species. <s> It belongs to the subgenus "Polydaedalus", along with the Nile, the ornate and other monitors. <s> Information about the diet of savannah monitors in the wild has been recorded in Senegal and Ghana. <s> It feeds almost exclusively on arthropods and molluscs. <s> In Senegal, "Iulus" millipedes were the most common prey of adults; in Ghana, small crickets formed the bulk of the diet of animals less than 2 months old; orthopterans (especially "Brachytrupes"), scorpions and amphibians were the most common prey of animals 6–7 months old . <s> Its range extends throughout sub-Saharan Africa from Senegal east to Sudan and south almost to the Congo River and Rift Valley, where they are replaced by "V. albigularis". <s> "V. exanthematicus" is primarily a ground-dwelling species that shelters in burrows, although it is sometimes found in bushes or low trees. <s> In the coastal plain of Ghana, "V. exanthematicus" juveniles are often associated with the burrows of the giant cricket "Brachytrupes".
simple: The savannah monitor (or Bosc's monitor) is a medium-sized monitor lizard from Africa. <s> Its scientific name is "Varanus exanthematicus". <s> Information about the diet of Savannah monitors in the wild has been recorded in Senegal and Ghana. <s> It feeds almost exclusively on arthropods and molluscs. <s> Its range extends throughout sub-Saharan Africa, from Senegal east to Sudan and south almost to the Congo River and Great Rift Valley. <s> It is a ground-dwelling species which shelters in burrows, although it is sometimes found in bushes or low trees.

title: Christopher Malcolm
complex: Christopher Malcolm (19 August 1946 – 15 February 2014) was a Scottish television and film actor, director and producer. <s> He first achieved notability for his role as Brad Majors in the original stage production of "The Rocky Horror Show". <s> Malcolm was born in Aberdeen, Scotland, and was brought up in Canada after his family emigrated to British Columbia in the late 1940s. <s> He attended the University of British Columbia, where he worked and studied theatre. <s> His daughter reported his death from cancer, aged 67, on 15 February 2014, via Twitter.
simple: Christopher "Chris" Malcolm (19 August 1946 – 15 February 2014) was a Scottish actor, director and producer. <s> He was born in Aberdeen, Scotland. <s> He was brought up in Canada after his family emigrated to Vernon, British Columbia in the late 1940s. <s> Malcolm died from cancer on 15 February 2014, aged 67, in London, England. <s> His death was reported by his daughter, Morgan.

title: Sodium iodide
complex: Sodium iodide (chemical formula NaI) is an ionic compound formed from the chemical reaction of sodium metal and iodine. <s> Under standard conditions, it is a white, water-soluble solid comprising a 1:1 mix of sodium cations (Na) and iodide anions (I) in a crystal lattice.
simple: Sodium iodide is a chemical compound. <s> It is composed of sodium and iodide ions. <s> The chemical formula is NaI.

title: Boeing 80
complex: The Boeing 80 was an American airliner of the 1920s. <s> A three-engined biplane, the Model 80 was built by the Boeing Airplane Company for Boeing's own airline, Boeing Air Transport, successfully carrying both airmail and passengers on scheduled services. <s> Boeing Air Transport was formed on February 17, 1927 by William Boeing to operate the Contract Air Mail (CAM) service between San Francisco and Chicago (CAM.18), taking over the route on July 1, 1927. <s> The route was initially operated by single-engined Boeing 40A biplanes, which could carry four passengers, which provided a useful supplement to the subsidized revenue from carrying airmail. <s> In order to take better advantage of passenger traffic, Boeing decided that it needed a larger aircraft that was more suitable for passenger carrying, and in early 1928 designed a trimotor aircraft capable of carrying 12 passengers, the Model 80. <s> Unlike the Fokker F-10 and Ford Trimotors operated by other U.S. airlines, the Model 80 was a biplane, chosen to give good takeoff and landing performance when operating from difficult airfields on its routes, many of which were at relatively high altitude. <s> The fuselage was of fabric covered steel and aluminium tube construction, and carried its 12 passengers in three-abreast seating in a well-appointed cabin. <s> The flight crew of two sat in an enclosed flight deck forward of the passenger cabin. <s> The wings were of fabric covered steel and duralumin construction, with detachable wingtips to aid storage in hangars. <s> The first Model 80, powered by three Pratt & Whitney Wasp radial engines, flew on July 27, 1928. <s> It was followed by three more Model 80s before production switched to the improved Model 80A, which was longer, allowing 18 passengers to be carried, and was powered by more powerful Pratt & Whitney Hornet engines, first flying on July 18, 1929 and receiving its airworthiness certificate on August 20, 1929. <s> The Model 80 carried out its first scheduled mail and passenger service for Boeing Air Transport on September 20, 1928, and soon proved successful. <s> The improved Model 80A entered service in September 1929. <s> In May 1930, Boeing Air Transport introduced female flight attendants, hiring eight including chief stewardess Ellen Church; all were unmarried registered nurses. <s> Flights carrying stewardesses began on May 15. <s> The Model 80 and 80A remained in service with Boeing Air Transport (later renamed United Airlines) until replaced by the Boeing 247 twin-engined monoplane in 1934. <s> A single Model 80A-1, modified as a freighter for use in Alaska, was salvaged from a dump at Anchorage Airport in 1960, and following restoration is now on display at the Museum of Flight in Seattle. <s> "Data from" Boeing Aircraft since 1916General characteristics* Crew: Three* Capacity: 18 passengers* Payload: 898 lb cargo (408 kg) air-cooled radials, 525 hp (392 kW) each Performance )* Service ceiling: 14,000 ft (4,270 m)* Rate of climb: 900 ft/min (4.6 m/s)
simple: The Boeing 80, sometimes called the Boeing Model 80 or just the Model 80, was an American airliner. <s> It was a biplane with three engines. <s> The Boeing 80 was built by the Boeing Airplane Company. <s> Boeing Air Transport was started on February 17, 1927 by William Boeing. <s> On July 1, 1927, planes from Boeing Air Transport started flying mail from San Francisco to Chicago. <s> Boeing decided to make a plane to carry passengers. <s> In 1928 it designed the Model 80. <s> The Boeing 80 could carry 12 people. <s> The pilots sat in a cockpit in front of the passengers. <s> The first Boeing 80 took off on July 27, 1928. <s> The Boeing 80 first flew for Boeing Air Transport on September 20, 1928. <s> The Boeing 80A started being used in September 1929. <s> In May 1930, Boeing Air Transport hired eight female flight attendants. <s> They first flew on May 15. <s> The Boeing 80 and 80A were used until the Boeing 247 replaced them in 1934. <s> One Boeing 80A was found in a dump at Anchorage Airport in 1960. <s> It was fixed up and it is now in the Museum of Flight in Seattle. <s> "Data from" Boeing Aircraft since 1916General characteristics* Crew: Three* Capacity: 18 passengers* Payload: 898 lb cargo (408 kg) air-cooled radials, 525 hp (392 kW) each Performance )* Service ceiling: 14,000 ft (4,270 m)* Rate of climb: 900 ft/min (4.6 m/s)

title: Hans von Bülow
complex: Hans Guido Freiherr von Bülow (January 8, 1830February 12, 1894) was a German conductor, virtuoso pianist, and composer of the Romantic era. <s> As one of the most distinguished conductors of the 19th century, his activity was critical for establishing the successes of several major composers of the time, especially Richard Wagner and Johannes Brahms. <s> Alongside Carl Tausig, Bülow was perhaps the most prominent of the early students of Hungarian virtuoso pianist, conductor and composer Franz Liszt—therein performed the first public performance of Liszt's Sonata in B minor in 1857. <s> He became acquainted with, fell in love and eventually married Liszt's daughter Cosima, who later left him for Wagner. <s> Noted for his interpretation of the works of Ludwig van Beethoven, he was one of the earliest European musicians to tour the United States. <s> Bülow was born in Dresden, to members of the prominent Bülow family. <s> From the age of nine, he was a student of Friedrich Wieck (the father of Clara Schumann). <s> However, his parents insisted that he study law instead of music, and they sent him to Leipzig. <s> There he met Franz Liszt, and on hearing some music of Richard Wagner—specifically, the premiere of "Lohengrin" in 1850—he decided to ignore the dictates of his parents and make himself a career in music instead. <s> He studied the piano in Leipzig with the famous pedagogue Louis Plaidy. <s> He obtained his first conducting job in Zurich, on Wagner's recommendation, in 1850. <s> Bülow had a strongly acerbic personality and a loose tongue; this alienated many musicians whom he worked with. <s> He was dismissed from his Zurich job for this reason, but at the same time he was beginning to win renown for his ability to conduct new and complex works without a score. <s> In 1851, he became a student of Liszt, marrying his daughter Cosima in 1857. <s> They had two daughters: Daniela, born in 1860 and Blandina, born in 1863. <s> During the 1850s and early 1860s he was active as a pianist, conductor, and writer, and became well known throughout Germany as well as Russia. <s> In 1857, he premiered Liszt's Piano Sonata in B minor in Berlin. <s> In 1864 he became the Hofkapellmeister in Munich, and it was at this post he achieved his principal renown. <s> He conducted the premieres of two Wagner operas, "Tristan und Isolde" and "Die Meistersinger von Nürnberg", in 1865 and 1868 respectively; both were immensely successful. <s> Meanwhile, however, Cosima had been carrying on an affair with Richard Wagner and gave birth to their daughter Isolde in 1865. <s> Two years later, they had another daughter, Eva. <s> Although Cosima and Wagner's affair was now open knowledge, Bülow still refused to grant his wife a divorce. <s> Finally, she gave birth to one final child––a son, Siegfried––and it was only then that the conductor at last relented. <s> Their divorce was finalized in 1870, after which Cosima and Wagner married. <s> Bülow never spoke to Wagner again and he did not see his former wife for 11 years afterwards, although he apparently continued to respect the composer on a professional level, as he still conducted his works and mourned Wagner's death in 1883. <s> In July 1882 he married the actress Marie Schanzer. <s> In addition to championing the music of Wagner, Bülow was a supporter of the music of both Brahms and Tchaikovsky. <s> He was the soloist in the world premiere of the Tchaikovsky Piano Concerto No. 1 in B-flat minor in Boston in 1875. <s> He was also a devotee of Frédéric Chopin's music; he came up with epithets for all of Chopin's Opus 28 Preludes, but these have generally fallen into disuse. <s> On the other hand, the D-flat major Prelude No. 15 is widely known by his title, the "Raindrop." <s> He was the first to perform (from memory) the complete cycle of Beethoven's piano sonatas, and with Sigmund Lebert, he co-produced an edition of the sonatas. <s> From 1878 to 1880 he was Hofkapellmeister in Hanover but was forced to leave after fighting with a tenor singing the "Knight of the Swan "Schwan"" role in "Lohengrin"; Bülow had called him the "Knight of the Swine "Schwein"". <s> In 1880 he moved to Meiningen where he took the equivalent post, and where he built the Meiningen Court Orchestra into one of the finest in Germany; among his other demands, he insisted that the musicians learn to play all their parts from memory. <s> It was during his five years in Meiningen that he met Richard Strauss (though the meeting actually took place in Berlin). <s> His first opinion of the young composer was not favorable, but he changed his mind when he was confronted with a sample of Strauss's "Serenade". <s> Later on, he used his influence to give Strauss his first regular employment as a conductor. <s> Like Strauss, Bülow was attracted to the ideas of Max Stirner, whom he reputedly had known personally. <s> In April 1892 Bülow closed his final performance with the Berlin Philharmonic (where he had been serving as Principal Conductor since 1887) with a speech "exalting" the ideas of Stirner. <s> Together with John Henry Mackay, Stirner's biographer, he placed a memorial plaque at Stirner's last residence in Berlin. <s> Some of his orchestral innovations included the addition of the five-string bass and the pedal timpani; the pedal timpani have since become standard instruments in the symphony orchestra. <s> His accurate, sensitive, and profoundly musical interpretations established him as the prototype of the virtuoso conductors who flourished at a later date. <s> He was also an astute and witty musical journalist. <s> In the late 1880s he settled in Hamburg, but continued to tour, both conducting and performing on the piano. <s> Bülow suffered from chronic neuralgiforme headaches, which were caused by a tumor of the cervical radicular nerves. <s> After about 1890 his mental and physical health began to fail, and he sought a warmer, drier climate for recovery; he died in a hotel in Cairo, Egypt at the age of 64, only ten months after his final concert performance.
simple: Hans von Bülow (born Dresden, 8 January 1830 ; died Cairo, 12 February 1894) was a German conductor and pianist. <s> He was one of the most famous conductors of the 19th century as well as being a famous pianist. <s> Bülow was born in Dresden. <s> When he was nine he had music lessons from Friedrich Wieck who was the father of Clara Schumann. <s> However, his parents said that he had to study law instead of music, and they sent him to Leipzig. <s> He decided to study music even though his parents did not want him to. <s> During this time he met Franz Liszt in Weimar and he heard him conduct the music of Wagner. <s> In 1857 he married Liszt’s daughter, Cosima. <s> They had two daughters. <s> He toured as pianist and conductor in Germany and Russia. <s> In 1864 he became the Hofkapellmeister in Munich. <s> He conducted the first performances of two Wagner operas: "Tristan und Isolde" (1865) and "Die Meistersinger von Nürnberg" (1868). <s> Meanwhile Cosima was having a love affair with Richard Wagner. <s> However, he always continued to show great respect for Wagner and continued to conduct his music. <s> When Wagner died in 1883 he was terribly sad. <s> He visited England and the USA where, as the solo pianist, he gave the first performance (world premiere) of Tchaikovsky’s Piano Concerto No. 1 in Boston in 1875. <s> He made the players perform from memory. <s> From 1878 to 1880 he was conductor in Hanover, but had to leave after a quarrel with a tenor. <s> In 1880 he went to Meiningen where he conducted the orchestra, making it one of the best orchestras in Germany. <s> During this time he met Richard Strauss in Berlin. <s> He also introduced timpani with pedals. <s> He was also very good at writing about music. <s> In the late 1880s he settled in Hamburg, but continued to tour, both conducting and performing on the piano. <s> Bülow had health problems which gave him very bad headaches. <s> He died in a hotel in Cairo, Egypt, ten months after his last concert performance.

title: Carl Duering
complex: Gerald Percy Fox (29 May 1923 – 1 September 2018), better known as Carl Duering, was a German-born British actor whose best known role is as Dr. Brodsky in Stanley Kubrick's "A Clockwork Orange". <s> He died in London in September 2018 at the age of 95.
simple: Carl Duering (born 29 May 1923) is a German-born British actor. <s> He is best known role is as Dr. Brodsky in Stanley Kubrick's 1971 movie "A Clockwork Orange".

title: 34th Annie Awards
complex: The ceremony for the 34th Annual Annie Awards, honoring the best in animation in 2006, was held on February 11, 2007 at the Alex Theatre in Glendale, California. <s> The nominations were announced on December 4, 2006. <s> Winners are marked in bold text. <s> Significant and benevolent or charitable impact on the art and industry of animation. <s> Recognition of lifetime or career contributions to the art of animation.
simple: The ceremony for the 34th Annual Annie Awards, honoring the best in animation in 2006, was held on February 11, 2007 at the Alex Theatre in Glendale, California. <s> The nominations were announced on December 4, 2006. <s> Winners are marked in bold text. <s> Significant and benevolent or charitable impact on the art and industry of animation. <s> Recognition of lifetime or career contributions to the art of animation.

title: North Canton, Ohio
complex: North Canton is a city in Stark County in the U.S. state of Ohio. <s> The population was 17,488 at the 2010 United States Census. <s> It is part of the Canton–Massillon metropolitan statistical area.
simple: North Canton is a city in Stark County, Ohio, United States. <s> The population was 17,488 at the 2010 census.

title: Rifa`i
complex: Rifa`i (also "Rufa`i", "Rifa`iyya", "Rifa`iya", Arabic, الرفاعية) is an eminent Sufi order (tariqa) founded by Ahmed ar-Rifa'i and developed in the Lower Iraq marshlands between Wasit and Basra. <s> The Rifa'iyya had its greatest following until the 15th century C.E. when it was overtaken by the Qadiri order.
simple: The Rifai Sufi order or "Tariqah" was established by Hazrat Sheikh Ahmed Ar-Rifai in Iraq.

title: Havelian
complex: Havelian is the second largest municipality in the Abbottabad District, in the Hazara Division, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan. <s> It serves as the headquarters for Havelian Tehsil.
simple: It is in Abbottabad District in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province.

title: Pseudobufo subasper
complex: Pseudobufo subasper is a species of toad in the family Bufonidae. <s> It is monotypic within the genus Pseudobufo. <s> It is found in Indonesia and Malaysia. <s> Its natural habitats are subtropical or tropical swamps and swamps. <s> It is threatened by habitat loss. <s> This toad can only be found in peat swamps. <s> They have fully webbed hind feet and are closely associated with water.
simple: Pseudobufo subasper is a species of toad in the Bufonidae family. <s> It is the only species in the genus Pseudobufo. <s> They are found in Indonesia and Malaysia. <s> They live in subtropical or tropical swamps. <s> They are threatened by habitat loss. <s> This toad can only be found in peat swamps. <s> They have fully webbed back feet.

title: Beetlejuice
complex: Beetlejuice is a 1988 American fantasy-comedy-horror film directed by Tim Burton, produced by The Geffen Company and distributed by Warner Bros. <s> The plot revolves around a recently deceased young couple (Alec Baldwin and Geena Davis) who become ghosts haunting their former home, and an obnoxious, devious poltergeist named Betelgeuse (pronounced and occasionally spelled Beetlejuice in the movie and portrayed by Michael Keaton) from the Netherworld who tries to scare away the new inhabitants (Catherine O'Hara, Jeffrey Jones, and Winona Ryder) permanently. <s> Barbara and Adam Maitland decide to spend their vacation decorating their idyllic Connecticut country home. <s> Relative Jane Butterfield, a pushy real estate agent, hounds them with purchase offers that she solicits against their will. <s> As the two are driving home from a trip to town, Barbara swerves to avoid a dog and the car plunges into a river. <s> Jane immediately sells the house to the Deetz family, from New York City. <s> Charles Deetz is a former real estate developer; his wife Delia, a sculptor; and his thirteen year old goth daughter Lydia, from his first marriage, is an aspiring photographer. <s> Under the guidance of interior designer Otho, Delia begins to transform the house into a posh modern art piece.
simple: Beetlejuice is a 1988 American fantasy-comedy-horror movie directed by Tim Burton. <s> The movie stars Alec Baldwin, Geena Davis, Winona Ryder and Michael Keaton as Beetlejuice. <s> Barbara (Geena Davis) and Adam (Alec Baldwin) Maitland decide to spend their holiday decorating their New England country home. <s> Driving back from a trip to town, they crash the car and are killed. <s> The couple's house is then sold and in move the new owners from New York City. <s> The Deetzes, who are Charles (Jeffrey Jones) and his wife Delia (Catherine O'Hara), her friend Otho (Glenn Shadix) and Charles' goth daughter Lydia (Winona Ryder) from his first marriage.

title: Hemocyanin
complex: Hemocyanins (also spelled haemocyanins and abbreviated Hc) are proteins that transport oxygen throughout the bodies of some invertebrate animals. <s> These metalloproteins contain two copper atoms that reversibly bind a single oxygen molecule (O). <s> They are second only to hemoglobin in frequency of use as an oxygen transport molecule. <s> Unlike the hemoglobin in red blood cells found in vertebrates, hemocyanins are not bound to blood cells but are instead suspended directly in the hemolymph. <s> Oxygenation causes a color change between the colorless Cu(I) deoxygenated form and the blue Cu(II) oxygenated form. <s> Hemocyanins are found only in the Mollusca and Arthropoda: the earliest discoveries of hemocyanins were in the snail "Helix pomatia" (a mollusc) and in the horseshoe crab (an arthropod). <s> They were subsequently found to be common among crustaceans and are utilized by some land arthropods such as the tarantula "Eurypelma californicum", the emperor scorpion, and the centipede "Scutigera coleoptrata".
simple: Haemocyanin (or hemocyanin) is a protein which transports oxygen in the bodies of some invertebrates. <s> Their active centre has two copper atoms which reversibly bind a single oxygen molecule (O). <s> Unlike the hemoglobin in red blood cells found in vertebrates, hemocyanins are not bound to blood cells. <s> Hemocyanins are found only in the Mollusca and Arthropoda.

title: Tatosoma
complex: Tatosoma is a genus of moths in the family Geometridae first described by Arthur Gardiner Butler in 1874. <s> The species in this genus are found only in New Zealand.
simple: Tatosoma is a genus of moths.

title: Insjön
complex: Insjön is a locality situated in Leksand Municipality, Dalarna County, Sweden with 2,149 inhabitants in 2010. <s> In 1899 Åhléns started out as the mail order business Åhlén & Holm.
simple: Insjön is a locality in Leksand Municipality in Dalarna County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 2,149 people lived there.

title: First Boer War
complex: The First Boer War ( , literally "First Freedom War"), also known as the First Anglo-Boer War, the Transvaal War or the Transvaal Rebellion, was a war fought from 16 December 1880 until 23 March 1881 between the United Kingdom and Boers of the Transvaal (as the South African Republic was known while under British administration). <s> The war resulted in Britain’s accession to the establishment of the Second Republic. <s> In the 19th century a series of events occurred in the southern part of the African continent, with the British from time to time attempting to set up a single unified state there, while at other times wanting to control less territory. <s> Following the Battle of Blaauwberg (1806) Britain had officially acquired the Cape of Good Hope in South Africa from the Dutch in 1815 after the Napoleonic Wars. <s> Certain groups of Dutch-speaking settler farmers ("Boers") resented British rule, even though British control brought some economic benefits. <s> Successive waves of migrations of Boer farmers (known as "Trekboers" which literally means "transhumant farmers"), probed first east along the coast away from the Cape toward Natal, and thereafter north toward the interior, eventually establishing the republics that came to be known as the Orange Free State and the Transvaal (literally "across/beyond the Vaal River"). <s> The Trekboers were farmers, gradually extending their range and territory with no overall agenda. <s> The formal abolition of slavery in the British Empire in 1834 led to more organised groups of Boer settlers attempting to escape British rule, some travelling as far north as modern-day Mozambique. <s> This became known as the Great Trek, and those who took part in it are called Voortrekkers.
simple: On 16 December 1880 the First Boer War began. <s> In the 19th Century Scramble for Africa, the British Empire tried to control all of southern Africa. <s> They won control of the Cape of Good Hope in 1815 at the end of the Napoleonic Wars. <s> Many Boers (Dutch, German and French farmers) did not like Britain controlling the area. <s> The British taxed them, made English the official language, and in 1834 abolished slavery.

title: Game Boy Color
complex: The Game Boy Color (GBC) is a handheld game console manufactured by Nintendo, which was released on October 21, 1998, in Japan, and later released in November of the same year to international markets. <s> It is the successor of the Game Boy and continued in the Game Boy family. <s> The last "Game Boy Color" game ever released was the Japanese exclusive "Doraemon no Study Boy: Kanji Yomikaki Master", which was released in Japan on July 18, 2003. <s> In North America, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets", released on November 15, 2002, was the last game released. <s> In Europe the last game ever released was "Hamtaro: Ham-Hams Unite!"
simple: The Game Boy Color is a video game console manufactured by Nintendo. <s> It was first introduced in Japan in October 1998 and released in North America, Europe and Australia in November 1998. <s> The Game Boy Color is almost as powerful as the Nintendo Entertainment System. <s> It is the successor to the original Game Boy, but it precedes the Game Boy Advance. <s> The last game released for Game Boy Color was "Harry Potter And The Chamber of Secrets" in 2002.

title: Personal name
complex: A personal name or full name is the set of names by which an individual is known and that can be recited as a word-group, with the understanding that, taken together, they all relate to that one individual. <s> In many cultures, the term is synonymous with the "birth name" or "legal name" of the individual. <s> The academic study of personal names is called anthroponymy. <s> It is nearly universal for people to have names; the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child declares that a child has the right to a name from birth.
simple: A personal name is the label which identifies an individual person. <s> The Convention on the Rights of the Child specifies that a child has the right from birth to a name.

title: Millennium Force
