complex: Millennium Force is a steel roller coaster located at Cedar Point amusement park in Sandusky, Ohio. <s> Manufactured by Intamin, it was the park's fourteenth roller coaster dating back to the opening of Blue Streak in 1964. <s> Upon completion in 2000, Millennium Force broke six world records and was the world's first "giga coaster", a term coined by Intamin and Cedar Point to represent roller coasters that exceed 300 ft in height and complete a full circuit. <s> It was briefly the tallest and fastest in the world until Steel Dragon 2000 opened later the same year. <s> The ride is also the third-longest roller coaster in North America following The Beast at Kings Island and Fury 325 at Carowinds.
simple: Millennium Force is a steel giga roller coaster built by Intamin at Cedar Point in Sandusky, Ohio, United States. <s> When it opened on May 13, 2000, it was the world's first giga roller coaster at 310 feet tall. <s> It was also the world's tallest and fastest roller coaster for a short time until Steel Dragon 2000 opened later that year. <s> It is also the second longest roller coaster in North America after The Beast at Kings Island.

title: Zac Efron
complex: Zachary David Alexander Efron ( ; born October 18, 1987) is an American actor and singer. <s> He began acting professionally in the early 2000s and rose to prominence in the late 2000s for his leading role as Troy Bolton in the "High School Musical" franchise (2006–2008). <s> During this time, he also starred in the musical film "Hairspray" (2007) and the comedy film "17 Again" (2009). <s> He has since appeared in the films "New Year's Eve" (2011), "The Lucky One" (2012), "The Paperboy" (2012), "Neighbors" (2014), "Dirty Grandpa" (2016), "" (2016), "Baywatch" (2017), "The Greatest Showman" (2017) and "Extremely Wicked, Shockingly Evil and Vile" (2019). <s> Efron was born in San Luis Obispo, California, and later moved to Arroyo Grande, California. <s> His father, David Efron, is an electrical engineer at a power station, and his mother, Starla Baskett, is a secretary who worked at the same power plant. <s> Efron has a brother, Dylan, and had, as he has described, a "normal childhood" in a middle-class family. <s> His last name, "Efron" (אפרון), is a Jewish surname, taken from a Biblical place name. <s> Zac has described himself as Jewish; though he was raised in an agnostic household and did not practice religion as a child. <s> "People" magazine reported in 2007 that Efron and Vanessa Hudgens began dating in 2005 during the filming of "High School Musical", although "Us" magazine reported, after the two broke up in December 2010, that they "met in 2005 while making the first "High School Musical" flick, and became a romantic item about two years later." <s> Efron began a romantic relationship with model and entrepreneur Sami Miró in September 2014.
simple: Zachary David Alexander "Zac" Efron (18 October 1987) is an American actor and singer. <s> He is most famous for his role in the "High School Musical" series. <s> He also starred in the movies "Hairspray", "17 Again" and Charlie St. Cloud. <s> His mother, Starla Baskett, is a former secretary and his father, David is engineer. <s> He has a little brother, Dylan (1991). <s> He was dating Vanessa Anne Hudgens, his co-star from "High School Musical".

title: Johnny Kemp
complex: Johnny Kemp (August 2, 1959 – April 16, 2015) was a Bahamian singer, songwriter, and record producer. <s> He began his career as a songwriter in late 1979 and is perhaps best known for his solo work, including his single "Just Got Paid" (1988), which was nominated for a Grammy Award for Best R&B Song in 1989. <s> Kemp began singing in nightclubs in the Bahamas at age 13. <s> He moved to Harlem, New York in 1979 with the band Kinky Fox. <s> In the early 1980s, Kemp became a successful session musician and songwriter, singing backup for the B. B. & Q. Band on their 1982 album "All Night Long" (on which he co-wrote several tracks) and for Change on their 1982 album "Sharing Your Love" (on which he co-wrote "Take You To Heaven"). <s> He also appeared on the obscure Network LP I Need You in 1984, where he had lead vocals on the song "Cover Girl", later re-recorded for his self-titled debut solo album. <s> Kemp was found dead on April 16, 2015 off the coast of Montego Bay, according to Jamaican police. <s> He was 55 years old. <s> Police believe he was walking on some rocks, lost his balance, fell, hit his head, and then drowned; he had been seen earlier that day in the area. <s> He was scheduled to be on the Tom Joyner Foundation-hosted annual "Fantastic Voyage" cruise as a performer when his body was found; reports state he did not board the ship. <s> He is survived by his wife, Deidre Fisher-Kemp, and their two sons.
simple: Jonathan "Johnny" Kemp (2 August 1959 – 16 April 2015) was a Bahamian singer-songwriter and record producer. <s> His best known song is "Just Got Paid", which he got a Grammy Award nomination. <s> He began singing at nightclubs in the Bahamas at 13. <s> In 1979, he moved to New York City, New York in the United States and later signed with Columbia Records. <s> Kemp was found dead on 16 April 2015 on a beach in Montego Bay, St. James, Jamaica. <s> He was 55 and is believed to have fallen, hit his head on some rocks and drowned. <s> He was married and had two sons.

title: 1981–85 Nordic Football Championship
complex: The 1981–85 Nordic Football Championship was the 13th Nordic Football Championship staged. <s> Four Nordic countries participated: Denmark, Finland, Norway and Sweden. <s> Denmark won the tournament, its third Nordic Championship win.
simple: The 1981–85 Nordic Football Championship was the 13th Nordic Football Championship. <s> Four Nordic countries were in the tournament, Denmark, Finland, Norway and Sweden. <s> Denmark ended up winning their 3rd title.

title: East River
complex: The East River is a salt water tidal estuary in New York City. <s> The waterway, which is actually not a river despite its name, connects Upper New York Bay on its south end to Long Island Sound on its north end. <s> It separates the borough of Queens on Long Island from the Bronx on the North American mainland, and also divides Manhattan from Queens and Brooklyn, which are also on Long Island. <s> Because of its connection to Long Island Sound, it was once also known as the "Sound River".
simple: The East River is a tidal strait in New York City. <s> It connects Upper New York Bay on its south end to Long Island Sound on its north end. <s> It separates Long Island, including the boroughs of Queens and Brooklyn, from the island of Manhattan and the Bronx.

title: Heliocentrism
complex: Heliocentrism is the astronomical model in which the Earth and planets revolve around the Sun at the center of the Solar System. <s> Historically, heliocentrism was opposed to geocentrism, which placed the Earth at the center. <s> The notion that the Earth revolves around the Sun had been proposed as early as the 3rd century BC by Aristarchus of Samos, but at least in the medieval world, Aristarchus's heliocentrism attracted little attention—possibly because of the loss of scientific works of the Hellenistic Era. <s> It was not until the 16th century that a mathematical model of a heliocentric system was presented, by the Renaissance mathematician, astronomer, and Catholic cleric Nicolaus Copernicus, leading to the Copernican Revolution. <s> In the following century, Johannes Kepler introduced elliptical orbits, and Galileo Galilei presented supporting observations made using a telescope. <s> Nicolaus Copernicus in his "De revolutionibus orbium coelestium" ("On the revolution of heavenly spheres", first printed in 1543 in Nuremberg), presented a discussion of a heliocentric model of the universe in much the same way as Ptolemy in the 2nd century had presented his geocentric model in his "Almagest". <s> Copernicus discussed the philosophical implications of his proposed system, elaborated it in geometrical detail, used selected astronomical observations to derive the parameters of his model, and wrote astronomical tables which enabled one to compute the past and future positions of the stars and planets.
simple: Heliocentrism is the idea that the Earth and other planets revolve around the Sun, which is the center of the solar system. <s> Many people proposed heliocentrism, such as Aristarchus of Samos from ancient Greece, but Nicolaus Copernicus was the first to think of good reasons why it is true. <s> Other astronomers who made further advances after Copernicus were Johannes Kepler and Galileo Galilei. <s> Copernicus explained why these things happen in 1543, when he published the book "De revolutionibus orbium coelestium" ("On the revolutions of the heavenly spheres").

title: June Brown
complex: June Muriel Brown, (born 16 February 1927) is an English actress, known for her role as Dot Cotton in the BBC soap opera "EastEnders" from 1985 onwards. <s> In 2005, she won Best Actress at the Inside Soap Awards, and in the same year, also received the Lifetime Achievement award at the British Soap Awards.
simple: June Muriel Brown, MBE (born 16 February 1927) is an English actress. <s> She is known for her role as Dot Cotton in the BBC soap opera "EastEnders" since 1985.

title: Diocese of Truro
complex: The Diocese of Truro (established 1876) is a Church of England diocese in the Province of Canterbury which covers Cornwall, the Isles of Scilly and a small part of Devon. <s> The bishop's seat is at Truro Cathedral. <s> The diocese's area is that of the county of Cornwall, including the Isles of Scilly, as well as two parishes in neighbouring Devon (St Giles on the Heath and Virginstow). <s> It was formed on 15 December 1876 from the Archdeaconry of Cornwall in the Diocese of Exeter. <s> It is, therefore, one of the younger dioceses. <s> The Christian faith, however, has been present in the region since at least the 4th century – more than 100 years before there was an Archbishop of Canterbury. <s> Many of the communities in the diocese, as well as the parish churches, bear a Celtic saint's name, which is a reminder of the links with other Celtic lands, especially Ireland, Wales and Brittany.
simple: The Diocese of Truro is a Church of England diocese in the Province of Canterbury. <s> The area included in the diocese is that of the county of Cornwall including the Isles of Scilly. <s> It was formed in 1876 from the western parts of the Diocese of Exeter and the first bishop was appointed in 1877. <s> The Christian faith has been alive in the region since at least the 4th century AD. <s> Many of the communities in the diocese, as well as the parish churches, bear a Celtic saint's name, which is a reminder of the links with other Celtic lands.

title: 2019 El Paso shooting
complex: A mass shooting occurred at a Walmart store in El Paso, Texas, United States, on the morning of August 3, 2019. <s> A gunman shot and killed 22 people and injured 24 others. <s> The Federal Bureau of Investigation is investigating the shooting as an act of domestic terrorism and a possible hate crime. <s> Patrick Wood Crusius was arrested shortly after the shooting started, and was charged with capital murder. <s> A 21-year-old white male, he was last known to have lived in his family's home in Allen, Texas, around 650 mi from El Paso. <s> He graduated in 2017 from Plano Senior High School and was enrolled at Collin College from 2017 until spring 2019. <s> The incident was mentioned by Pope Francis during a speech in St. Peter's Square on August 4, in which he condemned attacks on defenseless people and said he was spiritually close to the victims, the wounded, and the families affected by the attacks that had "bloodied Texas, California, and Ohio". <s> The Gilroy Garlic Festival shooting happened in California around a week before the El Paso shooting, while the 2019 Dayton shooting occurred in Ohio less than 24 hours after.
simple: A mass shooting took place at a Walmart store in El Paso, Texas, United States, on the morning of August 3, 2019. <s> A single gunman killed 22 people and injured 24 more. <s> The FBI is investigating the shooting as an act of domestic terrorism and a possible hate crime. <s> Patrick Wood Crusius, age 21, was arrested shortly after the shooting began and charged with capital murder. <s> The 2019 Dayton shooting occurred the following day.

title: Interest
complex: Interest, in finance and economics, is payment from a borrower or deposit-taking financial institution to a lender or depositor of an amount above repayment of the principal sum (that is, the amount borrowed), at a particular rate. <s> It is distinct from a fee which the borrower may pay the lender or some third party. <s> It is also distinct from dividend which is paid by a company to its shareholders (owners) from its profit or reserve, but not at a particular rate decided beforehand, rather on a pro rata basis as a share in the reward gained by risk taking entrepreneurs when the revenue earned exceeds the total costs. <s> The rate of interest is equal to the interest amount paid or received over a particular period divided by the principal sum borrowed or lent (usually expressed as a percentage). <s> Compound interest means that interest is earned on prior interest in addition to the principal. <s> Due to compounding, the total amount of debt grows exponentially, and its mathematical study led to the discovery of the number "e". <s> In practice, interest is most often calculated on a daily, monthly, or yearly basis, and its impact is influenced greatly by its compounding rate.
simple: Interest is the cost for borrowing money or the payment for lending money. <s> Usually, this is fixed as a percentage of the amount of money borrowed (which is called "interest rate"). <s> This is called compound interest. <s> Compound interest will cause the amount to grow each year.

title: Stratford-upon-Avon
complex: Stratford-upon-Avon , commonly known as just Stratford, is a market town and civil parish in the Stratford-on-Avon District, in the county of Warwickshire, England, on the River Avon, 91 mi north west of London, 22 mi south east of Birmingham, and 8 mi south west of Warwick. <s> The estimated population in 2007 was 25,505, increasing to 27,445 at the 2011 Census.
simple: Stratford-upon-Avon is a town in England. <s> It lies on the River Avon, 22 miles (35 km) south east of Birmingham and 8 miles (13 km) south west of the county town, Warwick.

title: Ross School of Business
complex: The Stephen M. Ross School of Business (Ross) is the business school of the University of Michigan. <s> Numerous publications have ranked the Ross School of Business' Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA), Master of Business Administration (MBA) and Executive Education programs among the top in the country and the world. <s> The school offers bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees, as well as an executive education program. <s> Ross also offers dual degrees with other University of Michigan colleges and schools.
simple: The Ross School of Business is the business school of the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor. <s> Ross offers undergraduate, graduate, and doctoral degrees, as well as an executive education program. <s> Ross also offers dual degrees with the colleges and schools of urban planning, engineering, medicine, law, education, nursing, information, music, and School of Natural Resources and Environment (SNRE).

title: Discography
complex: Discography is the study and cataloging of published sound recordings, often by specified artists or within identified musical genres. <s> The exact information included varies depending on the type and scope of the discography, but a discography entry for a specific recording will often list such details as the names of the artists involved, the time and place of the recording, the title of the piece performed, release dates, chart positions, and sales figures. <s> The term "discography" was popularized in the 1930s by collectors of jazz records. <s> Jazz fans did research and self-published discographies about when jazz records were made and what musicians were on the records, as record companies did not commonly include that information on or with the records at that time. <s> Two early jazz discographies were "Rhythm on Record" by Hilton Schleman and "Hot Discography" by Charles Delaunay.
simple: Discography is the study and listing of sound recordings. <s> The term "discography" became popular in the 1930s by collectors of jazz records. <s> Jazz fans did research and self-published discographies about when jazz records were made and what musicians were on the records, as record companies did not commonly include that information on/with the records at that time.

title: Potomac, Maryland
complex: Potomac is a census-designated place (CDP) in Montgomery County, Maryland, United States, named for the nearby Potomac River. <s> In 2013, CNNMoney listed Potomac as the most affluent town with more than 25,000 residents in the United States, based on median household income. <s> Potomac is also the seventh-most top-educated American small town according to "Forbes". <s> "Bloomberg Businessweek" labeled Potomac as the twenty-ninth-richest zip code in the United States in 2011, stating that it had the largest population of any U.S. town with a median income of more than $240,000. <s> In 2012, The Higley Elite 100 published a list of highest-income neighborhoods by mean household income, which included four neighborhoods in Potomac; one of these neighborhoods, "Carderock-The Palisades" was ranked the highest-income neighborhood in the United States, followed by "Beverly Hills-North of Sunset" in Beverly Hills, California, and "Swinks Mill-Dominion Reserve" of McLean, Virginia. <s> More recently, two Potomac neighborhoods were ranked among the ten wealthiest neighborhoods in the country by CNBC in 2014. <s> In 2018, data from the American Community Survey revealed that Potomac was the sixth-wealthiest city in the United States. <s> Many Potomac residents work in nearby Washington, D.C.
simple: Potomac is a census-designated place (CDP) in Montgomery County, Maryland, United States, named for the nearby Potomac River. <s> In 2013, CNNMoney listed Potomac as the most affluent town in all the United States based on median household income. <s> Potomac is also the seventh-most top-educated American small town according to "Forbes". <s> In 2018, data from the American Community Survey revealed that Potomac was the sixth-wealthiest city in the United States.

title: Palau at the Olympics
complex: Palau had its debut at the Summer Olympic Games in 2000 in Sydney. <s> Palau has not yet participated in any Winter Olympic Games.
simple: Palau's team first competed at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney.

title: Yamato Province
complex: Yamato Province (大和国 , Yamato no Kuni ) was a province of Japan, located in Kinai, corresponding to present-day Nara Prefecture in Honshū. <s> It was also called Washū (和州 ) . <s> Yamato consists of two characters, 大 "great", and 和 "Wa". <s> At first, the name was written with one different character , but due to its offensive connotation, for about ten years after 737, this was revised to use more desirable characters (see Names of Japan). <s> The final revision was made in the second year of the Tenpyō-hōji era (c. 758). <s> It is classified as a great province in the "Engishiki". <s> The battleship "Yamato", the flagship of the Japanese Combined Fleet during World War II, was named after this ancient province. <s> The provincial capital was Wakigami in Katsujō District (modern northeastern Gose), but accompanying the Heijō-kyō capital transfer, it was moved to Takaichi District (Jōroku in modern Kashihara, where the Ōgaru and Ishikawa towns meet, called "Karu no Chimata"). <s> The exact location of the capital is guessed at by various sources, but not known for sure. <s> There was no shugo's mansion; the Kōfuku-ji played that role.
simple: Yamato Province (大和国, Yamato no Kuni) was an old province of Japan in the area of Nara Prefecture on the island of Honshū. <s> It was also called Washū (和州). <s> The battleship "Yamato" was named after this ancient province. <s> The "Yamato" was the flagship of the Imperial Japanese Navy fleet during World War II, <s> The ancient capital city of the province was Wakigami in Katsujō District. <s> When the capital of Japan was moved to Heijō-kyō, the capital of the province was established in Takaichi District. <s> The exact locations are not known.

title: Mill Valley, California
complex: Mill Valley is a city in Marin County, California, United States, located about 14 mi north of San Francisco via the Golden Gate Bridge and 52 miles from Napa Valley. <s> The population was 13,903 at the 2010 census.
simple: Mill Valley is a city of Marin County in the state of California, United States. <s> It is about 14 mi north of San Francisco via the Golden Gate Bridge. <s> The population was 13,903 at the 2010 census.

title: Jan de Graaff
complex: Jan de Graaff (21 April 1943 – 30 March 2014) was a Dutch television journalist. <s> He started his job in 1962 for the news agency "UPI", from 1966 he worked for VARA on radio and television, including as editor of "Behind the News". <s> He was born in The Hague, South Holland. <s> Jan de Graaff died on 30 March 2014 in Tilburg, North Brabant. <s> He was 70 years old.
simple: Jan de Graaff (21 April 1943 – 30 March 2014) was a Dutch television journalist. <s> He started his job in 1962 for the news agency "UPI", from 1966 he worked for VARA on radio and television, including as editor of "Behind the News". <s> He was born in The Hague, South Holland. <s> Jan de Graaff died on 30 March 2014 in Tilburg, North Brabant. <s> He was 70 years old.

title: Stratovarius
complex: Stratovarius is a Finnish heavy metal band that formed in 1984. <s> Since their formation, they have released 15 studio albums, 4 DVDs and 5 live albums.
simple: Stratovarius is a Finnish power metal band that formed in 1983.

title: Shyok River
complex: The Shyok River ( ; literally ""The River of Death"" in Yarkandi Uyghur) flows through northern Ladakh in India and the Ghangche District of Gilgit–Baltistan of Pakistan spanning some 550 km . <s> The Shyok River, a tributary of the Indus River, originates from the Rimo Glacier, one of the tongues of Siachen Glacier. <s> The river widens at the confluence with the Nubra River. <s> The alignment of the Shyok river is very unusual, originating from the Rimo glacier, it flows in a southeasterly direction and, joining the Pangong range, it takes a northwestern turn, flowing parallel to its previous path. <s> The Shyok flows in a wide valley, suddenly entering a narrow gorge near Yagulung , continuing through Bogdang, Turtuk and Tyakshi before crossing into Pakistan. <s> The Shyok joins the Indus at Keris, to the east of the town of Skardu. <s> The Nubra river, originating from the Siachen glacier, also behaves like the Shyok. <s> Before Tirkit, the SE flowing river Nubra takes a NW turn on meeting the river Shyok. <s> The similarity in the courses of these two important rivers probably indicates a series of paleo fault lines trending NW-SE in delimiting the upper courses of the rivers. <s> The importance of the Indus and the Shyok rivers is in the deposition of the thick Quaternary sediments—a treasure trove for geology researchers.
simple: The Shyok River is a river flowing through Disputed Area Ladakh and the Northern Areas of Pakistan (Ghanche District). <s> Shyok river (a tributary of the Indus) originates from the Rimo glacier, one of the tongues of Siachen Glacier and becomes very wide at the confluence with the Nubra River (a tributary of Shyok, originating from Siachen Glacier). <s> The alignment of the Shyok river is very unusual, originating from the Rimo glacier it flows in a SE direction and at joining the Pangong range it takes a NW turn and flows parallel to its previous path. <s> The Shyok flowing in a wide valley suddenly enters a narrow gorge after Chalunka and then joins the Indus at Skardu (Pakistan). <s> The Nubra river originating from the Siachen glacier also behaves like the Shyok, before Tirit the SE flowing river takes a NW turn on meeting the river Shyok. <s> The similarity in the courses of these two important rivers probably indicates a series of palaeo fault lines trending NW-SE in delimiting the upper courses of the rivers. <s> The importance of the Indus River and the Shyok rivers is in the deposition of a huge thickness of Quaternary sediments a treasure trove for geology researchers.

title: P. J. Patterson
complex: Percival Noel James Patterson, ON, PC, QC (born 10 April 1935), is a Jamaican former politician who served as the sixth Prime Minister of Jamaica from 1992 to 2005. <s> He was the leader of the People's National Party from 1992 to 2005, and the Member of Parliament (MP) for the constituency of Westmoreland South Eastern from 1970 to 1980 (when he lost to Euphemia Williams of the Jamaica Labour Party) and again from 1989 to 1993. <s> Following a constituency reorganization, he served as the MP for Westmoreland Eastern from 1993 to 2005. <s> He retired from all of these positions in March 2005. <s> He was married to Shirley Field-Ridley (d. 1982) with whom he had two children, Richard and Sharon.
simple: Percival Noel James Patterson, ON, PC, QC (born 10 April 1935), is a Jamaican politician. <s> He served as the sixth Prime Minister of Jamaica from 1992 to 2006. <s> He was the leader of the People's National Party from 1992 to 2006 and as the Member of Parliament (MP) from 1970 to 1980 when he lost to the Jamaica Labour Party Euphemia Williams, and again from 1989 to 1993. <s> He served as the MP for Westmoreland Eastern from 1993 to 2006. <s> He retired in March 2006.

title: Logan County, Nebraska
complex: Logan County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 763. <s> Its county seat is Stapleton. <s> Logan County was formed in 1885. <s> It was named for Civil War General John A. Logan.
simple: Logan County is a county in the U.S. state of Nebraska. <s> As of the 2010 census, 763 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Stapleton. <s> It was founded in 1885.

title: University of Salamanca
complex: The University of Salamanca is a Spanish higher education institution, located in the city of Salamanca, west of Madrid, in the autonomous community of Castile and León. <s> It was founded in 1134 and given the Royal charter of foundation by King Alfonso IX in 1218. <s> It is the oldest university in the Spanish-speaking world and the third oldest university in the entire world still in operation.
simple: The University of Salamanca is a Spanish higher education institution. <s> It is in the town of Salamanca, west of Madrid, in the autonomous community of Castile and León. <s> The University of Salamanca was one of 100 finalists for the 12 Treasures of Spain in 2007. <s> It was established in 1134 and given the Royal charter of establishment by King Alfonso IX in 1218.

title: Gary Thorne
complex: Gary Thorne (born June 9, 1948) is the lead play-by-play announcer for MASN. <s> He has also worked for ESPN and ABC, including National Hockey League, Major League Baseball, college football, and the Frozen Four hockey tournament. <s> He also works for World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE), where he is the narrator for the "WrestleMania Rewind" program on its WWE Network streaming video service.
simple: Gary Thorne (born June 9, 1948, in Bangor, Maine) is an American sportscaster. <s> He also calls Little League World Series games for ABC and ESPN and some Major League Baseball games for ESPN.

title: Frances Bean Cobain
complex: Frances Bean Cobain (born August 18, 1992) is an American visual artist and model. <s> She is the only child of Nirvana frontman Kurt Cobain and Hole frontwoman Courtney Love. <s> Frances Cobain was born on August 18, 1992, at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles, California. <s> She was named after Frances McKee, the guitarist for the Scottish indie pop duo The Vaselines.
simple: Frances Bean Cobain (born August 18, 1992) is an American visual artist and former model. <s> She is the only child of Kurt Cobain and Courtney Love. <s> She was born in Los Angeles.

title: Baptismal font
complex: A baptismal font is an article of church furniture used for baptism.
simple: A baptismal font is a permanent or semi-permanent basin where baptisms are performed.

title: Ringwoodite
complex: Ringwoodite is a high-pressure phase of MgSiO (magnesium silicate) formed at high temperatures and pressures of the Earth's mantle between 525 and depth. <s> It is polymorphous with the olivine phase forsterite (a magnesium iron silicate). <s> Ringwoodite is notable for being able to contain hydroxide ions (oxygen and hydrogen atoms bound together) within its structure. <s> Combined with evidence of its occurrence deep in the Earth's mantle, this suggests that there is from one to three times the world ocean's equivalent of water in the mantle transition zone from 410 to 660 km deep. <s> This mineral was first identified in the Tenham meteorite in 1969, and is inferred to be present in large quantities in the Earth’s mantle.
simple: It is a type of olivine which is formed at high temperatures and pressures in the Earth's mantle between 525 and 660 km deep. <s> Olivine is a magnesium iron silicate. <s> Ringwoodite is notable because to contains hydroxide ions (oxygen and hydrogen atoms bound together) in its structure. <s> This suggests that there is from one to three times the world ocean's equivalent of water in the mantle's transition zone from 410 to 660 km deep. <s> This mineral was first identified in a meteorite in 1969. <s> It may be present in large quantity in the Earth’s mantle.

title: Johnston's African dormouse
complex: The Johnston's African dormouse ("Graphiurus johnstoni") is a species of rodent in the family Gliridae. <s> It is found in Malawi, Zambia, and Zimbabwe. <s> Its natural habitat is moist savanna.
simple: The Johnston's African Dormouse ("Graphiurus johnstoni") is a species of rodent in the Gliridae family. <s> It is found in Malawi, Zambia, and Zimbabwe. <s> Its natural habitat is moist savanna.

title: Elmore Leonard
complex: Elmore John Leonard Jr. (October 11, 1925August 20, 2013) was an American novelist, short story writer, and screenwriter. <s> His earliest novels, published in the 1950s, were Westerns, but he went on to specialize in crime fiction and suspense thrillers, many of which have been adapted into motion pictures. <s> Among his best-known works are "Get Shorty", "Out of Sight", "Swag", "Hombre", "Mr. Majestyk", and "Rum Punch" (adapted as the film "Jackie Brown"). <s> Leonard's writings include short stories that became the films "3:10 to Yuma" and "The Tall T", as well as the FX television series "Justified". <s> Leonard was born in New Orleans, Louisiana, the son of Flora Amelia (née Rive) and Elmore John Leonard, Sr. <s> Because his father worked as a site locator for General Motors, the family moved frequently for several years. <s> In 1934, the family settled in Detroit. <s> He married Beverly Clare Cline in 1949, and they had five children together—two daughters and three sons—before divorcing in 1977. <s> His second marriage in 1979, to Joan Leanne Lancaster (aka Joan Shepard), ended with her death in 1993. <s> Later that same year, he married Christine Kent and they divorced in 2012. <s> Leonard spent the last years of his life with his family in Oakland County, Michigan. <s> He suffered a stroke on July 29, 2013. <s> Initial reports stated that Leonard was recovering but on August 20, 2013, Leonard died at his home in the Detroit suburb of Bloomfield Hills of stroke complications. <s> He was 87 years old. <s> Leonard is survived by his five children, 13 grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
simple: Elmore John Leonard, Jr. (October 11, 1925 – August 20, 2013) was an American novelist and screenwriter. <s> His best-known works are "Get Shorty", "Out of Sight", "Hombre", "Mr. Majestyk", and "Rum Punch". <s> He was also writing for the TV series "Justified". <s> Leonard was born on October 11, 1925 in New Orleans, Louisiana. <s> Leonard was married to Beverly Cline from 1949 until they divorced in 1977. <s> He had five children with Cline. <s> Then he was married to Joan Shepard from 1979 until her death in 1993. <s> Leonard spent the last years of his life with his family in Oakland County, Michigan. <s> He suffered a stroke on July 29, 2013. <s> Reports stated that Leonard was recovering from the stroke. <s> On August 20, 2013, Leonard died at his home in Bloomfield Hills (a Detroit suburb) of complications from the stroke. <s> He was 87 years old.

title: Saltsjöbaden
complex: Saltsjöbaden is a locality in Nacka Municipality, Stockholm County, Sweden with 9,491 inhabitants in 2010. <s> It lies on the Baltic Sea coast.
simple: Saltsjöbaden is a locality in Nacka Municipality, Stockholm County, Sweden. <s> In 2010, 9,491 people lived there. <s> It is located on the Baltic Sea coast.

title: Germano Boettcher Sobrinho
complex: Germano Boettcher Sobrinho (14 March 1911 – 9 June 1977) was a Brazilian football player. <s> He has played for Brazil national team.
simple: Germano Boettcher Sobrinho (born 14 March, 1911) is a former Brazilian football player. <s> He has played for Brazil national team.

title: Liceo Agustín Ross Edwards
complex: Liceo Agustín Ross Edwards is a Chilean public (municipal) high school located in Pichilemu, Cardenal Caro Province. <s> It is named after Agustín Ross Edwards, a Chilean politician and known for building the historic centre of the town of Pichilemu. <s> The high school was created in 1979, and works as a Humanistic Scientific high school. <s> The high school has employed the Complete Scholar Journey since 1998. <s> The Liceo Agustín Ross Edwards' principal is Juan Antonio Farías Catalán. <s> As of 2012, LARE had 562 students, and 38 teachers. <s> The president of the parents' center ("centro de padres") is Marco Antonio Salgado Contreras, and the president of the students' center ("centro de alumnos") is Matías Lizana Calderón.
simple: Agustín Ross High School, Liceo Agustín Ross Edwards or just L.A.R.E. is a Chilean public high school located in the coastal town of Pichilemu. <s> It is named after Agustín Ross Edwards, a Chilean politician and known by his works in the city. <s> The High School was created in 1979. <s> As of 1998, the High School started using the Complete Scholar Journey . <s> Has 562 students and 39 teachers.

title: La Dolce Vita
complex: La Dolce Vita (] ; Italian for "the sweet life" or "the good life") is a 1960 Italian drama film directed and co-written by Federico Fellini. <s> The film follows Marcello Rubini (Marcello Mastroianni), a journalist writing for gossip magazines, over seven days and nights on his journey through the "sweet life" of Rome in a fruitless search for love and happiness. <s> "La Dolce Vita" won the "Palme d'Or" (Golden Palm) at the 1960 Cannes Film Festival and the Oscar for Best Costumes.
simple: La Dolce Vita is a 1960 Italian comedy-drama movie. <s> It follows Marcello Rubini, a gossip columnist, across seven days and nights in Rome. <s> Marcello Mastroianni plays the gossip columnist.

title: Woodward County, Oklahoma
complex: Woodward County is a county located in the U.S. state of Oklahoma. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 20,081. <s> Its county seat is Woodward.
simple: Woodward County is a county in the U.S. state of Oklahoma. <s> Its county seat is Woodward.

title: Prefectures of Greece
complex: During the first administrative division of independent Greece in 1833–1836 and again from 1845 until their abolition with the Kallikratis reform in 2010, the prefectures were the country's main administrative unit. <s> They are now defunct, and have been approximately replaced by regional units.
simple: The land of Greece was divided in Prefectures from 1833 to 1836. <s> It was divided again from 1845 until the Kallikratis reform in 2010.

title: Pennsylvania Route 274
complex: Pennsylvania Route 274 (PA 274) is a 44 mi state highway located in Franklin and Perry Counties in Pennsylvania. <s> The western terminus is at PA 75 in the Fannett Township community of Doylesburg. <s> The eastern terminus is at an interchange with U.S. Route 11 (US 11)/US 15 in Duncannon. <s> PA 274 is a two-lane undivided road that runs through rural areas in the Ridge-and-Valley Appalachians.
simple: Pennsylvania Route 274 (PA 274) is a state highway in Franklin and Perry Counties in Pennsylvania. <s> It is 44 mi long. <s> The western end of the highway is at Pennsylvania Route 75 in Fannett Township, Pennsylvania. <s> The eastern end is at US 11/US 15 in Duncannon.

title: The Edge of Glory
complex: "The Edge of Glory" is a song by American singer Lady Gaga from her second studio album, "Born This Way" (2011). <s> The song was released on May 9, 2011 as the album's third single. <s> Initially released as one of two promotional singles for "Born This Way", it shortly became a single following its success in digital outlets worldwide.
simple: "The Edge of Glory" is a song by American pop singer Lady Gaga from her third album "Born This Way". <s> It was released as the third single from the album on May 17, 2011.

title: Kaltukatjara
complex: Kaltukatjara (Docker River) is a remote Indigenous Australian community in the Northern Territory of Australia. <s> It is southwest of Alice Springs, west of the Stuart Highway, near the Western Australia and Northern Territory border. <s> At the 2006 census, Kaltukatjara had a population of 355. <s> The community is also known as Docker River, which is the European name for the township. <s> It is on a wadi called the Docker Creek on the north side of the west end of the Petermann Ranges in the southwest corner of Northern Territory in Australia. <s> The site that is now Kaltukatjara was originally named Docker River by Ernest Giles during his expedition of 1872. <s> Pastors Duguid and Strehlow surveyed the area in the 1930s with a view to establishing a settlement for the people in the area. <s> It was decided not to proceed with this at that time. <s> During the 30s and 40s Luther(a)n missionaries told the Pitjantjatjara people of the Kaltukatjara area to go to Areyonga (then an outstation of Hermannsburg mission) where they would be supplied with food and clothing. <s> Although many Anangu moved in of their own free will, some stayed in the Petermanns. <s> In the 1960s Areyonga Anangu strongly desired to move back to the area around Docker River and with government assistance a permanent settlement was established there in 1967-8. <s> Over 300 Anangu moved to establish the new settlement. <s> By the proclamation of the Aboriginal Lands Rights (N.T.) Act, 1976, Anangu in the region gained freehold title to these traditional lands an area of 44,970 square kilometres. <s> Kaltukatjara lies on the Tjukaruru Road which becomes the Great Central Road when it crosses into Western Australia 7 kilometres to the west. <s> Before 2008-07-01, Kaltukatjara was served by the Kaltukatjara Community Council, composed of twelve residents who are elected annually. <s> The Council served as the local government and qualified as a "local government area". <s> On 2008-07-01, it became part of the MacDonnell Region. <s> Electricity is provided by 3 diesel power generators. <s> Roads within the township are sealed but the Petermann Road (the main road to the community) is unsealed. <s> There is a Lutheran church with a resident pastor, overseen by the Lutheran Church's Finke River Mission board.
simple: Kaltukatjara (') is a town in the southwest of the Northern Territory of Australia. <s> It is about 670 km southwest of Alice Springs, and 8 km from the border with Western Australia. <s> In the 2006 census, Kaltukatjara had a population of 355. <s> It is also called Docker River in English. <s> The settlement was named "Docker River" after the stream that flows through the community. <s> This stream was given its name by the explorer Ernest Giles when he travelled through the area in 1872. <s> In 1976, the Aboriginal Land Rights Act was passed in the Northern Territory. <s> Kaltukatjara is governed by Kaḻṯukatjara Community Council, a local government council with 12 members. <s> Power is supplied by three large generators. <s> While the roads in the town are sealed, roads out of the town are gravel and can be closed for up to a week if it rains. <s> There is also a Lutheran church.

title: José Marrone
complex: José Carlos Marrone (25 October 1915 in Buenos Aires – 27 June 1990 in Buenos Aires) was an Argentine actor and humorist. <s> His beginning was in vaudeville theaters and the radio; afterwards he hosted several children-oriented TV shows, such as "El Circo de Marrone" (Marrone's Circus), playing the clown character "Pepitito". <s> His recurring catchphrase was "Cheee!" <s> He married twice and had his daughter "Coqui", with his first wife, Rosa. <s> While still married, Marrone fell in love with "Juanita Martínez", but they waited to get together until Rosa died. <s> In 2001, eleven years after Marrone's death, Juanita committed suicide, and her body was found with a picture of Marrone in her hands.
simple: José Carlos Marrone (October 25, 1915 in Buenos Aires – June 27, 1990 in Buenos Aires) was an Argentine actor and comedian. <s> His career began when he performed as a vaudeville in theaters and the radio. <s> He hosted several children-oriented TV shows, such as "El Circo de Marrone" (Marrone's Circus), playing the clown character "Pepitito". <s> His recurring catchphrase was "Cheee!". <s> He married twice and had a daughter, "Coqui", with his first wife, Rosa. <s> Still married, Marrone fell in love with Juanita Martínez, but they waited to get together until Rosa died. <s> In 2001, a decade after Marrone's death, Juanita committed suicide, and her body was found with a picture of Marrone in her hands.

title: Ménil
complex: Ménil is a commune in the Mayenne department in north-western France. <s> Its population in the census of 1999 was of 785 inhabitants.
simple: Ménil is a commune of 785 people (1999).

title: Municipalities of Japan
complex: Japan has three levels of government: national, prefectural, and municipal. <s> The nation is divided into 47 prefectures. <s> Each prefecture consists of numerous municipalities, with 1,719 in total (January 2013 figures) . <s> There are four types of municipalities in Japan: cities, towns, villages and special wards (the "ku" of Tokyo). <s> In Japanese, this system is known as "shikuchōson" (市区町村 ) , where each kanji in the word represents one of the four types of municipalities. <s> Some designated cities also have further administrative subdivisions, also known as wards.
simple: Since the 19th century, Japan has been divided into 47 prefectures; and each prefecture has many districts and municipalities. <s> There is a fourth type of municipality — the 23 special wards of Tokyo. <s> Municipalities in Japan (市区町村, "shikuchōson") are the local governments and sub-divisions of the island nation.

title: Juan Sebastián Verón
complex: Juan Sebastián Verón (] ; born 9 March 1975) is a retired Argentine footballer and current chairman of Estudiantes de La Plata, where he had served as Director of Sports. <s> A former midfielder, Verón's career started in Estudiantes, continued in Argentina's Boca Juniors, and included stints in several clubs in the Italian Serie A (where he won the "Scudetto" with Lazio and with Internazionale, and a UEFA Cup with Parma), and England's Manchester United and Chelsea.
simple: Juan Sebastián Verón (born 9 March 1975) is an Argentine football player.

title: Zlín Z-37
complex: The Zlin Z-37 Čmelák (Czech: "Bumblebee"), also known as LET Z-37 Čmelák is an agricultural aircraft which was manufactured in Czechoslovakia. <s> It is powered by a Soviet-built Ivchenko reciprocating engine.
simple: The Zlín Z-37 Čmelák (Czech: "Bumblebee") is an agricultural aircraft.

title: John Soane
complex: Sir John Soane ( ; né Soan; 10 September 1753 – 20 January 1837) was an English architect who specialised in the Neo-Classical style. <s> The son of a bricklayer, he rose to the top of his profession, becoming professor of architecture at the Royal Academy and an official architect to the Office of Works. <s> He received a knighthood in 1831. <s> In 1792, Soane bought a house at 12 Lincoln's Inn Fields, London. <s> Later purchasing 13 Lincoln's Inn Fields, he used the house as his home and library, but also entertained potential clients in the drawing room. <s> The houses along with 14 Lincoln's Inn Fields, is now Sir John Soane's Museum and is open to the public for free.
simple: Sir John Soane (10 September 1753 – 20 January 1837) was an English architect. <s> He was knighted in 1831. <s> His house in Lincoln's Inn Fields is now Sir John Soane's Museum and is open to the public.

title: Mississippi County, Arkansas
complex: Mississippi County is a county located in the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 46,480. <s> There are two county seats, Blytheville and Osceola. <s> The county was formed on November 1, 1833, and named for the Mississippi River which borders the county to the east. <s> Mississippi County is part of the First Congressional District in Arkansas.
simple: Mississippi County is a county of the U.S. state of Arkansas. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 46,480. <s> There are two county seats, Blytheville and Osceola. <s> The county was founded on November 1, 1833, and named for the Mississippi River which borders the county to the east.

title: Ludwig Rellstab
complex: Heinrich Friedrich Ludwig Rellstab (13 April 179927 November 1860) was a German poet and music critic. <s> He was born and died in Berlin. <s> He was the son of the music publisher and composer Johann Carl Friedrich Rellstab. <s> An able pianist, he published articles in various periodicals, including the influential liberal "Vossische Zeitung", and launched the music journal "Iris im Gebiete der Tonkunst", which was published in Berlin from 1830 to 1841. <s> His outspoken criticism of the influence in Berlin of Gaspare Spontini landed him in jail in 1837. <s> The first seven songs of Franz Schubert's "Schwanengesang" have words by Rellstab, who had left them in 1825 with Beethoven, whose assistant Anton Schindler passed them on to Schubert. <s> His work was also set to music by Franz Liszt. <s> He is also known to have given Beethoven's Piano Sonata No. 14 in C-sharp minor, Op. 27/2, its famous nickname "Moonlight Sonata".
simple: Heinrich Friedrich Ludwig Rellstab (13 April 1799 – 27 November 1860) was a German poet and music critic. <s> He was born and died in Berlin. <s> The first seven songs of Franz Schubert's "Schwanengesang" have words by Rellstab, who had left them in 1825 with Beethoven, whose assistant Anton Schindler passed them on to Schubert. <s> His work was also set to music by Franz Liszt. <s> He is also known to have given Beethoven's Piano Sonata No. 14 in C-sharp minor, Op. 27/2 its famous nickname "Moonlight Sonata".

title: Rafael Sánchez Ferlosio
complex: Rafael Sánchez Ferlosio (4 December 1927 – 1 April 2019) was a Spanish writer. <s> In 2004 he was awarded the Premio Cervantes for his literary oeuvre. <s> He was married to fellow writer Carmen Martín Gaite. <s> Sánchez Ferlosio was born in Rome, Italy. <s> His father, Rafael Sánchez Mazas, a minor writer, was a founder and leader of Falange. <s> Sánchez Ferlosio won the Nadal Award for his novel "El Jarama", a realistic depiction of a weekend party. <s> He contributed to the awakening of Spanish literature after the end of the Civil War, working alongside young writers such as Juan Goytisolo and Ana María Matute. <s> After the success of his first book, he renounced writing for twenty years. <s> He never gave the reason for his silence, but many critics assumed it was a form of silent opposition to the Francoist State. <s> He died in Madrid, aged 91.
simple: Rafael Sánchez Ferlosio (4 December 1927 – 1 April 2019) was a Spanish writer. <s> In 2004, he was awarded the Premio Cervantes for his written work in the Spanish language. <s> Sánchez Ferlosio was married to writer Carmen Martín Gaite. <s> Sánchez Ferlosio Rome, Lazio, Italy. <s> His mother was Italian. <s> His Spanish father, Rafael Sánchez Mazas (1894–1966), was a nationalist writer and a leader of the Falange. <s> He also won a Premio Nadal for his novel "El Jarama" (1955). <s> He helped writing in Spain to become popular again after the Spanish Civil War, along with other young writers such as Juan Goytisolo and Ana María Matute. <s> He later stopped writing for around twenty years. <s> He never said publicly why this was but critics have said it may have been a silent dislike of the Spanish military dictatorship of Francisco Franco. <s> Sánchez Ferlosio died in Madrid on 1 April 2019, at the age of 91.

title: George E. R. Kinnear II
complex: George Espy Ridgeway "Gus" Kinnear II(January 12, 1928 – August 9, 2015) was a four star admiral in the United States Navy who served as U.S. Military Representative, NATO Military Committee from 1981 to 1982. <s> He was born in Mounds, Oklahoma. <s> He attended George Washington University and Stanford University. <s> Kinnear died on August 9, 2015, at the age of 87. <s> Kinnear was promoted to Rear Admiral and returned to sea as commander of Carrier Group Two in 1974-75, serving in the Tonkin Gulf, where he implemented the first digital sea-borne carrier battle group C4ISR system code named "Outlaw Hawk".
simple: George E. R. "Gus" Kinnear II (January 12, 1928 – August 9, 2015) was a American four star admiral in the United States Navy. <s> He served as U.S. Military Representative, NATO Military Committee from 1981 to 1982. <s> He was born in Mounds, Oklahoma. <s> He attended George Washington University and Stanford University. <s> Kinnear died in York Harbor, Maine at the age of 87.

title: Old College, University of Edinburgh
complex: Old College is a building of the University of Edinburgh, Scotland. <s> It is located on South Bridge, and presently houses parts of the University's administration, the University of Edinburgh School of Law, and the Talbot Rice Gallery.
simple: Old College is a building in Edinburgh, United Kingdom. <s> It is part of University of Edinburgh.

title: Lake Baikal
complex: Lake Baikal ( ; Russian: , ; , "Baigal nuur"; , "Baigal nuur", etymologically meaning, in Mongolian, "the Nature Lake") is a rift lake in Russia, located in southern Siberia, between Irkutsk Oblast to the northwest and the Buryat Republic to the southeast. <s> Lake Baikal is the largest freshwater lake by volume in the world, containing 22–23% of the world's fresh surface water. <s> With 23615.39 km3 of fresh water, it contains more water than the North American Great Lakes combined. <s> With a maximum depth of 1642 m , Baikal is the world's deepest lake. <s> It is considered among the world's clearest lakes and is considered the world's oldest lake – at 25–30 million years. <s> It is the seventh-largest lake in the world by surface area. <s> Like Lake Tanganyika, Lake Baikal was formed as an ancient rift valley, having the typical long, crescent shape with a surface area of 31722 km2 . <s> Baikal is home to thousands of species of plants and animals, many of which exist nowhere else in the world. <s> The lake was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996. <s> It is also home to Buryat tribes who reside on the eastern side of Lake Baikal, raising goats, camels, cattle, sheep, and horses, where the mean temperature varies from a winter minimum of -19 °C to a summer maximum of 14 °C . <s> Lake Baikal is in a rift valley, created by the Baikal Rift Zone, where the Earth's crust is slowly pulling apart. <s> At 636 km long and 79 km wide, Lake Baikal has the largest surface area of any freshwater lake in Asia, at 31722 km2 , and is the deepest lake in the world at 1642 m . <s> The bottom of the lake is 1186.5 m below sea level, but below this lies some 7 km of sediment, placing the rift floor some 8 - below the surface, the deepest continental rift on Earth. <s> In geological terms, the rift is young and active – it widens about 2 cm (0.8 in) per year. <s> The fault zone is also seismically active; hot springs occur in the area and notable earthquakes happen every few years. <s> The lake is divided into three basins: North, Central, and South, with depths about 900 m , 1600 m , and 1400 m , respectively. <s> Fault-controlled accommodation zones rising to depths about 300 m separate the basins. <s> The North and Central basins are separated by Academician Ridge, while the area around the Selenga Delta and the Buguldeika Saddle separates the Central and South basins. <s> The lake drains into the Angara tributary of the Yenisei. <s> Notable landforms include Cape Ryty on Baikal's northwest coast. <s> Baikal's age is estimated at 25–30 million years, making it the most ancient lake in geological history. <s> It is unique among large, high-latitude lakes, as its sediments have not been scoured by overriding continental ice sheets. <s> Russian, U.S., and Japanese cooperative studies of deep-drilling core sediments in the 1990s provide a detailed record of climatic variation over the past 6.7 million years. <s> Longer and deeper sediment cores are expected in the near future. <s> Lake Baikal is the only confined freshwater lake in which direct and indirect evidence of gas hydrates exists. <s> The lake is completely surrounded by mountains. <s> The Baikal Mountains on the north shore, the Barguzin Range on the northeastern shore, and the taiga are technically protected as a national park. <s> It contains 27 islands; the largest, Olkhon, is 72 km long and is the third-largest lake-bound island in the world. <s> The lake is fed by as many as 330 inflowing rivers. <s> The main ones draining directly into Baikal are the Selenga River, the Barguzin River, the Upper Angara River, the Turka River, the Sarma River, and the Snezhnaya River. <s> It is drained through a single outlet, the Angara River. <s> Lake Baikal is rich in biodiversity. <s> It hosts more than 1,000 species of plants and 2,500 species of animals based on current knowledge, but the actual figures for both groups are believed to be significantly higher. <s> More than 80% of the animals are endemic. <s> The Baikal seal or "nerpa" ("Pusa sibirica") is found throughout Lake Baikal. <s> It is one of only three entirely freshwater seal populations in the world, the other two being subspecies of ringed seals. <s> Fewer than 65 native fish species occur in the lake basin, but more than half of these are endemic. <s> The families Abyssocottidae (deep-water sculpins), Comephoridae (golomyankas or Baikal oilfish), and Cottocomephoridae (Baikal sculpins) are entirely restricted to the lake basin. <s> All these are part of the Cottoidea and are typically less than 20 cm long. <s> Of particular note are the two species of golomyanka ("Comephorus baicalensis" and "C. dybowskii"). <s> These long-finned, translucent fish typically live in open water at depths of 100 - , but occur both shallower and much deeper. <s> Together with certain abyssocottid sculpins, they are the deepest living freshwater fish in the world, occurring to near the bottom of Lake Baikal. <s> The golomyankas are the primary prey of the Baikal seal and represent the largest fish biomass in the lake. <s> Beyond members of Cottoidea, there are few endemic fish species in the lake basin. <s> The most important local species for fisheries is the omul ("Coregonus migratorius"), an endemic whitefish. <s> It is caught, smoked, and then sold widely in markets around the lake. <s> Also, a second endemic whitefish inhabits the lake, "C. baicalensis".
simple: Lake Baikal is a huge lake in Siberia, Russia. <s> It is the biggest fresh water reservoir in the world. <s> It holds about 20% of the world's unfrozen surface fresh water, <s> Lake Baikal fills an ancient rift valley, just as Lake Tanganyika does in East Africa. <s> It is home to more than 1,700 species of plants and animals, two-thirds of which can be found nowhere else in the world. <s> The lake is a UNESCO World Heritage Site. <s> At the Baikal Rift Zone, the Earth's crust pulls apart. <s> Baikal is about 636 km long. <s> It is the deepest lake in the world at 1642 m. <s> The bottom of the lake is 1186.5 m below sea level, but below this lies some 7 km of sediment. <s> This means the rift floor is 8 - below the surface: the deepest continental rift on Earth. <s> In geological terms, the rift is young and active – it widens about two cm per year. <s> The fault zone is also seismically active; there are hot springs in the area and notable earthquakes every few years. <s> At its deepest point, it is 1700 m deep. <s> Baikal's age is 25–30 million years: it is one of the oldest lakes. <s> It is unique among large, high-latitude lakes, because its sediments have not been scoured by overriding continental ice sheets. <s> U.S. and Russian studies of core sediment in the 1990s gave a detailed record of climatic variation over the past 250,000 years. <s> Longer and deeper sediment cores are expected soon. <s> Lake Baikal is the only confined freshwater lake in which evidence of gas hydrates exists. <s> The lake is completely surrounded by mountains. <s> The Baikal Mountains on the north shore and the taiga are protected as a national park. <s> It has 27 islands; the largest, Olkhon, is 72 km long and is the third-largest lake-bound island in the world. <s> The lake is fed by as many as 330 inflowing rivers. <s> It is drained through a single outlet, the Angara River. <s> Over 60% of animals are endemic; that means of 52 species of fish 27 are endemic. <s> Baikal also hosts a species of seals, Baikal seal or "nerpa". <s> The omul fish ("Coregonus autumnalis migratorius") is local to Lake Baikal. <s> It is fished, smoked, and sold on all markets around the lake.

title: Arçonnay
complex: Arçonnay is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Arçonnay is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Jon Batiste
complex: Jonathan Batiste (born November 11, 1986) is an American musician, bandleader, and television personality. <s> He has recorded and performed with artists in various genres of music (Stevie Wonder, Prince, Willie Nelson, Lenny Kravitz, Ed Sheeran, and Mavis Staples), released recordings consistently since 2005 and performed in more than 40 countries. <s> Batiste regularly tours with his band Stay Human, and appears with them nightly as Bandleader and Musical Director on "The Late Show with Stephen Colbert". <s> Batiste also serves as the Music Director of The Atlantic and the Creative Director of the National Jazz Museum in Harlem.
simple: Jonathan "Jon" Batiste (born November 11, 1986) is an American singer, multi-instrumentalist, educator, and bandleader. <s> Batiste is known for being the music director and bandleader for "The Late Show with Stephen Colbert".

title: Melissa Villaseñor
complex: Melissa Villaseñor (born October 9, 1987) is an American actress, stand-up comedian and impressionist. <s> She is a cast member on "Saturday Night Live", having joined in the forty-second season in 2016. <s> Her other credits include voice work on several episodes of "OK K.O.!
simple: Melissa Villaseñor (born October 9, 1987) is an American actress, stand-up comedian, and impressionist. <s> She is currently a cast member on "Saturday Night Live" since 2016, making her the first Latina on "SNL".

title: Adam Deadmarsh
complex: Adam Richard Deadmarsh (born May 10, 1975) is a former Canadian professional ice hockey player who played in the NHL with the Quebec Nordiques, Colorado Avalanche and the Los Angeles Kings. <s> Deadmarsh was later a video coordinator and assistant coach with the Avalanche, before concussion issues forced him to step down after the season, nine years after his playing career ended for the same reason. <s> Deadmarsh was drafted by the Quebec Nordiques in the 1993 NHL Entry Draft, first round, fourteenth overall, from the Portland Winterhawks of the Western Hockey League. <s> He played for the Avalanche team that won the Stanley Cup in 1996. <s> His name was initially misspelled "Deadmarch" on the Cup, but was later corrected; it was the first time a misspelling on the Stanley Cup had ever been corrected. <s> He was traded to the Los Angeles Kings on February 21, 2001 along with Aaron Miller, a player to be named later (Jared Aulin), and Colorado's first round pick in the 2001 NHL Entry Draft (Dave Steckel) for Rob Blake and Steve Reinprecht. <s> Among his final accomplishments in the NHL, Deadmarsh became a playoff hero for vaulting the Kings past the heavily favoured Detroit Red Wings in round one of the 2001 Stanley Cup Playoffs, after trailing late in Game 4 by three goals while his team was already down two games to one. <s> Los Angeles went on to lose in the conference semifinals to his former team, the Avalanche, in seven games; the Avalanche would eventually win their second Stanley Cup. <s> A U.S. citizen by virtue of having an American mother, Deadmarsh played for Team USA in the 1996 World Cup of Hockey, the 1998 Winter Olympics, and the 2002 Winter Olympics, winning a gold medal in 1996 and a silver medal in 2002. <s> After missing the most of the 2002–03 NHL season and the entire 2003–04 NHL season due to two concussions (and the next season due to the NHL lockout), Deadmarsh (unofficially) announced his retirement on September 22, 2005 citing the previous concussion as an inability to play further. <s> He was honored on March 20, 2006 before a game between the Avalanche and Kings at Staples Center in downtown Los Angeles, California for his dedication to both teams.
simple: Adam Richard Deadmarsh (born May 10, 1975) is a Canadian-American retired professional ice hockey right winger. <s> He played with the Quebec Nordiques, Colorado Avalanche, and Los Angeles Kings. <s> Before playing in the NHL, Deadmarsh played 4 seasons with the Portland Winter Hawks of the Western Hockey League (WHL). <s> He was drafted with the 14th overall pick by the Quebec Nordiques in the 1993 NHL Entry Draft. <s> During his time with the Avalanche, Deadmarsh won the Stanley Cup in 1996. <s> His name was misspelled as "Deadmarch" when the names were being added to the Cup. <s> It was the first time that a misspelling on the Stanley Cup had ever been corrected. <s> On February 21, 2001, the Avalanche traded Deadmarsh along with Aaron Miller in exchange for Jared Aulin, and Colorado's first round pick in the 2001 NHL Entry Draft (Dave Steckel) for Rob Blake and Steven Reinprecht. <s> During round one of the 2001 Stanley Cup Playoffs, Deadmarsh scored an overtime goal which caused the Kings defeat the very favoured Detroit Red Wings. <s> The Kings would lose against his old team, the Avalanche, in seven games. <s> The Avalanche would end up winning their second Stanley Cup. <s> Deadmarsh played for Team USA during the 1996 World Cup of Hockey, the 1998 Winter Olympics, and the 2002 Winter Olympics. <s> He won a gold medal in 1996 and a silver medal in 2002. <s> Deadmarsh would miss most of the 2002–03 NHL season because of a concussion and missed the whole 2003–04 NHL seasonbecause of another concussion. <s> On September 22, 2005, he announced that he was retiring from playing professional ice hockey. <s> On March 20, 2006, Deadmarsh was honoured before a game between the Avalanche and Kings at Staples Center.

title: Okunino
complex: Okunino is a village in Gmina Miastko, Bytów County, Pomeranian Voivodeship, in northern Poland. <s> It lies approximately 22 km south-west of Bytów and 71 km south-west of Gdańsk (capital city of the Pomeranian Voivodeship). <s> From 1975 to 1998 the village was in Słupsk Voivodeship.
simple: Okunino is a village in Gmina Miastko, Bytów County, Pomeranian Voivodeship, in northern Poland. <s> It is about 22 km south-west of Bytów and 71 km south-west of Gdańsk (capital city of the Pomeranian Voivodeship). <s> From 1975 to 1998 the village was in Słupsk Voivodeship.

title: Tenpyō
complex: Tenpyō (天平 ) was a Japanese era name (年号 , "nengō" , "year name") after "Jinki" and before "Tenpyō-kanpō." <s> This period spanned the years from August 729 through April 749. <s> The reigning emperor was Shōmu"-tennō" (聖武天皇 ) .
simple: Tenpyō (天平), also romanized as Tempyō, was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") after "Jinki" and before "Tenpyō-kanpō." <s> This period started in August 729 and ended in April 749. <s> The reigning emperor was Shōmu"-tennō" (聖武天皇).

title: Peter Groeger
complex: Peter Groeger (1 June 1933 in Gröbzig, Free State of Anhalt – 16 January 2018 in Berlin) was a German actor, director, and voice actor.
simple: Peter Groeger (June 1, 1933 – January 16, 2018) was an (East)-German actor, director, and voice actor. <s> He was born in Gröbzig, Free State of Anhalt. <s> Groeger died in Berlin on January 16, 2018 at the age of 84.

title: Lipki, Kireyevsky District, Tula Oblast
complex: Lipki is a town in Kireyevsky District of Tula Oblast, Russia, located 38 km south of Tula, the administrative center of the oblast. <s> Population: (2010 Census) (2002 Census) (1989 Census) <s> The village of Lipki has been known since at least the 17th century. <s> In 1949, it was granted urban-type settlement status due to the development of coal deposits.
simple: Lipki (, 53°57'N 37°42'E) is a town in Tula Oblast, Russia. <s> Lipki is located 38 km south of Tula. <s> The village of Lipki has been known since the 17th century.

title: Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem
complex: Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem (also known as AVP:R) is a 2007 American science fiction action film directed by the Brothers Strause (Colin and Greg Strause) in their directorial debut and written by Shane Salerno. <s> The film stars Steven Pasquale, Reiko Aylesworth, John Ortiz, Johnny Lewis, and Ariel Gade. <s> It is a sequel to the 2004 film "Alien vs. Predator" and the second and latest installment in the "Alien vs. Predator" franchise, continuing the crossover between the "Alien" and "Predator" franchises. <s> "Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem" was released on December 25, 2007 in the United States. <s> The film grossed $129 million at the worldwide box office, making it the lowest grossing film in both the "Alien" and "Predator" franchises when accounting for inflation. <s> The film was critically panned, with particular criticism directed towards the plot and poor lighting in the film.
simple: Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem (also known as AVPR) is a 2007 American science fiction horror movie directed by The Brothers Strause (Colin and Greg Strause) in their directorial debut, written by Shane Salerno, and starring Steven Pasquale, Reiko Aylesworth, John Ortiz, Johnny Lewis, and Ariel Gade. <s> It is a sequel to "Alien vs. Predator" (2004) and the second and latest installment in the Alien vs. Predator franchise, continuing the crossover of the Alien and Predator franchises. <s> The movie was released on December 25, 2007, and it grossed $129 million, behind the predecessor, which grossed $172 million.

title: Holly Madison
complex: Holly Madison (born December 23, 1979) is a model, showgirl, television personality and "New York Times" best-selling author. <s> Madison is known for her role in the E! reality television show "The Girls Next Door" and for her own series, "Holly's World". <s> In July 2015, Madison released her first book and memoir, "".
simple: Holly Sue Cullen (born December 23, 1979), the model is known mostly as Holly Madison, is an American model and television personality. <s> She is best known for being one of Hugh Hefner's girlfriends on the reality television series "The Girls Next Door". <s> She also had her own reality series, "Holly's World".

title: Ace Frehley
complex: Paul Daniel "Ace" Frehley ( ; born April 27, 1951) is an American musician and songwriter best known as the original lead guitarist, occasional lead vocalist and co-founding member of the rock band Kiss. <s> He invented the persona of The Spaceman (a.k.a. Space Ace) and played with the group from its inception in 1973 until his departure in 1982. <s> After leaving Kiss, Frehley embarked on a solo career, which was put on hold when he rejoined Kiss in 1996 for a highly successful reunion tour. <s> Frehley's second tenure with Kiss lasted until 2002, when he left at the conclusion of what was originally purported to be the band's Farewell Tour. <s> His most recent solo album, "Spaceman", was released on October 19, 2018.
simple: Paul Daniel "Ace" Frehley (born April 27, 1951- 2017) is an American guitarist best known as one of the first members of the rock band Kiss. <s> Frehley played with the group from 1973 until 1982. <s> His second time playing with Kiss stopped in 2002 when he left the band at the end of their world tour.

title: Let's Go All the Way (song)
complex: "Let's Go All the Way" is a song by American group Sly Fox. <s> Released as a single in December 1985 from their debut studio album of the same name, the record entered the "Billboard" chart on December 28 and reached the top ten in both the U.S. and the UK. <s> Despite receiving considerable commercial and critical success, the group failed to match expectations with their later singles, and are sometimes referred to as a one-hit wonder. <s> The song was covered in 1999 by supergroup The Wondergirls in a more rock style and it was re-recorded in 2013 along with actor and singer-songerwriter Ashley Hamilton and British singer Robbie Williams for the soundtrack of Iron Man 3: Heroes Fall.
simple: "Let's Go All the Way'" is a 1986 dance-pop/new wave song by the American pop band Sly Fox. <s> It is the first single from their only album "Let's Go All the Way", which was released in 1985. <s> The song was used in the movie Ferris Bueller's Day Off and Loverboy and was also covered in 1999 by The Wondergirls and again in 2000 by the horrorcore band Insane Clown Posse.

title: States of Germany
complex: Germany is a federal republic consisting of sixteen states ( , plural ; commonly informally and ). <s> Since today's Germany was formed from an earlier collection of several states, it has a federal constitution, and the constituent states retain a measure of sovereignty.
simple: The Federal Republic of Germany (FRG) has 16 states .

title: Marion Strecker
complex: Marion Strecker (born October 17, 1960 in São Paulo) is a Brazilian journalist, photographer and entrepreneur, known as one of the pioneers of the Internet industry in South America . <s> Since 2011 she has been living in San Francisco, California, and working as an Editor-at-Large for UOL, a major content portal in Brazil. <s> Since 2010 she has also been a columnist for "Folha de S.Paulo", one of the largest newspaper in circulation in Brazil, writing in the Market section about technology, innovation and behavior. <s> Strecker is one of the original founders of UOL . <s> She served as the Content VP of the company for 15 years, from 1996 until 2011. <s> Before joining the team that founded UOL, Marion Strecker worked at the Folha de S.Paulo Newsroom from 1984 to 1996. <s> She was a writer, an art critic, editor of the cultural section, editor of supplements, planning coordinator, coordinator of special reports, special reporter, director of the archives and director of the Folha News Agency. <s> Strecker was one of the authors of the "Folha Newsroom Manual". <s> After coordinating the Digitization of the Newspaper Archives Project in the early 90s, Strecker led a team that developed many high tech products like audiotext services (1993), the newspaper's full text annual CD-ROMs (1994–96) and a system similar to a BBS, which gave all the Folha de S.Paulo journalists and foreign correspondents access to the archives online, using telephone lines and microcomputers. <s> Because of this work, Strecker was honored with the Folha Award on Journalism, Special Category, in 1995. <s> Also in charge of the Folha News Agency since 1994, Strecker led the team which created the first website for Folha's Media Group in Brazil (launched on July 9, 1995). <s> Later that year, Strecker put together the first content team for the launch of UOL in April 1996. <s> The company soon became the leader in the Brazilian internet market. <s> Strecker holds a Bachelor’s Degree in Social Communication from the Pontifical Catholic University of São Paulo (PUC-SP). <s> In the 90s, she had a brief career as a Professor of New Technologies for Communication at Casper Líbero College of Journalism in São Paulo. <s> Since the 80s, she has contributed as a writer to several magazines and an invited speaker to many seminars and conferences in Brazil, US and Europe - the Abraji International Congress on Investigative Journalism in São Paulo (2011); the International Symposium on Online Journalism at the University of Texas in Austin (2009 and 2003); the ONA Conference (Online News Association) in New York City (2005); the IIR’Broadband Content Congress and the News World Conference in Barcelona (2000) and the International Seminar on Online Journalism MediaOn in São Paulo (2009 and 2007). <s> Early in her career as a journalist, she was a writer and a co-editor with Lisette Lagnado of "Arte em São Paulo", a magazine founded by the Brazilian painter Luiz Paulo Baravelli and dedicated to the visual arts. <s> Before starting her career in journalism and online media, Strecker was a music teacher and a performer. <s> She was also a shareholder of Colégio Modelo, an Elementary, Middle and High School in São Paulo, founded by her father, Professor Nilo Campos Gomes. <s> Strecker is married to the Brazilian journalist , with whom she has two children, Theo and Helena.
