title: Saint-Mars-d'Outillé
complex: Saint-Mars-d'Outillé is a commune in the Sarthe department in the region of Pays-de-la-Loire in north-western France.
simple: Saint-Mars-d'Outillé is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Sarthe department in the west of France.

title: Kettleburgh
complex: Kettleburgh is a small village and civil parish in the Suffolk Coastal district, in the county of Suffolk. <s> The population of this Civil Parish at the 2011 Census was 231.
simple: Kettleburgh is a village and civil parish in Suffolk Coastal, Suffolk, England.

title: Vasily Chuikov
complex: Vasily Ivanovich Chuikov (12 February 1900 – 18 March 1982) was a Soviet military officer. <s> He was the commander of the 62nd Army which saw heavy combat during the Battle of Stalingrad. <s> Following World War II, Chuikov was Chief of the Group of Soviet Forces in Germany (1949–53), commander of the Kiev Military District (1953–60), Chief of the Soviet Armed Forces and Deputy Minister of Defense (1960–64), and head of the Soviet Civil Defense Forces (1961–72). <s> Chuikov was twice awarded the titles Hero of the Soviet Union (1944 and 1945) and was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross by the United States for his actions during the Battle of Stalingrad. <s> In 1955, he was named a Marshal of the Soviet Union. <s> Following his death in 1982, he was interred at the Stalingrad Memorial at the base of the Mamayev Hill, which had been the site of heavy fighting.
simple: Vasily Chuykov (February 12, 1900 - March 18, 1982) was a Soviet military leader. <s> During World War II he was commanding the 62nd army, with which he was especially outstanding himself in the Battle of Stalingrad. <s> He was twice Hero of the Soviet Union (1944, 1945). <s> He was made Marshal of the Soviet Union in 1955.

title: Shilin District
complex: Shilin District (also spelled "Shihlin District") is a district of Taipei and home to a large foreign population, mainly concentrated in the Tianmu area. <s> It has long been a top choice for expatriates from Europe, the United States, and Japan to live, run businesses, and establish embassies and offices due mainly to the natural environment—sitting at the foot of Yangmingshan—and because the international schools are all located here. <s> The central command of the Republic of China Navy is located in Shilin. <s> Shilin is foremost a residential district and has several famous neighborhoods, such as Waishuangxi and Tianmu. <s> Kuomintang leader Chiang Kai-shek lived in Shilin after moving the Chinese Nationalist government to Taiwan after the Chinese Civil War. <s> The district is divided up into 51 villages , which are further divided up into 987 neighborhoods . <s> The district can be said to be the origin of culture in Taipei. <s> During the Qing Dynasty, many private, public and community schools were opened in the area. <s> During the Japanese era, a national learning center was set up at Zhishanyan. <s> Shilin has three universities: Ming Chuan University, Soochow University, and the Chinese Culture University. <s> Several international schools, including the Taipei American School, Taipei Japanese School, The Primacy Collegiate Academy and Taipei European School are located in this district. <s> The district is also home to two vocational colleges, four senior high schools, eight junior high schools, and twenty elementary schools.
simple: Shilin District is a district of Taipei, Republic of China. <s> The district is divided into 51 villages (里), which are further divided up into 987 villages (鄰). <s> The culture of Taipei is said to be started in Shilin district. <s> Shilin has three universities: Ming Chuan University, Soochow University, and the Chinese Culture University. <s> Some international schools, like the Taipei American School, Taipei Japanese School, and Taipei European School are in this district. <s> The district is also has vocational colleges, four senior high schools, eight junior high schools, and twenty elementary schools.

title: Spjutsbygd
complex: Spjutsbygd is a locality situated in Karlskrona Municipality, Blekinge County, Sweden with 383 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Spjutsbygd is a locality in Karlskrona Municipality in Blekinge County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 383 people lived there.

title: Luke M. Griswold
complex: Luke M. Griswold (1837-1892) was a recipient of the Medal of Honor. <s> He was awarded the Medal of Honor "for extraordinary heroism in action while serving on board the U.S.S. Rhode Island which was engaged in saving the lives of the officers and crew of the U.S.S. Monitor, 30 December 1862 near Cape Hatteras, North Carolina. <s> Participating in the hazardous rescue of the officers and crew of the sinking Monitor, Ordinary Seaman Griswold, after rescuing several of the men, became separated in a heavy gale with other members of the cutter that had set out from the Rhode Island, and spent many hours in the small boat at the mercy of the weather and high seas until finally picked up by a schooner 50 miles east of Cape Hatteras."
simple: Luke M. Griswold (1837 – 1892) was a sailor in the U.S Navy during the American Civil War. <s> Luke M. Griswold was born in 1837 in Massachusetts. <s> He died in 1892. <s> Griswold's official Medal of Honor citation reads: Served on board the U.S.S. Rhode Island which was engaged in saving the lives of the officers and crew of the Monitor, 30 December 1862. <s> The crew members spent many hours at sea before being picked up. <s> Participating in the hazardous rescue of the officers and crew of the sinking Monitor, Griswold, after rescuing several of the men, became separated in a heavy gale with other members of the cutter that had set out from the Rhode Island, and spent many hours in the small boat at the mercy of the weather and high seas until finally picked up by a schooner 50 miles east of Cape Hatteras.

title: Penalty kick (association football)
complex: A penalty kick (commonly known as a penalty or a PK) is a method of restarting play in association football, in which a player is allowed to take a single shot on the goal while it is defended only by the opposing team's goalkeeper. <s> It is awarded when a foul punishable by a direct free kick is committed by a player in their own penalty area.
simple: A penalty kick (short pen) is a type of free kick in football. <s> A penalty kick is taken by the team which has been fouled if the violent act is made in the penalty box.

title: Ulster Scots people
complex: The Ulster Scots (Ulster-Scots: "Ulstèr-Scotch"), also called Ulster Scots people ("Ulstèr-Scotch fowk") or, outside the British Isles, Scots-Irish ("Scotch-Airisch"), are a demographic group in Ireland who describe themselves as such, found mostly in the province of Ulster and to a lesser extent in the rest of Ireland. <s> Their ancestors were mostly Protestant Presbyterian Lowland Scottish migrants, the largest numbers coming from Galloway, Lanarkshire, Renfrewshire, Ayrshire and the Scottish Borders, with others coming from further north in the Scottish Lowlands and, to a much lesser extent, from the Highlands. <s> These Scots migrated to Ireland in large numbers both as a result of the government-sanctioned Plantation of Ulster, a planned process of colonisation which took place under the auspices of James VI of Scotland and I of England on land confiscated from members of the Gaelic nobility of Ireland who fled Ulster, and as part of a larger migration or unplanned wave of settlement. <s> Ulster Scots emigrated onwards from Ireland in significant numbers to what is now the United States and to all corners of the then-worldwide British Empire—what are now Canada, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa, the West Indies, to British India and to a lesser extent to Argentina and Chile. <s> Scotch-Irish (or Scots-Irish) is a traditional term for Ulster Scots who emigrated to North America.
simple: Ulster-Scots were largely descended from colonists from Galloway, Ayrshire, and the Scottish Borders Country, although some descend from people further north in the Scottish Lowlands and the Highlands. <s> These people first began to occupy Ireland in large numbers with the Plantation of Ulster, ordered by James I of England on land taken from the Irish nobility, mostly in the Province of Ulster. <s> Ulster-Scots emigrated in significant numbers to the United States and all corners of the British Empire — Canada, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa — and to a lesser extent to Argentina and Chile in South America. <s> "Scotch-Irish" is a traditional term for Ulster Scots who later emigrated to what is now the United States; "Scots-Irish" is a more recent form of the American term, the term has usually been Scotch-Irish in America, as evident in Merriam-Webster dictionaries, where the term Scotch-Irish is recorded from 1744, while Scots-Irish is not recorded until 1972.

title: Serial film
complex: A serial film, film serial (or just serial), movie serial or chapter play, is a motion picture form popular during the first half of the 20th century, consisting of a series of short subjects exhibited in consecutive order at one theater, generally advancing weekly, until the series is completed. <s> Generally, each serial involves a single set of characters, protagonistic and antagonistic, involved in a single story, which has been edited into chapters after the fashion of serial fiction and the episodes cannot be shown out of order or as a single or a random collection of short subjects. <s> Each chapter was screened at a movie theater for one week, and ended with a cliffhanger, in which characters found themselves in perilous situations with little apparent chance of escape. <s> Viewers had to return each week to see the cliffhangers resolved and to follow the continuing story. <s> Movie serials were especially popular with children, and for many youths in the first half of the 20th century a typical Saturday matinee at the movies included at least one chapter of a serial, along with animated cartoons, newsreels, and two feature films.
simple: A movie serial is a movie broken into a several segments called "chapters" or "episodes". <s> Each chapter was shown at the same theater for one week. <s> A chapter ended with a cliffhanger, in which the hero or heroine was left in a dangerous situation. <s> Viewers had to return each week to see the cliffhanger resolved and to follow the continuing story. <s> Movie serials were popular with children.

title: Sajid Nawaz
complex: Sajid Nawaz Khan ( ; born 25 March 1975) is a Pakistani politician who had been a member of the National Assembly of Pakistan, from June 2013 to May 2018. <s> Khan was born on 25 March 1975 to politician Haji Mohammad Nawaz. <s> He holds a degree of Master of Business Administration. <s> He joined politics after the death of his father Haji Mohammad Nawaz. <s> Khan ran for the seat of Provincial Assembly of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa as an independent candidate from Constituency PK-07 (Peshawar-VII) in 2008 Pakistani general election but was unsuccessful. <s> He secured 2,038 and lost the seat to a candidate of Pakistan Peoples Party. <s> Khan later joined Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) and was awarded a PTI ticket to run in 2013 Pakistani general election despite opposition from the PTI chapter in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. <s> He was elected to the National Assembly of Pakistan as a candidate of PTI from Constituency NA-3 (Peshawar-III) in June 2013 election. <s> He secured 66,528 votes and defeated Haji Ghulam Ali.
simple: Sajid Nawaz Khan (; born 25 March 1975) is a Pakistani politician and a member of the National Assembly of Pakistan since June 2013. <s> Khan was born on 25 March 1975 CS1 maint: BOT: original-url status unknown (link) to a politician Haji Mohammad Nawaz. <s> He has a degree of Master of Business Administration. <s> He joined politics after the death of his father Haji Mohammad Nawaz. <s> He ran for the seat of Provincial Assembly of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa as an independent candidate from constituency PF-7 (Peshawar-VII) in Pakistani general election, 2008 but was unsuccessful. <s> He got 2,038 and lost the seat to a candidate of Pakistan Peoples Party. <s> He later joined Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf (PTI) and was awarded a PTI ticket to run in 2013 election despite opposition from the PTI Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. <s> He was elected to the National Assembly of Pakistan as a candidate of PTI from Constituency_NA-3 NA-3 (Peshawar-III) in Pakistani general election, 2013. <s> He got 66,528 votes.

title: Chlamydia trachomatis
complex: "Chlamydia trachomatis" is a gram-negative bacterium that can replicate only within a host cell. <s> Over the course of the "C. trachomatis" life cycle, the bacteria take on two distinct forms.
simple: Chlamydia trachomatis is a small bacterium, is one of three species in the genus "Chlamydia".

title: Ray Comfort
complex: Ray Comfort (born 5 December 1949) is a New Zealand-born Christian minister and evangelist who lives in the United States. <s> Comfort started Living Waters Publications, as well as the ministry "The Way of the Master", in Bellflower, California, and has written several books.
simple: Ray Comfort (born December 5, 1949) is a New Zealand-born American Christian minister and evangelist of Jewish descent. <s> He started Living Waters Publications and "The Way of the Master", with Kirk Cameron, and has written many books.

title: Ian McDiarmid
complex: Ian McDiarmid ( ; born 11 August 1944) is a Scottish actor and director best known for portraying Emperor Palpatine in the "Star Wars" film series. <s> He has received an Olivier Award for Best Actor and a Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Play for his performances. <s> McDiarmid was born in Carnoustie, Scotland. <s> He became a theatre aficionado when he was five years old, when his father took him to see an act named Tommy Morgan at a theatre in Dundee. <s> In 2004, he stated, "It sort of fascinated me, and it also scared me. <s> All those lights, all that make-up. <s> I said to myself, 'I don't know what this is, but I want it.'" <s> However, fearing his father's disapproval, McDiarmid attended Queens College, Dundee, (now the University of Dundee, but then a constituent part of the University of St Andrews), where he received a M.A. in psychology. <s> Soon after, he decided to pursue a career in the theatre instead, and took acting training courses at the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama in Glasgow. <s> In 1968, McDiarmid received a gold medal for his work, the first of many recognitions given to him for his work in the theatre. <s> McDiarmid claimed he became its recipient "by doing all the boring jobs you have to do when you are young, to eke out an existence." <s> After a minor part in the film "Dragonslayer", McDiarmid was cast by George Lucas in "Return of the Jedi" as Emperor Palpatine, the main villain. <s> Sixteen years after appearing in "Return of the Jedi", he reprised the role as the character's younger incarnation of Senator (and later Chancellor) Palpatine and Sith Lord Darth Sidious in the prequel films: "The Phantom Menace", "Attack of the Clones", and "". <s> The prequels had him play two faces to his character; he re-created his diabolical interpretation of Palpatine from "Return of the Jedi" when playing Darth Sidious, the Chancellor's Sith alter ego, but created a pleasant, charming character in Palpatine's public persona.
simple: Ian McDiarmid (pronounced ) is a Scottish theatre actor and director. <s> He was born 11 August 1944. <s> Worldwide, he is most famous for his role as Emperor Palpatine in the Star Wars live action movie series. <s> McDiarmid was born in Carnoustie in Tayside. <s> Soon after, he decided he wanted a career in the theatre instead, and took acting training courses at the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama in Glasgow. <s> In 1968, McDiarmid got a gold medal for his acting work. <s> McDiarmid was cast by George Lucas in "" as Emperor Palpatine, the main villain. <s> Sixteen years later, he came back to the role as a younger Senator and Chancellor in the "Star Wars" prequel movies. <s> The prequels had him play two faces to his character: He created an pleasant and likeable character in Palpatine's public face.

title: Helsinki Olympic Stadium
complex: The Helsinki Olympic Stadium ( ; ), located in the Töölö district about 2.3 km from the centre of the Finnish capital Helsinki, is the largest stadium in the country, nowadays mainly used for hosting sports events and big concerts. <s> The stadium is best known for being the centre of activities in the 1952 Summer Olympics. <s> During those games, it hosted athletics, equestrian show jumping, and the football finals.
simple: Helsinki Olympic Stadium (or Olympiastadion) is a sports stadium in Helsinki, Finland. <s> The 1952 Summer Olympics took place in the stadium.

title: Laurent Clerc
complex: Louis Laurent Marie Clerc (] ; 26 December 1785 – 18 July 1869) was a French teacher called "The Apostle of the Deaf in America" and was regarded as the most renowned deaf person in American Deaf History. <s> He was taught by Abbe Sicard and deaf educator Jean Massieu, at the Institution Nationale des Sourds-Muets in Paris. <s> With Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet, he co-founded the first school for the deaf in North America, the Asylum for the Education and Instruction of the Deaf and Dumb, on April 15, 1817 in the old Bennet's City Hotel, Hartford, Connecticut. <s> The school was subsequently renamed the American School for the Deaf and in 1821 moved to 139 Main Street, West Hartford. <s> The school remains the oldest existing school for the deaf in North America. <s> Laurent Clerc was born December 26, 1785 in La Balme-les-Grottes, Isère, a village on the northeastern edge of Lyon to Joseph-François Clerc and Marie-Élisabeth Candy in the small village of La Balme, where his father was the mayor.
simple: Laurent Clerc (born Louis Laurent Marie Clerc December 26, 1785 in France - July 18, 1869) co-founded the first school for the deaf (people who cannot hear) in the United States. <s> Clerc and Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet founded that school on April 15, 1817 in an old hotel. <s> The school moved to its present location in 1821 and is now named The American School for the Deaf. <s> The American School for the Deaf is the oldest school for the deaf in the United States.

title: Virology
complex: Virology is the study of viruses – submicroscopic, parasitic particles of genetic material contained in a protein coat – and virus-like agents. <s> It focuses on the following aspects of viruses: their structure, classification and evolution, their ways to infect and exploit host cells for reproduction, their interaction with host organism physiology and immunity, the diseases they cause, the techniques to isolate and culture them, and their use in research and therapy.
simple: Virology is the study of viruses such as the cold virus.

title: Spree
complex: The Spree (] ; , ) is a river that flows through the Saxony, Brandenburg and Berlin states of Germany, and in the Ústí nad Labem region of the Czech Republic. <s> Approximately 400 km in length, it is a left bank tributary of the River Havel, which itself flows into the Elbe and then the North Sea. <s> It is the river on which the original centre of Berlin was built.
simple: The Spree is a river in the north-east of Germany. <s> The river is 400 km long.

title: Boisleux-Saint-Marc
complex: Boisleux-Saint-Marc is a commune in the Pas-de-Calais department in the Hauts-de-France region in northern France.
simple: Boisleux-Saint-Marc is a commune.

title: Carlos Mancheno Cajas
complex: Carlos Mancheno Cajas (October 9, 1902 – October 11, 1996) was President of Ecuador of Ecuador from 23 August 1947 to 2 September 1947. <s> Mancheno assumed control after a coup d'état he led deposed President José María Velasco. <s> Velasco left the country, returning later both to Ecuador and to the presidency. <s> Mancheno himself was removed only ten days after taking control, and Velasco's vice-president, Mariano Suárez, assumed the presidency.
simple: Carlos Mancheno Cajas (October 9, 1902 - October 11, 1996) was President of Ecuador from 23 August 1947 to 2 September 1947. <s> Mancheno died on October 11, 1996 in Guayaquil, Ecuador from natural causes, aged 94. <s> Mancheno assumed control after a coup d'état he led deposed President José María Velasco. <s> Velasco left the country, returning later both to Ecuador and the to presidency. <s> Mancheno himself was removed only ten days after taking control, and Velasco's vice-president, Mariano Suárez Veintimilla, assumed the presidency.

title: Orp-Jauche
complex: Orp-Jauche is a Walloon municipality located in the Belgian province of Walloon Brabant. <s> On January 1, 2008, Orp-Jauche had a total population of 8,400.
simple: Orp-Jauche is a municipality found in the Belgian province of Walloon Brabant.

title: Sleepy Hollow (film)
complex: Sleepy Hollow is a 1999 American gothic supernatural horror film directed by Tim Burton. <s> It is a film adaptation loosely based on Washington Irving's 1820 short story "The Legend of Sleepy Hollow", and stars Johnny Depp and Christina Ricci, with Miranda Richardson, Michael Gambon, Casper Van Dien, and Jeffrey Jones in supporting roles. <s> The plot follows police constable Ichabod Crane (Depp) sent from New York City to investigate a series of murders in the village of Sleepy Hollow by a mysterious Headless Horseman. <s> The film had its world premiere at Mann's Chinese Theatre on November 17, 1999 and was released in the United States on November 19, 1999, by Paramount Pictures. <s> It received generally positive reviews from critics, with many praising the performances, direction, screenplay, and musical score, as well as, dark humor, visual effects and atmosphere. <s> It grossed approximately $207 million worldwide. <s> "Sleepy Hollow" won the Academy Award for Best Art Direction.
simple: Sleepy Hollow is a 1999 American horror movie directed by Tim Burton. <s> It stars Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci, Christopher Walken, Ian McDiarmid, Sir Michael Gambon, Sir Christopher Lee, Michael Gough, Richard Griffiths, Jeffrey Jones, Martin Landau and Miranda Richardson. <s> The movie is based on a book by Washington Irving called The Legend of Sleepy Hollow. <s> It is about the murders of Sleepy Hollow, New York which Ichabod Crane (Johnny Depp) has to investigate and find out who is the killer. <s> When the movie went to box office it was a success and it made roughly $207 million worldwide.

title: Huancayo
complex: Huancayo (] ; in ] , '(place) with a (sacred) rock') is the capital of Junín Region, in the central highlands of Peru.
simple: Huancayo is a city in Peru. <s> It is the capital of Junín Region.

title: County Carlow
complex: County Carlow is a county in Ireland, part of the South-East Region and the province of Leinster. <s> It is named after the town of Carlow, which lies on the River Barrow. <s> Carlow County Council is the local authority.
simple: County Carlow is a county of Ireland. <s> It is in the province of Leinster. <s> It is named after the town of Carlow.

title: Bludenz District
complex: The Bezirk Bludenz is an administrative district ("Bezirk") in Vorarlberg, Austria. <s> Area of the district is 1,287.63 km2, population is 61,407 (January 1, 2012), and population density 48 persons per km2. <s> Administrative center of the district is Bludenz. <s> The district is divided into 29 municipalities, one of them is a town, and two of them are market towns.
simple: The Bludenz District is an administrative district ("Bezirk") of the state of Vorarlberg, Austria. <s> It has an area of 1,287.63 km2. <s> As of 2012 about 61,407 people lived there. <s> The administrative center of the district is Bludenz.

title: Karel Schoeman
complex: Karel Schoeman (] , 26 October 1939 in Trompsburg, South Africa – 1 May 2017 in Bloemfontein, South Africa) was a South African novelist, historian, translator and man of letters. <s> He was the author of 19 novels and numerous works of history. <s> He was one of South Africa's most honoured authors. <s> Schoeman wrote primarily in Afrikaans, although several of his non-fiction books were originally written in English. <s> His novels are increasingly being translated into other languages, notably, English, French and Dutch. <s> Schoeman committed suicide at a retirement center in South Africa at the age of 77, writing about dying with dignity in his suicide statement. <s> A previous attempt failed when he was 75.
simple: Karel Schoeman (26 October 1939 – 1 May 2017) was a South African novelist, historian, and translator. <s> He was the author of 19 novels and many works of history. <s> He was one of South Africa's most honored authors. <s> Schoeman wrote mainly in Afrikaans, although several of his non-fiction books were originally written in English. <s> His novels are increasingly being translated into other languages, notably, English, French and Dutch. <s> Shoeman died in an act of suicide by refusing to eat or drink at a retirement center in South Africa at the age of 77.

title: Death hoax
complex: A death hoax is a deliberate or confused report of someone's death that turns out to be incorrect and murder rumors. <s> In some cases it might be because the person has intentionally faked death.
simple: A death hoax is a false report of someone's death. <s> In some cases, it might be because the person has faked their own death on purpose.

title: Rupert Sheldrake
complex: Alfred Rupert Sheldrake (born 28 June 1942) is an English author, and researcher in the field of parapsychology, who proposed the concept of morphic resonance, a conjecture which lacks mainstream acceptance and has been characterised as pseudoscience. <s> He worked as a biochemist at Cambridge University from 1967 to 1973 and as principal plant physiologist at the International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics in India until 1978. <s> Sheldrake reported "being drawn back to a Christian path" during his time in India, and self-identifies as Anglican. <s> Sheldrake is married to therapist, voice teacher and author Jill Purce. <s> They have two sons, the biologist Merlin Sheldrake and the musician Cosmo Sheldrake. <s> Reviews of Sheldrake's books have at times been extremely negative over their scientific content, but some have been positive. <s> In 2009, Adam Rutherford, geneticist and deputy editor of "Nature", criticised Sheldrake's books for containing research that was not subjected to the peer-review process expected for science, and suggested that his books were best "ignored." <s> In September 1981, "Nature" published an editorial about "A New Science of Life" entitled "A book for burning?" <s> In January 2013, Sheldrake gave a TEDx lecture at TEDxWhitechapel in East London roughly summarising ideas from his book, "The Science Delusion". <s> In his talk, Sheldrake stated that modern science rests on ten dogmas which "fall apart" upon examination and promoted his hypothesis of morphic resonance.
simple: Alfred Rupert Sheldrake (born 28 June 1942) is an English author. <s> From 1967 to 1973 he was a biochemist and cell biologist at Cambridge University., Then he went to work in India from 1974 to 1978. <s> He is married to Jill Purce. <s> In 2009 Adam Rutherford, the deputy editor of a scientific journal called "Nature", wrote in the Guardian about him and his book "A New Science of Life". <s> His first book, "A New Science of Life", was published in 1981. <s> He gave a TEDx talk in 2013 on his book "The Science Delusion" that was banned.

title: Ockelbo BBK
complex: Ockelbo BBK is a basketball club in Ockelbo, Sweden. <s> The club was established in 1969 and the women's team played in Elitserien between 1995-1999. <s> The men's team qualified for the Swedish Basketball League in 2003. <s> Suffering from economic problems in 2006, the club applied for bankruptcy to the Gävle District Court on 13 February 2007. <s> The men's team first played the two remaining games of the regular season.
simple: Ockelbo BBK is a basketball club in Ockelbo in Sweden. <s> The club was established in 1969. <s> The women's team played in Elitserien between 1995-1999. <s> The men's team qualified for the Swedish Basketball League in 2003. <s> In 2006 the club was suffering from economic problems in 2006. <s> The club applied for bankruptcy to the Gävle District Court on 13 February 2007. <s> The men's team first played the two remaining games of the regular season.

title: Time Protocol
complex: The Time Protocol is a network protocol in the Internet Protocol Suite defined in 1983 in RFC 868 by Jon Postel and K. Harrenstein. <s> Its purpose is to provide a site-independent, machine readable date and time. <s> The Time Protocol may be implemented over the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or the User Datagram Protocol (UDP). <s> A host connects to a server that supports the Time Protocol on port 37. <s> The server then sends the time as a 32-bit unsigned integer in binary format and in network byte order, representing the number of seconds since 00:00 (midnight) 1 January, 1900 GMT, and closes the connection. <s> Operation over UDP requires the sending of any datagram to the server port, as there is no connection setup for UDP.
simple: The TIME service is an Internet protocol defined in RFC 868. <s> Its purpose is to provide a site-independent, machine readable date and time. <s> TIME can operate over either TCP or UDP. <s> When operating over TCP, a host connects to a server that supports the TIME protocol on TCP port 37. <s> The server then sends the time as a 32-bit unsigned binary number in network byte order representing a number of seconds since 00:00 (midnight) 1 January, 1900 GMT and closes the connection.

title: Bill Torrey
complex: William Arthur Torrey (June 23, 1934 – May 2, 2018) was a Canadian hockey executive. <s> He served as a general manager in the National Hockey League for the Oakland Seals, New York Islanders, and Florida Panthers. <s> He developed the Islanders into a dynasty that won four consecutive Stanley Cups. <s> He was often known as "The Architect", and "Bow-Tie" Bill, after the signature bow tie he always wore. <s> Torrey was elected to the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1995. <s> He is honoured with a banner in Barclays Center along with Al Arbour and six of the players he drafted. <s> Torrey's banner has the words "The Architect" and the image of a bowtie. <s> Torrey had four sons, and ten grandchildren. <s> Torrey died at his home in West Palm Beach, Florida, on the evening of May 2, 2018.
simple: William Arthur Torrey (June 23, 1934 – May 2, 2018) was a Canadian hockey executive. <s> He served as a general manager in the National Hockey League for the Oakland Seals, New York Islanders, and Florida Panthers. <s> He owned the Islands when they won four Stanley Cups. <s> He was often known as "The Architect," and "Bow-Tie" Bill, after the signature bow tie he always wore. <s> Torrey was elected to the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1995. <s> Torrey died at his home in West Palm Beach, Florida, on the evening of May 2, 2018, aged 83.

title: Mürwik
complex: Mürwik is a community of Flensburg on the east side of the Flensburg Firth. <s> It is on the Angeln peninsula. <s> Mürwik is the location of the Naval Academy at Mürwik, which is the main academy that trains German Navy officers. <s> Nazi Germany's final government, the Flensburg government, was located in Mürwik. <s> Especially in Germany, it's also known for the sail training ship Gorch Fock of the Naval Academy Mürwik and for the database of traffic violators of Germany ("Kraftfahrt-Bundesamt", often short: "KBA").
simple: It is on the east side of the Flensburg Firth (estuary) on the peninsula of Angeln. <s> It was where the last government of Nazi Germany, called the Flensburg government led by Karl Dönitz was located. <s> It is well known for the Naval Academy Mürwik with its sail training ship Gorch Fock.

title: Pre-shared key
complex: In cryptography, a pre-shared key (PSK) is a shared secret which was previously shared between the two parties using some secure channel before it needs to be used. <s> To build a key from shared secret, the key derivation function is typically used. <s> Such systems almost always use symmetric key cryptographic algorithms. <s> The term PSK is used in Wi-Fi encryption such as Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA), where the method is called WPA-PSK or WPA2-PSK, and also in the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP), where it is known as EAP-PSK. <s> In all these cases, both the wireless access points (AP) and all clients "share" the same key. <s> The characteristics of this secret or key are determined by the system which uses it; some system designs require that such keys be in a particular format. <s> It can be a password, a passphrase, or a hexadecimal string. <s> The secret is used by all systems involved in the cryptographic processes used to secure the traffic between the systems. <s> Crypto systems rely on one or more keys for confidentiality. <s> One particular attack is always possible against keys, the brute force key space search attack. <s> A sufficiently long, randomly chosen, key can resist any practical brute force attack, though not in principle if an attacker has sufficient computational power (see password strength and password cracking for more discussion). <s> Unavoidably, however, pre-shared keys are held by both parties to the communication, and so can be compromised at one end, without the knowledge of anyone at the other. <s> There are several tools available to help one choose strong passwords, though doing so over any network connection is inherently unsafe as one cannot in general know who, if anyone, may be eavesdropping on the interaction. <s> Choosing keys used by cryptographic algorithms is somewhat different in that any pattern whatsoever should be avoided, as any such pattern may provide an attacker with a lower effort attack than brute force search.
simple: In cryptography, a pre-shared key or PSK is a shared secret which was previously shared between the two parties using some secure channel before it is used. <s> Such systems almost always use symmetric key cryptographic algorithms. <s> The term is used in Wi-Fi encryption such as WEP or WPA, where both the wireless access points (AP) and all clients "share" the same key. <s> The characteristics of this secret or key are determined by the system which uses it; some system require that such keys be in a specific format. <s> It can be a password like 'bret13i', a passphrase like 'Idaho hung gear id gene', or a hexadecimal string like '65E4 E556 8622 EEE1'. <s> The secret is used by all systems involved in the cryptographic processes used to secure the traffic between the systems. <s> There are several tools available to help one choose a strong key.

title: Hunza Valley
complex: Hunza (Burushaski: ہنزو , Wakhi "shina", and ) is a mountainous valley in the Gilgit-Baltistan region of Pakistan. <s> Hunza is situated in the extreme northern part of the region, bordering with the Wakhan Corridor of Afghanistan and the Xinjiang region of China.
simple: Hunza Valley is a mountainous valley near Gilgit in the Northern Areas of Pakistan.

title: IC 10
complex: IC 10 is an irregular galaxy in the constellation Cassiopeia. <s> It was discovered by Lewis Swift in 1887 and in 1935 Nicholas Mayall became the first to suggest that the object is extragalactic. <s> Edwin Hubble suspected it might belong to the Local Group of galaxies, but its status remained uncertain for decades. <s> The radial velocity of IC 10 was measured in 1962, and it was found to be approaching the Milky Way at approximately 350 km/s, strengthening the evidence for its membership in the Local Group. <s> Its membership in the group was finally confirmed in 1996 by direct measurements of its distance based on observations of Cepheids. <s> Despite its closeness, the galaxy is rather difficult to study because it lies near the plane of the Milky Way and is therefore heavily obscured by interstellar matter. <s> The apparent distance between IC 10 and the Andromeda Galaxy is about the same as the apparent distance between the Andromeda Galaxy and the Triangulum Galaxy, which suggests that IC 10 may belong to the M31 subgroup. <s> IC 10 is the only known starburst galaxy in the Local Group of galaxies. <s> It has many more Wolf–Rayet stars per square kiloparsec (5.1 stars/kpc) than the Large Magellanic Cloud (2.0 stars/kpc) or the Small Magellanic Cloud (0.9 stars/kpc). <s> Although the galaxy has a luminosity similar to the SMC, it is considerably smaller. <s> Its higher metallicity compared to the SMC suggests that star formation activity has continued for a longer time period. <s> The evolutionary status of the Wolf–Rayet stars suggests that they all formed in a relatively short timespan. <s> The ratio between the two types of Wolf–Rayet stars (WC stars and WN stars) in IC 10 is very different from the ratio in other galaxies in the Local Group, which may be somehow due to the starburst nature of the galaxy. <s> Currently, the galaxy produces stars at the rate of 0.04–0.08 solar masses per year, which means that the gas supply in the galaxy can last for only a few billion years longer. <s> Observations of IC 10 in the far-infrared show that the dust in this mild starburst galaxy is deficient in small grains. <s> It is hypothesized that any small grains that formerly existed were destroyed by strong ultraviolet radiation in the areas around the hot luminous stars that were formed in the galaxy's recent burst of star formation. <s> The galaxy has a huge envelope of hydrogen gas, with an apparent size measuring 68′ × 80′, which is far larger than the apparent size of the galaxy in visible light (5.5′ × 7.0′). <s> IC 10 is also unusual in the respect that the visible part of the galaxy seems to rotate in a different direction than the outer envelope. <s> It has a H II nucleus.
simple: IC 10 is an irregular galaxy in the constellation Cassiopeia. <s> It was discovered in 1887. <s> Edwin Hubble suspected it might belong to the Local Group of galaxies, but this was uncertain for decades. <s> The radial velocity of IC 10 was measured in 1962. <s> It is approaching the Milky Way at about 350 km/s. <s> This strengthened the evidence for its being in the Local Group. <s> Its membership in the group was finally confirmed in 1996 by measurements of its distance by observations of Cepheids. <s> Despite its closeness, the galaxy is rather difficult to study because it lies near the galactic plane of the Milky Way. <s> It is heavily obscured by interstellar matter. <s> The apparent distance between IC 10 and the Andromeda Galaxy is about the same as the apparent distance between the Andromeda Galaxy and the Triangulum Galaxy, which suggests that IC 10 may belong to the M31 subgroup. <s> IC 10 is the only known starburst galaxy in the Local Group of galaxies. <s> It has many more Wolf-Rayet stars per square kiloparsec (5.1 stars/kpc2) than the Large Magellanic Cloud (2.0 stars/kpc2) or the Small Magellanic Cloud (0.9 stars/kpc2). <s> Although the galaxy has a luminosity similar to the SMC, it is much smaller. <s> The evolutionary status of the Wolf-Rayet stars suggests they all formed in a relatively short period. <s> The galaxy produces stars at the rate of 0.04–0.08 solar masses per year, which means that the gas supply in the galaxy can last for a few billion years longer. <s> Observations of IC 10 in the far-infrared show that the dust in this mild starburst galaxy is deficient in small grains. <s> Perhaps small grains were destroyed by strong ultraviolet radiation in the areas around the hot luminous stars. <s> The galaxy has a huge envelope of hydrogen gas, with an apparent size measuring 68′ × 80′, which is far larger than the apparent size of the galaxy in visible light (5.5′ × 7.0′). <s> IC 10 is also unusual in the respect that the visible part of the galaxy seems to rotate in a different direction than the outer envelope. <s> It has an H II nucleus.

title: John Forrest Dillon
complex: John Forrest Dillon (December 25, 1831 – May 6, 1914) was an attorney in Iowa and New York, a Justice of the Iowa Supreme Court and a United States Circuit Judge of the United States Circuit Courts for the Eighth Circuit. <s> He authored a highly influential treatise on the power of states over municipal governments. <s> Born on December 25, 1831, in Northampton, (then part of Montgomery County, now part of Fulton County), New York, Dillon received a Doctor of Medicine in 1850 from the University of Iowa. <s> He read law in 1852. <s> He entered private practice in Davenport, Iowa from 1852 to 1853. <s> He was county attorney for Scott County, Iowa from 1853 to 1858. <s> He was a Judge of the Iowa District Court for the Seventh Judicial District from 1858 to 1862. <s> He was a Justice of the Iowa Supreme Court from 1862 to 1868. <s> While on the federal bench, Dillon wrote "Municipal Corporations" (1872), one of the earliest systematic studies of the subject. <s> He also authored "Removal of Cases from State Courts to Federal Courts" and "Municipal Bonds", both in 1876. <s> On February 17, 1876, during the Whiskey Ring graft prosecutions, Justice Dillon ruled Ulysses S. Grant's deposition for Orville E. Babcock was admissible in court. <s> Following his resignation from the federal bench, Dillon was a Professor of law for Columbia University from 1879 to 1882. <s> He resumed private practice in New York City, New York from 1882 to 1914. <s> He was the Storrs Professor of law at Yale University from 1891 to 1892. <s> He died on May 6, 1914, in New York City. <s> A memorial fountain to Dillon was erected in downtown Davenport in 1918, carved of Indiana limestone in Romanesque style, by sculptor Harry Liva. <s> In 1853, Dillon married Anna Margery Price (born 19 June 1835). <s> They had two sons and a daughter. <s> Anna and their daughter, Mrs. Annie Dillon Oliver, died in the sinking of the French ocean liner SS "La Bourgogne" in July, 1898. <s> Dillon's oldest son, Hiram Price Dillon (1855–1918), became a lawyer in Iowa and a Master of Chancery in federal court. <s> John F. Dillon's sister married John B. Jordan, a Davenport merchant. <s> That marriage produced a daughter Jennie, who married Louis Stengel. <s> Louis and Jennie Stengel had a son, Charles Dillon (Casey) Stengel, named after the Judge, who had a long career as a baseball player and manager. <s> The theory of state preeminence over local governments was expressed as Dillon's Rule in an 1868 case: "Municipal corporations owe their origin to, and derive their powers and rights wholly from, the legislature. <s> It breathes into them the breath of life, without which they cannot exist. <s> As it creates, so may it destroy. <s> If it may destroy, it may abridge and control". <s> By contrast, the Cooley Doctrine, or the doctrine of home rule, expressed the theory of an inherent right to local self-determination. <s> In a concurring opinion, Michigan Supreme Court Judge Thomas M. Cooley in 1871 stated, "local government is a matter of absolute right; and the state cannot take it away". <s> In "Municipal Corporations" (1872), Dillon explained that in contrast to the powers of states, which are unlimited but for express restrictions under the state or federal constitution, municipalities only have the powers that are expressly granted to them. <s> This formulation of the scope of municipal power came to be known as "Dillon's Rule." <s> It holds that municipal governments have only the powers expressly granted to them by the state legislature, those powers necessarily implied by the express powers, and those that are essential and indispensable to the municipality's existence and functioning. <s> Further, the powers expressly granted to the municipality should be narrowly construed, and any ambiguities in the legislative grant of power should be resolved against the municipality. <s> However, when the state has not specifically directed the method by which the municipality may implement its granted power, the municipality has the discretion to choose the method so long as its choice is reasonable. <s> The Supreme Court of the United States cited "Municipal Corporations" and fully adopted Dillon's emphasis on state power over municipalities in "Hunter v. Pittsburgh", which upheld the power of Pennsylvania to consolidate the city of Allegheny into the city of Pittsburgh, despite the objections of a majority of Allegheny's residents. <s> The Court's ruling that states could alter or abolish at will the charters of municipal corporations without infringing upon contract rights relied upon Dillon's distinction between public, municipal corporations and private ones. <s> However, the Court did not prevent states from passing legislation or amending their constitutions to explicitly allow home rule. <s> This constitutional allowance was reiterated in "Trenton v. New Jersey", where the Supreme Court held that "In the absence of state constitutional provisions safeguarding it to them, municipalities have no inherent right of self-government which is beyond the legislative control of the state, but are merely departments of the state, with powers and privileges such as the state has seen fit to grant, held and exercised subject to its sovereign will”. <s> Hundreds of United States court decisions have employed the Dillon Rule to determine the scope of municipal powers and rights. <s> Critics of the rule have argued that it imposes unreasonable constraints on the ability of communities to govern themselves and undermines democracy or that local self-government is a matter of natural right that does not need to be conferred by higher political structures. <s> Some have suggested that Dillon's approach derived from the contemporary view that cities were inherently corrupt political organs. <s> States which do not follow Dillon's Rule—"home rule" states, including Dillon's own Iowa—remain in the minority, despite the significant decrease in the public perception of municipal corruption.
simple: John Forrest Dillon (December 25, 1831 – May 6, 1914) was an American judge. <s> He wrote an important book on the power of states about municipal governments. <s> Dillon was born in Northampton, Montgomery County, New York. <s> Shortly after beginning to work as a doctor, he switched to studying law, and was admitted to the Iowa bar in 1852. <s> He was elected as the Scott County prosecutor after a brief private practice in 1853, and was then elected to a judgeship in Iowa's 7th Judicial Circuit in 1858. <s> He joined to the Iowa Supreme Court in 1862 and served until 1869, when he was appointed by President Grant to the United States Circuit Court. <s> While Dillon was a federal judge, he wrote "Municipal Corporations" (1872), which was one of the earliest books to present the subject, and people still study it today. <s> He was also the author of "Removal of Cases from State Courts to Federal Courts" and "Municipal Bonds", both in 1876. <s> On February 17, 1876, Justice Dillon ruled Ulysses S. Grant's deposition for Orville E. Babcock was admissible in court during the Whiskey Ring graft prosecutions. <s> After leaving the Circuit Court, Dillon was a professor at Columbia Law School from 1879 until 1882, where he taught real estate and equity. <s> He then taught at Yale Law School from 1891 until 1892. <s> Dillon then returned to private practice until his death in 1914 in New York City. <s> A memorial fountain to Dillon was built in downtown Davenport, Iowa in 1918. <s> Sculptor Harry Liva carved it out of Indiana limestone in Romanesque style. <s> Dillon's oldest son, Hiram Price Dillon (1855 – 1918), also became a lawyer in Iowa, and a Master of Chancery in federal court. <s> The theory of state preeminence over local governments was called the "Dillon Rule" in an 1868 case: "Municipal corporations owe their origin to, and derive their powers and rights wholly from, the legislature. <s> It breathes into them the breath of life, without which they cannot exist. <s> As it creates, so may it destroy. <s> If it may destroy, it may abridge and control." <s> As opposed to the Dillon Rule, the Cooley Doctrine expressed the theory of an inherent right to local self-determination. <s> In a concurring opinion, Michigan Supreme Court Judge Thomas M. Cooley in 1871 stated: “Local government is a matter of absolute right; and the state cannot take it away.” <s> In "Municipal Corporations" (1872), Dillon explained that in contrast to the powers of states, which are unlimited but for express restrictions under the state or federal constitution, municipalities only have the powers that the state legislature expressly gives to them. <s> This formulation of the scope of municipal power came to be known as the "Dillon Rule". <s> It says that municipal governments only have the powers that are expressly granted to them by the state legislature, those that are necessarily implied from that grant of power, and those that are essential and indispensable to the municipality's existence and functioning. <s> If the legislative grant of power is unclear, it should be read narrowly. <s> However, when the state has not specifically directed the method by which the municipality may implement its granted power, the municipality has the discretion to choose the method so long as its choice is reasonable. <s> The Supreme Court of the United States cited Dillon's book "Municipal Corporations" and fully adopted Dillon's emphasis on state power over municipalities in "Merrill v. Monticello," 138 U.S. 673 (1891), reaff'd. <s> "Hunter v. Pittsburgh", 207 U.S. 161 (1907), which upheld the power of Pennsylvania to consolidate the city of Allegheny into the city of Pittsburgh, despite the wishes of the majority of Allegheny residents to be a separate city. <s> The Court's ruling that states could alter or abolish at will the charters of municipal corporations without infringing upon contract rights relied upon Dillon's separation of public, municipal corporations from private ones. <s> Hundreds of U.S. court decisions to the present day have employed the Dillon Rule to determine the scope of municipal powers and rights. <s> Critics of the rule say that it imposes unreasonable constraints on the ability of communities to govern themselves and so undermines democracy, and even that local self-government is a matter of natural right that does not need to be conferred by higher political structures. <s> It has also been suggested that Dillon's approach came from the view at that time that cities were inherently corrupt political organs. <s> Today, most states in the United States follow the Dillon Rule.

title: Danielson, Connecticut
complex: Danielson is a borough in the town of Killingly in Windham County, Connecticut, United States. <s> The population was 4,051 at the 2010 census.

title: Kenneth Williams
complex: Kenneth Charles Williams (22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988) was an English actor, best known for his comedy roles and in later life as a raconteur and diarist. <s> He was one of the main ensemble in 26 of the 31 "Carry On" films, and appeared in many British television programmes and radio comedies, including series with Tony Hancock and Kenneth Horne. <s> He died on 15 April 1988 in his flat; his last words (recorded in his diary) were "Oh, what's the bloody point?" <s> and the cause of death was an overdose of barbiturates. <s> An inquest recorded an open verdict, as it was not possible to establish whether his death was a suicide or an accident.
simple: Kenneth Charles Williams (22 February 1926 - 15 April 1988) was a British comedy actor and comedian. <s> He acted in movies including 26 "Carry On"s. <s> He was born in North London and died there of a barbiturate overdose.

title: Confidence interval
complex: In statistics, a confidence interval (CI) is a type of interval estimate, computed from the statistics of the observed data, that might contain the true value of an unknown population parameter. <s> The interval has an associated confidence level, or coverage that, loosely speaking, quantifies the level of confidence that the deterministic parameter is captured by the interval. <s> More strictly speaking, the confidence level represents the frequency (i.e. the proportion) of possible confidence intervals that contain the true value of the unknown population parameter. <s> In other words, if confidence intervals are constructed using a given confidence level from an infinite number of independent sample statistics, the proportion of those intervals that contain the true value of the parameter will be equal to the confidence level. <s> Confidence intervals consist of a range of potential values of the unknown population parameter. <s> However, the interval computed from a particular sample does not necessarily include the true value of the parameter. <s> Based on the (usually taken) assumption that observed data are random samples from a true population, the confidence interval obtained from the data is also random. <s> The confidence level is designated prior to examining the data. <s> Most commonly, the 95% confidence level is used. <s> However, other confidence levels can be used, for example, 90% and 99%. <s> Factors affecting the width of the confidence interval include the size of the sample, the confidence level, and the variability in the sample. <s> A larger sample will tend to produce a better estimate of the population parameter, when all other factors are equal. <s> A higher confidence level will tend to produce a broader confidence interval. <s> A machine fills cups with a liquid, and is supposed to be adjusted so that the content of the cups is 250 g of liquid. <s> As the machine cannot fill every cup with exactly 250.0 g, the content added to individual cups shows some variation, and is considered a random variable X. <s> This variation is assumed to be normally distributed around the desired average of 250 g, with a standard deviation, σ, of 2.5 g. To determine if the machine is adequately calibrated, a sample of "n" = 25 cups of liquid is chosen at random and the cups are weighed. <s> The resulting measured masses of liquid are "X", ..., "X", a random sample from "X". <s> To get an impression of the expectation "μ", it is sufficient to give an estimate. <s> If we take another sample of 25 cups, we could easily expect to find mean values like 250.4 or 251.1 grams. <s> A sample mean value of 280 grams however would be extremely rare if the mean content of the cups is in fact close to 250 grams. <s> There is a whole interval around the observed value 250.2 grams of the sample mean within which, if the whole population mean actually takes a value in this range, the observed data would not be considered particularly unusual. <s> Such an interval is called a confidence interval for the parameter "μ". <s> How do we calculate such an interval? <s> The endpoints of the interval have to be calculated from the sample, so they are statistics, functions of the sample "X", ..., "X" and hence random variables themselves. <s> dependent on the parameter "μ" to be estimated, but with a standard normal distribution independent of the parameter "μ". <s> Hence it is possible to find numbers −"z" and "z", independent of "μ", between which "Z" lies with probability 1 − α, a measure of how confident we want to be. <s> We take 1 − α = 0.95, for example. <s> This might be interpreted as: with probability 0.95 we will find a confidence interval in which the value of parameter "μ" will be between the stochastic endpoints <s> This does not mean there is 0.95 probability that the value of parameter "μ" is in the interval obtained by using the currently computed value of the sample mean, <s> Instead, every time the measurements are repeated, there will be another value for the mean of the sample. <s> In 95% of the cases "μ" will be between the endpoints calculated from this mean, but in 5% of the cases it will not be. <s> The actual confidence interval is calculated by entering the measured masses in the formula. <s> As the desired value 250 of "μ" is within the resulted confidence interval, there is no reason to believe the machine is wrongly calibrated. <s> The calculated interval has fixed endpoints, where μ might be in between (or not). <s> Thus this event has probability either 0 or 1. <s> One cannot say: "with probability (1 − "α") the parameter "μ" lies in the confidence interval." <s> One only knows that by repetition in 100(1 − "α")% of the cases, "μ" will be in the calculated interval. <s> In 100α% of the cases however it does not. <s> And unfortunately one does not know in which of the cases this happens. <s> That is (instead of using the term "probability") why one can say: "with confidence level 100(1 − α) %, "μ" lies in the confidence interval." <s> The figure on the right shows 50 realizations of a confidence interval for a given population mean "μ". <s> If we randomly choose one realization, the probability is 95% we end up having chosen an interval that contains the parameter; however, we may be unlucky and have picked the wrong one. <s> We will never know; we are stuck with our interval.
simple: In statistics a confidence interval is a special form of estimating a certain parameter. <s> The likelihood that the parameter will be in the interval is called confidence level. <s> The confidence interval is based on the observations from a sample, and hence differs from sample to sample. <s> People may speak about the "95% confidence interval". <s> In common usage, a claim to 95% confidence in something is normally taken as indicating virtual certainty. <s> For a given estimation procedure in a given situation, the higher the confidence level, the wider the confidence interval will be. <s> A machine fills cups with margarine. <s> For the example, the machine is adjusted so that the content of the cups is 250g of margarine. <s> As the machine cannot fill every cup with exactly 250g, the content added to individual cups shows some variation, and is considered a random variable X. <s> This variation is assumed to be normally distributed around the desired average of 250g, with a standard deviation of 2.5g. To determine if the machine is adequately calibrated, a sample of "n" = 25 cups of margarine is chosen at random and the cups are weighed. <s> The weights of margarine are "X", ..., "X", a random sample from "X". <s> To get an impression of the expectation μ, it is sufficient to give an estimate. <s> If we take another sample of 25 cups, we could easily expect to find values like 250.4 or 251.1 grams. <s> A sample mean value of 280 grams however would be extremely rare if the mean content of the cups is in fact close to 250g. <s> There is a whole interval around the observed value 250.2 of the sample mean within which, if the whole population mean actually takes a value in this range, the observed data would not be considered particularly unusual. <s> Such an interval is called a confidence interval for the parameter "μ". <s> How do we calculate such an interval? <s> The endpoints of the interval have to be calculated from the sample, so they are statistics, functions of the sample "X", ..., "X" and hence random variables themselves. <s> dependent on the parameter μ to be estimated, but with a standard normal distribution independent of the parameter "μ". <s> Hence it is possible to find numbers −"z" and "z", independent of "μ", where "Z" lies in between with probability 1 − α, a measure of how confident we want to be. <s> We take 1 - α = 0.95. <s> This might be interpreted as: with probability 0.95 we will find a confidence interval in which we will meet the parameter "μ" between the stochastic endpoints <s> This does not mean that there is 0.95 probability of meeting the parameter μ in the calculated interval. <s> Every time the measurements are repeated, there will be another value for the mean of the sample. <s> In 95% of the cases "μ" will be between the endpoints calculated from this mean, but in 5% of the cases it will not be. <s> The actual confidence interval is calculated by entering the measured weights in the formula. <s> As the desired value 250 of "μ" is within the resulted confidence interval, there is no reason to believe the machine is wrongly calibrated. <s> The calculated interval has fixed endpoints, where μ might be in between (or not). <s> Thus this event has probability either 0 or 1. <s> We cannot say: "with probability (1 − α) the parameter "μ" lies in the confidence interval." <s> We only know that by repetition in 100(1 − α) % of the cases μ will be in the calculated interval. <s> In 100α % of the cases however it does not. <s> And unfortunately we do not know in which of the cases this happens. <s> That's why we say: "with confidence level 100(1 − α) %, "μ" lies in the confidence interval." <s> The figure on the right shows 50 realisations of a confidence interval for a given population mean μ. <s> If we randomly choose one realisation, the probability is 95% we end up having chosen an interval that contains the parameter; however we may be unlucky and have picked the wrong one. <s> We'll never know; we are stuck with our interval.
