title: Paulie
complex: Paulie is a 1998 American adventure fantasy comedy film about a disobedient bird named Paulie, starring Tony Shalhoub, Cheech Marin, Gena Rowlands, Hallie Eisenberg, and Jay Mohr. <s> Mohr performs both the voice of Paulie and the on-screen supporting role of Benny, a character who has a lot of dialogue with Paulie. <s> Directed by John Roberts and written by Laurie Craig, the film's production budget was $23 million.
simple: Paulie is a 1998 family movie about a talking parrot named "Paulie". <s> It stars Jay Mohr as Paulie's voice and Tony Shalhoub as a janitor who finds the parrot kept captive in a biological research laboratory. <s> It also stars Gena Rowlands, Cheech Marin, Bruce Davison, Trini Alvarado, and Buddy Hackett in his final film role. <s> It was directed by John Roberts and written by Laurie Craig, and it was produced by Mark Gordon, Gary Levinsohn, and Allyson Lyon Segan for Mutual Film Company and DreamWorks.

title: Bernina District
complex: Bernina District is a former administrative district in the canton of Graubünden, Switzerland. <s> It had an area of 237.2 km2 and a population of 4,619 in 2015. <s> It was replaced with the Bernina Region on 1 January 2017 as part of a reorganization of the Canton. <s> Bernina District consisted of two sub-districts, Brusio and Poschiavo, each of which contains a single municipality of the same name.
simple: Bernina is a district in the canton of Graubünden, Switzerland. <s> It has an area of 237.2 km2 and a population of 4,687 people (as of December 2004). <s> Bernina consists of two "Kreise" (sub-districts) Brusio and Poschiavo, each of which contains a single municipality of the same name.

title: Šumadija
complex: Šumadija is a geographical region in the central part of Serbia. <s> The area used to be heavily covered with forests, hence the name (from "šuma" 'forest'). <s> The city of Kragujevac is the center of the region, and the administrative center of the Šumadija District in the Šumadija and Western Serbia statistical region. <s> Šumadija is located between rivers Sava and Danube in the north, river Great Morava in the east, river West Morava in the south, and Kolubara, Ljig and Dičina in the west. <s> According to some interpretations (for example, physiologist J. Cvijić and ethnologist J. Erdeljanović), the northern border of Šumadija lay between Avala and Kosmaj mountain. <s> According to that view, the capital of Serbia, Belgrade does not belong to this region. <s> During the 18th century, the forests and hills of Šumadija were the refuge for the hajduk bands (brigands, rebels, guerilla fighters) that fought against Ottoman occupation. <s> Parts of the Sanjak of Smederevo, all of Šumadija, were liberated by the Austrian army in 1718, resulting in the establishment of the Kingdom of Serbia (1718–39). <s> After the Austro-Russian–Turkish War (1735–39), the sanjak was re-established. <s> In 1788, the Habsburg-organized Serbian Free Corps liberated Šumadija, which, after subsequent Austrian military involvement, came together with the rest of the sanjak under Habsburg occupation (1788–92). <s> The First Serbian Uprising, which broke out in 1804, saw the region liberated under self-organized Serbian rebels led by Šumadijan-born Karađorđe, the national hero of Serbia. <s> The Second Serbian Uprising in 1815 was led by Miloš Obrenović who successfully repelled Ottoman forces and, by 1830, gained full autonomy for Serbia, leading to the independence of central Serbia after several centuries under Ottoman rule. <s> Between 1922 and 1929, one of the administrative units in the Kingdom of Yugoslavia was the Šumadijska Oblast. <s> It roughly included territory of present-day Šumadija District with its administrative seat in Kragujevac, which is the seat of the modern district as well.
simple: Šumadija (Serbian Cyrillic: Шумадија) is a geographical region in Serbia. <s> The area was heavily forested, hence the name ("Šuma" - forest). <s> The city of Kragujevac is the center of the region, and the administrative center of the Šumadija District in Central Serbia. <s> Šumadija is located between rivers Sava and Danube in the north, river Velika Morava in the east, river Zapadna Morava in the south, and Kolubara, Ljig and Dičina in the west. <s> According to some interpretations (for example, physiologists such as Jovan Cvijić and ethnologist such as Erdeljanović.), <s> , the northern border of Šumadija lay between Avala and Kosmaj mountain. <s> According to that view, the capital of Serbia, Belgrade does not belong to this region. <s> During the 18th century, the forests of Šumadija were the refuge for the Hajduks that fought against Ottoman occupation. <s> The first Serbian uprising in 1804 was led by national hero Karađorđe. <s> The second Serbian uprising in 1815 was led by Miloš Obrenović who successfully repelled the Turkish forces and, by 1830, Serbia had gained its full autonomy. <s> Between 1922 and 1929, one of the administrative units of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia was named Šumadijska Oblast. <s> It roughly included territory of present-day Šumadija District with its administrative seat in Kragujevac, which is the seat of the modern district as well.

title: Franz M. Wuketits
complex: Franz Manfred Wuketits (5 January 1955 – 6 June 2018) was an Austrian biologist, university teacher and epistemologist. <s> He wrote extensively on epistemology, the history and theory of biology, evolution theory, evolutionary ethics, evolutionary epistemology and sociobiology. <s> From 1987 till 2004 he was employed at the University of Graz where he taught the philosophy of biology. <s> He also had guest professorships at several other universities including the Vienna University of Technology (1998–2004) and, in Palma de Majorca, at the University of the Balearic Islands (2006, 2008, 2009, 2010).
simple: Franz Manfred Wuketits (5 January 1955 – 6 June 2018) was an Austrian biologist, university teacher and epistemologist. <s> He has written on epistemology, the history and theory of biology, evolution theory, evolutionary ethics, evolutionary epistemology and sociobiology. <s> From 1987 till 2004 he was employed at the University of Graz where he taught the philosophy of biology. <s> He also had guest professorships at several other universities including the Vienna University of Technology (1998–2004) and, in Palma de Majorca, at the University of the Balearic Islands (2006, 2008, 2009, 2010).

title: Fremantle
complex: Fremantle is a major Australian port city in Western Australia, located at the mouth of the Swan River. <s> Fremantle Harbour serves as the port of Perth, the state capital. <s> Fremantle was the first area settled by the Swan River colonists in 1829. <s> It was declared a city in 1929, and has a population of approximately 29,000. <s> The city is named after Captain Charles Fremantle, the English naval officer who established a camp at the site on 2 May 1829. <s> The city contains well-preserved 19th century buildings and other heritage features.
simple: Fremantle is a port city in Western Australia. <s> It was established by English people who arrived there in 1829 and established the Swan River Colony. <s> The city is named after Charles Fremantle who was the captain of the first ship to arrive there.

title: Myeong-dong
complex: Myeongdong (Korean: ; Hanja: ; lit. <s> 'bright cave' or 'bright tunnel' ) is a dong in Jung-gu, Seoul, South Korea between Chungmu-ro, Eulji-ro, and Namdaemun-ro. <s> It covers 0.99km2 with a population of 3,409 and is mostly a commercial area, being one of Seoul's main shopping, parade route and tourism districts. <s> In 2011, 2012 and 2013, Myeong-dong was listed as the ninth most expensive shopping street in the world. <s> The area is known for its two historically significant sites, namely the Myeongdong Cathedral and the Myeongdong Nanta Theatre. <s> Myeongdong dates back to the Joseon Dynasty when it was called "Myeongryebang" (Korean: ; Hanja: ) and mostly a residential area. <s> During the Japanese era the name was changed to "Myeongchijeong" (Korean: ; Hanja: , "Meijicho" in Japanese pronunciation) and became more of a commercial district, being influenced by the rising commerce in the neighboring Chungmuro area. <s> It became the official district of Myeongdong in 1946, after independence. <s> Myeongdong is one of Seoul's main shopping districts featuring mid-to-high priced retail stores and international brand outlets, including Lacoste, Polo Ralph Lauren, H&M, Zara, Forever 21, Bulgari and Louis Vuitton, as well as Korean cosmetics brands such as Nature Republic, Missha, The Face Shop and Skin Food. <s> It is a particularly popular area for young people and tourists as a center for fashion and sight-seeing. <s> Several large shopping centers and department stores are in the district including Lotte Department Store, Shinsegae Department Store, Migliore, M Plaza, and Noon Square. <s> The southern part of Myeongdong is served by Station #424, Myeong-dong on Line 4 of the Seoul Subway, while the northern area is closer to Station #202, Euljiro 1-ga on Line 2.
simple: Myeong-dong (, literally means 'bright town') is an area in Jung-gu, Seoul, South Korea. <s> It is mostly a commercial area, being one of the main shopping and tourism districts in Seoul. <s> During the Joseon Dynasty era, it was mostly a residential district called Myeongryebang . <s> Later on, under the Japanese colonization, the name was changed to Myeongchijeong . <s> Finally it was changed to the current name, Myeong-dong in 1946, after independence. <s> In Myeong-dong, there are several large department stores and shopping malls such as Lotte , Shinsegae , Migliore and Noon square. <s> There are two Seoul Subway stations near the district; Station #202, Euljiro 1-ga on Line 2 on the north end of the area, Station #424, Myeong-dong on Line 4 on the south end of the area.

title: Knut's party
complex: A Knut's party or Knut's dance ( , literally: "Christmas tree plundering") is a tradition in Sweden on St. Knut's Day (13 January), which marks the end of the Christmas and holiday season, which includes Advent Sunday, Saint Lucy's Day, Christmas, New Year and Epiphany. <s> It is also known as "Dancing out Christmas" ("Dansa ut julen") or "Throw out the Tree" ("Kasta ut granen"). <s> The present day tradition has changed very little since the 1870s. <s> During the 20th century, the Knut's party became mainly associated with children and candy. <s> The observance of the feast peaked during 1950–70. <s> In private homes, there is often a party mainly for children. <s> The Christmas decorations are then put aside. <s> Such parties are also common in schools, kindergartens, churches and other places. <s> In many towns, the illumination of the public Christmas tree is switched off, accompanied by an outdoor Knut's dance for the community. <s> In some areas the feast is known as "Julgransskakning" ("Shaking the Christmas tree"). <s> Party activities involve singing and dancing around the Christmas tree, "looting" the tree of ornamental candy and apples, smashing the gingerbread house into pieces and eating it, opening Christmas crackers that have been used as decorations in the tree, lotteries, creating a "" ("fishing pond") where children will "fish" for toys and candy or a treasure hunt. <s> The songs and dances are essentially the same as those performed at Christmas and Midsummer, and some songs with verses about the end of Christmas, such as "Raska fötter springa tripp, tripp, tripp", may especially emphasize such verses.
simple: A Knut's party or Knut's dance (, literally: "Christmas tree pludering") is a tradition in Sweden on St. Knut's Day (13 January). <s> It has changed very little since the 1870s. <s> In private homes, especially children often have a party. <s> The Christmas decorations are then put aside. <s> Such parties are even common at schools, Kindergartens, churches and other associations. <s> In many towns the public Christmas tree is taken out of usage for the bypassed Christmas by holding an outdoor Knut's dance. <s> They dance around the Christmas tree and smash the gingerbread house into pieces.

title: Houseplant
complex: A houseplant is a plant that is grown indoors in places such as residences and offices, namely for decorative purposes, but studies have also shown them to have positive psychological effects and as well as help with indoor air purification, since some species, and the soil-dwelling microbes associated with them, reduce indoor air pollution by absorbing volatile organic compounds including benzene, formaldehyde, and trichloroethylene. <s> While generally toxic to humans, such pollutants are absorbed by the plant and its soil-dwelling microbes without harm.
simple: A houseplant is any kind of decorative plant.

title: Lakeville, Connecticut
complex: Lakeville is a village and census-designated place in Litchfield County, Connecticut, bordering Dutchess County, New York. <s> It is within the area of the Town of Salisbury but has its own zip code (06039). <s> It is southwest of Salisbury Village on U.S. Route 44. <s> The Hotchkiss and Indian Mountain Schools are located in Lakeville. <s> New England's oldest Methodist congregation is in Lakeville.
simple: Lakeville is a village and census-designated place in Litchfield County, Connecticut. <s> It is within the area of the Town of Salisbury. <s> It is southwest of Salisbury Village on U.S. Route 44. <s> New England's oldest Methodist congregation is in Lakeville.

title: Undulator
complex: An undulator is an insertion device from high-energy physics and usually part of a larger installation, a synchrotron storage ring, or it may be a component of a free electron laser. <s> It consists of a periodic structure of dipole magnets. <s> These can be permanent magnets or superconducting magnets. <s> The static magnetic field alternates along the length of the undulator with a wavelength formula_1. <s> Electrons traversing the periodic magnet structure are forced to undergo oscillations and thus to radiate energy. <s> The radiation produced in an undulator is very intense and concentrated in narrow energy bands in the spectrum. <s> It is also collimated on the orbit plane of the electrons. <s> This radiation is guided through beamlines for experiments in various scientific areas. <s> where "e" is the electron charge, "B" is the magnetic field, "formula_1" is the spatial period of the undulator magnets, "formula_4" is the electron rest mass, and "c" is the speed of light. <s> This parameter characterizes the nature of the electron motion. <s> For formula_5 the oscillation amplitude of the motion is small and the radiation displays interference patterns which lead to narrow energy bands. <s> If formula_6 the oscillation amplitude is bigger and the radiation contributions from each field period sum up independently, leading to a broad energy spectrum. <s> In this regime of fields the device is no longer called an "undulator"; it is called a wiggler. <s> The usual description of the undulator is relativistic but classical. <s> This means that although a precise calculation is tedious, the undulator can be seen as a black box, where only functions inside the device affect how an input is converted to an output; an electron enters the box and an electromagnetic pulse exits through a small exit slit. <s> The slit should be small enough such that only the main cone passes, and the side lobes of the wavelength spectra can be ignored. <s> Undulators can provide several orders of magnitude higher flux than a simple bending magnet and as such are in high demand at synchrotron radiation facilities. <s> For an undulator with N periods, the brightness can be up to formula_7 more than a bending magnet. <s> The first factor of N occurs because the intensity is enhanced up to a factor of N at harmonic wavelengths due to the constructive interference of the fields emitted during the N radiation periods. <s> The usual pulse is a sine with some envelope. <s> The second factor of N comes from the reduction of the emission angle associated with these harmonics, which is reduced as 1/N. <s> When the electrons come with half the period, they interfere destructively, the undulator stays dark. <s> The same is true, if they come as a bead chain. <s> The polarization of the emitted radiation can be controlled by using permanent magnets to induce different periodic electron trajectories through the undulator. <s> If the oscillations are confined to a plane the radiation will be linearly polarized. <s> If the oscillation trajectory is helical, the radiation will be circularly polarized, with the handedness determined by the helix. <s> If the electrons follow the Poisson distribution a partial interference leads to a linear increase in intensity. <s> In the free electron laser the intensity increases exponentially with the number of electrons. <s> An undulator's figure of merit is spectral radiance. <s> The Russian physicist Vitaly Ginzburg showed theoretically that undulators could be built in a 1947 paper. <s> Julian Schwinger published a useful paper in 1949 that reduced the necessary calculations to Bessel functions, for which there were tables. <s> This was significant for solving the design equations as digital computers were not available to most academics at that time. <s> Hans Motz and his coworkers at Stanford University demonstrated the first undulator in 1952. <s> It produced the first manmade coherent infrared radiation. <s> The design could produce a total frequency range from visible light down to millimeter waves.
simple: An undulator is an insertion device from high-energy physics and usually part of a larger installation, a synchrotron storage ring. <s> It consists of a periodic structure of dipole magnets. <s> A static magnetic field is alternating along the length of the undulator with a wavelength formula_1. <s> Electrons traversing the periodic magnet structure are forced to undergo oscillations. <s> The radiation produced in an undulator is very intense and concentrated in narrow energy bands in the spectrum. <s> The light beam is also collimated on the orbit plane of the electrons. <s> This radiation is guided through beamlines for experiments in various scientific areas. <s> where "e" is the particle charge, "B" is the magnetic field, "formula_3", "formula_4" is the electron rest mass and "c" is the speed of light, characterizes the nature of the electron motion. <s> For formula_5 the oscillation amplitude of the motion is small and the radiation displays interference patterns which lead to narrow energy bands. <s> If formula_6 the oscillation amplitude is bigger and the radiation contributions from each field period sum up independently, leading to a broad energy spectrum. <s> When K is much bigger than 1, the device is no longer called an "undulator"; it is called a wiggler. <s> This means that though the precision calculation is tedious the undulator can be seen as a black box. <s> An electron enters this box and an electromagnetic pulse exits through a small exit slit. <s> The slit should be small enough so that only the main cone passes, so that the side lobes may be ignored. <s> Undulators can provide hundreds of time more magnetic flux than a simple bending magnet and as such are in high demand at synchrotron radiation facilities. <s> For an undulator that repeat N times (N periods), the brightness can be up to formula_7 more than a bending magnet. <s> The intensity is enhanced up to a factor of N at harmonic wavelengths due to the constructive interference of the fields emitted during the N radiation periods. <s> The usual pulse is a sine wave with some envelope. <s> The second factor of N comes from the reduction of the emission angle associated with these harmonics, which is reduced in proportion to 1/N. <s> When the electrons come with half the period, they interfere destructively. <s> So, the undulator stays dark. <s> The same is true if the electrons come as a bead chain. <s> The polarization of the emitted radiation can be controlled by using permanent magnets to induce different periodic electron trajectories through the undulator. <s> If the oscillations are confined to a plane the radiation will be linearly polarized. <s> If the oscillation trajectory is helical, the radiation will be circularly polarized, with the handedness determined by the helix. <s> If the electrons follow the Poisson distribution, a partial interference leads to a linear increase in intensity. <s> In the free-electron laser the intensity increases exponentially with the number of electrons. <s> Physicists measure an undulator's effectiveness in terms of spectral radiance. <s> The Russian physicist V.L. Ginzburg showed that undulators could be made in principle in a 1947 paper. <s> The first undulator was built by Hans Motz and his coworkers at Stanford in 1953. <s> One of their undulators produced the first ever coherent infrared radiation. <s> Their total frequency range was from visible light down to millimeter waves.

title: W. C. Fields
complex: William Claude Dukenfield (January 29, 1880 – December 25, 1946), better known as W. C. Fields, was an American comedian, actor, juggler, and writer. <s> Fields' comic persona was a misanthropic and hard-drinking egotist, who remained a sympathetic character despite his supposed contempt for children and dogs.
simple: W. C. Fields (January 29, 1880 – December 25, 1946) was an American comic actor.

title: Cecilia (Spanish singer)
complex: Evangelina Sobredo Galanes, known as Cecilia, (October 11, 1948 – August 2, 1976) was a Spanish singer-songwriter. <s> She took her stage name from the song "Cecilia" by Simon and Garfunkel. <s> The daughter of diplomats, she was born in Madrid, spent her childhood in several countries (Spain, The United Kingdom, The United States, Jordan, Portugal) and was raised by an American nun. <s> She attained a bachelor's degree in law in Spain before deciding to dedicate herself to music and composition. <s> Her ironic and lyrical songs, sung in a tiny voice, contributed to the existentialist and feminist movements of Spanish "canción protesta" ("protest songs") of the 1960s and 1970s. <s> On 2 August 1976, Cecilia and the musicians of her band drove back to Madrid after a concert in Vigo, Galicia. <s> Early in the morning, they were involved a car accident near Benavente. <s> She, along with musician José Luis González, died. <s> She was buried in the Madrilenian Cementerio de la Almudena. <s> Like many other artists in Spain, Cecilia had to deal with the censorship of General Franco ́s government. <s> Some lyrics and photographs from the albums had to be slightly altered or even removed to be approved. <s> Those elements with references to feminism or to the Spanish Civil War were specially conflictuous. <s> The song "Un millón de muertos" ("A million dead") after being altered and presented as "Un millón de sueños" ("A million dreams") was not approved to be played on the radio ("No radiable"). <s> "Cecilia 2" was the name that replaced "Me quedaré soltera" ("I will remain single") as the album title due to the feminism behind that statement. <s> The front cover of the record, originally showing a pregnant Cecilia, was promptly removed by the record company. <s> The super-hit "Mi querida España" had some words deleted on the final version to minimize subtle references to the Civil War and the end of the dictatorship. <s> However, the authentic lyrics made it to print and came out in the inner side of the gatefold cover of the album.
simple: Evangelina Sobredo Galanes also known as Cecilia (b. 11 October, 1948, Madrid, Spain - d. 2 August, 1976, Castile and León, Spain) was a Spanish singer-songwriter. <s> Galanes took her stage name "Cecilia" from the Simon and Garfunkel song of the same name. <s> During her childhood she lived in other countries such as the United Kingdom, the United States, Portugal, Algeria and Jordan. <s> On 2 August 1976, Cecilia was returning from a concert in Vigo, Galicia. <s> Cecilia was buried in La Almudena's cemetery in Madrid. <s> Like many other artists in Spain, Cecilia had to deal with the censorship of General Franco ́s government. <s> Some lyrics and photographs from the albums had to be changed or even removed before they were approved. <s> Any mention of feminism or to the Spanish Civil War were controversial. <s> The song "Un millón de muertos" ("A million dead") even after being changed to "Un millón de sueños" ("A million dreams") was not approved to be played on the radio in Spain. <s> "Cecilia 2" was the name that replaced "Me quedaré soltera" ("I will remain single") as the album name due to the feminism behind that statement. <s> The front cover of the record, originally showing a pregnant Cecilia, was promptly removed by the record company. <s> The super-hit "Mi querida España" had some words deleted on the final version to minimize references to the Civil War and the end of the dictatorship. <s> However, the original lyrics made it into print and came out in the inner side of the gatefold cover of the album.

title: Headquarters
complex: Headquarters (commonly referred to as HQ or HD) denotes the location where most, if not all, of the important functions of an organization are coordinated. <s> In the United States, the corporate headquarters represents the entity at the center or the top of a corporation taking full responsibility for managing all business activities. <s> In the United Kingdom, the term head office is most commonly used for the HQs of large corporations. <s> The term is also used regarding military organizations.
simple: Headquarters is a name given to the main building of an organization where most of its functions are done. <s> The term is also used regarding military organizations.

title: Lolita (1997 film)
complex: Lolita is a 1997 American-French drama film directed by Adrian Lyne and written by Stephen Schiff. <s> It is the second screen adaptation of Vladimir Nabokov's novel of the same name and stars Jeremy Irons as Humbert Humbert and Dominique Swain as Dolores "Lolita" Haze, with supporting roles by Melanie Griffith as Charlotte Haze, and Frank Langella as Clare Quilty. <s> The film is about a middle-aged male professor, Humbert, who rents a room in the house of the widow Charlotte Haze and becomes sexually attracted to her adolescent daughter Dolores, also called "Lo" or "Lolita". <s> The film had difficulty finding an American distributor and premiered in Europe before being released in America. <s> The film was eventually picked up in the United States by Showtime, a cable network, before finally being released theatrically by The Samuel Goldwyn Company. <s> The performances by Irons and Swain impressed audiences, but, although praised by some critics for its faithfulness to Nabokov's narrative, the film received a mixed critical reception in the United States.
simple: Lolita is a 1997 French-American drama movie. <s> The film had difficulty finding an American distributor and premiered in Europe before being released in America. <s> The film was eventually picked up in the United States by Showtime, a cable network, before finally being released theatrically by The Samuel Goldwyn Company.

title: Early Christianity
complex: Early Christianity covers the period from its origins (c. 30–36) until the First Council of Nicaea (325). <s> This period is typically divided into the Apostolic Age (c. 30–100) and the Ante-Nicene Period (c. 100–325). <s> Early Jewish Christians referred to themselves as 'The Way' , probably coming from , "prepare the way of the Lord." <s> According to , the term "Christian" was first used in reference to Jesus's disciples in the city of Antioch, meaning "followers of Christ," by the non-Jewish inhabitants of Antioch. <s> The earliest recorded use of the term "Christianity" was by Ignatius of Antioch, in around 100 AD.
simple: Early Christianity is known as the Christianity of around the three centuries (1st, 2nd, 3rd, early 4th) between the time of the Crucifixion of Jesus (c.26-36) and the First Council of Nicaea in 325. <s> The major source for the Apostolic Age (c.30-c.100) is the Acts of the Apostles. <s> The term "Christian" was first applied to members of the church at Antioch according to Acts 11:26.

title: Chantonnay
complex: Chantonnay is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Chantonnay is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Athlete (band)
complex: Athlete are an English indie rock band formed in Deptford, London, comprising Joel Pott (lead vocals and guitar), Carey Willetts (bass and backing vocals), Stephen Roberts (drums and backing vocals) and Tim Wanstall (keyboards and backing vocals).
simple: Athlete are an English band from South London.

title: Kay Lenz
complex: Kay Ann Lenz (born March 4, 1953) is an American actress. <s> A former child performer, Lenz has worked primarily in television and has won two Emmy Awards. <s> Lenz was born in Los Angeles, California, the daughter of Ted Lenz, a producer-commentator father and Kay Miller Lenz, a model-radio engineer mother. <s> She appeared on television as a baby held by a guest on a program that her father produced. <s> Lenz began working as a child actress, beginning with appearances in three episodes of "This Is the Life" when she was 14, She went on to appear in such television shows as "The Andy Griffith Show" (in the episode "Opie's Group" (1967) under the stage name Kay Ann Kemper) as well as in stage productions. <s> She made a brief appearance ( billed as Kay Ann Kemper) in a small role in "American Graffiti" (1973) as Jane, a girl at a dance. <s> She achieved recognition for her title-role performance as the free spirit who captivates William Holden in "Breezy", directed by Clint Eastwood. <s> In 1984 she appeared in Rod Stewart's music video for the song "Infatuation". <s> She won an Emmy in 1989 for "Midnight Caller". <s> She was also nominated for an Emmy for her role as flinty lawyer Maggie Zombro in the police/legal drama "Reasonable Doubts".
simple: Kay Lenz (born March 4, 1953) is an American actress and former child performer. <s> She has worked mainly in television. <s> She has received two Emmy Awards. <s> She was born in Los Angeles, California. <s> She played Jane in "American Graffiti". <s> She also played Maggie Zombro in "Reasonable Doubts".

title: Conservation biology
complex: Conservation biology is the management of nature and of Earth's biodiversity with the aim of protecting species, their habitats, and ecosystems from excessive rates of extinction and the erosion of biotic interactions. <s> It is an interdisciplinary subject drawing on natural and social sciences, and the practice of natural resource management. <s> The term conservation biology and its conception as a new field originated with the convening of "The First International Conference on Research in Conservation Biology" held at the University of California, San Diego in La Jolla, California in 1978 led by American biologists Bruce A. Wilcox and Michael E. Soulé with a group of leading university and zoo researchers and conservationists including Kurt Benirschke, Sir Otto Frankel, Thomas Lovejoy, and Jared Diamond. <s> The meeting was prompted by the concern over tropical deforestation, disappearing species, eroding genetic diversity within species. <s> The conference and proceedings that resulted sought to initiate the bridging of a gap between theory in ecology and evolutionary genetics on the one hand and conservation policy and practice on the other. <s> Conservation biology and the concept of biological diversity (biodiversity) emerged together, helping crystallize the modern era of conservation science and policy. <s> The inherent multidisciplinary basis for conservation biology has led to new subdisciplines including conservation social science, conservation behavior and conservation physiology.
simple: Conservation biology is the study of the nature and status of Earth's biodiversity, aimed to protect species, their habitats, and ecosystems from threatening to extinction. <s> It combines subjects ranged from sciences to economics and the practice of natural resource management. <s> The name "conservation biology" was introduced as the title of a meeting held at the University of California in 1978. <s> Both conservation biology and the concept of biodiversity influence conservation policy.

title: Group velocity
complex: The group velocity is often thought of as the velocity at which energy or information is conveyed along a wave. <s> In most cases this is accurate, and the group velocity can be thought of as the signal velocity of the waveform.
simple: Group velocity is often considered to be the wave velocity at which information travels.

title: Korean Air
complex: Korean Air Lines Co., Ltd. , operating as Korean Air, is the largest airline and flag carrier of South Korea based on fleet size, international destinations and international flights. <s> The airline's global headquarters are located in Seoul, South Korea. <s> Korean Air was founded as Korean National Airlines in 1946.
simple: Korean Air is the flag carrier and largest airline of South Korea. <s> Its headquarters are in Seoul.

title: Discovery Channel
complex: Popular programs on the channel have included the Shark Week programming event, "Deadliest Catch", "MythBusters", "How It's Made", "Dirty Jobs", "Cash Cab", and "Man vs. Wild". <s> Christopher Lowell won a Daytime Emmy Award in 2000 for "The Christopher Lowell Show" (which aired on the Discovery Channel from 1998 to 2001).
simple: It has programs such as "Man vs. Wild", "A Haunting", "The Last Day of the Dinosaurs", "MythBusters", and "Dirty Jobs".

title: Bronies: The Extremely Unexpected Adult Fans of My Little Pony
complex: Bronies: The Extremely Unexpected Adult Fans of My Little Pony (formerly titled BronyCon: The Documentary) is a 2012 documentary film centering on bronies, the adult fans of the 2010 animated television series "". <s> The film, funded through crowd-sourcing via Kickstarter, was originally envisioned to follow voice actor and executive producer John de Lancie to the 2012 Summer BronyCon in New Jersey. <s> The project raised much more than anticipated, allowing it to grow in scope to bring on Lauren Faust, "Friendship Is Magic"'s original creator, and Tara Strong, a principal voice actress on the show, as executive producers and to include additional convention footage from European conventions. <s> The film was released on DVD and Blu-ray, with an option for additional new features, on February 17, 2013. <s> Digital streaming of the film on various services began on September 13, 2013.
simple: Bronies: The Extremely Unexpected Adult Fans of My Little Pony is a 2012 documentary film about bronies. <s> These are adult fans of the 2010 animated television series, "". <s> The creator of "Friendship Is Magic" executive-produced it. <s> The film was released on DVD and Blu-ray on February 17, 2013.

title: Wu Zetian
complex: Wu was the concubine of Emperor Taizong. <s> After his death, she married his successor—his ninth son, Emperor Gaozong, officially becoming Gaozong's "huanghou" (皇后, empress consort, title for the reigning emperor's main consort) in 655, although having considerable political power prior to this. <s> After Gaozong's debilitating stroke in 660, Wu Zetian became administrator of the court, a position equal to the emperor's until 705. <s> Since the time of Qin Shi Huang (259–210 BC) the Emperor of China used the title "huangdi" (皇帝, translated as "emperor" or "empress (regnant)" as appropriate). <s> Wu Zetian was the only woman in the history of China to assume the title of "huangdi". <s> Her tenure as de facto ruler of China and officially regent Tang dynasty (first through her husband and then through her sons, from 665 to 690) was not without precedent in Chinese history; however, she broke precedent when she founded her own dynasty in 690, the Zhou (周) (interrupting the Tang dynasty), ruling personally under the name Sacred and Divine Huangdi (聖神皇帝), and variations thereof, from 690 through 705. <s> Wu Zetian proclaimed herself as the ruler of the "Zhou dynasty", named after the historical Zhou dynasty (1046–256 BC); and, thus, from 690 to 705 the Chinese Empire was known as the Zhou dynasty. <s> The traditional historical view, however, is to discount Wu's "Zhou dynasty": dynasties by definition involve the succession of rulers from one family: Wu's "Zhou dynasty" was founded by her, and ended within her lifetime, with her abdication (705).
simple: Wu was a concubine of Emperor Taizong. <s> After his death, she married his successor and 9th son, Emperor Gaozong in 655. <s> After Gaozong's stroke in 660, Wu Zetian ruled as effective sovereign until 705. <s> She ruled under the name of her self-proclaimed Zhou Dynasty, from 690 to 705.

title: Mark Rydell
complex: Mark Rydell (born March 23, 1929) is an American actor, film director and producer. <s> He has directed many Academy Award-nominated films including "The Fox" (1967), "The Reivers" (1969), "Cinderella Liberty" (1973), "The Rose" (1979), "The River" (1984) and "For the Boys" (1991). <s> He was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Director for "On Golden Pond" (1981).
simple: Mark Rydell (born Mortimer Horace Rydell; March 23, 1929) is an American actor, movie director and producer. <s> Rydell has directed many Academy Award-nominated movies including "The Fox" (1967), "The Reivers" (1969), "Cinderella Liberty" (1973), "The Rose" (1979), "The River" (1984) and "For the Boys" (1991). <s> Rydell was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Director for "On Golden Pond" (1981).

title: Friderico-Francisceum
complex: The Friderico-Francisceum (FFG) is a gymnasium in Bad Doberan, Germany. <s> After Frederick Francis II died in 1883, his successor Frederick Francis III named the school "Friderico-Francisceum" in honour of the founder. <s> In 1889, the gymnasium moved into its present-day building at "Alexandrinenplatz". <s> The schoolhouse had been constructed by Doberan-based architect Gotthilf Ludwig Möckel. <s> After the German reunification, the school was adjusted to West German educational norms in 1991. <s> The course system was adopted and students attended the gymnasium from grade 5 on. <s> Additionally, the original name "Friderico-Francisceum" has been reintroduced. <s> A newly built extension building right behind the main building opened in 2001, providing modern-day classrooms and teaching material.
simple: The Friderico-Francisceum is a secondary school (“gymnasium”). <s> It is in Bad Doberan, a town in Germany. <s> Its name is "Friderico-Francisceum", because the founder was named Frederick Francis II. <s> The main building of the school was built in 1889. <s> The architect of the building was Gotthilf Ludwig Möckel. <s> A new school building behind the old one opened in 2001.

title: Leevi Lehto
complex: Leevi Lehto (23 February 1951 – 22 June 2019) was a Finnish poet, translator, and programmer. <s> His translations, some forty books in total, range from mystery writing to philosophy, sociology, and poetry, including work by Louis Althusser, Gilles Deleuze, George Orwell, Stephen King, Ian McEwan, Josef Skvorecky, Walter Benjamin, John Keats, John Ashbery, Mickey Spillane and Charles Bernstein. <s> His latest work is the new Finnish translation of "Ulysses" by James Joyce. <s> Lehto died of multiple system atrophy on 22 June 2019, aged 68.
simple: Leevi Lehto (23 February 1951 – 22 June 2019) was a Finnish poet, translator, and programmer. <s> He translated the works of Louis Althusser, Gilles Deleuze, George Orwell, Stephen King, Ian McEwan, Josef Skvorecky, Walter Benjamin, John Keats, John Ashbery, Mickey Spillane and Charles Bernstein. <s> His best known work was theFinnish translation of "Ulysses" by James Joyce. <s> Lehto died of multiple system atrophy in Helsinki on 22 June 2019, aged 68.

title: NYPD Blue
complex: NYPD Blue is an American police procedural drama television series set in New York City, exploring the struggles of the fictional 15th Precinct detective squad in Manhattan. <s> Each episode typically intertwines several plots involving an ensemble cast. <s> The show was created by Steven Bochco and David Milch, and was inspired by Milch's relationship with Bill Clark, a former member of the New York City Police Department who eventually became one of the show's producers. <s> The series was originally broadcast on the ABC network, debuted on September 21, 1993‚ and aired its final episode on March 1, 2005. <s> It was ABC's longest-running primetime one-hour drama series until "Grey's Anatomy" surpassed it in 2016.
simple: NYPD Blue is an American television police drama set in New York City, inside the fictional 15th precinct of Manhattan. <s> The show was made by Steven Bochco and David Milch. <s> Its episodes were shown on the ABC network from its beginning on September 21, 1993 to March 1, 2005.

title: John Wall (inventor)
complex: John Wall (26 June 1932 – 27 January 2018) was an English design engineer, amateur astronomer, amateur telescope maker and member of the British Astronomical Association. <s> He lived in Coventry, England. <s> He is also known for designing dialyte based refracting telescopes, coming up with the "Zerochromat" retrofocally corrected refractor, including a folded 30-inch f/12 version he built in 1999. <s> This refracting telescope is the largest ever built by an individual and the equal fifth-largest refractor ever built. <s> Wall died on 27 January 2018.
simple: John Wall (26 June 1932 – 27 January 2018) was an English design engineer, amateur astronomer, and amateur telescope maker. <s> He was a member of the British Astronomical Association until his death in 2018. <s> He was known for designing dialyte based refracting telescopes, coming up with the "Zerochromat". <s> Wall died on 27 January 2018 in Coventry, Warwickshire at the age of 85.

title: Tremors (film)
complex: Tremors is a 1990 American monster comedy film directed by Ron Underwood, produced by Gale Anne Hurd, Brent Maddock, and S. S. Wilson, and written by Maddock, Wilson, and Underwood. <s> "Tremors" was released by Universal Pictures and stars Kevin Bacon, Fred Ward, Finn Carter, Michael Gross, and Reba McEntire.
simple: Tremors is an American science fiction comedy horror movie. <s> It is set in Nevada and is directed by Ron Underwood. <s> The screenplay was written by S.S. Wilson and Brent Maddock.

title: Ottenbach, Switzerland
complex: Ottenbach is a municipality in the district of Affoltern in the canton of Zürich in Switzerland.
simple: Ottenbach is a municipality of the district of Affoltern in the canton of Zurich in Switzerland.

title: Gold Coast (Florida)
complex: The Gold Coast is a region of the U.S. state of Florida. <s> It is located on the Atlantic coast of South Florida, including the cities of Miami, Ft. Lauderdale and West Palm Beach though its definition has changed over time. <s> One of the best known of Florida's vernacular regions, the name is a reference to the wealth and ritzy tropical lifestyle that characterizes the area.
simple: Gold Coast is a region on the southwestern coast of the US state of Florida between Tequesta and Florida City. <s> It includes the cities of Miami and Fort Lauderdale, as well as West Palm Beach, Boca Raton,and Hollywood.

title: Arch bridge
complex: An arch bridge is a bridge with abutments at each end shaped as a curved arch. <s> Arch bridges work by transferring the weight of the bridge and its loads partially into a horizontal thrust restrained by the abutments at either side. <s> A viaduct (a long bridge) may be made from a series of arches, although other more economical structures are typically used today. <s> Possibly the oldest existing arch bridge is the Mycenaean Arkadiko Bridge in Greece from about 1300 BC. <s> The stone corbel arch bridge is still used by the local populace. <s> The well-preserved Hellenistic Eleutherna Bridge has a triangular corbel arch. <s> The 4th century BC Rhodes Footbridge rests on an early voussoir arch. <s> Although true arches were already known by the Etruscans and ancient Greeks, the Romans were – as with the vault and the dome – the first to fully realize the potential of arches for bridge construction. <s> A list of Roman bridges compiled by the engineer Colin O'Connor features 330 Roman stone bridges for traffic, 34 Roman timber bridges and 54 Roman aqueduct bridges, a substantial part still standing and even used to carry vehicles. <s> A more complete survey by the Italian scholar Vittorio Galliazzo found 931 Roman bridges, mostly of stone, in as many as 26 different countries (including former Yugoslavia). <s> Roman arch bridges were usually semicircular, although a number were segmental arch bridges (such as Alconétar Bridge), a bridge which has a curved arch that is less than a semicircle. <s> The advantages of the segmental arch bridge were that it allowed great amounts of flood water to pass under it, which would prevent the bridge from being swept away during floods and the bridge itself could be more lightweight. <s> Generally, Roman bridges featured wedge-shaped primary arch stones (voussoirs) of the same in size and shape. <s> The Romans built both single spans and lengthy multiple arch aqueducts, such as the Pont du Gard and Segovia Aqueduct. <s> Their bridges featured from an early time onwards flood openings in the piers, e.g. in the Pons Fabricius in Rome (62 BC), one of the world's oldest major bridges still standing. <s> The Romans also introduced segmental arch bridges into bridge construction. <s> The 330 m Limyra Bridge in southwestern Turkey features 26 segmental arches with an average span-to-rise ratio of 5.3:1, giving the bridge an unusually flat profile unsurpassed for more than a millennium. <s> Trajan's bridge over the Danube featured open-spandrel segmental arches made of wood (standing on 40 m concrete piers). <s> This was to be the longest arch bridge for a thousand years both in terms of overall and individual span length, while the longest extant Roman bridge is the 790 m long Puente Romano at Mérida. <s> The late Roman Karamagara Bridge in Cappadocia may represent the earliest surviving bridge featuring a pointed arch. <s> In medieval Europe, bridge builders improved on the Roman structures by using narrower piers, thinner arch barrels and higher span to rise ratios on bridges. <s> Gothic pointed arches were also introduced, reducing lateral thrust, and spans increased as with the eccentric Puente del Diablo (1282). <s> The 14th century in particular saw bridge building reaching new heights. <s> Span lengths of 40 m , previously unheard of in the history of masonry arch construction, were now reached in places as diverse as Spain (Puente de San Martín), Italy (Castelvecchio Bridge) and France (Devil's bridge and Pont Grand) and with arch types as different as semi-circular, pointed and segmental arches. <s> The bridge at Trezzo sull'Adda, destroyed in the 15th century, even featured a span length of 72 m , not matched until 1796. <s> Stone, brick and other such materials are strong in compression and somewhat so in shear, but cannot resist much force in tension. <s> As a result, masonry arch bridges are designed to be constantly under compression, so far as is possible. <s> Each arch is constructed over a temporary falsework frame, known as a centring. <s> In the first compression arch bridges, a keystone in the middle of the bridge bore the weight of the rest of the bridge. <s> The more weight that was put onto the bridge, the stronger its structure became. <s> Masonry arch bridges use a quantity of fill material (typically compacted rubble) above the arch in order to increase this dead-weight on the bridge and prevent tension from occurring in the arch ring as loads move across the bridge. <s> Other materials that were used to build this type of bridge were brick and unreinforced concrete. <s> When masonry (cut stone) is used the angles of the faces are cut to minimize shear forces. <s> Where random masonry (uncut and unprepared stones) is used they are mortared together and the mortar is allowed to set before the falsework is removed.

title: Anupam Sen
complex: Anupam Sen (born 5 August 1940) is an social activist. <s> He is currently serving as the vice-chancellor of Premier University, Chittagong. <s> He was awarded Ekushey Padak in 2014 by the Government of Bangladesh.
simple: Anupam Sen (born August 5, 1940) is a Bangladeshi academic and social scientist. <s> Currently, he is serving as Vice-chancellor of Premier University, Chittagong. <s> He was awarded Ekushey Padak in 2014 by the Government of Bangladesh.

title: London and South Western Railway
complex: The London and South Western Railway (LSWR or L&SWR) was a railway company in England from 1838 to 1922. <s> Starting as the London and Southampton Railway, its network extended from London to Plymouth via Salisbury and Exeter, with branches to Ilfracombe and Padstow and via Southampton to Bournemouth and Weymouth. <s> It also had many routes connecting towns in Hampshire and Berkshire, including Portsmouth and Reading. <s> In the grouping of railways in 1923 the LSWR amalgamated with other railways to create the Southern Railway.
simple: The London and South Western Railway (LSWR) was a railway company in England from 1838 to 1922. <s> It started as the London and Southampton Railway from Waterloo station to Southampton. <s> Later, the network extended to Plymouth via Salisbury and Exeter. <s> There were branches to Ilfracombe and Padstow. <s> Beyond Southampton there were branches to Bournemouth and Weymouth. <s> The LSWR also had many routes connecting towns in Hampshire and Berkshire, including Portsmouth and Reading. <s> In the grouping of railways in 1923 the LSWR joined with other railways to create the Southern Railway.

title: Seychelles
complex: Seychelles ( ; ] or ] ), officially the Republic of Seychelles ( ; Creole: "La Repiblik Sesel"), is an archipelago country in the Indian Ocean. <s> The capital of the 115-island country, Victoria, lies 1500 km east of mainland East Africa. <s> Other nearby island countries and territories include Comoros, Mayotte (region of France), Madagascar, Réunion (region of France) and Mauritius to the south; as well as the Maldives and Chagos Archipelago to the east. <s> With a population of roughly , it has the smallest population of any sovereign African country. <s> Seychelles is divided into twenty-six administrative regions comprising all of the inner islands. <s> Eight of the districts make up the capital of Seychelles and are referred to as Greater Victoria. <s> Another 14 districts are considered the rural part of the main island of Mahé with two districts on Praslin and one on La Digue which also includes respective satellite islands. <s> The rest of the Outer Islands (" ") are the last district recently created by the tourism ministry. <s> An island nation, Seychelles is located in the Indian Ocean, northeast of Madagascar and about 1600 km east of Kenya. <s> The Constitution of Seychelles lists 155 named islands and a further 7 reclaimed islands have been created subsequent to the publication of the Constitution. <s> The majority of the islands are uninhabited, with many dedicated as nature reserves. <s> Seychelles is among the world's leading countries to protect lands for threatened species, allocating 42% of its territory for conservation. <s> Like many fragile island ecosystems, Seychelles saw the loss of biodiversity when humans first settled in the area, including the disappearance of most of the giant tortoises from the granitic islands, the felling of coastal and mid-level forests, and the extinction of species such as the chestnut flanked white eye, the Seychelles parakeet, and the saltwater crocodile. <s> However, extinctions were far fewer than on islands such as Mauritius or Hawaii, partly due to a shorter period of human occupation (since 1770). <s> Seychelles today is known for success stories in protecting its flora and fauna. <s> The rare Seychelles black parrot, the national bird of the country, is now protected. <s> The granitic islands of Seychelles are home to about 75 endemic plant species, with a further 25 or so species in the Aldabra group. <s> Particularly well-known is the coco de mer, a species of palm that grows only on the islands of Praslin and neighbouring Curieuse. <s> Sometimes nicknamed the "love nut" because the shape of its "double" coconut resembles buttocks, the coco-de-mer produces the world's heaviest seed. <s> The jellyfish tree is to be found in only a few locations on Mahe. <s> This strange and ancient plant in a genus of its own ("Medusagyne") seems to reproduce only in cultivation and not in the wild. <s> Other unique plant species include Wright's gardenia ("Rothmannia annae") found only on Aride Island Special Reserve. <s> The freshwater crab genus "Seychellum" is endemic to the granitic Seychelles, and a further 26 species of crabs and five species of hermit crabs live on the islands. <s> The Aldabra giant tortoise now populates many of the islands of Seychelles; the Aldabra population is the largest remaining. <s> These unique reptiles can be found even in captive herds. <s> The granitic islands of Seychelles may support distinct species of Seychelles giant tortoises; the status of the different populations is currently unclear. <s> There are several unique species of orchid on the islands. <s> The marine life around the islands, especially the more remote coral islands, can be spectacular. <s> More than 1,000 species of fish have been recorded. <s> Since the use of spearguns and dynamite for fishing was banned through efforts of local conservationists in the 1960s, the wildlife is unafraid of snorkelers and divers. <s> Coral bleaching in 1998 has damaged most reefs, but some reefs show healthy recovery (e.g., Silhouette Island). <s> French and English are official languages along with Seychellois Creole, which is primarily based upon French. <s> However, nowadays the language is often laced with English words and phrases. <s> Including second-language speakers, Seychellois is the most-spoken official language in the Seychelles, followed by French and English. <s> 87% of the population speaks Seychelles Creole, 51% speaks French, and 38% speaks English. <s> Most business and official meetings are conducted in English and nearly all official websites are in English. <s> National Assembly business is conducted in Creole, but laws are passed and published in English. <s> During the plantation era, cinnamon, vanilla and copra were the chief exports. <s> In 1965, during a three-month visit to the islands, futurist Donald Prell prepared for the then-crown colony Governor General an economic report containing a scenario for the future of the economy. <s> Quoting from his report, in the 1960s, about 33% of the working population worked at plantations, and 20% worked in the public or government sector. <s> The Indian Ocean Tracking Station on Mahé used by the Air Force Satellite Control Network was closed in August 1996 after the Seychelles government attempted to raise the rent to more than $10,000,000 per year. <s> In 1971, with the opening of Seychelles International Airport, tourism became a significant industry, essentially dividing the economy into plantations and tourism. <s> The tourism sector paid better, and the plantation economy could only expand so far.

title: Nancy Travis
complex: Nancy Ann Travis (born September 21, 1961) is an American actress. <s> Travis was born in Queens, the daughter of Theresa, a social worker, and Gordon Travis, a sales executive. <s> Travis was raised in Framingham, Massachusetts, and Baltimore, Maryland. <s> She was raised Catholic.
simple: Nancy Travis (born September 21, 1961 in New York City) is a television and movie actress. <s> Travis was born in New York City, the daughter of Theresa, a social worker, and Gordon Travis, a sales executive. <s> Travis was raised in Boston, Massachusetts, and Baltimore, Maryland.

title: Saffron cod
complex: The saffron cod "(Eleginus gracilis)" is a commercially harvested fish closely related to true cods (genus "Gadus"). <s> It is dark grey-green to brown, with spots on its sides and pale towards the belly. <s> It may grow to 60 cm and weigh up to 1.3 kg. <s> Its range spans the North Pacific, from Korea and the Sea of Okhotsk in the west to the northern Gulf of Alaska and eastern Banks Island in the east. <s> It normally occurs in shallow coastal waters at less than 60 m depth but may also be found at depths up to 200 m. <s> The saffron cod may also enter brackish and even fresh waters, occurring quite far up rivers and streams, but remaining within regions of tidal influence. <s> Saffron cods begin to mature during their third year of life. <s> They feed on fish and small crustaceans. <s> They are commercially fished in many areas of the northwestern Pacific. <s> The country with the largest catch is Russia. <s> It is used for human consumption in the Russian Federation and Japan, fresh or frozen.
simple: The saffron cod "(Eleginus gracilis)", is a type of fish. <s> They are closely related to true cods (genus "Gadus"). <s> It is dark grey-green to brown, with spots on its sides and pale towards the belly. <s> It may grow to 60 cm and weigh up to 1.3 kg. <s> It normally is found in shallow coastal waters at less than 60 m depth. <s> It may also be found at depths up to 200 m. <s> The saffron cod may also enter brackish and even fresh waters, occurring quite far up rivers and streams. <s> Saffron cods begin to mature during their third year of life. <s> They feed on fish and small crustaceans. <s> They are commercially fished in many areas of the northwestern Pacific. <s> The country with the largest catch is Russia. <s> It is used for human's to eat in the Russian Federation and Japan, fresh or frozen.

title: Jean-Louis Koszul
complex: Jean-Louis Koszul (] ; January 3, 1921 – January 12, 2018) was a French mathematician, best known for studying geometry and discovering the Koszul complex. <s> He was a second generation member of Bourbaki. <s> He lectured at many universities and was appointed in 1963 professor in the Faculty of Science at the University of Grenoble. <s> He was a member of the French Academy of Sciences. <s> He died on January 12, 2018 at the age of 97, nine days after his 97th birthday.
simple: Jean-Louis Koszul (]; January 3, 1921 – January 12, 2018) was a French mathematician. <s> Koszul was best known for studying geometry and discovering the Koszul complex. <s> From 1980 until his death, Koszul was a member of the French Academy of Sciences. <s> Koszul died on January 12, 2018 in Paris at the age of 97.

title: Lawnchair Larry flight
complex: The 45-minute successful flight of Larry Walters on July 2, 1982, was in a homemade airship made of an ordinary patio chair and 45 helium-filled weather balloons. <s> The aircraft rose to an altitude of over 15000 ft and floated from the point of takeoff in San Pedro, California, into and violating controlled airspace near Los Angeles International Airport. <s> During the landing, the aircraft became entangled in power lines, but Walters was able to safely climb down. <s> The flight attracted worldwide media attention and inspired a later movie and imitators. <s> Lawrence Richard Walters (April 19, 1949 – October 6, 1993) had often dreamed of flying, but was unable to become a pilot in the United States Air Force because of his poor eyesight. <s> He first thought of using weather balloons to fly at age 13, after seeing them hanging from the ceiling of a military surplus store. <s> He had a career as an American truck driver. <s> In 1982, he decided to try his flying idea. <s> His intention was to float over the Mojave Desert and then use a pellet gun to burst some of the balloons in order to land. <s> In mid-1982, Walters and his girlfriend at the time, Carol Van Deusen, purchased 45 8 ft weather balloons and obtained helium tanks from California Toy Time Balloons. <s> They used a forged requisition from his employer, FilmFair Studios, saying the balloons were for a television commercial. <s> On July 2, 1982, Walters attached 43 of the balloons to his lawn chair, filled them with helium, put on a parachute, and strapped himself into the chair in the backyard of a home at 1633 West 7th Street in San Pedro. <s> He took his pellet gun, a CB radio, sandwiches, beer, and a camera. <s> When his friends cut the cord that tied his lawn chair to his Jeep, Walters's lawn chair rose rapidly to a height of about 16000 ft and was spotted from two commercial airliners. <s> He slowly drifted over Long Beach and crossed the primary approach corridor of Long Beach Airport. <s> After 45 minutes in the sky, Walters shot several balloons, taking care not to unbalance the load. <s> He then accidentally dropped his pellet gun overboard. <s> He descended slowly, until the balloons' dangling cables got caught in a power line at 432 45th Street in Long Beach. <s> The power line broke, causing a 20-minute electricity blackout. <s> He landed unharmed on the ground. <s> Walters was immediately arrested by waiting members of the Long Beach Police Department. <s> Regional safety inspector Neal Savoy was reported to have said, "We know he broke some part of the Federal Aviation Act, and as soon as we decide which part it is, some type of charge will be filed. <s> If he had a pilot's license, we'd suspend that, but he doesn't." <s> Walters initially was fined $4,000 for violations under U.S. Federal Aviation Regulations, including operating an aircraft within an airport traffic area "without establishing and maintaining two-way communications with the control tower." <s> Walters appealed, and the fine was reduced to $1,500. <s> A charge of operating a "civil aircraft for which there is not currently in effect an airworthiness certificate" was dropped, as it was not applicable to his class of aircraft. <s> The aircraft was dubbed "Inspiration I". <s> Lawn Chair Larry was awarded the title of "At-Risk Survivor" in the 1993 Darwin Awards. <s> After his flight, Walters was briefly in demand as a motivational speaker, and quit his job as a truck driver. <s> He was featured in a Timex print ad in the early 1990s, but never made much money from his fame. <s> The lawn chair used in the flight was reportedly given to an admiring boy named Jerry, though Walters regretted doing so when the Smithsonian Institution asked him to donate it to its museum. <s> Twenty years later, Jerry sent an email to Mark Barry, a pilot who had documented Walters' story and dedicated a website to it, and identified himself. <s> The chair was still sitting in his garage, attached to some of the original tethers and water jugs used as ballast. <s> The chair was on loan to the San Diego Air and Space Museum, on exhibition through 2014. <s> Later in his life, Walters hiked the San Gabriel Mountains and did volunteer work for the United States Forest Service. <s> He later broke up with his girlfriend of 15 years and could only find work sporadically as a security guard. <s> On October 6, 1993, at the age of 44, Walters committed suicide by shooting himself in the heart in Angeles National Forest.

1993) was an American truck driver. <s> Walters had always dreamed of flying. <s> He was unable to become a pilot in the United States Air Force because he could not see well enough. <s> Walters had helium tanks from California Toy Time Balloons. <s> They used a fake letter from his employer, FilmFair Studios. <s> It said the balloons were for a television commercial. <s> On 2 July 1982 he flew very high in the sky in a homemade aircraft. <s> He planned to attach a few large balloons filled with helium to his lawnchair and then float above his backyard. <s> They went to the backyard of a home at 1633 W. 7th St. in San Pedro Walters attached the balloons to his lawnchair, filled them with helium. <s> He put on a parachute and used belts to hold himself in the chair. <s> He tied 105 large helium balloons to his lawn chair. <s> He took his pellet gun, a CB radio, sandwiches, cold beer, and a camera. <s> His friends cut the rope that tied his lawn chair to his Jeep and Walters' lawnchair went up very quickly. <s> He slowly passed over Long Beach and moved into the space where airplanes came into Long Beach Airport. <s> After 45 minutes in the sky, he shot several balloons. <s> Then he accidentally dropped his pellet gun. <s> He went down slowly until cables hanging from the balloon got caught in an electrical power line. <s> This caused a blackout in a Long Beach neighborhood for 20 minutes. <s> The Long Beach Police Department was waiting for him. <s> They arrested him immediately. <s> At first, Walters was fined US$4,000 for breaking U. S. Federal Aviation Regulations. <s> Walters tried to have the fine cancelled. <s> It was reduced to US$1,500. <s> After his flight, he quit his job as a truck driver. <s> He was in a Timex print advertisement in the early '90s, He also gave speeches to help people get more confidence. <s> But, he never made much money from being famous. <s> Later, Walters realized that was a mistake when the Smithsonian Institute asked him to donate it to its museum. <s> Twenty years later, Jerry contacted Mark Barry. <s> Barry is a pilot who wrote about Walters and made a website about his flight. <s> The chair was still sitting in Jerry's garage and had some of the original ropes and water jugs. <s> Walters hiked in the San Gabriel Mountains and did volunteer work for the United States Forest Service. <s> He broke up with his girlfriend after 15 years. <s> He worked as a security guard sometimes. <s> In 1993, Walters shot himself in the heart in Angeles National Forest and died. <s> He was 44 years old.

title: Henrik Eriksson (cross-country skier)
complex: Henrik Eriksson, born 1974, is a Swedish former cross-country skier. <s> When it came to club competitions, he competed for IFK Mora. <s> Competing at elite level between 1994 and 2006, he participated at Vasaloppet several times, winning the event in 2001. <s> In Vasaloppet 2002, he ended up 9th and Vasaloppet in 2004 he ended up 10th.
