title: Jewish Territorial Organization
complex: The Jewish Territorial Organisation, known as the ITO, was a Jewish political movement which first arose in 1903 in response to the British Uganda Offer, but which was institutionalized in 1905. <s> Its main goal was to find an alternative territory to that of the Land of Israel, which was preferred by the Zionist movement, for the creation of a Jewish homeland. <s> The organization embraced what became known as "Jewish Territorialism" also known as "Jewish Statism" (though not to be confused with the political philosophy of the same name). <s> The ITO was dissolved in 1925. <s> The Jewish Colonization Association, created in 1891 by the Baron Maurice de Hirsch, was aimed at facilitating mass emigration of Jews from the Russian Empire and other Eastern European countries, by settling them in agricultural colonies on lands purchased by the committee, particularly in North and South America (especially Argentina). <s> Before 1905 some Zionist leaders took seriously proposals for Jewish homelands in places other than the Land of Israel. <s> Theodor Herzl hoped for a Jewish homeland in the Land of Israel but recognized that global events demanded an immediate solution to the Jewish problem, in Russia at least, even if that solution required Jewish refugees to settle outside of Eretz Israel. <s> Theodor Herzl's "Der Judenstaat" argued for a Jewish state in either Palestine, "our ever-memorable historic home", or Argentina, "one of the most fertile countries in the world". <s> Many of the socialist Zionist groups were more territorialist than Zionist, such as Nachman Syrkin's Zionist Socialist Workers Party (the Z.S.). <s> In 1903 British cabinet ministers suggested the British Uganda Program, land for a Jewish state in "Uganda" (actually in modern Kenya). <s> Herzl initially rejected the idea, preferring Palestine, but after the April 1903 Kishinev pogrom Herzl introduced a controversial proposal to the Sixth Zionist Congress to investigate the offer as a temporary measure for Russian Jews in danger. <s> Notwithstanding its emergency and temporary nature, the proposal still proved very divisive, and widespread opposition to the plan was demonstrated by a walkout led by the Russian Jewish delegation to the Congress. <s> Few historians believe that such a settlement scheme could have attracted immigrants, Jewish financial support, or international political support. <s> Since there was strong support on the part of some members of the Zionist leadership, however, peace was kept in the movement by the time-honored parliamentary maneuver of voting to establish a committee for the investigation of the possibility, which was not finally dismissed until the 7th Zionist Congress in 1905. <s> The Jewish Territorial Organization (ITO) was founded by British Jewish author, critic, and activist Israel Zangwill and British Jewish journalist Lucien Wolf in 1903 and institutionalized in 1905. <s> The establishment was a response to Herzl's rejection of Uganda proposal, as the ITO led by Zangwill split off from the Zionist movement. <s> It attempted to locate territory suitable for Jewish settlement in various parts of America (e.g. Galveston), and on the African, Asian, and Australian continents, yet with little success. <s> In 1905 the members of the Seventh Zionist Congress formally rejected the Uganda Scheme. <s> Following the rejection of the East Africa offer, Zangwill contacted Lucien Wolf, an English Jewish journalist and member of the Board of Deputies of British Jews, the main representative body of Anglo Jewry. <s> Wolf was an opponent of political Zionism, but did support the creation of Jewish colonies in the Diaspora. <s> In August 1905 Zangwill and Wolf met to discuss the Uganda Scheme, and in subsequent correspondence between the two we learn that both supported the creation of a Jewish colony in British East Africa. <s> Wolf had objected to any specifically "Jewish national homeland", that is to say a state which ghettoized Jews, preserving Jewish customs and law as the basis for governance. <s> Though Zangwill's literary works suggest his nostalgia for the ghetto, he too recognized the need for a modern Jewish polity. <s> Both concurred that a self-governing Jewish territory should be based on a preponderance of Jews in the region rather than British legislative fiat, and both concurred that the new government should be formed on a modern, democratic basis rather than some earlier biblical ideal or Eastern European Kehilla structure. <s> This basic agreement between Zangwill and Wolf would lead to the formation of the Jewish Territorial Organisation (ITO), an organisation dedicated to "obtaining a large tract of territory (preferably within the British Empire) wherein to found a Jewish Home of Refuge", and to the elevation of Zangwill to the ITO presidency. <s> After the October Revolution there was in the USSR a Territorialist effort in Ukraine, the Crimea and then in a region surrounding Birobidzhan, where a Jewish Autonomous Region was established in 1934. <s> (The Jewish Autonomous Oblast (JAO) ( , "Yevreyskaya avtonomnaya oblast"; ) is still today an autonomous oblast situated in Russia's far east.) <s> In the United States, the Organization for Jewish Colonization in Russia worked to encourage the emigration and settlement of Jews there. <s> In the face of the looming Nazi genocide, Isaac Nachman Steinberg established the Freeland League for Jewish Territorial Colonization in the United States in 1935. <s> This organization attempted, unsuccessfully, to pursue Jewish autonomy by obtaining a large piece of territory in sparsely populated areas in Ecuador, Australia, or Surinam. <s> One of the more well-known ventures was the Kimberley Plan, to secure land in Australia. <s> The Kimberley Plan was officially vetoed on 15 July 1944 by Australian Prime Minister, John Curtin, who informed Steinberg that the Australian government would not "depart from the long-established policy in regard to alien settlement in Australia" and could not "entertain the proposal for a group settlement of the exclusive type contemplated by the Freeland League". <s> After the establishment of the State of Israel in 1948, Steinberg criticized the exclusivist politics of the Israeli government and continued his attempts to create a non-nationalist Jewish settlement in some other region of the world. <s> After Steinberg's death in 1957 the Freeland League was led by Mordkhe Schaechter, who gradually changed the focus of the organization to more cultural, Yiddishist goals.
simple: Territorialism, also known as Statism (but not to be confused with another belief also called statism), was a Jewish political movement related to Zionism. <s> The ITO broke up in 1925. <s> The Jewish Colonization Association, started in 1891 by the Baron Maurice de Hirsch, was started to help move many Jews from Russia and other Eastern European countries. <s> Before 1905, some Zionist leaders were thinking about making places for Jews to call home other than Palestine. <s> Theodor Herzl's "Der Judenstaat" argued for a Jewish state in either Palestine, "our ever-memorable historic home", or Argentina, "one of the most fertile countries in the world". <s> Many of the socialist Zionist groups were more territorialist than Zionist, such as Nachman Syrkin's Zionist Socialist Workers Party (the Z.S.). <s> In 1903, British cabinet ministers suggested the British Uganda Programme, land for a Jewish state in "Uganda" (the land they were thinking about is actually in the modern country of Kenya). <s> At first, Herzl said no to the idea, because he liked Palestine better. <s> After the April 1903 Kishinev pogrom, in which many Jews were violently attacked in Russia, Herzl suggested to the Sixth Zionist Congress to look at the offer as a temporary way to keep Russian Jews safe. <s> The plan was very controversial, and many Russian Jews were so upset that they walked out of the meeting. <s> Few historians believe that such a settlement idea could have attracted immigrants, received much money in donations, or been supported by many other countries. <s> Because some members of the Zionist leadership liked the idea, however, peace was kept in the movement because they voted to start a committee to look at the possibility. <s> Because of this, the Jewish Territorialist Organization (ITO) led by Israel Zangwill split off from the Zionist movement. <s> It tried to find land where Jews could settle in different parts of America (e.g. Galveston), Africa, Asia, and Australia, but with little success. <s> They did not officially say no to the idea until the Seventh Zionist Congress in 1905. <s> Apart from the (ITO), within the USSR there was also a Territorialist effort in Ukraine, the Crimea and then in a region around Birobidzhan, where a Jewish Autonomous Region was started in 1934. <s> As the Holocaust became close and as Nazis were discriminating against Jews in Germany, Isaac Nachman Steinberg started the Freeland League in the United States in 1935. <s> This organization tried, but did not succeed, to start a new Jewish country by getting a large piece of land in places in Ecuador, Australia, or Suriname where not many people lived. <s> One of the more well-known tries was the Kimberley Plan, to get land in Australia. <s> After the State of Israel was created in 1948, Steinberg had criticized the exclusivist politics of the Zionist government and continued his attempts to create a non-nationalist Jewish settlement in some other part of the world. <s> After Steinberg died in 1957, the Freeland League was led by Mordkhe Schaechter, who gradually changed the focus of the organization to more cultural, Yiddishist goals.

title: Camberwell railway station (England)
complex: Camberwell is a closed railway station in Camberwell, South London, England. <s> It opened in 1862 but was closed to passengers in 1916 and closed to all traffic in 1964. <s> The possibility of the station's re-opening has been raised in recent years.
simple: Camberwell is a closed railway station in Camberwell, South London, England. <s> It was opened in 1862 by the London, Chatham and Dover Railway. <s> It closed to passengers in 1916 and closed to all traffic in 1964.

title: Pandemic Studios
complex: Pandemic Studios was an independent developer founded in 1998. <s> Between 2007 and 2009 it became an Electronic Arts-owned developer, and shortly afterwards closed. <s> It was an American and Australian video game developer with offices in Los Angeles, California and Brisbane, Australia. <s> Notable titles include "Full Spectrum Warrior", "", "Dark Reign 2", "Destroy All Humans!", <s> , "", "", "" and "The Saboteur". <s> The company's president Josh Resnick and CEO Andrew Goldman — both formerly worked at Activision, along with most of the original team members from Battlezone and Dark Reign founded the company in 1998. <s> Pandemic was founded with an equity investment by Activision in 1998. <s> The Company's name was narrowed down from around six choices, including Seismic .I <s> In the end, Pandemic was chosen as the company's name. <s> Pandemic's first two games, "" and "Dark Reign 2", were both sequels to Activision games. <s> In February 2009, their office in Brisbane, Australia was shut down. <s> In November 2009, Electronic Arts cut a total of 1,500 jobs which affected various studios, including shutting down of Pandemic. <s> On November 17, 2009, EA officially confirmed Pandemic Studios' closure, laying off 228 employees. <s> EA absorbed 35 Pandemic employees into its EA Los Angeles studio to support "The Saboteur" and an unannounced project which was later revealed to be "Mercs Inc", a sequel to the "Mercenaries" series. <s> In response, a few former employees of Pandemic created an Office Space-style video where they are shown smashing their office printer.
simple: Pandemic Studios was a video game developer that was started in 1998. <s> It became owned by Electronic Arts from 2007 to 2009. <s> It was an Australian and American company, with offices in Brisbane and Los Angeles. <s> Pandemic Studios developed the first two main titles of the successful ; those were "" and "". <s> Their office in Brisbane was closed in February 2009. <s> In November 2009, Electronic Arts cut a total of 1,500 jobs, including at Pandemic. <s> The company was officially closed on 17 November 2009. <s> The rest of the staff were moved to EA Los Angeles to support "Mercs Inc", a sequel to the "Mercenaries" series.

title: Homophone
complex: A homophone is a word that is pronounced the same (to varying extent) as another word but differs in meaning. <s> A homophone may also differ in spelling.
simple: Homophones are words that sound the same as another word but have a different meaning, and often a different spelling.

title: 1964 Summer Paralympics
complex: The 1964 Summer Paralympics (Japanese: 第二回パラリンピック夏季競技大会 , Hepburn: Dai Ni-kai Pararinpikku Kyōgi Taikai ) , originally known as the 13th International Stoke Mandeville Games and also known as Paralympic Tokyo 1964, were the second Paralympic Games to be held. <s> They were held in Tokyo, Japan, and were the last Summer Paralympics to take place in the same city as the Summer Olympics until the 1988 Summer Paralympics.
simple: The 1964 Summer Paralympics took place in Tokyo, Japan.

title: Lockheed Martin X-35
complex: The Lockheed Martin X-35 was a concept demonstrator aircraft (CDA) developed by Lockheed Martin for the Joint Strike Fighter program. <s> The X-35 was declared winner over the competing Boeing X-32 and a developed, armed version went on to enter production in the early 21st century as the F-35 Lightning II.
simple: The Lockheed-Martin X-35 is a prototype aircraft designed and built in the United States. <s> It was selected against the Boeing X-32 for the Joint Strike Fighter program.

title: Michael Jayston
complex: Michael James (born 29 October 1935), known professionally as Michael Jayston, is an English actor. <s> He appeared in the BBC comedy series "Only Fools and Horses" episode Time on Our Hands in 1996, playing Raquel's father, James. <s> He also portrayed The Valeyard in all fourteen episodes of the 1986 "Doctor Who" serial "The Trial of a Time Lord", alongside Colin Baker and the late Linda Bellingham.
simple: Michael James (born 29 October 1935), known professionally as Michael Jayston, is an English actor. <s> He appeared in the BBC comedy series "Only Fools and Horses" in 1996, playing Raquel's father. <s> He also played The Valeyard in the 1986 "Doctor Who" serial The Trial of a Time Lord.

title: Marta Arce Payno
complex: Marta Arce Payno (born 27 July 1977) is a B3 classified Spanish judo competitor who has represented Spain at the 2004, 2008 and 2012 Summer Paralympics where s has won a pair of silver medals and a bronze medal. <s> The first IPC European Judo Championships Arce competed in were the ones hosted in Città di Castello where she picked up a gold medal.
simple: Marta Arce Payno (born July 27, 1977 in Valladolid) is a judo athlete from Spain. <s> She competed in judo at the 2004 Summer Paralympics, 2008 Summer Paralympics and 2012 Summer Paralympics.

title: Ancient woodland
complex: In the United Kingdom, an ancient woodland is a woodland that has existed continuously since 1600 or before in England, Wales and Northern Ireland (or 1750 in Scotland). <s> Planting of woodland was uncommon before those dates, so a wood present in 1600 is likely to have developed naturally. <s> For many species of animal and plant, ancient woodland sites provide the sole habitat, and for many others, conditions on these sites are much more suitable than those on other sites. <s> Ancient woodland in the UK, like rainforest in the tropics, is home to rare and threatened species. <s> For these reasons ancient woodland is often described as an irreplaceable resource, or 'critical natural capital'. <s> The analogous term used in the United States is "Old-growth forest". <s> Ancient woodland is formally defined on maps by Natural England and equivalent bodies. <s> Mapping of ancient woodland has been undertaken in different ways and at different times, and the quality and availability of data varies from region to region, although there are some efforts to standardise and update it. <s> Many ancient woodlands have legal protection of various types, but it is not automatically the case that any ancient woodland is protected. <s> Some examples of ancient woodland are nationally or locally designated, for example as Sites of Special Scientific Interest.
simple: Ancient woodland is the name used in the United Kingdom for woodland which has existed continuously since 1600 or before in England and Wales (or 1750 in Scotland). <s> Before those dates, planting of new woodland was uncommon, so a wood present in 1600 was likely to have developed naturally. <s> For many species of animal and plant, ancient woodland sites provide the only habitat. <s> For many others, conditions on these sites are much more suitable than those on other sites. <s> Ancient woodland in the UK, like rainforest in the tropics, is home to rare and threatened species, more than any other UK habitat. <s> For these reasons ancient woodland is often described as an irreplaceable resource, or 'critical natural capital'. <s> The American name for these forests is "old growth forest". <s> Ancient woodland is formally defined on maps by Natural England and equivalent bodies. <s> Many ancient woodlands have legal protection, but an ancient woodland is not automatically protected.

title: Flag of El Salvador
complex: The flag of El Salvador features a horizontal triband of cobalt blue-white-cobalt blue, with the coat of arms centered and entirely contained within the central white stripe. <s> This design of a triband of blue-white-blue is commonly used among Central American countries.
simple: It has two horizontal blue bands at the top and bottom and a white band in the middle with the Coat of arms of El Salvador in the center.

complex: Richard Herrmann (28 January 1923 in Katowice, Poland – 27 July 1962) was a German football player. <s> He played for the clubs 1.
simple: Richard Herrmann (28 January 1923 - 27 July 1962) was a German football player.

title: Peak District
complex: The Peak District is an upland area in England at the southern end of the Pennines. <s> It is mostly in northern Derbyshire, but also includes parts of Cheshire, Greater Manchester, Staffordshire, West Yorkshire and South Yorkshire. <s> An area of great diversity, it is mostly split into the Dark Peak, where most of the moorland is found and the geology is gritstone, and the limestone area of the White Peak. <s> The Peak District National Park became the first national park in the United Kingdom in 1951. <s> With its proximity to the cities of Manchester, Stoke-on-Trent, Derby and Sheffield, and access by road and rail, it attracts millions of visitors every year. <s> The Peak District is at the southern end of the Pennines and much of the area is upland above 1000 ft . <s> Its high point is Kinder Scout at 2087 ft . <s> Despite its name, the landscape generally lacks sharp peaks, and is characterised mostly by rounded hills, plateaus, valleys, limestone gorges and gritstone escarpments (the "edges"). <s> The area, mostly rural, is surrounded by conurbations and large urban areas including Manchester, Huddersfield, Sheffield, Derby and Stoke-on-Trent. <s> The Peak is formed almost exclusively from sedimentary rocks dating from the Carboniferous period. <s> They comprise the Carboniferous Limestone, overlying Gritstone and the Coal Measures which occur only on the extreme margins and infrequent outcrops of igneous rocks including lavas, tuffs and volcanic vent agglomerates. <s> The general geological structure is that of a broad dome, whose western margins have been most intensely faulted and folded. <s> Uplift and erosion have effectively sliced the top off the dome to reveal a concentric outcrop pattern with Coal Measures rocks on the eastern and western margins, Carboniferous Limestone at the core and with rocks of Millstone Grit outcropping between them. <s> The southern edge of the dome is overlain by sandstones of Triassic age though they barely impinge on the National Park. <s> The White Peak is the central and southern section where Carboniferous Limestone is found at or near the surface. <s> The Dark Peak to the north, east and west is characterised by Millstone Grit outcrops and broad swathes of moorland. <s> Earth movements after the Carboniferous period resulted in the up-doming of the area and, particularly in the west, the folding of the rock strata along north–south axes. <s> The region was raised in a north–south line which resulted in the dome-like shape and the shales and sandstones were worn away until limestone was exposed. <s> At the end of this period, the Earth's crust sank here which led to the area being covered by sea, depositing a variety of new rocks. <s> Some time after its deposition, mineral veins were formed in the limestone. <s> The veins and rakes have been mined for lead since Roman times. <s> The Peak District was covered by ice during at least one of the ice ages of the last 2 million years (probably the Anglian glaciation of around 450,000 years ago) as evidenced by the patches of glacial till or boulder clay that can be found across the area. <s> It was not covered by ice during the last glacial period, which peaked around 20,000–22,000 years ago. <s> A mix of Irish Sea and Lake District ice abutted against its western margins. <s> Glacial meltwaters eroded a complex of sinuous channels along this margin of the district during this period. <s> Glacial meltwaters contributed to the formation and development of many caves in the limestone area. <s> Wild animal herds roamed the area, and their remains have been found in several of the local caves. <s> The different types of rock beneath the soil strongly influence the landscape; they determine the type of vegetation that will grow, and ultimately the type of animal that will inhabit the area. <s> Limestone has fissures and is soluble in water, therefore rivers have been able to carve deep, narrow valleys. <s> The rivers then often find routes underground, creating cave systems. <s> Millstone Grit is insoluble but porous, absorbing water which seeps through the grits, until it meets the less porous shales beneath, creating springs where it reaches the surface. <s> The shales are friable and easily attacked by frost and form areas that are vulnerable to landslides, as on Mam Tor.
simple: The Peak District is an upland area in England at the southern end of the Pennines. <s> It is mostly in northern Derbyshire but also includes parts of Cheshire, Greater Manchester, Staffordshire and Yorkshire. <s> The northern 'Dark Peak' is where most of the moorland is found. <s> The Peak District National Park became the first national park in the United Kingdom in 1951. <s> It attracts many visitors every year. <s> Much of the area is uplands above 1000 ft, with a high point on Kinder Scout of 2087 ft. Despite its name, the landscape generally lacks sharp peaks, but has rounded hills and gritstone escarpments (the "edges"). <s> The area is surrounded by major conurbations, including Huddersfield, Manchester, Sheffield, Derby and Stoke-on-Trent. <s> The Peak District is formed almost exclusively from sedimentary rocks dating from the Carboniferous period. <s> They comprise the Carboniferous limestone, the overlying gritstone and finally the coal measures at the margins of the area. <s> There are outcrops of igneous rocks including lavas, tuffs and volcanic vent agglomerates. <s> Earth movements after the Carboniferous period resulted in the up-doming of the area. <s> This resulted in the dome-like shape. <s> The shale and sandstone were worn away until limestone was exposed. <s> At the end of this period, the Earth's crust sank here which led to the area being covered by sea, depositing a variety of new rocks. <s> Some time after its deposition, mineral veins were formed in the limestone. <s> These veins and rakes have been mined for lead since Roman times. <s> The Peak District was covered by ice during at least one of the ice ages of the last 2 million years. <s> Glacial meltwaters eroded a complex of sinuous channels along the margin of the Peak District during this period. <s> Glacial meltwaters helped form many of the caves in the limestone area. <s> Wild animal herds roamed the area, and their remains have been found in several of the local caves. <s> The different types of rock that lie beneath the soil strongly influence the landscape. <s> They determine the vegetation and so the animals that will live in the area. <s> Limestone has fissures (cracks) and is soluble in water, so rivers carve deep, narrow valleys. <s> These rivers then often find a route underground, creating cave systems. <s> Millstone Grit on the other hand is insoluble but porous, so it absorbs water. <s> Water moves through the grits until it meets the less porous shales beneath, creating springs when it reaches the surface again. <s> The shales are friable and easily attacked by frost. <s> They form areas where landslides may occur, as on Mam Tor.

title: Sic semper tyrannis
complex: Sic semper tyrannis is a Latin phrase meaning "thus always to tyrants".
simple: Sic semper tyrannis is a Latin phrase attributed to Marcus Iunius Brutus, one of the people who assassinated Julius Caesar. <s> It can be translated as "Thus always to tyrants". <s> It is a shortened version of the phrase "Sic semper evello mortem tyrannis" ("Thus always I bring death to tyrants").

title: The Kippax
complex: The Kippax was one of the best known and vocally active terraced stands at Manchester City's Maine Road ground. <s> Originally the Popular Side when the stadium opened in 1923, its name was changed in 1956 when the club gained planning permission to build a roof to shield fans from the rain. <s> It was named after Kippax Street which ran along this side of the ground. <s> The Kippax was unusual in that, unlike at most other grounds, it occupied a full side rather than an end of the ground as with goal end terraces like Liverpool's Kop, Manchester United's Stretford End, Everton's Gwladys Street, Newcastle United's Gallowgate or Aston Villa's Holte End. <s> In the summer of 1994, due to the Taylor Report, the Kippax was demolished. <s> A new all seater stand was built in its place and opened by City legend Bert Trautmann in October 1995. <s> It housed 10,178 seated fans, had three tiers and was at the time the highest stand in the country. <s> The club left Maine Road in May 2003 and relocated to the City of Manchester Stadium. <s> The old stadium was demolished in early 2004. <s> Unofficially, the East Stand at the new stadium is also called The Kippax.
simple: The Kippax was one of the most well known stands at Manchester City's Maine Road Ground. <s> The Kippax was unusual in that unlike in most other grounds, this area of support occupied a full side rather than an end of the ground. <s> In 1994, due to the Taylor Report, the new redeveloped, all seater stand was opened by City legend Bert Trautmann. <s> It housed 10,000 fans and had three levels. <s> At the time it was the highest stand in the country. <s> The club left the Maine Road ground in 2003 and moved to the new City of Manchester Stadium.. <s> Unofficially, the East stand in the new stadium is also named Kippax.

title: Villemer, Yonne
complex: Villemer is a former commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France. <s> On 1 January 2016, it was merged into the new commune of Valravillon.
simple: Villemer is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Virieu-le-Petit
complex: Virieu-le-Petit is a former commune in the Ain department in eastern France. <s> On 1 January 2019, it was merged into the new commune Arvière-en-Valromey.
simple: Virieu-le-Petit is a former commune. <s> On 1 January 2019, it was merged into the new commune of Arvière-en-Valromey.

title: Complaint
complex: In legal terminology, a complaint is any formal legal document that sets out the facts and legal reasons (see: cause of action) that the filing party or parties (the plaintiff(s)) believes are sufficient to support a claim against the party or parties against whom the claim is brought (the defendant(s)) that entitles the plaintiff(s) to a remedy (either money damages or injunctive relief). <s> For example, the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure (FRCP) that govern civil litigation in United States courts provide that a civil action is commenced with the filing or service of a pleading called a complaint. <s> Civil court rules in states that have incorporated the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure use the same term for the same pleading. <s> In some jurisdictions, specific types of criminal cases may also be commenced by the filing of a complaint, also sometimes called a criminal complaint or felony complaint. <s> Most criminal cases are prosecuted in the name of the governmental authority that promulgates criminal statutes and enforces the police power of the state with the goal of seeking criminal sanctions, such as the State (also sometimes called the People) or Crown (in Commonwealth realms). <s> In the United States, the complaint is often associated with misdemeanor criminal charges presented by the prosecutor without the grand jury process. <s> In most U.S. jurisdictions, the charging instrument presented to and authorized by a grand jury is referred to as an indictment. <s> For example, in United States federal courts, any person who is at least 18 years old and not a party may serve a summons and complaint in a civil case. <s> The defendant must submit an answer within 21 days after being served with the summons and complaint, or request a waiver, according to FRCP Rule 12. <s> After the civil complaint has been served to the defendants, the plaintiff must, as soon as practicable initiate a conference between the parties to plan for the rest of the discovery process and then the parties should submit a proposed discovery plan to the judge within 14 days after the conference.
simple: In legal terminology, a complaint is any formal legal document that establishes the facts and legal reasons for a lawsuit. <s> In some jurisdictions, specific types of criminal cases may also be started by the filing of a complaint. <s> This is also called a criminal complaint or felony complaint. <s> All criminal cases are prosecuted in the name of the governmental authority. <s> This is the same authority whose criminal laws were broken and who enforces criminal statutes. <s> The government is sometimes called "the state", "the People" or "the Crown" (in Commonwealth realms). <s> In the United States, the complaint is often associated with misdemeanor charges presented by the prosecutor without the grand jury process. <s> In most US jurisdictions, the document presented to and authorized by a grand jury is called an indictment. <s> Once a defendant receives notice of a complaint, they must reply within a specified period of time with an answer.

title: Milton J. Rosenberg
complex: Milton J. "Milt" Rosenberg (April 15, 1925 – January 9, 2018) was a prominent social psychologist who was professor of psychology at the University of Chicago and was the host of a long-running radio program in Chicago, Illinois. <s> Rosenberg, born in New York City, attended Brooklyn College (BA, 1946), the University of Wisconsin (MA, 1948), and the University of Michigan (PhD, 1953). <s> He began his teaching career as an Instructor in Psychology at the University of Michigan (1952–54). <s> Rosenberg died in Chicago on January 9, 2018 of complications from pneumonia at the age of 92.
simple: Milton James "Milt" Rosenberg (April 15, 1925 – January 9, 2018) was an American social psychologist. <s> He was professor of psychology at the University of Chicago and was the host of a long-running radio program "Extension 720" in WGN in Chicago. <s> He was born in New York City. <s> Rosenberg died in Chicago on January 9, 2018 of complications from pneumonia at the age of 92.

title: Systole
complex: The systole is the part of the cardiac cycle during which some chambers of the heart muscle contract after refilling with blood. <s> The term "systole" originates from New Latin via Ancient Greek συστολή (sustolē): from συστέλλειν (sustellein, "to contract") via [σύν (syn, "together") + στέλλειν (stellein, "send"). <s> The use of systole, "to contract", is very similar to the use of the English term "to squeeze". <s> When, in late ventricular diastole, the atrial chambers contract, they send blood down to the larger, lower ventricle chambers. <s> When normal flow is completed, the ventricles are filled and the valves to the atria are closed. <s> The ventricles now perform systole isovolumetrically, which is contraction while all valves are closed—ending the first stage of systole. <s> The second stage proceeds immediately, pumping oxygenated blood from the left ventricle through the aortic valve and aorta to all body systems, and simultaneously pumping oxygen-poor blood from the right ventricle through the pulmonic valve and pulmonary artery to the lungs. <s> Thus, the pairs of chambers (upper atria and lower ventricles) contract in alternating sequence to each other. <s> First, atrial contraction feeds blood into the ventricles, then ventricular contraction pumps blood out of the heart to the body systems, including the lungs for resupply of oxygen. <s> When blood pressure is stated for medical purposes, it is usually written with the systolic and diastolic pressures separated by a slash, for example, 120/80 mmHg. <s> This clinical notation is not a mathematical figure for a fraction or ratio, nor a display of a numerator over a denominator.
simple: It happens right after diastole, when the heart refills with blood. <s> They contract (squeeze) during the last part of diastole, and send blood down to the larger, lower ventricles. <s> When the ventricles are filled and the valves to the atria are closed, the ventricles contract. <s> So, the atria and ventricles contract in sequence. <s> Then, the left and right ventricles contract. <s> (The ventricles are the largest parts of the heart, which pump blood to the body and lungs.) <s> The left and right atria feed blood into the ventricles. <s> When blood pressure is measured for medical purposes, systolic pressure is the first number in the "ratio" of systolic to diastolic pressure. <s> For example, if a person's blood pressure is 120/80, 120 is the systolic pressure, and 80 is the diastolic pressure.

title: Albion, Dane County, Wisconsin
complex: Albion is a town in Dane County, Wisconsin, United States, located about 27 miles southeast of Madison on Interstate 90. <s> The population was 1,823 at the 2000 Census. <s> The unincorporated communities of Albion, Highwood, Hillside, and Indian Heights are located in the town.
simple: Albion is a town in Dane County, Wisconsin, United States. <s> 1,823 people lived there as of the year 2000.

title: ATLAS experiment
complex: ATLAS (A Toroidal LHC ApparatuS) is one of the seven particle detector experiments constructed at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), a particle accelerator at CERN (the European Organization for Nuclear Research) in Switzerland. <s> The experiment is designed to take advantage of the unprecedented energy available at the LHC and observe phenomena that involve highly massive particles which were not observable using earlier lower-energy accelerators. <s> ATLAS was one of the two LHC experiments involved in the discovery of the Higgs boson in July 2012. <s> It was also designed to search for evidence of theories of particle physics beyond the Standard Model. <s> The ATLAS detector is 46 metres long, 25 metres in diameter, and weighs about 7,000 tonnes; it contains some 3000 km of cable. <s> The experiment is a collaboration involving roughly 3,000 physicists from over 175 institutions in 38 countries. <s> The project was led for the first 15 years by Peter Jenni, between 2009 and 2013 was headed by Fabiola Gianotti, from 2013 to 2017 by David Charlton, and afterwards by Karl Jakobs. <s> Construction was completed in 2008 and the experiment detected its first single beam events on 10 September of that year. <s> Data taking was then interrupted for over a year due to an LHC magnet quench incident.
simple: ATLAS (A Toroidal LHC ApparatuS) is the biggest experiment at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC). <s> It is one of the seven particle detector experiments (ALICE, ATLAS, CMS, TOTEM, LHCb, and LHCf) built at the LHC. <s> LHC is a new particle accelerator at the European Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN) in Switzerland. <s> ATLAS studies highly massive particles which could not be studied using earlier lower-energy accelerators. <s> ATLAS is 46 metres long and 25 metres in diameter, weighing about 7,000 tonnes. <s> The project is led by Fabiola Gianotti. <s> The project began operation on 10 September 2008.

title: Andelain
complex: Andelain is a commune in the Aisne department and Hauts-de-France region of northern France.
simple: Andelain is a commune. <s> It is in the Picardie region in the Aisne department in the north of France.

title: Larimer County, Colorado
complex: Larimer County is one of the 64 counties in the U.S. state of Colorado. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 299,630. <s> The county seat and most populous city is Fort Collins. <s> The county was named for William Larimer, Jr., the founder of Denver. <s> Larimer County comprises the Fort Collins, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The county is located at the northern end of the Front Range, at the edge of the Colorado Eastern Plains along the border with Wyoming. <s> Larimer County was created in 1861, and was named after General William Larimer. <s> According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 2634 sqmi , of which 2596 sqmi is land and 38 sqmi (1.4%) is water.
simple: Larimer County is one of the 64 counties in the U.S. state of Colorado. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 299,630. <s> The county seat and most populous city is Fort Collins. <s> The county was named for William Larimer, Jr., the founder of Denver. <s> It is at the northern end of the Front Range, at the edge of the Colorado Eastern Plains along the border with Wyoming. <s> Larimer County was founded in 1861. <s> The county has a total area of 2634 sqmi.

complex: Ñeembucú (] ; Guaraní: "Ñe'ẽmbuku") is a department located in the south of the Eastern Region of Paraguay. <s> The capital is Pilar. <s> The department is almost entirely rural, and is home to some of the oldest and best-preserved Jesuit ruins, which are located near the town of Humaitá.

title: Division of Lyons
complex: The Division of Lyons is an Australian electoral division in Tasmania. <s> The division was created at the Federal redistribution of 12 September 1984 as a reconfigured version of the abolished Division of Wilmot. <s> The name jointly honours Joseph Lyons, Prime Minister of Australia 1932–39, Member for Wilmot from 1929–39, and his wife Dame Enid Lyons, the first woman elected to the Australian House of Representatives (1943) and subsequently the first female member of Cabinet (1949–51). <s> Joseph Lyons had previously represented Wilmot at the state level from 1909 to 1929. <s> It has been a marginal seat, changing hands between the Australian Labor Party and the Liberal Party. <s> It is located in central Tasmania, stretching from the eastern to northern coast and includes such places as New Norfolk, Deloraine and St Marys, as well as the outer northern suburbs of Hobart.
simple: The Division of Lyons is an Australian electoral division in Tasmania. <s> It was set up in 1984 is named for Joseph Lyons, Prime Minister of Australia 1931-39, Member for Wilmot from 1929–39, and his wife Dame Enid Lyons. <s> Dame Enid was the first woman elected to the Australian House of Representatives in 1943 and the first female member of Cabinet (1949–51). <s> It is covers an area of 32,910 km2 central Tasmania, stretching from the eastern to western coasts and includes such places as New Norfolk, Deloraine and St Marys.

title: Angry Anderson
complex: Gary Stephen "Angry" Anderson AM (born 5 August 1947) is an Australian rock singer-songwriter, television presenter-reporter and actor. <s> He has been the lead vocalist with the hard rock band Rose Tattoo since 1976.

title: Carl Fredrik af Wingård
complex: Carl Fredrik af Wingård (born 26 September 1781 in Stockholm, died 19 September 1851) was a Swedish Lutheran archbishop of the Church of Sweden, Professor at Uppsala University, and politician. <s> He served as Archbishop of Uppsala 1839–1851. <s> He was also holder of seat 10 in the Swedish Academy.
simple: Carl Fredrik af Wingård, born 26 September 1781 in Stockholm, Sweden, dead 19 September 1851 in Sunnersta, Sweden was a Swedish politician and Lutheran clergyman. <s> He verved as the Church of Sweden Archbishop of Uppsala, between 1839 and 1851.

title: Stepan Shakaryan
complex: Stepan Grigori Shakaryan ( , 23 October 1935 – 22 June 2019) was an Armenian jazz and classical composer, pianist, People's Artist of the Republic of Armenia (2017), and professor at Yerevan State Conservatory. <s> Stepan Shakaryan was born on 23 October 1935, in Baku. <s> In 1952 he moved to Yerevan.

title: Oxford Circus tube station
complex: Oxford Circus is a London Underground station serving Oxford Circus at the junction of Regent Street and Oxford Street, with entrances on all four corners of the intersection. <s> The station is an interchange between the Bakerloo, Central and Victoria lines. <s> As of 2017 , it is the third busiest station on the London Underground. <s> On the Central line it is between Bond Street and Tottenham Court Road, on the Bakerloo line it is between Regent's Park and Piccadilly Circus, and on the Victoria line it is between Green Park and Warren Street.
simple: Oxford Circus is a London Underground station serving Oxford Circus at the junction of Regent Street and Oxford Street, with entrances on all four corners of the intersection. <s> The station is an interchange between the Central, Victoria and Bakerloo Lines. <s> It is the third busiest station on the network and the busiest without connection to the National Rail service.

title: Nixa, Missouri
complex: Nixa is a city in Christian County, Missouri, United States. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city population was 19,022. <s> The population was estimated in 2016 at 21,201. <s> It is also part of the Springfield, Missouri Metropolitan Statistical Area. <s> The area was first settled by farmers who located their farms along the wooded streams near present-day Nixa. <s> The area became a crossroads, as it was a half-day ride with a team of horses from Springfield. <s> Teamsters found it a convenient stopover site when hauling freight between Springfield and Arkansas. <s> The village became known as Faughts. <s> An early resident, Nicholas A. Inman, was a blacksmith from Tennessee, who set up a shop in 1852. <s> When a post office was opened, a town meeting was held to decide on a name for the new community. <s> Because of his years of service to the community, the town was suggested to be named for him. <s> Another suggestion was "nix" because the community was "nothing but a crossroads". <s> The name Nix was finally decided upon, and Inman's middle initial "a" was added to get the unique name of Nixa. <s> The village incorporated on June 10, 1902. <s> Nixa is located at (37.045253, -93.298755). <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 8.48 sqmi , all land. <s> The modern city rests on and around seven hills. <s> Currently, Nixa Public Schools operates four elementary schools for students in kindergarten through fourth grade: Helen-Matthews Elementary, Espy Elementary, Century Elementary, and the newest, High Pointe Elementary (named so because it sits on the highest elevation in Christian County), opened in August 2007. <s> Also, two intermediate schools serve students in the fifth and sixth grades—Inman Intermediate and Summit Intermediate; one junior high school, Nixa Junior High, and one high school, Nixa Public High School are in the district. <s> Also, a magnet school hosts kindergarten through 6th grade- John Thomas School of Discovery. <s> The old Main Street Elementary School building has become an administrative building, named Faught Administration Center. <s> The Nixa school district is widely considered one of the best in Missouri, receiving the Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education's Distinction in Performance Award for each of the last five years. <s> In its Missouri Assessment Program, Nixa Junior High placed fifth in the state in science, eighth in math, and 18th in English. <s> The high school was ranked fourth in the state for high academic performance. <s> In the Robert Ludlum novels and films (fiction), Nixa is the birthplace of Jason Bourne/David Webb. <s> "The Bourne Supremacy" revealed that Bourne's real name was David Webb and that he was born in Nixa, Missouri. <s> Several streets in a residential neighborhood northeast of downtown are named for performers on ABC-TV's "Ozark Jubilee", including Nixa native Slim Wilson. <s> They include Slim Wilson Boulevard, Red Foley Court, Zed Tennis Street, Bill Ring Court, (Speedy) Haworth Court and Ozark Jubilee Drive. <s> A 2013 episode of the Investigation Discovery television series "Beauty Queen Murder" featured a murder in Nixa—the 1985 death of Jackie Johns was not settled until 2010, when DNA evidence proved that fellow Nixa resident Gerald Carnahan had raped and murdered the young lady.

title: Adolfo Pérez Esquivel
complex: Adolfo Pérez Esquivel (born November 26, 1931) is an Argentine activist, community organizer, art painter, writer and sculptor. <s> He was the recipient of the 1980 Nobel Peace Prize for his opposition to Argentina's last civil-military dictatorship (1976-1983), during which he was detained, tortured, and held without trial for 14 months; during that period he also received, among other distinctions, the Pope John XXIII Peace Memorial. <s> Pérez Esquivel was detained by the Brazilian Military Police in 1975. <s> He was jailed in 1976 in Ecuador, along with Latin American and North American bishops. <s> He was detained in Buenos Aires in 1977 by the Argentine Federal Police, tortured, and held without trial for 14 months; during that, he received, among other distinctions, the Pope John XXIII Peace Memorial.
simple: Adolfo Pérez Esquivel (born November 26, 1931) is an Argentine activist, community organizer, art painter, writer and sculptor. <s> He was the recipient of the 1980 Nobel Peace Prize for his criticism of the Argentina's last civil-military dictatorship (1976-1983). <s> He was detained, tortured, and held without trial for 14 months; during that period he also received, among other distinctions, the Pope John XXIII Peace Memorial.

title: Toyama (city)
complex: Toyama (富山市 , Toyama-shi , ]) is the capital city of Toyama Prefecture, Japan, located on the coast of the Sea of Japan in the Chūbu region on central Honshū, about 200 km north of the city of Nagoya and 300 km northwest of Tokyo. <s> s of 01 2019 , the city had an estimated population of 415,844 in 176,643 households, and a population density of 335 persons per km2.
simple: Toyama (富山市, Toyama-shi) is a city in the Chūbu region of Japan on the island of Honshu. <s> It is the capital city of Toyama Prefecture.

title: Declaration of Arbroath
complex: The Declaration of Arbroath ( ; ; ) is a declaration of Scottish independence, made in 1320. <s> It is in the form of a letter in Latin submitted to Pope John XXII, dated 6 April 1320, intended to confirm Scotland's status as an independent, sovereign state and defending Scotland's right to use military action when unjustly attacked. <s> Generally believed to have been written in the Arbroath Abbey by Bernard of Kilwinning, then Chancellor of Scotland and Abbot of Arbroath, and sealed by fifty-one magnates and nobles, the letter is the sole survivor of three created at the time. <s> The others were a letter from the King of Scots, Robert I, and a letter from four Scottish bishops which all made similar points. <s> The Declaration was part of a broader diplomatic campaign which sought to assert Scotland's position as an independent kingdom, rather than being a feudal land controlled by England's Norman kings, as well as lift the excommunication of Robert the Bruce. <s> The pope had recognised Edward I of England's claim to overlordship of Scotland in 1305 and Bruce was excommunicated by the Pope for murdering John Comyn before the altar in Greyfriars Church in Dumfries in 1306. <s> There are 39 names—eight earls and thirty one barons—at the start of the document, all of whom may have had their seals appended, probably over the space of some weeks and months, with nobles sending in their seals to be used. <s> On the extant copy of the Declaration there are only 19 seals, and of those 19 people only 12 are named within the document. <s> It is thought likely that at least 11 more seals than the original 39 might have been appended. <s> The Declaration was then taken to the papal court at Avignon by Bishop Kininmund, Sir Adam Gordon and Sir Odard de Maubuisson. <s> The Pope heeded the arguments contained in the Declaration, influenced by the offer of support from the Scots for his long-desired crusade if they no longer had to fear English invasion. <s> He exhorted Edward II in a letter to make peace with the Scots, but the following year was again persuaded by the English to take their side and issued six bulls to that effect. <s> On 1 March 1328 the new English king, Edward III signed a peace treaty between Scotland and England, the Treaty of Edinburgh-Northampton. <s> In this treaty, which was in effect for five years until 1333, Edward renounced all English claims to Scotland. <s> Eight months later, in October 1328, the interdict on Scotland, and the excommunication of its king, were removed by the Pope. <s> US Senate Resolution 155 of 10 November 1997 states that the Declaration of Arbroath, the Scottish Declaration of Independence sic, was signed on 6 April 1320 and the American Declaration of Independence was modelled on that inspirational document. <s> However, although this influence is accepted by some historians, it is disputed by others.
simple: The Declaration of Arbroath is a declaration of Scottish independence, made in 1320. <s> It was a letter sent to Pope John XXII, dated 6 April 1320. <s> The declaration confirmed Scotland's status as a independent, sovereign state and defended Scotland's right to use military action when unjustly attacked. <s> Dated April 1320 the Declaration of Arbroath was a letter to Pope John XXII at Avignon from fifty leading men of Scotland. <s> Bernard Linton, Chancellor of Scotland and Abbot of Arbroath is believed to be the author. <s> It was written at the monastery of Arbroath in Scotland. <s> Accused of murdering Comyn Bruce was excommunicated by the Pope. <s> The letter was signed at Arbroath by eight earls and thirty-one barons. <s> There were 39 names, (eight Scottish earls and thirty one barons), who signed the document with their seals. <s> The pope was impressed by the declaration and with the promise by the Scottish barons to support the pope's crusade. <s> He encouraged Edward II to make peace with the Scots. <s> Finally in October 1328 a peace treaty was agreed to between Scotland and England. <s> Edward III gave up all claims on Scotland. <s> The interdict on Scotland and the excommunication of its king were finally removed. <s> In 1998 The United States Congress resolved that the US Declaration of Independence has been modeled on the Declaration of Arbroath.

title: Annette Funicello
complex: Annette Joanne Funicello (October 22, 1942 – April 8, 2013) was an American actress and singer. <s> Funicello began her professional career as a child performer at the age of twelve. <s> She rose to prominence as one of the most popular Mouseketeers on the original "Mickey Mouse Club". <s> As a teenager, she transitioned to a successful career as a singer with the pop singles "O Dio Mio", "Tall Paul" and "Pineapple Princess", as well as establishing herself as a film actress, popularizing the successful "Beach Party" genre alongside co-star Frankie Avalon during the mid-1960s. <s> In 1992, Funicello announced that she had been diagnosed with multiple sclerosis. <s> She died of complications from the disease on April 8, 2013. <s> Annette Joanne Funicello was born in Utica, New York, to Italian Americans Virginia Jeanne (née Albano; 1921 – 2007) and Joseph Edward Funicello (1916 – 2009). <s> Her family moved to Southern California when she was four years old.
simple: Annette Joanne Funicello (October 22, 1942 – April 8, 2013) was an American singer, movie and television series actress. <s> Funicello was one of the most popular "Mouseketeers" on the "Mickey Mouse Club" in the 1950s. <s> She went public with her multiple sclerosis in 1992. <s> She died from the disease on April 8, 2013. <s> She was born in Utica, New York to Italian American parents and moved to Southern California when she was four.

title: Antwerp
complex: Antwerp ( ; ] ; ] ) is a city in Belgium, and is the capital of Antwerp province in Flanders. <s> With a population of 520,504, it is the most populous city proper in Belgium, and with a metropolitan area housing around 1,200,000 people, it's the second largest metropolitan region after Brussels in Belgium.
simple: Antwerpen is a city in Antwerp province in the north of Belgium.

title: Nyasasaurus
complex: Nyasasaurus (meaning "Lake Nyasa lizard") is an extinct genus of dinosauriform reptile from the Middle Triassic Manda Formation of Tanzania that appears to be the earliest known dinosaur. <s> The type species "Nyasasaurus parringtoni" was first described in 1956 in the doctoral thesis of English paleontologist Alan J. Charig, but it was not formally described until 2013. <s> Previously, the oldest record of dinosaurs was from Argentina and dated back to the late Carnian stage, about 231.4 million years ago. <s> "Nyasasaurus" comes from a deposit that dates back to the Anisian stage, meaning that it predates other early dinosaurs by about 12 million years.
simple: Nyasasaurus ("Lake Nyasa lizard") is an extinct genus of Archosaur reptile from the Middle Triassic Manda Beds of Tanzania. <s> It may be the earliest known dinosaur. <s> Previously, the oldest record of dinosaurs was from Argentina and dated back to the Upper Triassic Carnian stage, about 231.4 million years ago (mya). <s> "Nyasasaurus" comes from a deposit that dates back to the Middle Triassic Anisian stage, meaning that it predates other early dinosaurs by about 15 million years.

title: Ectasian
complex: The Ectasian Period (from Greek ἔκτασις "(éktasis)", meaning "extension") is the second geologic period in the Mesoproterozoic Era and lasted from round 5 Mya ago to round 5 Mya (million years ago). <s> Instead of being based on stratigraphy, these dates are defined chronometrically. <s> This period is interesting for the first evidence of sexual reproduction. <s> The 1.2 billion years old Hunting Formation on Somerset Island, Canada, dates from the end of the Ectasian. <s> It contains the microfossils of the multicellular filaments of "Bangiomorpha pubescens" (type of red algae), the first taxonomically resolved eukaryote. <s> This was the first organism that exhibited sexual reproduction, which is an essential feature for complex multicellularity. <s> Complex multicellularity is different from "simple" multicellularity, such as colonies of organisms living together.
simple: The Ectasian is the second geological period in the Mesoproterozoic. <s> This period shows for the first evidence of sexual reproduction. <s> It began 1.4 billion years ago and ended at 1.2 billion years ago. <s> The 1.2 billion-year-old Hunting Formation on Somerset Island, Canada, is from the end of the Ectasian. <s> It has the microfossils of the multicellular filaments of "Bangiomorpha pubescens" (a type of red algae). <s> This was the first organism that had sexual reproduction.

title: Helen Prejean
complex: Helen Prejean, C.S.J. (born April 21, 1939, in Baton Rouge, Louisiana) is a Roman Catholic sister, a member of the Congregation of St. Joseph based in New Orleans, and a leading American advocate for the abolition of the death penalty. <s> Prejean has founded the groups SURVIVE, to help families of victims of murder and related crimes. <s> She served as the National Chairperson of the National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty from 1993 to 1995. <s> She helped establish The Moratorium Campaign, seeking an end to executions and conducting education on the death penalty. <s> Helen Prejean was born in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, the daughter of Augusta Mae (née Bourg; 1911–1993), a nurse, and Louis Sebastian Prejean (1893–1974), a lawyer. <s> She joined the Sisters of Saint Joseph of Medaille in 1957. <s> In 1962, she received a Bachelor of Arts in English and Education from St. Mary's Dominican College, New Orleans, Louisiana. <s> In 1973, she earned a Master of Arts in religious education from Saint Paul University, an affiliated college of the University of Ottawa. <s> She has been the Religious Education Director at St. Frances Cabrini Parish in New Orleans, the Formation Director for her religious community, and has taught junior and senior high school. <s> Her efforts began in New Orleans, Louisiana, in 1981. <s> In 1982 an acquaintance asked her to correspond with convicted murderer Elmo Patrick Sonnier, held on death row in the Louisiana State Penitentiary, known as Angola. <s> Sonnier had been sentenced to death by electrocution. <s> She visited Sonnier in prison and agreed to be his spiritual adviser in the months leading up to his execution. <s> The experience gave Prejean greater insight into the process involved in executions, for the convict, families, and others in the prison, and she began speaking out against capital punishment. <s> At the same time, she founded "Survive", an organization devoted to counseling the families of victims of violence. <s> Prejean has since ministered to other inmates on death row and witnessed several more executions. <s> She served as National Chairperson of the National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty from 1993 to 1995. <s> She published "Dead Man Walking" (1993, ), an account of her relationship with Sonnier and other inmates on death row, and the factors related to her growing opposition to the death penalty. <s> The book was adapted for a 1995 feature film of the same name; she was portrayed by Susan Sarandon. <s> In 1999, Prejean formed Moratorium 2000, a petition drive that eventually grew into a national education campaign, The Moratorium Campaign, seeking to declare a moratorium to executions. <s> It was initially staffed by Robert Jones, Theresa Meisz, and Jené O'Keefe. <s> The organization Witness to Innocence, composed of death row survivors who were exonerated after being convicted for crimes they did not commit, was started under The Moratorium Campaign. <s> Prejean wrote a second book, "The Death of Innocents: An Eyewitness Account of Wrongful Executions" (2004). <s> She tells of two men, Dobie Gillis Williams and Joseph O'Dell, whom she accompanied to their executions. <s> She believes that both men were innocent of the crimes for which they were convicted. <s> The book also examines the recent history of death penalty decisions by the Supreme Court of the United States and the record of George W. Bush as Governor of Texas. <s> In 1998, Prejean was given the Pacem in Terris Award, named after a 1963 encyclical letter by Pope John XXIII that calls on all people of good will to secure peace among all nations. <s> "Pacem in terris" is Latin for "Peace on Earth." <s> Prejean now bases her work at the death Penalty Discourse Network in New Orleans. <s> She gives talks about the issues across the United States and around the world. <s> She and her sister Mary Ann Antrobus have also been deeply involved at a center in Nicaragua called Friends of Batahola. <s> Prejean has given commencement addresses to more than 50 colleges and universities around the world.
simple: Helen Prejean (born April 21, 1939 in Baton Rouge, Louisiana) is a Roman Catholic nun. <s> She is a member of the Congregation of St. Joseph. <s> Helen Prejean was born to Augusta Mae (née Bourg; 1911–1993), a nurse, and Louis Sebastian Prejean (1893–1974), a lawyer. <s> She joined the Sisters of Saint Joseph of Medaille in 1957. <s> In 1962, she received a Bachelor of Arts in English and Education from St. Mary’s Dominican College in New Orleans, Louisiana. <s> In 1973, she earned a Master of Arts in religious education from Saint Paul University in Ottawa, Canada. <s> Prejean began to work with prisoners on death row in 1981, in New Orleans, Louisiana. <s> In 1982, a friend asked her to write to Elmo Patrick Sonnier, who was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death by electrocution. <s> Prejean visited Sonnier in prison and agreed to be his spiritual adviser in the months leading up to his execution. <s> Doing this made Prejean more aware of the process involved in executions. <s> She began speaking out against the death penalty. <s> At the same time, she also founded "Survive", an organization that counseled the families of victims of violence. <s> Since 1982, Prejean has ministered to many other inmates on death row, and has witnessed several more executions. <s> She served as National Chairperson of the National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty from 1993 to 1995. <s> Prejean wrote a book called "Dead Man Walking" about her relationship with Sonnier and other inmates on death row. <s> In 1999, Prejean formed Moratorium 2000, a petition drive that eventually grew into a national education campaign, The Moratorium Campaign. <s> The organization Witness to Innocence, a group of death row survivors who were convicted for crimes they did not commit, started under The Moratorium Campaign. <s> Prejean published her second book, "The Death of Innocents: An Eyewitness Account of Wrongful Executions", in December 2004. <s> In this book, she tells the story of two men, Dobie Gillis Williams and Joseph O'Dell, whom she accompanied to their executions. <s> She believes that both men were innocent. <s> The book also examines the recent history of death penalty decisions by the Supreme Court of the United States and looks at the track record of George W. Bush as Governor of Texas. <s> In 1998, Prejean was given the Pacem in Terris Award. <s> This award was named after a 1963 encyclical letter by Pope John XXIII that calls on all people of good will to make peace among all countries. <s> "Pacem in terris" is Latin for "Peace on Earth." <s> Prejean now bases her work at the Death Penalty Discourse Network in New Orleans, and spends her time giving talks across the United States and around the world. <s> She and her sister, Mary Ann Antrobus, have been deeply involved at a center in Nicaragua called Friends of Batahola. <s> Prejean has given commencement (graduation) addresses to more than 50 colleges and universities around the world.

title: Patti LaBelle
complex: Patti LaBelle (born Patricia Louise Holte; May 24, 1944) is an American singer, actress, and entrepreneur. <s> LaBelle began her career in the early 1960s as lead singer and front woman of the vocal group, Patti LaBelle and the Bluebelles. <s> Following the group's name change to Labelle in the early 1970s, they released the iconic disco song "Lady Marmalade" and the group later became the first African-American vocal group to land the cover of "Rolling Stone" magazine.
simple: Patti LaBelle (born Patricia Louise Holt on May 24, 1944) is an American R&B and Soul singer. <s> She was the lead singer of Patty La Belle and the Bluebells during the 1960s and 70s.

title: Jorge Sampaio
complex: Jorge Fernando Branco de Sampaio, , , (] ) (born 18 September 1939) is a Portuguese lawyer and politician who was the 18th President of Portugal from 1996 to 2006. <s> In May 2006, Sampaio was appointed by the United Nations Secretary-General as his first Special Envoy for the Global Plan to Stop Tuberculosis. <s> In April 2007, current UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon designated him as High Representative for the Alliance of Civilizations, a position he held till September 2012.
simple: Jorge Fernando Branco de Sampaio, , , (] ) (born 18 September 1939) is a Portuguese lawyer and politician. <s> He was the 18th President of Portugal from 1996 to 2006. <s> In May 2006, Sampaio was appointed by the United Nations Secretary-General as his first Special Envoy for the Global Plan to Stop Tuberculosis. <s> In April 2007, current UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon designated him as High Representative for the Alliance of Civilizations, a position he held till September 2012.

title: Vakıflı, Samandağ
complex: Vakıflı Köyü ( Vak'ëf, ] ) is the only remaining Armenian village in Turkey. <s> Located on the slopes of Musa Dagh in the Samandağ district of Hatay Province, the village overlooks the Mediterranean Sea and is within eyesight of the Syrian border. <s> It is home to a community of about 130 Turkish-Armenians. <s> The local Western Armenian dialect is highly divergent and cannot be fully understood by other Western Armenians.
simple: Vakıflı Köyü ( — Vakif) is the only ethnic Armenian village in Turkey. <s> It is on the slopes of Musa Dagh in the Samandağ district of Hatay Province. <s> There are about 130 Turkish-Armenians.

title: Capri
complex: Capri ( , , ] , ] ) is an island located in the Tyrrhenian Sea off the Sorrentine Peninsula, on the south side of the Gulf of Naples in the Campania region of Italy. <s> The main town Capri that is located on the island shares the name. <s> It has been a resort since the time of the Roman Republic. <s> Some of the main features of the island include the Marina Piccola (the little harbour), the Belvedere of Tragara (a high panoramic promenade lined with villas), the limestone crags called sea stacks that project above the sea (the faraglioni), the town of Anacapri, the Blue Grotto ("Grotta Azzurra"), the ruins of the Imperial Roman villas, and the various towns surrounding the Island of Capri including Positano, Amalfi, Ravello, Sorrento, Nerano, and Naples. <s> Capri is part of the region of Campania, Metropolitan City of Naples. <s> The town of Capri is a "comune" and the island's main population centre. <s> The island has two harbours, Marina Piccola and Marina Grande (the main port of the island). <s> The separate "comune" of Anacapri is located high on the hills to the west. <s> The etymology of the name Capri is unclear; it might either be traced back to the Ancient Greeks (Ancient Greek κάπρος "kapros" meaning "wild boar"), the first recorded colonists to populate the island. <s> But it could also derive from Latin "capreae" (goats). <s> Fossils of wild boars have been discovered, lending credence to the "kapros" etymology; on the other hand, the Romans called Capri "goat island". <s> Finally, there is also the possibility that the name derives from an Etruscan word for "rocky", though any historical Etruscan rule of the island is disputed. <s> Augustus' successor Tiberius built a series of villas at Capri, the most famous of which is the Villa Jovis, one of the best-preserved Roman villas in Italy. <s> In 27 AD, Tiberius permanently moved to Capri, running the Empire from there until his death in 37 AD.
simple: Capri is an island in the Tyrrhenian Sea. <s> It is on the north side of the Gulf of Naples, Italy. <s> The main town on the island shares the name. <s> It has been a resort since the time of the Roman Republic. <s> Features of the island are the Belvedere of Tragara (a high panoramic promenade lined with villas), the limestone crags called sea stacks that project above the sea (the "Faraglioni"), the town of Anacapri, the Blue Grotto ("Grotta Azzurra"), and the ruins of the Imperial Roman villas. <s> Capri is part of the region of Campania, Province of Naples. <s> Most people on the island live in the town of Capri. <s> The island has two harbours, Marina Piccola and Marina Grande (the main port of the island). <s> The separate "comune" of Anacapri is high on the hills to the west. <s> The etymology of the name 'Capri' is unclear. <s> The Emperor Tiberius lived here from 26–31 AD.

title: Forest-l'Abbaye
complex: Forest-l'Abbaye is a commune in the Somme department in Hauts-de-France in northern France.
simple: Forest-l'Abbaye is a commune.

title: List of rivers of France
complex: This is a list of rivers that are at least partially in France. <s> The rivers are grouped by sea or ocean. <s> The rivers flowing into the sea are sorted along the coast. <s> Rivers flowing into other rivers are listed by the rivers they flow into. <s> Some rivers (e.g. Sûre/Sauer) do not flow through France themselves, but they are mentioned for having French tributaries. <s> They are given in "italics". <s> For clarity, only rivers that are longer than 50 km (or have longer tributaries) are shown. <s> In French, rivers are traditionally classified either as "fleuves" when they flow into the sea (or into a desert or lake), or as "rivières" when they flow into another river. <s> The "fleuves" are shown in bold. <s> The rivers in this section are sorted north-east (Netherlands) to south-west (Calais). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted east (Calais) to west (Brest). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted north (Brest) to south (Spain). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted west (Spain) to east (Italy). <s> The rivers in this section are listed counterclockwise along the Corsican coast starting from Cap Corse.
simple: This is a list of rivers that are at least partially in France. <s> The rivers are grouped by sea or ocean. <s> In French, rivers are called "fleuves" when they flow into the sea (or into a desert or lake). <s> They are called "rivières" when they flow into another river. <s> The "fleuves" are shown in bold. <s> The rivers in this section are sorted north-east (Netherlands) to south-west (Calais). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted east (Calais) to west (Brest). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted north (Brest) to south (Spain). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted west (Spain) to east (Italy). <s> The rivers in this section are sorted clockwise along the Corsican coast starting from Cap Corse.

title: Clyde Wells
complex: Clyde Kirby Wells, (born November 9, 1937) was the fifth Premier of Newfoundland from 1989 to 1996, and subsequently Chief Justice of Newfoundland and Labrador, sitting on the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador (Court of Appeal) from 1998 to 2009. <s> Wells retired as Premier in January 1996 and returned to private legal practice.
simple: Clyde Kirby Wells, (born November 9, 1937) is a Canadian politician. <s> He was the fifth Premier of Newfoundland and Labrador from 1989 to 1996. <s> He was the Chief Justice of Newfoundland and Labrador, sitting on the Supreme Court of Newfoundland and Labrador (Court of Appeal) from 1998 to 2009.

title: Positron emission tomography
complex: Positron-emission tomography (PET) is a nuclear medicine functional imaging technique that is used to observe metabolic processes in the body as an aid to the diagnosis of disease. <s> The system detects pairs of gamma rays emitted indirectly by a positron-emitting radioligand, most commonly fluorine-18, which is introduced into the body on a biologically active molecule called a radioactive tracer. <s> Different ligands are used for different imaging purposes, depending on what the radiologist/researcher wants to detect. <s> Three-dimensional images of tracer concentration within the body are then constructed by computer analysis.
simple: Positron Emission Tomography (often called PET) is a medical imaging technique. <s> Different tracers are used for different kinds of scans.

title: Séranon
complex: Séranon is a commune in the Alpes-Maritimes department in southeastern France.
simple: Séranon is a commune.

title: Genevieve
complex: Saint Genevieve ( ; ; from Gaullish "geno" "race, lineage" and "uida" "sage") (Nanterre, 419/422 AD – Paris 502/512 AD), is the patron saint of Paris in the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox traditions. <s> Her feast day is kept on January the 3rd. <s> She was born in Nanterre and moved to Paris after encountering Germanus of Auxerre and Lupus of Troyes and dedicated herself to a Christian life. <s> In 451 she led a "prayer marathon" that was said to have saved Paris by diverting Attila's Huns away from the city. <s> When the Germanic king Childeric I besieged the city in 464, she acted as an intermediary between the city and its besiegers, collecting food and convincing Childeric to release his prisoners. <s> Clovis I founded an abbey where Genevieve might minister, and where she herself was later buried. <s> Under the care of the Benedictines, who established a monastery there, the church witnessed numerous miracles wrought at her tomb. <s> As Genevieve was popularly venerated there, the church was rededicated in her name; people eventually enriched the church with their gifts.
simple: Saint Genevieve is a saint in Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox tradition. <s> She is the patron saint of Paris. <s> Her feast day is kept on January the 3rd. <s> In 451 she led a "prayer marathon" in Paris that was said to divert Attila's Huns away from the city. <s> In 464 Childeric I besieged the city and conquered it. <s> She negotiated to collect food and convinced Childeric to release his prisoners. <s> Clovis I founded an abbey where Genevieve could minister. <s> She was later buried there. <s> The church witnessed numerous miracles at her tomb.

title: Evana Manandhar
complex: Evana Manandhar is a Nepalese business woman, model and beauty pageant titleholder who was crowned Miss Nepal 2015 World on 18 April 2015 at an event held at Hotel Annapurna.
simple: Evana Manandhar (born 26 November 1991) in Kathmandu, Nepal is a Nepali Model, Business woman and the title winner of Miss Nepal 2015. <s> She represened Nepal in Miss World 2015 which was held in Sanya, China.

title: Method (computer programming)
complex: A method in object-oriented programming (OOP) is a procedure associated with a message and an object. <s> An object consists of data and behavior.
simple: In object-oriented programming, a method is a part of an object.

title: Ethernet hub
complex: An Ethernet hub, active hub, network hub, repeater hub, multiport repeater, or simply hub is a network hardware device for connecting multiple Ethernet devices together and making them act as a single network segment. <s> It has multiple input/output (I/O) ports, in which a signal introduced at the input of any port appears at the output of every port except the original incoming. <s> A hub works at the physical layer (layer 1) of the OSI model. <s> A repeater hub also participates in collision detection, forwarding a jam signal to all ports if it detects a collision. <s> In addition to standard 8P8C ("RJ45") ports, some hubs may also come with a BNC or an Attachment Unit Interface (AUI) connector to allow connection to legacy 10BASE2 or 10BASE5 network segments. <s> Historically, the main reason for purchasing hubs rather than switches was their price.
simple: An ethernet hub is an electronic device that runs a computer network. <s> Some hubs may also come with a BNC and/or Attachment Unit Interface (AUI) connector to allow connection to legacy 10BASE2 or 10BASE5 network segments. <s> Hubs can be used for: Historically, the main reason for purchasing hubs rather than switches was their price.
