complex: Bjuv Municipality is a municipality in Skåne County in South Sweden in southern Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in the town of Bjuv.
simple: Bjuv Municipality is a municipality in Skåne County in southern Sweden. <s> The seat is in Bjuv.

title: Petiville, Calvados
complex: Petiville is a commune in the Calvados department in the Normandy region in northwestern France.
simple: Petiville, Calvados is a commune.

title: Mud bogging
complex: Mud bogging (also known as mud racing, mud running, mud drags, or mudding) is a form of off-road motorsport popular in Canada and the United States in which the goal is to drive a vehicle through a pit of mud or a track of a set length. <s> Winners are determined by the distance traveled through the pit. <s> However, if several vehicles are able to travel the entire length, the time taken to traverse the pit will determine the winner. <s> Typically, vehicles competing in mud bogs are four-wheel drives. <s> The motor sport is overseen by sanctioning bodies like the "American Mud Racing Association", and the "National Mud Racing Organization (NMRO)", that oversee each class, develop and maintain the relationship with track owners to provide a racer and fan-friendly facility, ensure the sponsors get a good return, and help govern the sport.
simple: Mud bogging (sometimes called mud racing, mud running, mud drags, or mudding) is a type of off-road motorsport. <s> It is popular in Canada and the United States. <s> The goal of mud bogging is to drive a vehicle through a pit of mud. <s> Winners are decided by the distance they get through the pit. <s> However, if several vehicles are able to travel the entire length, the time taken to go through the pit will decide the winner. <s> Usually, vehicles competing in mud bogs are four-wheel drives. <s> The motor sport is managed by groups like the "American Mud Racing Association". <s> and the "National Mud Racing Organization (NMRO)".

title: Erstfeld
complex: Erstfeld is a municipality in the canton of Uri in Switzerland. <s> Erstfeld has an area, as of 2006 , of 59.2 km2 . <s> Of this area, 11.7% is used for agricultural purposes, while 29.2% is forested.
simple: Erstfeld is a municipality in the canton of Uri in Switzerland. <s> It has an area of 59.20 km2.

title: Fikile Mbalula
complex: Fikile April Mbalula (born 8 April 1971 in the Free State) is a South African politician who is currently serving as Minister of Transport. <s> He previously served as both Minister and Deputy Minister of Police and Minister of Sports and Recreation. <s> Mbalula is a member of the National Executive Committee of the African National Congress and former leader of the African National Congress Youth League. <s> Mbalula was appointed Deputy Minister of Police in the cabinet of Jacob Zuma in May 2009 and later became the Minister of Sport and Recreation after President Jacob Zuma changed his cabinet. <s> On 31 March 2017, following a controversial reshuffling in the cabinet, Mbalula was appointed as Minister of Police taking over from Nathi Nhleko after lobbying from the ANC Youth League and possibly as a reward for loyalty towards Zuma, according to media speculation.
simple: Fikile April Mbalula (born 8 April 1971 in the Free State) is a South African politician and former Minister of Police of South Africa. <s> In 2011, he was promoted to minister of Sports and Recreation. <s> Mbalula also serves as President of the African National Congress Youth League. <s> Mbalula was appointed deputy police minister in Jacob Zuma's cabinet in 2009.

title: Fexhe-le-Haut-Clocher
complex: Fexhe-le-Haut-Clocher is a Walloon municipality located in the Belgian province of Liège. <s> On January 1, 2006, Fexhe-le-Haut-Clocher had a total population of 3,019.
simple: Fexhe-le-Haut-Clocher is a municipality in the Belgian province of Liège.

title: San Francisco Ballet
complex: San Francisco Ballet is a ballet company, founded in 1933 as the San Francisco Opera Ballet under the leadership of ballet master Adolph Bolm. <s> The company is currently based in the War Memorial Opera House, San Francisco, under the direction of Helgi Tomasson. <s> San Francisco Ballet was the first professional ballet company in the United States. <s> It is among the world's leading dance companies, presenting more than 100 performances annually, with a repertoire that spans both classical and contemporary ballet.
simple: The San Francisco Ballet (SFB) is a ballet company. <s> It was founded in 1933 as part of the San Francisco Opera Ballet. <s> The company is based in the War Memorial Opera House in San Francisco, California under the direction of Helgi Tomasson who has been directing it since 1985. <s> SFB is the first professional ballet company in the United States.

title: Toyota 4Runner
complex: The Toyota 4Runner (Japanese: トヨタ・フォーランナー , Toyota Fōran'nā ) is a compact, later mid-size sport utility vehicle produced by the Japanese manufacturer Toyota and sold throughout the world from 1984 to present. <s> In Japan, it is known as the Toyota Hilux Surf (Japanese: トヨタ・ハイラックスサーフ , Toyota Hairakkususāfu ) which was withdrawn from the market in 2009. <s> The original 4Runner was a compact SUV and little more than a Toyota pickup truck with a fiberglass shell over the bed, but the model has since undergone significant independent development into a cross between a compact and a mid-size SUV. <s> All 4Runners have been built in Japan at Toyota's plant in Tahara, Aichi, or at the Hino Motors (a Toyota subsidiary) plant in Hamura. <s> In 1988, the 22R-E engine was joined by an optional 3.0 L V6 engine, the 3VZ-E. <s> This engine was significantly larger and more powerful although not as reliable as the original 4-cylinder offering. <s> Trucks sold with the V6 engine were equipped with the same heavy duty rear differential that was used in the turbocharged trucks, as well as a completely new transmission and transfer case; the transfer case was chain driven, although considered less rugged, created less cab noise than the old gear-driven unit used behind the four-cylinder engine. <s> Nearly all second generation 4Runners were four-door models; however, from launch in 1989 to May 1993, a two-door model was also produced. <s> These models are similar to the four-door models of the time in that the bodies were formed as a single unit, instead of the fiberglass tops used in the first generation 4Runners.
simple: The Toyota 4Runner is a Sports utility vehicle made by Toyota. <s> The 4Runner was first sold in 1984 as a camper version of the Toyota Hi-Lux, sharing the same parts and engines. <s> The 4Runner was a compact SUV until 1996. <s> Toyota makes the 4Runner in Tahara, Japan as well as the Hino factory. <s> The 4Runner got a bigger V6 engine in 1988. <s> The 4Runner was sold as a 2-door model alongside the 4-door until 1992.

title: Équihen-Plage

simple: Équihen-Plage is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Nord-Pas-de-Calais in the Pas-de-Calais department in the north of France.

title: Abalak Department
complex: Abalak is a department of the Tahoua Region in Niger. <s> Its capital lies at the city of Abalak. <s> As of 2011, the department had a total population of 112,273 people.
simple: Abalak is a department of the Tahoua Region in Niger. <s> Its capital is the city of Abalak. <s> As of 2011, 112,273 people lived there.

title: Ulster Scots dialects
complex: Ulster Scots or Ulster-Scots (" "), also known as Ulster Scotch, Scots-Irish and Ullans, is the Scots language as spoken in parts of Ulster in Ireland. <s> It is generally considered a dialect or group of dialects of Scots, although groups such as the Ulster-Scots Language Society and Ulster-Scots Academy consider it a language in its own right, and the Ulster-Scots Agency and former Department of Culture, Arts and Leisure have used the terminology Ulster-Scots language.
simple: Ulster Scots, sometimes called Ullans, is a dialect of Lowland Scots that is spoken in some of the northern parts of Ireland, across Ulster.

title: Cavalier County, North Dakota
complex: Cavalier County is a county in the U.S. state of North Dakota. <s> It is south of the Canada–US border with Manitoba. <s> As of the 2010 United States Census, the population was 3,993. <s> Its county seat is Langdon. <s> The city of Cavalier is in nearby Pembina County.
simple: Cavalier County is a county located in the U.S. state of North Dakota. <s> As of the 2010 census, 3,993 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Langdon.

title: Dompierre-sur-Yon
complex: Dompierre-sur-Yon is a commune in the Vendée department in the Pays de la Loire region in western France.
simple: Dompierre-sur-Yon is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Pays de la Loire in the Vendée department in the west of France.

title: Review
complex: A review is an evaluation of a publication, service, or company such as a movie (a movie review), video game (video game review), musical composition (music review of a composition or recording), book (book review); a piece of hardware like a car, home appliance, or computer; or an event or performance, such as a live music concert, play, musical theater show, dance show, or art exhibition. <s> In addition to a critical evaluation, the review's author may assign the work a rating to indicate its relative merit. <s> More loosely, an author may review current events, trends, or items in the news. <s> A compilation of reviews may itself be called a review. <s> "The New York Review of Books", for instance, is a collection of essays on literature, culture, and current affairs. <s> "National Review", founded by William F. Buckley, Jr., is an influential conservative magazine, and "Monthly Review" is a long-running socialist periodical. <s> A user review refers to a review written by a user or consumer for a product or a service based on her experience as a user of the reviewed product. <s> Popular sources for consumer reviews are e-commerce sites like Amazon.com, Zappos or lately in the Yoga field for schools such as Banjaara Yoga and Ayurveda, and social media sites like TripAdvisor and Yelp. <s> E-commerce sites often have consumer reviews for products and sellers separately. <s> Usually, consumer reviews are in the form of several lines of texts accompanied by a numerical rating. <s> This text is meant to aid in shopping decision of a prospective buyer. <s> A consumer review of a product usually comments on how well the product measures up to expectations based on the specifications provided by the manufacturer or seller. <s> It talks about performance, reliability, quality defects, if any, and value for money. <s> Consumer review, also called 'word of mouth' and 'user generated content' differs from 'marketer generated content' in its evaluation from consumer or user point of view. <s> Often it includes comparative evaluations against competing products. <s> Observations are factual as well as subjective in nature. <s> Consumer review of sellers usually comment on service experienced, and dependability or trustworthiness of the seller. <s> Usually, it comments on factors such as timeliness of delivery, packaging, and correctness of delivered items, shipping charges, return services against promises made, and so on.
simple: A review is an evaluation of a publication, service, or company. <s> Popular reviews are about movies, video games, musical compositions or books. <s> An event or performance like a live music concert, play, musical theater show, dance show, or art exhibition are commonly reviewed. <s> In addition to a critical evaluation, the review's author may assign the work a rating to indicate its relative merit. <s> A compilation of reviews may itself be called a review. <s> "The New York Review of Books", for instance, is a collection of essays on literature, culture, and current affairs. <s> "National Review", founded by William F. Buckley, Jr., is an influential conservative magazine. <s> "Monthly Review" is a long-running socialist periodical. <s> A user review is one written by someone for a product or a service based on his or her own experience with the reviewed product. <s> Popular sources for consumer reviews are e-commerce sites like Amazon.com or Zappos. <s> Social media sites like TripAdvisor and Yelp contain user reviews. <s> E-commerce sites often have consumer reviews for products and sellers separately. <s> Usually, consumer reviews are in the form of several lines of texts accompanied by a numerical rating. <s> This text is meant to help shoppers make a decision about a product. <s> A consumer review of a product usually has comments on how well the product meets a user's expectations. <s> It talks about how well it does its job, how reliable it is and its quality for the price. <s> Consumer reviews are also called word of mouth. <s> They may comment on how dependable or trustworthy a seller is.

title: Masaki Yokotani

title: Adrastea (moon)
complex: Adrastea ( ; Greek: ), also known as Jupiter XV , is the second by distance, and the smallest of the four inner moons of Jupiter. <s> It was discovered in photographs taken by "Voyager 2" in 1979, making it the first natural satellite to be discovered from images taken by an interplanetary spacecraft, rather than through a telescope. <s> It was officially named after the mythological Adrasteia, foster mother of the Greek god Zeus—the equivalent of the Roman god Jupiter. <s> Adrastea was discovered by David C. Jewitt and G. Edward Danielson in "Voyager 2" probe photographs taken on July 8, 1979, and received the designation S/1979 J 1 . <s> Although it appeared only as a dot, it was the first moon to be discovered by an interplanetary spacecraft. <s> Soon after its discovery, two other of the inner moons of Jupiter (Thebe and Metis) were observed in the images taken a few months earlier by "Voyager 1". <s> The "Galileo" spacecraft was able to determine the moon's shape in 1998, but the images remain poor. <s> In 1983, Adrastea was officially named after the Greek nymph Adrastea, the daughter of Zeus and his lover Ananke. <s> Adrastea has an irregular shape and measures 20×16×14 km across. <s> A surface area estimate would be between 840 and 1,600 (~1,200) km. <s> This makes it the smallest of the four inner moons. <s> The bulk, composition and mass of Adrastea are not known, but assuming that its mean density is like that of Amalthea, around 0.86 g/cm, its mass can be estimated at about 2 × 10 kg. <s> Amalthea's density implies that the moon is composed of water ice with a porosity of 10–15%, and Adrastea may be similar. <s> No surface details of Adrastea are known, due to the low resolution of available images. <s> Adrastea is the smallest and second-closest member of the inner Jovian satellite family. <s> It orbits Jupiter at a radius of about 129,000 km (1.806 Jupiter radii) at the exterior edge of the planet's Main Ring. <s> Adrastea is one of only three moons in the Solar System known to orbit its planet in less than the length of that planet's day—the other two being Jupiter's innermost moon Metis, and Mars' moon Phobos. <s> The orbit has very small eccentricity and inclination—around 0.0015 and 0.03°, respectively. <s> Inclination is relative to the equator of Jupiter.
simple: Adrastea or Jupiter XV, is the second closest moon to Jupiter. <s> It was found by David C. Jewitt and G. Edward Danielson in "Voyager 2" probe photographs taken in 1979 and received the designation S/1979 J 1. <s> Adrastea was found in "Voyager 1 and 2" images, but appeared only as a dot. <s> The "Galileo" spacecraft was able to see its shape, but the images remain poor. <s> In 1983, it was named after the mythological Adrastea, who was a daughter of Jupiter and Ananke. <s> Adrastea is non-spherical and measures 20x16x14 km3 across. <s> What Adrastea is made of and the mass of Adrastea are not known, but assuming that its mean density is like that of Amalthea (~0.86 g/cm3) its mass can be estimated at ~2×10 kg. <s> Amalthea's density implies that moon is composed of water ice with a porosity of 10-15%, and Adrastea may be similar. <s> No surface details of Adrastea are known, due to the low resolution of available images. <s> Adrastea is the smallest and second closest member of the closer moons to Jupiter. <s> It orbits Jupiter at ~129,000 km (1.806 Jupiter radii) within the planet's Main Ring. <s> The orbital eccentricity of ~0.0015 and inclination of ~ 0.03° relative to the equator of Jupiter are very small.

title: Zard
complex: Zard (ザード , Zādo ) was a Japanese pop rock group. <s> Originally a group of five members, with lead vocalist Izumi Sakai as its only constant member. <s> Zard's work was sold under the record label B-Gram Records, Inc. <s> Their most popular and successful songs are "Makenaide" (1993) (負けないで ) , "Yureru Omoi" (1993) (揺れる想い ) , and "My Friend" (1996). <s> As of 2014, Zard has sold over 37 million records, making them one of the best-selling music artists in Japan. <s> Founding member Izumi Sakai died on May 27, 2007 at the age of 40 in Keio University Hospital. <s> She entered the hospital in June 2006 after discovering she had cervical cancer and had the tumor removed. <s> In April 2007, however, the cancer had spread to her lungs, resulting in her re-admittance to hospital.
simple: Zard was a J-pop music group. <s> Zard's member was Izumi Sakai. <s> Izumi Sakai died on May 27, 2007. <s> She had cervical cancer.

title: Sinusitis
complex: Sinusitis, also known as a sinus infection or rhinosinusitis, is inflammation of the mucous membrane that lines the sinuses resulting in symptoms. <s> Common symptoms include thick nasal mucus, a plugged nose, and facial pain. <s> Other signs and symptoms may include fever, headaches, a poor sense of smell, sore throat, and a cough.
simple: Sinusitis means infection or inflammation of the sinuses, which are air-filled spaces inside the bones of the face. <s> There are many symptoms, including thick nasal mucus, a plugged nose, and pain in the face.

title: Andrey Kharitonov
complex: Andrey Igorevich Kharitonov ( ; 25 July 1959 – 23 June 2019) was a Soviet and Russian film and theater actor, director, screenwriter. <s> He is best known for roles in films "The Gadfly", "" and "The Invisible Man". <s> In January 2019, it became known that Andrey had stomach cancer. <s> On June 23, 2019 Kharitonov died.
simple: Andrey Igorevich Kharitonov (; 25 July 1959 – 23 June 2019) was a Soviet and Russian actor, director and screenwriter. <s> He is known for roles in movies such as "The Gadfly" (1980), "The Invisible Man" (1984), "The Life of Klim Samgin" (1988) and "The Devil's Flower" (2010). <s> In January 2019, it was announced that Kharitonov was diagnosed with stomach cancer. <s> He died on 23 June 2019 in Moscow, at the age of 59.

title: Tawakkol Karman
complex: Tawakkul Abdul-Salam Karman ( "Tawakkul 'Abd us-Salām Khalid Karmān"; also Romanized "Tawakul", "Tawakel") (born 7 February 1979) is a Yemeni journalist, politician, and human rights activist. <s> She leads the group "Women Journalists Without Chains," which she co-founded in 2005. <s> She became the international public face of the 2011 Yemeni uprising that is part of the Arab Spring uprisings. <s> In 2011, she was reportedly called the "Iron Woman" and "Mother of the Revolution" by some Yemenis. <s> She is a co-recipient of the 2011 Nobel Peace Prize, becoming the first Yemeni, the first Arab woman, and the second Muslim woman to win a Nobel Prize. <s> Karman gained prominence in her country after 2005 in her roles as a Yemeni journalist and an advocate for a mobile phone news service denied a license in 2007, after which she led protests for press freedom. <s> She organized weekly protests after May 2007 expanding the issues for reform. <s> She redirected the Yemeni protests to support the "Jasmine Revolution," as she calls the Arab Spring, after the Tunisian people overthrew the government of Zine El Abidine Ben Ali in January 2011. <s> She has been a vocal opponent who has called for the end of President Ali Abdullah Saleh's regime. <s> Nobel Laureate Tawakkol Karman was born on 7 February 1979 in Shara'b As Salam, Taiz Governorate, Yemen. <s> She grew up near Taiz, which is the third largest city in Yemen and is described as a place of learning in a conservative country. <s> She studied in Taiz. <s> She is the daughter of Abdel Salam Karman, a lawyer and politician, who once served and later resigned as Legal Affairs Minister in Ali Abdullah Saleh's government. <s> She is the sister of Tariq Karman, who is a poet, and Safa Karman, who is a lawyer the first Yemeni citizen to graduate from Harvard Law School. <s> Safa is also a journalist and works as a journalist for "Al-Jazeera". <s> She is married to Mohammed al-Nahmi and is the mother of three children. <s> Karman earned an undergraduate degree in commerce from the University of Science and Technology, a graduate degree in political science from the University of Sana'a. <s> In 2012, she received an Honorary Doctorate in International Law from University of Alberta in Canada.
simple: Tawakel Karman (born 7 February 1979) came to international attention as a leader in the 2011 Yemeni uprising, part of the Arab Spring. <s> She is one of the people who started the group "Women Journalists Without Chains". <s> Yemenis have called her "Iron Woman" and "Mother of the Revolution." <s> She won the 2011 Nobel Peace Prize with two other women. <s> She is the first Yemeni and the first Arab woman to win the prize. <s> She is the second Muslim woman to win any Nobel Prize and the youngest Nobel Peace Laureate. <s> She became well known in Yemen after 2005. <s> As a journalist, she helped a mobile phone news service after the government did not give them a license. <s> She led protests for press freedom and organized weekly protests for reform. <s> She lead the Yemini protests to support the Arab Spring after the Tunisian people overthrew the government of Zine El Abidine Ben Ali in January 2011. <s> She has opposed President Ali Abdullah Saleh and thinks he should not be president any longer. <s> She is married to Mohammed al-Nahmi <s> Karman earned a college degree in commerce from the University of Science and Technology, Sana'a. <s> She also completed a graduate degree in political science from the University of Sana'a.

title: Sakurai's Object
complex: Sakurai's Object (V4334 Sagittarii) is a star in the constellation of Sagittarius. <s> It is thought to have previously been a white dwarf that, as a result of a very late thermal pulse, swelled and became a red giant. <s> It is located at the center of a planetary nebula and is believed to currently be in thermal instability and within its final shell helium flash phase. <s> Sakurai's Object and other similar stars are expected to end up as helium-rich white dwarfs after retracing their evolution track from the "born-again" giant phase back to the white dwarf cooling track. <s> There are few other suspected "born-again" objects, one example being FG Sagittae.
simple: Sakuri's Object , also known as V4334 Sagittarii, is a star in the Sagittarius constellation. <s> It is thought it was a white dwarf that swelled and became a red giant. <s> It is at the center of a planetary nebula. <s> Sakurai's Object and other similar stars are expected to end up as helium-rich white dwarfs. <s> They go through a "born-again" giant phase back to the white dwarf cooling track.

title: West End Girls
complex: "West End Girls" is a song by the British pop duo Pet Shop Boys. <s> Written by Neil Tennant and Chris Lowe, the song was released twice as a single. <s> The song’s lyrics are concerned with class and the pressures of inner-city life which were inspired partly by T. S. Eliot's poem "The Waste Land". <s> It was generally well received by contemporary music critics and has been frequently cited as a highlight in the duo's career. <s> The first version of the song was produced by Bobby Orlando and was released on Columbia Records' Bobcat Records imprint in April 1984, becoming a club hit in the United States and some European countries. <s> After the duo signed with EMI, the song was re-recorded with producer Stephen Hague for their first studio album, "Please". <s> In October 1985, the new version was released, reaching number one in the United Kingdom and the United States in 1986. <s> In 1987, the song won Best Single at the Brit Awards, and Best International Hit at the Ivor Novello Awards. <s> In 2005, 20 years after its release, the song was awarded Song of The Decade between the years 1985 and 1994 by the British Academy of Composers and Songwriters. <s> In 2015 the song was voted by the British public as the nation's 12th favourite 1980s number one in a poll for ITV. <s> "West End Girls" is a synthpop song influenced by hip hop music. <s> The song's socially conscious streak, as well as the propulsive bass line, derives from Grandmaster Flash's protest rap song "The Message".
simple: West End Girls is a pop song from the British duo Pet Shop Boys. <s> The lyrics are about inner-city life and class. <s> The first version of the song was released in April 1984. <s> It became a club hit in the United States and some European countries. <s> When the duo signed with British record company EMI, the song was re-recorded for their first studio album "Please". <s> In October 1985, the new version was released. <s> It hit #1 in the United Kingdom and the United States in 1986. <s> In 1987, the song won Best Single at the BRIT Awards. <s> In 2005, more than 20 years after its release, the song was awarded Song of the Decade between 1985 and 1994 by British Academy of Composers and Songwriters. <s> The song is mixed with hip hop music.

title: Fakenham
complex: Fakenham is a market town and civil parish in Norfolk, England. <s> It is situated on the River Wensum, about 19 mi north east of King's Lynn, 19 mi south west of Cromer, and 25 mi north west of Norwich. <s> The civil parish has an area of 3.49 mi2 and in the 2001 census had a population of 7,357 in 3,292 households, the population increasing to 7,617 at the 2011 census. <s> For the purposes of local government, the parish falls within the district of North Norfolk.

title: Area code 268
complex: Area code 268 is the telephone area code of Antigua and Barbuda. <s> The 268 area code, or "(ANT)" was created during a split from the original 809 area code which began permissive dialing 1 April 1996 and ended 31 March 1997. <s> The 268 area code is part of the North American Numbering Plan (NANP). <s> When in Antigua and Barbuda, use the seven digits alone. <s> When calling to Antigua and Barbuda from anywhere in the United States or Canada simply dial 1(268) + the seven-digit phone number.

title: Kim Byung-ji

title: Elmer Gedeon
complex: Elmer John Gedeon (April 15, 1917 – April 20, 1944) was a professional baseball player, appearing in several games for the Washington Senators in . <s> Gedeon and Harry O'Neill were the only two Major League Baseball players killed during World War II. <s> Gedeon flew several missions in the European Theater of Operations as an officer of the United States Army Air Forces before being shot down over France. <s> During college at the University of Michigan, Gedeon became an All-American in track and field, and earned varsity letters in both football and baseball. <s> He tied a world record in the high hurdles in 1938. <s> After graduating, Gedeon had a stint in Major League Baseball as an outfielder for the Washington Senators. <s> Gedeon spent most of the 1939 and 1940 baseball seasons in the minor leagues, but he was called up to the Senators in September 1939. <s> Gedeon's baseball career was cut short when he was drafted by the United States Army in early 1941. <s> He trained as a bomber pilot, and was decorated for bravery after his plane crashed on a training flight in 1942. <s> He later served in combat, and was shot down and killed while piloting a B-26 bomber on a mission over France in April 1944.
simple: Elmer John Gedeon (April 15, 1917 – April 20, 1944) is one of only two Major League Baseball players killed in action during World War II. <s> He was also a multi-sport star in college at the University of Michigan. <s> At Michigan, Gedeon became an All-American in track and field, and earned varsity letters in both American football and baseball. <s> He tied a world record in the high hurdles in 1938. <s> After graduating, Gedeon had a position in Major League Baseball as an outfielder for the Washington Senators. <s> Gedeon spent most of the 1939 and 1940 baseball seasons in the minor leagues. <s> He was called up to the Senators in September 1939. <s> Gedeon's was drafted by the United States Army in early 1941. <s> He trained as a bomber pilot. <s> He served in combat, and was shot down and killed in France, April of 1944.

title: Exogamy
complex: Exogamy is the social norm of marrying outside one's social group. <s> The group defines the scope and extent of exogamy, and the rules and enforcement mechanisms that ensure its continuity. <s> One form of exogamy is dual exogamy, in which two groups engage in continual wife exchange.
simple: Exogamy is when a person ought to marry someone from outside a certain group. <s> Exogamy is used to make a connection between two groups.

title: Madera County, California
complex: Madera County, officially the County of Madera, is a county at the geographic center of the U.S. state of California. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 150,865. <s> The county seat is Madera. <s> Madera County comprises the Madera, CA Metropolitan Statistical Area, which is included in the Fresno-Madera, CA Combined Statistical Area. <s> It is located in the eastern San Joaquin Valley and the central Sierra Nevada.

title: Stanisław Kowalski
complex: Stanisław Kowalski (born April 14, 1910) is a Polish centenarian Masters athlete, competing in sprinting, shot put and discus. <s> When he competed at the Polish Veterans Championships on June 28, 2015, in Torun, Poland he became the world's oldest athlete. <s> On that day, Kowalski ran the 100 metres in 34.50, threw the shot put 4.27 m and the discus 7.50 m . <s> By competing in those events, he surpassed the accomplishments of John Whittemore, who competed at 104 years 10 months. <s> By virtue of his age being beyond 105 years old, he necessitates the creation of a new age division for World Masters Athletics, the M105 division of which he was the only member to have competed. <s> Thus all of his performances are world records. <s> M100 world record holder Hidekichi Miyazaki turned 105 on September 22, 2015 and two days later joined Kowalski as the second competitor in the division though Kowalski was 77 days older when he competed.

title: Crime in Bahrain
complex: There is a low rate of crime in Bahrain. <s> Incidents of petty crime such as pickpocketing and bag snatching are reported especially in the old market areas (souks). <s> Incidents of violent crime is uncommon, but increasing. <s> Much of the crime in the nation is committed by the large South Asian population of guest workers. <s> Though small in size, there is a growing underground drug market in the country. <s> According to Emile Nakhleh, approximately 65% of violent crime and theft are committed by foreign citizens residing in Bahrain. <s> Charisse Tia Maria Coston and Freda Adler in their book "Victimizing Vulnerable Groups" analyzed the reasons behind the low crime rate in Bahrain. <s> The society of Bahrain follows the teachings of the Qur'an; the Qur'an influences political, economic and social environment. <s> Islam, which is most important in the structure of Bahraini society, teaches wrongdoings will result in downfall of societies and try to uproot crime by exerting influence upon human conscience. <s> This internalization of the religion of Islam is analyzed as a cause behind law-abiding behavior among Bahraini people where violation of law is considered violation of the principles of God. <s> Bahrain is a destination country for men and women trafficked for the purposes of involuntary servitude and commercial sexual exploitation. <s> Men and women from Africa, South Asia and Southeast Asia migrate voluntarily to Bahrain to work as laborers or domestic servants where some face conditions of involuntary servitude such as unlawful withholding of passports, restrictions on movements, non-payment of wages, threats and physical or sexual abuse. <s> Women from Eastern Europe, Central Asia, Southeast Asian country like Thailand and North African nation like Morocco are trafficked to Bahrain for the purpose of commercial sexual exploitation. <s> Threat of terrorist attack is a matter of concern. <s> The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) of the Government of Australia advised travelers "to exercise a high degree of caution in Bahrain" due to high threat of terrorism. <s> According to the DFAT, terrorists can target shopping areas, supermarkets, embassies, hotels, restaurants, clubs, cinemas and theaters, schools, places of worship, outdoor recreation events and tourist areas. <s> In the Corruption Perceptions Index 2007, Bahrain was ranked 46th out of 179 countries for corruption (least corrupt countries are at the top of the list). <s> On a scale of 0 to 10 with 0 the most corrupt and 10 the most transparent, Transparency International rated Bahrain 5.0.

title: Silicone
complex: Silicones, also known as polysiloxanes, are polymers that include any synthetic compound made up of repeating units of siloxane, which is a chain of alternating silicon atoms and oxygen atoms, combined with carbon, hydrogen, and sometimes other elements. <s> They are typically heat-resistant and either liquid or rubber-like, and are used in sealants, adhesives, lubricants, medicine, cooking utensils, and thermal and electrical insulation. <s> Some common forms include silicone oil, silicone grease, silicone rubber, silicone resin, and silicone caulk. <s> Silicones are used in many products. <s> Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry lists the following major categories of application: Electrical (e.g., insulation), electronics (e.g., coatings), household (e.g., sealants and cooking utensils), automobile (e.g., gaskets), aeroplane (e.g., seals), office machines (e.g., keyboard pads), medicine and dentistry (e.g., tooth impression molds), textiles and paper (e.g., coatings).
simple: Silicones (/'sIlIkən/) are polymers that include any inert, synthetic compound made up of repeating units of siloxane. <s> This is a functional group of two silicon atoms and one oxygen atom frequently combined with carbon and/ or hydrogen. <s> They are typically heat-resistant and rubber-like. <s> Silicones are used in sealants, adhesives, lubricants, medicine, cooking utensils, and thermal and electrical insulation. <s> Some common forms include silicone oil, silicone grease, silicone rubber, silicone resin, and silicone caulk. <s> Silicone is also used for cosmetics.

title: 2018 Horizon Air Q400 incident
complex: On August 10, 2018, a Horizon Air Bombardier Dash 8 Q400 was stolen from Seattle–Tacoma International Airport (Sea–Tac) in SeaTac, Washington. <s> The perpetrator, 29-year-old Richard Russell, was a Horizon Air ground service agent with no piloting experience. <s> He performed an unauthorized takeoff and two McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle fighters were subsequently scrambled to intercept the aircraft. <s> Sea–Tac air traffic control made radio contact with Russell, the sole occupant, who described himself as a "broken guy, got a few screws loose I guess." <s> Approximately one hour and 15 minutes after takeoff, Russell committed suicide by intentionally crashing the aircraft on the lightly-populated Ketron Island in Puget Sound. <s> Seattle–Tacoma air traffic control (ATC) maintained radio contact with the occupant.
simple: On August 10, 2018, a Horizon Air Bombardier Dash 8 Q400 was stolen from Seattle–Tacoma International Airport ("Sea–Tac") in SeaTac, Washington. <s> The man responsible was 29-year-old Richard Russell. <s> He was a Horizon Air ground service operator with no piloting experience. <s> Russell performed an unauthorized takeoff and flew southward as F-15 fighter jets were scrambled to take down the plane. <s> Sea–Tac air traffic control made radio contact with Russell. <s> He was killed when the plane crashed on sparsely populated Ketron Island in Puget Sound.

title: Trumpet Concerto (Arutiunian)
complex: Alexander Arutunian’s Trumpet Concerto in A♭ major (1950) is the Armenian composer's sixth major composition, a "virtuoso showpiece" composed in 1949-1950. <s> According to J. Sundram, "it is an energetic powerhouse of Eastern European lyricism and harmonic textures". <s> Arutunian's engaging and idiomatic trumpet concerto was "quickly assimilated into the standard trumpet repertoire worldwide, earning highest international praise from audiences, critics and performers". <s> In an interview with Allan Kozinn of "The New York Times", Philip Smith, the former principal trumpeter of the New York Philharmonic, observed that Arutunian's Trumpet Concerto was frequently chosen as an audition piece at Juilliard. <s> "One of the reasons this piece has become so popular..." Smith said, "is just that it's a flashy piece.

Sundram, "it is an energetic powerhouse of Eastern European lyricism and harmonic textures". <s> According to Philip Smith, the principal trumpet of the New York Philharmonic, Arutunian's Trumpet Concerto is too much popular among the trumpet players.

title: Warren Skorodenski
complex: Warren Skorodenski (born March 22, 1960) is a retired professional ice hockey goaltender who played for the Chicago Black Hawks and the Edmonton Oilers in the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> While playing for the New Brunswick Hawks during the 1981–82 AHL season, Skorodenski shared the Harry "Hap" Holmes Memorial Award for the American Hockey League's lowest goals against average with teammate Bob Janecyk. <s> As Murray Bannerman's backup in Chicago in 1984–85, Skorodenski recorded the league's highest save percentage, at 0.903. <s> He retired in 1991.
simple: Warren Skorodenski (born March 22, 1960 in Winnipeg, Manitoba) is a Canadian retired professional ice hockey goaltender. <s> Frederick played a total of 35 games in the National Hockey League (NHL) with the Chicago Black Hawks and Edmonton Oilers. <s> He played for the New Brunswick Hawks, the AHL affiliate of the Black Hawks. <s> During that time, he was able to win the Harry "Hap" Holmes Memorial Award for being the goalie with the lowest goals against average and shared the award with his teammate Bob Janecyk. <s> He was called up by the Black Hawks during the 1981-82 NHL season. <s> During the 1984-85 NHL season, he was called up and played as Murray Bannerman backup. <s> He recorded the league's highest save percentage, at 0.903. <s> He retired from playing professional ice hockey in 1990.

title: Nagoya University of Foreign Studies
complex: Nagoya University of Foreign Studies (名古屋外国語大学 , Nagoya gaikokugo daigaku ) is a private university located in Nissin City, Aichi Prefecture in the “Chubu” (central) area of Japan. <s> Founded in 1988, it is known domestically by the name “Nagoya Gaidai” and its English abbreviation as NUFS. <s> Nagoya University of Foreign Studies (NUFS) is the only university specializing in international studies and foreign languages education in the Chubu(Central)Region of Japan.
simple: The Nagoya University of Foreign Studies is in Nisshin, Aichi Prefecture, Japan. <s> it started in 1988.

title: Mohamed ElBaradei
complex: Mohamed Mustafa ElBaradei ( , ] ; born 17 June 1942) is an Egyptian law scholar and diplomat who served as Vice-President of Egypt on an interim basis from 14 July 2013 until his resignation on 14 August 2013. <s> He was the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), an intergovernmental organization under the auspices of the United Nations, from 1997 to 2009. <s> He and the IAEA were jointly awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2005. <s> ElBaradei was also featured in the Western press regarding recent politics in Egypt, particularly the 2011 revolution which ousted President Hosni Mubarak, and was the main player in the 2013 Egyptian coup d'état. <s> ElBaradei was born and raised in Giza Governorate, Greater Cairo, Egypt. <s> He was one of five children of Mostafa ElBaradei, an attorney who headed the Egyptian Bar Association.
simple: Mohamed ElBaradei (born June 17, 1942) is an Egyptian scientist, administrator, politician, diplomat and 2005 recipient of the Nobel Prize for Peace. <s> ElBaradei is best known as the former Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) "(1997-2009)". <s> ElBaradei and the IAEA were both awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2005. <s> ElBaradei was born and raised in Cairo, Egypt.

title: Just a Dream (Nelly song)
complex: "Just a Dream" is a song performed by American singer and rapper Nelly, released as the lead single from his 2010 album "5.0" and appears as the fourth track. <s> The song was written by Mitch J, Nelly, Rico Love, Jim Jonsin and Frank Romano with Jonsin and Love producing the song. <s> The song was released on August 16, 2010 to iTunes Stores around the world for digital download. <s> It was released alongside the promotional single, "Tippin' In da Club".
simple: "Just a Dream'" is a 2010 Hip hop/R&B/pop song by American rapper Nelly. <s> It was the first single from his sixth studio album 5.0. <s> The song was released on August 16, 2010.

title: Växjö Cathedral
complex: Växjö Cathedral (Swedish: "Växjö domkyrka") in the centre of Växjö, Sweden, is the seat of the bishop of the Diocese of Växjö in the Church of Sweden.
simple: The Växjö Cathedral is a cathedral in the town of Växjö in Sweden. <s> It belongs to the Växjö Cathedral Parish of the Church of Sweden.

title: Bill Monbouquette
complex: William Charles Monbouquette (August 11, 1936 – January 25, 2015) was an American Major League Baseball (MLB) right-handed pitcher. <s> He pitched for the Boston Red Sox (1958–65), Detroit Tigers (1966–67), New York Yankees (1967–68), and the San Francisco Giants (1968). <s> He was an All-Star for three seasons of his 11-year major league career. <s> Monbouquette died on January 25, 2015, aged 78 at Brigham and Women's Hospital in Medford Massachusetts. <s> He was buried in Oak Grove Cemetery, Medford, Massachusetts.
simple: William Charles Monbouquette (August 11, 1936 – January 25, 2015) was an American professional baseball pitcher. <s> He played in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the Boston Red Sox (1958–1965), Detroit Tigers (1966–1967), New York Yankees (1967–1968), and the San Francisco Giants (1968). <s> Monbouquette died on January 25, 2015 in Gloucester, Massachusetts, aged 78.

title: Ånge Municipality
complex: Ånge Municipality ("Ånge kommun") is a municipality in Västernorrland County, northern Sweden. <s> Its seat is located in Ånge.

title: Arbana Xharra
complex: Arbana Xharra is an Albanian investigative journalist from Kosovo. <s> She has won numerous awards for her reporting and was a 2015 recipient of the International Women of Courage Award from the US State Department. <s> Arbana Xharra has been working as a journalist since 2001. <s> She worked for "Koha Ditore", the first independent newspaper established in Kosovo, in 2006 and 2007. <s> She has been a contributor to "Balkan Insight" and is currently editor-in-chief of "Zëri". <s> Arbana Xharra believes that for democracy to flourish, the press must have the right to investigate public concerns. <s> She has written about a wide range of issues including a 2006 investigation on government expense reports and financial mismanagement; a 2007 examination of inflation and food shortages; a report in 2010 questioning how the assets of the state-run Telecom of Kosovo were being used; and relationships between businesses and politics. <s> Xharra faced legal action in 2012 when a report she prepared on government corruption linked a local business with politicians. <s> She was exonerated by the court, whose ruling stated that she had complied with the Code of Ethics for print media of Kosovo. <s> Over an 18-month period beginning in 2012, Xharra investigated the rise in religious activity since the collapse of socialism in the former Yugoslavia. <s> She reported on religious extremism and its impact on society. <s> By evaluating Islamic extremists operating in Kosovo, she discovered links with terrorist organizations. <s> Uncovering operational and financial links, Xharra was able to assist the government in efforts to address the problem, but the reports caused her to receive death threats and public attacks on her reputation. <s> She reported them to the police, but with no consequences. <s> Xharra was three-time winner of the UNDP Prize for her articles on corruption in Kosovo in 2006, 2007, and 2008. <s> In 2012 she was awarded a Balkan Fellowship for Journalistic Excellence and studied the changing attitudes towards Islam in Kosovo. <s> In 2013 she was awarded the "Rexhai Surroi Award" by the KOHA Group for an article on extremism and the "Stirring Up Debate Award" from INPO Ferizaj (Progress Initiative) for creating public discourse on religious extremism. <s> In 2015 she won the US Secretary of State's International Women of Courage Award for the European division.
simple: Arbana Xharra is a journalist from Kosovo. <s> In 2015 she won the International Women of Courage Award from the US State Department. <s> Arbana Xharra became a journalist in 2001. <s> She worked for "Koha Ditore", Kosovo's first independent newspaper, in 2006 and 2007. <s> She wrote for "Balkan Insight" and is now editor-in-chief of "Zëri". <s> In 2006 she investigated government expense reports and problems with financial management. <s> In 2007, she wrote about inflation and food shortages. <s> In 2010 she wrote a report about the finances of the state-run Telecom of Kosovo. <s> In 2012, Xharra had legal problems. <s> She wrote a report about government corruption and about politicians' connections with local business. <s> They said she followed the Code of Ethics for print media of Kosovo. <s> In 2012, Xharra investigated the increase of religious activity in the former Yugoslavia. <s> She wrote about religious extremism and its effect on society. <s> When she investigated Islamic extremists in Kosovo, she found connections with terrorist organizations. <s> Xharra's report helped the government with the problem. <s> Xharra won the UNDP Prize three times--in 2006, 2007, and 2008--for her articles on corruption in Kosovo. <s> In 2012 she won a Balkan Fellowship for Journalistic Excellence and studied the changing attitudes towards Islam in Kosovo. <s> In 2013 she won the "Rexhai Surroi Award" from the KOHA Group for an article on extremism. <s> She also won the "Stirring Up Debate Award" from INPO Ferizaj for starting public discussion on religious extremism. <s> In 2015 she won the US Secretary of State's International Women of Courage Award.

title: Weddings Parties Anything
complex: were an Australian folk rock band formed in 1984 in Melbourne and continuing until 1999. <s> Their name came from The Clash song ("Revolution Rock") and musicologist Billy Pinnell described their first album as the best Australian rock debut since Skyhooks' "Living in the '70s". <s> Musically, Weddings, Parties, Anything. <s> were a combination of Australian indie and garage rock, sixties folk, punk and (later) country and are usually described as being a folk rock band.

title: Electorates of the Australian states and territories
complex: A State Electoral District is an electorate within the Lower House or Legislative Assembly of Australian states and territories. <s> Most state electoral districts (except the Australian Capital Territory and Tasmania, which have multi-member electorates using a proportional voting method) send a single member to a state or territory's parliament using the preferential method of voting. <s> The area of a state electoral district is dependent upon the Electoral Acts in the various states and vary in area between them. <s> At present, there are 409 state electoral districts in Australia. <s> State electoral districts do not apply to the Upper House, or Legislative Council, in those states that have one (New South Wales, South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Western Australia). <s> In New South Wales and South Australia, MLCs represent the entire state, in Tasmania they represent single-member districts, and in Victoria and Western Australia they represent a region formed by grouping electoral districts together. <s> There are five electorates for the Legislative Assembly, each with five members each, making up 25 members in total. <s> There are currently 93 electoral districts in New South Wales. <s> There are 25 single-member electoral divisions in the Northern Territory, and 17 former divisions. <s> There are 93 electoral districts in Queensland, for the Legislative Assembly of Queensland. <s> Information about the QLD electoral districts for the 2006 elections can be obtained from the Electoral Commission of Queensland website. <s> There are 47 single-member electoral districts in South Australia, for the South Australian House of Assembly. <s> There are 15 electoral divisions in Tasmania for the upper house Legislative Council. <s> There are 88 electoral districts in Victoria, for the Victorian Legislative Assembly. <s> There are 59 single-member electoral districts in Western Australia for the Western Australian Legislative Assembly. <s> 42 are in the Perth metropolitan area and 17 are in the rest of the state.
simple: State Electoral District means an electorate in the Lower House or Legislative Assembly of Australian states and territories. <s> Most state electoral districts (except Australian Capital Territory and Tasmania, which have multi-member electorates using a proportional voting method) send a single member to a state or territory's parliament using the preferential method of voting. <s> The size of a state electoral district depends on the Electoral Acts in the state and vary in size between them. <s> At present, there are 407 state electoral districts in Australia. <s> State electoral districts do not apply to the Upper House, or Legislative Council, in the states which have one (New South Wales, South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria and Western Australia). <s> In New South Wales and South Australia, MLCs represent the entire state, in Tasmania they represent single-member districts, and in Victoria and Western Australia they represent a region formed by grouping electoral districts together. <s> There are three electorates for the Legislative Assembly, two with five members each, and one with seven members, making up seventeen members in total. <s> There are currently 93 electoral districts in New South Wales. <s> There are 25 single-member electoral divisions in the Northern Territory, and 13 former divisions. <s> There are 89 electoral districts in Queensland, for the Legislative Assembly of Queensland. <s> There are 47 single-member electoral districts in South Australia, for the South Australian House of Assembly. <s> There are 5 electoral divisions in Tasmania. <s> There are 88 electoral districts in Victoria, for the Victorian Legislative Assembly. <s> There are 59 single-member electoral districts in Western Australia for the Western Australian Legislative Assembly. <s> 42 are in the Perth metropolitan area and 17 are in the rest of the state.

title: List of Rugrats episodes
complex: "Rugrats" is an American animated television series created by Arlene Klasky, Gábor Csupó and Paul Germain. <s> The show focuses on a group of toddlers, most prominently Tommy, Chuckie, twins Phil and Lil, and Angelica, and their day-to-day lives, usually involving common life experiences that become adventures in the babies' imaginations. <s> Adults in the series are almost always unaware of what the children are up to. <s> The series premiered on Sunday, August 11, 1991, as the second Nicktoon after "Doug" and preceding "The Ren & Stimpy Show". <s> Production initially halted in 1993 after 65 episodes, with the last episode airing on May 22, 1994. <s> From 1995 to 1996, the only new episodes broadcast were "A Rugrats Passover" and "A Rugrats Chanukah", two Jewish-themed episodes that received critical acclaim; during this time, well after the end of the show's production run, "Rugrats" began to receive a boost in ratings and popularity with constant reruns on Nickelodeon. <s> In 1996, Klasky Csupo Animation began producing new episodes, and the show's fourth season began airing in 1997. <s> As a result of the show's popularity, a series of theatrical films were released; "The Rugrats Movie", which introduced Tommy's younger brother Dil, was released in 1998, "," which introduced Kimi, Kira and Fifi released in 2000, and "Rugrats Go Wild", a crossover film with fellow Klasky Csupo series "The Wild Thornberrys", released in 2003. <s> The final episode aired on August 1, 2004, bringing the series to a total of 172 episodes and 9 seasons during a 13-year run. <s> On July 21, 2001, Nickelodeon broadcast the made-for-TV special "All Growed Up" in celebration of the series' 10th anniversary. <s> The special acted as a pilot for the "Rugrats" spin-off series "All Grown Up!", <s> , which chronicles the lives of the babies and their parents after they age 10 years. <s> Another spin-off series, "Rugrats Pre-School Daze", was considered, but only four episodes were produced. <s> Two direct-to-video specials were released in 2005 and 2006, under the title "Rugrats Tales from the Crib". <s> Tie-in media for the series include video games, comics, toys, and various other merchandise. <s> In the United States, episodes 102, 111, 123 and 124 were held over from this season and ended up airing during Season 7. <s> The first Klasky Csupo logo still appeared after the second logo appeared at the end of The Rugrats Movie. <s> The second logo did not appear until "Runaway Reptar". <s> During season 7, "Rugrats" made a change with a different format that consisted of three episodes per show. <s> Additionally, all half-hour stories from this point on had two ad breaks instead of one. <s> This is the only season of "Rugrats" to have three episodes per show. <s> The original format for "Rugrats" was brought back for season 8. <s> However, the half-hour episodes retain having two commercial breaks. <s> The first Klasky Csupo logo appeared after the credits in the early airings of this season. <s> However, the Season 8 DVD from Amazon.com, "The '90s Are All That" and the later airings kept the second logo. <s> The third Klasky Csupo logo appeared after the credits in the early airings of this season. <s> However, the Season 9 DVD from Amazon.com, "The '90s Are All That" and the later airings kept the second logo. <s> Nickelodeon and Amazon.com produce DVDs of new and old Nickelodeon shows through the CreateSpace service. <s> Using a concept similar to print on demand, Amazon manufactures the discs, cover art, and disc art. <s> s of May 9, 2014 , Seasons 1–9 were available. <s> s of February 2017 , the Amazon.com releases have been discontinued. <s> In Australia, Beyond Home Entertainment has released all 9 seasons on DVD. <s> In May 2017, Nickelodeon and Paramount Home Entertainment released Seasons 1 and 2 on DVD. <s> In February 2018, Nickelodeon and Paramount Home Media Distribution released Seasons 3 and 4 on DVD. <s> These movies are direct-to- DVD movies that are part of the "Rugrats" series.

title: Nikolay Neprimerov
complex: Nikolay Neprimerov (1 May 1921 – 11 January 2017) was a Doctor of Technical Sciences and professor of physics at the Kazan State University. <s> Neprimerov was Head of the Department of Radioelectronics of the Kazan University for 32 years and is author of more than 150 scientific papers and 9 monographs. <s> He also authored a book about the everyday life of military pilots during World War II. <s> He was awarded numerous honours and medals, among them the Russian Federation Government Prize in Science and Technology . <s> Neprimerov dedicated more than 40 years to and is internationally known for physical research in oil recovery.

title: Luciano Vincenzoni
complex: Luciano Vincenzoni (] ; 7 March 1926 – 22 September 2013) was an Italian screenwriter, known as the "script doctor". <s> He wrote for some 65 films between 1954 and 2000. <s> Vincenzoni was born in Treviso, Veneto. <s> He is probably best known in world cinema for his script writing of Sergio Leone's "For a Few Dollars More" (1965) and "The Good, the Bad and the Ugly" in 1966, but he also wrote for a number of other Spaghetti Westerns.

title: Goygol District
complex: Goygol ( , "Ҝөјҝөл", گويگول) is a rayon (district) in northwestern Azerbaijan. <s> Formerly known as Khanlar, the region was renamed "Goygol" after Lake Goygol, the famous blue lake, by the decision of the Parliament of Azerbaijan on April 25, 2008. <s> The administrative center of the rayon is the city of Goygol.

title: Igualada
complex: Igualada (] ) is a municipality in the province of Barcelona in Catalonia, Spain. <s> It is located on the left bank of the Anoia River and at the western end of the Igualada-Martorell-Barcelona railway. <s> Igualada is the capital and central market of the Anoia comarca, a rich agricultural and wine-producing district. <s> The population, as of 2009 , is 38,918. <s> The city is 65 km west of Barcelona and 20 km west of the famous mountain and monastery of Montserrat.

title: Hans Spemann
complex: Hans Spemann (27 June 1869 – 9 September 1941) was a German embryologist who was awarded a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1935 for his discovery of the effect now known as embryonic induction, an influence, exercised by various parts of the embryo, that directs the development of groups of cells into particular tissues and organs. <s> From 1919 Spemann was Professor of Zoology at the University of Freiburg-im-Breisgau, where he continued his line of enquiry until in 1937 he was relieved of his post to be replaced by one of his first students, Otto Mangold.
simple: Hans Spemann (27 June 1869 – 9 September 1941) was a German doctor. <s> He won the 1935 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, for his discovery of the 'organizer effect' in embryonic development

title: Thomas Kuhn
complex: Thomas Samuel Kuhn ( ; July 18, 1922 – June 17, 1996) was an American philosopher of science whose 1962 book "The Structure of Scientific Revolutions" was influential in both academic and popular circles, introducing the term "paradigm shift", which has since become an English-language idiom. <s> Kuhn's work has been extensively used in social science; for instance, in the post-positivist/positivist debate within International Relations.
simple: Thomas Kuhn (1922-1996) was an American physicist, and philosopher of science. <s> He introduced the idea of paradigm shift.

title: Isle of Mull
complex: The Isle of Mull (Scottish Gaelic An t-Eilean Muileach, ] ) or just Mull (] ; , ] ) is the second-largest island of the Inner Hebrides (after Skye) and lies off the west coast of Scotland in the council area of Argyll and Bute. <s> With an area of 875.35 km2 , Mull is the fourth-largest Scottish island and the fourth-largest island surrounding Great Britain (excluding Ireland). <s> In the 2011 census the usual resident population of Mull was 2,800, which was a slight increase on the 2001 figure of 2,667. <s> In the summer the population is supplemented by many tourists. <s> Much of the population lives in Tobermory, the only burgh on the island until 1973 and its capital. <s> Tobermory is also home to Mull's only single malt Scotch whisky distillery, Tobermory distillery (formerly Ledaig).

title: Marty Napoleon
complex: Marty Napoleon (June 2, 1921 – April 27, 2015) was an American jazz pianist born in Brooklyn, New York, perhaps best known for having replaced Earl Hines in Louis Armstrong's All Stars in 1952. <s> In 1946 he worked with Gene Krupa and went on to work with his uncle Phil Napoleon, a trumpeter, in Phil's Original Memphis Five. <s> In the 1950s he also worked with his brother Teddy Napoleon, a pianist, and from 1966 to 1971 he performed with Armstrong again. <s> Napoleon was born Matthew Napoli in Brooklyn to Sicilian immigrants; he later legally changed his name.
simple: Marty Napoleon (June 2, 1921 – April 27, 2015) was an American jazz pianist. <s> He was best known for having replaced Earl Hines in Louis Armstrong's All Stars in 1952. <s> He also worked with Gene Krupa, Phil Napoleon, Teddy Napoleon, Charlie Ventura, Kai Winding and Rex Stewart. <s> Napoleon was born in Brooklyn, New York City to Italian immigrants from Sicily.

title: Emersons Green
complex: Emersons Green is a town and parish in the unitary authority of South Gloucestershire just to the north of Bristol, England. <s> It was developed from farming land during the 1990s and early 21st century, and sits within the historic parish of Mangotsfield. <s> Coal was mined from the area during the 19th century.
simple: Emersons Green is an area with lots of houses, just to the north of Bristol, in England. <s> Emersons Green is in South Gloucestershire. <s> It used to be just farming land between Mangotsfield and Downend, but in the 1990s houses, schools and shops were built.

title: Motor–generator
complex: A motor–generator (an M–G set) is a device for converting electrical power to another form. <s> Motor–generator sets are used to convert frequency, voltage, or phase of power. <s> They may also be used to isolate electrical loads from the electrical power supply line. <s> Large motor–generators were widely used to convert industrial amounts of power while smaller motor–generators (such as the one shown in the picture) were used to convert battery power to higher DC voltages. <s> Motor–generator sets have been replaced by semiconductor devices for some purposes. <s> In the past, a popular use for MG sets was in elevators.
simple: A motor–generator is a device for converting electrical power to another form. <s> Motor–generator sets are used to convert frequency, voltage, or phase of power. <s> They may also be used to isolate electrical loads from the electrical power supply line. <s> Large motor–generators were widely used to convert industrial amounts of power while smaller motor–generators were used to convert battery power to higher voltages. <s> Nowadays, motor–generators have largely been replaced by semiconductor devices.

title: Ray Gosling
complex: Raymond Arthur Gosling (5 May 1939 – 19 November 2013) was an English broadcaster, journalist, author, and gay rights activist. <s> He wrote and presented several hundred television and radio documentaries and regional programmes for BBC Radio 4 and Granada Television from the 1960s to 1980s on quirky aspects of life in different British towns and cities. <s> His later documentaries focused on his personal life and his emergence as a gay activist. <s> He was described as "one of the most uniquely talented figures in the history of British broadcasting." <s> In February 2010, he claimed during a local BBC television programme to have killed a lover in an act of euthanasia. <s> He was briefly arrested, but the claims were false and he was later given a suspended sentence for wasting police time. <s> Gosling was born in Northampton in 1939. <s> He was educated at Northampton Grammar School and the University of Leicester, and also briefly worked as a railway signalman, before dropping out to become the manager of a band, and then working in a factory in London and as a youth worker in Leicester. <s> Over the years Gosling wrote and presented more than a hundred television documentaries, as well as several hundred radio documentaries. <s> In the 1960s and 1970s he was one of the best known faces in television documentary programming. <s> In this period he also hosted a weekly North-West regional programme on Granada TV, "On Site", in which members of the public, in a different town each week, confronted officialdom with their concerns and complaints. <s> His 1974 Granada series "Gosling's Travels" was praised by the "Sunday Telegraph" and compared to documentaries by John Betjeman and Ian Nairn. <s> He specialised in "the sideways look at such eclectic and quintessentially British institutions as the working classes... and faded seaside towns, the minutiae of life." <s> Gosling died, aged 74, at the Queen's Medical Centre in Nottingham on 19 November 2013.
simple: Raymond Arthur "Ray" Gosling (5 May 1939 – 19 November 2013) was an English broadcaster, journalist, writer, and LGBT rights activist. <s> He was best known for writing and presenting several hundred television and radio documentaries and regional programmes for BBC Radio 4 and Granada Television <s> In February 2010, he claimed during a local BBC television programme to have killed a lover in an act of euthanasia. <s> He was arrested, but the claims weren't real and he was given a suspended sentence for wasting police time. <s> Gosling was born on 5 May 1939 in Northampton, Northamptonshire. <s> He went to Northampton Grammar School and the University of Leicester. <s> Gosling died on 19 November 2013 at the Queen's Medical Centre in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire. <s> He was 74 years old.

title: Vladimir Kazachyonok
complex: Vladimir Aleksandrovich Kazachyonok ( ; 6 September 1952 – 26 March 2017) was a Soviet football player and Russian coach. <s> He was the academy director with FC Zenit Saint Petersburg until his death in 2017. <s> Kazachyonok made his debut for USSR on December 1, 1976 in a friendly against Brazil. <s> He also played in a UEFA Euro 1980 qualifier against Finland. <s> On 26 March 2017, it was reported that Kazachyonok died in Saint Petersburg at the age of 64.
simple: Vladimir Aleksandrovich Kazachyonok (; 6 September 1952 – 26 March 2017) was a Soviet football player and Russian coach. <s> He was the academy director with FC Zenit Saint Petersburg until his death in 2017. <s> Kazachyonok made his debut for USSR on December 1, 1976 in a friendly against Brazil. <s> He also played in a UEFA Euro 1980 qualifier against Finland. <s> Kazachyonok died on 26 March 2017 in Saint Petersburg, Russia from a suspected heart attack at the age of 64.

title: Grains of Selim
complex: Grains of Selim are the seeds of a shrubby tree, "Xylopia aethiopica", found in Africa. <s> The seeds have a musky flavor and are used as a spice in a manner similar to black pepper, and as a flavouring agent that defines , the dominant style of coffee in Senegal. <s> It is also known as Kani pepper, Senegal pepper, Ethiopian pepper, and (historically) Moor pepper and Negro pepper. <s> It also has many names in native languages of Africa, the most common of which is in the Wolof language (this is the name used on most packages of ). <s> It is called 'Etso' in the Ewe language of Ghana. <s> It is sometimes referred to as African pepper or Guinea pepper, but these are ambiguous terms that may refer to Ashanti pepper and grains of paradise, among others.
simple: It is made from the seeds of the shrub "Xylopia aethiopica", found in Africa. <s> The seeds have a musky flavor. <s> Other names include kimba pepper, African pepper, Moor pepper, Negro pepper, Kani pepper, Kili pepper, Sénégal pepper, Ethiopian pepper and Guinea pepper. <s> The spice is sometimes confused with grains of paradise.

title: Pacifier
complex: A pacifier (American English) or dummy (British English and Australian English), also known as a binky, soother (Canadian English), teether or Dodie is a rubber, plastic or silicone nipple given to an infant to suckle upon. <s> In its standard appearance it has a teat, mouth shield, and handle.

title: Rebecka Liljeberg
complex: Rebecka Månstråle Liljeberg (born 13 May 1981) is a Swedish former actress best known for her performance in Swedish film "Show Me Love (Fucking Åmål) (1998)". <s> Rebecka was born in the town of Turinge, Sweden to an 18-year-old Swedish mother Kristina, and a 24-year-old Finnish father, Jyrki. <s> Her parents divorced when she was only one year old. <s> At the age of 9, Liljeberg began her acting career when she won a role in the series "Sunes jul". <s> Between 1993 and 1997, she became involved in amateur theatre, which she continued until landing a role in the film "Närkontakt" later in 1997. <s> However, it was the following year she got her breakthrough in the Lukas Moodysson film "Show Me Love (Fucking Åmål) (1998)". <s> She quit high school to make the film, which ultimately won her the 1999 Guldbagge award for best actress, together with Alexandra Dahlström. <s> After her roles in "Fucking Åmål" and "Sherdil", Liljeberg began an adult education course in order to graduate from high school. <s> While studying, she also starred in the relatively successful arthouse film "Bear's Kiss" which was her first and only English-speaking film. <s> In 2002, she completed the adult education course, and went on to study medicine at the Karolinska Institutet in Stockholm, one of the largest medical universities in Europe. <s> Rebecka stopped acting after her film "Bear's Kiss (2002)" and now works as a pediatrician. <s> She lives in Stockholm.
simple: Rebecka Månstråle Liljeberg (born 13 May 1981) is a Swedish actress. <s> She was born in Turinge, about 40 km southwest of Stockholm, and moved around Sweden for much of her youth. <s> Liljeberg's mother was relatively young when she was born, and her parents divorced when she was one year old. <s> At the age of 9 (1991), Liljeberg began her acting career when she won a role in the series "Sunes jul". <s> Between 1993 and 1997, she became played in amateur theatre, which she continued with until gaining a role in the movie "Närkontakt" later in 1997. <s> The following year she won her breakthrough role in the Lukas Moodysson movie "Fucking Åmål". <s> For the movie she stopped his study in high school to take up the role, which ultimately won her the 1999 Guldbagge Award for Best Actress, together with Alexandra Dahlström. <s> After her roles in "Fucking Åmål" and "Sherdil", Liljeberg began an adult education course in order to graduate from high school. <s> While studying, she also played in "Bear's Kiss", and voiced a character in the Swedish version of IMAX movie "T-Rex: Back to the Cretaceous". <s> In 2002, she completed the adult education course, and is now studying medicine at the Karolinska Institute to become a pediatrician. <s> Liljeberg now lives in Stockholm with her boyfriend Alexander Skepp.

complex: Zdeněk Svěrák (born 28 March 1936) is a Czech actor, humorist and scriptwriter, and one of the most well-known and popular Czech cultural personalities. <s> Since 1968 he has apppeared in 32 films. <s> Svěrák has won three Magnesia Litera awards for his writing. <s> In 2004 he won the Readers' Choice award for his book "Jaké je to asi v čudu".

title: International Opium Convention
complex: The International Opium Convention, signed at The Hague on January 23, 1912 during the First International Opium Conference, was the first international drug control treaty. <s> It was registered in "League of Nations Treaty Series" on January 23, 1922. <s> The United States convened a 13-nation conference of the International Opium Commission in 1909 in Shanghai, China in response to increasing criticism of the opium trade. <s> The treaty was signed by Germany, the United States, China, France, the United Kingdom, Italy, Japan, the Netherlands, Persia, Portugal, Russia, and Siam. <s> The Convention provided, "The contracting Powers shall use their best endeavours to control, or to cause to be controlled, all persons manufacturing, importing, selling, distributing, and exporting morphine, cocaine, and their respective salts, as well as the buildings in which these persons carry such an industry or trade." <s> The Convention was implemented in 1915 by the United States, Netherlands, China, Honduras, and Norway. <s> It went into force globally in 1919, when it was incorporated into the Treaty of Versailles. <s> The primary objective of the convention was to introduce restrictions on exports as opposed to imposing prohibition or criminalising the use and cultivation of opium, coca, and cannabis. <s> That explains the withdrawal of the United States and China, which were gravitating towards prohibitionist approaches, as well as the beginning of negotiations leading to the 1925 International Opium Convention in Geneva. <s> A revised International Opium Convention "International Convention relating to Dangerous Drugs" was signed at Geneva on February 19, 1925, which went into effect on September 25, 1938, and was registered in "League of Nations Treaty Series" on the same day. <s> It introduced a statistical control system to be supervised by a Permanent Central Opium Board, a body of the League of Nations. <s> Egypt, with support from China and United States, recommended that a prohibition on hashish be added to the Convention, and a sub-committee proposed the following text: The use of Indian hemp and the preparations derived therefrom may only be authorized for medical and scientific purposes. <s> The raw resin (charas), however, which is extracted from the female tops of the cannabis sativa L, together with the various preparations (hashish, chira, esrar, diamba, etc.) of which it forms the basis, not being at present utilized for medical purposes and only being susceptible of utilisation for harmful purposes, in the same manner as other narcotics, may not be produced, sold, traded in, etc., under any circumstances whatsoever. <s> India and other countries objected to this language, citing social and religious customs and the prevalence of wild-growing cannabis plants that would make it difficult to enforce. <s> Accordingly, this provision never made it into the final treaty. <s> A compromise was made that banned exportation of "Indian hemp" to countries that have prohibited its use, and requiring importing countries to issue certificates approving the importation and stating that the shipment was required "exclusively for medical or scientific purposes." <s> It also required Parties to "exercise an effective control of such a nature as to prevent the illicit international traffic in Indian hemp and especially in the resin." <s> These restrictions still left considerable leeway for countries to allow production, internal trade, and use of cannabis for recreational purposes. <s> The Convention was superseded by the 1961 Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs.
simple: The International Opium Convention was the first drug control treaty (or agreement). <s> It was signed at The Hague in The Netherlands on January 23, 1912. <s> The United States organised a conference between 13 countries called the International Opium Commission in 1909 in Shanghai, China because people complained more and more about opium trade. <s> The treaty was signed by Germany, the United States, China, France, the United Kingdom, Italy, Japan, The Netherlands, Persia, Portugal, Russia, and Siam. <s> The Convention said that "The contracting Powers shall use their best endeavours to control, or to cause to be controlled, all persons manufacturing, importing, selling, distributing, and exporting morphine, cocaine, and their respective salts, as well as the buildings in which these persons carry such an industry or trade." <s> The Convention was implemented in 1915 by the United States, Netherlands, China, Honduras, and Norway. <s> It went into force around the world in 1919 when it became part of the Treaty of Versailles. <s> A modified International Opium Convention was signed on February 19, 1925, which started on September 25, 1928. <s> It introduced control system to be looked after by a Permanent Central Opium Board, part of the League of Nations. <s> Egypt, with support from China and United States, recommended that a ban on hashish be added to the Convention, and a sub-committee proposed the following text: The use of Indian hemp and the preparations derived therefrom may only be authorized for medical and scientific purposes. <s> The raw resin (charas), however, which is extracted from the female tops of the cannabis sativa L, together with the various preparations (hashish, chira, esrar, diamba, etc.) of which it forms the basis, not being at present utilized for medical purposes and only being susceptible of utilisation for harmful purposes, in the same manner as other narcotics, may not be produced, sold, traded in, etc., under any circumstances whatsoever. <s> India and other countries did not agree to this language, saying social and religious customs and that wild-growing cannabis plants being available in many places, that would make it difficult to enforce, so this never made it into the final treaty. <s> A compromise was made that banned the export of "Indian hemp" to countries that have banned its use. <s> Importing countries were made to issue certificates approving the import and stating that the shipment was required "exclusively for medical or scientific purposes." <s> It also required Parties to "exercise an effective control of such a nature as to prevent the illicit international traffic in Indian hemp and especially in the resin." <s> These restrictions still made it easy for countries to allow production, internal trade, and use of cannabis for recreational purposes. <s> The Convention was superseded by the 1961 Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs.

title: Florennes
complex: Florennes (] ) is a Walloon municipality located in Belgium in the province of Namur. <s> On 1 January 2006 Florennes had a total population of 10,754.
