title: San Luis Rey River
complex: The San Luis Rey River is a river in northern San Diego County, California. <s> The river's headwaters are in the Palomar Mountain Range and Cleveland National Forest, near Palomar Mountain and the Santa Rosa Mountains. <s> The river mouth, on the Pacific Ocean, is in northern Oceanside. <s> The San Luis Rey River bike path runs along it for its last 9 mi . <s> The river is over 69 mi long and drains 562 sqmi . <s> There is little water in the river during most of the year, but it can have very large flows during winter storms.
simple: The San Luis Rey River is a river in the southern part of the U.S. state of California. <s> It begins in the Cleveland National Forest, near a mountain called Palomar Mountain, in several forks. <s> It then turns west and flows to its mouth at the Pacific Ocean. <s> Its watershed covers an area of 562 square miles.

title: A Tale of Two Cities
complex: A Tale of Two Cities (1859) is a historical novel by Charles Dickens, set in London and Paris before and during the French Revolution. <s> The novel tells the story of the French Doctor Manette, his 18-year-long imprisonment in the Bastille in Paris and his release to live in London with his daughter Lucie, whom he had never met.
simple: A Tale of Two Cities is a book written by Charles Dickens.

title: Shuchō
complex: Shuchō (朱鳥 ) , alternatively read as "Suchō" or "Akamitori", was a Japanese era name (年号 , "nengō" , "year name") after a gap following "Hakuchi" (650–654) and before another gap lasting until "Taihō" (701–704). <s> This "Shuchō" period briefly spanned a period of mere months, June through September 686. <s> The reigning sovereigns were Tenmu"-tennō" (天武天皇 ) and Jitō"-tennō" (持統天皇 ) . <s> The system of Japanese era names was not the same as Imperial reign dates.
simple: Shuchō (朱鳥), also romanized as Suchō or Akamitori, was a Japanese era name (年号, "nengō", lit. <s> "year name") which lsated only a few monthsfrom June through September 686. <s> The reigning monarchs were Temmu"-tennō" (天武天皇) and Jitō"-tennō" (持統天皇). <s> The system of Japanese era names was not the same as Imperial reign dates.

title: Heqet
complex: Heqet (Egyptian " ", also " " "Heqtit") is an Egyptian goddess of fertility, identified with Hathor, represented in the form of a frog. <s> To the Egyptians, the frog was an ancient symbol of fertility, related to the annual flooding of the Nile.

title: Destroy All Humans! (2005 video game)
complex: is an action-adventure video game developed by Pandemic Studios and published by THQ for PlayStation 2 and Xbox. <s> The game is set in 1959 in the United States, and parodies the lifestyles, pop culture, and political attitudes of this time period. <s> The player controls Cryptosporidium 137 (a reference to the protozoan parasite "Cryptosporidium"), a member of the fictional Furon race of alien life, who has come to Earth to harvest DNA from humans to continue the cloning process of his species. <s> A full remake of the game is currently set for a 2020 release.
simple: is a video game developed by Pandemic Studios and published by THQ. <s> It was released for the Xbox and PlayStation 2 game consoles. <s> The game is set in 1950s U.S. and parodies the lifestyles, pop culture, and politics of this time period. <s> The player controls Cryptosporidium 137, a member of the Furon race of aliens, who has come to Earth to harvest DNA from humans to continue the cloning process of his species.

title: Intensive care unit
complex: An intensive care unit (ICU), also known as an intensive therapy unit or intensive treatment unit (ITU) or critical care unit (CCU), is a special department of a hospital or health care facility that provides intensive treatment medicine. <s> In 1854, Florence Nightingale left for the Crimean War, where triage was used to separate seriously wounded soldiers from the non-life-threatening conditions. <s> Until recently, it was reported that Nightingale reduced mortality from 40% to 2% on the battlefield. <s> Although this was not the case, her experiences during the war formed the foundation for her later discovery of the importance of sanitary conditions in hospitals, a critical component of intensive care. <s> In response to a polio epidemic (where many patients required constant ventilation and surveillance), Bjørn Aage Ibsen established the first intensive care unit in Copenhagen in 1953. <s> The first application of this idea in the United States was in 1955 by William Mosenthal, a surgeon at the Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center. <s> In the 1960s, the importance of cardiac arrhythmias as a source of morbidity and mortality in myocardial infarctions (heart attacks) was recognized.
simple: An intensive care unit (ICU), critical care unit (CCU), intensive therapy unit (ITU), or intensive treatment unit (ITU) is a special part of a hospital. <s> In 1854, Florence Nightingale went to the Crimean War. <s> Nightingale reduced death rates from 40% to 2% by creating the concept of intensive care. <s> Because of a polio epidemic, Bjørn Ibsen established the first intensive care unit in Copenhagen in 1953. <s> The first person to use this idea in the United States was Dr. William Mosenthal, a surgeon at the Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center.

title: Baker County, Georgia
complex: Baker County is a county in Georgia. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 3,451. <s> The county seat and only city is Newton. <s> The county was created December 12, 1825 from the eastern portion of Early County by an act of the Georgia General Assembly and is named for Colonel John Baker, a hero of the American Revolutionary War.
simple: Baker County, Georgia is a county in Georgia. <s> Its county seat is Newton.

title: George Drennen Fischer
complex: George Drennen Fischer was an American activist and spokesman for the National Education Association. <s> He presented the Statement on Comprehensive Preschool Education and Child Day Care Act of 1969 before the Select Subcommittee on Education, February 27, 1970. <s> He also published on the state of Native American education with Walter Mondale. <s> His actions got him placed on the master list of Nixon political opponents.

title: Onagawa, Miyagi
complex: Onagawa (女川町 , Onagawa-chō ) is a town located in Miyagi Prefecture, Japan. <s> s of 01 2019 , the town had an estimated population of 5,870, and a population density of 90 persons per km2 in 3,148 households. <s> The total area of the town is 65.35 sqkm . <s> Onagawa was one of the most heavily damaged communities by the 11 March 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami. <s> The tsunami reached in excess of 15 m in height and swept 1 km inland, claiming 827 lives and destroying 70% of the buildings in the town. <s> At least 12 of the town's 25 designated evacuation sites were inundated by the tsunami.
simple: Onagawa is a town in Miyagi Prefecture. <s> The town was badly damaged by the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami. <s> The tsunami reached a maximum of 15 metres in height and went as much as one kilometer in from the coast.

title: Ocellated turkey
complex: The ocellated turkey ("Meleagris ocellata") is a species of turkey residing primarily in the Yucatán Peninsula. <s> A relative of the wild turkey ("Meleagris gallopavo"), it was sometimes previously treated in a genus of its own ("Agriocharis"), but the differences between the two turkeys are currently considered too small to justify generic segregation.
simple: An ocellated turkey ("Meleagris ocellata") is a turkey (a large bird) that is named for the eye-like spots on the tail feathers ("ocellated" means having eye-like spots).

title: Sue Ane Langdon
complex: Sue Ane Langdon (born Sue Lookhoff; March 8, 1936) is an American actress. <s> She has appeared in dozens of television series and had featured roles in films like "A Guide for the Married Man" and "The Cheyenne Social Club", both directed by Gene Kelly, as well as "The Rounders" opposite Henry Fonda and Glenn Ford and a pair of Elvis Presley movies, "Roustabout" and "Frankie and Johnny". <s> She began her performing career singing at Radio City Music Hall and acting in stage productions. <s> In the mid-1960s, she appeared in the Broadway musical "The Apple Tree", which starred Alan Alda. <s> Langdon was born in Paterson, New Jersey, to Albert G. Lookhoff and Grace (née Huddle), an operatic soprano.
simple: Sue Ane Langdon (previously Sue Lookhoff; born 8 March 1936) is a retired American actress. <s> She began her career with singing and theatre. <s> Langdon was born in Paterson, New Jersey.

title: Perth and Kinross
complex: Perth and Kinross ( ; ) is one of the 32 council areas of Scotland and a Lieutenancy Area. <s> It borders onto the Aberdeenshire, Angus, Argyll and Bute, Clackmannanshire, Dundee, Fife, Highland and Stirling council areas. <s> Perth is the administrative centre. <s> With the exception of a large area of south-western Perthshire, the council area mostly corresponds to the historic counties of Perthshire and Kinross-shire.
simple: Perth and Kinross ("Peairt agus Ceann Rois" in Gaelic) is one of 32 unitary council areas in Scotland. <s> It borders onto the Aberdeenshire, Angus, City of Dundee, Fife, Clackmannanshire, Stirling, Argyll and Bute and Highland council areas. <s> Perth is the administrative centre. <s> It corresponds broadly, but not exactly, with the former counties of Perthshire and Kinross-shire.

title: Kaiserschmarrn
complex: Kaiserschmarrn or Kaiserschmarren (Emperor's Mess) is a sweet dessert that takes its name from the Austrian emperor (Kaiser) Franz Joseph I, who was very fond of this kind of fluffy shredded pancake. <s> Kaiserschmarrn is a popular meal or dessert in Austria, Bavaria, and many former parts of the Habsburg Monarchy, e.g. Hungary, Slovenia, and northern Croatia, which usually use the name as a loan word or translations of it. <s> In Slovenia, it is called "cesarski praženec" or "šmorn". <s> Its Hungarian name is "császármorzsa"; its Czech name is "(Císařský) trhanec" or "kajzršmorn". <s> Kaiserschmarren is a light, caramelized pancake made from a sweet batter using flour, eggs, sugar, salt, and milk, baked in butter. <s> Kaiserschmarren can be prepared in different ways. <s> When making Kaiserschmarren the egg whites are usually separated from the yolk and beaten until stiff; then the flour and the yolks are mixed with sugar, and the other ingredients are added, including: nuts, cherries, plums, apple jam, or small pieces of apple, or caramelized raisins and slivered almonds. <s> The last mentioned ingredients (nuts, cherries, plums, apple jam, or small pieces of apple, or caramelized raisins and chopped almonds) aren't in the original recipe and just additions made by some cooks based on their personal preferences. <s> In the original recipe there are only raisins (which, before cooking, are soaked in rum). <s> The pancake is split with two forks into pieces while frying and usually sprinkled with powdered sugar, then served hot with apple or plum sauce or various fruit compotes, including plum, lingonberry, strawberry, or apple. <s> Kaiserschmarren is eaten like a dessert, or it can also be eaten for lunch at tourist places like mountainside restaurants and taverns in the Austrian Alps, as a quite filling meal. <s> Traditionally, Kaiserschmarren is accompanied with "Zwetschgenröster", a fruit compote made out of plums.
simple: Kaiserschmarrn is a well-known Austrian dessert. <s> It was popular in the former Austria–Hungary as well as in Bavaria. <s> The Czech name is "trhanec" or "kajzršmorn". <s> In Hungary it is called "császármorzsa" or simply "smarni". <s> Kaiserschmarrn is a light, caramelized pancake. <s> It is made from a sweet batter using flour, eggs, sugar, salt, and milk, baked in butter. <s> Kaiserschmarrn can be prepared in different ways. <s> When making Kaiserschmarrn the egg-whites are usually separated from the yolk and beaten until stiff. <s> Then the flour and the yolks are mixed with sugar, and the other ingredients are added. <s> The pancake is split into pieces while frying, shredded after preparation. <s> It is usually sprinkled with powdered sugar, then served hot with apple or plum sauce or various fruit compotes. <s> Kaiserschmarrn is eaten like a dessert. <s> Traditionally Kaiserschmarrn is served with "Zwetschkenröster", a fruit compote made out of Plums.

title: Tipsport liga (hockey)
complex: The Slovak Tipsport Liga (Slovenská Extraliga) is the highest-level ice hockey league in Slovakia. <s> Since the 2018–19 season, the league also includes two teams from Hungary.
simple: The Slovak Extraliga is the top level ice hockey league in Slovakia.

title: Doni (footballer)
complex: Doniéber Alexander Marangon (born 22 October 1979), known as Doni, is a Brazilian former footballer who played as a goalkeeper.
simple: Doniéber Alexander Marangon (born 22 October 1979) is a Brazilian football player.

title: Lake Alexandrina (South Australia)
complex: Lake Alexandrina is a freshwater lake located in the Fleurieu and Kangaroo Island and Murray Mallee regions of South Australia, adjacent to the coast of the Southern Ocean, about 100 km south-east of Adelaide. <s> The lake adjoins the smaller Lake Albert; together they are known as the Lower Lakes. <s> The lake was named after Princess Alexandrina, niece and successor of King William IV of Great Britain and Ireland. <s> When the princess ascended the throne and took the name Queen Victoria there was some talk of changing the name of the lake to Lake Victoria, but the idea was dropped.
simple: Lake Alexandrina is a large lake about 45 mi south east of Adelaide, South Australia. <s> Sturt named the lake after Princess Alexandrina, who later became Queen Victoria.

title: Tiengemeten
complex: Tiengemeten is an island in the Dutch province of South Holland. <s> It is a part of the municipality of Korendijk, and lies about 11 km south of Spijkenisse. <s> Before 1984 the island was administratively split between Goudswaard and Zuid-Beijerland.
simple: Tiengemeten is an island of the province of South Holland, the Netherlands. <s> It lies in the Haringvliet and belongs to the municipality of Korendijk.

title: Borna, Leipzig
complex: Borna (] ) is a town in the Free State of Saxony, Germany, capital of the Leipzig district. <s> It is situated approximately 30 km southeast of Leipzig city. <s> It has approx. 22,000 inhabitants.
simple: Borna is a town in the rural district Leipzig, in Saxony, Germany. <s> It is located about 25 km southeast of Leipzig.

title: Eric Shinseki
complex: Eric Ken Shinseki ( ; born November 28, 1942) is a retired United States Army general who served as the seventh United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs (2009–2014). <s> His final United States Army post was as the 34th Chief of Staff of the Army (1999–2003). <s> Shinseki is a veteran of two tours of combat in the Vietnam War, in which he was awarded three Bronze Star Medals for valor and two Purple Hearts.
simple: Eric Ken Shinseki (born November 28, 1942) is a retired United States Army four-star general who was serving as the 7th United States Secretary of Veterans Affairs. <s> His last U.S. Army position was as the 34th Chief of Staff of the Army (1999-2003).

title: Thirunallar
complex: Thirunallar is a small town in Karaikal, India, in the Union Territory of Puducherry, and can be reached by road from the town of Karaikal, an enclave which lies within the neighbouring state of Tamil Nadu. <s> Thirunallar is most noted for the shrine of Lord Sani (Saturn), Tirunallar Saniswaran Temple within the temple dedicated to Lord Darbharanyeswaran, a form of Lord Shiva. <s> This is the only temple that is dedicated to Lord Shani (Saneeswaran, in Tamil). <s> Whenever (planet) Saturn transits from one zodiac sign to another (an occurrence roughly every 2.5 years), millions throng this shrine for worship. <s> The legendary King Nala is said to have been relieved of his afflictions caused by the malefic influence of Saturn, after worship in this temple. <s> Of the numerous theertams (sacred bathing places), the Nala theertam is the most important one. <s> It is believed that by bathing here, one washes off all kinds of misfortunes and afflictions caused by one's past of karmas (in terms of deities, Lord Shani or Saturn is said to be the dispenser of karmas (both good and bad), but also one whose Grace, particularly at this shrine, can dispel bad karmas or, at least, make them bearable) <s> The name ThiruNallar(u) is believed to represent the association of King Nala of the Nishadha country who was delivered from the bad effects of Shani (Saturn) by invoking the Lord's mercy here (Nala + Aru = Nallaru). <s> The word "Aru" here denotes "to heal" and the two words taken together means the place where Nala was redeemed from the (malefic) hold of Saturn through the Lord's Grace.
simple: Thirunallar is a small town in the district of Karaikal, Puducherry Union territory, India. <s> Thirunallar is specially famous for the temple dedicated to Lord Shani, or Lord Saturn. <s> The temple of this town is the only temple dedicated to Lord Shani in the whole world. <s> Whenever Lord Saturn passes from one zodiac sign to the other (Sani Peyarchi), millions of people comes to Thirunallar for worshiping the lord. <s> Thirunallar is believed to be named for King Nala, the king of the country of Nishadha.

title: Statute of Westminster 1931
complex: The Statute of Westminster 1931 is an Act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom whose modified versions are now domestic law within Australia and Canada; it has been repealed in New Zealand and implicitly in former Dominions that are no longer Commonwealth realms. <s> Passed on 11 December 1931, the act, either immediately or upon ratification, effectively both established the legislative independence of the self-governing Dominions of the British Empire from the United Kingdom and bound them all to seek each other's approval for changes to monarchical titles and the common line of succession. <s> It thus became a statutory embodiment of the principles of equality and common allegiance to the Crown set out in the Balfour Declaration of 1926. <s> As the statute removed nearly all of the British parliament's authority to legislate for the Dominions, it had the effect of making the Dominions largely sovereign nations in their own right. <s> It was a crucial step in the development of the Dominions as separate states. <s> The Statute of Westminster's relevance today is that it sets the basis for the continuing relationship between the Commonwealth realms and the Crown.
simple: The Statute of Westminster 1931 is an Act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom. <s> It is still law in each of the Commonwealth realms. <s> It was passed on 11 December 1931. <s> The Act gave equality to the self-governing dominions of the British Empire. <s> Its current relevance is that it sets the basis for the continuing relationship between the Commonwealth realms and the Crown.

title: Cerise (color)
complex: Cerise ( or ; ] ) is a deep to vivid reddish pink. <s> The colour or name comes from the French word "cerise", meaning cherry in French. <s> According to the Oxford English Dictionary, the first recorded use of "cerise" as a colour name in English was in "The Times" of November 30, 1858. <s> This date of 1858 as the date of first use of the color name is also mentioned in the 1930 book "A Dictionary of Color". <s> However, it was used at least as early as 1845 in a book of crochet patterns. <s> In the 1950s, a popular brand of colored pencils, "Venus Paradise", had a colored pencil called Hollywood cerise which was this color. <s> Before being renamed "Hollywood cerise" in the 1940s, the color had been known, since its inception in 1922, simply as Hollywood. <s> The color irresistible is displayed at right.
simple: Cerise is a rose-red color. <s> The "cerise" name comes from the French word meaning cherry. <s> The word "cherry" itself comes from the Norman "cherise". <s> According to Maerz and Paul in their "Dictionary of Color", the first recorded use of "cerise" as a color name in English was in 1858. <s> However, it was used at least as early as 1846 in a book of crochet patterns. <s> In the 1950s, a popular brand of colored pencils, Venus Paradise, had a colored pencil called "Hollywood cerise" . <s> Before being renamed "Hollywood cerise" in the 1940s, the color had before that, since 1922, been known simply as "Hollywood". <s> At right is displayed the color cerise.

title: Choi Sung-kuk
complex: Choi Sung-Kuk (born 8 February 1983) is a former South Korean footballer who played the forward position.
simple: Choi Sung-Kuk (born 8 February 1983) is a South Korean football player.

title: Eredivisie
complex: The Eredivisie (] ; ""Honour Division"" or ""Premier Division"") is the highest echelon of professional football in the Netherlands. <s> The league was founded in 1956, two years after the start of professional football in the Netherlands. <s> As of the 2018–19 season it is ranked the 11th best league in Europe by UEFA.
simple: Eredivisie is a football league which is top division in Netherlands. <s> It was created in 1956. <s> Before 1956, the teams competed in the Netherlands Football League Championship.

title: Thubten Zopa Rinpoche
complex: Thubten Zopa Rinpoche (Tibetan: ཐུབ་བསྟན་བཟོད་པ་ , Wylie: "Thub-bstan Bzod-pa" <s> Thubten Zopa Rinpoche, also called Lama Zopa Rinpoche has an extensive biography of him in the book "The Lawudo Lama" by Jamyang Wangmo. <s> Early in life, he was recognized as the reincarnation of the Lawudo Lama Kunzang Yeshe, from the same region (hence the title "Rinpoche"). <s> He took his monastic vows at Dungkar Monastery in Tibet where he travelled in 1957. <s> Lama Zopa is most noteworthy as the co-founder, with Lama Yeshe, of Kopan Monastery and the Foundation for the Preservation of the Mahayana Tradition (FPMT). <s> In 1972 he along with Lama Yeshe founded Tushita Meditation Centre near McLeod Ganj at village Dharamkot in Himachal Pradesh. <s> Since the 1984 death of Lama Yeshe, Lama Zopa has served as the FPMT's spiritual director. <s> FPMT states that, "under Rinpoche’s guidance, FPMT plans to build two large statues of the future Buddha, Maitreya, in Bodhgaya and Kushinagar in India; The Sera Je Food Fund, which offers three vegetarian meals a day to all 2,500 monks studying at Sera Je Monastery in south India; Animal Liberation events around the world, at which creatures, big and small, are freed from immediate harm or blessed every year– the total number of animals liberated to date (by Lama Zopa Rinpoche or those inspired by him) is over 200,000,000 and counting!" <s> Lama Zopa Rinpoches's books are published by Wisdom Publications and Lama Yeshe Wisdom Archive. <s> Free transcripts of some of his teachings are available from the Lama Yeshe Wisdom Archive.
simple: Thubten Zopa Rinpoche (born 1946) is a lama from Nepal. <s> There is an extensive biography of him in the book 'The Lawudo Lama', by Jamyang Wangmo. <s> He took his monks vows at Dungkar Monastery in Tibet and has received teachings from many high lamas. <s> Lama Zopa is the co-founder, with Lama Yeshe, of Kopan Monastery and the FPMT. <s> Since the 1984 death of Lama Yeshe, Lama Zopa has served as the FPMT's spiritual director. <s> Zopa's books are published by Wisdom Publications. <s> Free books and a vast online collection of his teachings are available from the Lama Yeshe Wisdom Archive.

title: February
complex: February is the second and shortest month of the year in the Julian and Gregorian calendar with 28 days in common years and 29 days in leap years, with the quadrennial 29th day being called the "leap day". <s> It is the first of five months to have a length of fewer than 31 days (the other four months that fall under this category are: April, June, September, and November), and the only month to have a length of fewer than 30 days, with the other seven months having 31 days. <s> In 2019, February 28 days. <s> February is the third and last month of meteorological winter in the Northern Hemisphere. <s> In the Southern Hemisphere, February is the third and last month of summer (the seasonal equivalent of August in the Northern Hemisphere, in meteorological reckoning). <s> The Roman month "Februarius" was named after the Latin term "februum", which means "purification", via the purification ritual "Februa" held on February 15 (full moon) in the old lunar Roman calendar. <s> January and February were the last two months to be added to the Roman calendar, since the Romans originally considered winter a monthless period. <s> They were added by Numa Pompilius about 713 BC. <s> February remained the last month of the calendar year until the time of the decemvirs (c. 450 BC), when it became the second month. <s> At certain intervals February was truncated to 23 or 24 days, and a 27-day intercalary month, Intercalaris, was inserted immediately after February to realign the year with the seasons. <s> February is also the only month of the calendar that, once every six years and twice every 11 years consecutively, either back into the past or forward into the future, has four full 7-day weeks. <s> In countries that start their week on a Monday, it occurs as part of a common year starting on Friday, in which February 1st is a Monday and the 28th is a Sunday; this occurred in 1965, 1971, 1982, 1993, 1999 and 2010, and occur will again in 2021. <s> In countries that start their week on a Sunday, it occurs in a common year starting on Thursday, with the next occurrence in 2026, and previous occurrences in 1987, 1998, 2009 and 2015. <s> The pattern is broken by a skipped leap year, but no leap year has been skipped since 1900 and no others will be skipped until 2100. <s> The western zodiac signs of February are Aquarius (until February 19) and Pisces (February 20 onwards).
simple: February (Feb.) is the 2nd month of the year, coming between January and March, with 28 days in common years, and 29 days in leap years. <s> February begins on the same day of the week as March and November in common years, and August in leap years. <s> February is the second month of the year, coming between January and March, and is also the shortest month, with 28 days in a common year, and 29 days in a leap year. <s> February begins on the same day of the week as March and November in common years and on the same day of the week as August in leap years. <s> In a leap year, February is the only month to begin and end on the same day of the week. <s> This year February 28 days in it. <s> February is a winter month in the Northern Hemisphere and a summer month in the Southern Hemisphere. <s> In each hemisphere, it is the seasonal equivalent of August in the other. <s> The name comes either from the Roman god Februus or else from "februa", the festivals of purification celebrated in Rome every fifteenth of this month. <s> February is one of the last two months to be added to the calendar at the beginning of the year (the other is January). <s> February is also the only month of the calendar that, once every six years and twice every 11 years consecutively, either back into the past or forward into the future, will have four full 7-day weeks. <s> In countries that start their week on a Monday, it occurs as part of a common year starting on Friday, in which February 1st is a Monday and the 28th is a Sunday, this was observed in 2010 and can be traced back 11 years to 1999, 6 years back to 1993, 11 years back to 1982, 11 years back to 1971 and 6 years back to 1965, and will be observed in 2021. <s> In countries that start their week on a Sunday, it occurs in a common year starting on Thursday, with the next occurrence in 2026, and previous occurrences in 2015 (11 years earlier than 2026), 2009 (6 years earlier than 2015), 1998 (11 years earlier than 2009) and 1987 (11 years earlier than 1998). <s> This works unless the pattern is broken by a skipped leap year, but no leap year has been skipped since 1900 and no others will be skipped until 2100. <s> The zodiac signs for February are Aquarius (January 21 to February 19), and Pisces (February 20 to March 20).

title: Mechanical energy
complex: In physical sciences, mechanical energy is the sum of potential energy and kinetic energy. <s> It is the energy associated with the motion and position of an object. <s> The principle of conservation of mechanical energy states that in an isolated system that is only subject to conservative forces, the mechanical energy is constant. <s> If an object moves in the opposite direction of a conservative net force, the potential energy will increase; and if the speed (not the velocity) of the object changes, the kinetic energy of the object also changes.
simple: In physics, mechanical energy describes the potential energy and kinetic energy present in the components of a mechanical system. <s> The conservation of mechanical energy is a principle which states that under certain conditions, the total mechanical energy of a system is constant.

title: Jan-Michael Vincent
complex: Jan-Michael Vincent (July 15, 1944 – February 10, 2019) was an American actor. <s> He was best known for having played helicopter pilot Stringfellow Hawke on the television series "Airwolf" (1984–1986) and the protagonist, Matt Johnson, in the 1978 film "Big Wednesday". <s> He also starred as Byron Henry in "The Winds of War". <s> Vincent died on February 10, 2019, aged 74, in Asheville, North Carolina due to cardiac arrest while hospitalized at Mission Hospital Memorial Campus. <s> Bradycardia, a decreased heart rate, was listed as an underlying cause of death.
simple: Jan-Michael Vincent (July 15, 1945 – February 10, 2019) was an American actor. <s> He was well known for playing helicopter pilot Stringfellow Hawke on the television series "Airwolf" from 1984 to 1986 and the protagonist, Matt Johnson, in the 1978 movie "Big Wednesday". <s> Vincent died of cardiac arrest at a hospital in Asheville, North Carolina on February 10, 2019, aged 73.

title: Muhsin Musabah
complex: Muhsin Musabah Faraj Fairouz (born October 1, 1964) is a retired United Arab Emirati footballer. <s> He played as a goalkeeper for the United Arab Emirates national football team as well as the Sharjah Club in Sharjah.
simple: Muhsin Musabah (born 1 October 1964) is a former United Arab Emirati football player. <s> He has played for United Arab Emirates national team.

title: Wrasse
complex: The wrasses are a family, Labridae, of marine fish, many of which are brightly colored. <s> The family is large and diverse, with over 600 species in 81 genera, which are divided into 9 subgroups or tribes. <s> They are typically small fish, most of them less than 20 cm long, although the largest, the humphead wrasse, can measure up to 2.5 m . <s> They are efficient carnivores, feeding on a wide range of small invertebrates. <s> Many smaller wrasses follow the feeding trails of larger fish, picking up invertebrates disturbed by their passing. <s> Juveniles of some representatives of the genera "Bodianus", "Epibulus", "Cirrhilabrus", "Oxycheilinus", and "Paracheilinus" hide among the tentacles of the free-living mushroom coral "Heliofungia actiniformis". <s> The word "wrasse" comes from the Cornish word "wragh", a lenited form of "gwragh", meaning an old woman or hag, via Cornish dialect "wrath". <s> It is related to the Welsh "gwrach" and Breton "gwrac'h". <s> Wrasses have protractile mouths, usually with separate jaw teeth that jut outwards. <s> Many species can be readily recognized by their thick lips, the inside of which is sometimes curiously folded, a peculiarity which gave rise the German name of "lip-fishes" ("Lippfische".) <s> and the Dutch name of "lipvissen". <s> The dorsal fin has eight to 21 spines and six to 21 soft rays, usually running most of the length of the back. <s> Wrasse are sexually dimorphic. <s> Many species are capable of changing sex. <s> Juveniles are a mix of males and females (known as initial-phase individuals), but the largest adults become territory-holding (terminal phase) males.
simple: The wrasses are a family, the Labridae, of marine fish, many of which are brightly coloured. <s> The family is large and diverse, with over 600 species in 82 genera. <s> They are typically small fish, mostly less than 20 cm long, although the largest, the Humphead wrasse, can measure up to 2.5 m. <s> They are efficient carnivores, feeding on a wide range of small invertebrates. <s> Many smaller wrasses follow the feeding trails of larger fish, picking up invertebrates disturbed by their passing. <s> The word "wrasse" comes via Cornish from the Welsh word "gwrach" meaning an old woman or hag. <s> Wrasses can put their jaws forwards, usually with separate jaw teeth that jut outwards. <s> Many species can be recognized by their thick lips. <s> The inside of these lips is curiously folded, which gave rise the German name of "Lippfische". <s> The dorsal fin has 8–21 spines and 6–21 soft rays, usually running most of the length of the back. <s> Wrasse are sexually dimorphic. <s> Many species are capable of changing sex. <s> Juveniles are a mix of males and females (known as Initial Phase or IP individuals) but the largest adults become territory-holding (Terminal Phase or TP) males.

title: S.L. Benfica
complex: Sport Lisboa e Benfica ComC MHIH OM (] ), commonly known as Benfica, is a Portuguese sports club based in Lisbon. <s> It is best known for the professional football team playing in the Primeira Liga, the top flight of the Portuguese football league system, where they are the current champions and the most successful club in terms of titles won. <s> Benfica have won a record 37 Primeira Liga, a record 26 Taça de Portugal (and 4 consecutively), a record 7 Taça da Liga (and 4 consecutively), 8 Supertaça Cândido de Oliveira and 3 Campeonato de Portugal (and 2 consecutively) – totalling 81 domestic trophies – and 2 European Cups (consecutively won) – totalling 83 trophies, or 84 including the Latin Cup. <s> Therefore, in terms of overall trophies, Benfica is the most decorated club in Portuguese football.
simple: Sport Lisboa e Benfica, simply known as Benfica or SLB, is a professional football team from Portugal. <s> It is based in the capital city of Portugal, Lisbon. <s> They are one of the most successful teams in the Primeira Liga. <s> Benfica has won 36 Portuguese Leagues, 29 Portuguese Cups, 7 League Cups, 7 Portuguese Supercups and 2 UEFA Champions League titles.

title: Nyctalopia
complex: Nyctalopia , also called night-blindness, is a condition making it difficult or impossible to see in relatively low light. <s> It is a symptom of several eye diseases.
simple: Nyctalopia (Greek for Night blindness) is a disease of the human eyes.The eyes of people who are night-blind cannot adapt to situations where there is relatively little light; as a result, they have trouble seeing in such situations.

title: Relief
complex: Relief is a sculptural technique where the sculpted elements remain attached to a solid background of the same material. <s> The term "relief" is from the Latin verb "relevo", to raise.
simple: Relief is a way of making sculptures or carvings.

title: Listed building
complex: A listed building, or listed structure, is one that has been placed on one of the four statutory lists maintained by Historic England in England, Historic Environment Scotland in Scotland, Cadw in Wales, and the Northern Ireland Environment Agency in Northern Ireland. <s> There are estimated to be about 500,000 actual buildings listed, as listing entries can apply to more than one building. <s> In England and Wales, the management of listed buildings is the responsibility of local planning authorities and the Department for Communities and Local Government (i.e., not DCMS, which originally listed the building). <s> There is a general principle that listed buildings are put to 'appropriate and viable use' and recognition that this may involve the re-use and modification of the building.
simple: A listed building, in the United Kingdom, is a building that has been placed on the Statutory List of Buildings of Special Architectural or Historic Interest. <s> In the UK, there are about 500,000 listed buildings. <s> In England and Wales, there are three kinds of listed buildings: There used to be a fourth kind of listed building: Grade III.

title: Laduz
complex: Laduz is a former commune in the Yonne department in Bourgogne-Franche-Comté in north-central France. <s> On 1 January 2016, it was merged into the new commune of Valravillon.
simple: Laduz is a commune. <s> It is found in the Yonne department in the center of France.

title: Grimms' Fairy Tales
complex: Grimms' Fairy Tales, originally known as the Children's and Household Tales ( , ] ), is a collection of fairy tales by the Grimm brothers or "Brothers Grimm", Jakob and Wilhelm, first published on 20 December 1812. <s> The first edition contained 86 stories, and by the seventh edition in 1857, had 211 unique fairy tales. <s> The first volume of the first edition was published in 1812, containing 86 stories; the second volume of 70 stories followed in 1815. <s> For the second edition, two volumes were issued in 1819 and a third in 1822, totaling 170 tales. <s> The third edition appeared in 1837; fourth edition, 1840; fifth edition, 1843; sixth edition, 1850; seventh edition, 1857. <s> Stories were added, and also subtracted, from one edition to the next, until the seventh held 211 tales. <s> All editions were extensively illustrated, first by Philipp Grot Johann and, after his death in 1892, by German illustrator Robert Leinweber. <s> The first volumes were much criticized because, although they were called "Children's Tales", they were not regarded as suitable for children, both for the scholarly information included and the subject matter. <s> Many changes through the editions – such as turning the wicked mother of the first edition in "Snow White" and "Hansel and Gretel" (shown in original Grimm stories as Hänsel and Grethel) to a stepmother, were probably made with an eye to such suitability. <s> Jack Zipes believes that the Grimms made the change in later editions because they “held motherhood sacred”. <s> They removed sexual references—such as Rapunzel's innocently asking why her dress was getting tight around her belly, and thus naively revealing to the witch Dame Gothel her pregnancy and the prince's visits—but, in many respects, violence, particularly when punishing villains, was increased. <s> The brothers' initial intention of their first book, Children’s and Household Tales, was to establish a name for themselves in the world. <s> After the first book was published in 1812, they began their second volume, "German Legends," which was published in 1818. <s> The book that started their international success was not any of their tales, but Jacob’s publication of "German Grammar" in 1819. <s> This was one year after their publication of the "German Legends". <s> In 1825, the Brothers published their "Kleine Ausgabe" or "small edition", a selection of 50 tales designed for child readers. <s> This children's version went through ten editions between 1825 and 1858. <s> The Grimms believed that the most natural and pure forms of culture were linguistic and based in history. <s> The work of the Brothers Grimm influenced other collectors, both inspiring them to collect tales and leading them to similarly believe, in a spirit of romantic nationalism, that the fairy tales of a country were particularly representative of it, to the neglect of cross-cultural influence. <s> Among those influenced were the Russian Alexander Afanasyev, the Norwegians Peter Christen Asbjørnsen and Jørgen Moe, the English Joseph Jacobs, and Jeremiah Curtin, an American who collected Irish tales. <s> There was not always a pleased reaction to their collection.
simple: Children's and Household Tales , commonly known as Grimms' Fairy Tales , is a collection of German fairy tales published by Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm, the Brothers Grimm. <s> It contained 86 stories. <s> On December 20, 1812, the Grimms published the first volume of the first edition. <s> The second volume of 70 stories was published in 1814. <s> For the second edition, two volumes were issued in 1819 and a third in 1822, totalling 170 tales. <s> The third edition appeared in 1837; fourth edition, 1840; fifth edition, 1843; sixth edition, 1850; seventh edition, 1857. <s> Stories were added, and also deleted, from one edition to the next, until the seventh held 211 tales. <s> All editions were extensively illustrated, first by Philipp Grot Johann and, after his death in 1892, by Robert Leinweber. <s> The first volumes were much criticized because they were considered unsuitable for children, both for the scholarly information included and the subject matter. <s> Many changes through the editions – such as turning the wicked mother of the first edition in "Snow White" and "Hansel and Gretel" to a stepmother, were probably made with an eye to such criticism. <s> They removed sexual references—such as Rapunzel's innocently asking why her dress was getting tight around her belly, and thus naïvely revealing her pregnancy and the prince's visits to her stepmother—but, in many respects, violence, particularly when punishing villains, was increased. <s> In 1825, the Grimms published their "Kleine Ausgabe" or "small edition," a selection of 50 tales designed for child readers. <s> This children's version went through ten editions between 1825 and 1858. <s> The work of the Brothers Grimm influenced other collectors, both inspiring them to collect tales and leading them to similarly believe, in a spirit of romantic nationalism, that the fairy tales of a country were particularly representative of it, to the neglect of cross-cultural influence. <s> Among those influenced were the Russian Alexander Afanasyev, the Norwegians Peter Christen Asbjørnsen and Jørgen Moe, the English Joseph Jacobs, and Jeremiah Curtin, an American who collected Irish tales.

title: Instrumentation
complex: Instrumentation engineering is the engineering specialization focused on the principle and operation of measuring instruments that are used in design and configuration of automated systems in electrical, pneumatic domains etc and the control of quantities being measured. <s> They typically work for industries with automated processes, such as chemical or manufacturing plants, with the goal of improving system productivity, reliability, safety, optimization and stability. <s> To control the parameters in a process or in a particular system, devices such as microprocessors, microcontrollers or PLCs are used, but their ultimate aim is to control the parameters of a system.
simple: Instrumentation is the science of measurement and control over variables. <s> The engineering behind instrumentation focuses on the mechanics and operation of measuring instruments. <s> They typically work for industries with automated processes, such as chemical or manufacturing plants, with the goal of improving system productivity, reliability, safety, and stability. <s> To control the variables in a process, a computer or mechanism may be used.

title: Benedito de Assis da Silva
complex: Benedito de Assis da Silva (November 12, 1952 – July 6, 2014), commonly known as Assis was a Brazilian footballer who achieved notoriety playing for Fluminense. <s> More recently he was working as a manager for Fluminense's youth team. <s> Assis died on July 6, 2014 due to multiple organ failure at the age of 61.
simple: Benedito de Assis da Silva (November 11, 1952 – July 6, 2014), commonly known as Assis was a Brazilian footballer. <s> He played for Fluminense. <s> He was working as a manager for Fluminense's youth team until his death in 2014. <s> Assis died on July 6, 2014 due to multiple organ failure at the age of 61.

title: Villenave-d'Ornon
complex: Villenave d’Ornon (Gascon: "Vilanava d’Ornon") is a commune in the Gironde department in Nouvelle-Aquitaine in southwestern France.
simple: Villenave-d'Ornon is a commune. <s> It is found in the region Aquitaine in the Gironde department in the southwest of France.

title: Jinzū River
complex: The Jinzū River (神通川 , Jinzū-gawa ) is a river that flows from Gifu Prefecture to Toyama Prefecture in Japan. <s> It is called Miya River (宮川 "Miya-gawa") in Gifu. <s> It is 120 km in length and has a watershed of 2720 km2 .
simple: The Jinzū River (神通川, Jinzū-gawa) is a river which flows from Gifu Prefecture to Toyama Prefecture in Japan. <s> It is called Miya River (宮川 "Miya-gawa") in Gifu. <s> It is 120 km long and has a watershed of 2,720 km2.

title: Sodium nitrite
complex: Sodium nitrite is an inorganic compound with the chemical formula NaNO. <s> It is a white to slightly yellowish crystalline powder that is very soluble in water and is hygroscopic. <s> It is a useful precursor to a variety of organic compounds, such as pharmaceuticals, dyes, and pesticides, but it is probably best known as a food additive used in processed meats and (in some countries) in fish products. <s> Sodium nitrite is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines as it is an efficient drug in case of cyanide poisoning. <s> It is used together with sodium thiosulfate. <s> Historically, salt has been used for the preservation of meat. <s> The salt-preserved meatproduct was usually brownish-gray in color. <s> When sodium nitrite is added with the salt, the meat develops a red, then pink color, which is associated with cured meats such as ham, bacon, hot dogs, and bologna. <s> While this chemical will prevent the growth of bacteria, it can be toxic in high amounts for animals and humans. <s> Sodium nitrite's LD in rats is 180 mg/kg and its human LD is 71 mg/kg, meaning a 65 kg person would likely have to consume at least 4.6 g to result in death. <s> To prevent toxicity, sodium nitrite (blended with salt) sold as a food additive is dyed bright pink to avoid mistaking it for plain salt or sugar. <s> Nitrites are not naturally occurring in vegetables in significant quantities.
simple: Sodium nitrite is a chemical compound. <s> It contains sodium and nitrite ions. <s> Its chemical formula is NaNO. <s> It is a white or yellowish crystalline compound. <s> It is used to make other chemicals and to get rid of sodium azide. <s> It is used in meat like ham to preserve it. <s> It is toxic in large amounts. <s> Sodium nitrite used in food is colored bright pink so it is not mistaken for salt or sugar.

title: Arrondissement of Briançon
complex: The arrondissement of Briançon is an arrondissement of France in the Hautes-Alpes department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region. <s> It has 36 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Briançon is a French arrondissement in the Hautes-Alpes department, Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region. <s> The "arrondissement" of Briançon is the most northern of the Hautes-Alpes department.

title: Marly-Gomont
complex: Marly-Gomont is a commune in the Aisne department and Hauts-de-France region of northern France.
simple: Marly-Gomont is a commune.

title: Engollon
complex: Engollon is a former municipality in the district of Val-de-Ruz in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> The municipalities of Boudevilliers, Cernier, Chézard-Saint-Martin, Coffrane, Dombresson, Engollon, Fenin-Vilars-Saules, Fontainemelon, Fontaines, Les Geneveys-sur-Coffrane, Les Hauts-Geneveys, Montmollin, Le Pâquier, Savagnier and Villiers merged on 1 January 2013 into the new municipality of Val-de-Ruz.
simple: Engollon was a municipality of the district Val-de-Ruz in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland. <s> On 1 January 2013 the municipalities of Boudevilliers, Cernier, Chézard-Saint-Martin, Coffrane, Dombresson, Engollon, Fenin-Vilars-Saules, Fontainemelon, Fontaines, Les Geneveys-sur-Coffrane, Les Hauts-Geneveys, Montmollin, Le Pâquier, Savagnier and Villiers joined together and became the new municipality of Val-de-Ruz.

title: BBC Radio Scotland
complex: BBC Radio Scotland is BBC Scotland's national English-language radio network. <s> It broadcasts a wide variety of programmes. <s> It replaced the Scottish BBC Radio 4 opt-out service of the same name from 23 November 1978. <s> BBC Radio Scotland was founded as a full-time radio network on 23 November 1978. <s> Previously it was possible only to opt out of BBC Radio 4, and the service was known as Radio 4 Scotland or, formally on air, as "BBC Scotland Radio 4". <s> The establishment of a separate network was made possible when Radio 4 became a fully UK-wide network when it moved from medium wave to long wave and new VHF (FM) transmitters were brought into service so that Radio 4 and Radio Scotland no longer had to share on FM. <s> However it was not until the early 1990s that Radio 4 was available on FM across all of Scotland so for its first decade on air, the station only broadcast during the day so that Radio 4 could be heard on Radio Scotland's transmitters in the evening to compensate for poorer AM reception after dark. <s> The station broadcasts a wide range of programming, including news, debate, music, drama, comedy and sports. <s> News and current affairs programming has always constituted the dominant part of BBC Radio Scotland's schedules, especially on weekdays. <s> In addition to regular, mostly hourly, news bulletins, the station broadcasts a wide range of longer, more in-depth news and current affairs strands. <s> "Good Morning Scotland" (weekdays, 0600–0900) is Scotland's longest-running radio programme and one of the most popular in the country, providing regular news, sport, business, travel and weather bulletins along with interviews and in-depth reports in a manner similar to BBC Radio 4's "Today" programme, but from a Scottish perspective. <s> It also features the daily religious slot "Thought for the Day", again similar to that broadcast on Radio 4's "Today" programme. <s> The other daily news and current affairs strands are the "Morning Call" phone-in with Kaye Adams and Louise White (0900-1200), "John Beattie" (1200–1330) and "Newsdrive" (1600–1830). <s> BBC Radio Scotland also air live First Minister's Questions from the Scottish Parliament (Thu, 1200-1230 (MW)) and "Brian Taylor's Big Debate" hosted by BBC Scotland's political editor and is in a similar format to "Question Time" (Fri, 1215–1300). <s> Weekend current affairs programming includes weekend editions of "Good Morning Scotland" (0800-1000), "Shereen" (Sat, 1000–1200) and "Business Scotland" (Sat, 0600-0630, repeated Sun, 0730–0800). <s> During the station's downtime, BBC Radio Scotland simulcasts BBC Radio 5 Live programmes (0100–0600 daily). <s> As with BBC Radio 5 Live nationally, BBC Radio Scotland carries most of the major sporting events linked to its coverage area, holding non-exclusive rights to the Scottish Premier League and producing several editions of its "Sportsound" programme on a multitude of frequencies on Saturdays during the season. <s> The station also broadcasts live commentaries from both of Scotland's domestic football cup competitions, Scotland football internationals and European games affecting Scottish teams and the rugby union Six Nations championships. <s> Alongside the main live coverage, Radio Scotland also produces popular sporting magazine shows such as football fanzine "Off the Ball" and the multi-sports programme "Sports Nation", presented by former Scotland rugby player, John Beattie. <s> Every weekday evening during the football season, "Sportsound" also broadcasts on MW, 1810–19.00, looking at different aspects of Scottish football in tandem with live games. <s> BBC Radio Orkney and BBC Radio Shetland both air a half-hour daily news programme - "Around Orkney" (0730–0800) and "Good Evening Shetland" (1730–1800). <s> During the winter months, this is supplemented for both areas by an hour-long programme, broadcast Monday-Friday, between 1805–1900. <s> Local news and weather bulletins are broadcast from news studios in Selkirk, Dumfries, Aberdeen and Inverness on weekdays at 0630, 0730, 0830, 1230, 1630 and 1730. <s> The title "Head of Radio, Scotland" was applied to cover not only the Radio Scotland service but also BBC Scotland's radio productions for other networks.
simple: BBC Radio Scotland is BBC Scotland's national English language radio network. <s> It broadcasts a wide variety of programming including news, sport, music, the arts, comedy, drama, history and lifestyle. <s> It replaced the Scottish opt-out part of BBC Radio 4 in November 1978. <s> BBC Radio Scotland was founded as a full-time radio network in 1978, although the name had been used since 1974 for the Scottish opt-out parts of BBC Radio 4. <s> The creation of a separate network was made possible when Radio 4 became a fully national network and moved from medium wave to long wave. <s> The station broadcasts a wide range of programming including news, debate, music and sport commentaries. <s> News and current affairs programming has always constituted the dominant part of BBC Radio Scotland's schedules, especially on weekdays. <s> In addition to regular news bulletins (usually hourly), the station broadcasts a wide range of longer in-depth news and current affairs programmes. <s> Good Morning Scotland (weekdays, 0600-0900) is Scotland's longest-running radio programme and one of the most popular in the country. <s> It provides regular news, sport, business, travel and weather bulletins along with interviews and in-depth reports. <s> It is similar to BBC Radio 4's "Today" programme, but from a Scottish perspective. <s> It also includes the daily religious slot "Thought for the Day", again similar to that broadcast on Radio 4's "Today" programme. <s> The other daily news and current affairs strands are the "Morning Extra" phone-in (0905-1000), "Scotland Live" (1200-1245), "Newsdrive" (1600-1800) and the political news programme "Scotland At Ten" (2205-2230). <s> Weekend programmes include "Newsweek Scotland" (Sat, 0800-0900), "Shereen" (Sun, 0900-1000) and "The Business" (Sun, 1000-1030). <s> Like Radio 5 Live, BBC Radio Scotland covers most of the major sporting events in Scotland. <s> It holds exclusive rights to the Scottish Premier League and operates its Sportsound programme on a multitude of frequencies on Saturdays when games are being played. <s> Other sporting events that can be heard on Radio Scotland include both of Scotland's domestic football cup competitions, Scotland football internationals and European games affecting Scottish teams and the rugby union Six Nations championships. <s> Alongside the live action sports programmes, Radio Scotland also produces popular sporting shows such as football fanzine Off the Ball, phone-in forum "Your Call with Jim Traynor" and the multi-sports programme "Sports Weekly", presented by former Scotland rugby player, John Beattie. <s> Orkney and Shetland each have a half hour daily news programme — "Around Orkney" (0730-0800) and "Good Evening Shetland" (1730-1800). <s> During the winter months, this is supplemented for both areas by an hour long programme, broadcast Monday-Friday, between 1805-1900. <s> Local bulletins are broadcast from Selkirk, Dumfries, Aberdeen and Inverness throughout the day. <s> Controllers of BBC Radio Scotland hold the title "Head of Radio, BBC Scotland" on account of BBC Scotland's radio productions for other BBC networks.

title: Nick Palatas
complex: Nicholas Edward Palatas (born January 22, 1988) is an American actor. <s> Palatas has appeared in two short films, titled "The Erogenous Zone" and "Love" and has been in several ads. <s> In 2009, he played Norville "Shaggy" Rogers in the film, "Scooby-Doo! <s> The Mystery Begins" and reprised the role in "Scooby-Doo! <s> Curse of the Lake Monster" which aired in October 2010. <s> A newcomer to the Scooby-Doo series, Palatas took over for Matthew Lillard. <s> Palatas has two brothers, Phillip Palatas and actor Cameron Palatas. <s> He is married to Marissa Denig (sister of actress Maggie Grace), with whom he has one daughter.
simple: Nicholas Edward "Nick" Palatas (born January 22, 1988) is an American actor. <s> He has appeared in two short movies, titled "The Erogenous Zone" and "Love" and has been in several ads. <s> In 2009, he played Norville "Shaggy" Rogers in the movie, "Scooby-Doo! <s> The Mystery Begins" and reprised the role in "Scooby-Doo! <s> Curse of the Lake Monster" which released in October 2010. <s> Palatas has two brothers, Phillip Palatas and actor Cameron Palatas. <s> He is married to Marissa Denig (sister of actress Maggie Grace), with whom he has two children, Vienna and Edward.

title: Bill Schuette
complex: William Duncan Schuette ( ; born October 13, 1953) is an American lawyer and politician who served as the 53rd attorney general of Michigan from 2011 to 2019. <s> He was the unsuccessful Republican nominee for Governor of Michigan in the 2018 gubernatorial election, losing to Democrat Gretchen Whitmer.
simple: William Duncan Schuette ( ; born October 13, 1953) is an American politician and lawyer. <s> He is the 53rd and current Attorney General of Michigan. <s> He was the Republican nominee for Governor of Michigan in the 2018 gubernatorial election loosing to Gretchen Whitmer.

title: South Asian river dolphin
complex: The South Asian river dolphin ("Platanista gangetica") is an endangered freshwater or river dolphin found in the region of Indian Subcontinent which is split into two subspecies, the Ganges river dolphin ("P. g. gangetica")(~3,500 individuals) and the Indus river dolphin ("P. g. minor")(~1,500 individuals). <s> The Ganges river dolphin is primarily found in the Ganges and Brahmaputra Rivers and their tributaries in India, Bangladesh and Nepal, while the Indus river dolphin is now found only in the main channel of the Indus River in Pakistan and active channels connected to it between the Jinnah and Kotri barrages. <s> From the 1970s until 1998, they were regarded as separate species; however, in 1998, their classification was changed from two separate species to subspecies of a single species (see taxonomy below). <s> The Ganges river dolphin has been recognized by the government of India as its National Aquatic Animal and is the official animal of the Indian city of Guwahati.
simple: The South Asian river dolphin ("Platanista gangetica") is a freshwater or river dolphin found in India, Bangladesh, Nepal and Pakistan. <s> It is split into two subspecies, the Ganges river dolphin ("P. g. gangetica") and Indus river dolphin ("P. g. minor"). <s> From the 1970s until 1998, they were regarded as separate species; however, in 1998, their classification was changed from two separate species to subspecies of a single species.

title: Henryk Średnicki
complex: Henryk Średnicki (17 January 1955 – 10 April 2016) was a Polish amateur boxer who represented his native country twice at the Summer Olympics, starting in 1976. <s> Średnicki was best known for winning the world title at the second World Amateur Boxing Championships in 1978, beating Cuba's Héctor Ramírez in the final.
simple: Henryk Średnicki (17 January 1955 – 10 April 2016) was a Polish amateur boxer. <s> He represented his native country twice at the Summer Olympics, starting in 1976 (Montreal, Canada). <s> Średnicki was best known for winning the world title at the second World Amateur Boxing Championships in 1978, beating Cuba's Héctor Ramírez in the final.

title: Foxearth
complex: Foxearth is a village on the borders of north Essex and Suffolk in England, between Long Melford and Cavendish. <s> Foxearth is an ancient settlement in north Essex.
simple: Foxearth is a village and civil parish in Braintree district, Essex, England.

title: La Plata County, Colorado
complex: La Plata County is one of the 64 counties in the U.S. state of Colorado. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 51,334. <s> The county seat is Durango. <s> The county was named for the La Plata River and the La Plata Mountains. <s> "La plata" means "the silver" in Spanish.
simple: La Plata County is one of the 64 counties in the U.S. state of Colorado. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 51,334. <s> The county seat is Durango. <s> The county was named for the La Plata River and the La Plata Mountains. <s> "La plata" means "the silver" in Spanish.

title: Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis
complex: The (BWV; Bach works catalogue; ] ) is a catalogue of compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach. <s> It was first published in 1950, edited by Wolfgang Schmieder. <s> The catalogue's second edition appeared in 1990. <s> An abbreviated version of that second edition, known as BWV, was published in 1998. <s> BWV numbers were assigned to 1,126 compositions in the 20th century, and more have been added to the catalogue. <s> The (Anh.; Annex) of the BWV lists over 200 lost, doubtful and spurious compositions.
simple: Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (BWV) is a list of all the pieces of music by Johann Sebastian Bach that are known. <s> In English it means Bach Works Catalogue. <s> The catalogue was made by Wolfgang Schmieder in 1950. <s> Those doubtful pieces of music are listed separately as "BWV Anhang" (BWV appendix).

title: York Cottage
complex: In 1893, it was given by the future King Edward VII, then the Prince of Wales, as a wedding gift to his son Prince George, the Duke of York (later King George V), who lived there with his wife, the future Queen Mary, after their marriage. <s> The couple lived there for 33 years until the death of Queen Alexandra in 1925; their five youngest children were born there. <s> Today, York Cottage is the estate office for Sandringham; holiday accommodation and flats for estate employees also occupy part of the building.
simple: King George V and his wife, Queen Mary, lived in the house after their marriage in 1893. <s> Some of the building is also used as flats for estate employees and holiday accommodation.

title: Arrondissement of Bourges
complex: The arrondissement of Bourges is an arrondissement of France in the Cher department in the Centre-Val de Loire region. <s> It has 128 communes.
simple: The arrondissement of Bourges is an arrondissement of France, in the Cher department, Centre-Val de Loire region. <s> The "arrondissement" of Bourges is the central "arrondissement" of the Cher department.

title: Edward Brooke
complex: Edward William Brooke III (October 26, 1919 – January 3, 2015) was an American Republican politician. <s> In 1966, he became the first African American popularly elected to the United States Senate. <s> He represented Massachusetts in the Senate from 1967 to 1979. <s> Born and raised in Washington, D.C., Brooke graduated from the Boston University School of Law after serving in the United States Army during World War II. <s> After serving as chairman of the Finance Commission of Boston, Brooke won election as Massachusetts Attorney General in 1962. <s> In 1966, he defeated Democratic Governor Endicott Peabody in a landslide to win election to the Senate. <s> Edward William Brooke III was born on October 26, 1919, in Washington, D.C., to Edward William Brooke Jr. and Helen (Seldon) Brooke. <s> He was the second of three children; He was raised in a middle-class section of the city, and attended Dunbar High School, then one of the most prestigious academic high schools for African Americans. <s> After graduating in 1936, he enrolled in Howard University, where he first considered medicine, but ended up studying social studies and political science. <s> Brooke graduated in 1941, and enlisted in the United States Army immediately after the Japanese Attack on Pearl Harbor. <s> Brooke was commissioned as an officer, served five years in the Army, saw combat in Italy during World War II as a member of the segregated 366th Infantry Regiment, and earned a Bronze Star Medal. <s> In Italy Brooke met his future wife Remigia Ferrari-Scacco, with whom he had two daughters, Remi and Edwina. <s> Following his discharge, Brooke graduated from the Boston University School of Law in 1948. <s> "I never studied much at Howard," he reflected, "but at Boston University, I didn't do much else but study." <s> His papers are stored at Boston University's Howard Gotlieb Archival Research Center. <s> In September 2002, he was diagnosed with breast cancer and assumed a national role in raising awareness of the disease among men. <s> On January 3, 2015, Brooke died at his home in Coral Gables, Florida, at the age of 95. <s> He was buried at Arlington National Cemetery, Section 8, Site 5190-5-RH.
simple: Edward William Brooke III (October 26, 1919 – January 3, 2015) was an American politician. <s> Brooke was the first African-American politician to be popularly elected to the Senate. <s> He was elected to the United States Senate as a Republican from Massachusetts in 1966. <s> He was raised in Washington, D.C. and Boston, Massachusetts. <s> Brooke studied at Howard University and the Boston University School of Law. <s> He beat his Democratic rival Endicott Peabody by many votes. <s> Brooke was born on October 26, 1919 in Washington, D.C. <s> He married Remigia Ferrari-Scacco in 1947. <s> In September 2002, he was diagnosed with breast cancer. <s> He worked at raising awareness of the disease among men. <s> Their marriage would last until Brooke's death in 2015. <s> He lived in Coral Gables, Florida. <s> On January 3, 2015, Brooke died at his home in Coral Gables, Florida at the age of 95 from natural causes.

title: Across the Tracks
complex: Across the Tracks is a 1991 American independent film drama about track and field. <s> It was directed and written by Sandy Tung. <s> "Across the Tracks" is the story of two brothers who have gone very different ways in their past, and who now must learn to deal with each other again. <s> Joe (Brad Pitt) is the older of the two. <s> He is a good student and runner set on winning a track scholarship to Stanford University.
simple: Across the Tracks is a 1991 American independent drama movie. <s> This movie is about two brothers who have gone different ways in the past. <s> They are learning to deal with each other again. <s> Joe is played by Brad Pitt.

title: Camcorder
complex: A camcorder is an electronic device originally combining a video camera and a videocassette recorder. <s> More recent devices capable of recording video are camera phones and digital cameras primarily intended for still pictures; the term "camcorder" may be used to describe a portable, self-contained device, with video capture and recording its primary function, often having advanced functions over more common cameras.
simple: Camcorder are electronic devices which combines a video camera and a video recorder. <s> Most devices capable of recording video are camera phones and digital cameras primarily intended for still pictures. <s> The term "camcorder" is used to describe a portable, self-contained device, with video capture and recording as its primary function.

title: Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe
complex: Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe (MKvs.DCU) is a crossover fighting video game between "Mortal Kombat" and the DC Comics fictional universe, developed and published by Midway Games (their last entry in the franchise before they went bankrupt in 2009 and sold the franchise to Warner Bros. <s> The game is also the eighth instalment in the main "Mortal Kombat" series, despite the story not being connected to the first seven games or any other game that was released after this one.
simple: Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe is an Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 fighting game released in 2008. <s> It is a crossover video game where "Mortal Kombat" characters fight DC Comics ones.

title: Champs-Élysées
complex: The Avenue des Champs-Élysées ( , , ] ) is an avenue in the 8th arrondissement of Paris, France, 1.9 km long and 70 m wide, running between the Place de la Concorde and the Place Charles de Gaulle, where the Arc de Triomphe is located. <s> It is known for its theatres, cafés, and luxury shops, for the annual Bastille Day military parade, and as the finish of the Tour de France cycle race. <s> On 20 April 2017, a police officer was shot dead on the Champs-Élysées by an extremist and two other officers were injured. <s> They were all sitting in a parked police van, when the attacker pulled up in front of the van.
simple: The Champs-Élysées is a long and very famous street in Paris. <s> It links the Arc de Triomphe and the Place de la Concorde. <s> On 20 April 2017, two ISIS-claimed gunmen opened fired and killed one police officer and injured another at Champs-Élysées.

title: Chris Birchall
complex: Christopher Birchall CM (born 5 May 1984) is a former professional footballer who played as a midfielder. <s> He scored 21 goals in 322 league and cup appearances in a 16-year professional career, and scored four goals in 43 international matches.
simple: Chris Birchall (born 5 May 1984) is a Trinidad and Tobago football player.

title: Rypin
complex: Rypin is a town in Poland, in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship, about 50 km east of Toruń. <s> It is the capital of Rypin County. <s> Population is 16,950 (2009).
simple: Rypin is a town in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship, Poland. <s> Rypin is about 50 km east of Toruń. <s> It is the capital of Rypin County. <s> In 2009, 16,950 people lived there.

title: Igor Sergeyev
complex: Igor Dmitriyevich Sergeyev (20 April 1938 — 10 November 2006) was a Soviet/Russian military officer who was Minister of Defense of Russia from 22 May 1997 to 28 March 2001. <s> He was the first and (as of 2019) the only Marshal of the Russian Federation.
simple: Igor Dmitrievich Sergeev (Russian: Игорь Дмитриевич Сергеев; 20 April 1938 — 10 November 2006) was a Russian politician. <s> He served as a Minister of Defence of Russia from 22 May 1997 to 28 March 2001.

title: Pansexuality
complex: Pansexuality, or omnisexuality, is the sexual, romantic or emotional attraction towards people regardless of their sex or gender identity. <s> Pansexual people may refer to themselves as gender-blind, asserting that gender and sex are not determining factors in their romantic or sexual attraction to others. <s> The prefix "pan-" comes from the Ancient Greek word for "all, every", "πᾶν"; "omni-" comes from the Latin word for "all", "omnis". <s> The hybrid words "pansexual" and "pansexualism" were first attested in 1917, denoting the idea "that the sex instinct plays the primary part in all human activity, mental and physical", a reproach (credited to Sigmund Freud) levelled at early psychology.
simple: Pansexual people are people attracted to people regardless of their gender. <s> Bisexual people are attracted to both sexes (males and females), usually to those who identify as boys or girls or as men or women, while pansexuality means attraction to people of any gender (including those who may not identify as boys or girls or as men or women) or to those who are intersex. <s> Pansexuality is the opposite of asexuality, as pansexuality means a person may be sexually attracted to anyone, but asexuality means a person is sexually attracted to no one. <s> Some who identify as pansexual call themselves "gender blind" because they do not consider gender important when they are attracted to others. <s> However, pansexuals are not necessarily sexually attracted to everyone they meet, nor do they necessarily have strong sex drives. <s> The word "pansexual" comes from the Greek word 'pan-', meaning "all".

title: SABMiller
complex: SABMiller plc was a multinational brewing and beverage company headquartered in Woking, England on the outskirts of London until 10 October 2016 when it was acquired by Anheuser-Busch InBev. <s> Prior to that date, it was the world's second-largest brewer measured by revenues (after Anheuser-Busch InBev) and was also a major bottler of Coca-Cola. <s> Its brands included Fosters, Miller, and Pilsner Urquell. <s> It operated in 80 countries worldwide and in 2009 sold around 21 billion litres of beverages. <s> Since 10 October 2016, SABMiller has been a business division of Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV, a Brazilian-Belgian corporation with headquarters in Leuven. <s> SABMiller was founded as South African Breweries in 1895 to serve a growing market of miners and prospectors in and around Johannesburg. <s> Two years later, it became the first industrial company to list on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange. <s> From the early 1990s onwards, the company increasingly expanded internationally, making several acquisitions in both emerging and developed markets. <s> In 1999, it formed a new UK-based holding company, SAB plc, and moved its primary listing to London. <s> In May 2002, SAB plc acquired Miller Brewing, forming SABMiller plc. <s> The origins of the company date back to the foundation of South African Breweries in 1895 in South Africa. <s> For many decades, the operations of South African Breweries were mainly limited to southern Africa, where it had established a dominant position in the market during South African Apartheid, until 1990 when it began investing in Europe. <s> After acquiring SABMiller, Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV agreed on 21 December 2016 to sell the former SABMiller Ltd. business in Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary and Romania to Asahi for US$7.8 billion. <s> The deal includes popular brands such as Pilsner Urquell, Tyskie, Lech, Dreher, Ursus, Timisoreana and Kozel.
simple: SABMiller plc is a multinational brewing and beverage company headquartered in London, England. <s> It is the world's second-largest brewer measured by revenues (after the Belgian-Brazilian-American Anheuser-Busch InBev) and is also a major bottler of Coca-Cola. <s> Its brands include Fosters, Grolsch, Miller, Peroni and Pilsner Urquell. <s> It has operations in 80 countries world-wide and in 2009 sold around 21 billion litres of beverages. <s> SABMiller's origins date back to the foundation of South African Breweries in 1895 as to serve a growing market of miners and prospectors in and around Johannesburg. <s> Two years later, it became the first industrial company to list on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange. <s> From the early 1990s onwards, the company increasingly expanded internationally, making several acquisitions in both emerging and developed markets. <s> In 1999, it formed a new UK-based holding company, SAB plc, and moved its primary listing to London. <s> In May 2002, SAB plc acquired Miller Brewing, forming SABMiller plc. <s> In October 2015, Anheuser-Busch InBev announced plans to acquire SABMiller for £69 billion ($104 billion).

title: Aubigny-aux-Kaisnes
complex: Aubigny-aux-Kaisnes is a commune in the department of Aisne in the Hauts-de-France region of northern France. <s> List of Successive Mayors of Aubigny-aux-Kaisnes
simple: Aubigny-aux-Kaisnes is a commune.

title: Prime Minister of Spain
complex: The Prime Minister of Spain, officially the President of the Government of Spain , is the head of the government of Spain. <s> The office was established in its current form by the Constitution of 1978 and originated in 1823 as a chairmanship of the extant Council of Ministers. <s> Pedro Sánchez of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE) has been Prime Minister since 2 June 2018, after a successful motion of no confidence against former Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy. <s> The Sánchez government technically ceased on 29 April 2019 after the 2019 Spanish general election, and has been acting ever since. <s> The most recent Prime Minister to die was Adolfo Suárez (served 1976–1981) on 23 March 2014, aged 81.
simple: The President of the Government of Spain, , is the head of Government of Spain. <s> The office was created by the Constitution of 1978. <s> The current Prime Minister is Pedro Sánchez. <s> The most recent Prime Minister to die was Adolfo Suárez (served 1976–1981) on 23 March 2014, aged 81.

title: Shad Begum
complex: Shad Begum is a social worker from Dir Lower, Pakistan. <s> She comes from a religious and middle class family. <s> She is the first university-educated female in her family. <s> She says, she always got support from her father, brothers and husband for her social work. <s> Ms Shad founded the Association for Behaviour and Knowledge Transformation (ABKT) for the development of women in the area in 1994. <s> Initially ABKT was known as Anjuman Behbood-i-Khawateen Talash. <s> She faced many challenges and difficulties in the man dominated conservative society of the area. <s> She shifted the organization office to Peshawar when the Taliban rose in the area and she was threatened by unidentified militants. <s> The association has contributed in female education, political awareness and health improvement projects in the area. <s> Furthermore, the association has also carried out projects like construction of hanging bridges, installation of hand pumps, sinking wells, paving streets, provision of small loans to local traders and capacity building of women at grassroots level. <s> The association gets funding from Pakistani and international agencies. <s> She was awarded with the International Women of Courage Award by the US First Lady Michelle Obama and the Secretary of State Hillary Clinton on Thursday 8 March 2012. <s> The area where she comes from is very conservative and there are very few working women. <s> She had requested several news reporters not to spread the news because of security reasons.
simple: Shad Begum (شاد بیگم) is a social worker from Pakistan. <s> Shad comes from a conservative and religious family. <s> She is the first woman in her family to study in a university. <s> Shad says she always got support for her work from her father, her brothers, and her husband. <s> In 1994, Shad started the Association for Behaviour and Knowledge Transformation (ABKT). <s> Shad had many problems because the society is conservative and dominated by men. <s> When the Taliban came to the area, Shad was threatened, so she moved the office to Peshawar. <s> The organization helps women in the area with projects for education, politics, and health. <s> It also has projects for bridges, pumps, wells, streets, and loans for small business. <s> The association gets its money from the Pakistani government and from international groups. <s> There are very few working women.

title: Archer Heights, Chicago
complex: Archer Heights is a neighborhood in Chicago, Illinois, one of the 77 official community areas of Chicago. <s> Archer Avenue runs from south of Chicago's downtown area, through the southwest side of Chicago and beyond into the southwest suburbs, along what was once a Native American trail. <s> The neighborhood is bounded by the Stevenson Expressway to the north, the CTA Orange Line to the south, the Corwith railyard to the east, and the railroad tracks/Knox Avenue to the west.
simple: Archer Heights is a neighborhood in Chicago, Illinois. <s> It is one of the 77 official community areas of Chicago. <s> The area was once a Native American trail. <s> The neighborhood is bounded by the Stevenson Expressway to the north, the CTA Orange Line to the south, the Corwith railyard to the east, and the railroad tracks/Knox Avenue to the west.

title: George Fox
complex: George Fox (July 1624 – 13 January 1691) was an English Dissenter, who was a founder of the Religious Society of Friends, commonly known as the Quakers or Friends. <s> The son of a Leicestershire weaver, he lived in times of social upheaval and war.
