simple: George Fox (July 1624 – 13 January 1691) was one of the people that left the Church of England. <s> He was a founder of the Religious Society of Friends, also known as the "Quakers."

title: Graham Stark
complex: Graham William Stark (20 January 1922 – 29 October 2013) was an English comedian, actor, writer and director. <s> The son of a purser on transatlantic liners, Stark was born in New Brighton (part of Wallasey) in Wirral, Cheshire, England. <s> He attended Wallasey Grammar School and made his professional stage debut aged 13 in pantomime at the Lyceum Theatre in London. <s> Stark was also an accomplished stills photographer. <s> He was the last known performer to have appeared on "The Goon Show" during its original run. <s> In 2003 he published an autobiography, "Stark Naked". <s> He died in London on 29 October 2013 at age 91, after suffering a stroke.
simple: Graham William Stark (20 January 1922 – 29 October 2013) was an English comedian, actor, writer and director. <s> Stark was born on 20 January 1922 in Wallasey, Cheshire, England. <s> He studied at Wallasey Grammar School. <s> Stark was also an accomplished stills photographer. <s> Stark died in London on 29 October 2013 after suffering a stroke.

title: Dick Scobee
complex: Francis Richard Scobee (May 19, 1939 – January 28, 1986) was an American pilot, engineer and astronaut. <s> He was killed while he was commanding the Space Shuttle "Challenger" in 1986, which suffered catastrophic booster failure during launch of the STS-51-L mission. <s> In April 1984, he piloted "Challenger" mission STS-41-C, which successfully deployed one satellite and repaired another. <s> Selected for NASA Astronaut Corps in January 1978, Scobee completed his training in August 1979. <s> While awaiting his first orbital spaceflight mission, he served as an instructor pilot for the Shuttle's 747 carrier aircraft. <s> Scobee was assigned commander for the ill-fated STS-51-L mission. <s> The mission, designed to deploy a satellite to study the approaching Halley's Comet and to inaugurate the Teacher in Space Project, was delayed numerous times due to bad weather and technical glitches. <s> When the mission finally did lift off the pad, a solid rocket booster O-ring seal failure destroyed the shuttle 73 seconds into the flight, killing Scobee and the other six crew members; the disaster, viewed live on national television, prompted several days of national mourning, as well as a major shakeup at NASA. <s> He died a lieutenant colonel. <s> At T+68 into the mission, the CAPCOM Richard Covey informed the crew that they were "go at throttle up", and Scobee confirmed the call – his last recorded words were his response, "Roger, go at throttle up." <s> The shuttle broke up 73 seconds into the flight, and at an altitude of 48,000 feet (14.6 km). <s> His parents were William and Francis Scobee; he married Virginia June Kent (now June Scobee Rodgers); he had two children, Kathie R. Scobee Fulgham and Lieutenant General Richard W. Scobee. <s> He is buried in Arlington National Cemetery.
simple: Francis Richard "Dick" Scobee (May 19, 1939 - January 28, 1986) was an American astronaut. <s> He was flying as the commander of Space Shuttle "Challenger" when the shuttle exploded. <s> In April 1984, Scobee piloted the "Challenger" mission STS-41-C, which successfully deployed one satellite and repaired another. <s> Scobee was selected for NASA's astronaut program in January 1978 and he completed his training in August 1979. <s> He was elevated to the role of spacecraft commander for the STS-51-L mission ("Challenger" mission). <s> The mission was designed to deploy a satellite to study the approaching Halley's Comet and to inaugurate the Teacher in Space Project. <s> It was delayed several times due to bad weather and technical glitches. <s> When they did the mission, an O-ring seal failure destroyed the shuttle 73 seconds into the flight, killing Scobee and the other six members of the crew; the tragedy was viewed live on national television and prompted several days of national mourning. <s> Scobee is survived by his wife Virginia June Kent, and two children, Kathie R. (Scobee) Fulgham and Brigadier General Richard W. Scobee, USAF.

title: Needham–Schroeder protocol
complex: The Needham–Schroeder protocol is one of the two key transport protocols intended for use over an insecure network, both proposed by Roger Needham and Michael Schroeder.
simple: The term Needham-Schroeder protocol can refer to one of two communication protocols intended for use over an insecure network, both protocols designed by Roger Needham and Michael Schroeder.

title: Radu Vasile
complex: Radu Vasile (] ; 10 October 1942 – 3 July 2013) was a Romanian politician, historian and poet. <s> Originally a member of the Christian-Democratic National Peasants' Party, Vasile served as the Prime Minister of Romania between April 17, 1998, and December 13, 1999, and was notably confronted with the last Mineriad (February 1999). <s> Between 2000 and 2004, he was a Senator from the Democratic Party (PD). <s> Vasile published poetry under the pen name "Radu Mischiu".
simple: Radu Vasile (10 October 1942 – 3 July 2013) was a Romanian historian, poet and politician. <s> He was the 57th Prime Minister of Romania, serving from 17 April 1998 to 13 December 1999. <s> He was also a Senator from the Democratic Party (PD) from 2000 to 2004. <s> Aside from politics, Vasile used to write poetry under the pen name "Radu Mischiu".

title: Hotpants
complex: Hotpants or hot pants describe extremely short shorts. <s> The term was first used by "Women's Wear Daily" in 1970 to describe shorts made in luxury fabrics such as velvet and satin for fashionable wear, rather than their more practical equivalents that had been worn for sports or leisure since the 1930s.
simple: Hot pants, or 'short shorts', are a fashion item from the 1960s which is still popular today.

title: Brahmagupta
complex: Brahmagupta (born 598 CE , died 668 CE ) was an Indian mathematician and astronomer. <s> He is the author of two early works on mathematics and astronomy: the "Brāhmasphuṭasiddhānta" (BSS, "correctly established doctrine of Brahma", dated 628), a theoretical treatise, and the "Khaṇḍakhādyaka" ("edible bite", dated 665), a more practical text. <s> Brahmagupta was the first to give rules to compute with "zero". <s> The texts composed by Brahmagupta were in elliptic verse in Sanskrit, as was common practice in Indian mathematics. <s> As no proofs are given, it is not known how Brahmagupta's results were derived.
simple: Brahmagupta (born 598 CE, died 668 CE) was an Indian mathematician and astronomer. <s> He was the author of two early works on mathematics and astronomy: the "Brāhmasphuṭasiddhānta" (BSS, "correctly established doctrine of Brahma", dated 628). <s> Brahmagupta was the first to give rules to compute with "zero". <s> The texts composed by Brahmagupta were composed in elliptical verse in Sanskrit, as was common practice in Indian mathematics. <s> As no proofs are given, it is not known how Brahmagupta's results were derived.

title: Suman Sahai
complex: Suman Sahai is an Indian activist and the founder of Gene Campaign. <s> Sahai obtained a Ph.D. from the Indian Agricultural Research Institute in 1975. <s> She then successively worked at the University of Alberta, University of Chicago, and the University of Heidelberg, where she obtained her habilitation in human genetics. <s> According to the Web of Science, Sahai has published over 40 articles, mostly on policy issues relating to genetically modified organisms, which have been cited over 150 times, giving her an h-index of 7. <s> She is director of the NGO, Gene Campaign. <s> In April 2013, Sahai was shown to have committed plagiarism in her habilitation thesis, which had been submitted to the University of Heidelberg in 1986. <s> In addition, she was accused of presenting herself as being or having been a professor at that University, without ever actually having occupied such a position. <s> On 14 April 2013, the University of Heidelberg confirmed that plagiarism had taken place, that Sahai has no right to call herself a professor of the University of Heidelberg, and that in consequence Sahai had agreed to renounce her "venia legendi".
simple: Suman Sahai is an Indian activist and the founder of Gene Campaign. <s> Sahai got a Ph.D. from the Indian Agricultural Research Institute in 1975. <s> She then worked at the University of Alberta, University of Chicago, and the University of Heidelberg, where she did her habilitation in human genetics. <s> The Web of Science shows that Sahai has published over 40 articles. <s> They are mostly on policy issues dealing with genetically-modified organisms. <s> Her articles have been cited over 150 times and she has an h-index of 7. <s> She is director of the non-governmental organization, Gene Campaign. <s> In April 2013 it was shown that Sahai committed plagiarism in her habilitation thesis. <s> She had submitted this thesis to the University of Heidelberg in 1986. <s> She was also accused of presenting herself as being or having been a professor at that University. <s> The University of Heidelberg confirmed on 14 April, 2013, that plagiarism had taken place. <s> The university also said that Sahai has no right to call herself a professor of the University of Heidelberg.

title: Five Finger Death Punch
complex: Five Finger Death Punch, often shortened to Five Finger or Death Punch, also abbreviated as 5FDP or FFDP, is an American heavy metal band from Las Vegas, Nevada. <s> Formed in 2005, the band's name comes from kung fu cinema. <s> The band originally consisted of vocalist Ivan Moody, guitarist Zoltan Bathory, guitarist Caleb Andrew Bingham, bassist Matt Snell, and drummer Jeremy Spencer. <s> Bingham was replaced by guitarist Darrell Roberts in 2006, who was then replaced by Jason Hook in 2009.
simple: Five Finger Death Punch is an American heavy metal band from Los Angeles, California. <s> Five Finger Death Punch has five members in the band; the current band members are Zoltan Bathory, Jason Hook, Chris Kael, Ivan Moody and Jeremy Spencer.

title: Stade de Kadiogo
complex: Stade de Kadiogo is a multi-use stadium in Kadiogo, Burkina Faso. <s> It is used mostly for football matches and is the home stadium of Rail Club du Kadiogo. <s> The stadium holds 8,000 people.
simple: Stade de Kadiogo is a stadium in Kadiogo, Burkina Faso. <s> It is used mostly for football games and is the home stadium of Rail Club du Kadiogo. <s> The stadium holds 8,000 people.

title: Jacqueline Hill
complex: Grace Jacqueline Hill (17 December 1929 – 18 February 1993) was a British actress known for her role as Barbara Wright in the BBC science-fiction television series "Doctor Who". <s> As the history teacher of Susan Foreman, the Doctor's granddaughter, Barbara was the first "Doctor Who" companion to appear on-screen in 1963, with Hill speaking the series' first words. <s> She played the role for nearly two years, leaving the series in 1965 at the same time as fellow actor William Russell (who played the companion Ian Chesterton). <s> Hill returned to "Doctor Who" in 1980 for an appearance in the serial "Meglos", as the Tigellan priestess Lexa. <s> Hill made her stage debut in London's West End in "The Shrike". <s> Many more roles followed, including "Fabian of the Yard" and "An Enemy of the People". <s> In 1958 she married the director Alvin Rakoff, having the previous year appeared in his BBC adaptation of Rod Serling's American TV play "Requiem For A Heavyweight". <s> This production featured former bit-part actor Sean Connery; Hill had recommended that Rakoff cast him, because she believed Connery would be popular with female viewers. <s> Hill preferred the historical "Doctor Who" stories; her favourite serials were "The Aztecs" and "The Crusade". <s> Shortly after leaving the series in 1965 she gave up acting in order to raise a family, resuming her career in 1978. <s> Her later TV credits included "Tales of the Unexpected" and the 1978 BBC Television Shakespeare version of "Romeo and Juliet" (as Lady Capulet), which was directed by her husband. <s> Jacqueline Hill died of breast cancer in 1993, aged 63.
simple: Jacqueline Hill (17 December 1929 – 18 February 1993) was an English actress. <s> She was best known for her role as Barbara Wright in the BBC science fiction television series "Doctor Who". <s> Hill returned for an appearance in the 1980 "Doctor Who" story "Meglos", as the priestess Lexa. <s> She was first on stage in London's West End in "The Shrike". <s> Many more roles followed, including, on television, "Shop Window", "Fabian of the Yard" and "An Enemy of the People". <s> In 1958 she married the director Alvin Rakoff. <s> The previous year she was in his BBC adaptation of Rod Serling's American television play "Requiem for a Heavyweight". <s> After leaving "Doctor Who" in 1965 she gave up acting to raise a family. <s> She gained further TV credits in, amongst other programmes, "Tales of the Unexpected" and as Lady Capulet in the BBC Television Shakespeare version of "Romeo and Juliet" in 1978. <s> Jacqueline Hill died of bone cancer in 1993.

title: Adolphe Dugléré
complex: Adolphe Dugléré ] (3 June 1805 in Bordeaux – 4 April 1884 in Paris) was a French chef and a pupil of Marie-Antoine Carême. <s> Dugléré was a "chef de cuisine" to the Rothschild family until 1848, and was manager at the restaurant "Les Frères Provençaux" at the Palais-Royal from 1848 to 1866 which was owned by three men from Provence named Barthélémy, Maneille and Simonas (who were, in reality, not brothers). <s> In 1866 he became the head chef of the Café Anglais (founded 1802), which became the most famous Paris restaurant of the 19th century and where he is believed to have created the dish "Pommes Anna". <s> It was here in 1867 that Dugléré served a famous meal that became known as the Dîner des trois empereurs, ('Dinner of the Three Emperors') for Tsar Alexander II of Russia, his son the tsarevitch (who later became Tsar Alexander III) and King William I of Prussia, as well as Prince Otto von Bismarck who were in Paris for "L'Exposition Universelle". <s> The table service used for this meal is on display to this day at the oldest existing restaurant in Paris, "Tour d'Argent" which is owned by the descendants of Claudius Burdet, the last owner of Café Anglais which was demolished in 1913. <s> The most famous dish attributed to Dugléré is almost certainly "Pommes Anna". <s> Other dishes created by Dugléré include "Potage Germiny", a sorrel soup created for Charles Lebègue, Comte de Germiny, governor of the Bank of France, "Poularde Albufera", dedicated to Maréchal Suchet, Duke of Albufera, "Soufflé à l'anglaise", "Sole Dugléré" and "Culotte de bœuf Salomon", (dedicated to Salomon de Rothschild) and "Barbue à la Dugléré" (brill in tomato and parsley sauce). <s> He is also credited with inventing "Tournedos Rossini", but this dish has also been credited to both Escoffier as well as Carême (although not the title itself). <s> It was composer Gioachino Rossini who dubbed Dugléré "Le Mozart de la cuisine" (The Mozart of the Kitchen). <s> Legend has it that on one occasion Rossini was in the restaurant and asked that Dugléré prepare his "filet" at his table in a chafing dish.
simple: Adolphe Dugléré (born Bordeaux, June 3, 1805 - died Paris April 4, 1884) was a French chef and a pupil of Carême. <s> Dugléré was a "chef de cuisine" to the Rothschild family until 1848, and was manager at the restaurant "Les Frères Provençaux" at the Palais-Royal from 1848 to 1866 which was owned by three men from Provence named Barthélémy, Maneille and Simonas (who were, in reality, not brothers). <s> In 1866 he became the head chef of the which was the most famous Paris restaurant of the 19th century and where he is believed to have created the dish "Pommes Anna". <s> It was at the Café Anglais in 1867 that Dugléré served a famous meal that became known as the Dîner des trois empereurs, for Tsar Alexander II of Russia, his son the tsarevitch (who later became Tsar Alexander III) and King William I of Prussia, as well as Prince Otto von Bismarck who were in Paris for "L'Exposition Universelle". <s> The table service used for this meal is on display to this day at the oldest existing restaurant in Paris, "La Tour d'Argent" which is owned by the descendants of Claudius Burdel, the last owner of Café Anglais which was demolished in 1913. <s> The most famous dish attributed to Dugléré is almost certainly "Pommes Anna". <s> Other dishes created by Dugléré include "Potage Germiny", a sorrel soup created for the Count of Germiny, governor of the Bank of France, "Poularde Albufera", dedicated to Maréchal Suchet, Duke of Albufera, "Soufflé à l'anglaise", "Sole Dugléré" and "Culotte de bœuf Salomon", (dedicated to Salomon de Rothschild) and "Barbue à la Dugléré" (brill in tomato and parsley sauce). <s> He is also credited with inventing "Tournedos Rossini", but this dish has also been credited to both Escoffier as well as Carême (although not the title itself). <s> It was composer Gioachino Rossini who dubbed Dugléré "Le Mozart de la cuisine" (The Mozart of the Kitchen).

title: Westlake Village, California
complex: Westlake Village is a city in Los Angeles County on its western border with Ventura County. <s> The planned community of Westlake, built with a lake at the center, straddles the line between Los Angeles and Ventura counties.
simple: Westlake Village is a city in Los Angeles County on its western border with Ventura County.

title: Newbiggin-on-Lune
complex: Newbiggin-on-Lune is a village in the Eden district of Cumbria, England. <s> Historically in Westmorland it is about 4 mi south west of Kirkby Stephen, and lies on the main A685 route from Brough to Tebay.
simple: Newbiggin-on-Lune is a village in Cumbria, England.

title: Saint-Malo
complex: Saint-Malo ( , , ] ; Gallo: "Saent-Malô"; ) is a historic French port in Brittany on the Channel coast. <s> The population, in 2012, was 44,620 – though this can increase to up to 200,000 in the summer tourist season. <s> With the suburbs included, the metropolitan area's population is approximately 153,000 (2011).
simple: Saint-Malo is a port city in Brittany, France. <s> However, it can be nearly 200,000 in the summer with tourists.

title: Perry King
complex: Perry Firestone King (born April 30, 1948) is an American actor. <s> He is best known for his role in the television series "Riptide" (1984–1986). <s> King was born in Alliance, Ohio; his father was a physician. <s> His maternal grandfather was Maxwell Perkins, a well-known editor for the publishing house Charles Scribner's Sons.
simple: Perry Firestone King (born April 30, 1948) is an American actor. <s> King played the role of Cody Allen on the detective series "Riptide" from 1984 to 1986. <s> He was born in Alliance, Ohio.

title: Hurricane David
complex: Hurricane David was an extremely deadly hurricane which caused massive loss of life in the Dominican Republic in August 1979. <s> A Cape Verde hurricane that reached Category 5 hurricane status on the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale, David was the fourth named tropical cyclone, second hurricane, and first major hurricane of the 1979 Atlantic hurricane season, traversing through the Leeward Islands, Greater Antilles, and East Coast of the United States during late August and early September. <s> David was the first hurricane to affect the Lesser Antilles since Hurricane Inez in 1966. <s> With winds of 175 mph (280 km/h), David was the only storm of Category 5 intensity to make landfall on the Dominican Republic in the 20th century and the deadliest since the 1930 Dominican Republic Hurricane, San Zenon, killing over 2,000 people in its path. <s> In addition, until Hurricane Maria in 2017, David was the deadliest Dominican tropical cyclone since the 1834 Padre Ruíz hurricane, which killed over 200 people. <s> David is believed to have been responsible for 2,068 deaths, making it one of the deadliest hurricanes of the modern era. <s> It caused torrential damage across its path, most of which occurred in the Dominican Republic where the hurricane made landfall as a Category 5 hurricane. <s> The name David was retired following this storm because of its devastation and high death toll, and will never be used again for an Atlantic hurricane, making it the first male hurricane name in the Atlantic Ocean to be retired. <s> It was replaced with Danny for the 1985 season.
simple: Hurricane David was a very strong hurricane killing many. <s> Hurricane David killed 2,068 and caused over $1.5 billion in damage. <s> This hurricane caused a lot of damage as it slammed into Dominican Republic as a category 5 hurricane and was it struck Florida as a category 2 hurricane. <s> Because it killed so many people in Dominican Republic, the name David was retired. <s> This was the first male name retired in the Atlantic Ocean. <s> Meaning, David will never be used as a name of a storm in the Atlantic Ocean. <s> The name Danny replaced it in 1985, 1991, 1997, 2003, and 2009.

title: David Bergland
complex: David Peter Bergland (June 4, 1935 – June 3, 2019) was an American politician who was the United States Libertarian Party's nominee for President of the United States in the 1984 presidential election, and also served twice as the Chair of the Libertarian National Committee. <s> Bergland received the Libertarian Party's presidential nomination in the 1984 presidential election. <s> He and his running mate, Jim Lewis, received 228,111 (0.3%). <s> Bergland died on June 3, 2019, one day short of his 84th birthday, of prostate cancer.
simple: David Peter Bergland (June 4, 1935 – June 3, 2019) is an American politician. <s> He was the United States Libertarian Party's nominee at the 1983 Libertarian National Convention for President of the United States in the 1984 presidential election. <s> Bergland died of prostate cancer on June 3, 2019, one day short of his 84th birthday.

title: Free Realms
complex: Free Realms was a massive multiplayer online role playing video game, developed by Sony Online Entertainment (SOE) for the PC, Mac, and PlayStation 3, set in a fantasy-themed world named Sacred Grove. <s> The game was released on April 29, 2009 for Windows. <s> The game restricted to free-to-play up to level 20, although there was access to additional game content via a membership fee. <s> The game allowed the player to fight, interact with other players, and more. <s> The game was shut down on March 31, 2014; SOE stated that they no longer had enough resources to maintain the game's servers.
simple: Free Realms is a massively multiplayer online role-playing game. <s> It is set in a fantasy-themed world, named "Sacred Grove". <s> It was made by Sony Online Entertainment for PC, Mac and PlayStation 3. <s> The game was released on 29 April 2009. <s> On March 31, 2014, the game was officially shut down.

title: Alveolate
complex: The alveolates (meaning "with cavities") are a group of protists, considered a major clade and superphylum within Eukarya, and are also called Alveolata.
simple: The Alveolata is a grouping of protists.

title: Sonia Bashir Kabir
complex: Sonia currently serves as Vice President and Co-Founder of D Money Bangladesh Limited (a Fin-Tech startup), independent board director of IPDC Bank, Vice President and Co-Founder of Bangladesh Women in Technology (BWIT). <s> Besides co-founding Tech Startups Syntec & Pulse (health), Uqeel.com (legal tech) and Digiland (blockchain) in Bangladesh, Sonia has served as the Managing Director for Microsoft Bangladesh, Myanmar, Nepal, Bhutan and Laos, Country Director of Dell Bangladesh, Director Business Development for South East Asia, New Emerging Markets in Microsoft and Chief Operating Officer for Aamra Technologies Ltd. <s> Sonia has also served as a Board Member of Bangladesh Association of Software and Information Services (BASIS) from 2016-2018. <s> Sonia currently serves in the Board of BRAC University, Advisory Board of the School of Business and the School of Computer Science of North South University and in the School of Business Advisory Board of Independent University Bangladesh. <s> Former UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon appointed Sonia in 2015 to the Governing Council of the Technology Bank for the Least Developed Countries (LDC) for a 3-year term. <s> She was elected as Vice Chairman of UN Technology Bank in 2017. <s> Sonia completed her Senior Cambridge from Green Herald International School (St. Francis Xavier's) and Higher Secondary Certificate from Viqarunnisa Noon School and College. <s> She lived in Silicon Valley, Northern California for 20 years where she was educated and trained. <s> She has a Bachelor of Science (BS) degree from California State University and a Master of Business Administration (MBA) from Santa Clara University. <s> Sonia was a Bangladeshi national athlete; she has played for Abahani women's Volleyball and Cricket team and continued playing for Bangladesh National Volleyball team. <s> After completing her MBA, Sonia worked in Silicon Valley for Fortune 100 companies (Sun Microsystems & Oracle), startups & in the financial district. <s> Her expertise include strategic planning & growth, sales execution, financial management, team building and change management. <s> She is an Advisory Council Member of Toru (Institute of Inclusive Innovation); Board of Trustees Member of Jaago Foundation and Governing Board Member for Bangladesh Youth Leadership Center (BYLC). <s> Sonia is also the Founder President of TiE Dhaka and has served in the Boards of the American International School, Dhaka, Bangladesh Employers Federation, Bangladesh Cricket Board (Women's Wing), Abahani Women's Games Development Committee and Women Entrepreneur's Association.
simple: She serves on boards of the Bangladesh Association of Software and Information Services (BASIS), the business and computer science schools of North South University and the business school of the Independent University Bangladesh. <s> Former UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon appointed Sonia in 2015 to the Governing Council of the Technology Bank for the Least Developed Countries (LDC) for a 3 year term. <s> After that she educated and trained in Silicon Valley. <s> She lived in Northern California for 20 years. <s> She was a national athlete and she has played for Bangladesh National Volleyball team and Bangladesh National Cricket team. <s> Before joining the national team she played both volleyball and cricket for Abahani. <s> After completing MBA, Sonia worked in Silicon Valley for Fortune 100 companies including Sun Microsystems and Oracle. <s> Her expertise includes strategic planning and growth, sales execution, financial management, team building and change management. <s> She is the Founder President of TiE Dhaka, Co-founder of Bangladesh Women in IT (BWIT) and Board Member of the American International School, Dhaka. <s> She is also Director of Women Entrepreneurs’ Association (WEA), Member of Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) Women’s Wing and Member, Abahani Women’s Games Development Committee (AWGDC).

title: Brandon railway station
complex: Brandon railway station is on the Breckland line in the east of England, serving the town of Brandon, Suffolk, although the station is actually situated across the county boundary in Norfolk. <s> The line runs between in the west and in the east. <s> Brandon is 86 mi from London Liverpool Street via . <s> It is managed by Greater Anglia, which operates most of the services.
simple: Brandon railway station is a small station in Norfolk, England for Brandon in Suffolk. <s> Trains are currently run by Greater Anglia.

title: Malibu, California
complex: Malibu (Spanish: "Malibú)" is a beach city in western Los Angeles County, California, situated about 30 mi west of Downtown Los Angeles. <s> It is known for its Mediterranean climate and its 21 miles strip of the Malibu coast, incorporated in 1991 into the City of Malibu. <s> The area is known for being the home of Hollywood movie stars, people in the entertainment industry, and other affluent residents. <s> Most Malibu residents live within a few hundred yards of Pacific Coast Highway (State Route 1), which traverses the city, with some residents living up to a mile away from the beach up narrow canyons. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city population was 12,645.
simple: Malibu is a beach city in western Los Angeles County, California, situated about 30 mi west of Downtown Los Angeles. <s> Known for its Mediterranean climate, a 21 miles strip of the Malibu coast incorporated in 1991 into the City of Malibu. <s> The area is known for being the home of Hollywood movie stars, people in the entertainment industry, and other affluent residents. <s> Most Malibu residents live within a few hundred yards of Pacific Coast Highway (State Route 1), which traverses the city, with some residents living up to a mile away from the beach up narrow canyons. <s> As of the 2010 census, the city population was 12,645.

title: Deadlock
complex: In concurrent computing, a deadlock is a state in which each member of a group is waiting for another member, including itself, to take action, such as sending a message or more commonly releasing a lock. <s> Deadlock is a common problem in multiprocessing systems, parallel computing, and distributed systems, where software and hardware locks are used to arbitrate shared resources and implement process synchronization.
simple: Deadlock is a common problem in multiprocessing where many processes share a specific type of mutually exclusive resource known as a "software lock" or "soft lock".

title: Vár
complex: In Norse mythology, Vár or Vór (Old Norse, meaning either "pledge" or "beloved") is a goddess associated with oaths and agreements. <s> Vár is attested in the "Poetic Edda", compiled in the 13th century from earlier traditional sources; the "Prose Edda", written in the 13th century by Snorri Sturluson; and kennings found in skaldic poetry and a runic inscription. <s> Scholars have proposed theories about the implications of the goddess. <s> Ninth Var: she listens to people's oaths and private agreements that women and men make between each other. <s> Thus these contracts are called "varar". <s> She also punishes those who break them. <s> In addition, Vár appears twice more in the "Prose Edda".
simple: Vár is a goddess of promises and agreements in Norse mythology. <s> Her name means 'pledge' or 'beloved'. <s> Vár is described in the Poetic Edda and the Prose Edda. <s> She listens to people that make agreements with one another. <s> The contracts that Vár makes are called "varar". <s> She also punishes those that break their promises and contracts.

title: Poul Nyrup Rasmussen
complex: Poul Oluf Nyrup Rasmussen (] , informally Poul Nyrup, born 15 June 1943), was Prime Minister of Denmark from 25 January 1993 to 27 November 2001 and President of the Party of European Socialists (PES) from 2004 to 2011. <s> He was the leader of the governing Social Democrats from 1992 to 2002. <s> He was a member of the European Parliament from 2004 to 2009.
simple: Poul Oluf Nyrup Rasmussen (], informally Poul Nyrup, born 15 June 1943) is a Danish politician. <s> He was the Prime Minister of Denmark from 25 January 1993 to 27 November 2001 and President of the Party of European Socialists (PES) from 2004 to 2011. <s> He was the leader of the governing Social Democrats from 1992 to 2002. <s> He was a member of the European Parliament from 2004 to 2009.

title: British Rail Class D3/9
complex: British Rail Class D3/9 was a class of four locomotives built by the London and North Eastern Railway at their Doncaster Works in England. <s> It was a diesel powered locomotive in the pre-TOPS period.
simple: British Rail Class D3/9 was a class of four locomotives built by the London and North Eastern Railway at their Doncaster Works in England. <s> It was a diesel powered locomotive in the pre-TOPS period.

title: Jefferson City, Missouri
complex: Jefferson City, officially the City of Jefferson and informally Jeff City, is the capital of the U.S. state of Missouri and the 15th most populous city in the state. <s> It is also the county seat of Cole County and the principal city of the Jefferson City Metropolitan Statistical Area, the second-most-populous metropolitan area in Mid-Missouri and the fifth-largest in the state. <s> Most of the city is in Cole County, with a small northern section extending into Callaway County. <s> Jefferson City is named for Thomas Jefferson, the third President of the United States. <s> Jefferson City is located on the northern edge of the Ozark Plateau on the southern side of the Missouri River in a region known as Mid-Missouri. <s> It is 30 miles south of Columbia, Missouri, and sits at the western edge of the Missouri Rhineland, one of the major wine-producing regions of the Midwest. <s> The city is dominated by the domed Capitol, which rises from a bluff overlooking the Missouri River to the north; Lewis and Clark passed the bluff on their historic expedition upriver before Europeans established any settlement there. <s> In pre-Columbian times, this region was home of an ancient people known only as the "Mound Builders", having been replaced by Osage Native Americans. <s> In the late 17th century, frontiersmen started to inhabit the area, including Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac, Louis Jolliet, Jacques Marquette, Robert de LaSalle, and Daniel Boone, with the latter having the greatest influence on the region. <s> Daniel Boone's son, Daniel Morgan Boone, would later lay out Jefferson City in the early 19th century. <s> When the Missouri Territory was organized in 1812, St. Louis was Missouri's seat of government, and St. Charles would serve as the next capital. <s> However, in the middle of the state, Jefferson City was chosen as the new capital in 1821, when Thomas Jefferson was still living. <s> The village first was called "Lohman's Landing", and when the legislature decided to relocate there, they proposed the name "Missouriopolis" before settling on the city of "Jefferson" to honor Thomas Jefferson. <s> Over the years, the city became to be most often referred to as "Jefferson City" and the name stuck. <s> For years, this village was little more than a trading post located in the wilderness about midway between St. Louis and Kansas City. <s> In 1825, the settlement was incorporated as a city and a year later, the Missouri legislature first met in Jefferson City. <s> Jefferson City was chosen as the site of a state prison. <s> This prison, named the Missouri State Penitentiary, opened in 1836. <s> This prison was home to multiple infamous Americans, including former heavyweight champion Sonny Liston, assassin James Earl Ray, and bank robber Pretty Boy Floyd. <s> During the Civil War, Jefferson City was occupied by Union troops and the elected state legislature was driven from Jefferson City by Union General Nathaniel Lyon. <s> Some of the legislators later reconvened in Neosho and passed an ordinance of secession. <s> Missouri was claimed by both the Confederacy and the Union, as was neighboring state Kentucky. <s> Missourians were strongly divided and many people in the state—especially in St. Louis—supported the Union, while other areas (such as Missouri's Little Dixie) were strongly pro-Confederate along the Missouri River between Jefferson City and Kansas City. <s> German immigrants created vineyards in small towns on either side of the Missouri River, especially on the north from the city east to Marthasville, located outside of St. Louis. <s> Known as the "Missouri Rhineland" for its vineyards and first established by German immigrants in the mid-1800s, this region has become part of Missouri's agricultural and tourist economy. <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 37.58 sqmi , of which 35.95 sqmi is land and 1.63 sqmi is water. <s> As of the census of 2010, there were 43,079 people, 17,278 households, and 9,969 families residing in the city. <s> The population density was 1198.3 PD/sqmi . <s> There were 18,852 housing units at an average density of 524.4 /sqmi . <s> The racial makeup of the city was 78.0% White, 16.9% African American, 0.3% Native American, 1.8% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 0.8% from other races, and 2.2% from two or more races. <s> Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 2.6% of the population. <s> Jefferson City Public School District currently operates Jefferson City High School, two middle schools, and eleven elementary schools. <s> The district will open Capital City High School in Fall 2019. <s> Lincoln University is a public historically black university with open enrollment and certificate, associate, bachelor, and graduate programs. <s> Columbia College, William Woods University, Metro Business College, and Merrell University also have campuses in the city with varying degree levels and options. <s> Although Jefferson City is one of the four state capitals that is not served by an Interstate highway, Interstate 70 passes by the city 30 mi to the north in Columbia. <s> U.S. highways in the city include U.S. Routes 50, 54, and 63. <s> Missouri Routes 179 and 94 also run through the city, giving it four highways that intersect with I-70. <s> The city is served by nearby Columbia Regional Airport. <s> JeffTran, the city operated public transit system, provides year-round bus service during traditional weekday business hours, but is currently considering the extension of service hours to include evenings and weekends.
simple: Jefferson City is the capital of the U.S. state of Missouri. <s> It is also county seat of Cole County. <s> Jefferson City was named after Thomas Jefferson, the third president of the United States. <s> Jefferson City is on the northern edge of the Ozark Plateau on the southern side of the Missouri River near the geographic center of the state, in a region known as Mid-Missouri. <s> It is at the western edge of the Missouri Rhineland, one of the major wine-producing regions of the Midwest. <s> In pre-Columbian times, this region was home of an ancient people known only as the Mound Builders. <s> When the Missouri Territory was organized in 1812, St. Louis was the seat of government. <s> St. Charles next served as the capital. <s> The new state legislature decided to build a new capital city in the middle of the state in 1821. <s> A village was already there called Lohman's Landing. <s> For years the village was little more than a trading post located in the wilderness about midway between St. Louis and Kansas City. <s> In 1826 the Missouri legislature first met here and in 1839 the settlement was incorporated as a city. <s> Jefferson City was selected as the site for a state prison and, in 1836, the Missouri State Penitentiary was opened. <s> The prison was home to a number of infamous Americans, including: former heavyweight champion Sonny Liston, assassin James Earl Ray, and bank robber Charles "Pretty Boy" Floyd. <s> During the American Civil War, Jefferson City was occupied by Union troops. <s> Many of the people in the state supported the Union, although Missouri's Little Dixie section along the river in western counties was strongly Confederate. <s> German immigrants created vineyards in small towns on either side of the Missouri River, especially on the north from Jefferson City east to Marthasville outside St. Louis. <s> Known as the Missouri Rhineland for its vineyards, first established by German immigrants in the mid-19th century, this area has become a part of the agricultural and tourist economy. <s> According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 28.3 sqmi, of which, 27.2 sqmi is land and 1.0 sqmi (3.61%) is water. <s> As of the 2010 census, the population was 43,079. <s> Jefferson City is served by the Jefferson City Public School District, which operates Jefferson City High School, Simonsen 9th Grade Center, Lewis and Clark Middle School and Thomas Jefferson Middle School, and eleven elementary schools. <s> Lincoln University is a public historically black university with open enrollment and certificate, associate, bachelor, and graduate programs. <s> Columbia College, Linn State Technical College, William Woods University, Metro Business College, and Merrell University also have locations in Jefferson City with varying degree levels and options. <s> Jefferson City is one of four state capitols in United States that are not served by an interstate highway. <s> Interstate 70 passes by the city 30 mi to the north, in Columbia. <s> U.S. Highways in the city include U.S. Route 50, U.S. Route 54, and U.S. Route 63. <s> Also Route 179 and Route 94 run through the city, giving it four highways that intersect with I-70. <s> Jefftran operates a public bus system year-round.

title: Millennium University
complex: The Millennium University or TMU is a non governmental university located at Dhaka, Bangladesh. <s> The university is sponsored by Khan Foundation, a Philanthropic Private Development Organisation (PVDO) and established under the Private University Act 1992. <s> It is affiliated by the Government of Bangladesh and overseen by the University Grants Commission Bangladesh.
simple: The Millennium University or TMU is a Bangladeshi private university. <s> This university was established in 2004 by Khan Foundation.

title: The Keg
complex: The Keg is a Canadian-owned chain of steakhouse restaurants and bars located in Canada and the United States. <s> The original "The Keg and Cleaver" restaurant was founded by George Tidball, in 1971, at a location in North Vancouver, British Columbia. <s> By February 2018, The Keg had expanded to 160 locations in Canada and the United States, when Canadian food industry giant Cara Operations (now known as Recipe Unlimited) purchased the chain for $200 million, from then owners David Aisenstat (49%) and Fairfax Financial (51%).
simple: The Keg is a Canadian steakhouse chain of restaurants. <s> It has restaurants in both Canada and the United States. <s> It was started by George Tidball in North Vancouver, British Columbia in 1971.

title: Torreón Municipality
complex: Torreón is one of the municipalities of Coahuila de Zaragoza, a state in north-eastern Mexico. <s> The city of Torreón is the municipal seat for Torreón Municipality. <s> The municipality covers an area of 1947.7 km2.
simple: Torreón is one of the 38 municipalities of Coahuila, in northeastern Mexico. <s> The municipal seat is Torreón. <s> The municipality covers an area of 1947.7 km2.

title: Clubfoot
complex: Clubfoot is a birth defect where one or both feet are rotated inward and downward. <s> The affected foot and leg may be smaller than the other. <s> In about half of those affected, both feet are involved. <s> Most cases are not associated with other problems.
simple: A club foot or clubfoot, also called congenital talipes equinovarus (CTEV), is a birth defect. <s> In about half of children born with club foot both feet are affected.

title: Ismaïl Aissati
complex: Ismaïl Aissati (born 16 August 1988) is a Moroccan footballer who plays for Denizlispor as a midfielder.
simple: Ismaïl Aissati (born 16 August 1988) is a Dutch football player.

title: Daisen, Akita
complex: Daisen (大仙市 , Daisen-shi ) is a city in Akita Prefecture, Japan.
simple: Daisen (大仙市, Daisen-shi) is a Japanese city in Akita Prefecture on the island of Honshu.

title: Lijepa naša domovino
complex: "Lijepa naša domovino" (] ; ) is the national anthem of Croatia. <s> It is often referred to as just "Lijepa naša" in Croatia, which is also a phrase widely used as a metonym for the country. <s> The original lyrics were written by Antun Mihanović and first published under the title "Horvatska domovina" ("Croatian homeland") in 1835. <s> In 1846, the music amateur Josip Runjanin (1821–1878) composed the music for "Horvatska domovina".
simple: The National Anthem of Croatia is named "Lijepa naša domovino" which means "Our beautiful homeland". <s> The singing text was written by a Croatian composer "Antun Mihanović" and music to it was made by "Josif Runjanin".

title: Harry Hood (footballer)
complex: Henry Anthony Hood (3 October 1944 – 26 May 2019) was a Scottish football player and manager. <s> A forward noted for his skill, he played for Clyde (two spells), Celtic, Motherwell and Queen of the South in Scotland, Sunderland in England and San Antonio Thunder in the United States. <s> He won eleven domestic honours with Celtic. <s> He later managed Albion Rovers and Queen of the South, and was a businessman involved in the hospitality sector. <s> Born in Glasgow and raised in the city's Garthamlock neighbourhood, Hood's older brother Jackie was also a footballer who won the Liverpool Senior Cup while a reserve player at Everton but had returned to Scotland and local Junior club St Roch's by the time his younger sibling was starting his career. <s> Harry Hood initially attended school at St Aloysius College where rugby union was the chosen sport. <s> Seeking a schoolboy appearance for Scotland, he moved to Holyrood Secondary School but was overlooked for the national schoolboy squad as he had already registered as a senior player at St Roch's. <s> After a battle with cancer, Hood died around 6:30am on 26 May 2019, aged 74.
simple: Henry Anthony Hood (3 October 1944 – 26 May 2019) was a Scottish football player and manager. <s> During the 1960s and 1970s, he played for Clyde, Celtic, Motherwell and Queen of the South in Scotland, Sunderland in England and San Antonio Thunder in the United States. <s> He won over ten domestic honours with Celtic. <s> He later managed Albion Rovers and Queen of the South during the early 1980s. <s> Hood was born in Glasgow. <s> Hood died on 26 May 2019, at the age of 74.

title: Gesves
complex: Gesves (] ; Walloon: "Djeve") is a Walloon municipality located in the Belgian province of Namur. <s> This municipality contains the town of Gesves, as well as the villages of Faulx-Les-Tombes, Haltinne, Mozet, and Sorée.
simple: Gesves is a municipality in the Belgian province of Namur.

title: Millionaires (duo)
complex: Millionaires is an American electronic music duo consisting of sisters Melissa Marie Green and Allison Maria Green. <s> The group, formed in August 2007, are widely known for mixing heavily explicit lyrics with a heavy electropop backing. <s> Dani Artaud was in the original line-up. <s> Their image and lyrics have generated strong controversy (mainly for using explicit words in nearly all of their songs). <s> The group has released three EPs, several singles—including "Stay the Night", which managed to chart for a short time in the UK—and their debut album, "Tonight", released in March 2013. <s> In March 2016 they released a single with producer Wade Martin titled "When I'm Single". <s> Millionaires started in August 14, 2007 (according to their Myspace signup) "as an accident" when sisters Melissa and Allison Green used GarageBand. <s> The song was titled "I Like Money", and the teens then created a corresponding MySpace profile named Millionaires. <s> The third member, Dani Artaud, joined the group after Melissa Marie asked her to join. <s> Later, they created their second song, called "Hoe Down". <s> They began to perform shows in California and traveled only small distances for gigs. <s> They got spots in music festivals such as Rockin' Roots, Bamboozle Left 2008, and Audio Overload 2008. <s> In July 2008, they went on their first tour, co-headlining with Breathe Carolina across California and other Western states. <s> Later in July, they headlined the Get F$cked Up tour. <s> That same month, they performed their Myspace song "I Move It" on MTV's "TRL" as part of On the Radar, a segment where popular "hipster" bands perform. <s> They made a short song titled "Ooh Uh Huh", which became the theme song for MTV's reality show "A Double Shot at Love" with the Ikki Twins. <s> Their song "Hey Rich Boy" was also used as the theme for MTV's "Teen Cribs". <s> Their song "Alcohol" was also featured on the soundtrack for the third series of "Skins". <s> Their songs "I Like Money" and "I Move It" were featured on the MTV show "My Life as Liz". <s> Their cover of Chic's song "Le Freak" is featured on the MTV film "Turn the Beat Around". <s> The girls started up again in January and February 2009 on their Just Got Paid, Let's Get Laid tour, which sold out on every stop. <s> They also teamed up with hardcore techno DJ S3RL and made the Myspace single "Martinis & Mixed Feelings", for which an electro/techno remix was made.
simple: Millionaires is an American electronic trio from Los Angeles, California. <s> It was started in 2007 by three girls, Melissa Marie Green, Allison Green, and Dani Artaud. <s> Millionaires started in August 2007, when Melissa Marie and Allison made a song on their new laptop with GarageBand. <s> They named the song "I Like Money", and decided they needed a name for themselves to make a MySpace profile for the song. <s> Soon after, Dani came in the mix, and they made their second song, "Hoe Down." <s> After a few months, they began to perform shows locally and traveled only small distances for shows. <s> They got spots in music festivals such as Rockin Roots,Bamboozle Left 2008,and Audio Overload 2008. <s> By July 2008, they were ready to tour and they went out on their first tour co-headlining with another band, Breathe Carolina across the West coast. <s> Later in July, they headlined the GET F$CKED UP tour. <s> In July 2008, they performed on MTV's TRL as part of On The Radar, a show where popular bands not signed to a record label perform. <s> They made a short song titled "Ooh Uh Huh", which became the theme song for MTV's reality show "A Double Shot At Love" with the Ikki twins. <s> Their song "Hey Rich Boy" was also used as the theme for MTV's Teen Cribs. <s> The girls returned in January and February 2009 on their Just Got Paid, Let's Get Laid tour, which sold out every date.

title: Battle of Guam (1944)
complex: The Second Battle of Guam (21 July – 10 August 1944) was the American recapture of the Japanese-held island of Guam, a U.S. territory in the Mariana Islands captured by the Japanese from the U.S. in the 1941 First Battle of Guam during the Pacific campaign of World War II. <s> Guam, at 212 square miles (543 square kilometers), is the largest island of the Marianas, with a length of 32 miles (52 km) and a width ranging from 12 miles (19.31 km) to four miles (6.44 km) at different points of the island. <s> It had been a United States possession since its capture from Spain in 1898 until it was captured by the Japanese on 10 December 1941, following the attack on Pearl Harbor. <s> During the Japanese occupation of Guam, it was not as heavily fortified as the other Mariana Islands such as Saipan that had been Japanese possessions since the end of World War I. <s> But by 1944, Guam had a large Japanese garrison. <s> The Allied plan for the invasion of the Marianas, Operation "Forager", called for heavy preliminary bombardment, first by carrier aircraft and USAAF bombers based in the Marshall Islands to the east, then once air superiority was gained, close bombardment by battleships, cruisers, and destroyers. <s> Saipan, Tinian, and Guam were chosen as the targets due to their size, their suitability as a base for supporting the next stage of operations toward the Philippines, Taiwan, and the Ryukyu Islands. <s> The seaport at Apra Harbor was suitable for the largest ships; and air bases for Boeing B-29 Superfortresses could be built from which to bomb Japan. <s> B-24 Liberators from the Marianas could also bomb Iwo Jima and the Bonin Islands, such as Chichi Jima. <s> The invasion of Saipan was scheduled for 15 June 1944, with landings on Guam tentatively set for 18 June. <s> The original timetable was optimistic, however. <s> A large Japanese carrier attack and stubborn resistance by the unexpectedly large Japanese garrison on Saipan led to the invasion of Guam being postponed for a month. <s> Guam, ringed by reefs, cliffs, and heavy surf, presents a formidable challenge for any attacker. <s> Underwater demolition teams reconnoitered the beaches and removed obstacles from 14–17 July. <s> Despite the obstacles, on 21 July, the American forces landed on both sides of the Orote Peninsula on the western side of Guam, planning to secure Apra Harbor. <s> The 3rd Marine Division landed near Agana to the north of Orote at 08:29, and the 1st Provisional Marine Brigade landed near Agat to the south. <s> Japanese artillery sank 20 U.S. LVTs and inflicted heavy casualties on the landing troops, especially of the 1st Provisional Marine Brigade, but by 09:00 marines and tanks were ashore at both beaches. <s> By nightfall, the U.S. Marines, and soldiers of the 77th Infantry Division had established beachheads about 2000 m deep. <s> Japanese counterattacks were made throughout the first few days of the battle, mostly at night, using infiltration tactics. <s> The Japanese penetrated the American defenses several times but were driven back with heavy losses of men and equipment. <s> The U.S. Army's 77th Infantry Division had a more difficult landing on 23–24 July. <s> Lacking amphibious vehicles, they had to wade ashore from the edge of the reef where the landing craft dropped them off. <s> The men stationed in the 2 beachheads were pinned down by heavy Japanese fire, making initial progress inland quite slow. <s> Supply was very difficult for the landing troops on Guam in the first days of the battle. <s> Landing ships could not come closer than the reef, several hundred yards from the beach and amphibious vehicles were scarce. <s> The 1st Provisional Brigade blocked off the Orote Peninsula on 25 July, and that same night Japanese Lt. General Takashina counterattacked, coordinated with a similar attack against the 3rd Division to the north. <s> The next day, General Obata reported, "our forces failed to achieve the desired objectives." <s> Lieutenant General Takeshi Takashina was killed on 28 July, and Lieutenant General Hideyoshi Obata took over the command of the Japanese defenders. <s> On 28 July, the 2 beachheads were linked, and by 29 July, the Americans secured the peninsula. <s> The Japanese counterattacks against the American beachheads, as well as the fierce fighting, had exhausted the Japanese. <s> At the start of August, they were running out of food and ammunition, and they had only a handful of tanks left. <s> Obata withdrew his troops from southern Guam, planning to make a stand in the mountainous central and northern part of the island, "to engage in delaying action in the jungle in northern Guam to hold the island as long as possible". <s> On 10 August, organized Japanese resistance ended, and Guam was declared secure, but 7,500 Japanese soldiers were estimated to be at large. <s> The next day, Obata committed ritual suicide at his headquarters on Mount Mataguac after he had sent a farewell message to Japan. <s> A few Japanese soldiers held out in the jungle after the fighting on Guam. <s> On 8 December 1945, three U.S. Marines were ambushed and killed. <s> On 24 January 1972, Japanese Army Sergeant Shoichi Yokoi was discovered by hunters on the island. <s> He had lived alone in a cave for 28 years, near Talofofo Falls. <s> Guam was turned into a base for Allied operations after the battle. <s> 5 large airfields were built by the Navy Seabees and African American Aviation Engineering Battalions. <s> Army Air Forces B-29 bombers flew from Northwest Field and North Field on Guam to attack targets in the Western Pacific and on mainland Japan. <s> Liberation Day continues to be celebrated on Guam every 21 July.
simple: The Second Battle of Guam (July 21 — August 10, 1944) was the capture of Guam by the United States from Japanese control. <s> The battle was during the Pacific campaign of World War II. <s> Guam is the largest island of the Marianas. <s> It had been a United States island since its capture from Spain in 1898. <s> It was captured by the Japanese on December 10, 1941. <s> It was not as fortified as the other Mariana Islands, such as Saipan. <s> The Allied plan for the invasion of the Marianas was for heavy bombing by planes and then bombing by battleships. <s> Guam was chosen as a target because it was big enough to be a base for the next attacks on the Philippines, Taiwan and the Ryukyu Islands. <s> The harbor at Apra could take the largest ships. <s> The invasion of Saipan was planned for June 15, 1944, with landings on Guam planned for June 18. <s> A large Japanese carrier attack and heavy fighting in Saipan led to the invasion of Guam being delayed for a month. <s> Guam is surrounded by reefs, cliffs, and heavy waves. <s> This makes Guam hard to attack. <s> On July 21, the Americans landed on both sides on the western side of Guam. <s> The 3rd Marine Division landed at 08:28. <s> The 1st Provisional Marine Brigade landed to the south. <s> Japanese artillery sank 20 Landing Ships. <s> By 09:00 men and tanks were on both beaches. <s> By nightfall the Americans controlled the beachs about 2,000 meters deep. <s> Japanese attacks were made throughout the first few days. <s> The 77th Infantry Division had to walk through the shallow water. <s> Supply was very difficult for the Americans in the first days of the battle. <s> Lieutenant General Takeshi Takashina was killed on July 28, and Lieutenant General Hideyoshi Obata took over the command of the defenders. <s> The attacks against the American beaches, as well as the violent fighting, had tired out the Japanese. <s> At the start of August they were running out of food and ammunition and had only a few tanks left. <s> Obata moved to the mountainous central and northern part of the island. <s> The next day, Obata committed ritual suicide. <s> A few Japanese soldiers hid in the jungle. <s> On December 8, 1945, three U.S. Marines were killed. <s> On January 24, 1972, Sergeant Shoichi Yokoi was discovered by hunters. <s> He had lived alone in a cave for 27 years. <s> After the battle, Guam was turned into a base for Allied operations. <s> Five large airfields were built by the Seabees. <s> B-29 bombers flew from the island to attack targets in the Western Pacific and on mainland Japan. <s> Liberation Day continues to be celebrated on Guam every July 21.

title: Winston L. Shelton
complex: Winston Laverne Shelton (May 3, 1922 – April 15, 2019) was an American inventor, electrical engineer and entrepreneur who was awarded 76 US patents as an individual or as part of a team, as well as many corresponding patents. <s> Shelton's patents have had an impact relating to home washing machines and the preparation of food in both the Quick Service Restaurant (QSR) industry and fine dining. <s> Technologies Shelton developed while an engineer at General Electric are still in use after more than fifty years. <s> His patent for the modern "Washing Machine" (US 3257830 A), licensed in 1965 to General Electric has been referenced in over 40 subsequent patents. <s> Born in Lockwood, West Virginia, in 1922, Shelton was the youngest of Naaman Shelton Sr. (1889–1962) and Opal Dell (née Keenan) Shelton's (1895–1979) five children. <s> Opal Shelton operated the "Cross Roads Restaurant", a roadside diner next to the family's Standard Oil service station in Clay, West Virginia, where young Shelton had his first exposure to food service, helping his mother in the diner's kitchen.
simple: Winston Laverne Shelton (May 3, 1922 – April 15, 2019) was an American inventor, engineer and businessman. <s> He was awarded 76 patents in the United States by himself or as part of a team. <s> He founded Winston Industries, which was in use in more than 120 countries at the time of Shelton's death in 2019. <s> He died on April 15, 2019, at the age of 96. <s> His patents have impacted modern washing machines and the fast food industry. <s> His washing machine patent for General Electric, (US 3257830 A), was referenced in over 40 patents afterwards. <s> Shelton was born in Lockwood, West Virginia.

title: Mikhail Gurevich (aircraft designer)
complex: Mikhail Iosifovich Gurevich (12 January 1893 O.S. 31 December 1892 – 12 November 1976) was a Soviet aircraft designer, a partner (with Artem Mikoyan) who co-founded the famous MiG military aviation bureau. <s> MiG is an abbreviation of their surnames.
simple: Mikhail Iosifovich Gurevich (12 January 1893 – 12 November 1976) was a Soviet aircraft designer. <s> He was in a partnership with Artem Mikoyan and co-founded the famous MiG military aviation bureau.

title: Equals sign
complex: In linguistic interlinear glosses, an equals sign is conventionally used to mark clitic boundaries: the equals sign is placed between the clitic and the word that the clitic is attached to. <s> The symbol used to denote inequation (when items are not equal) is a slashed equals sign "≠" (U+2260; 2260,Alt+X in Microsoft Windows). <s> In LaTeX, this is done with the "\neq" command.
simple: The equals sign is placed between the things stated to be exactly equal or the same. <s> The symbol used to say when items are not equal is "≠" (slashed equal sign).

title: Gardner Dozois
complex: Gardner Raymond Dozois ( ; July 23, 1947 – May 27, 2018) was an American science fiction author and editor. <s> He was the founding editor of "The Year's Best Science Fiction" anthologies (1984–present) and was editor of "Asimov's Science Fiction" magazine (1984–2004), garnering multiple Hugo and Locus Awards for those works almost every year. <s> He also won the Nebula Award for Best Short Story twice. <s> He was inducted to the Science Fiction Hall of Fame on June 25, 2011. <s> Dozois was born July 23, 1947, in Salem, Massachusetts. <s> He graduated from Salem High School with the Class of 1965. <s> From 1966 to 1969 he served in the Army as a journalist, after which he moved to New York City to work as an editor in the science fiction field. <s> One of his stories had been published by Frederik Pohl in the September 1966 issue of "If" but his next four appeared in 1970, three in Damon Knight's anthology series "Orbit". <s> Dozois said that he turned to reading fiction partially as an escape from the provincialism of his home town. <s> He was badly injured in a taxi accident after returning from a Philadelphia Phillies game in 2004 (causing him to miss Worldcon for the first time in many years) but made a full recovery. <s> On July 6, 2007, Dozois had surgery for a planned quintuple bypass operation. <s> A week later, he experienced complications which prompted additional surgery to implant a defibrillator. <s> Dozois died on May 27, 2018, of a systemic infection at a hospital in Philadelphia at the age of 70. <s> As a writer, Dozois mainly worked in shorter forms. <s> He won the Nebula Award for best short story twice: once for "The Peacemaker" in 1983, and again for "Morning Child" in 1984. <s> His short fiction has been collected in "The Visible Man" (1977), "Geodesic Dreams" (a best-of collection), "Slow Dancing through Time" (1990, collaborations), "Strange Days" (2001, another best-of collection), "Morning Child and Other Stories" (2004) and "When the Great Days Come" (2011). <s> As a novelist, Dozois's oeuvre is significantly smaller. <s> He was the author of one solo novel, "Strangers" (1978), as well as a collaboration with George Alec Effinger, "Nightmare Blue" (1977), and a collaboration with George R. R. Martin and Daniel Abraham for "Hunter's Run" (2008). <s> After becoming editor of "Asimov's", Dozois's fiction output dwindled. <s> His 2006 novelette "Counterfactual" won the Sidewise Award for best alternate-history short story. <s> Dozois also wrote short fiction reviews for "Locus". <s> Michael Swanwick, one of his co-authors, completed a long interview with Dozois covering every published piece of his fiction. <s> "Being Gardner Dozois: An Interview by Michael Swanwick" was published by Old Earth Books in 2001. <s> It won the Locus Award for Non-Fiction and was a finalist for the Hugo Award for Best Related Book. <s> Dozois was known primarily as an editor, winning the Hugo Award for Best Professional Editor 15 times in 17 years from 1988 to his retirement from "Asimov's" in 2004. <s> George R. R. Martin described him as the most important and influential editor in science fiction since John W. Campbell. <s> In addition to his work with "Asimov's" (of which he was the first associate editor in 1976), he also worked in the 1970s with magazines such as "Galaxy Science Fiction", "If", "Worlds of Fantasy", and "Worlds of Tomorrow". <s> Dozois was also a prolific short fiction anthologist. <s> After resigning from his "Asimov's" position, he remained the editor of the anthology series "The Year's Best Science Fiction", published annually since 1984. <s> In three decades "Locus" readers have voted it the year's best anthology almost 20 times and the runner-up almost 10 times. <s> And, with Jack Dann, he edited a long series of themed anthologies, each with a self-explanatory title such as "Cats", "Dinosaurs", "Seaserpents", or "Hackers". <s> Dozois consistently expressed a particular interest in adventure SF and space opera, which he collectively referred to as "center-core SF".
simple: Gardner Raymond Dozois (July 23, 1947 – May 27, 2018) was an American science fiction writer and editor. <s> He was editor of "Asimov's Science Fiction" magazine from 1984 to 2004. <s> He won several Hugo and Nebula awards. <s> Dozois was born on July 23, 1947 in Salem, Massachusetts. <s> He was in the Army from 1966 to 1969 as a journalist. <s> He then moved to New York City to work as a science fiction editor. <s> Dozois said that one reason he started reading fiction was to escape from his isolated home town. <s> In 2004, Dozois was badly injured in a traffic accident while going home in a taxi from a Philadelphia Phillies game. <s> He missed Worldcon for the first time in many years because of the accident. <s> He did make a full recovery. <s> On July 6, 2007, Dozois had a planned heart surgery. <s> A week later, he experienced problems and had another operation to put in a defibrillator. <s> On May 27, 2018, Dozios died of multiple organ failure complicated by an infection at a hospital in Philadelphia at the age of 70. <s> Dozois mostly wrote short stories. <s> He won the Nebula Award for best short story twice: once for "The Peacemaker" in 1983, and again for "Morning Child" in 1984. <s> His short fiction has been collected in "The Visible Man" (1977), "Geodesic Dreams" (a best-of collection), "Slow Dancing through Time" (1990, with other authors), and "Strange Days" (2001, another best-of collection). <s> He wrote one novel by himself, "Strangers" (1978). <s> He wrote, "Nightmare Blue" (1977) with George Alec Effinger. <s> Dozois also wrote "Hunter's Run" (2008) with George R. R. Martin and Daniel Abraham. <s> After he became editor of "Asimov's", Dozois wrote less fiction. <s> His 2006 novelette "Counterfactual" won the Sidewise Award for best alternate-history short story. <s> Dozois also agreed to write short fiction reviews for "Locus". <s> Michael Swanwick published a book-length interview with Dozois in 2001. <s> The book was called "Being Gardner Dozois". <s> It won the 2002 Locus Award for Non-Fiction. <s> Dozois mainly worked as an editor. <s> He won 15 Hugo Awards for Best Professional Editor, nearly every year between 1988 and his retirement from "Asimov's" in 2004. <s> He also worked in the 1970s with magazines such as "Galaxy Science Fiction", "If", "Worlds of Fantasy", and "Worlds of Tomorrow". <s> After leaving "Asimov's", he continued as the editor of the series "The Year's Best Science Fiction". <s> This has been published each year since 1984. <s> He also edited a long series of themed anthologies with Jack Dann. <s> Each book has a title that explains the theme, such as "Cats", "Dinosaurs", "Seaserpents", or "Hackers". <s> Dozois always said he was especially interested in adventure science fiction and space opera.

title: Emma Caulfield
complex: Emma Caulfield Ford (born Emma M. Chukker; April 8, 1973) is an American actress best known for her role as Anya Jenkins on the television series "Buffy the Vampire Slayer" (1998–2003), as well as Susan Keats, a love interest of Brandon Walsh's on the television series "Beverly Hills, 90210". <s> Her film roles include "Darkness Falls" (2003) and "TiMER" (2009).
simple: Emma Caulfield (born Emma Chukker in San Diego, California on April 8, 1973) is an American actress. <s> She is best known for her role as ex-demon Anya on the television series "Buffy the Vampire Slayer".

title: Spring Offensive
complex: The 1918 Spring Offensive, or Kaiserschlacht ("Kaiser's Battle"), also known as the Ludendorff Offensive, was a series of German attacks along the Western Front during the First World War, beginning on 21 March 1918, which marked the deepest advances by either side since 1914. <s> The Germans had realised that their only remaining chance of victory was to defeat the Allies before the overwhelming human and matériel resources of the United States could be fully deployed. <s> They also had the temporary advantage in numbers afforded by the nearly 50 divisions which had been freed by the Russian withdrawal from the war by the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk.
simple: The 1918 Spring Offensive or Kaiserschlacht ("Kaiser's Battle"), also known as the Ludendorff Offensive, was a series of German attacks along the Western Front during World War I, which marked the deepest advances by either side since 1914. <s> The German authorities had realised that their only remaining chance of victory was to defeat the Allies before the overwhelming human and matériel resources of the United States could be deployed. <s> They also had the advantage of nearly 50 divisions freed by the Russian surrender (Treaty of Brest-Litovsk).

title: Chong Yong-de
complex: Chong Yong-De (Korean: 정용대, Hanja: 鄭容臺, born 4 February 1978), is a former Japanese-born South Korean midfielder.

title: The Bourne Supremacy (film)
complex: The Bourne Supremacy is a 2004 action film featuring Robert Ludlum's Jason Bourne character. <s> Though it takes the name of the second Bourne novel, its plot is entirely different. <s> The film was directed by Paul Greengrass from a screenplay by Tony Gilroy. <s> Universal Pictures released the film to theaters in the United States on July 23, 2004. <s> It is the second in the "Jason Bourne" film series. <s> It is preceded by "The Bourne Identity" (2002) and followed by "The Bourne Ultimatum" (2007), "The Bourne Legacy" (2012), and "Jason Bourne" (2016).
simple: The Bourne Supremacy is a 2004 action spy movie featuring Robert Ludlum's Jason Bourne character. <s> Though it takes the name of the second Bourne novel, its plot is entirely different. <s> The movie was directed by Paul Greengrass from a screenplay by Tony Gilroy. <s> Universal Pictures released the movie to theaters in the United States on July 23, 2004. <s> It is the second in the Jason Bourne movie series. <s> It is preceded by "The Bourne Identity" (2002) and followed by "The Bourne Ultimatum" (2007), "The Bourne Legacy" (2012), and "Jason Bourne" (2016).

title: Bertie Ahern
complex: Bartholomew Patrick "Bertie" Ahern (born 12 September 1951) is an Irish former Fianna Fáil politician who served as Taoiseach from 1997 to 2008, Leader of Fianna Fáil from 1994 to 2008, Leader of the Opposition from 1994 to 1997, Tánaiste and Minister for Arts, Culture and the Gaeltacht from November 1994 to December 1994, Deputy Leader of Fianna Fáil from 1992 to 1994, Minister for Industry and Commerce in January 1993, Minister for Finance from 1991 to 1994, Minister for Labour from 1987 to 1991, Government Chief Whip and Minister of State at the Department of Defence from March 1982 to December 1982 and Lord Mayor of Dublin from 1986 to 1987. <s> He served as a Teachta Dála (TD) from 1977 to 2011.
simple: Patrick Bartholomew "Bertie" Ahern (; born 12 September 1951, Dublin) is a former Taoiseach of Ireland leader of Fianna Fáil, the Irish Republic's largest political party.

title: Sikorsky HH-52 Seaguard
complex: The Sikorsky HH-52 Seaguard (company designation S-62) was a single turbine engine, three-blade rotor amphibious helicopter. <s> Originally developed as a commercial venture by the Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation of Stratford, Connecticut, it was used by the United States Coast Guard primarily for air-sea rescue. <s> The HH-52 has been replaced by non-amphibious types such as the HH-65 Dolphin, which rely solely on the use of a winch from a low hover to conduct rescue operations.
simple: The Sikorsky HH-52 Seaguard is an American helicopter built by Sikorsky as S-62's model. <s> It was replaced by Aérospatiale HH-65 Dolphin.

title: Abiola Ajimobi
complex: Isiaka Abiola Ajimobi (born 16 December 1949) is a Nigerian politician from Oyo State ,south-western Nigeria. <s> He was formerly the Managing Director/Chief Executive Officer of the National Oil and Chemical Marketing Company a subsidiary of Shell Petroleum, Nigeria.
simple: Abiola Ajimobi is a Nigerian politician, and former member of the Senate of Nigeria. <s> He is the executive governor of Oyo State.

title: Santa Fe Province
complex: The Province of Santa Fe ( , ] ) is a province of Argentina, located in the center-east of the country. <s> Neighboring provinces are from the north clockwise Chaco (divided by the 28th parallel south), Corrientes, Entre Ríos, Buenos Aires, Córdoba, and Santiago del Estero. <s> Together with Córdoba and Entre Ríos, the province is part of the economico-political association known as the Center Region. <s> Santa Fe's most important cities are Rosario (population 1,193,605), the capital Santa Fe (369,000), Rafaela (100,000), Reconquista (99,000) Villa Gobernador Gálvez (74,000), Venado Tuerto (69,000), and Santo Tomé (58,000).
simple: The Invincible Province of Santa Fe is a province of Argentina. <s> It is in the center-east of the country. <s> Santa Fe's most important cities are Rosario, the capital Santa Fe, Rafaela, Villa Gobernador Gálvez, Venado Tuerto, Reconquista, and Santo Tomé.
