simple: Armenia Time (AMT) is the standard time that is used in Armenia.

title: Bike path
complex: A bike path is a bikeway separated from motorized traffic and dedicated to cycling or shared with pedestrians or other non-motorized users. <s> In the US a bike path sometimes encompasses "shared use paths", "multi-use path", or "Class III bikeway" is a paved path that has been designated for use by cyclists outside the right of way of a public road. <s> It may or may not have a center divider or stripe to prevent head-on collisions. <s> In the UK, a "shared-use footway" or "multi-use path" is for use by both cyclists and pedestrians. <s> Bike paths that follow independent rights-of-way are often used to promote recreational cycling. <s> In Northern European countries, cycling tourism represents a significant proportion of overall tourist activity. <s> Extensive interurban bike path networks can be found in countries such as Denmark or the Netherlands, which has had a national system of cycle routes since 1993. <s> These networks may use routes dedicated exclusively to cycle traffic or minor rural roads whose use is otherwise restricted to local motor traffic and agricultural machinery. <s> The "Fietspad" or Bicycle Path in the Netherlands is logically constructed to link shops, housing, stations, schools, workplaces for everyday cycling. <s> The more sensible approach is based on efforts to increase Utility cycling. <s> In countries like Denmark, the Netherlands and Germany the high levels of utility cycling also includes shopping trips e.g. 9% of all shopping trips in Germany are by bicycle.
simple: A bicycle path is a way marked for people on bicycles to use. <s> Many bicycle path networks can be found in countries such as Denmark or Netherlands, which has had a national system of cycle routes since 1993. <s> These networks may use routes dedicated exclusively to cycle traffic or minor rural roads whose use is otherwise restricted to local motor traffic and agricultural machinery. <s> The Dutch word "Fietspad" means Bicycle Path in English. <s> In the Netherlands you can go on the bicycle path to the shops, housing, stations, schools, and workplaces. <s> The more sensible approach is based on efforts to increase Utility cycling. <s> In countries like Denmark, the Netherlands and Germany the high levels of utility cycling also includes shopping trips e.g. 9% of all shopping trips in Germany are by bicycle.

title: Island Nights' Entertainments
complex: Island Nights' Entertainments (also known as "South Sea Tales") is a collection of short stories by Robert Louis Stevenson, first published in 1893. <s> It would prove to contain some of his final completed work before his death in 1894. <s> The dedication was written in January 1892 in a letter to Charles Baxter, Robert Louis Stevenson's friend and adviser, and the book finally published in 1893.
simple: Island Nights' Entertainments is a book of three short stories by Robert Louis Stevenson. <s> It was published in 1893. <s> It is also known as "South Sea Tales". <s> He died in 1894.

title: Saturn's Gallic group of satellites
complex: The Gallic group is a dynamical grouping of the prograde irregular satellites of Saturn following similar orbits. <s> Their semi-major axes range between 16 and 19 Gm, their inclinations between 35° and 40°, and their eccentricities around 0.53. <s> The International Astronomical Union (IAU) reserves names taken from Gallic mythology for these moons. <s> Similar mean orbital elements led the discoverers to postulate a common origin for the group in a breakup of a larger body. <s> The group was later found to be physically homogeneous, all satellites displaying "light-red" colour (colour indices B − V = 0.91 and V − R = 0.48) and similar infrared indices <s> Remarkably, recent observations revealed that the largest member of the group, Albiorix, displays actually two different colours: one compatible with Erriapus and Tarvos, and another less red. <s> Instead of the common progenitor, it was postulated that Tarvos and Erriapus could be fragments of Albiorix, leaving a large, less red crater. <s> Such an impact would require a body with the diameter in excess of 1 km and relative velocity close to 5 km/s, resulting in a large crater with the radius of 12 km. <s> Numerous, very large craters observed on Phoebe, prove the existence of such collisions in the Saturnian system's past.
simple: The Gallic group is a dynamical grouping of the prograde irregular satellites of Saturn following similar orbits. <s> The diagram illustrates the Gallic group in relation to other irregular satellites of Saturn. <s> Their semi-major axes range between 16 and 19 Gm, their inclinations between 35° and 40°, and their eccentricities around 0.53. <s> The International Astronomical Union (IAU) reserves names taken from Gallic mythology for these moons. <s> Similar mean orbital elements led the discoverers to postulate a common origin for the group in a break up of a larger body. <s> The group was later found to be physically homogenous, all satellites displaying "light-red" colour (colour indices B − V = 0.91 and V − R = 0.48) and similar infrared indices <s> Remarkably, recent observations revealed that the largest member of the group, Albiorix, displays actually two different colours: one compatible with Eriapo and Tarvos, and another less red. <s> Instead of the common progenitor, it was postulated that Tarvos and Erriapus could be fragments of Albiorix, leaving a large, less red crater. <s> Such an impact would require a body with the diameter in excess of 1 km and relative velocity close to 5 km/s, resulting in a large crater with the radius of 12 km. <s> Numerous, very large craters observed on Phoebe, prove the existence of such collisions in the Saturnian system's past.

title: Brian Gallant
complex: Brian Alexander Gallant, Q.C. (born April 27, 1982) is a Canadian politician who served as the 33rd Premier of New Brunswick from October 7, 2014 until November 9, 2018. <s> Of Acadian and Dutch descent, Gallant practised as a lawyer before winning the Liberal leadership in October 2012, securing the riding of Kent in a by-election on April 15, 2013, shortly followed by his swearing in as Leader of the Opposition. <s> After the 2014 election, in which the Progressive Conservative government of David Alward was defeated, Gallant was sworn in as Premier at the age of 32. <s> Gallant represents the riding of Shediac Bay-Dieppe. <s> At age 32, he was the second youngest Premier of New Brunswick to assume office (George Edwin King became premier at age 30 in 1870.) <s> When Gallant left office at age 36, he was the youngest premier in Canada.
simple: Brian Alexander Gallant (born April 27, 1982) is a Canadian politician. <s> He is the 33rd and current Premier of New Brunswick since October 7, 2014. <s> At age 32, he was the second youngest Premier of New Brunswick to assume office. <s> Currently, at age , Gallant is the youngest premier in Canada.

title: Gyula Kosice
complex: Gyula Kosice (born Ferdinand Fallik; April 26, 1924 – May 25, 2016) was a Czechoslovakian-born Argentine sculptor, plastic artist, and poet. <s> He was one of the most important figures in kinetic and luminal art and luminance vanguard. <s> He created monumental sculptures, hydrospatial walks, hydrowalls, etc. <s> He made more than 40 personal and 500 collective exhibitions all over the world. <s> He is remembered for his innovative contributions to the kinetic art movement in Argentina. <s> He was the first to use neon light and gas, creating nonrepresentational patterns in his sculptures. <s> He created many monumental sculptures, hydrospatial walks, and hydrowalls using these elements.
simple: Gyula Kosice, born Ferdinand Fallik (April 26, 1924 – May 25, 2016), was a Czechoslovakian-born naturalized Argentine sculptor, plastic artist, theoretician and poet. <s> He was one of the most important figures in kinetic. <s> He created monumental sculptures, hydrospatial walks, hydrowalls, etc. <s> He made more than 40 personal and 500 collective exhibitions all over the world. <s> Kosice was the first artist to use neon in sculpture and early on water in his work.

title: Mr. Catra
complex: Wagner Domingues Costa (5 November 1968 – 9 September 2018), known professionally as Mr. Catra, was a Brazilian funk singer and actor. <s> He was known in Brazilian pop culture for his large number of children, having two wives, and his famous laugh at the beginning or ending of his songs. <s> Catra was diagnosed with stomach cancer in January 2017 and died on September 9, 2018.
simple: Wagner Domingues Costa (November 5, 1968 – September 9, 2018), known professionally as Mr. Catra, was a Brazilian funk singer and actor. <s> He was known in Brazilian pop culture for his large number of children, 32 total and having two wives. <s> He was also known for his famous laugh at the beginning or ending of his songs. <s> Mr. Catra died on September 9, 2018 from stomach cancer in São Paulo at the age of 49.

title: Lions Gate Bridge
complex: The Lions Gate Bridge, opened in 1938, officially known as the First Narrows Bridge, is a suspension bridge that crosses the first narrows of Burrard Inlet and connects the City of Vancouver, British Columbia, to the North Shore municipalities of the District of North Vancouver, the City of North Vancouver, and West Vancouver. <s> The term "Lions Gate" refers to The Lions, a pair of mountain peaks north of Vancouver.
simple: The Lions Gate Bridge is a suspension bridge in Vancouver, British Columbia.

title: TNA Television Championship
complex: The TNA Television Championship was a professional wrestling championship owned by the promotion Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (TNA, now Impact Wrestling). <s> It was introduced on the October 23, 2008 episode of TNA's television program "TNA Impact!" <s> as the TNA Legends Championship. <s> It was later known as the TNA Global Championship and the TNA King of the Mountain Championship. <s> The title appeared in Global Force Wrestling (GFW), during a talent exchange partnership. <s> As a professional wrestling championship, it was won via a planned ending to a match or awarded to a wrestler because of a storyline. <s> All title changes occurred at TNA-promoted events. <s> Reigns that occurred on "TNA Impact!, <s> ," or its later title "Impact Wrestling," usually aired on tape delay. <s> The first champion was Booker T. <s> The final champion was Lashley, as the title was retired on August 12, 2016. <s> There were a total of 25 reigns among 19 wrestlers. <s> The title was introduced during a storyline that pitted young talent within the company against veterans of professional wrestling. <s> In the weeks leading up to the unveiling of the physical belt, Booker T carried around a steel briefcase. <s> On the October 23, 2008, episode of "Impact!", <s> , Booker T introduced the belt by removing it from the briefcase, announcing its name as the "TNA Legends Championship", and declaring himself the first champion. <s> He went on to state that the championship was his and that he would defend it when he saw fit; this meant that the championship was unsanctioned by TNA in the storyline. <s> On March 15, 2009, at TNA's Destination X pay-per-view (PPV) event, A.J. Styles defeated Booker T to win the championship. <s> Afterwards on the March 19, 2009, episode of "Impact!", <s> , Styles was credited as becoming the first-ever TNA Grand Slam Champion, by winning the World Heavyweight (NWA or TNA), the World Tag Team (NWA or TNA), the TNA X Division Championship, and the Legends Championship. <s> TNA Management Director Jim Cornette then announced that the TNA Legends Championship had become an official TNA sanctioned championship thanks to Styles defeating Booker T for it legally via the contract the two had signed to make the match official. <s> On the October 29, 2009, episode of "Impact!", <s> , then-champion Eric Young renamed the title the "TNA Global Championship". <s> He went on to declare that he was not going to defend it against any American wrestlers nor on American soil. <s> However, Young's first defense was on the December 10, 2009, episode of "Impact!" <s> in Orlando, Florida against Japanese female wrestler Hamada. <s> Young's second, third and fourth defenses lived up to his earlier decree, when he defended against Suicide in Glasgow, Hamada in Bournemouth, and unsuccessfully against Welsh wrestler Rob Terry in Cardiff, Wales at a live event on January 27, 2010. <s> On the July 22, 2010, episode of "Impact!", <s> , Terry lost the Global Championship to A.J. Styles. <s> Styles then renamed the title the "TNA Television Championship" on the July 29, 2010, episode of "Impact!". <s> On the April 19, 2012, episode of the newly titled "Impact Wrestling", TNA General Manager Hulk Hogan ordered that the TNA Television Championship had to be defended every week. <s> The weekly title defenses lasted until the June 21, 2012, episode of "Impact Wrestling". <s> On July 3, 2014, TNA Executive Director Kurt Angle declared the championship inactive. <s> The title was reactivated on June 25, 2015, by TNA under the new name of the "TNA King of the Mountain Championship." <s> TNA announced that a new champion would be determined in a King of the Mountain match at their Slammiversary PPV event on June 28. <s> Jeff Jarrett defeated Matt Hardy, Eric Young, Drew Galloway, and Bobby Roode to win the championship. <s> The title ended up appearing in GFW at a July 9 live event where Young attacked Jarrett and stole the championship belt. <s> The inaugural champion was Booker T, who awarded the championship to himself on the October 23, 2008, episode of "Impact!". <s> Eric Young holds the record for most reigns, with three, and is the only wrestler to hold the title under all four of its incarnations. <s> Abyss' second reign is the longest in the title's history at 396 days. <s> PJ Black and Lashley share the record for shortest reign in the title's history at one day. <s> Abyss holds the record for combined days as champion, with 460.
simple: The TNA King of the Mountain Championship is a professional wrestling championship in Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (TNA). <s> The championship was debuted on the October 23, 2008 episode of "TNA Impact!" <s> and was originally called the "TNA Legends Championship". <s> The first champion was Booker T. <s> Booker T revealed the championship after he took it out of a steel briefcase that he had been carrying around in the weeks leading up to the reveal. <s> He named it the "TNA Legends Championship" and declared himself as the first champion. <s> A.J. Styles defeated Booker T at Destination X on March 15, 2009 to win the championship. <s> Winning the title made Styles the first-ever TNA Grand Slam Champion after he had won the World Heavyweight (NWA or TNA), the World Tag Team (NWA or TNA), and the TNA X Division Championship along with the Legends Championship. <s> The Management Director of TNA Jim Cornette announced that the Championship became an official TNA sanctioned championship because Styles defeated Booker T for it legally by the contract the two had signed to make the match official. <s> When Eric Young held the championship, he renamed it the "TNA Global Championship" on the October 29, 2009 episode of "Impact!" <s> and said that he was not going to defend it against any American wrestlers or on American soil. <s> Young was defeated by Rob Terry during a live event in Cardiff, Wales on January 27, 2010. <s> Terry lost the championship to A.J. Styles on the July 22 episode of "Impact!". <s> Styles renamed it the "TNA Television Championship" on the July 29 episode. <s> It was declared defunct by the (storyline) TNA Executive Director Kurt Angle on July 3, 2014. <s> On July 3, 2014, the TNA Executive Director Kurt Angle declared that the Television Championship would become inactive. <s> The title was reactivated under the new name "TNA King of the Mountain Championship" on June 25, 2015. <s> On June 25, 2015, the championship was reactivated under the new name "TNA King of the Mountain Championship." <s> It was announced by TNA that there would be a new champion crowned in a King of the Mountain match at Slammiversary. <s> At Slammiversary, Jeff Jarrett defeated Matt Hardy, Eric Young, Drew Galloway, and Bobby Roode to win the championship. <s> The championship did appear at a GFW live event on July 9 where Young attacked Jarrett and stole the championship. <s> He awarded himself the championship on the October 23, 2008 episode of "Impact!". <s> The longest reigns in the championship's history was Abyss' second reign which lasted 396 days. <s> The shortest reign was PJ Black's first reign which lasted only 1 day.

title: Afonso IV of Portugal
complex: Afonso IV (] ; 8 February 129128 May 1357), called the Brave , was King of Portugal from 1325 until his death. <s> He was the only legitimate son of King Denis of Portugal by his wife Elizabeth of Aragon. <s> On 12 September 1309, Afonso married Beatrice of Castile, daughter of Sancho IV of Castile, and María de Molina, and had four sons and three daughters. <s> Afonso broke the tradition of previous kings and did not have any children out of wedlock.
simple: Afonso IV (ɐˈfõsu; 8 February 1291 – 28 May 1357), called the Brave , was the seventh king of Portugal and the Algarve from 1325 until his death. <s> He was the only son that King Denis of Portugal had with his wife Elizabeth of Aragon. <s> Afonso married Beatrice of Castile (1293–1359) in 1309, daughter of Sancho IV, King of Castile and María de Molina, and had four sons and three daughters by her.

title: Independence Day Award
complex: The Independence Day Award , also termed Independence Award , Swadhinata Padak, and Swadhinata Puroskar, is the highest state award given by the government of Bangladesh. <s> Introduced in 1977, this award is bestowed upon Bangladeshi citizens or organizations in recognition of substantial contribution to one of many fields, including the War of Liberation, the Language Movement, education, literature, journalism, public service, science and technology, medical science, social science, song, games and sports, fine arts, rural development, and other areas. <s> Each awardee receives a gold medal, a certificate of honour, and a sum of cash. <s> The amount of the cash reward was originally 20,000 takas, but was subsequently increased to 100,000 takas in 2004. <s> A cabinet committee on national awards prepares the list of each year's nominees and forwards the list to the head of the government for final approval.
simple: The Independence Day Award is the highest state award given by the government of Bangladesh. <s> It is also termed Independence Award, Swadhinata Padak, and Swadhinata Puroskar. <s> The award was introduced in 1977 and since then it has been given to Bangladeshi citizens or organizations in recognition of substantial contribution to one of many fields, including the War of Liberation, the Language Movement, education, literature, journalism, public service, science and technology, medical science, social science, song, games and sports, fine arts, rural development, and other areas. <s> Each awardee receives a gold medal, a certificate of honour, and a sum of cash. <s> The amount of the cash reward was originally taka 20 thousand, but later in 2004, it was increased to taka one lac (.10 million in Bangladeshi currency).

title: Statistical population
complex: In statistics, a population is a set of similar items or events which is of interest for some question or experiment. <s> A statistical population can be a group of existing objects (e.g. the set of all stars within the Milky Way galaxy) or a hypothetical and potentially infinite group of objects conceived as a generalization from experience (e.g. the set of all possible hands in a game of poker).
simple: In statistics, a population is a set of things from which samples may be drawn.

title: Eutrophication
complex: Eutrophication most commonly arises from the oversupply of nutrients, most commonly as nitrogen or phosphorus, which leads to overgrowth of plants and algae in aquatic ecosystems. <s> After such organisms die, bacterial degradation of their biomass results in oxygen consumption, thereby creating the state of hypoxia. <s> Some algal blooms resulting from eutrophication, otherwise called "harmful algal blooms", are toxic to plants and animals. <s> Toxic compounds can make their way up the food chain, resulting in animal mortality.
simple: Eutrophication is what a water-based ecosystem does when too many nutrients are added to it. <s> Eutrophication is mainly caused by two nutrients, phosphorus and nitrogen. <s> The major consequence of eutrophication are algal blooms.

title: T.J. Miller
complex: Todd Joseph “T.J.” Miller (born June 4, 1981) is an American actor, stand-up comedian, provocateur, producer and writer. <s> As a commercial actor, he voices a talking ball of mucus in commercials for Mucinex and stars as Greg the Genie in a promotional campaign for Slim Jim meat snacks. <s> In Miller's film debut, "Cloverfield", he appeared onscreen for only a few minutes, but his voice was heard in almost every scene as the character who videotaped most of the events depicted. <s> In 2009, he played Cessna Jim in "" and the dim-witted grindcore musician Rory in Mike Judge's comedy "Extract".
simple: Todd Joseph "T. J." Miller (born June 4, 1981) is an American actor and stand-up comedian. <s> His first role in a movie was "Cloverfield", in which he played the character who videotaped most of the scenes.

title: Alfta GIF
complex: Alfta GIF is a sports club in Alfta, Sweden, established on 10 November 1900. <s> The club runs handball, ice hockey and soccer, earlier even bandy. <s> The men's bandy team played in the Swedish top division in 1941. <s> The men's soccer team has played in the Swedish third division. <s> The ice hockey section was established in 1947. <s> The skiing and track and field athletics sections have been inactive since 2002.
simple: Alfta GIF is a sports club in Alfta in Sweden. <s> It was established on 10 November 1900. <s> The club runs handball, ice hockey and soccer. <s> Earlier the club also ran bandy. <s> The men's bandy team played in the Swedish top division in 1941. <s> The men's soccer team has played in the Swedish third division. <s> The ice hockey section was established in 1947. <s> The skiing and track and field athletics sections have been inactive since 2002.

title: Itaipu Dam
complex: The Itaipu Dam ( , ; ] , ] ) is a hydroelectric dam on the Paraná River located on the border between Brazil and Paraguay. <s> The construction of the dam was first contested by Argentina, but the negotiations and resolution of the dispute ended up setting the basis for Argentine–Brazilian integration later on. <s> In 1994, the American Society of Civil Engineers elected the Itaipu Dam as one of the seven modern Wonders of the World. <s> In 1995, the American magazine "Popular Mechanics" published the results.
simple: The Itaipu Dam is a hydroelectric (making electricity by the movement of water) dam on the Paraná River, on the border between Brazil and Paraguay. <s> It is listed as one of the Seven Wonders of the Modern World.

title: Saitama Prefecture
complex: Saitama Prefecture (埼玉県 , "Saitama-ken" ) is a prefecture of Japan located in the Kantō region. <s> The capital is the city of Saitama. <s> Saitama Prefecture was formerly part of the old Musashi Province. <s> Saitama Prefecture is bordered by Tokyo, Chiba, Ibaraki, Tochigi, Gunma, Nagano, and Yamanashi Prefectures. <s> It is located central-west of the Kanto region, measuring 103 km from east to west and 52 km from north to south.
simple: Saitama Prefecture (埼玉県, "Saitama-ken") is a prefecture in the Kantō region of Japan on the island of Honshu. <s> Saitama is in the Kantō region. <s> The capital is the city of Saitama. <s> Saitama Prefecture was formerly part of the old Musashi Province. <s> The prefecture shares borders with Chiba Prefecture, Ibaraki Prefecture, Gunma Prefecture, Nagano,Tochigi Prefecture, Yamanashi Prefecture and Tokyo.

title: Autonomic dysreflexia
complex: Autonomic dysreflexia (AD), also previously known as mass reflex, is a potential medical emergency classically characterized by uncontrolled hypertension and bradycardia, although tachycardia is known to commonly occur. <s> AD occurs most often in individuals with spinal cord injuries with lesions at or above the T6 spinal cord level, although it has been reported in patients with lesions as low as T10. <s> Guillain–Barré syndrome may also cause Autonomic Dysreflexia.
simple: Autonomic dysreflexia (AD), also called autonomic hyperreflexia, is a medical emergency. <s> AD usually happens in people with spinal cord injuries that have caused damage above the sixth thoracic vertebra (T6, which is about at the same level of the armpits). <s> However, AD sometimes happens in people with spinal damage as low as their tenth thoracic vertebra (T10, which is about a few inches above the level of the belly button).

title: Martha Reeves
complex: Martha Rose Reeves (born July 18, 1941) is an American R&B and pop singer and former politician, and is the lead singer of the Motown girl group Martha Reeves and the Vandellas. <s> They scored over a dozen hit singles, including "Come and Get These Memories", "Nowhere to Run", "Heat Wave", "Jimmy Mack", and their signature "Dancing In The Street". <s> From 2005 until 2009, Reeves served as an elected council woman for the city of Detroit, Michigan. <s> Martha Rose Reeves was born in Eufaula, Alabama, the first daughter of Elijah Joshua Reeves and Ruby Lee Gilmore Reeves, and the third of the couple's 11 children. <s> She was a baby when the family moved from Eufaula to Detroit, Michigan, where her grandfather, Reverend Elijah Reeves, was a minister at Detroit's Metropolitan Church. <s> The family was very active in the church and its choir.
simple: Martha Rose Reeves (born July 18, 1941) is an American musician and former politician. <s> Together, their hits included "Dancing in the Street" and "Heat Wave". <s> She was a councilwoman in Detroit, Michigan. <s> Reeves was a Detroit Councilwoman between 2005 and 2009. <s> She was born in Alabama. <s> She was raised in Detroit.

title: Simone Biles
complex: Simone Arianne Biles (born March 14, 1997) is an American artistic gymnast. <s> Biles is the 2016 Olympic individual all-around, vault and floor gold medalist, and balance beam bronze medalist. <s> She was part of the gold-medal-winning team dubbed the "Final Five" at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro. <s> Biles is a four-time World all-around champion (2013–15, 2018), four-time World floor exercise champion (2013–15, 2018), two-time World balance beam champion (2014, 2015), the 2018 World vault champion, a six-time United States national all-around champion (2013–16, 2018, 2019), and a member of the gold-medal-winning American teams at the 2014, 2015, and 2018 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships. <s> Additionally, she is a three-time World silver medalist (2013 and 2014 on vault, 2018 on uneven bars) and a three-time World bronze medalist (2015 on vault, 2013 and 2018 on balance beam). <s> Having won a combined total of twenty-five Olympic and World Championship medals, Biles is the most decorated American gymnast. <s> Biles became the sixth woman to win an individual all-around title at both the World Championships and the Olympic Games. <s> Biles set an American record for most gold medals in women's gymnastics at a single Olympic Games (four). <s> At the 2018 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships in Doha, Biles became the female gymnast with the most World all-around titles (4) and total World medals (20), as well as the gymnast with the most World gold medals of any gender (14).
simple: Simone Arianne Biles (born March 14, 1997) is an American artistic gymnast. <s> Biles is the 2016 Olympic individual all-around, vault and floor gold medalist. <s> She was part of the gold medal-winning team dubbed the "Final Five" at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro. <s> Biles is a three-time world all-around champion (2013–15), three-time world floor champion (2013–15), two-time world balance beam champion (2014, 2015), four-time United States national all-around champion (2013–16), and a member of the gold medal-winning American teams at the 2014 and 2015 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships. <s> Having won a combined total of nineteen Olympic and World Championship medals, Biles is the most decorated American gymnast. <s> With her win in Rio, Biles became the sixth woman to have won an individual all-around title at both the World Championships and the Olympic Games. <s> With four Olympic gold medals, Biles set a new American record for most gold medals in women’s gymnastics at a single game.

title: Falmouth, Cornwall
complex: Falmouth ( ; ) is a town, civil parish and port on the River Fal on the south coast of Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. <s> It has a total resident population of 21,797 (2011 census).
simple: Falmouth (meaning mouth of the River Fal) is a town on the south coast of Cornwall.

title: Principle of relativity
complex: In physics, the principle of relativity is the requirement that the equations describing the laws of physics have the same form in all admissible frames of reference.
simple: In physics, the principle of relativity is the requirement that the equations describing the laws of physics is as same as the all frames of reference.

title: Nippon Budokan
complex: Nippon Budokan (日本武道館 , Nippon Budōkan ) , often shortened to simply Budokan, is an indoor arena located in Chiyoda, Tokyo, Japan. <s> Budokan was originally built for the judo competition in the 1964 Summer Olympics, hence its name, which translates in English as "Martial Ways Hall". <s> Its primary purpose is to host martial arts contests and for a time was a popular venue for Japanese professional wrestling.
simple: Nippon Budokan is an arena in Chiyoda-ku, Tokyo. <s> It was used as the judo stadium at the 1964 Summer Olympics.

title: Hernandez v. Texas
complex: Hernandez v. Texas, 347 U.S. 475 (1954), was a landmark case, "the first and only Mexican-American civil-rights case heard and decided by the United States Supreme Court during the post-World War II period." <s> In a unanimous ruling, the court held that Mexican Americans and all other nationality groups in the United States have equal protection under the 14th Amendment of the U.S. Constitution. <s> The ruling was written by Justice Earl Warren. <s> This was the first case in which Mexican-American lawyers had appeared before the US Supreme Court. <s> Peter Hernandez, a Mexican-American agricultural worker, was convicted for the 1951 murder of Joe Espinosa. <s> Hernandez's "pro bono" legal team, including Gustavo C. García, wanted to challenge what they knew was "the systematic exclusion of persons of Mexican origin from all types of jury duty in at least seventy counties in Texas." <s> They appealed Hernandez's conviction claiming that Mexican Americans were treated as a class apart and subject to social discrimination in Jackson County, where the case had been tried. <s> They were systematically excluded from the grand jury and jury. <s> Hernandez's defense lawyers demonstrated that, although numerous Mexican Americans were citizens and had otherwise qualified for jury duty in Jackson County, during the previous 25 years no Mexican Americans (or, more precisely, no one with a Hispanic surname) were among the 6,000 persons chosen to serve on juries. <s> This resulted in Hernandez having been deprived of equal protection of the law under the Fourteenth Amendment, as juries were restricted by ethnicity. <s> Hernandez and his lawyers appealed to the Texas Supreme Court. <s> They appealed to the United States Supreme Court through a writ of certiorari. <s> The legal team included García, Carlos Cadena and John J. Herrera of the League of United Latin American Citizens, and James DeAnda and Cris Alderete of the G. I. Forum, both activist groups for civil rights for Mexican Americans. <s> These were the first Mexican-American lawyers to represent a defendant before the US Supreme Court, which heard their arguments on January 11, 1954. <s> Chief Justice Earl Warren and the rest of the Supreme Court unanimously ruled in favor of Hernandez, and required he be retried by a jury composed without discrimination against Mexican Americans. <s> The Court held that the Fourteenth Amendment protects persons beyond the racial classes of white or black, and extends protection to nationality groups as well. <s> The ruling was an extension of protection in the Civil Rights Movement to nationality groups within the country and an acknowledgement that, in certain times and places, groups other than blacks (African Americans) could be discriminated against. <s> The ultimate effect of this ruling was that the protection of the 14th Amendment was ruled to cover any national or ethnic groups of the United States for which discrimination could be proved.
simple: Hernandez v. Texas, 347 U.S. 475 (1954), was a landmark decision by the United States Supreme Court. <s> In a unanimous ruling, the Court held that Mexican Americans and all other racial or national groups in the United States had equal protection under the 14th Amendment of the U.S. Constitution. <s> Mexican Americans were such a "special class" and were entitled to equal protection under the Fourteenth Amendment. <s> The ruling was written by Chief Justice Earl Warren. <s> This was the first case in which Mexican-American lawyers had appeared before the US Supreme Court. <s> Pete Hernandez, a Mexican-American agricultural worker, was convicted for the 1950 murder of Joe Espinosa. <s> Hernandez's "pro bono" legal team, including Gustavo C. García, wanted to challenge what they knew was "the systematic exclusion of persons of Mexican origin" from all types of jury duty in at least seventy counties in Texas. <s> His defense lawyers argued that persons of Mexican descent had not been allowed to serve on juries even though numerous Mexican Americans were citizens and had qualified for jury duty in Jackson County. <s> Even though 14 percent of the county was Hispanic, none had served on juries for at least the last 25 years. <s> This meant Hernandez had been deprived of his Fourteenth Amendment rights. <s> Hernandez and his lawyers appealed to the Supreme Court of Texas, then to the United States Supreme Court through a writ of certiorari. <s> The unanimousmajority opinion was delivered by Chief Justice Earl Warren. <s> The Court ruled the Fourteenth Amendment protects persons beyond the racial classes of white or black, and extends protection to other racial or national groups, as well as legal classes. <s> The ultimate effect of this ruling was that the protection of the 14th Amendment was ruled to cover any racial, national and ethnic groups of the United States for which discrimination could be proved.

title: Cesare Bovo
complex: Cesare Bovo (born 14 January 1983) is an Italian professional footballer who plays as a centre back for Lecce.
simple: Cesare Bovo (born 14 January 1983) is an Italian football player.

title: Comanche County, Texas
complex: Comanche County is a county located on the Edwards Plateau in Central Texas. <s> As of the 2010 census, its population was 13,974. <s> The county seat is Comanche. <s> The county was founded in 1856 and is named for the Comanche Native American tribe.
simple: Comanche County is a county in the U.S. state of Texas. <s> In 2010, 13,974 people lived there. <s> The county seat is Comanche.

title: Alexi Lalas
complex: Panayotis Alexander "Alexi" Lalas (born June 1, 1970) is an American retired soccer player who played mostly as a defender. <s> Lalas is best known for his participation with the United States men's national soccer team in the 1994 FIFA World Cup, where he was a standout player on the team with his distinctive long beard and hair.
simple: Alexi Lalas (born 1 June 1970) is a former American soccer player.

title: Sofia Church, Jönköping
complex: Sofia Church is a church building in western Jönköping in Sweden. <s> Belonging to Sofia-Järstorp Parish of the Church of Sweden, it was opened on 8 April 1888, on Octave of Easter.
simple: Sofia Church is a church in the town of Jönköping in Sweden. <s> It belongs to Sofia-Järstorp Parish of the Church of Sweden. <s> It was opened on 8 April 1888.

title: Barnyard (film)
complex: Barnyard (marketed as Barnyard: The Original Party Animals) is a 2006 computer-animated comedy film produced by O Entertainment and distributed by Paramount Pictures. <s> The film is directed, produced, and written by Steve Oedekerk, the co-creator of "" and the spin-off television series "". <s> It stars Kevin James, Courteney Cox, Sam Elliott, Danny Glover, Wanda Sykes, Andie MacDowell and David Koechner, with supporting roles done by Jeff Garcia, Tino Insana, Dom Irrera, Cam Clarke, Rob Paulsen, S. Scott Bullock, John DiMaggio, Maurice LaMarche, Fred Tatasciore and Lloyd Sherr. <s> Most of the production was carried out in San Clemente, California. <s> Otis (Kevin James) is a carefree young cow who prefers playing with his friends rather than accept responsibility. <s> His strict father Ben (Sam Elliott) is the leader of the barnyard. <s> After Otis interrupts a barnyard meeting with his wild antics, Ben has a talk with his son, warning him that he will never be happy if he spends his life partying without acting more maturely. <s> Otis ignores his advice and leaves to have fun with his friends Pip the Mouse (Jeff Garcia), Freddy the Ferret (Cam Clarke), Peck the Rooster (Rob Paulsen) and Pig the Pig (Tino Insana). <s> That same day, Otis meets a pregnant cow named Daisy (Courtney Cox), who is accompanied by her friend, Bessy (Wanda Sykes). <s> That night, the animals throw a party in the barn. <s> All the animals at the barnyard are there except Ben, who guards the fence line. <s> Otis is assigned a shift along with Ben, but Otis talks himself out of work. <s> Before Otis leaves, Ben tells him that the night he found him as a baby calf stumbling alone in the meadow, he swore he saw the stars dance, thus giving him reason to know his place was at the farm. <s> Later, Ben takes on a pack of coyotes led by Dag (David Koechner), plundering the chicken coop. <s> He manages to fight off the pack until he is bitten on the leg by the red coyote, making him fall. <s> The Coyotes pile on Ben, but he manages to grab Dag and escapes the pile. <s> He threatens to punch Dag but lets him go, scaring away him and the coyotes. <s> Ben falls on the ground, exhausted. <s> Otis is alerted and he runs outside to his father, who dies in his arms. <s> The next morning, Ben is buried on a hill by the farmer (Fred Tatasciore), and the other animals mourn Ben after the farmer leaves. <s> After Ben's death, all the animals elect Otis as the new leader of the barnyard. <s> Otis shirks his duties by leaving Freddy and Peck in charge of the coop, then helps the trouble-making "Jersey Cows"; Eddy, Igg, and Bud (S. Scott Bullock, John DiMaggio, and Maurice LaMarche) teach a lesson to a mean, fat youngster called Snotty Boy (Steve Oedekerk) for cow-tipping, eluding the police along the way. <s> Later that night, when Otis is holding Daisy's hoof under the starlight, he overhears the coyotes chasing a rabbit and leaves Daisy to pursue the coyotes and avenge his father. <s> Otis tries to attack Dag and his pack but is outnumbered. <s> Since Otis is weaker, Dag proposes a deal: he and his pack will take various barnyard animals at random times and that, if Otis tries to stand up to them, they will slaughter everyone at the barnyard. <s> Otis decides to leave the barnyard, realizing that his chances of victory are slim. <s> The next morning, before leaving, Otis is informed that the Coyotes took some hens including Maddy (Madeline Lovejoy), a little chick who is one of Otis' friends. <s> Otis realizes that he has been fooled by Dag, as he was not expecting him and the coyotes until tonight, and sets off to rescue the chickens. <s> Otis confronts the pack but is easily defeated after Dag bites him in the leg; however, Pip, Pig, Freddy, Peck, Miles (Danny Glover), Ben's old friend, and the Jersey Cows arrive to help Otis. <s> Dag tries to attack Otis from behind, but Otis is alerted when Peck successfully manages to crow a warning. <s> Otis catches Dag and warns him to never return to the barnyard. <s> Otis then swings Dag out of the junkyard with a golf club, finally avenging his father's death. <s> After hijacking a biker gang's motorcycles from the diner, Otis and the rest make it back to the barn to witness Daisy giving birth to a calf that she names Li'l Ben. <s> Otis then takes full responsibility and becomes the new leader of the barnyard as he watches the stars of himself, Daisy and Lil' Ben dance just like Ben said.
simple: Barnyard is an animated movie which first shown in theaters on August 4, 2006. <s> It was directed by Steve Oedekerk. <s> Otis is a cow who likes to play. <s> His father Ben is the leader of the barnyard when the farmer is away. <s> Otis interrupts a barnyard meeting with his wild behavior, His father tells Otis he will never be happy if he just goofs off, and that he should grow up. <s> Otis ignores his advice and leaves to have fun with his friends: Pip the mouse, Pig the pig, Freddy the ferret, and Peck the chicken. <s> That same day, Otis meets a new cow, Daisy, who is pregnant. <s> She is with Bessy, another female cow. <s> That night the animals have a party in the barn. <s> All the animals are there except Ben, who is guarding the animals. <s> Ben talks with Otis and says the day he found him alone in the meadow, the stars danced. <s> Later on, Ben has to fight a pack of coyotes led by Dag. <s> They are raiding the chicken coop. <s> Ben is bitten in the leg by a coyote, and he falls down. <s> The coyotes pile on Ben, but he manages to grab Dag and escapes the pile. <s> The hens cheer, but Ben falls on the ground, tired. <s> Etta, a hen, runs into the barn and tells Otis, who runs outside to his father. <s> After Ben's death, all the animals elect Otis as the new leader of the Barnyard. <s> He gets out of his duties by leaving Freddy and Peck in charge of the coop. <s> Later, Otis is sitting with Daisy and he overhears the coyotes chasing a hare. <s> Otis tries to attack Dag but is outsmarted. <s> Since Otis is weaker, Dag makes a deal that he and his pack will take some of the animals, but if he tries to stand up for all of them, they will kill everyone. <s> Otis decides to leave the barnyard because he has no chance against the coyotes. <s> The next morning, before leaving, Otis finds out that the coyotes have taken some hens and a chick. <s> Otis knows that he has been tricked by Dag, as he was not expecting them until tonight. <s> He goes to rescue the poultry. <s> Otis confronts the pack but is easily defeated. <s> Pip, Pig, Freddy, Peck and Miles the Mule arrive to help them, along with the gophers and Jersey Cows. <s> Dag tries to sneak attack Otis from behind, but Otis is alerted when Peck successfully yells a warning. <s> Otis catches Dag and tells the coyote to never return. <s> Dag is swung out of the junkyard by Otis's golf skills. <s> Otis and the rest make it back to the barnyard. <s> Daisy gives birth to a calf whom she names Ben.

title: First Coast
complex: Florida's First Coast, or simply the First Coast, is a region of the U.S. state of Florida, located on the Atlantic coast of North Florida. <s> The First Coast refers to the same general area as the directional region of Northeast Florida. <s> It roughly comprises the five counties surrounding Jacksonville: Duval, Baker, Clay, Nassau, and St. Johns, largely corresponding to the Jacksonville metropolitan area, and may include other nearby areas such as Putnam and Flagler counties in Florida and Camden County, Georgia. <s> The name originated in a marketing campaign in the 1980s, and has since emerged as one of Florida's best known vernacular regions. <s> Enterprise Florida, the state's economic development agency, identifies "Northeast Florida" as one of eight economic regions used by the agency and other state and outside entities.
simple: The First Coast is a region of the U.S. state of Florida. <s> It is also called Florida's First Coast. <s> The First Coast includes five counties around Jacksonville: Duval, Clay, Nassau and St. Johns. <s> Its name comes from a marketing campaign in the 1980s.

title: Polypropylene
complex: Polypropylene (PP), also known as polypropene, is a thermoplastic polymer used in a wide variety of applications. <s> It is produced via chain-growth polymerization from the monomer propylene. <s> PP can be made translucent when uncolored but is not as readily made transparent as polystyrene, acrylic, or certain other plastics. <s> It is often opaque or colored using pigments. <s> Many objects are made with polypropylene precisely because it is resilient and resistant to most solvents and glues. <s> Also, there are very few glues available specifically for gluing PP.
simple: Polypropylene (PP), or polypropene, is a type of plastic. <s> As a plastic it can be made translucent but usually is opaque and often brightly colored. <s> It is tough, and resists many solvents, acids and bases.

title: Vanessa Lachey
complex: Vanessa Joy Lachey (née Minnillo; born November 9, 1980 ) is an American-Filipino television personality, beauty queen, fashion model, television host and actress. <s> She was also named Miss Teen USA in 1998. <s> She has been a New York-based correspondent for "Entertainment Tonight" and hosted "Total Request Live" on MTV. <s> Vanessa Joy Minnillo was born at USAF Clark Regional Medical Center in Angeles City, Pampanga, Philippines. <s> Her father, Vincent Charles Minnillo, is an American citizen from Cleveland, Ohio of Italian and Irish descent, while her mother, Helen Ramos Bercero, is from Manila, Philippines. <s> Minnillo has an adopted brother who is two years older.
simple: Vanessa Joy Lachey (née Minnillo; born November 9, 1980) is an American television personality, fashion model, and actress. <s> She was named Miss Teen USA in 1998. <s> She has also been a correspondent for "Entertainment Tonight" from 2005 to 2007 and hosted "Total Request Live" on MTV. <s> Minnillo was born in Angeles, Pampanga, Philippines. <s> Her mother is Filipino and her father is an American of Ashkenazi Jews, Irish and Italian ancestry.

title: Storvik
complex: Storvik is a locality situated in Sandviken Municipality, Gävleborg County, Sweden with 2,165 inhabitants in 2010.
simple: Storvik is a locality in Sandviken Municipality in Gävleborg County in Sweden. <s> In 2010, 2,165 people lived there.

title: Eamon (singer)
complex: Eamon Doyle (born September 19, 1983), professionally known as Eamon, is an American R&B singer-songwriter and harmonicist. <s> He is known for his hit single, "Fuck It (I Don't Want You Back)". <s> Eamon was born Eamon Jonathan Doyle in Staten Island, New York City, the son of Diane (née Zizzo), an Italian American nurse, and Walter Doyle, a counselor with a private practice, of Irish descent. <s> His father was a member of a doo-wop group by the name of "The Elations". <s> He began singing at age nine and touring and performing with his father's group at the same age. <s> At 15, while working in a music studio, he caught the attention of songwriter/producer Milk Dee, who had worked with musicians such as MC Lyte, Janet Jackson, and Mary J. Blige. <s> Dee and his co-producer Mark Passy helped refine Eamon's sound. <s> Eamon was eventually signed to Jive Records. <s> After the success of "Fuck It (I Don't Want You Back)", Eamon released a second single, "I Love Them Ho's (Ho-Wop)". <s> The song did not match the success of its predecessor, although it was a top 10 hit in Denmark, where it peaked at number seven on the Danish Singles Chart.
simple: Eamon Jonathan Doyle, professionally known as Eamon, is an American R&B singer-songwriter and harmonicist. <s> He is known for his hit single, "Fuck It (I Don't Want You Back)". <s> Eamon was born Eamon Jonathan Doyle in Staten Island, New York City. <s> His mother Diane was a nurse and his father Walter Doyle was a counselor. <s> He began singing at age nine and started to perform and tour with his father's group a R&B group called "The Elations". <s> When he was 15 he began to work with songwriter and producer, Milk Dee, who had worked with many hip hop and R&B artists such as MC Lyte, Janet Jackson and Mary J. Blige. <s> After Eamon had released his debut single "Fuck It (I Don't Want You Back)", a female R&B singer from Staten Island called Frankee released her debut single which was an answer back to "Fuck It (I Don't Want You Back)".

title: Saint-Lô
complex: Saint-Lô ( , ] ) is a commune in north-western France, the capital of the Manche department in the region of Normandy.
simple: Saint-Lô is a commune. <s> It is in the Manche department in west France.

title: Division of Paterson
complex: The Division of Paterson is an Australian electoral division in the state of New South Wales. <s> It is located just north of Newcastle, on the coast of the Tasman Sea. <s> The division is named after federation-era poet and author Banjo Paterson and was originally created in 1949 and abolished in 1984. <s> It was recreated after a redistribution in 1992. <s> The division is centred on the lower Hunter Valley and the outer suburbs of Greater Newcastle. <s> It includes the city of Maitland and the towns of Kurri Kurri, Nelson Bay, Raymond Terrace and Salamander Bay. <s> It covers most of the Port Stephens, and Maitland local government areas along with a small outer part of the City of Newcastle and parts of the northern end of the City of Cessnock. <s> Paterson was first created at the redistribution of 11 May 1949. <s> It was named after Banjo Paterson although there is conjecture that it was originally named after Colonel William Paterson who also gave his name to the Paterson River and the town of Paterson, both of which were situated within the electorate. <s> It was first contested at the 1949 election. <s> At the time it included the towns of Singleton, Maitland and Muswellbrook. <s> Redistributions eventually moved the electorate north until it included Gunnedah and Mudgee. <s> This incarnation was held by the conservative parties—Liberal and National—for its entire existence, and for most of that time was safely conservative. <s> The original electorate was abolished at the 11 October 1984 redistribution. <s> At the redistribution of 31 January 1992 the electorate was recreated, covering a similar area to the original electorate. <s> It extended from the lower Hunter Valley in the south to the Manning River in the north, and the Great Dividing Range in the west.
simple: The Division of Paterson is an Australian electoral division in the state of New South Wales. <s> It is just north of Newcastle, on the coast of the Tasman Sea. <s> The division was first set up in 1949 and abolished in 1984. <s> The division is named after poet and author Banjo Paterson. <s> It was recreated after a redistribution in 1992. <s> It includes the towns of Anna Bay, Bulahdelah. <s> It is possible that is was named after Colonel William Paterson who also gave his name to the Paterson River and the town of Paterson, both of which were in the electorate. <s> It was first contested at the 1949 election. <s> In 1949 the division included Singleton, Maitland and Muswellbrook. <s> Redistributions moved the electorate north until it included Gunnedah and Mudgee. <s> The original electorate was abolished in 1984. <s> In 1992 it was recreated covering a similar area to the original electorate.

title: Trams in Kraków
complex: Trams in Kraków are a tram public transit system in Kraków, Poland. <s> The tramway has been in operation since 1882. <s> There are 22 ordinary, 2 fast, and 3 night tram lines with a total line length of 347 km .
simple: They are like Buses in Kraków, but these are trams and not buses. <s> The rail system of Kraków has been in operaration since 1882 (115 years ago).

title: 731 Lexington Avenue
complex: 731 Lexington Avenue is a 55-story building with a roof height of 806 ft . <s> As of January 2019, it is the 30th-tallest building in New York City and the 61st-tallest building in the United States.
simple: It is 246 meters (806 feet) tall.

title: List of Team Umizoomi episodes

title: Canadian Conference of Mennonite Brethren Churches
complex: The Canadian Conference of Mennonite Brethren Churches (CCMBC) is a community of about 250 diverse Mennonite Brethren (MB) congregations spread across Canada, united through their evangelical Anabaptist beliefs and values and by their mission to grow healthy churches, helping them reach their worlds.
simple: The Canadian Conference of Mennonite Brethren Churches is a Protestant Christian denomination in Canada.

title: Oak
complex: An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin "oak tree") of the beech family, Fagaceae. <s> There are approximately 600 extant species of oaks. <s> The common name "oak" also appears in the names of species in related genera, notably "Lithocarpus" (stone oaks), as well as in those of unrelated species such as "Grevillea robusta" (silky oaks) and the Casuarinaceae (she-oaks). <s> The genus "Quercus" is native to the Northern Hemisphere, and includes deciduous and evergreen species extending from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in the Americas, Asia, Europe, and North Africa. <s> North America contains the largest number of oak species, with approximately 90 occurring in the United States, while Mexico has 160 species of which 109 are endemic. <s> The second greatest center of oak diversity is China, which contains approximately 100 species. <s> Oaks have spirally arranged leaves, with lobate margins in many species; some have serrated leaves or entire leaves with smooth margins. <s> Many deciduous species are marcescent, not dropping dead leaves until spring. <s> In spring, a single oak tree produces both male flowers (in the form of catkins) and small female flowers. <s> The fruit is a nut called an acorn or oak nut borne in a cup-like structure known as a cupule; each acorn contains one seed (rarely two or three) and takes 6–18 months to mature, depending on their species. <s> The acorns and leaves contain tannic acid, which helps to guard from fungi and insects. <s> The live oaks are distinguished for being evergreen, but are not actually a distinct group and instead are dispersed across the genus. <s> The oak tree is a flowering plant.
simple: The oak tree is a tree or shrub in the genus "Quercus". <s> There are about 600 living species. <s> The common name "oak (Oaks)" may also appear in the names of species in related genera, such as "Lithocarpus". <s> The genus "Quercus" is native to the Northern Hemisphere. <s> It includes deciduous and evergreen species from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in Asia and the Americas. <s> North America has the largest number of oak species: about 90 occur in the United States. <s> Mexico has 160 species, of which 109 are endemic. <s> The second greatest center of oak diversity is China, which has about 100 species. <s> Oaks have spirally arranged leaves, with rounded edges in many species; some have leaves with jagged edges or entire leaves with smooth margins. <s> Many deciduous species do not drop dead leaves until spring. <s> In spring, a single oak tree produces both male flowers (as catkins) and small female flowers. <s> The fruit is a nut called an acorn, carried in a cup-like structure. <s> Each acorn has one seed (rarely two or three) and takes 6–18 months to mature, depending on species. <s> The so-called "live oaks" are evergreen. <s> The oak is a kind of hardwood forest tree.

title: Bridgestone Arena
complex: Bridgestone Arena (originally Nashville Arena, and formerly Gaylord Entertainment Center and Sommet Center) is a multi-purpose venue in downtown Nashville, Tennessee, that was completed in 1996, and is the home of the Nashville Predators of the National Hockey League. <s> In 1997, it was the venue of the United States Figure Skating Championships, and in 2004 hosted the USA Gymnastics National Championships. <s> It was the home of the Nashville Kats franchise of the Arena Football League from 1997 until 2001, and hosted the team's revival from 2005 to 2007, when the Kats folded. <s> Bridgestone Arena has a seating capacity of 17,113 for ice hockey, 19,395 for basketball, 10,000 for half-house concerts, 18,500 for end-stage concerts and 20,000 for center-stage concerts, depending on the configuration used. <s> It has also hosted several professional wrestling events and a boxing card since its opening.
simple: The Bridgestone Arena is a sports arena in Nashville, Tennessee. <s> The arena opened on December 18, 1996, and is the current home to the Nashville Predators of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> The arena is formerly known as Nashville Arena, Gaylord Entertainment Center, and Sommet Center. <s> The arena was also home to the Nashville Kats of the Arena Football League from 1997 until 2001 when the franchise was sold and was moved to Georgia to become the Georgia Force. <s> The arena currently seats 19,395 for basketball and 17,113 for ice hockey.

title: North Berwick
complex: North Berwick ( ; ) is a seaside town and former royal burgh in East Lothian, Scotland. <s> It is situated on the south shore of the Firth of Forth, approximately 20 mi east-northeast of Edinburgh.
simple: North Berwick is a town in East Lothian, Scotland.

title: Harvey Keitel
complex: Harvey Keitel ( ; born May 13, 1939) is an American actor and producer. <s> He has starred in films such as "Mean Streets" (1973), "Taxi Driver" (1976), "The Duellists" (1977), "Bugsy" (1991), "Thelma & Louise" (1991), "Reservoir Dogs" (1992), " Sister Act" (1992), "The Piano" (1993), "Pulp Fiction" (1994), "From Dusk till Dawn" (1996), "Cop Land" (1997), "Red Dragon" (2002), "The Grand Budapest Hotel" (2014), and "Isle of Dogs" (2018).
simple: Harvey Keitel (born May 13, 1939) is an American actor. <s> He has played in movies such as "Reservoir Dogs", "Pulp Fiction", "Smoke", and "Thelma and Louise".

title: Felanitx
complex: Felanitx or Felanich is a municipality in the Spanish autonomous community of the Balearic Islands, located in the southeast of Majorca, 48 kilometres (30 miles) from the capital Palma de Mallorca.
simple: It is 48 km from Palma.

title: Scottish Green Party
complex: The Scottish Green Party ( ; ; branded Scottish Greens) is a green political party in Scotland. <s> The party has six MSPs in the Scottish Parliament as of 2016.
simple: The Scottish Green Party is a political party in Scotland that has close relations to the Green Party of England and Wales.

title: Brooks Orpik
complex: Richard Brooks Orpik (born September 26, 1980) is an American former professional ice hockey defenseman. <s> He has previously played for the Pittsburgh Penguins and the Washington Capitals of the National Hockey League (NHL). <s> Orpik has won the Stanley Cup twice: in 2009 with Pittsburgh and in 2018 with Washington. <s> Orpik played three seasons at Boston College for the Eagles ice hockey team, winning the Hockey East playoff championship in 1999 and 2001, as well as the NCAA Men's Ice Hockey Championship in 2001. <s> His younger brother Andrew was also a hockey player, playing for Boston College and having a brief minor league career. <s> Orpik was drafted in the first round, 18th overall, of the 2000 NHL Entry Draft by the Pittsburgh Penguins. <s> He began his professional career with the Wilkes-Barre/Scranton Penguins of the American Hockey League (AHL) during the 2001–02 season. <s> He made his NHL debut during the 2002–03 season, playing in six games and recording no points. <s> After earning a permanent roster spot on the team the next year, Orpik played in 79 games, registering one goal, nine assists and 127 penalty minutes. <s> On March 4, 2006, Orpik boarded Carolina Hurricanes forward Erik Cole, fracturing a vertebra in Cole's neck. <s> Orpik was suspended three games for the illegal hit. <s> Cole did not return until Game 6 of the 2006 Stanley Cup Finals. <s> In the summer of 2008, Orpik signed a new six-year, $22.5 million contract with the Penguins. <s> In October 2008, he was named an alternate captain (interim while Sergei Gonchar was injured) of the Penguins, along with Evgeni Malkin, behind captain Sidney Crosby. <s> On June 12, 2009, Orpik and the Penguins became Stanley Cup champions by defeating the Detroit Red Wings in Game 7 of the 2009 Stanley Cup Finals. <s> He was the first native of California to win the Stanley Cup. <s> On July 1, 2014, the Washington Capitals signed Orpik to a five-year, $27.5 million contract as an unrestricted free agent. <s> On June 25, 2019, Orpik announced his retirement from professional hockey.
simple: Richard Brooks Orpik (born September 26, 1980) is an American former professional ice hockey defenseman. <s> He most recently played for the Washington Capitals where he was an alternate captain. <s> He has also played for the Pittsburgh Penguins. <s> Before playing in the NHL, Orpik played 3 years of college hockey at Boston College with the Eagles. <s> He was drafted with the 18th overall pick by the Pittsburgh Penguins in the 2000 NHL Entry Draft. <s> His made his NHL debut with the Penguins during the 2002–03 NHL season, playing in 6 games and recording no points. <s> On July 2, 2008, the Penguins signed Orpik to a six-year, $22.5 million contract. <s> On June 12, 2009, Orpik was able to win the Stanley Cup with the Penguins when they defeated the Detroit Red Wings in Game 7. <s> On July 1, 2014, Orpik was signed to a 5-year, $27.5 million contract by the Washington Capitals. <s> On June 25, 2019, Orpik announced his retirement from professional hockey following 15 NHL seasons.

title: Hendrik Lorentz
complex: Hendrik Antoon Lorentz ( ; 18 July 1853 – 4 February 1928) was a Dutch physicist who shared the 1902 Nobel Prize in Physics with Pieter Zeeman for the discovery and theoretical explanation of the Zeeman effect. <s> He also derived the transformation equations underpinning Albert Einstein's theory of special relativity. <s> Hendrik Lorentz was born in Arnhem, Gelderland, Netherlands, the son of Gerrit Frederik Lorentz (1822–1893), a well-off horticulturist, and Geertruida van Ginkel (1826–1861). <s> In 1862, after his mother's death, his father married Luberta Hupkes. <s> Despite being raised as a Protestant, he was a freethinker in religious matters. <s> From 1866 to 1869, he attended the "Hogere Burger School" in Arnhem, a new type of public high school recently established by Johan Rudolph Thorbecke. <s> His results in school were exemplary; not only did he excel in the physical sciences and mathematics, but also in English, French, and German. <s> In 1870, he passed the exams in classical languages which were then required for admission to University. <s> In 1905, Einstein would use many of the concepts, mathematical tools and results Lorentz discussed to write his paper entitled "On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies", known today as the theory of special relativity. <s> Because Lorentz laid the fundamentals for the work by Einstein, this theory was originally called the "Lorentz-Einstein theory". <s> Lorentz was one of few scientists who supported Einstein's search for general relativity from the beginning – he wrote several research papers and discussed with Einstein personally and by letter. <s> For instance, he attempted to combine Einstein's formalism with Hamilton's principle (1915), and to reformulate it in a coordinate-free way (1916). <s> In January 1928, Lorentz became seriously ill, and died shortly after on February 4.
simple: Hendrik Antoon Lorentz (18 July 1853 – 4 February 1928) was a Dutch physicist. <s> In 1902, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics together with Pieter Zeeman for the discovery and theoretical explanation of the Zeeman effect. <s> He also derived the transformation equations that were later used by Albert Einstein to describe space and time. <s> Hendrik Lorentz was born in Arnhem, Gelderland (The Netherlands), the son of Gerrit Frederik Lorentz (1822–1893). <s> In 1862, after his mother's death, his father married Luberta Hupkes. <s> In 1905, Einstein would use many of the concepts to write his paper entitled "On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies", known today as the theory of special relativity. <s> Because Lorentz laid the fundamentals for the work by Einstein, this theory was originally called the "Lorentz-Einstein theory". <s> Lorentz was one of few scientists who supported Einstein's search for general relativity from the beginning – he wrote several research papers and discussed with Einstein personally and by letter. <s> For instance, he attempted to combine Einstein's formalism with Hamilton's principle (1915). <s> In January 1928, Lorentz became seriously ill, and died shortly after on February 4.

title: V. V. Giri
complex: Varahagiri Venkata Giri (10 August 1894 – 24 June 1980), commonly known as V. V. Giri, was the fourth president of India from 24 August 1969 to 24 August 1974. <s> As president, Giri was the only person to be elected as an independent candidate. <s> He was succeeded by Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed as president in 1974. <s> After the end of his full term, Giri was honoured by the Government of India with the Bharat Ratna in 1975. <s> Giri died on 24 June 1980. <s> His great grandson V. Giri Shankar is an Advocate of the Madras High Court, Chennai.
simple: Varahagiri Venkata Giri commonly known as V. V. Giri, was the fourth President of India. <s> He was also the 3rd Vice President of India. <s> He was the President from 24 August 1969 to 24 August 1974. <s> As President, Giri was the only person to be elected as an independent candidate. <s> He was succeeded by Fakhruddin Ali Ahmed as President in 1974. <s> After the end of his full term, Giri was honoured by the Government of India with the Bharat Ratna in 1975. <s> Giri died on 24 June 1980.

title: Artificial leather
complex: Artificial leather, also called synthetic leather is a material intended to substitute for leather in upholstery, clothing, footwear, and other uses where a leather-like finish is desired but the actual material is cost-prohibitive or unsuitable. <s> Artificial leather is marketed under many names, including "leatherette", "faux leather", "vegan leather", "PU leather" and "pleather".
simple: Artificial leather is a substance used as a replacement for real leather.

title: Piotr Świerczewski
complex: Piotr Jarosław Świerczewski (] ; born April 8, 1972) is a retired Polish football player. <s> During his 20-year professional career, he played for clubs such as Lech Poznań, GKS Katowice, AS Saint-Étienne (France), SC Bastia (France), Gamba Osaka (Japan), Olympique Marseille (France), Birmingham City F.C. (England), Polonia Warsaw and ŁKS Łódź. <s> He played for the Polish national team, winning 70 caps and scoring a goal. <s> He was a participant at the 1992 Summer Olympics, where Poland won the silver medal and at the 2002 FIFA World Cup.
simple: Piotr Jarosław Świerczewski (born 8 April 1972, Nowy Sącz) is a Polish football player. <s> He has played for Poland national team.

title: Chesapeake Bay
complex: The Chesapeake Bay is an estuary in the U.S. states of Maryland and Virginia. <s> The Bay is located in the Mid-Atlantic region and is primarily separated from the Atlantic Ocean by the Delmarva Peninsula with its mouth located between Cape Henry and Cape Charles. <s> With its northern portion in Maryland and the southern part in Virginia, the Chesapeake Bay is a very important feature for the ecology and economy of those two states, as well as others. <s> More than 150 major rivers and streams flow into the Bay's 64299 sqmi drainage basin, which covers parts of six states (New York, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, Virginia and West Virginia) and all of Washington, D.C. <s> The Bay is approximately 200 mi long from its northern headwaters in the Susquehanna River to its outlet in the Atlantic Ocean. <s> It is 2.8 mi wide at its narrowest (between Kent County's Plum Point near Newtown and the Harford County shore near Romney Creek) and 30 mi at its widest (just south of the mouth of the Potomac River). <s> Total shoreline including tributaries is 11684 mi , circumnavigating a surface area of 4479 sqmi . <s> Average depth is 21 ft , reaching a maximum of 174 ft . <s> The Bay is spanned twice, in Maryland by the Chesapeake Bay Bridge from Sandy Point (near Annapolis) to Kent Island and in Virginia by the Chesapeake Bay Bridge-Tunnel connecting Virginia Beach to Cape Charles. <s> Known for both its beauty and bounty, the Bay has become "emptier", with fewer crabs, oysters and watermen in past years.
simple: The Chesapeake Bay is the largest estuary in the United States. <s> It lies off the Atlantic Ocean and is surrounded by Maryland and Virginia. <s> The bay's watershed covers 64299 sqmi in the District of Columbia and parts of six states: New York, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, and West Virginia. <s> More than 150 rivers and streams drain into it. <s> The Chesapeake Bay is about 200 miles (300 km) long, from the Susquehanna River in the north to the Atlantic Ocean. <s> At its narrowest point between Kent County's Plum Point (near Newtown) and the Harford County shore near Romney Creek, the bay isabout 2.8 miles (4.5 km) wide. <s> At the widest location, it is 30 miles (50 km) wide. <s> The Chesapeake Bay Bridge crosses the bay in Maryland from Sandy Point (near Annapolis) to Kent Island. <s> The Chesapeake Bay Bridge-Tunnel in Virginia connects Virginia Beach to Cape Charles.

title: Yacht
complex: A yacht is a watercraft used for pleasure or sports. <s> The term originates from the Dutch word "jacht" (which means "hunt"), and originally referenced light, fast sailing vessels that the Dutch Republic navy used to pursue pirates and other transgressors around and into the shallow waters of the Low Countries. <s> The yacht was popularized by Charles II of England as a pleasure or recreation vessel following his restoration in 1660. <s> Sailing yachts can range in overall length (Length Over All—LOA) from about 6 m to well over 30 m , where the distinction between a yacht and a ship becomes blurred. <s> Most privately owned yachts fall in the range of about 7 m -14 m . <s> The cost of building and keeping a yacht rises quickly as length increases. <s> In the United States, sailors tend to refer to smaller yachts as sailboats, while referring to the general sport of sailing as yachting. <s> Within the limited context of sailboat racing, a yacht is any sailing vessel taking part in a race, regardless of size.
simple: A yacht is a type of boat which is mainly used for recreation. <s> The name comes from the Dutch word "jachtschip", which originally meant "hunting-boat" or "fast boat". <s> Most privately owned yachts fall in the range of about 7 m-14 m; the cost of building and keeping a yacht rises quickly as length increases. <s> In the United States, sailors tend to refer to smaller yachts as sailboats, while referring to the general sport of sailing as yachting. <s> In sailboat racing, a yacht is any sailing vessel taking part in a race.

title: Hancock County, Illinois
complex: Hancock County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> According to the 2010 census, it has a population of 19,104. <s> Its county seat is Carthage, and its largest city is Hamilton. <s> The county is made up of rural towns with many farmers. <s> Hancock County was formed, on January 13, 1825, out of Pike County. <s> It was named in honor of John Hancock, who signed the Declaration of Independence.
simple: Hancock County is a county in the U.S. state of Illinois. <s> According to the 2010 census, it has a population of 19,104. <s> Its county seat is Carthage, and largest city is Hamilton. <s> The county is made up of rural towns with many farmers. <s> Hancock County was founded in 1825 and named in honor of John Hancock, who clearly signed the Declaration of Independence.
